(25, 'E2--0025AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'My Forty Five Years of Teaching at U.P. (1957-2002)\nMarino M. Mena ', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(26, 'E2-0026AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Globalization : its impact on environment \nMarino M. Mena ', 'This paper only focuses on the impact of globalization on the environment. The term \"globalization\" is interpreted as a \"free market concept that calls for a borderless world\" - the definition adopted by the organizers of the 2002 EWC/EWCA International Conference in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. The term \"environment\" as used here only refers to the natural environment and not in its broadest sense which could include, for example, the internal and external forces which have an effect on a company\'s operation and success. The paper specifically respond to the organizers\' question : Can the Asia-Pacific nations prepare themselves to minimize the negative effects and maximize the positive advantages?\" My answer to this question is \"yes, provided the measures as recommended herein are considered as integral part of globalization\". The challenge of globalization with respect to the environment is how to have adequate and implementable environmental management program while pursuing the economic thrust of globalization which is to avail of the advances in science and technology so as to expand the businesses, to increase productivity with products of global quality, and thus, to provide better and more opportunities for the people in a global context. Globalization will challenge our people to gear up for competition. However, environmental management has to be an integral part of the overall effort. The resources of the nature and the quality of the environment hae to be sustained because they belong to the past, the present, and the future. ', 'Globalization\nEnvironmental management program\nEnvironmental management ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(27, 'E2-0027AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Value and Ethics in Engineering Practice\nMarino M. Mena ', '', 'Engineering practice\nValues\nEthics', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(28, 'E2-0028AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Let us unite for the sake of the future : an appeal to the silent majority \nMarino M. Mena ', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(29, 'E2-0029AC', '', 'Thoughts on Sustainable Development and Education\nMarino M. Mena \n\nRegional Conference in the Philippines\nTheme : Asia and the Pacific Facing the New Millenium : Challenges, Opportunities and Responses ', '', '', 'Shangri-la EDSA Plaza Hotel, Ortigas Center, Metro Manila : January 28-29, 1999', '', '', 'Sustainable Development : Its Implications to Engineering Education by Marino M. Mena ', 'Sustainable development is the challenge of meeting human needs for natural resources, industrial products, energy, food, transportation, shelter and effective waste management while conserving and protecting environmental quality and the natural resource base essential for future development. Meeting such a challenge requires the concerted effort among all sectors of society in order for us to achieve broader social needs. The education sector has an important role to play in this effort. It is the purpose of this paper to discuss the implications of sustainable development and the expected response of engineering education to the challenge as we move towards the new millennium. ', 'Sustainable development\nEngineering education', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(30, 'E2-0030AC', '', '2000 EWC/EWCA International Conference \n\nTheme : Building an Asia/Pacific Community : The East-West Center in the 21st Century ', '', '', 'Hawaiian Regent Hotel\n2552 Kalakua Avenue\nHonolulu, Hawaii 96815-3699\nUSA\n\nJuly 4-8, 2000', '', '', 'Engineering Education for the Environment : A Continuing Challenge in the 21st century \nby Marino M.', 'Responding to the increasing demands of modern society for a better and sustainable environment will continue to be a major global challenge in the 21st century. In the field of engineering society calls for engineering who are environmentally educated and who will be able to balance technical with socio-economic-ecological efficiency in their planning, design, construction, operation, maintenance and monitoring of engineering projects. These demands have broadened the role in society of the engineering profession and as a consequence, have increased the responsibilities of engineering education. Both sectors, in cooperation with the other sectors of society, have to work together for a better and sustainable environment. How these two sectors can effectively respond to the environmental challenge is the main focus of this paper. ', 'Engineering education', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(31, 'E2-0031AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Notes on the Philosophy and Concept of Ecology and Sustainable Development \nby Marino M. Mena ', 'Sustainable development, although basically an economic-growth concept, is ecology-related. Sustainable development is the challenge of meeting human needs for natural resources, industrial products, energy, food, transportation, shelter, and effective waste management while conserving and protecting environmental quality and the natural-resource base essential for future development. Meeting such a challenge requires the concerted effort among all sectors of human society : the government and the private sectors, the entrepreneurs and the industrialists, the producers and the consumers, the professionals and the scientists, the teachers and the students, the NGOs and the people. The concept of sustainable development aims to achieve economic growth without destroying the natural-resource base essential for meeting the needs of the future generations. Man cannot achieve this goal if he does not recognize the reality that he is part of a life-support system composed of the atmosphere, water, minerals, soil, plants, animals and micro-organisms that function together to keep the whole system viable. It is therefore obvious that sustainable development and ecology are inter-related. The following discussion focuses on this philosophy. ', 'Sustainable development\nEcology', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(32, 'E2-0032AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'My vision for a municipality : towards a meaningful and sustainable socio-economic development \nby M', '', 'Sustainable socio-economic development ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(33, 'E2-0033AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Trends and perspectives in Philippine Engineering Education towards the next millennium \nby Marino M', 'As the world gears towards the new millennium Y2K it is essential for us to make an assessment of our past achievements and to identify the changes that we have to make in order to respond to the demands of the future. One of the areas which has to be dynamic to keep pace with the rapid advances in scientific knowledge is education in general and engineering education in particular. This paper focuses on trends and perspectives in engineering education in the Philippines in general and at the College of Engineering, University of the Philippines in particular. The new millennium will have challenges at various geographical levels which will have implications on engineering education. It is important that the changes are made at the proper time and in the right direction. ', 'Engineering education--Philippines', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(34, 'E2-0034AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Global trends and issues in civil engineering education\nby Marino M. Mena ', 'Societies throughout the world are aware of the achievements in civil engineering. It is recognized world-wide that the civil engineer is one major instrument in development and change and plays a fundamental role in shaping the world. But development is now more and more a compromise between that which is technically possible, that which is considered economically attractive, and that which is acceptable on environmental grounds. The concept of sustainable development has emerged in the last decades of the 20th century and is gaining global acceptance. Information and communication technology (ICT) is now a global tool for development. We are moving rapidly towards on e-environment. The questions are : What are the implications of these global trends and issues on civil engineering education? Is the present professional education and training for the civil engineer adequate to meet these new challenges? How could the civil engineering education be able to respond to these challenges? This paper aims to answer these questions and hopefully will be useful to civil engineering education planners, administrators and educators. ', 'Civil engineering education\nSustainable development ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(35, 'E2-0035AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Setting objectives and strategies for technical education \nby Marino M. Mena ', 'A former deputy minister of education in the 1980s said : \"The Philippine educational system is irrelevant and elitist, is not attuned to the needs of the times, and is oriented more to the welfare of the rich\". (Bulletin Today, February 16, 1980)\nIn the case of engineering education programs in the Philippines, we also often hear people from industry saying that \"real\" engineering is not that which is practiced in the classroom with fully specified problems and specific answers obtainable by analytical methods. There is considerable confusion and misunderstanding both in industry and among educators concerning the roles to be played by engineering and/or technician programs and by their graduates. This situation results in the employment of engineers who are performing as technicians of technologists. This mismatch leads to the perception that engineering graduates lack the knowledge and skills to meet the needs of industry. It is the purpose of this paper to address this problem. It discusses the processes involved in the setting up of objectives and the strategies for the attainment of these objectives. ', 'Technical education\nEngineering education programs', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(36, 'E2-0036AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Strategies in upgrading engineering education : academe viewpoint\nby Marino M. Mena ', '', 'Engineering education', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
