(73, 'E2-0073AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Thirty-six years of engineering research in energy (1957-1993) \nby Ibarra E. Cruz, Ph.D.\n\nPresented ', 'Thirty-six years of engineering research in energy are reviewed, covering a period that started in 1957, when the engineering graduate program at the University of the Philippines was in its earliest stages, up to the present time. Titles and brief descriptions of research projects which are known to the author are presented. Discussed are problems of inadequate funding and inexperienced researchers tackling ambitious studies in the early years. Recounted are the euphoria of the golden years when the energy crisis brought a deluge of research money in the mid-70ss, and the frustrations of the lean years of declining research funds due to a softening of petroleum prices in the mid-80s. A story is told of the struggle of graduate students and faculty members of the U.P. College of Engineering to conduct laboratory experiments under less than ideal conditions and of the failures and the successes leading to national energy programs that aimed at the widespread use of producer gas, alcohol and coconut oil as substitute fuels for gasoline and diesel. The story is concluded with a forecast of researches that should be continued in 1994 to the year 2000, with high hopes that the accomplishments of the past thirty-six years will be continued and expanded.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(74, 'E2-0074AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Disaster risk management background of dmaps for infrastructure \nby Benito M. Pacheco, PhD, PE \n\nPhi', 'The first part of this paper is a situationer for the Philippines in the most recent (2009) UN global assessment report that ranked it among the first 14 of approximately 200 countries and economies whose population is most at risk from earthquakes, cyclones, landslides, and floods. Second is an introduction of DMAPS for Infrastructure, a new (2009) public-private partnership agreement for disaster mitigation, adaptation, and preparedness strategies for infrastructure, involving scientists and engineers in the Philippines; this may be viewed as having evolved from the Philippine Institute of Civil Engineers DMAPS that was first conceptualized five years earlier (2004), and DQRP that was first institutionalized four years even before (2000), both volunteerism programs by Filipino civil engineers. Third and main part is a framework of concepts and terminologies that the author proposes for engineers and scientists to harmonize among themselves and with professionals in finance, medicine, and other disciplines. The author proposes that fundamental issues common to various professional disciplines concerning the management of risk be associated with four general steps of risk management, easily remembered as R-I-S-K : Recognize, Impute an estimate, Survey over time, and Keep inside tolerance range. The particular type of risk needs to be clearly recognized (in step 1 of risk management), before deciding on the ordinal or other level of measure to impute an estimate (in step 2 of risk management). The older paradigm of managing disaster meets the newer paradigm of managing risk, at the step of surveying the risk over time (in step 3 of risk management), by virtue of the recognition that risk factors do evolve. Risk reduction is cited as the preferred mode of keeping disaster risk inside the tolerance range, yet many risk control modes indeed exist (in step 4 of risk management) from many viewpoints. Highlights of the four steps of the risk management spiral are summarized; ideally, each complete cycle of risk management R-I-S-K brings down the level of uncertainty and reduces the risk. It is proposed that the DMAPS for Infrastructure public-private partnership program be viewed in this framework. In appendices, this paper includes three essays that offer an alternative way of appreciating risk management concepts and terminologies. ', 'Risk factor\nHazard\nExposure\nVulnerability\nUncertainty\nHuman factor\nRisk management spiral\nVolunteerism ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(75, 'E2-0075AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Computer simulation of fuel consumption in driving cycles\nby Gino T. Bautista, B.S.M.E\nMay 1988', 'A computer model for simulating fuel consumption of a road vehicle over any prescribed driving cycle was developed using steady-state performance data from chassis dynamometer tests. The method is simple and does not require sophisticated chassis dynamometer test facilities. The method also eliminates variances due to driving style. It was determined that the predictions of the computer model agree closely with fuel consumption figures from actual road tests. The use of steady-state performance data from chassis dynamometer tests was found to be suitable in predicting fuel consumption of driving cycles. This study and its conclusions are limited to diesel engine driven road vehicles. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(76, 'E2-0076AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Progress report no. 10 of the ESA-UNET Subproject B : research on industrial wastewater treatment.\nM', 'Work progressed on the finalization of research reports and publications. Regular communication was maintained on these subjects. The different participating universities started preparing plans for future activities after this project phase along the lines sketched in the mid-term workshop report. A proposal was made to hold a final workshop at ITB Bandung in November and submitted to the European Union. Preparations of the workshop are in progress. During the workshop in Bandung the final results of the projects will be presented and plans will be made for future activities. The core future activity will be joint research with industry from each participating ASEAN country. The output from project A on technology transfer will be used as input for the formulation of plans for further network development and interaction between universities and industry for the specific topic of industrial wastewater treatment. The output of the workshop will be a clear strategy on how to tackle this issue and what should be the role of the participating universities, companies and RIET in future activities, like joint-ventures, technology transfer and dissemination of research results. The final workshop will also provide an excellent opportunity for interaction with Indonesian industry and for a discussion on the experiences in the joint formulation of research plans with industry from each ASEAN country. Mr. Chu of the University of Malaya and Mr. Noort of the TU Delft participated in the general ESA-UNET network meeting in Aachen in June. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
