(190, 'E2-0190AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Table of Contents\nForeword\nExtent of Implementation\nPresent State of the Campus\nProposed Development Plans ', '', '(1970, March 23) U.P. Master Development Plan ', 'The Master Development Plan for the Diliman Campus of the University of the Philippines at Quezon City was prepared by the Office of Campus Planning in 1965-66. Its principal aims was and is to serve as the principal base for a continuous, comprehensive, and ultimate development program. This report is a revised and updated edition of that Plan, as taken from the students\' point of view. \nAt the start of the second semester, the CE 80 class was organized into a mock consulting firm in order to evaluate and update the 1966 UP Master Plan. After a series of lectures and orientation conducted by Prof. Felisberto Reyes, Dr. Goodman, Dean Aurelio Juguilon, Prof. Perlito C. Reyes and Prof. Delfin Zapanta, the class was subdivided into teams and sub-teams.\nUpon the organization of the class, a survey of what has been accomplished by way of implementation of the UP Master Plan. A report on this regard has already been submitted and is included here in the earlier part for comprehensiveness. Intensive studies and researches on the original charts, schemes, and other documents of the Office of Campus Planning were undertaken to evaluate all conditions and factors bearing on the preparation of a comprehensive campus development plan. Emphasis of the investigations were on the changes, if any, of the conditions and factors affecting the plans. No major revisions are recommended onthe Land Use Plan. \nAs students intested in the fundamentals of planning, the team also covered the general context of campus current problems, development, objectives, planning guidelines and the rationale behind the proposals- most of which were carry-overs from the original edition. \nThe proposals presented here took cognizance of the setbacks and problems that besetted the original plan. Consideration of relevant data and factors were, in no small measure, in-debted to the following : Director Tomacruz of the President\'s Advisory Committee on Campus Planning and Development, Engineer Jose Giron, Engineering Department of the Office of the Physical Plant, Prof. Perlito C. Reyes, Architect Novenario, and numerous other individuals without whom this report would not have been possible. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(191, 'E2-0191AC', '', '1984 Revised Code of the University of the Philippines (2nd Draft) ', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Consonant to the fundamental principle of democratic law-making that the sentiments of those who are to be governed by the rules must be taken into consideration, the various sectors of the university community were represented in the Commitee created to revise the University Code. The different constituencies were then provided copies of the completed first draft. Public hearings were subsequently conducted in the four autonomous campuses for wider and more systematic discussion of the proposed rules. \nWithin the constraints of law and reason, this second draft of the proposed Revised University Code reflects the results of the discussions. While all interests and opinions could not be accomodated, revisions and modifications were incorporated to safeguard high academic standards, to render the university processes more open to democractic participation, to enhance individual and institutional academic freedom, to protect the rights of individual members of the academic community against the tyranny of numbers, to simplify and clarify procedures whether they pertain to personnel action or disciplinary proceedings, and to expand benefits where reasonably allowed by limited resources.\nIn the face of sometimes irresponsible conflicting claims, the Code Committee continued to be guided by the principles that animated the preparation of the first draft in the formulation of the provisions of the second draft. ', 'Cortes, Irene R. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(192, 'E2-0192AC', '', 'The Revised Code of the University of the Philippines (Approved by the Board of Regents on January 9, 1961)', 'Quezon City', 'University of the Philippines Press', '1961', 'The University Charter\nBook I. Governmental and Administrative Affairs\nPreliminary Title\nGeneral Provisions\nTitle One. The Government of the University\nTitle Two. The Organization of Instruction and Research\nTitle Three. The University Departments\nTitle Four. Conditions of Employment\nTitle Five. Business and Financial Administration\nBook II. Academic Affairs\nTitle One. Academic Calendar and Classes\nTitle Two. Admission and Registration\nTitle Three. Curricular changes\nTitle Four. Examinations and Grades\nTitle Five. Rules on Scholastic Standing\nTitle Six. Graduation\nBook III. Student Affairs\nTitle One. Student Services\nTitle Two. Extra-Curricular Activities\nTitle Three. Conduct and Discipline \nConcluding Title. Amendment and Repeal\nIndex \n', '', '', 'The publication of a revised code of the University of the Philippines has been a pressing need for the orderly administration and operation of the University since the reestablishment and transfer of its principal campus from Manila to Quezon City. The old Code was designed and intended for the University of pre-war days. It was sufficiently adequate under the conditions then existing. But after the War it became obviously out of place and outdated in several respects under different surroundings and before novel problems obtaining on the new campus. The marked increase in student enrollment, the changed physical environment, and the new academic atmosphere had called for a revision of many parts of the old Code. The Board of Regents, therefore, upon the recommendation of the University President, decided to update the University regulations so as to fit them to present needs and conditions and to make them more responsive and better suited to the problems of the University. The work of revision lasted over a period of one year. After this work was finished, it was submitted to the Board of Regents for consideration. About six months had elapsed before this body finally approved it on January 9, 1961. The revised Code took effect on February 15, 1961 when the Board confirmed its previous action. ', 'Sinco, V.G.', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(193, 'E2-0193AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, December 28) Memorandum for the Board of Regents regarding rules ', '', 'Romulo, Carlos P. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(194, 'E2-0194AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Rules and Regulations in the Discipline of UP Faculty Members and Employees ', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(195, 'E2-0195AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Table of Contents\nThe University Charter\nBook I. Governmental and Administrative Affairs\nTitle One. The Government of the University System\nTitle Two. The Organization of Instruction and Research\nTitle Three. The University Departments\nTitle Four. Conditions of Employment\nTitle Five. Business and Financial Administration\nBook II. Academic Affairs\nTitle One. Academic Calendar and Classes\nTitle Two. Admission and Registration\nTitle Three. Curricular Changes\nTitle Four. Examinations and Grades\nTitle Five. Rules on Scholastic Standing \nTitle Six. Graduation\nBook III. Student Affairs\nTitle One. Student Services\nTitle Two. Extra-Curricular Activities\nTitle Three. Conduct and Discipline\nConcluding Title. Amendment and Repeal \n\n', '', '(1961, January 9) The Revised Code of the University of the Philippines (Approved 682nd Special B/R ', 'Preface\nThis publication was prepared pursuant to Administrative Order No. 260, dated October 22, 1974, designating the U.P. Law Center \"to collate, update and publish the Revised Code of the University of the Philippines System preparatory to the comprehensive revision of said code.\"\nThe execution of this task was by no means easy. Firstly, there was the difficulty of searching for the relevant laws, resolutions, and executive and administrative orders. This problem was particularly met with respect to the period from 1961-1969, when the University System still had no Official Gazette. For this period, the Center heavily relied on materials provided by the Office of the President and the Office of General Services. For the years following this period, the Center had to depend mostly on the Official Gazette in additon to materials made available by the above-mentioned offices. \nDifficulty of access to the needed materials was not the only problem. As difficult, if not more difficult, was the selection of the materials, which were numerous, and how to incorporate them in the provisions of the Code. This problem was especially encoutered in connection with laws, resolutions and executive and administrative orders which, while not expressly amending, modifying, amplifying, superseding, or repealing certain provisions of the Code, have the implied effect of doing so. Some of these simply cannot be incorporated in the Code without entailing substantial revision of entire chapters, even titles, of it. At the same time, they are so imporant that they cannot be left unaccounted for. \nIn view of this problem, the Center incorporated in the provisions of the Code only those laws and Board resolutions which expressly amend the charter and the Code and such of those which do so impliedly as can be incorporated without entailing the problem adverted to above. As to other laws, resolutions and executive and administrative orders, the Center has no recourse except to resort to the use of footnotes and appendices. Many of the footnotes make reference to the appendices while others explain or amplify certain provisions of the Code in the light of developments since 1961. \nThis work does not claim to be free from error. It is entirely possible that there might be some emission of important rules or resolutions which can qualify for incorporation in the Code or as appendices. But, on the basis of the available materials, the Center certainly did its best to make this edition of the COde as exhaustive, accurate and useful as possible, not only as a guide for the University officialdom and populace but as a material for the projected revision of the Code. \nAcknowledgment must be made of the special contribution of the Division of Research and Law Reform of the U...Law Center to which this job was entrusted, particularly Prof. Esteban B. Bautista, Assistant Head of the Division, who prepared the manuscript; Prof. Sulpicio Guevara, Division Head, who went over the manuscript and made valuable suggestions; the Division\'s clerical force - Mr. Primo S. Arinas, Mrs. Zenaida P. Cruz, Miss Elizabeth O. Rivera, and Mrs. Milagros A. Gallardo - who did the stenciling and helped in the proof-reading; and the Administrative Division which tool care of the mimeographing and binding. ', 'Bacungan, Froilan M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
