(592, 'E2-0592AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1979, September 24) Engineering Education Program', 'We were recently informed by EDPITAF that from 18 to 25 new EDPITAF grantees will be enrolling in the Engineering Education Program in November, 1979.\nAs agreed upon previously, the first education course that will be given to new students in the Master of Engineering (Engineering Education) program is EDFD 201. May we therefore request your college to open one section of EDFP 201 for the Engineering Education majors in the second semester of academic year 1979-1980?', 'Ramos, Paz G.\nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(593, 'E2-0593AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1980, September 2) Cost of Tuition Fee for the whole course and other expenses, besides tuition fee', 'In reply to your letter dated August 27, 1980, we are pleased to furnish you with the following information :\n1. The tuition fee charged in the Graduate Program is P50/unit, exlcusive of miscellaneous fees which amount to P153.50 per semester.\n2. A minimum requirement of at least one year residence and 30 units of graduate courses must be fulfilled by each graduate student. \nPlease be also informed that our program in Environmental Engineering is a graduate program leading to a Master\'s degree. We do not have an undergraduate program in this field. However, Bachelor of Science Degree holders in Civil Engineering, Chemical Engineering, Sanitary Engineering, Public Health Engineering and/or their equivalent are eligible for admission to the program. The normal load in the graduate division is 9 to 12 units per semester. Although one year is the minimum requirement, a more reasonable estimate of the period of completion for a full-time graduate student is three semesters and possibly one summer, especially if the student\'s program requires thesis. ', 'Lorenzo, Rowan F. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(594, 'E2-0594AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1980, November 19) Attached Proposal for Continuing Education Program in Electrical Engineering ', '1. Both the College of Engineering and the National Engineering Center recognize the need. While the College of Engineering has been offering formal continuing education programs (MS and Diploma programs), the National Engineering Center has been sponsoring non-formal continuing education programs through a series of seminars and workshops. \n2. In areas where we still don\'t have existing programs, we institute such programs based on the need and our capability to offer such programs.\n3. We recall that in 1979, for example, the College of Engineering and the National Engineering Center extended to the Philippine Institute of Civil Engineers their facilities for the Continuing Education Seminar on Structural Analysis and Design of Small Dams. \n4. In principle this proposal of IIEE is the in line with the common efforts of the College of Engineering and the National Engineering Center in providing opportunities and facilities for continuing education to the members of the engineering profession. \n5. With regards therefore to the proposed program by the Institute of Integrated Electrical Engieering (IIEE), we suggest that we invite IIEE\'s duly authorized representative to a meeting with Dr. Luis M. Alarilla, Jr. representing the College of Engineering, and Professor Fortunato T. De la Peña, representing the NEC, for the purpose of discussing the details of the program. Among other things, the following details have discussed : \na. IIEE\'s areas of interest;\nb. Form of the program : short courses, seminars/workshops or in-plant courses;\nc. Background of participants\nd. Role of sponsoring agencies/professional societies ', 'Mena, Marino M. \nAbis, Leopoldo V. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(595, 'E2-0595AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1980, November 24) Proposal from Dr. Jose Azarcon, Chairman of IIEE\'s Ad Hoc Preparatory Committee ', 'The Office of the President, University of the Philippines, referred to us the proposal from Dr. Jose Azarcon, Chairman of IIEE\'s Ad Hoc Preparatory Committee, for the establishment of a continuing education program for electrical engineers. Initially, the proposal includes the following courses :\n- Protective Relaying\n- Design of Electrical Systems for Commercial and Industrial Building\n- Distribution Systems Engineering\n- Transmission Systems Engineering\n- Computer Programming\n- Application of Computers in Electrical Engineering \nThis proposal is in line with the common efforts of the U.P. College of Engineering and the National Engineering Center in providign opportunities and facilities for continuing education to members of the engineering profession. While the College of Engineering offers formal continuing educaton programs (such as MS and Diploma programs), the National Engineering Center has been sponsoring non-formal continuing education programs through a series of seminars and workshops.\nAs to the above-mentioned proposal for the institution of a continuing education program for electrical engineers, we want you to know that the U.P. College of Engineeringand the National Engineering Center would be willing to institute such a program in cooperation with the Institute of Integrated Electrical Engineers. We therefore would like to invite IIEE\'s representative to a meeting with Dr. Luis M. Alarilla, Jr., Chairman of our Department of Electrical Engineering, to represent the College of Engineering, and Prof. Fortunato T. dela Peña, representing the National Engineering Center. Should this be acceptable to you, the purpose of this meeting is to discuss the details of the proposal as well as how best it can be implemented. ', 'Mendoza, Luis\nMena, Marino M.\nAbis, Leopoldo V. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(596, 'E2-0596AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1981, February 12) Letter of invitation for professional membership to the Council of Technology an', 'I am honored to receive your letter of invitation for professional membership to the Council of Technology and Allied Sciences of the Philippines (COTASP). Being one who is presently in the field of engineering education, my primary interest is in the continuous advancement and constant improvement of all aspects of higher and continuing education which pertain to the teaching and training of professional engineers. I find the objectives of COTASP equivalent to this interest and I feel honored to accept your invitation. I hope that can be of assistance to COTASP\'s efforts towards improvements that will be important to the entire engineering profession as well as to the society it serves.', 'Mena, Marino M.\nGoce, Mariano M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(597, 'E2-0597AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1981, March 25) Appointed member of the College Committee on Admission and Readmission ', 'Please be informed that you are hereby appointed member of the COLLEGE COMMITTEE ON ADMISSION AND READMISSION effective April 1, 1981 vice Mr. Miguel Escoto, Jr. who left for studies abroad.\nThis Committee is in charge of admission of new students as well as readmission of dismissed students in the College of Engineering. The Chairman of the committee is Prof. Rodolfo U. Bulatao, and the other member is Mrs. Maria Luz S. Vencio. ', 'Mena, Marino M. \nRelucio, Noel V. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(598, 'E2-0598AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1981, August 14) Status of activities of the College Committee that was formed to formulate guideli', 'This is in reply to your letter of inquiry dated August 13, 1981 about the status of activities of the College Committee that was formed to formulate guidelines for the use of equipment and facilities. Please be informed that the Committee has not yet submitted its report. As soon as I receive the report, I would be very glad to discuss with you their recommendations with the end in view of adopting a working arrangement which will be mutually beneficial. \nI furnished the Committee with a copy of your letter for their information and guidance. The Committee is composed of the following : \n1. Professor Manuel C. Jabson III, Chairman\n2. Professor Cristy R. Hernandez, Member\n3. Professor Rodolfo M. Casiple, Member\n4. Professor Teodorico F. Festin, Member\n5. Professor Amante Mangaser, Member ', 'Abis, Leopoldo V. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(599, 'E2-0599AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1981, September 28) Recommendation for the inclusion of at least six (6) units in transportation pl', 'This has reference to your letter of September 22, 1981 regarding your recommendation for the inclusion of at least six (6) units in transportation planning and engineering in civil engineering curriculum. \nPlease be informed that the present civil engineering curriculum has already six (6) units in transportation. The following are required courses in the B.S. Program in civil engineering : \nCE 46; TRANSPORTATION ENGINEERING I. - Highway, railway, air and marine traffic characteristics. Geometric design of railroads, highways, marine and air terminals. Surveys and earthwork calculations. Prerequisite : GE 12 \n5 hours a week (2 class, 3 lab.); credit 3 units.\nCE 47; TRANSPORTATION ENGINEERING II. - Pavement design, construction and maintenance of roadways and air pavements. Planning of facilities.\nPrerequisites : CE 46 and CE 60\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units. \nShould you feel that there must be other topics other than those presently covered in the above-mentioned courses, please let us know. I will be very glad to request our Department of Civil Engineering to consider the possible inclusion of these relevant topics. \nIs it possible to invite your representative to a meeting with members of the civil engineering faculty who are handling transportation courses? If this is possible, kindly give us the name of your representative and his telephone number and we will arrange a meeting to discuss these curricular matters. ', 'Mena, Marino M. \nDans, Jose P. Jr. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(600, 'E2-0600AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1981, October 15) Review and Appraisal of all the Academic Programs offered by the College of Engin', 'In compliance to Memorandum No. 92 from the Office of the President, I am pleased to send herewith a review and appraisal of all the academic programs offered by the College of Engineering. Data on research and extension activities were previously sent to your Committee. ', 'Mena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(601, 'E2-0601AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1981, October 16) List of institutions and areas in whch the College of Engineering', 'As per your request I am pleased to transmit hereunder a shopping list of institutions and areas in whch the College of Engineering would like to promote cooperation and assistance. In general, we wish to promote cooperation in the fields of education and academic research in those fields which will enhance each institution\'s educational and academic roles. The following activities can be explored : \n1. Joint research and exchange of scholars and researchers pertaining thereto;\n2. Exchange of information and materials in those fields which are of interest to both Faculties;\n3. Exchange of graduate students. \nSpecial areas of interests : \n1. Management and production techniques which are best suited to the resources and future development potential of developing countries;\n2. Low-cost techniques which are compatible with local sociological conditions;\n3. Development of alternative sources of energy;\n4. Availability of training programs for engineering teachers from developing countries; \n5. Computers in engineering education;\n6. Environmental impact assessment of development projects ', 'Abad, Dr. Gemino H. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(602, 'E2-0602AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1982, January 14) Comments to the recommendation of the Committee to Review Academic Programs that ', 'This is in reply to your letter dated January 13, 1982 asking for our comments to the recommendation of the Committee to Review Academic Programs that the National Engineering Center be attached to the College of Engineering. We agree with this recommendation. \nIt will be recalled that in my memorandum to you dated May 20, 1980, I explained that the College of Engineering and the National Engineering Center cannot be independent for the following main reasons :\n1. Presently, the two units are dependent on common resources : staff, equipment and facilities. Unless a formal linkage is therefore established, we have two \"independent\" units which are dependent on the same resources and under such a situation, conflicts involving authority over personnel and priority to use of equipment and facilities and other problems are likely to arise.\n2. The College of Engineering, in recognition of its responsibilities, has to continue improving its capability in performing its three functions namely, teaching, research and extension service. It was precisely for this purpose that the College of Engineering established the U.P. Industrial Research Center, the National Hydraulics Research Center, the U.P. Building Research Services, the Transport Training Center and the Training Center for Applied Geodesy and Photogrammetry. And yet, under the present set-up, all these Centers were absorbed by the National Engineering Center. Thus, the College of Engineering will now be dependent on the National Engineering Center in carrying out its programs and activities especially those related to research and extension services. Should there be no formal linkage between the two units, the College of Engineering may find the need in the future to reinstitute the facilities that were absorbed by the NEC in order to perform the three above-mentioned functions which we feel are vital and necessary to the growth and progress of the College. \nIt will further be recalled that the faculty and administrative personnel of the College of Engineering in a meeting held on June 27, 1980 recommend to make the two headships concurrent positions as an alternatie arrangement for linkages between the College of Engineering and the National Engineering Center. This alternative was recommended as an initial step without prejudice to the consideration of other alternatives in the future. \nWe agree with the Committee\'s recommendation that \"all research and extension units shall be attached to academic degree-granting colleges/units to allow for the immediate interchange of resources among teaching, research and extension units and to make knowledge derived from research and extension readily available to academic departments.\" However, some problems may arise in the case of research centers which are multidisciplinary in character. It may be difficult to identify an academic college to which such centers can be best attached without reducing their effectiveness in carrying out their research activites. ', 'Alfonso, Dr. Oscar M. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(603, 'E2-0603AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1982, January 15) Comments on the recommendations of the Committee to Review Academic Programs', 'In reply to your Memorandum dated January 4, 1982, hereunder are our comments on the recommendations of the Committee to Review Academic Programs. \n1. On Section E : Curricular Programs\n2. On Section F : Graduate Studies\n3. On Section I. : Admission Policies \n4. On Section J : Research Priorities\n5. On Section K : Attachment of Research and Extension Units to Academic Degree-Granting Colleges/ Units \n6. On the abolition of programs, we recommend the phasing out (instead of \"abolish\") of the masteral programs in Engineering Sciences, Nuclear Engineering and Computer Science. However, we would like to recommend the continuation of the B.S. Geodetic Engineerig and B.S. Mining Engineering programs. ', 'Alfonso, Dr. Oscar M. \nMena, Marino M.  ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(604, 'E2-0604AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1982, February 9) Comments and suggestions posed by the Curriculum Committee of the Division of Nat', 'We received your February 5 letter which informed us of the comments and suggestions posed by the Curriculum Committee of the Division of Natural Sciences and Mathematics regarding the proposed Bachelor of Computer Science program. Please be informed that we have no objections to the suggestions.\nWe certainly hope that we will not encounter further difficulties during the cluster meeting and the University Council meeting. Again, we are very thankful for the cooperation and coordination that we have achieved. ', 'Mena, Marino M. \nNuqui, Honesto G. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(605, 'E2-0605AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1982, February 15) Comments on CRAP Recommendations ', 'I wish to transmit herewith for your information and consideration the comments and suggestions from the U.P. College of Engineering on the CRAP recommendations. This updates our previous report of January 15, 1982 which we submitted to Executive Vice-President Alfonso in response to his memorandum of January 4, 1982. The commens in said previous report were those of the College Executive Committee while the attached comments include those of the faculty as obtained in a faculty meeting held last Thursday, February 4, 1982. \nFirst of all, we welcome and support your efforts in initiating a review of existing university programs in the light of new directions towards which these programs must be addressed to as well as the adoption of revised and new guidelines/ criteria which university programs must satisfy so that the university will be more responsive to the interests and needs of the many constituencies it serves. We agree that (a) the university has to be very much concerned about what to teach and how to teach it: (b) the university, in the face of new demands in a changing society, has to recognize greater responsibilities than a few years ago; and (c) the university has to be recognized nationally and internationally as a leader in many matters relating to the academic field. To meet these new responsibilities, we also believe that the university has to use new approaches and to establish new priorities even if new risks have to be taken. It has been said that if there are no controversies or tensions involved in what we are doing, then we can\'t be doing anything much. If this is the test, then the controversies or tensions created by the CRAP are welcome signs. However, while we agree that new ideas will continue to be needed, they must be requierd to go through the mill of objection and analysis. This is the trial heat which true innovations must survive. It is in the spirit that we are pleased to react to the CRAP project. \nSecondly, we also wish to inform you of the survey that the U.P. College of Engineering conducted in 1980-1981 for the purpose of obtaining the opinions of educators, practicing engineers, government and private employers of engineers as well as future engineers regarding the needs and requirements of the future will serve as a reasonable basis for establishing practical guidelines for defining the long-term goals of engineering education in the Philippines. It is intended to identify and prioritize specific goal areas which are broadly classified into three categories namely, those related to (1) national tasks, (2) development of professional skills and (3) development of professional attitudes. Specifically, we want to attain the following aims : \n(1) To determine the basic educational needs and goals of engineers, not only for the immediate future but also for the decade ahead.\n(2) To determine the scope of education necessary to fill these needs that can best be accomplished at the undergraduate and graduate levels.\n(3) To study the adequacy of present engineering education and to consider possible improvements.\n(4) To study the need and scope of continuing education programs. \nThe engineering programs can then be reviewed in the light of newly identified areas and priorities. Changes can be introduced either to improve the existing programs or to institute new ones to meet new responsibilities. It was partly because of the result of this survey why we decided to propose a new program (MS and Ph.D.) in the field of Energy as well as a Bachelor degree in Computer Science. Attached is also a copy of the results of the survey. ', 'Mena, Marino M.', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(606, 'E2-0606AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1982, February 26) Invitation to a lecture on Solar Energy ', 'Lecture Topic : Potential and Problems in the Utilization of Solar Energy \nLecturer : Professor Gunther Lehner\nUniversity of Suttgart, Germany\nTime / Date : 10 :00 a.m., Monday, March 8, 1982\nPlace : GE Conference Room, MH 410\nCollege of Engineering ', 'Mena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(607, 'E2-0607AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1982, March 29) Resolution of the U.P. Mining and Metallurgical Engineering Alumni Association for ', 'I am transmitting herewith the resolution of the U.P. Mining and Metallurgical Engineering Alumni Association for the retention of the B.S. Mining Engineering Program at U.P. and which I received today. I already informed them of the results of the dialogue that the College of Engineering Executive Committee had with you last February 15, 1982 and they are glad to learn that the B.S. Mining Engineering Program will not be phased out. However, I made them understand that the program will be continually reviewed in accordance with the criteria that has been recommended by CRAP and/or those which will be eventually approved by the University as the criteria for such a review. \nThe attached resolution contains some information about the manpower requirements of the mining industry as well as the industry\'s contribution to the socio-economic development of the country. These information as well as our alumni\'s concern have convinced us more of the need to continue the B.S. Mining Engineering Program. However, we wish to assure you, Mr. President, that we will study in depth the problems and we will try to tap the alumni for assistance. In my talks with some of them, the alumni have expressed their willingness to extend such assistance. ', 'Mena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(608, 'E2-0608AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1982, June 18) Decision of the CAS Executive Committee regarding the Graduating Senior Seminar (GSS', 'This has reference to the attached decision of the CAS Executive Committee regarding the Graduating Senior Seminar (GSS). I was told that the College of Arts and Sciences did not offer GSS this first semester, 1982-83. However, there are a number of engineering students who expect to graduate at the end of the first semester, 1982-83 and who need GSS. It will be recalled that when the University Council approved the inclusion of GSS in the various University curricula, this is a course that will be offered by the Department of Political Science, College of Arts and Sciences. Other units of the University do not have the expertise to teach such a course and / or do not have the expertise to teach such a course and / or do not have the authority to offer it. For this reason, we would like to know the status of the attached recommendation of the College of Arts and Sciences since it also affects our engineering students who have to take GSS in order to graduate. This is urgent because the graduating seniors are afraid that may not be able to graduate this semester for failure to take GSS. ', 'Mena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(609, 'E2-0609AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1982, June 29) Proposed library accreditation standards for engineering education in the Philippine', 'Your special committee to study the nature of linkages/relationship between the U.P. Main Library and the unit libraries hereby submits its report. As proposed by the members of the committee, the proposed library accreditation standards for engineering education in the Philippines are appended to the report for information purposes. \nI wish to than the following who attended the Committee\'s meeting last Friday, June 25, at the College of Engineering:\nDean Josefa Saniel\nDr. Rene Mendoza\nMs. Clarisa Dimalanta\nMs. Violeta Encarnacion', 'Mena, Marino M. \nDe Guzman, Dean Raul P.  ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(610, 'E2-0610AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1983, January 3) An assessment of the direct admission of freshmen at the College of Engineering ', 'This is in connection with the direct admission of freshmen at the College of Engineering which was started last June, 1982. It will be recalled that the College of Engineering is one of the professional schools which participated in trying the effectiveness of the policy with regards to the direct admission of freshmen. An assessment of our experience is hereby being submitted for the purpose of identifying some problem areas which were encountered and recommending solutions to these problems. \nFirst of all, the assessment of the experiment\'s success or failure has to be made within the context of the objectives. I recall that the primary objective of the experiment is to decongest the registration at the College of Arts and Sciences and thus, reducing the difficulties encountered by the students during the registration period. Against this background, permit me to review the registration procedure for freshmen as applied during the first and second semesters of academic year 1982-83 and to identify the problems that were encountered during the registration process. Attached herewith is the flow chart for freshmen registration. \nProblems : \n1. It will be noted that it takes at least three (3) days for a freshman to complete his registration. Two (2) days are during the advanced registration period,a dn at least one (1) day during the regular registration period. \n2. The registrants get Form 5 (Long Form) only during the regular registration period. Yet some were told upon enlistment in CMT that the Long Form 5 is required. \n3. Those on free schedule go back to their advisers in engineering when the sections are closed. Yet the engineering advisers do not have the information on what sections are still open. Thus, the students have to go back and forth from CAS to Engineering. \n4. There were many who would take the free schedule than the blocks. \n5. The advisers assigned for freshmen have longer registration assignments because of the advanced registration. \nRecommendations :\n1. The time required for registration can be shortened through better planning and coordination. In this connection, we strongly recommend that the College of Engineering, in consultation with the Office of the Dean/Secretary and Departments concerned at the College of Arts and Sciences, prepare a reasonably good estimate of CAS subjects needed by engineering students. On the basis of this approved list of subjects, the required number of classcards will be issued to the College of Engineering through the College Secretary and the distribution of these classcards will be done at the College of Engineering. The adoption of this recommendation will very much simplify the registration process and provide the solution to the above-mentioned problems because it will mean that:\n(a) there is no need for advanced registration; \n(b) the freshmen and sophomore engineering students do not have to go to the College of Arts and Sciences for classcards except for very exceptional cases;\n(c) some of the steps in the registration process are no longer necessary which will shorten the time required for registration.\n2. Some of the engineering departments will be advised to have some engineering courses at the first and second year levels so as to decrease the demand for AS subjects at these levels.\n3. A continuing assessment of the registration process will be made for the purpose of improving the existing procedure. \nWe hope that the above recommendations merit your favorable consideration. Should you wish to discuss this with our staff in person, we would be very glad to meet with you and to discuss these problems which I am sure are of common interest. ', 'Angangco, Dean Ofelia R. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(611, 'E2-0611AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1983, August 31) Comments on the proposed guidelines by the Diliman University Council Committee on', 'In response to your memorandum dated 1 August 1983, I am pleased to submit hereunder some comments on the above subject matter which were suggested during the College Executive meeting held this afternoon.\nI. On Item 1 : Principles\nII. On Item 4 : Procedures', 'Mena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(612, 'E2-0612AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1983, September 28) Proposed donation of an IBM 370 Model 138 computer system. ', 'This letter is with regards to the proposed donation of an IBM 370 Model 138 computer system. This proposal has been discussed on a preliminary basis by your people and our representatives.\nThis serves to confirm our interest in the proposed donation of the computer system to the U.P. College of Engineering by your organization. On our part we are willing to assist in securing a favorable tax credits for your corporation as a result of the proposed donation. ', 'Mena, Marino M. \nEstuar, Dr. Fiorello R. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(613, 'E2-0613AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, January 23) Curricular matters approved by the faculty of the College of Engineering', 'I have the honor to recommend for approval by the University Council the following curricular matters approved by the faculty of the College of Engineering at its 241st meeting held on January 18, 1984 : \n(1) Proposed revised five-year curriculum leading to the degree of Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering, including the institution, revisions and abolition of undergraduate courses for this program (Annex \"A\").\n(2) Institution, revisions and abolition of graduate courses in Electrical Engineering (Annex \"A\" also).\n(3) Proposed revised five-year curriculum leading to the degree of Bachelor of Science in Industrial Engineering, including the institution, revisions and abolition of undergraduate courses for this progrma (Annex \"B\").\n(4) Proposed institution of a Diploma Program in Industrial Engineering, including the institution of new courses for this program (Annex \"B\" also).\n(5) Proposed revised curriculum for the masteral program in Industrial Engineering, including the institution, revisions and abolition of graduate courses (Annex \"B\" also).\n(6) Proposed revised five-year curriculum leading to the degree of Bachelor of Science in Metallurgical Engineering, including the institution, revisions and abolition of undergraduate courses for this program (Annex \"C\").\n(7) Proposed revised five-year curriculum leading to the degree of Bachelor of Science in Mining Engineering, including the institution, revisions and abolition of undergraduate courses for this program (Annex \"D\").\n(8) Proposed institution of a masteral program in Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering, including the institution of graduate courses needed in the program (Annex \"E\").\n(9) Institution of two courses in Energy Engineering : Energy 101 and Energy 197 (Annex \"F\").\n(10) Change in prerequisite in E.S. 26 and C.S. 51 (Annex \"F\" also). ', 'Mena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(614, 'E2-0614AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, June 28) Recommendation of Dr. Edgardo Pacheco of the Engineering Graduate Division for an in', 'Respectfully forwarded to President Alfredo L. Juinio, U.P. Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc., the attached recommendation of Dr. Edgardo Pacheco of the Engineering Graduate Division for an increase in the stipend of the UPERDFI graduate fellows in engineering from P700/month to P900/month effective July 1, 1984, recommending favorable consideration.\nThe following are UPERDFI graduate fellows :\n1. Ruth Concepcion Dellota, MS (Energy Engg)\n2. Bernardo Lejano, MS (CE)\n3. Enrique Medina, MS (CE)\n4. Lizardo Remojo, MS (CE) \nThe increase, if granted, will therefore involve an additional amount of P800/month or P9,600/year for the four fellows. ', 'Mena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(615, 'E2-0615AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, July 17) Functions of Committees in the College of Engineering \n(1) College Committee on Rese', 'As per your telephone call this morning, I am pleased to send herewith the functions of some of the Committees in the College of Engineering. This is in connection with the credit load that could be given to faculty members serving in said committees. ', 'Lee, Emeteria \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(616, 'E2-0616AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, July 19) Opinion Poll on the Academic Community\'s Perceptions of the University ', 'This is in response to your Memorandum No. 10 dated July 17, 1984 requesting us to identify the respondents from our unit in connection with the above-mentioned opinion poll. ', 'Tabujara, Chancellor Ernesto G. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(617, 'E2-0617AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, August 9) Research Planning Workshop', 'This has reference to your letter dated August 3, 1984 regarding the Research Planning Workshop on 7-8 September 1984. I nominate the following as the official representatives of the College of Engineering :\n1. Dr. Rogelio A. Panlasigui\nChairman, College Committee on Research and Publications\n2. Professor Nestor O. Rañeses\nMember, College Committee on Research and Publications ', 'Cortes, Vice-Chancellor Irene R. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(618, 'E2-0618AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, August 9)  Requesting for data on local and foreign linkages', 'In response to your Memorandum requesting for data on local and foreign linkages, we are pleased to inform you of the following linkages of the College of Engineering :\nI. Local\n1. Philippine Council for Industry and Energy Research and Development (PCIERD)\n2. Bureau of Energy Development (BED), Ministry of Energy\n3. Energy Research and Development Center of the Philippine National Oil Corporation\n4. U.P. Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. \nII. Foreign \n1. Founding Member of AEESEA, an Association of Engineering Education in Southeast Asia\n2. Member of UNESCO Regional Network on Appropriate Technology for Rural Development\n3. Member of International Cooperative Program for Energy Planning and Management\n4. UNDP\n5. UNESCO\n6. University of Wisconsin, U.S.A.', 'Marquez-Malixi, Josephine \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(619, 'E2-0619AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, August 30) Engineering catalogue which contains the Industrial Engineering Program', 'This is in response to your letter dated today requesting for a copy of the Industrial Engineering Program and inviting us to your next meeting on October 8, 1984. \nWe are pleased to send you herewith a copy of our engineering catalogue which contains the Industrial Engineering Program. Please also find enclosed in the catalogue the recent changes in the curriculum which was approved in the last meeting of the Diliman University Council.\nAs mentioned to you by Professor Escoto, Sr., students in our other engineering programs enroll in some Industrial Engineering courses either as a requirement or part of their electives. For example, the B.S. Mechanical Engineering program requires I.E. 31 (Industrial Organization and Management) as a fifth year subject. In the case of the B.S. Civil Engineering program, one of the required courses is a C.E. 24 (Construction Planning and Management). ', 'De Guzman, Mr. Raul P.\nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(620, 'E2-0620AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, October 31) Curricular matter approved by the faculty of the College of Engineering', 'I have the honor to recommend for approval by the University Council the following curricular matter approved by the faculty of the College of Engineering at its 244th meeting held on October 30, 1984 : \nThe proposed revised five-year curriculum leading to the degree of Bachelor of Science (Chemical Engineering), including the institution, revision, and abolition of courses (see attached).\nSimultaneously we are forwarding sufficient number of copies of the attached papers to Dr. Edgardo S. Pacheco, who is the chairman of the cluster on Science and Technology (Cluster \"C\").', 'Mena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(621, 'E2-0621AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, November 14) Comments on the Proposed B.S. Ch.E. Curriculum at UPLB (submitted by the UP Ch.E', 'Respectfully returned to Vice-President Cortes, the attached proposal to institute a B.S. Chemical Engineering at U.P. Los Baños, indorsing the attached comments and recommendations of our staff in the Department of Chemical Engineering. ', 'Mena, Marino M. \nCortez, Irene R. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(622, 'E2-0622AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, December 14) Attached communication from Mr. Alfonso V. Casimiro of Construction Manpower Dev', 'We welcome Mr. Casimiro\'s suggestion for a meeting for the purpose of discussing their programs for construction project managers and how these programs could relate to our academic programs in civil engineering. Certainly, such a dialogue could provide inputs to the upgrading of our academic programs. We can suggest a meeting during the second or third week of January, 1985. \nProfessor Felisberto G. L. Reyes and Professor Ulpiano Ignacio, Jr. of our Department of Civil Engineering can be invited to the meeting. I am willing to join them, if necessary. If you are available, your presence would be most desirable.\nAlso in our reply, we may inform them that the present curriculum in civil engineering, undergraduate and graduate, recognizes the importance of construction planning and management. The following are existing courses in our program.\nUndergraduate Level\nGraduate Level', 'Tabujara, Dr. Ernesto G. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(623, 'E2-0623AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, February 7) Nominate Dr. Edgardo S. Pacheco, Director of the Graduate Division in the College', 'I have the honor to nominate Dr. Edgardo S. Pacheco, Director of the Graduate Division in the College of Engineering, as a participant to the 23rd Annual National Conference of the Philippine Association for Graduate Educaiton which will be held on February 18-20, 1985, at the National Teachers\' College. \nThe College is willing to provide for Dr. Pacheco\'s expenses chargeable against our college budget. ', 'Arcellana, Dean Emerenciana Y.\nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(624, 'E2-0624AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, February 11) 1st Indorsement \nDr. Wilfredo I. Jose and Dr. Rogelio A. Panlasigui, Chairman an', 'Respectfully forwarded to Chancellor Ernesto G. Tabujara, through the Vice-Chancellor for Administration, University of the Philippines, recommending approval of the following : \n1. Thar Dr. Wilfredo I. Jose and Dr. Rogelio A. Panlasigui, Chairman and Professor of Chemical Engineering respectively, be allowed to participate on official time in the 46th Annual Convention of the Philippine Institute of Chemical Engineers on February 15-16, 1985;\n2. That their registration fee of P600 per participant be defrayed by the College of Engineering chargeable against its 1985 budget. \nOne of the responsibilities of engineering education is to supply the engineering profession with graduates who are able at graduation to perform satisfactorily the tasks of an engineering organization. This responsibility can be best performed through a continuing dialogue by our faculty with the members of the profession. It is for this reason that we are recommending the above-mentioned faculty members\' participation. ', 'Mena, Marino M.', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(625, 'E2-0625AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, February 20) Comments on the Proposed General Education Program ', 'Pursuant to your Memorandum No. 05 dated 1 February 1985, please be informed that the proposed General Education Program was discussed by the faculty of the College of Engineering during its meeting last 14 February 1985. It was agreed that the College of Executive Committee formulate our comments and recommendations on the basis of the discussion that transpired in said meeting and after further consultation with the faculty at the departmental level, the College Executive Committee hereby submits its recommendation as agreed upon during its meeting this morning. ', 'Tabujara, Chancellor Ernesto G. \nMena, Marino M. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(626, 'E2-0626AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, April 15) Proposed Programs in Construction Management ', 'As per agreement during our meeting this morning, I am pleased to send herewith a tentative list of courses that can be instituted to strengthen our undergraduate as well as graduate programs in civil engineering and thus, including construction management as a field of specialization. The topics included in these courses were based on the list that your Office furnished us. Some of these courses could also be taken as electives in the other engineering programs. Also attached is a copy of our admission policies and degree requirements in our Graduate Division. \nWith regards to the offering of short courses for practising engineers, this is one of the major activities of the National Engineering Center, University of the Philippines. I suggest that you communicate with Dr. Leopoldo V. Abis, Executive Director of the Center for the possibility of developing continuing education programs in the field of construction management.\nPlease accept our appreciation for initiating the dialogue with the construction industry. It is only through this continuing dialogue that we may be able to update our academic programs to meet the needs of industry. ', 'Mena, Marino M.\nCasimiro, Alfonso B. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(627, 'E2-0627AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2002, April 2) Volume 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5 of my \"Thoughts of Wisdom\"', 'I have an engineer friend who said to me : \"The place in the college where I stayed most is the Engineering Library.\" This is perhaps true to many of our students. \nIt is an old saying that it is not so much to know as to know what and where to find. The library is the first that usually comes to mind when one is confronted with the problem of where to find. It has been said that all that man has thought, all that man has done, the experience that has been bought with the sufferings of 3 hundred generations - al are garnered up for us in the world of books. \nI am pleased to share with you and the users of the Engineering Library these five volumes of my thoughts. You may be interested to read what I wrote on page 13 of Volume 3 on \"Engineering Library : Its Role\". The five volumes are : \nVolume 1 : Values of Life\nVolume 2 : Education : The Key to Succcess\nVolume 3 : Education and The Engineering Profession\nVolume 4 : Mathematics : Its Usefulness in Our Day to Day Living and in Engineering\nVolume 5 : Jokes and Lessons in Engineering Education', 'Mena, Marino M. \nGranda, Yolanda C. ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
