(892, 'E2-0892AC', '27', 'UP COE Technical Bulletin, Vol. 1, Number 1 (3 copies)', 'National Engineering Center ', 'U.P. Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. for the National Engineering Center ', 'March 2004', 'A Structured Approach to Designing the Balanced Scorecard : A Case Study by A.B.D. Siriban-Manalang\n\nFilipino Phoneme Recognition Trained on the Filipino Speech Corpus & TIMIT by R.C.L. Guevara\n\nPerformance of Code Position Modulation for 2.4 GHZ IEEE 802.15.4 PHY in Indoor Multipath Channels by J.S. Marciano, Jr.\n\nShort-Term Load Forecasting Using Holt-Winter\'s Method and Kalman Filtering by A.C. Nerves\n\nVideophotometric Velocimeter Using Temporal Cross-correlation by L.G. Sison', 'Technical Paper', 'A Structured Approach to Designing the Balanced Scorecard : A Case Study by Anna Bella D. Siriban-Ma', 'This paper presents a structured approach and methodology that uses the identity and business framework of the organization for the design of a balanced scorecard. It defines a sequential structured approach which starts from analyzing the entity with respect to its environment and multi-customer linkages in order to create a holistic integrative performance measure for the organization. It is applied to a system classified under the information technology industry which services multiple client companies belonging to another industry. \nThe process starts with the company recognizing its need for a holistic integrative approach to determining a performance measurement system that will show the status of strategies and goals achievement. The company reports regularly to higher members of the organization about its organization for the past period just completed. In one of its strategic planning sessions with its top management, the leaders of the company through the assistance of this consultant pinpointed the appropriateness of Kaplan and Norton\'s Balanced Scorecard approach to performance management. The paper progresses by transforming the qualitative measures in the initial design of the scorecard into quantitative indicators that can be monitored continously. The study concludes by identifying the targetrs and weights for each indicator. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(893, 'E2-0893AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Filipino Phoneme Recognition Trained on the Filipino Speech Corpus & TIMIT by Rowena Cristina L. Gue', 'This paper describes the experiments and results in the phoneme recognition of the Filipino Speech Corpus (FSC) using three sets of training data : TIMIT, FSC and TIMIT plus FSC. Multi-Layer Perceptrons (MLPs) were trained on these three sets of data. The resulting MLP weights were used to compute the corresponding phone posterior probability of speech samples from the FSC and TIMIT. Using three sets of language models, phone models and phone a priori probability, a Start Synchronous decoder was used to align the phones from the posterior probability. A comparison of the cross validation accuracy of the MLP training with the resulting phoneme recognition rates leads to two important conclusions about the development of a bilingual speech recognition system. First, the acoustic model of TIMIT plus FSC may be derived from a simple combination of the training data from the two corpora. Second, the language model of TIMIT plus FSC is not a simple combination of the language models of the two corpora. ', 'Bilingual speech recognition\nFilipino speech corpus\nMultilayer perceptrons\nStart-synchronous decoder\nPhoneme recognition', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(894, 'E2-0894AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Performance of Code Position Modulation for 2.4GHz IEEE 802.15.4 PHY in Indorr Multipath Channels by', 'This paper provides an introduction to the IEEE 802.15.4 standard, which specifies the physical (PHY) and medium access control (MAC) layers of low bit-rate wireless personal area networking (LR-WPAN) communication systems. We also present results of simulations representing our initial efforts in characterizing the performance of the physical layer (PHY) of the IEEE 802.15.4 Wireless Personal Area Network (WPAN) Standard in a wireless channel characterized by multipath propagation and additive white Gaussian noise (AWGN). In particular, the studies are conducted on the 2.4 GHz PHY, which specifies code position modulation (CPM) to achieve spectrum spreading of a maximum 250kbps data over a transmission bandwidth of 2MHz. A simple code correction technique using a look-up table was implemented at the receiver and the bit error rate (BER) is calculated for the JTC residential, commercial and office multipath propagation models. The results indicate that CPM provides a performance gain of between 4-11dB over conventional narrowband signaling at moderate signal-to-noise-ratio-per-bit levels. \nWe also present a summary of development activities conducted at the Communications Engineering Laboratory (CEL) of the Department of Electrical and Electronics Engineering of the University of the Philippines Diliman (UP EEE) in the area of LR-WPAN.', '802.15.4\nMultipath propagation\nWPAN\nZigbee', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(895, 'E2-0895AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Short-Term Load Forecasting Using Holt-Winter\'s Method and Kalman Filtering by Allan C. Nerves ', 'A comparative study of two methods for short-term forecasting of substation load is presented. Holt-Winter\'s method predicts the load using a weighted average of past load values that decrease exponentially with time. The Kalman filtering method with fading-memory implements a two-stage forecast where a first-stage mean is first determine and a second-stage correction is applied in real time using the forecast errors from the early hours of the day. Two years of hourly load data for an 110 kV substation are used to develop and test the forecasting models for the two methods. The performance of each method is evaluated using mean absolute error, mean absolute percent error, and mean square error. ', 'Exponential smoothing\nKalman filtering\nLoad forecasting\nSubstation load ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(896, 'E2-0896AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Videophotometric Velocimeter Using Temporal Cross-correlation by Luis G. Sison, Ph.D.', 'Frame-by-frame analysis is the most established and accurate technique for measuring blood flow in microcirculation using videophotometry. Automated analysis software such as Capiflow, which are based on temporal cross-correlation, have been shown to have no significant difference in mesured velocity compared to frame-by-frame analysis. However, these comparative studies did not investigate the causes and modes of possible failure in the temporal cross-correlation algorithm, nor did they study the effect of gross subject motion. In this first of a series of reports, we show that the temporal cross-correlation algorithm applied to single-point intensities typically yield errors  of less than 3 frames. However, significant error may result when the intensity history does not have significant variation during the time periods of interest, or when there is a significant background difference between the selected start and end points. ', 'Digital image processing\nMicrocirculation\nVelocimeter\nVideophotometry', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(897, 'E2-0897AC', '', 'UP COE Technical Bulletin, Vol. 1, Number 2', 'National Engineering Center ', 'U.P. Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. for the National Engineering Center ', 'September 2004', 'A Familiarization with Gold and the Jewelry Metals by E. Dlp. Clemente\n\nE-wastes in the Philippines : Issues and Measures by G.L. Peralta\n\nFilipino Word Recognition Using a Medium-Sized Dictionary by R.C.L. Guevara\n\nGIS and Multi-Agent Systems for Interactive Design of Policy in Natural Resource Management by R. Gonzalez, A. Mottet, S. Ladet, et. al. \n\nStrain Profile Effects on the Time Rate of Consolidation Settlements by M.A.H. Zarco', 'Technical Paper', 'A Familiarization With Gold and the Jewelry Metals by Eligia Dela Paz Clemente ', 'Traditionally, gold has been known for its use as a jewelry metal and has placed second to copper in importance as ornament only because of its cost and relative rarity. Aside from these two metals, however, platinum, silver, and nickel have also been identified in jewelries and ornaments. This paper aims to familiarize the reader with the different properties of each of the metal mentioned as well as alloys of gold commonly used in making jewelry. A short description of how gold is refined as well as the common analytical techniques for determining the amount of gold in jewelry is also included. To assist in identifying the authenticity of a piece of jewelry and give an estimate of its purity in karats, a short description of the touchstone method is also included in this paper. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(898, 'E2-0898AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'E-wastes in the Philippines : Issues and Measures by Genandrialine L. Peralta ', 'The continuous dependence on electronic equipment at home and in the workplace has given rise to a new environmental challenge : electronic wastes. Electronic wastes or e-wastes refer to electronic products that no longer satisfy the needs of the initial purchaser. These can include a wide variety of goods such as computers, cellular phones, TVs, refrigerators, air conditioners, washing machines, video cameras, etc. These equipment contain hazardous materials such as lead, beryllium, mercury, cadmium, and chromium that pose both an occupational and environmental health threat. Although electronic equipment are considered safe during use, the potential for release of their toxic ingredients increase during storage or disposal. Because of the growing number of discarded electronics resulting from rapid product obsolescence, this type of waste is an emerging concern among developing countries. In the Philippines, a study estimates the current and future volume of E-wastes with focus on televisions, refrigerators, air conditioners, washing machines and radios. Data from the National Statistics Office (NSO) serve as input to a simple end-of-life model for each electronic type. Then, mathematical equations are derived incorporating other factors such as volume of electronics in use, current end-of-life management practices, serviceable years of the product and disposal behavior of consumers. The accurate estimation of E-waste generation would be useful in policy making as well as in designing an effective management scheme to avoid potential threat as health impact or environmental pollutant. Preliminary estimates show that at the end of 2004, approximately 3 million units will become obsolete and by 2010 this amount will increase 1.5 times. ', 'Electronic wastes\nE-wastes estimation\nPhilippines ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(899, 'E2-0899AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Filipino Word Recognition Using a Medium-sized Dictionary by Rowena Cristina L. Guevara ', 'This paper describes the design, implementation, testing and analysis of errors in the development of word-level recognition of the Filipino Speech Corpus (FSC) using a medium-sized dictionary. A Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) was trained on discrete utterances of the words subcorpus of the FSC. The resulting MLP weights were used to compute the corresponding phone posterior probability of discrete utterances of the test data from the FSC words subcorpus. Using a language model, phone model, dictionary and phone a priori probability, a Start Synchronous decoder was used to decode the phone posterior probability into words. Analysis of the decoded words reveals the error pattern in the recognition system. Error correction schemes are recommended for post-decoding, which may be applied to the decoder output to improve the accuracy of recognition. ', 'Speech recognition\nFilipino speech corpus\nMultilayer perceptrons\nStart-synchronous decoder\nPhoneme recognition', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(900, 'E2-0900AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'GIS and Multi-agent systems for Interactive Design of Policy in Natural Resource Management by Rhodo', 'Increased agricultural abandonment and fast-growing tree species are transforming the landscape of Villelongue, a village located in the peripheral area of the Pyrenees National Park (France). The consequences on the future of the local agro-pastoral systems, on biodiversity, on tourism, as well as the benefits that may be derived from this naturally occurring process are not yet well founded. GIS were initially created to help scientists and local policy makers bring forth images of the changed environment that they manage together. MAS modelling techniques in linking natural and social processes were further used to better understand how the changes came about and how they are inter-related. Using diagrams, scientists debated with the government\'s land planning officer about the aspects to consider in getting a better picture of the problem situation; it highlights the strengths and weaknesses of interdisciplinary efforts to inform natural resource management policy, Further directions are posed. ', 'Participatory modelling and simulation\nMountain agriculture\nLand use change\nUML diagram\nConceptual modelling\nInter-disciplinary research', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(901, 'E2-0901AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Strain profile effects on the time rate of consolidation settlements by Mark H. Zarco', 'Consolidation settlements are a major consideration in the design of structures founded on soft clays. At present, analytical procedures used to estimate the rate at which these settlements occur are limited to cases involving uniform strain conditions under constant surcharge. In this paper, two procedures that consider effects of non-uniform strain profile on the time rate of consolidation settlements due to a time-dependent load are presented. Numerical experiments performed indicate that the rates of consolidation settlement predicted by the modified methods are in better agreement with field experience when compared to current analytical methods. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(902, 'E2-0902AC', '', 'UP COE Technical Bulletin, Vol. 2, Number 1 (2 copies)', 'National Engineering Center ', 'U.P. Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. for the National Engineering Center ', 'October 2006', 'Effect of Moving Storm Rainfall on Soil Erosion and Sediment Transport from Watersheds by G. Q. Tabios, III\n\nNovel Ways of Enhancing the Properties of Natural Materials by A. V. Amorsolo, Jr. \n\nRegionalized Flood Frequency Distributions and Parameters for Philippine Rivers Using L-Moments by L. Q. Liongson\n\nRhythm-aided, Discrete-word Filipino Speech Recognition by R. C. L. Guevara\n\nTheoretical and Practical Aspects of Infiltration Gallery Planning and Design by P. M. Castro', 'Technical Paper ', 'Effect of Moving Storm Rainfall on Soil Erosion and Sediment Transport from Watersheds by Guillermo ', 'This paper presents results of a simulation study to study the effect of storm rainfall movement on soil erosion and sediment transport from watersheds. The moving storm rainfall fields are stochastically generated using a Neyman-Scott process, space-time rainfall model. This model is used to generate spatially - and temporally-varying storm rainfall fields at different speeds and directions. For the different rainfall fields generated, the amount of soil erosion from overland flow planes and amount of sediment transported in the channels are calculated using the KINEROS2 model of the Agricultural Research Service of the U.S. Department of Agriculture. The KINEROS2 model is an event oriented, physically-based model to simulate the various watershed processes especially interception, infiltration, surface runoff and erosion from overland flow planes and channels for a given storm rainfall event. Two different watershed shapes are considered : a del-shaped watershed and an elongated watershed. This study shows that there are differences in flow and sediment hydrographs at different speeds and directions of the storm rainfall movement for the two watershed shapes considered. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
INSERT INTO `records` (`id`, `accessionNo`, `boxNumber`, `title`, `placeOfPublication`, `publisher`, `dateOfPublication`, `descriptionContent`, `type`, `paper`, `abstract`, `keywords`, `filePath`, `fileName`, `accessLevel`, `status`, `dateEncoded`, `updatedAt`) VALUES
(903, 'E2-0903AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Novel ways of enhancing the properties of natural materials by Alberto V. Amorsolo, Jr. ', 'Natural materials from plant, animal and ground sources have been useful to mankind since the dawn of civilization. However, the new generation of high technology products require materials with unusual combination of properties which become harder to find in natural materials. New and novel ways to overcome this limitation are therefore being devised to either significantly enhance the properties of these natural materials or transform them into hybrid structures with the desired combination of properties. These methods make use of the usual principle of changing the material property through a change in composition and/or structure (usually done at the microscale level). However, one of the breakthrough principles in creating a radically different set of materials from existing ones lies in reducing the physical dimensions of conventional materials to the nanoscale level. The development of a reliable technology for the creation of this new generation of nanomaterials appears to be major challenge for materials scientists and engineers of this century. ', 'Enhancement\nNanomaterials\nNatural materials\nMaterial properties ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(904, 'E2-0904AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Regionalized Flood Frequency Distributions and Parameters for Philippine Rivers Using L-Moments by L', 'This paper presents the results of the application of the method of L-moment ratios to obtain the probability distribution of the annual maximum flood peaks in two water resources regions in the Philippines. The parameters of the annual maximum floods such as the mean annual flood, are expressed in terms of regression relationships with basin properties such as catchment area and other basin properties. The Generalized Extreme Value or GEV is selected as candidate model for both single-site and regional flood frequency analysis, by using the L-moment ratio diagram. The L-moment ratios are regionalized by weighted-averaging according to the length of records of stations, after observing their low correlation with drainage area. Regional growth curves, or the equation of the ratio (T-year flood/mean annual flood) versus the return period T, are afterwards derived by substituting the regional average L-moment ratios in the GEV distribution. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(905, 'E2-0905AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Rhythm-aided, Discrete-word Filipino Speech Recognition by Rowena Cristina L. Guevara ', 'Filipino speech is syllable-timed. In this paper, syllable properties, rhythm and statistics were investigated. A subcorpus of three-syllable words from the Filipino speech Corpus with 6 speakers was used as experimental data. Several approaches to improving the performance of a Filipino speech recognition system using speech rhythm are described. These approaches will be used for designing dictionaries for decoding the phone posterior probabilities, and designing the post-processing stage of the decoder output in the next discrete-word Filipino speech recognition system of the Digital Signal Processing Laboratory. ', 'Filipino speech corpus\nMultilayer perceptrons\nSpeech recognition\nStart-synchronous decoder\nSyllabic rhythm', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(906, 'E2-0906AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Theoretical and Practical Aspects of Infiltration Gallery Planning and Design by Peter M. Castro ', 'The range of yields that may be expected through wet and dry periods is initially estimated for the candidate site. Alternative layouts of gallery pipes are configured in accordance with this range of yields. A groundwater flow model is employed to obtain the expected production rate for each alternative. Promising configurations are selected for design of pipe layouts, sizes and pumping schemes. Site investigations should be comprehensive so as to avoid wasting time and resources on sites that would likely turn out infeasible. Gallery pipes in high yield sites should be designed to flow full, while in low yield sites the pipes would have free surface flow. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(907, 'E2-0907AC', '', 'UP COE Technical Bulletin : Compilation of Abstracts 2011 Professorial Chair Awards Colloquium, Vol. 3, Number 1 ', 'National Engineering Center ', 'U.P. Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. for the National Engineering Center ', 'June 2011', 'Department of Chemical Engineering ', 'Abstract', 'Projecting electronic waste generation using an AI Artificial Neural Network Approach by Florencio C', 'The demand for new technology is unmatched at any time in human history. As people yearn for a better quality of life, industries are forced to churn out dizzying arrays of electronic goods to satisfy this demand. Consequently, consumer electronics are constantly being upgraded or scrapped as a result of technological advancement. Technology turnover has been so rapid that what are considered high-tech today are at the same time already on the verge of obsolescence. This situation has led to the generation of millions of tons of so-called electronic waste, more popularly known as e-waste. These products include household appliances, ICT and other business electronic equipment, lamps, and consumer and entertainment devices. The downside of the issue is that these materials contain hundreds of different materials that are toxic and hazardous thereby making recycling risky. Effective regulation requires an accurate estimate of the amount of e-waste generated in the country on an annual basis. This has not always been possible because of deficient recording mechanisms. This study aims to demonstrate a technique to estimate the generation rate of e-waste in the country using Artificial Neural Network (ANN). The independent variables from which the ANN learns the equation include among other factors population, GNP, household income level, educational attainment and power demand. ANN used 65% of the data while the remaining 35% was used to validate the model. The validated model was then used to project future e-waste generation. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(908, 'E2-0908AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Preparation of potassium ferrate from sludge and its performance in arsenite removal 2 from water by', 'An efficient and multifunctional chemical potassium ferrate (K2FeO4) has been successfully synthesized from drinking water treatment sludge (DWTS) based on a novel method via wet chemical route. The dried sludge was a viable starting material for ferrate synthesis due to its abundance in iron as confirmed by SEM/EDS. The ability of this hexavalent iron [Fe(VI)] solution in the removal of arsenite [As(III)] from water by oxidation and the subsequent arsenate [As(V)] coagulation by its reduction product was studied. Response surface methodology (RSM) particularly IV-Optimal statistical experimental design was used to investigate the effect of Fe (VI) dose and pH to percent As(III) removal. The response function coeffcieints were obtained from experimental data and it was shown that the predicted values and experimental results were in good agreement. The highest percent As (III) removal required a Fe (VI) dose of 100.04 uM and pH of 5.19. This research showed that IV-Optimal statistical design successfully determined the optimum major operating parameters for arsenic removal and it was concluded that the synthesized Fe (VI) is a promising chemical for the remediation of arsenic from solution by oxidation and regulation. ', 'Potassium ferrate\nOxidant\nCoagulant\nDrinking water treatment sludge\nArsenic removal\nIV-Optimal statistical design ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(909, 'E2-0909AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Co-production of alternative fuels for the Philippines by Rizalinda L. de Leon, Semirara Professoria', 'A large fraction of the cost of both bioethanol and biodiesel production has been attributed to the cost of feedstock. Hence process improvements result in only marginal production cost reduction. More efficient utilization of feedstock by producing a second fuel can enable the recovery of feedstock cost. This study assesses the co-production of two alternative fuels from one feedstock. Two production processes are considered : (1) the co-production of biodiesel and bioethanol from copra and; (2) the cogeneration of bio-oil and bioethanol from sugar cane. A technology assessment is performed on each of the two production processes. This includes an assessment of the feedstock, the product market trends, technical and economic evaluation of the process, including an assessment of expected waste streams. The assessment of the feedstock involves an analysis of the alternative uses of feedstock and its supply. Product market trends are then inferred from historical consumption data of the conventional fuels that are to be substituted by the alternative fuels. This is followed by a technical evaluation of the process, particularly the calculation of mass and energy process inputs and outputs including waste streams. An economic assessment involves a total production cost estimation and profitability analysis.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(910, 'E2-0910AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Degradation of reactive yellow 145 (RY 145) dye contaminated synthetic wastewater using electro-fent', 'Conventional wastewater treatment technologies are unable to eliminate dye molecules from industrial effluents. This study demonstrates the effectiveness of electro-Fenton (EF) based AOPs to degrade Reactive Yellow 145 (RY 145) dye-containing synthetic wastewater. Effects of initial dye concentration, initial pH, H2O2 dosage, Fe2+ dosage, current density and process intensification by UV (4-UW UV lamps) and ultrasonic (20 kHz ultrasonic processor) irradiation on RY 145 removal by electro-Fenton process were investigated. A quartz cylindrical batch reactor with RuO2/IrO2-coated titanium plate electrodes was used. Maximum dye removals of 99%, 95% and 86% were obtained for sonoelectro-Fenton (SEF), EF and photoelectron-Fenton (PEF) respectively after 20 minutes with corresponding initial rates of 0.1731, 0.1448, and 0.1209 M mion-1 for 0.49 mM RY 145 dye-containing synthetic wastewater. Verification experiments of optimized parameters were in proximity with predicted values. For SEF, 99.8% RY 145 removal was achieved after 20 minutes at optimum conditions. Fast initial RY 145 degradation fit a pseudo 2nd order kinetic model. Small footprint, potential for complete degradation of target pollutant with minimum or no sludge production and short reaction time make electro-Fenton based AOPs a viable solution to the growing need for efficient treatment of dye wastewater. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(911, 'E2-0911AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'An innovative application of thermal storage for temperature regulation by Angela D. Escoto, HOLCIM ', 'This paper discusses an innovative concept of utilizing a phase change material to regulate the temperature inside automobiles parked under the sun. Preliminary characterization of the phase change material will be done. A heat rejection system will be identified for continued operation while exposed to the heat source. Initial calculations will be presented. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(912, 'E2-0912AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Generating new ideas by probing paradigms by Wilfredo I. Jose, Sy Ling Chat Professorial Chair ', 'Many techniques on creativity and innovation are available and they can generate new ideas. This paper presents a method, which I developed in the last four decades. In my first job I developed a technique in creativity, but I was unaware of the mechanism. I used the technique in my research when I transferred to UP as an instructor. Based on the term paradigm, I called my process, \"probing paradigms\". After 10 years, I found its application in formulating teaching strategies and developing innovations. I knew I had an effective method but I did not have the appropriate framework and theoretical basis. I applied the technique to researches in environment, biotechnology and biochemical engineering, energy, design engineering, and others. Starting in 2005, I developed the framework, and finally completed the necessary theoretical basis in 2009. Essentially, with this method, we probe the paradigm of a topic, an area of study, or a specific field. We systematically map them in our mind. Connecting ideas in our mind results in new ideas. We can consider our brain as a powerful neural network computer and by recycling the ideas, we can refine the selection of ideas. Some examples of the results are presented. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(913, 'E2-0913AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Methane production and anaerobic treatment of sardines and mackerel wastewater in an expanded granul', 'As most municipalities in the Philippines are coastal, fish processing industry is economically important in the country. Many fish processing plants have to deal with problems associated with their wastewater and the need to comply with effluent standards. This study explored the possibility of treating fish processing wastewater using a high-rate system that produces energy in the form of methane gas. Fish processing wastewater contains high amounts of proteins and lipids, which are present as suspended solids. The results of this study showed that the hydrolysis of the particulate lipids is rate-limiting while that of proteins is relatively fast. For an influent wastewater containing about 4,000 mg/L total COD treated at 6 h hydraulic retention time (HR) and 16 kg/m-3 .d-1 COD loading rate in a one-phase expanded granular sludge bed (EGSB) reactor, 90% COD removal and 44% COD conversion to methane were achieved. In a two-phase EGSB reactor system operated at the same HRT and COD loading rate, 98% COD removal and 48% COD conversion to methane were achieved. A large part (46-50% of the influent COD was removed by adsorption to reactor surfaces and sludge particles. Thus, the hydrolysis of the particulate COD in the system must be optimized. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(914, 'E2-0914AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Department of Computer Science ', 'Abstract ', 'Some issues in distributed computation in natural computing with membranres by Henry N. Adorna, Alex', 'Membrane Computing is an unconventional computing paradigm introduced in the year 1998 by Gh. Paun. Associated with Membrane Computing is the computing model called P Systems. This computing model abstracts the functioning of a living cell, which could be single cell, or organized in tissues, organs or other types of cell population. In general, the internal compartmentalization which are hierarchically arranged plays a key role in the computation. This computing model performs computations in non-deterministic and (maximally) parallel manner. There are different variants of P Systems already introduced in the literature, since the year 1998. Surprisingly, the so-called hard problems in conventional computations, that is, via Turing machines is at most polynomially solvable (in time) at the expense of space by some appropriate P Systems. This model of computation attracts lots of attention from computing scientists. This paper considered a so-called distributed P Systems (dP Systems). dP Systems consists of at least two (2) P Systems communicating in order to perform a job. We discussed measures of complexity with respect to communication performed by the model in solving problem. Finally, a possibility for the computing model to be implemented in silico is proposed. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(915, 'E2-0915AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Minimum total edge length and results on local search algorithms by Tristan M. Basa, Cerlito San Jua', 'We consider a problem relation to optimal layout designs : Given a graph G (V, E), and a fixed set of points P1 [P] = [V], on a plane, how can we map V - P such that the resulting total edge length is minimal? This problem can be considered a special case of the general problem of TOTAL EDGE LENGTH wherein we minimize the total edge length for a general graph. We prove this special case to be NP-complete and apply well-know local search heuristics on the problem.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(916, 'E2-0916AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Metaheuristics in flood disaster management and risk assessment by Vena Pearl Bongolan, Cesar A. Bue', 'A conceptual area is divided into land-use zones, each of which is allowed to evolve under a physical constraint. A risk assessment method is then used to identify the flood risk in each zone using the following risk factors : the area\'s urbanized area ratio, literacy rate, mortality rate, percent of population under poverty,. radio/tv penetration and the state of structural and non-structural measures. Vulnerability is defined as a weighted-sum of these factors. A \'penalty\' is then imposed for reduced vulnerability. Optimization comparison are done with MatLab\'s Genetic Algorithms and Simulated Annealing; results show that simulated annealing finds \'extreme\' solutions, while genetic algorithms produce more realistic designs for cities. In related research, we also explored prioritization schemes for the components of vulnerability, as well as experiments with allowing interactions between related, but independent components. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(917, 'E2-0917AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract ', 'Alternative scoring systems for the speech phoneme recognition as educational aid for the deaf and h', 'The Speech and Phoneme Recognition as an Educational Aid for the Deaf and Hearing Impaired (SPREAD) application uses the Sphinx-4 voice recognition system to analyze the vocalization of the student and provide prompt feedback on their pronunciation. The packaging of the application as interactive game aims to provide additional motivation for the deaf and hearing impaired student through visual motivation for them to learn and appreciate speech. However, the scoring system of the application produced very low scores even on nearly accurate pronunciations. This paper will explore the reasons for this problem and will attempt to test alternative scoring systems in order to provide a more accurate assessment of the child\'s performance. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(918, 'E2-0918AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'A proposed database re-design for the University of the Philippines databases for open data access b', 'Access to data is an integral part of any research activity. The University of the Philippines, as an academic institution, collected data, e.g. grades, class size, case studies. etc., that should be openly available, i.e., no permission needed, for researchers, both from within the university or otherwise. Due to the personal nature of some types of data, access is restricted and requires to be applied for and approved. There are studies on how to anonymize these data on the database layer, i.e., K-Anonymity, on established and large databases. For relatively small databases and/or new databases, this paper proposes a re-designing of the database schema with privacy and open access in mind. As an example, the paper uses a standard student records database schema and presents way to introduce open access whilst preserving the privacy of the student. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(919, 'E2-0919AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Challenges and lessons in bridging the digital divide by Cedric Angelo M. Festin, Dado Maria and Ban', 'The Internet has been shown as an important tool for enhancing learning. The Philippines has not fully utilized this tool for varying reasons. Although Internet connectivity in the country has become more available, this is more true for urban areas. Access to affordable computers is also an issue. There is also the lack of a stable and affordable power supply for these computers. Moreover, the Internet is a relatively new medium that could be hard to navigate for those unfamiliar with it. We present our work that seeks to address two issues directly : access to affordable computers and assistance in navigating the Internet. Instead of using conventional desktop computers, we made use of thin clients. Aside from cost reduction, the use of thin clients also indirectly address the power issue. To address the second issue, we focus on the activity of using the Internet to augment formal learning, particularly for grade school Science and Mathematics education. With the assistance of the University of the Philippines NISMED, we have designed a framework that encompasses the classification and presentation of e-learning materials. We present the design and prototype of this framework and the challenges and lessons encountered in the process. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(920, 'E2-0920AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Practical challenges in developing secure real-time streaming for mobile devices by Susan P. Festin,', 'Mobile devices have increasingly become more ubiquitous, We have also seen an increase in the types of applications that are being developed for these devices. These devices have transcended their original function as telephones and are now also used as small and portable computers. Securing mobile applications present the challenge of optimizing the still limited (compared to desktop computers) computational, storage and power on mobile devices. Thus, security primitives for encryption need to be as fast and as lean as possible. \nWe present our recent work in developing a secure and real-time streaming application for two popular mobile platforms : iOS and Android. We focus on porting a new stream cipher, Rabbit, into these two platforms. Rabbit is designed to be lean and fast but since it is a new cipher, its use is still limited. Our experience has shownt that there are important challenges when developing secure applications for these platforms : openness and maturity of the platform APIs, availability of suitable codecs for audio and video, and access to lower level functions and/or hardware. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(921, 'E2-0921AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Pursuit and evasion of cubic graphs by Nestine Hope S. Hernandez, MIESCOR/Cesar Nuguid Professorial ', 'In this lecture, we discuss pursuit and evasion grame on cubic graphs. In a pursuit and evasion game, the pursuer tries to capture the evader while the evader tries to avoid capture. Cubic graphs are graphs in which all vertices have degree three, that is, exactly three edges are incident to a vertex. We consider the case where two pursuers attempt to capture the evader on a given cubic graph. All players have local visibility and pursuers can communicate with each other. We propose a winning strategy for the pursuers based on the positions of the players in the graph and the topology of their immediate neighborhood. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(922, 'E2-0922AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Analysis of human-computer interaction attributes of geographic information systems by Ligaya Leah L', 'The purpose of this study was to investigate the current advances in human-computer interaction principles utilized by geographic information system applications. A survey of human-computer interaction concepts was conducted. Identification of attributes important for GIS applications was made. The analysis focused on identifying application components and features that make the experience of mapping easy and intuitive for the users. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(923, 'E2-0923AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Folksonomy on collaborative use of rubrics on E-portfolio assessment system by Ma. Rowena C. Solamo,', 'As many people in the education sector are finding that standardized tests give little indication of what students can actually do in real world situations, they are looking at other means to assess learning of individuals. Performance-based assessment poses as an alternative which makes uses of rubrics as scoring or rating tool for products or performances. Projectrix, a cloud-based e-Portfolio Assessment System, is primarily built to collaboratively create and use rubrics as part of the learning assessment process where an online community defines links to work products and chooses people to assess them using rubrics. This research investigates the folksonomy, the resulting collective vocabulary with a focus on knowledge organization, within the collaborative use of rubrics as an alternative means to assess learning. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(924, 'E2-0924AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'On the controllability of the De St. Venant Equations by Adrian Roy L. Valdez, Beta Epsilon Professo', 'The de Sr. Venant equations are first order quasilinear hyperbolic partial differential equations modeling the flow of fluid in one-dimension. They are good at capturing the dynamics of shallow water. A main problem being addressed in this paper is if, indeed, a flow can be steered from one state to another by putting controls on the boundaries of the flow. The paper surveys current results on the main problem by looking at which states already have proven existence of boundary controls. Moreover, some numerical implementations of such controls when they exist are presented. Finally, some open problems shall be discussed. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(925, 'E2-0925AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'On the bounds of unsecured RSA secret keys by Philip Christian C. Zuniga, Marlon Bacani Professorial', 'We study in this research the bounds of RSA secret keys that make the RSA unsecured. Wiener was able to prove that if the magnitude of the secret key is less than 0.25, then the RSA is unsecured. It is conjectured that the actual bound is at 0.5. We extend in this paper Wiener\'s work, including the works of several other mathematicians to show a more extensive bound on unsecured keys, but in a special case where we assume that the factors of the RSA modulus have the same number of bits. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(926, 'E2-0926AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Electrical and Electronics Engineering Institute', 'Abstract', 'Doodletalk : a collaborative application on a mobile device over existing XMPP servers by Rowel O. A', 'The need for Internet collaboration is fueled by businesses that do not have the time and resources to transport all the needed employees located around the world to work on a project or collaborate on an idea. Current implementations of Internet collaboration are video-conferencing, VoIP conferencing and text-based document conferencing, e.g. Google Docs. Together with the recent surge of people having mobile devices with touch screens and wireless Internet access such as smartphones, a new way of collaboration on mobile devices has become our goal. We propose an approach that uses a virtual whiteboard that all collaborators can see and modify in realtime. It provides an intuitive communication medium, uses less badnwidth than video or voice conferencing and enables its users to easily communicate ideas such as design, strategy or plan. To detect the presence of other peers in the Internet we use existing XMPP servers, e,g, GoogleTalk and Facebook. It minimizes the chance of a user having to sign up and setup their contacts, increases the reachability of the user and does not require us to maintain a separate server. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(927, 'E2-0927AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract ', 'Area and performance trade-off in a viterbi error correction and detection hardware by Anastacia Bal', 'The emergence of high-speed networks for exchange, processing and storage of digital information has continuously increased the demand for efficient and reliable data transmission and storage systems. Errors in these systems cannot be avoided, and as such, error detection and correction schemes are typically employed. One of the most common of these schemes is the Viterbi algorithm. In this paper, trade-off between area and performance of different Viterbi decoder and encoder hardware is presented and analyzed. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(928, 'E2-0928AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Waveguide filters by Paul Jason R. Co, Vea Technology for All Centennial Professorial Chair Award', 'The increasing demand for broadband wireless access would translate into a huge market for microwave circuits and systems that are an integral part of these wireless communication systems. These microwave circuits are the building blocks of the backhaul systems of these broadband systems, as well as integral parts of other wireless systems such as radars and satellite communications. One of the most important microwave blocks in these communication systems is the filter. The filter is a device that is used to remove undesired signals, which would otherwise degrade the performance of our system. This research deals with the design, fabrication and characterization of filters that are operating in the X-band (8-12GHz). Operating at these microwave frequencies require specialized techniques to be applied in the design and implementation of these filters. Two waveguide filter topologies were designed and fabricated; namely the post waveguide filter and the iris waveguide filter. The designs were fabricated locally through a local metal manufacturing company and were tested in the Wireless Communications Engineering Laboratory. The fabricated fileters showed satisfactory results; with bandwidths of 3% and return losses of at least 15dB.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(929, 'E2-0929AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'A power supply aggregation model of small electric cooperatives in the Philippine restructured power', 'The Electric Power Industry Reform Act of 2001 (R.A. 9136) also known as the EPIRA law has restructured the Philippine power industry into functionality unbundled units. The EPIRA law mandates the establishment of a competitive generation and supply sectors and to strengthen the regulation of franchised transmission and distribution utilities in order to ensure the security of power supply and to reduce the power cost to consumers. After ten years of implementation, there is no sign that the objectives of law will be achieved. This study has analyzed the behavior of the generation companies and distribution utilities in the Philippines in bilateral power supply contracting and their participation in the wholesale spot market to determine the reasons why the energy security objective of the law was not achieved. A new model of power supply aggregation of small distribution utilities in a restructured power industry was developed to solve the power supply security problem which will also achieve the least-cost objectives of the EPIRA law. The aggregation model is implemented in 21 Electric Cooperatives in Mindanao Grid. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(930, 'E2-0930AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Multilevel extension of parallel sequence spread spectrum modulation scheme for high-speed rural poi', 'A technique utilizing a multilevel extension of Parallel Sequence Spread Spectrum (PSSS) for high spectral efficiency communications is presented. It is capable of achieving spectral efficiencies of up to 12 bits/s/Hz; hence a data rate of 1 Gbps over a single carrier is possible by using the whole 84.5 MHz bandwidth of the 2.4 GHz Wi-Fi band. It is intended for line-of-sight, rural backhaul applications where heavy multipath is not a primary consideration. We show the results of simulation and the subsequent implementation of the technique in actual hardware using a flexible Software-Defined Radio platform. The simulated and actual measurement results show a peak-to-average power ratio of 7.66 dB and a bit error rate (BER) performance close to that of 4096-QAM in an AWGN channel. Unlike QAM, however, the use of multi-level PSSS allows the bit rate to be readily scaled down in situations where the BER is too high. Established links can also be easily extended to point-to-multipoint without a significant increase in complexity. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(931, 'E2-0931AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Risk assessment of supplier bidding strategies in electricity markets by Allan C. Nerves, NAPOCOR Pr', 'A methodology is developed to quantify the financial risk for a multi-unit generation company with bilateral contracts in a competitive electricity market, using Value-at-Risk as a risk measure. A Monte Carlo simulation technique is used to calculate the Value-at-Risk by modeling different pricing scenarios, bids and schedules of generation. An artificial neural network is used to forecast hourly market prices which determine generating unit schedules through a price-based unit commitment method using a genetic algorithm approach. An economic dispatch then determines local generation and purchase schedules using a linear programming solution. The profit and loss distribution that is obtained from the Monte Carlo simulations becomes the basis for Value-at-Risk calculations. Bidding strategies are formulated from a sensitivity analysis of the Value-at-Risk for various market conditions. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(932, 'E2-0932AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Solar charge controller for group PCS by Manuel C. Ramos Jr. Dado and Maria Banatao Institute Profes', 'The use of solar power in rural areas is getting increasingly common nowadays. With a simple solar power system basically consisting of solar panels, batteries, and the load, it is relatively easy to setup and use solar energy to power lights, computers, and other electrically powered equipment. However, simple solar power systems are usually inefficient, i.e., they do not make full use of available solar energy. In some cases, lifetime of batteries are compromised making such systems economically inefficient. To address the shortcomings of simple solar power systems, we propose a smart solar charge controller to manage the system. Our system is designed to power personal computers and associated peripheral with the end goal of providing a completely solar powered networked classroom. Among the novel features of the smart solar charge controller are battery management with SOC tracking, high voltage DC bus, integrated DC bus communications and USB interface to the client computers. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(933, 'E2-0933AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'An integrated development environment for dual-core ARM7 architecture by Joy Alinda Reyes-Madamba, M', 'Embedded systems today are targeting high performance computing with low power consumption to satisfy the growing needs of users. The latest technique found in these designs use multi-core technology on embedded processors, such as the ARM7. To fully utilize the capability of dual-core ARM7 processors, software tools such as compilers and assemblers are designed specifically to transform high-level language applications to run efficiently in the target processors. These tools are also used to help ARM7 designers in formulating new techniques to further improve the performance of their processors. In this research, an integrated development environment (IDE) uses a compiler-assembler for the dual-core ARM7 architecture for runtime memory simulations. It allows selective optimization to aid a processor designer in determining high-level algorithms that would take advantage of the dual-core ARM7 architecture', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(934, 'E2-0934AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Entrepreneurship and engineering education technology by Luis G. Sison, Globe Telecom Inc. Professor', 'Entrepreneurship is widely acknowledged to be one of the major engines for growth and innovation. With companies like Apple and Facebook in the limelight, policy makers are trying to replicate the success of Silicon Valley but tend to focus more on the industrial policy side of development while ignoring the role of the technopreneurial culture. Despite UP Diliman\'s leadership in R&D (measured in terms of publications, personnel, and funding), many of our graduates, even in engineering, typically prefer to enter the profession through established technology companies, especially multinational corporations, leading to a discontinuity of technology transfer from the lab to industry. To encourage more students to be entrepreneurs, the campus has initiated different forms of support, including : participation in business plan competitions technology boot camps, technopreneurship classes, student events and contests such as the Engineering Marketing Congress; the campus technology business incubators : UP-Ayala TBI, Techportal at the UP-Ayala TechnoHub, and Open TBI, and the pre-incubation program at the DOST-UP Enterprise Center for Technopreneurship. In this work, we look at the impact of these initiatives and related factors, focusing on the startups in the TBI\'s and pre-incubation centers on campus. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(935, 'E2-0935AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'System for classroom scheduling by Tyrone W. Tai, Don Felipe Say and Therese Chua Say Professorial C', 'Classroom scheduling is one of the more tedious tasks at the start of the semester. This involves arranging classes, room usage, faculty loads and possibly student hours subject to constraints and limitations. Poor scheduling often lead to load imbalance and class conflict/unavailability for students. As the department/institute expands its scope and capacity, the more complicated the task becomes. Studies have shown that a deterministic method for arriving at an optimal solution is not feasible due to the large number of parameters. This system aims to assist class schedulers by interpreting and presenting relevant information in a timely manner. Inputs to the system include room information, course information, faculty information, and student course demands. Features include room/faculty conflict notification, detection of common availability, as well as current faculty load. Schedule will be tested by simulating. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(936, 'E2-0936AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Detection of millimeter movements using ultrasonic ranging and precise time synchronization in wirel', 'High accuracy movement detection is useful in many applications. One possible application is for landslide monitoring and prediction. Small movements in the millimeter range on a slope\'s surface are known to occur before an impending landslide. Observation of these millimeter movements at the soil surface is crucial for proper characterization of a landslide event. In this work, we developed a wireless sensor network platform that detects two-dimensional movements with sub-millimeter accuracy in a controlled environment. This was achieved through the use of omni-directional ultrasonic ranging, cross-correlation of ultrasonic pulses, and precise time synchronization between sensor nodes. The synchronization protocol is based on IEEE 1588, which was optimized for implementation in a wireless sensor network. Our experiment results show that the sensor node clocks can maintain worst-case synchronization error of at most one microsecond relative to the reference clock. This enables the system to detect movements with sub-millimeter accuracy, with initial distances of up to two meters between sensor nodes. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(937, 'E2-0937AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Department of Geodetic Engineering ', 'Abstract ', 'Characterization of submarine groundwater discharge dynamics using radon monitoring and electrical r', 'Significant amounts of nutrients can be delivered to the coastal waters through submarine groundwater discharge (SGD), threatening coral reefs. The dynamics of SGD must be well characterized to be able to adequately quantify loading of nutrients and contaminants. For this purpose, radon (222Rn) monitoring and electrical resistivity tomography (ERT) were utilized in Bolinao, Pangasinan and in Puerto Galera, Oriental Mindoro. In Puerto Galera Bay, radon inventory was monitored in 2 coves to estimate SGD rates. Measurements at a distance of about 100 meters from the shore yielded an average Rn concentration of 19 Bq/m3, with maximum of 39 Bq/m3 and minimum of 5 Bq/m3 during low tide and high tide, respectively. Based on one-day continuous radon measurement at two coves of the bay, groundwater flux in the range of 0.5-2.0 cm/hour. In Bolinao, time-lapse shore-parallel and shore-perpendicular ERT transect surveys were conducted to identify seepage zones. Continuous radon monitoring was simultaneously made in order to estimate SGD rates. These measurements were then compared against each other to examine the possibility of estimating groundwater flux from ERT measurements alone. Shore-parallel ER profiles showed the occurence of groundwater seepage at several areas during low tide only. On the other hand, the shore-perpendicular ER profiles showed that SGD mainly occurs at the beach-near shore reef interface. Increases in radon inventories corresponded well with higher increases in ER values. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(938, 'E2-0938AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Land valuation using spatial-based support system by Florence A. Galeon, SR Metals Inc. Professorial', 'Professional valuers until now perform land valuation based on their intuition and experiences. A technique of valuing land more logically and quantitatively can be introduced to reduce the subjectivity. This paper envisions the development of a spatial-based support system to enhance and hasten the ferreting out of land values using the Direct Market Comparison Approach. A mathematical model developed using Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP) and Goal Programming (GP) was utilized for calculation. Land value factors from literature and surveys of valuation specialists determine the significant parameters of the model. Flood Risk is added as one of the major parameters for this study. Spatial data are gathered and incorporated in a Geographic Information System (GIS) platform. This valuation method is tested to determine the land values of the informal settlement areas within the University of the Philippines Visayas Cebu Campus (UPVCC). The 13 hectares informal settlement areas are digitized from a high resolution QuickBird satellite image. Analysis tools in GIS are used to approximate the shapes of land parcels from Thiessen polygons. Initial samples gathered for validation show promising results, that at 95% CI, there is no significant difference between the system-generated values and the expert-determined values. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(939, 'E2-0939AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Potential impact of tectonic motion on PRS92-Linked Cadastral Surveys by Epifanio D. Lopez, Felipe F', 'The Philippine Archipelago, also known as the Philippine Mobile Belt (PMB) in the field of geology, is subjected to complex tectonic plate deformation processes along its western and eastern boundary zones. In the east, the Philippine Sea Plate subducts the PMB in an oblique west-northwesterly direction; while in the west, the Eurasia-Sundaland crustal block subducts the PMB in an easterly direction. Extensive collaborative plate convergence researches using Global Positioning Systems, such as the Geodynamics of South and Southeast Asia (GEODYSSEA) Project, have established that these crustal plate boundary convergence processes have been absorbed by the Philippine Trench/East Luzon Trench and the Manila Trench, respectively. Furthermore, the subduction processes have resulted in accumulated strain and movement along the left-lateral strike-slip Philippine Fault Zone (PFZ), extending for about 1200 km from northwest Luzon to eastern Mindanao. An analysis of the potential impact of the PFZ slip rate of ~2.5 cm/year (Aurelio et al, 1997; Barrier et al., 1991; Duquesnoy et al., 1994) on positioning accuracies in the Philippine Reference System of 1992 (PRS92) and PRS92-linked cadastral survey projects located along, or in the immediate vicinity of, the PFZ is the major objective of this study. Preliminary results of the effect of tectonic motion on the proposed PRS92 upgrade to zero-order accuracy (1:1,000,000) and densification within the International Terrestrial Reference Framework (ITRF) are also presented. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(940, 'E2-0940AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Reducing heterogeneity in environmental and natural resources (ENR) data layers - a case study of Ph', 'Science and engineering projects and researches rely on scientific data collected from different sources and context. In order to successfully utilize these data, investigators need to effectively access, decode, organize and interpret existing data to their process and methodology. The seriousness of these steps in data handling has varying levels of risk to the result of the process and thus to the community. Errors in data use and interpretation can be rooted from syntactic and semantic heterogeneity in data from different sources. The study focuses on reviewing the different data layers created and published by different national government agencies producing ENR datasets. In order to integrate these data layers, heterogeneity problems should be addressed. Two main tasks were performed to reduce complexities of these datasets. First, syntactic and structural similarities of geographic data were characterized to improve integration. Secondly, semantic of the data using ontologies were built by inferring relations between classes of data. Formal modeling languages such as UML will be used to document the result of the study. Geographical information from the Department of Agriculture (DA), Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR), and the National Economic Development Authority (NEDA) were used to demonstrate the approach.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
