(941, 'E2-0941AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Shallow water hydrographic charting using high-resolution satellite imagery by Enrico C. Paringit, P', 'This paper introduces the needs, methods and applications of high-resolution satellite remote sensing in mapping coastal and near shore marine resources. Analysis of coastal environment using optical imaging sensors presents a very interesting challenge and intriguing paradox. To be able to perform coastal habitat mapping, one must first overcome the obfuscating effects of the water layer. Variable depth and the presence of optically-active constituents in the intervening water introduce errors in benthic cover classification. On the other hand, methods to estimate bathymetry from optical imagery is met with complications posed by the variety of benthic cover present in the coastal bottom and the non-uniform distribution of water quality. Furthermore, estimation of water quality parameters, though quiet established for the deep oceans, is not immediately applicable to shallow coastal zones due to the presence of river outfall sediments and visibility of bottom. Therefore, a three-pronged approach must be pursued to come up a simultaneous solution to bottom cover composition, depth and water quality retrieval from a single satellite imagery. Previously, such attempts were not possible due to limited number of bands. With the availability of WorldView-2 sensor, there is bright prospect to develop, apply and operationalize such technique. The main objective of this study is to develop a method to simultaneously retrieve bottom benthic cover, depth and water quality from tropical coastal reef using 8-band Worldview-2 data. The proposed method is a combination of spectral mixture model and two-stream radiative transfer model that estimates fractional cover and depth simultaneously. We introduce additional components for estimating the total suspended sediments and chlorophyll and quite possibly yellow matter (detritus). Field surveys were carried to obtain field benthic cover data, field bottom spectra and precise shallow-water bathymetry. The study area is in Bolinao, Pangasinan, Luzon, Philippines where a variety of corals and abundant seagrass meadows are present. This study area is also an active coastal fisheries zone making it an interesting site for doing studies. Results indicate relatively better performance of Worldview-2 image over Quickbird in classifying different benthic habitats. However, they have insignificant difference in depth estimation except horizontal resolution. Comparison of Worldview 2 images classification and bathymetry estimates in also reveal consistency in results. Further, we tested he efficacy of the additional in estimation optically-active water constituents. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(942, 'E2-0942AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Institute of Civil Engineering ', 'Abstract ', 'Governance systems in infrastructure projects by Alexis A. Acacio, Cristy R. Hernandez Professorial ', 'Most infrastructure projects are executed with only the engineering part in mind. Due to this, certain lapses and problems arise due to a lack of clear cut governance mechanisms in the project. These mechanisms are discussed in this paper. In describing the governance process, the entire project life cycle is used as the baseline of analysis- taking into consideration the various stages of : Project concept; Project design; Project construction and; Project turn-over. The pitfalls of poor governance mechanisms are also discussed in this paper. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(943, 'E2-0943AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Analysis of wave loading on protection works for a coastal mangrove planting zone by Eric C. Cruz, S', 'Fully-grown mangroves provide natural protection to the coasts by acting as energy dissipation zones of waves that would otherwise approach the coast with full force. By trapping littoral sediments via their unique root system, they also effectively stabilize the shoreline. Results from various studies indicate, however. that mangroves in the country have decreased at an average rate of 4.7 hectares annually, thus exacerbating the vulnerability of the coasts particularly in the face of natural disasters and climate change. A community-engaged movement has embarked on a program to rehabilitate mangrove areas in the country and to plant mangrove saplings in new pilot areas. Due to the low success rate of earlier rehabilitation programs where the saplings are immediately exposed to the wave environment, it was recognized that protection works must be in place prior to transplanting. To increase the success rate of the program, it is necessary to provide temporary protection to young mangrove saplings. Once pilot planting zones are determined according to bio-physical criteria, the need for protection against waves is assessed from engineering analysis of the storm-induced wave climate at the site. This study focuses on the application of numerical simulations to determine the wave loading on a pilot mangrove planting zone, the development of design criteria and subsequent design of protection works to ensure a high survival rate of mangrove saplings. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(944, 'E2-0944AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Greening of Philippine Concretes : Use of Mineral Admixtures by Nathaniel B. Diola, Jose Ma. Diego d', 'Climate change mitigation and adaptation has become a driving force for industries to go green. The production of ordinary Portland cement (OPC), specifically the clinkering process, is known to contribute to carbon dioxide emissions. The use of mineral admixtures as partial replacement to OPC is one strategy adopted worldwide to lessen the requirement for OPC clinker. In the Philippines, a dramatic shift to the use of blended cements resulted after a Philippine National Standard for blended cement was adopted. This paper presents a review of the various mineral admixtures used in blended cements. It also discusses issues associated with the use of blended cements among which is the performance of blended cement compared to ordinary Portland cement. Type I ordinary Portland cement and two local brands of Type IP blended cements were used to create mortar samples, which were cured and tested. Durability parameters such as porosity, permeability and diffusivity were determined experimentally to characterize each type of cement. These tests were performed to aid in the selection of binders for durable concrete. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(945, 'E2-0945AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'A simple technique for considering the vintage of a building in analytically deriving fragility curv', 'Building fragility curves show the probability of exceedance of a particular damage state versus the ground motion intensity (in terms of PGA or MMI) due to an earthquake. However, the design standard for a specific building archetype changed several times as understanding of the behaviour of structures subjected to earthquakes improved. Thus, there exist in our building stock, buildings of the same archetype but have different \"vintage\" normally based on the structural code used during the time of construction. This paper presents a simple technique for considering the effect of the vintage of a building in analytically deriving fragility curves of archetype building frame models used for loss estimation in disaster risk management. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(946, 'E2-0946AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Hydrological modeling studies for proposed flood-control dams in the Marikina River Basin by Leonard', 'Tropical Storm Ondoy (Ketsana) crossed Metro Manila and the adjacent river basins in a late wet-season episode of 2009, starting in the evening of September 25, 2009 and continuing into the next day of September 26, 2009. TS Ondoy brought very intense and heavy rainfall to the region - record amounts of rains fell over a very short time period of 12 hours to 24 hours, which are estimated to occur at an average annual frequency of 1 in 100 years or even higher, depending on the measuring location in the region. The rains generated record-magnitude flood flows and inundation in the Pasig-Marikina River Basin in Metro Manila, and the Laguna de Bay region. This paper describes the application of the distributed watershed rainfall-runoff model SWATCH in order to simulate the TS Ondoy floods and other floods of lower return periods (2 years to 100 years) in the upper Marikina River Basin, using as input the spatially-interpolated rainfall network data and available topographic, soil/geology and river-geometry data. The SWATCH model consists of a tree-network of several variable rectangular surface/soil/aquifer storage nodes and overland/channel flow links, with accounting of soil moisture, evapo-transpiration, infiltration and recharge to groundwater, and routing of overland and channel flows, interflow and baseflow into aggregated total streamflows. Using the model-computed inflow flood hydrographs, the options of single or cascade of flood-control storage dams (with selected reservoir-storage and spillway capacities) for attenuation of floods peaks and volumes, and downstream flood hazard reduction are initially evaluated by flood-routing studies. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(947, 'E2-0947AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract ', 'Qualitative and quantitative attributes of risk factors in disaster risk management by Benito M. Pac', 'Disaster risk management, including disaster risk reduction, being multi-disciplinary has borrowed concepts, terminologies and practices from many fields including insurance and financial risk management, community development, emergency management, medicine and engineering. This paper examines the evolution of Hazard, Exposure and Vulnerability as three generic risk factors that conveniently capture the major aspects of natural disaster risks including earthquake, windstorm, flood, landslide, and the like. In the analysis, both the qualitative and quantitative attributes of each risk factor are examined. The use of these risk factors is illustrated with the author\'s proposed RISK MAPR2 framework of action in DRM.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(948, 'E2-0948AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Survival versus sustainability : challenges to environmentally sustainable transport by Hilario Sean', 'Transportation in developing countries such as the Philippines is still largely characterized by undesirable practices and systems that are considered unsustainable. The use and proliferation of two-stroke motorcycles and tricycles, use of inefficient transportation modes, the paradigm of vicious cycle in road construction, high rate of road crashes, aging and smoke-belching vehicles, and high private car usage are among the problems. This study will try to investigate the inertia that makes it difficult to adopt EST amidst the largely accepted benefits of EST in many local government units (LGUs), even with the political support of national agencies. It hypothesizes that survival is still the predominant force which resists the adoption of EST.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(949, 'E2-0949AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract ', 'Numerical model to predict time to initiate concrete cover cracking due to corrosion by Norbert S. Q', 'Corrosion of RC structures in marine environment presents an economic, not to mention structural, problem as repair and rehabilitation of corroded structures draw significant portion of the budget allotted for infrastructures. Once cracks start to form and propagate due to chloride ingress, the useful life of the structure is significantly diminished and expensive repair and rehabilitation is the only recourse to extend the service life of the structure. The ability to predict the time to initiate corrosion and the time to initiate cracking of the RC cover can provide useful information that allows one to put in place less expensive maintenance procedures to extend the service life of the structure. In this paper, a numerical model to predict the time to initiate concrete cover cracking is developed. Results of the model were compared to published experimental data and excellent agreements were recorded. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(950, 'E2-0950AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Traffic congestion in Metro Manila : is the UVVRP still effective? by Jose Regin F. Regidor, Pozzola', 'The Unified Vehicular Volume Reduction Program (UVVRP), more popularly known as the \"number coding\" scheme was originally developed as a short-term travel demand management (TDM) measure in the light of on-going construction of transportation infrastructure projects in the 1990\'s. Although the scheme was not meant to be a long-term policy, the UVVRP is at present still implemented along major roads in Metro Manila albeit with some modifications like the mid-day window. With the completion of those major infrastructure projects, various transportation stakeholders, particularly those who are significantly disrupted by the UVVRP are critical of its continuous implementation, especially now that the authorities are leaning towards imposing the scheme on public transportation. A study was conducted in 2004 to evaluate the UVVRP. Several scenarios were developed to evaluate traffic performance for variations to the schemes. The conclusion at the time was that UVVRP was effective enough to address traffic congestion. With the present experience of traffic congestion along major roads throughout the day there is a clamor for revisiting the UVVRP and to determine if it is still effective in curbing congestion. This paper examines the UVVRP and presents the way forward for addressing congestion in Metro Manila. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(951, 'E2-0951AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Relating the air permeability of mayon sand with its soil-water retention curve : measurements and m', 'Air permeability (ka) and soil-water retention curve are two important parameters that are needed when simulating the movement of volatile organic chemicals in the subsurface. In this study, we measured the air permeability and soil-water retention curve of sand obtained within the vicinity of Mayon Volcano in the Philippines, across a wide range of matric potentials and soil-water contents. Samples were prepared (1) by adding a pre-determined amount of water to sand, left to equilibrate in a sealed bag, and repacked at a bulk density of 1.5 g/cm3 for air permeability; or (2) by saturating repacked 1.5 g/cm3 sands and draining to a desired matric potential in a sandbox or a pressure plate apparatus for the soil-water retention curve. In addition, independent data sets of air permeability where obtained on 1.5 g/cm3 sand samples drained to different matric potentials. The variation of ka with soil-air content showed an increase in ka during the drainage of the bigger pores (effective diameter > 0.33 mm) while no further significant increase in air permeability when effective pore size of less than 0.03 mm has been drained. A power law ka model was fitted into the ka data for > - 100 cm H2O (pF 2 where pF = log (- in cm H2O) while a constant value described the ka in the dry region where < - 100 cm H2O. A ka (pF) model was developed by combining the developed ka model with the van Genuchten soil-water retention model and tested on the independent ka(pF) data sets/. The developed model reasonably captured the behavior of the air permeability as a function of matric potential. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(952, 'E2-0952AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Towards a safer intersection design by Ricardo G. Sigua, Prof. Emeritus Norbert S. Vila Professorial', 'Intersections play a major role in the road transportation system of any town or city. Good design and proper application of traffic control devices to strengthen the design concept used are vital to successful operation of intersections. The paper revisits and presents a single fundamental design concept : Guide all road users on the appropriate path and action they should take while approaching and/or negotiating an intersection. This basic concept, the author believes, would help our road designers and traffic managers in putitng order to many problematic intersections in Metro Manila and other towns and cities in the country. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(953, 'E2-0953AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Need for climate change studies and parameters prior to climate change adaptation efforts in the Phi', 'This paper discusses and advocates the need for climate change studies and parameters in order to develop climate change adaptation efforts in the Philippines. There are 6 global climate change scenarios entertained by IPCC. This requires deciding what global climate change scenarios are appropriate for our country which should be a national effort. Once the climate change scenarios are selected, then proper guidelines and research on what GCM Model (result) to adopt since are over 20 or so GCM\'s currently available. Also, since GCM\'s are ran at spatial resolutions of 150-300 km by 150-300 km and are unable to resolve important sub-grid scale features such as clouds and topography, then there is the need to downscale GCM results to regional/local climate characteristics. With properly downscaled climate change variables, these should be converted into appropriate planning, design or management parameters useful in developing climate change adaptation measures. Unfortunately, there are no studies done as a national effort to develop policies and management strategies to address flood risks, drought risk, crop yield or hydropower generation under climate change. This paper also not only discusses uncertainties in climate change process itself but also natural climate variabilities and uncertainties in ecosystem and socio-economic-political changes. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(954, 'E2-0954AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Using coco-peat as sorbent materials in removing heavy metals from aqueous solutions by Maria Antoni', 'Many wastewaters especially those coming from industrial activities contain dissolved heavy metals such as lead, copper, cadmium, and arsenic. Various methods are being employed to remove the dissolved ions from the solution. One of the treatment processes used is adsorption where the wastewater is made to pass through a sorbent material for removal to take place. This study investigates the efficacy of the coco-peat as a sorbent material, both in its fresh state and as activated carbon. This study determines the capacity of the coco peat to remove Cu, Pb, Cd, and As ions from aqueous solution. Coco peat was activated employing chemical activation, using ZnCl2 as chemical activating agent. Activated carbon from coco peat was found to have a high BET surface area of 2,121 m2/g and pore volume of 1.398cm3/g. The products were also characterized by using thermo gravimetric (TG), Scanning Electron Microscopy (SEM), and Fourier Transform Infrared (FTIR) spectra. Through batch experiments, the effects of various parameters such as contact time, initial metal concentrations, pH solution, adsorbent dosage, and temperature on the removal efficiencies were investigated. Coco peat was found to have high removal efficiency for Cu2+ and Pb2+.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(955, 'E2-0955AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Yielding and collapse of buildings subjected to strong ground motions by Eric Augustus J. Tingatinga', 'This study investigates nonlinear effects of gravity on the response of buildings subjected to strong earthquake-induced ground motions. Simple analytical building models are used to study the changes in the natural frequency, steady-state response, yielding and collapse. Governing equations are developed to take into account large displacements and numerical time-stepping methods are proposed to solve the equation. The preliminary study which emphasizes on elastic structures exhibiting geometric nonlinearity revealed that gravity decreases the natural frequency of the building and large displacement formulations showed that the natural frequency as well as response depends on ground motion amplitude. For the specific case of the shear-flexural building model used, for example, it was reported that the large amplitude response contains sub-harmonic components and damping decreases the higher mode contribution on the response. While the previous study is very important, the study of inelastic behavior is inevitable. To investigate yielding and collapse of buildings, an elastoplastic restoring force-displacement relation was used to emulate material nonlinearity. Numerical examples revealed that the decrease in restoring forces as a consequence of yielding causes the weight to become the dominant force in causing buildings to collapse. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(956, 'E2-0956AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Estimation of emissions and fuel consumption of sustainable transport measures in Metro Manila by Ka', 'Environmentally sustainable transport (EST) strategy measures for Metropolitan Manila are assessed in terms of reduction in local emissions, greenhouse gas emissions and energy demand. Measures include vehicle inspection, engine replacement, use of alternative fuels an biofuels, non-motorized transport, travel demand management and improvement of public transportation. Travel activity in terms of traffic volume and travel speeds of the travel demand forecast model estimates and the database of the 1996 Metro Manila Urban Transportation Integration Study (MMUTIS), emission factors from the Vehicular Emission Control Planning (VECP) project and fuel consumption factors from MMUTIS and recent studies on jeepneys and buses are utilized to generate the baseline emissions of criteria pollutants (HC, CO, NO2, PM and SO2), carbon dioxide emissions and energy demand (diesel, gasoline, alternative fuel/biofuel) in 2010 and 2015. Emissions and energy demand are estimated for each strategy measure and compared with respect to the baseline values. Measures such as implementation of vehicle inspection, public transport improvement, travel demand management and switch to 4-stroke tricycles contributed to higher overall emission reductions. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(957, 'E2-0957AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract ', 'Community-based methods for landslide risk reduction : state of the practice by Mark Albert H. Zarco', 'Despite the availability of hazard maps, engineering intervention methods, and early warning systems; the socio-economic costs due landslides continue to increase every year in the Philippines. Very often, existing hazard maps are either inaccurate, outdated, or are too technical to be understood and used in a meaningful manner by members of the local community living in the affected area. In other cases, early warning systems are prone to pilferage and vandalism. Existing engineering measures are often costly and unaffordable by most communities. This paper highlights the role of community based methods for landslide disaster risk reduction. The main advantage of community-based methods is their abiilty to empower communities by developing their capacity to recognize, document and monitor potential hazard zones within their communities. Making communities develop their own risk reduction strategies gives them a sense of ownership which is essential in minimizing the loss of life, limb and property due to natural disasters. Furthermore, the resulting outputs are easier to understand, and can be used in a more meaningful way for disaster risk reduction purposes. Various community based strategies for identifying, assessing and monitoring landslide risk are discussed. Examples of the application of community-based methods for landslide risk reduction here and abroad are discussed, as well as the issues that arise when such methods are implemented in local communities.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(958, 'E2-0958AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Department of Industrial Engineering & Operations Research', 'Abstract ', 'A design of an integrated computer-based information system for the University of the Philippines Di', 'The design and implementation of information systems in UP Diliman has always been done piece-meal and without systematic planning. This paper suggests an over-all design for an integrated, comprehensive computer-based information system for the whole of UP Diliman and proposes an organization for its information-related functions. The over-all system is broken up into modules such as an Academic Information Subsystem, Accounting Subsystem, etc. that can be implemented as the need becomes critical and when development resources can be made available.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(959, 'E2-0959AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'The UP College of Engineering\'s Role in Public Service by Aura C. Matias, UP Engineering Class of 19', 'Countries that achieve rapid development are those that adopted policies to promote science; technology and innovation. In the light of the commitment of the Aquino Administration to harness the full potential of S&T capabilities of our country, the UP College of Engineering (COE) is called upon to contribute its talent and resources towards rapid economic growth. The vision, mission and goals of the UP COE are presented to highlight its role in providing knowledge, progress and growth in the interest of public service. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(960, 'E2-0960AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'The four rationales of technology transfer : identifying technology transfer risks / Iris Ann G. Mar', 'Up until now, most technology transfer activities have been carried out on trial-and-error basis. However, recent studies have emerged to provide scientifically-based guides for technology transfer in recognition of the fact that technology transfer is important for global advancement. Along with these studies, this research aims to present a systematic methodology, called the Four Rationales of Technology Transfer, for identifying the risks of technology transfer. This methodology is derived from an empirical study conducted on 50 recently-implemented technology transfer projects. With the proposal of the methodology of Four Rationales of Technology Transfer and the presentation of the results of the empirical study, it is the hope of this research that future activities of technology transfer will become more successful.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(961, 'E2-0961AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Triz-driven sustainable innovation and technology model for SMES by Nestor O. Rañeses, UPIEAA Profes', 'While the small and medium industries (SMEs) numerically hogged the productive economic sectors at 99.6% of the total formal business establishments based on the 2009 NSO Survey, their economic contribution is still small to make them the primary engine for productivity improvement and economic growth. The lack and inadequate penetration, diffusion, and use of technology and innovation in starting, growing, and improving small and medium enterprises has been recognized as one of the major barriers for the slow growth of the SME sector. Using the Value Chain perspective and the TRIZ methodology, we present a TRIZ-driven sustainable innovation and technology model that aims to provide small and medium-sized entrepreneurs the mind-set and the behavioral model on how to secure and exploit technology and innovation to a trajectory of sustainable growth. Several cases will be presented. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(962, 'E2-0962AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Productivity of gold production by small scale mining and extraction industries by Virginia Soriano,', 'The Philippine gold industry has contributed largely to the country\'s economy by supporting more than one million people, as well as generating and supporting thousands of small scale enterprises/ businesses in mining, processing and jewelry manufacturing. This study aims to determine the productivity levels and the factors that influence the productivity of small scale gold mining and extraction. Based on the documentation  and analysis of small scale gold production sites located at the provinces of Benguet, Camarines Norte and Davao, there are different mining and extraction practices and methods depending on the type of inputs such as materials, energy, labor and equipment and the amount of quality of output that can be produced at the shortest time possible. The different methods used for mining include underground, open pit, sinking tunnel and seafloor mining. The different methods observed for the extraction of gold involved the use of rather toxic substances such as cyanide, mercury or zinc. Key issues and challenges were identified based on the observed practices for the mining and extraction processes. Research was done on the potential productivity growth that may be driven by technological and organizational improvements. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(963, 'E2-0963AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Department of Mechanical Engineering ', 'Abstract', 'Ejector Powerplant System by Menandro Serrano Berana, Emerson Professorial Chair in Mechanical Engin', 'This paper presents the potential application of ejector and the efficiency improvement it brings to powerplants that utilize low-temperature renewable and recoverable heat sources. The ejector significantly increases the efficiency of the organic Rankine cycle (ORC) by increasing the turbine temperature drop which is made possible by the expansion, mixing and recompression processes in the ejector. The driving fluid in the ejector of the modified cycle is the high-pressure liquid in the separator that is just circulated back to the evaporator in the ORC. Fundamental thermodynamic analysis of the ejector powerplant cycle was undertaken. Ammonia and propane, which are both natural working fluids, were used in the analysis. The analysis was limited by considering that the lowest pressure in the system must be higher than the atmospheric pressure to avoid vacuum leak. The calculation results showed that propane and ammonia can both give maximum efficiencies at different evaporator temperatures and fixed condenser temperatures in the range of 20-27%. It has been shown that propane can give higher efficiences and lower velocities in the ejector than ammonia at considerably lower evaporating temperatures, leading to more economical, safer and simpler design and operation. The ejector system with ammonia and propane as working fluids offers environment friendly power generation from low-temperature sources at improved efficiency. ', 'Ejector, powerplant, propane, ammonia, organic rankine cycle ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(964, 'E2-0964AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Development of a diesel hybrid vehicle prototype by Gerald Jo C. Denoga, Emerson Professorial Chair ', 'The research is about the development of a diesel hybrid vehicle. A small concept car was prototyped aimed at achieving high fuel mileage while still satisfying other consumer needs like speed, aesthetics, safety, usability and comfort. The design is comprehensive, including lightweight chassis design, aerodynamic shell design, calculated passenger safety, and optimized power generation. The drive train is based on a series hybrid system, using a single cylinder diesel engine directly coupled to an electric DC generator. The electricity produced is channeled in part to a motor and a super capacitor, which, at certain points, will be used to power the motor. The key feature of the drive train is the control system that ensures a fixed power draw from the engine corresponding to the load and speed of the diesel engine at optimum brake specific fuel consumption. The prototype vehicle was able to achieve an actual on-road mileage of at least 50 kilometers per liter. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(965, 'E2-0965AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'LPG in dual-fuel SI and CI engine applications - effects on maximum poewr and fuel consumption by Ed', 'This paper presents findings on the use of LPG as a substitute fuel for a gasoline car sedan and a diesel-powered container crane. Maximum power at the wheels is investigated with the gasoline car running on either gasoline or LPG. Tests for maximum power at various gear ratios were conducted using a chassis dynamometer. On the other hand, a comparsion of fuel consumption using either diesel only or diesel with LPG was conducted on a container crane used in port collections. The tests involved moving a loaded container van over a prescribed series of motions simulating actual cargo handling and repeating these for a pre-determined number of cycles. Fuel consumption was measured gravimetrically at the end of the last cycle. These tests were performed to determine fuel cost savings opportunities if LPG is used for crane operation. Results of dynamometer tests with LPG fuel confirmed reduction of maximum power. One reason for this is the displacement of intake air by the vaporized LPG fuel. This is also one reason why an LPG convesion kit should be tuned to the vehicle where it is installed. Use of LPG with diesel fuel for a turbocharged diesel engine for crane operations indicated opportunities for savings due to overall lower fuel consumption and fuel costs. There were no noticeable operating issues experienced when operating on dual-fuel mode for the diesel engine. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(966, 'E2-0966AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Design and production of a vehicle run by cordless drills by Joseph Gerard T. Reyes, Emerson Profess', 'This work was brought about by a plan to design and fabricate an entry that would compete in a race sponsored by a power tools manufacturer. It also provided an opportunity to dwell in further research into the local production of vehicles using prime movers other than conventional internal-combustion engines. For this particular case, four cordless drills were specified as the source of motive power for this vehicle. The conditions considered in the design were safety of the driver; maneuverability, reliability and endurance of the vehicle; a light vehicle mass and a fixed budget. In order to satisfy the given conditions, the design incorporated proper vehicle dimensions, drivetrain and controls, the use of items which could be acquired off-the-shelf and the use of conventional manufacturing processes. A prototype was constructed at the UP College of Engineering and underwent trial runs prior to competition. The results of the trial runs and its performance at the competition showed satisfactory results. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(967, 'E2-0967AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Department of Mining, Metallurgical and Materials Engineering ', 'Abstract', 'Surface modification of polymers by plasma treatment in an ion shower facility by Alberto V. Amorsol', 'Low density polyethylene (LDPE) and Kapton polyimide (PI) films were subjected to surface modification in an ion shower facility using argon and nitrogen plasma. Surface modification can improve the wettability and adhesion properties of polymers to other materials like metal films. This variable screening study focused on the contact angle response as a measure of wettability, employing a replicated fractional factorial experiment (1/2 of 2 4) for each polymer in which the factors are accelerating voltage (0.5 kV, 3.5 kV), type of plasma source gas (argon, nitrogen), exposure time (10 min, 30 min) and gas filling pressure (13 mTorr, 48 mTorr). Additional characterization made use of Atomic Force Microscopy and Fourier Transform Infrared (FTIR) Spectroscopy in ATR mode. All treatments in the variable screening experiments successfully reduced the contact angle indicating creation of a more hydrophilic surface. Both main effects and two-factor interaction effects turned out to have statistical significance at the 95% confidence level among certain parameters. The interactionsfound in both polymer systems imply that meaningful optimization can only be acieved by considering that effects of factors are not simply additive but could either be synergistic or anti-synergistic in nature.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(968, 'E2-0968AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Methane gas generation for dairy wastewater and expired produtcts via anaerobic digestion by Louerni', 'Dairy wastewater from the initial washing processes and expired products pulled out from the shelf have high concentrations of biochemical oxygen demand (BOD) and chemical oxygen demand (COD). Currently, these wastes are being stored awaiting treatment. During storage, the wastes already undergo biodegradation process. This study was done to simulate the biodegradation of the wastes and to determine if methane gas can be recovered during storage. Specifically, the study aimed to correlate the effect of COD values of the wastewater and expired products to the volume of methane gas generated in an anaerobic set-up. Each set-up of 1-liter capacity was monitored for 15 days without stirring and the volume of the generated gas was recorded. Anaerobic digestion was done without pH adjustment and seeding. Dairy wastewater was characterized (COD, pH and TSS) before and after treatment. The pH values and COD concentrations of the dairy wastewater samples ranged from 3.5-6 and 20,000-250,000 ppm respectively. The volume of gas generated was proportional to the COD concentration. A COD reduction of about 60% was achieved via anaerobic digestion. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(969, 'E2-0969AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Advancing nanotechnology in the country through utilization of locally available nanomaterials by Le', 'Nanotechnology has been the trend of research recently especially in materials primarily because of the unique properties and phenomena it brings out them, which typically are not observable in bulk dimensions. In the Philippines, a naturally occurring nanomaterial comes in the form of clay minerals, which, up to these days, have been mainly used for traditional applications such as pottery making and additives to cosmetics and agricultural fertilizers and other supplements. One of the hindrances to its utilization in nanotechnology is its purity because our material in the Philippines is often accompanied by oxides such as silica and iron oxide, among others. In this study, purification of nanoclay, specifically montmorillonite, from locally sourced clay and its utilization in fabrication of products for the environmental, semiconductor and energy applicants were investigated. It was shown in the characterizations of the material produced from nanoclay mixed with different polymer materials that addition of nanoclay enhanced and even modified to make them applicable to the applications mentioned above. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(970, 'E2-0970AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract', 'Molecular sieve materials : their synthesis, properties and application by Eduardo R. Magdaluyo, Jr.', 'A large number of molecular sieve materials have emerged in the past decade, with interesting structures, special types and aggregated states. They are usually composed of highly porous mineral or organometallic compounds, which can sieve out other molecules on the molecular scale. All the new developments in the syntheses and structural characterizations of the mesoporous materials open up an increasingly wider range of applications, from the traditional areas such as adsorption separation, catalysis and ion-exchange to electronics and nanotechnology. To describe a porous structure, several parameters may be used and these include the pore size and shape, the channel dimensionality, the composition and features of channel wall, among others. This paper covers the fundamental principles, synthetic strategies and techniques of the molecular sieve materials. The interesting properties associated to its structural framework and the different applications are also discussed. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(971, 'E2-0971AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract ', 'Heterocoagulation behavior of ultrafine hematite mineral particles with silica macroscopic collector', 'The attachment and detachment behaviors of ultrafine hematite particles (0.33 micron) onto silica macroscopic collector (104 micron) are investigated as a function of pH and electrolyte concentration using the column-bed method. The zeta-potential measurements showed that the iso-electric points (i.e.p.) of hematite and silica minerals are at around pH 2.0 and 7.2, respectively. Attachment of hematite particles onto silica is found to be optimum at conditions pH 3-6 when hematite particles have opposite surface potentials to that of silica collector. Detachment of hematite particles from silica collector is most effective at conditions pH 9-11 when the surface potentials of both hematite and silica particles are of the same negative potentials. It is also at these alkaline conditions that the attachment of hematite particles back to the silica surface is not possible because of the presence of an insurmountable energy barrier. There is a significant deceased of hematite particles attached onto and detached from silica collector as the concentration of the electrolyte is increased. The results are analyzed using the classical Darguin-Landue-Verveek-Overvick (DLVO) and Born repulsive energy theories. The mechanism established in this study can be used to explain mineral and material separation processes. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(972, 'E2-0972AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Abstract ', 'Ceramic foam for the photocatalytic degradation of organic pollutants by Jeffrey John Venezuela, Wil', 'The search for efficient yet inexpensive alternative methods of environmental decontamination has earned interest among researchers. Advanced photochemical oxidation (APO) processes, which include TiO2 as a photocatalyst, have flourished nowadays due to their wide application which includes wastewater treatment. This study focused on the design and implementation of an APO-based photochemical reactor utilizing macroporous cement-supported TiO2 nanotube with N and Fe3+ sensitizers. The hydrothermal method was employed in the synthesis of the nanotubes followed by doping with the sensitizers. Ceramic foams fabricated via a modified polymeric foam replication method using two different types of precursors were then coated with the doped TiO2. Characterization of the nanotube were then employed to determine its properties. The photocatalyticproperty of the ceramic foams were tested by determining the photodegradation of methyl orange upon exposure to white light. Transmission electron microscopy revealed the nanotube structure of titania after the hydrothermal treatment while XRD patterns confirmed the presence of anatase phase of TiO2 in the powders. The Brunauer-Emmet-Teller (BET) test results, on the other hand, showed a significant increase in the surface area which is typical of nanostructures. Photocatalytic tests on the TiO2-coated ceramic foams show a dependence of activity on the additoin of dopant and on the type of foam structure used. A reusability test on the foams suggests strong adhesion of the TiO2 on the foam and confirms its ability to withstand the rigors of practical application. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(973, 'E2-0973AC', '', 'UP COE Technical Bulletin : Compilation of Full Papers 2013 Teaching Research Grant (TRG), Volume 5, Number 1 (3 copies)', 'National Engineering Center ', 'U.P. Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. for the National Engineering Center ', 'October 2013', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Assessment of the Handling of Heat Exchanger Design Projects in ChE 133 (Heat and Mass Transfer Equi', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(974, 'E2-0974AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Comparison of the Shear Stresses of an Aluminum and Aluminum Carbon Composite Rectangular Shafts Usi', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(975, 'E2-0975AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Effect of Temperature and Type of Inorganic Acid in Acidolysis of Epoxy and Polyurethane Thermosetti', 'The study aims to determine the effect of temperature on the diffusion of strong inorganic acids, as a precursor to dissolution in epoxy and polyurethane thermosetting resins. Epoxy and polyurethane resins were immersed in 5M solutions of HNO3, H2SO4 and HCl at 30 degree celcius, 50 degree celcius and 80 degree celcius. From the relative changes in weight over a period of 12 days, the distribution coefficients were determined . Results showed an increase in the value of the diffusion coefficient with temperature. Moreover, both resins dissolved only in nitric acid at 80 degree celcius. In both resins, the nitric acid diffused the fastest and proved to be the most effective decomposing agent for the two polymers. ', 'Acidolysis, Epoxy, Polyurethane, Thermosets, Inorganic Acids, Diffusion', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(976, 'E2-0976AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Performance Comparison of Diesel and Auto-LPG Jeepney by Jose Gabriel E. Mercado, Department of Mech', 'Jeepneys are the most common mode of public transportation in the Philippines but most jeepneys in the country are powered by diesel engines that produces harmful emissions to the environment. The Philippine government now promotes the use of alternative fuels in public transportation to lessen the harmful emissions and to make us less dependent on fossil fuels. This study shows that Autho-LPG powered jeepney is a good alternative to the diesel-powered jeepney in most routes in the Philippines because with respect to Fuel Economy the Auto-LPG powered jeepney is 22.26% better than the Diesel Jeepney. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(977, 'E2-0977AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Mechanism Design of Work Loader for CNC Vertical Mill Using Graphical Synthesis Method by Jose, Ralp', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
INSERT INTO `records` (`id`, `accessionNo`, `boxNumber`, `title`, `placeOfPublication`, `publisher`, `dateOfPublication`, `descriptionContent`, `type`, `paper`, `abstract`, `keywords`, `filePath`, `fileName`, `accessLevel`, `status`, `dateEncoded`, `updatedAt`) VALUES
(978, 'E2-0978AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'One-dimensional unsteady-state heat transfer in a window shade coated with microencapsulated phase c', 'Phase change materials (PCM) are thermal energy substances that can absorb or release a large amount of heat at a constant temperature at it undergoes phase transition. PCMs are used in a number of applications such as thermal regulation and improvement of heat transfer. Microencapsulated PCMs (MPCMs) may be incorporated in window textile and shade to reduce space cooling load requirements due to solar gain through windows. An evaluation of the thermal performance of a window shade coated with MPCM is presented by modelling the transport phenomenon in the material as a one-dimensional unsteady-state heat transfer. The effect of the type of PCM, encapsulating material and thickness, type of coating, fabric properties, and PCM loading on the thermal performance may be investigated through the model. The temperature distribution in the fabric after a period of simulation time, the progression of the temperature of a fabric end, and the heat flux from the fabric to the room were generated from a proposed method of solution to the model and showed that the MPCM-coated fabric exhibits a much improved thermal resistance compared to an uncoated fabric. Only a short simulation time was considerd using the proposed method, however, due to the limitation imposed by the stability condition that demands a large amount of computer memory. Another method of solution must be explored to complete the simulations and gain more useful insights to the performance of the MPCM-coated shade as a thermal regulator.  ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(979, 'E2-0979AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Performance Evaluation of Selected Locally Available Cement in Stabilizing Soil for Pavement Base Pu', 'Cement treated base course are commonly used in high volume and load traffic areas, such as : airports, industrial areas, and major highways. Various materials such as soil, aggregates and recycled concrete may be treated with cement to improve its engineering properties. This study aims to investigate the effect of cement type and cement content to the strength properties of soil cement used as base courses of pavements. The strength parameter considered in this study is the soaked unconfined compressive strength, with minor testing for California Bearing Ratio (CBR). Soil samples from A-2-4 type of soil were used to produce cylindrical soil-cement specimens to be usef for standard compressive strength tests. Results show that for all cement types, there were significant increases in compressive strength of the soil cement samples for every 2% increment of cement content. In comparison with each other, there were significant 28-day strength differences among samples of varying cement type but with one cement content. Type I soil cement samples demonstrated high early strength and satisified the DPWH strength standard at the PCA recommended cement contents for design (5%, 7%, and 9%). With regard to the CBR, all the samples satisfied the DPWH standard of a minimum 110% CBR. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(980, 'E2-0980AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Plane Stress Computation of 94% Aluminum Oxide Orthogonal Cutting Tool using Finite Element Analysis', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(981, 'E2-0981AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Selecting and Tuning a Temperature Feedback Controller for Water Heating Process by Kristian July R.', 'Temperature control is ncessary for temperature-specific industrial operations in order to meet optimum operating conditions based on the desired product specifications. In line with this, an experiment on temperature control was conducted to select an appropriate feedback controller and determine its tuning parameters. A first order plus dead time (FOPDT) model was employed to characterize the system. Tuning parameters were determined through computer simulation using SciLab (version 5.0.3) by trial-and-error. Results show that upon using a PI controller with Kc=30.00 and K1=0.71, a temperature deviation of about 2 degree celcius for the half pail set-up and a 10-minute settling time deviation for the full pail set-up occured. This was due to several factors such as the ideality and absence of mixing in the mathematical model, and the difference in the conditions of the environment. Though a PID controller was theoretically used, a PI-controlled system was found to be more suitable.  ', 'Dead time, Time constant, PID controller, PI controller ', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(982, 'E2-0982AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper ', 'Land Use/Land Cover Map Generation of Panay, Guimaras and Negros Islands using Moderate Resolution S', 'This paper presents the results of using a series of moderate resolution (30m) Landsat images to derive a general land use/land cover (LULC) map of the islands of Panay, Guimaras and portions of Negros. The said images were pre-processed for atmospheric correction, cloud and cloud shadow filling and removal of noisy pixels. The six optical bands of Landsat ETM+ and an additional built-up index band were used as inputs to image classification, in per scene basis, via the Maximum Likelihood classifier. The said index band was derived from the three original Landsat bands and was used to aid in differentiating built-up and bare soil pixels. The classified image has a mean overall accuracy of 85.41% and kappa coefficient of 0.819 while the derived LULC map from this classification showed a class distribution of bare soil, paddy fields, forest, built-up, grass and water areas covering 33.4%, 11.3%, 13.3% 2.2%, 30.5% and 9.3% of the total area of the three Philippine islands. The study demonstrated the use of freely-available moderate resolution Landsat images to derive LULC maps, a very important spatial data that is often used in many research studies dealing with environmental planning and protection.  ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(983, 'E2-0983AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technical Paper', 'Thermal degradation kinetics and lifetime estimation of orthophthalic unsaturated polyester resins b', 'In this study, the model-free isoconversional methods of Vyazovkin, Ozawa-Flynn-Wall (OFW) and Kissinger-Akahira-Sunose (KAS) together with the master-plot method were used to study the non-isothermal thermal degradation kinetics of orthophthalic unsaturated polyester (ortho-UP). Non-isothermal experiments at four different heating rates (2, 5, 10 and 20 K/min) were conducted using thermogravimetric analysis (TGA). The experimental data was used to find the kinetic parameters (E, A and f (x) of this process. The dependence of the activation energy E with conversion, x were determined using the three isoconversional models. Likewise, the pre-exponential factor A and reaction model f(x) (or g(x)) were obtained using the master-plot method. Results show that the activation energy and pre-exponential factor for the thermal degradation of ortho-UP are E=144.036 kJ/mol and A=1.4595 x 10 10 min-1, respectively. A three-dimensional diffusion model, of the form g(x) = [1-(1-x) 1/3] 2, was determined to be the best kinetic model for this particular system. The consistency of the kinetic triplets [E, A and g (x)) were checked by comparing experimental and calculated x - T curves. ', 'Ortho-UP; TGA; Thermal degradation kinetics; Non-isothermal; Isoconversion; Model-Free', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(984, 'E2-0984AC', '28', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XI, Number 6', '', '', 'November-December 2001 ', 'UPD to implement modified RGEP in June by Chi Ibay\nPontiff espouses inter-religious collaboration; urges academe do the same\nThe role of the university in the promotion of inter-religious dialogue by His Eminence Francis Cardinal Arinze, D. D.\nCurbing the rise of sexual harassment cases in UPD by Bino Gamba\nAdvocacy for women\'s reproductive health and rights \nCBA faculty, students reap awards \nIn grateful collection by Oscar M. Alfonso\nChristmas 2001 on campus by Irwin Allen B. Rivera \nPrizes galore at UPD Christmas Party by Chris Aro\nIt\'s a bug\'s life : Fine arts does it again! by Irwin Allen B. Rivera\nArtist dean pays tribute to regents\nWinsome art by Prof. Ruben D. F. Defeo\nWritings on paper\nOpening the doors of the University : The UPD Infogate by Chris Aro\nBattle for VIC grounds\nNewbriefs\nBOR approves revised policy on study leave with pay by Bino Gamba\nUP to establish JAVA learning center by Len A. Familara\nUC changes final exams sked by Irwin Allen B. Rivera\nEduc is hiring full-time faculty\nMailbox\nObituary\nVisitacion Pesquera Nuval\nJimmy Rollon Rios\nFernando J. Espero, Jr. \nCAL holds first Gawad Leopoldo Yabes by Irwin Allen B. Rivera', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(985, 'E2-0985AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XII, Number 6', '', '', 'November-December 2002 ', 'Christmas comes early at UPD : Innovations mark this year\'s celebration on campus by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nA painting like no other?\nThe Infirmary gears for flight : next year, the Infirmary will be a first level referral hospital if plans fall through (First of a two-part series) by Chi A. Ibay\nNewsbriefs\nSolo parents\' act and maternity leave for unwed mothers\nUPFI accepting overseas donations\nPakyaw services\nLow priced books at OVCRD\' inventory sale\nOnline facility for woman advocates : makes available articles on women in local government in Asia and the Pacific by Bino Gamba\nObituaries\nMarina G. Dayrit\nJose B. Candano\nCristina Tan Decenteceo\nDealing with bomb threats : UPD invites experts to defuse anxiety on the matter by Haidee C. Pineda\nOn the \"Parisian Life\" of the GSIS by Prof. Santiago A. Pilar \nChronology of the controversy\nThe issue is not about art, it is about money by Prof. Virginia B. Dandan\nHounded by emotional and romantic arguments by Dr. Ana P. Labrador\nThe acquisition is contentious by Dr. Eufracio C. Abaya, Director, Office for Initiatives in Culture and the Arts\nCan the government really afford it? by Dr. Ricardo T. Jose, Assistant to the Chair, Department of History, CSSP\nDUP brings the story of Job to the stage : a play about man\'s faith and fate by Irwin Allen B. Rivera \nUPD\'s Bonsai Garden : the garden is now open for public viewing. Free admission by Haidee C. Pineda \nCFA marches again to hall of fame : carries the tail of the Lantern Parade with oomph! by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nAnd this year\'s winners are...College of Architecture bags overall best lantern award \nAng bansot na halamang makahoy : the art of miniaturizing trees, Philippine context by Haidee C. Pineda \nGawad Chancellor 2003 : who will be the 2003 Gawad Chanselor recipients? \nCBA holds alumni homecoming : 10 alumni cited for outstanding accomplishments in private businesses or in public service by Haidee C. Pineda\nUPD BA students win outstanding national award : UPCBA dominates team category since 1998 by Bino Gamba ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(986, 'E2-0986AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XII, Number 6', '', '', 'November-December 2003', 'With elections now approaching...\nThe country needs the creation of programmatic parties : experts say RP parties fail at aggregating people\'s interests, providing stability and empowering the marginalized by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nGIS technology is now at the Geography Department from manual to high-tech by Haidee C. Pineda \nUnderstanding Philippine politics \"The colonial political system ensured the exlusion of masses and control of elite.\" by Mariamme Jadloc \nPublic lecture\nTo \"WOW\" tourists, focus on 1 island...\nTourism expert says \"spokes-and-hub policy\" works in Philippine tourism promotion by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nI-Witness @ the Film Institute \nAward-winning episodes of the TV program unmasked Pinoy realities in a week-long festival by Riza A. Romero\nEndowment\nIntel turns over computers to NISMED \nNISMED is Intel\'s partner in world-class teacher development\nMapping out Geo\'s future \nChairperson lays out plans for the Geography Department\'s new look and thrusts\nFrom physical to virtual Beta Way : The fastest link to cyberspace\nBriefly\nLimitation of honoraria payments \nPerforming groups\nWhen Ambassadors sing\nUPSA\'s humble beginnings and triumps by Chi A. Ibay \nGallery hopping\nStrokes and cytes\nGonzalez\'s first solo exhibit shows off industrial materials as alternative painting media\nTheater\nA psychosomatic comedy : the story of a hypochondriac\'s self-deluding self-cure by Irwin Allen B. Rivera \nBook Review\nNo one is watching \nAn unexpected good read, despite the abused theme of psychotic serial killers \nSmaller and Smaller Circles by FH Batacan\nUniversity of the Philippines Press\nAphasia and watercolor : Former UP President Soriano holds art exhibit at the Philippine Heart Center by RIza A. Romero\n\"Simply\" enjoyable! UPD nagsama2 2geder to celebrate Christmas 2003\nDespite what others claim as a not so \"bongga\" affair this year, UPD went on to celebrate Christmas as early as December 1st, with the Carillon Bells pealing with Christmas Carols.\nThe anything goes parade by Irwin Allen B. Rivera \nIn Memoriam\nCesar Adib Majul, 79\nProminent Scholar and Former College of Arts and Sciences Dean Cesar Adib Majul passed away October 11 of a lingering illness in San Pablo, California. He was supposed to hav turned 80 on October 21. \nJosephin C. Sison, 60\nProf. Josephine Caccam Sison, Former Dean of the Institute of Library and Information Science (ILIS), died of a heart attack last December 7. She was 60 years old. \nThe UPD houses across the street are no longer eyesores\nThe houses are research stations that showcase indigenous materials \nEver wonder what the three houses across the Molave Residence Hall are for?\nCampus Facelift\nUPD revs up for coming year\nProjects have been lined up to improve campus services by Haidee C. Pineda\nCBA\'s new look welcomes alumni \nAngara unveils building marker\nJust in time for the celebration of UPD\'s Christmas Festivities, The College of Business Administration (CBA) completed its building make-over\nAt last! CAL has its own building \nThe 5-storey edifice is a culmination of years of dedicated work spanning three deanships.\nAfter years of sharing spaces with the College of Social Sciences and Philosophy at the Palma Hall, and lately scouting for available classrooms at other buildings like the College of Science and the College of Mass Communication, the College of Arts and Letters (CAL) now has a building to call its own. \nMilestone\nNadera is TOYM literature awardee \n3 UPD alumni are cited for outstanding achievements \nInstitute of Creative Writing Director Victor Emmanuel \'Vim\" D. Nadera Jr. has another title-slash-distinction to add to his numerous citations/trophies/medals that of being this year\'s recipient for the literature category of the Ten Outstanding Young Men (TOYM) of the country. \n2004 Gawad Chancellor call for nomianations\nThe awarding ceremony is set on February 27.\nAs early as November, the Office of the Chancellor released a call for nominations to the Gawad Chancellor that is scheduled on February 27.\n5th PAMANA volume launched \nBook is about RP social justice and human rights.\nThe National College of Public Administration and Governance-Center for Leadership, Citizenship and Democracy (NCPAG-CLCD) launched on December 12  the fifth volume of the PAMANA anthology series at the College\'s Audio-Visual Room.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(987, 'E2-0987AC', '', 'Extra UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XIII, Number 4', '', '', 'July 2003', 'UP evicts Arboretum\'s illegal occupants : UP reclaims Arboretum and NHRC by Chi A. Ibay with reports from the UP Diliman Information Office staff\nFrom the President\'s Desk\nThis morning, a combined team from the Quezon City Government, the Philippine National Police, and the University of the Philippines evicted some 700 intruders occupying a portion of the UP Arboretum along Commonwealth Avenue. \nChronology of Events\nThe Arboretum encroachment\nDemolition leads to arrests : mop up operations continue \nResearch equipment stolen \nAfter the eviction, the NHRC counts its loses\nMosque still stands\nDeconsecration process is being mapped out \nAs of presstime, the markeshift mosque inside the National Hydraulic Research Center (NHRC) compound still stands. \nBeleaguered paradise\nIn the beginning...\nThe arboretum is part of the University of the Philippines Property in Diliman, Quezon City Acquired by the University from the Philippine Government under then President Elpidio Quirino by way of a deed of sale dated March 1, 1949. It one of several parcels of land covered by Transfer Certificate Title (TCT) No. 9462 of the Registry of Deeds of Quezon City.\nFrom the Chancellor\'s Desk\nThis letter is in reaction to the letter to the editor signed by Mr. Lucman F. Esmael, President, Bago-Ingud Islamic Foundation, Barangay Culiat, Quezon City, which appeared in the July 8, 2003 issue of the Philippine Daily Inquirer.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(988, 'E2-0988AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XIII, Number 2', '', '', 'March-April 2003', 'Reinventing an ancient tradition : innovations add cool to 92nd graduation rites by Chi A. Ibay\nEven the Oblation, the University\'s revered and most recognizable symbol, was not spared. Like all graduates attending the commencement exercises, the status was draped with a sablay. \nCream of the Cream\nPledge of Loyalty 2003 \nWhat\'s better than? by Menardo \"Butch\" Jimenez Jr. \nI\'d like to thank the board of regents of this University for taking a big risk in getting a young person to give the commencement address. I\'m going to try my best to make sure that decision was right. \nNational Recovery Program : The nation\'s hope? Gringo\'s NRP draws mixed reactions from UPD by Haidee C. Pineda\nWar solves nothing \nThree institutions of higher learning denounce US move to attach Iraq by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nHours before the United States openly attacked Iraq, the Ateneo de Manila University, Miriam College and University of the Philippines held a joint press conference at the Faculty Center on March 20, to protest against US\' efforts of war. \nPhilippine version of overseas absentee voting \nMore complicated, cumbersome and costs more than the system adopted by rich countries by Eduardo V. Aro\nMinister Counselor and Consul General \nThe Philippine Embassy\nThe Hague, Netherlands\nBarriers to economic reform \nGerry Sicat says RP economic woes stem from discriminatory laws by Irwin Allen B. Rivera \nInt\'l Publication Award : 100 plus awards for UPD...2 for Natatanging Publikasyon sa Filipino and 1 for innovation in teaching.\nAt the recently held President\'s Award for Academic Distinction, more than 80 faculty and researchers from the UPD campus bagged a total of 135 awards for international publication, 2 for natatanging publikasyon sa Filipino and 1 for President\'s Award for Innovation in Teaching. \nTMC conducts seminar for Asean government execs\nBeefing up public-private collaboration in ST development, training and awareness. \nScience and technology managers and researchers from the different Asian countries participated in the first in a series of training seminars on Public-Private Collaboration in Science and Technology Development, Training and Awareness of the Technology Management Center, March 24 to 26 at the Century Park Hotel in Malate, Manila.\nAC now has Asean collection \nThe collection is the first of its kind in the UP System.\nIn a simple ceremony on March 27, the Asian Center (AC) launched the Asean Collection, which is a compilation of official documents and other related publications concerning Asean in the Philippines.\nThe Arboretum standoff\nCan UP win the war against squatting syndicates? by Chi A. Ibay\nGone today, here tomorrow. Like a bad dream that keeps recurring, the task of ridding UP property of illegal occupants is starting to look like the University\'s biggest nightmare.\nUP now has a film institute\nCMC FAVC merges with Film Center to create UPFI\nAfter nine years of waiting, the University of the Philippines finally implemented the creation of a UP Film Institute (UPFI) with the merging of the College of Mass Communication (CMC) Department of Film and Audio-Visual Communication (FAVC) and the UP Film Center (UPFC). \nCBA receives donations from alumni and student orgs \nDonations are for the UP modernization project\nFor two consecutive months, the College of Business Administration (CBA) received donations from its alumni and student organizations donations as part of the College and the University\'s modernization project. \nFeleo\'s fine art \nIn Unanan, his penchant for the mythical and the historical are in ample supply by Prof. Ruben D. F. Defeo\nRoberto Feleo does not hold exhibits so often. From the time he started formally exhibiting his work through solo exhibitions in 1985, he has only mounted 10 exhibits during the 18-year interim. \nCorredor exhibits\nCFA holds first exhibition season\nA series of exhibits is in store for all art aficionados, as the College of Fine Arts\' Corredor holds its first ever exhibition season\nCrossing spaces\nAn interactive display of arts and education elements\nAn appreciative audience from San Antonio Elementary School Mental Retardation Section gamely engaged in each of the activities the class of Theater 291 (Selected Seminars in Theater) prepared at the opening of Crossing Spaces on March 11.\nHarnessing art in a festival setting\nCFA caps initial course offerings to RGEP with students\' exhibits\nThe Corredor of the College of Fine Arts (CFA) was in a festive mood on March 21, as the class of Fine Arts 28 (Arts in the Philippines) and the class of Fine Arts 30 (Art Pleasures) mounted back-to-back exhibits to culminate the two new courses CFA offered this semester. \nBooks\nBook on simple stone tech launched\nA book on recent archaeological research\nCL launches books\nPart of UP\'s teaching, research and extension\nThree books on reproductive health, gender, rights and ethics were launched by the College of Law, the Office of the Chancellor and Reprocen on March 31\nCory inaugurates CBA lecture room \nCBA dedicates room in honor of Don Anselmo Trinidad\nNo less than former Philippine President Corazon C. Aquino graced the inauguration of the College of Business Administration\'s Don Anselmo Trinidad Sr. Lecture Room on March 15 as the Trinidad Family\'s Special Guest. The former president headed the ribbon cutting while father Patricio Lim performed the invocation and blessing. \nResearch\nTongonan is possible source of electricity\nFindings revealed at CS conference on R&D mathematical tools.\nThe Tongonan Geothermal Field in Leyte, the largest producing geothermal field in the country is a possible source of electricity. \nMilestones\nKicking in a la Jose Nacion Endriga by Dr. Oscar M. Alfonso\nTonight, it\'s the turn of Vice President for Public Affairs Jose Nacion Endriga to be honored by the President and by his colleagues and friends before he takes leave of Quezon Hall. You will listen and you will hear, Joe because the compliments notwithstanding, this is not a necrology. You are alive and kicking, thank our lucky stars for that. Alive and kicking. Must be those acupuncture pricks. \nIn the mail\nBriefly\nRATA for heads without official vehicles\nCredit Co-op holds 58th general assembly\nPolicy on Campus/College journal publications\nUPD adopts no smoking policy\nUPD implements the NGAS\nVarsity Letter Awards reived\nAfter 10 years, CHK again honors UP athletes with \"P\" for performance and Philippines\nAfter a decade of absence, the College of Human Kinetics once again held the UP Varsity Commencement and Recognition Day in honor of UP\'s athletes on March 14, presenting them with the Varsity Letter Awards (VLA)\nThis year\'s UAAP MVPs\nCalulo : women\'s taekwondo by Kristine Silverian P. Calulo, an interior design student only had good memories of the 65th UAAP.\nBreiva : junior table tennis \nWinning the most valuable player (MVP) and rookie of the year (ROY) simultaneously is every athlete\'s dream. Though, some say it is a shot in the dark. \nRemolacio : women\'s fencing \nOnly in her first playing year in the women\'s fencing team, fourth year human kinetics student Ma. Dinah A. Remolacio bagged the gold medal in women\'s foil individual category, while her team won the gold in team category. \nLabon : women\'s judo\nThe UP Women\'s Judo Team again made a statement at the 65th season of the Univerity Athletic Association of the Philippines (UAAP)\nBongga is new CHE dean\nCollege constituents unanimously endorsed former vice chancellor as dean by Haidee C. Pineda\nUnited. That best describes the faculty, staff, students and alumni of the College of Home Economics (CHE) as they unanimously nominated Demetria C. Bongga, erstwhile research and development vice chancellor, the new college dean\nBOR approves policies on teaching outside UP \nViolaters shall be subject to disciplinary action\nAt its 1168th meeting, the Board of Regents (BOR) approved the internal rules and procedures governing teaching outside UP.\nNew challenge for CHE dean\nBongga assumes duty for the love of the College\nWhat would it take to accept a deanship job which is far more different from a very promising position? The answer : love for the college.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(989, 'E2-0989AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XIII, Number 3', '', '', 'May-June 2003', 'Joya, Almario are National Artists \nTo date, 30 National Artists are UP alumni, out of 50 thus far honored. \nBy Prof. Ruben D.F. Defeo\nWith reports filed by Haidee C. Pineda \nTwo UPD artist-administrators-Jose T. Joya, Jr., first dean of the College of Fine Arts (CFA) after its split with the College of Architecture in 1980, and Virgilio S. Almario, newly installed dean of the College of Arts and Letters (CAL)-are proclaimed by President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo as National Artists for the Visual Arts and Literature, respectively, by virtue of Presidential Decree Nos. 383 to 387, signed on May 26, 2003. \nThe cost of UP education\nAlmario)* Pagpapakilala at pagkilala sa makata at kritiko by Dr. Galileo S. Zafra\nBilang makata, sya si Rio Alma. Bilang kritiko, siya si Virgilio S. Almario. Sa larangan ng panitikan, dalawa ang kanyang pangalan dahil kapwa niya puspusang isinulong ang pagtula at kritisismong pampanitikan. Sa katunayan, hindi sapat ang taguring makata at kritiko para saklawin ang kanyang mga akda at gawa sa iba pang larangan ng araling pangwika, edukasyon at administrasyong pangkultura na kasinsigasig niyang sinangkutan. \nUP gears for charter change\nMabuhay, Joya!* Joya finally makes it by Prof. Ruben D.F. Defeo\nLast June 3 was the 72nd birthday anniversary of the late Jose T. Joya Jr. and what a poignant birthday present to him that the official announcement declaring him as National Artist for the Visual Arts this year came out in the papers the same day. \nChacha anyone?\nSenate holds public hearing on proposed UP Charter by Chi A. Ibay\nThe Senate Committee on Education, Arts and Culture with joint committees on ways & means and finance conducted the third public hearing on the proposed UP Charter on May 16 at Pulungang Claro M. Recto, Bulwagang Rizal. Sen. Francis N. Pangilinan, Acting Chair of the Senate Committee on Education, Chaired the Assembly. \nUPD braces for SARS by Chi A. Ibay\nCampus adapts health measures in anticipation of student influx\nIt ain\'t over till it\'s over\nPrimer\nWhat the public should know about SARS?\nResearch\nThe cost of UP education\nHow much does UP spend on its various degree programs? by Bino C. Gamba\nWhich do you think is more costly for UP to offer? Fisheries in UP Visayas or Medicine in UP Manila\nDangerous minds\nDealing with risk behaviors among the Pinoy adolescents by Haidee C. Pineda\nNational hero Jose Rizal once said, \"Ang kabataan ang pag-asa ng bayan.\" without a doubt, the youths are the future leaders, but what if there values are altered by certain behaviors frowned upon by society? \nBooks\nWondering if its bull or bear?\nCBA puts out six new books.\nWell, wonder no more because just hot off the press are six new books from the College of Business Administration that could help you understand money matters or about finance and management, particularly in the Philippines. \nVargas Museum melioration drive \nThe Museum at the heart of UPD gets a facelift \nAlong Roxas Avenue, just beside the Bulwagang Rizal or Faculty Center is the Vargas Museum \nTheater\nChekhov\'s Three Sisters\nPlay opens DUP\'s 28th theatre season.\nConsidered by some critics as the 20th century\'s best drama, Anton Chekhov\'s Three Sisters is a depiction of posh life in a small provincial town outside of Moscow. The play is also dulaang UP\'s 28th theatre season offering. \nCabangis\'s square canvases* by Prof. Ruben D. F. Feleo\nThe abstract idiom is alive, well and kicking! \nBenjie Cabangis\'s Recent Paintings at the Crucible Art Gallery at SM Megamall stands out for showcasing works done in the non-representational, or what is generally referred to as the abstract idiom.\nArtist Talk\nMeps on her art and works\nCajipe-Endaya exhibit and gallery talk usher in Corredor\'s second season\nThe Corredor was packed. Faculty, artists, students and other guests of the night alternately listened and engaged the artist in a conversation - for even if it was a lecture, Gallery Talk, at the College of Fine Arts on June 19 was a lively interaction between Imelda Cajipe-Endaya, the artist, and her guests.\nThree-in-one show\nDasco, Briones, Valenzuela @ the West\nIf literature has its three musketeers and opera has its three tenors, three young artists- Denes Dasco, Hoche Briones, and Byron Valenzuela - have also banded together to mount three solo exhibits simultaneously happening at the West Gallery in SM Megamall. \nBriefly...\nCBA graduate tops CPA board\nNetwork awards outstanding CMC graduates\nNISMED trains science teachers on air \nSix more professional chairs for CBA \nP50 fee for replacement of stale or lost checks\nHappy birthday UP!\nUP turns 95. \nThe University of the Philippines turned 95 this year. UP was created on June 18, 1908. From a single campus in Manila, UP evolved into seven constituent universities in 11 campuses. \nUPD welcomes 3,000 freshmen\nScholars get a taste of UP life in the day-long fete\nFree food, free ride, free concert-freebies everywhere! Ah! the perks of being a freshman. \nAnd more briefly...\nInfo science seminar\nFilm students reap awards\n2 law alumni, UP\'s most outstanding \nArmando J. Malay* by Prof. Oscar L. Evangelista, Retired professor of History\nThe activist dean \nI first met Armando Malay in the Philippine Embassy in Rome in 1962 when I, with four other students from Cairo University, went on a month-long tour of Southern Europe. \nIn memoriam\nArmando Malay\nFarewell to the dean\nArmando J. Malay Sr., 89, former professor of journalism and communication died last May 15 from a stroke in Quezon City\nMaramag\nSpecial police captain of the UPD police, Florentino T. Maramag, 62 died of Myocardial infarction last May 30. \nCesar Concio\nAdieu to the campus architect\nCesar Homero Concio Sr., 96, the University\'s First University Architect died of old age, May 27 in Quezon City.\nElisa P. Arreza\nEducation Professor and Chair of the College of Education (CE) Divisions of Educational Leadership in Professional Services, Elisa Paqueo Arreza, 60, passed away June 3 of Bronchogenic Cancer. \nPanganiban\nElena Masangkay Panganiban, 59, former executive director of the local government academy, Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG, 1997-2000) and faculty at the National College of Public Administration and Governance (NCPAG), died of acute respiratory failure last June 22. \nMilestones \nEster Albano Garcia* Activisme Exemplaire by Dr. Oscar M. Alfonso\nSo. It has to come to this : the parting of the ways between Ester Albano Garcia and the government service that she graced. The way of all flesh. What a pity! \nThe importance of being Ernie \nPineda\'s goal : serve what the academe needs with speed, effectiveness and efficiency by Haidee C. Pineda\nJudging from his busy schedule that only allows him to grant brief and straightforward interviews, the new administration vice chancellor, is bent in providing the University\'s units with logistic support in terms of speed, efficiency and effectiveness without compromising the requirements of the existing bureaucratic rules. \nUP appointments \nDalisay is new VP for public affairs\nMulti-awarded writer, columnist and english professor Jose \"Butch\" Y. Dalisay, was appointed as the new UP Vice President for Public Affairs, succeeding another Jose-Jose N. Endirga, who retired on March 20. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(990, 'E2-0990AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XIV, Number 2', '', '', 'April-June 2004', 'A devoted teacher, a grateful scholar and the staples of a UPD graduation : what UPD graduates would remember in the 93rd commencement exercises. \nJust seven year\'s shy from its 100th anniversary, the UPD commencement exercises this year had the main ingredients of any graduation.\nISKO : higit sa lahat bayan!* I thank Chancellor Roman for inviting me to address you on this 93rd general commencement exercises of the University of the Philippines Diliman.\nArt and Culture\nAlumni Matters\nUPAA cites Manny Villar, Dolly Hernandez as this year\'s most distinguished alumni\n14 UPD alumni honored at 2004 homecoming.\nExemplary public service dedication to the development of science and mathematics education - are the achievements that earned for Senator Manuel B. Villar (BSBA \'70; MBA \'73) and educator Dolores F. Hernandez (BSE \'48 Cum Laude; Med \'56), this year\'s top honors at the UP Alumni Association (UPAA) Awards and Grand Alumni Homecoming on June 26. \nNostalgic and responsive by Irwin Allen B. Rivera\nThe UP alumni come home.\nAlumni get more involved in activities as they get older, especially the golden jubilarians - homecoming lolos and lolas enrolled at UP at the end of World War II\nAlumni council resolution no. 2004-1\nCalling on the UPAA membership, and strongly urging them to work for the adoption an implemented of UPAC resolution nos. 2003-1 and 2003-2, both dated June 20, 2003, on a Philippine Population Growth Policy\nA night of music, dancing and reminiscing\nThe 2004 Grand Alumni Homecoming\nAfter decades of not seeing each other, isn\'t it exciting to know what happened to your college friends, block mates or seatmates?\nThe truths of enrolemt growth in RP\nOnly 1 out of 2 students reach 4th year high school by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nThe country\'s growth in enrolment is very high compared to other developing countries. From this statement, one may gather that Philippine education is quite impressive. \n\'MICS\' test...it works! Senior eng\'g stude acclaimed for software development \nIn the recently concluded alumni gathering at the Ang Bahay ng Alumni, Senior Engineering Student Leonardo D. Pabroquez Jr. stood inconspicously together with his doting family for a photo-op. \nCBA alumni fund modernization projects \nUp for renovation are CBA classrooms, and seminar and lecture rooms. \nWith help from the College of Business Administration (CBA) Class of 1973, the college will be completing the renovation of nine rooms this year. \nPublic lecture\nKeeping connected\nStudy finds cellphone is a potent tool for the urban poor by Chi A. Ibay\nMore than luho or a luxury item, the cellular phone (cellphone) has become a necessity to the urban poor because among its other uses, it is an efficient tool for \"unity and concerted action.\"\nStat turns gold! \nKicks off anniv activities by transferring to new home\nWhat better way to turn a year older than by finding a new home to make a fresh start \n\"A monumental book by a remarkable author\"* by Prof. Hal Hill\nH.W. Arndt Professor of Southeast Asian Economies \nAustralian National University\nCanberra, Australia\nThis is a monumental book by a remarkable author, the living father of the modern economics profession in the Philippines, and arguably the most eminent academic economist in Southeast Asia. \nThe Political Economy of Permanent Crisis in the Philippines\nby Prof. Gerardo M. Lanuza\nDepartment of Sociology\nCollege of Social Sciences and Philosophy\nWalden Bello with Herbert Docena, Marissa De Guzman and May Lou Malig, The Anti-Development State : The Political Economy of Permanent Crisis in the Philippines, Department of Sociology, College of Social Sciences and Philosophy, 2004. pp. 342 + xiii.\nThe most recent book of Walden Bello, The Political Economy of Permanent Crisis in the Philippines, which he co-authored with three younger research assistants, has once again proven how prolific Walden is as an author. \nTaking a different route by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nBOR approves UPD request for units to draw their own selection process for deans. \nNine units - five in June and four in July - would be undergoing search for their respective deans. In an unprecedented event, these UPD units will adopt their own selection process. \nPeople\nMapping out SURP\'s future \nNew dean reveals his 10-year strategic plan\nYou are barely two months in your post as Dean. To your knowledge, UP has a limited budget. In addition, there is an exodus of junior faculty members and senior faculty in your unit are about to retire. \nSearch for next UP President on\nThe UP Board of Regents invites nominations until 5 P.M. of July 30, for the UP President who will succeed Dr. Francisco Nemenzo whose term expires on February 9, 2005. The UP Charter empowers the boad to appoint the president. \nGuidelines on professional chairs and faculty grants\nKeeping it practical \nCSWCD dean bares three-fold agenda\nHe expressed interest. No one else ran. He presented his vision/mission to the College constituents. From there, he was endorsed by the College to the Officials, was sworn in and on May 1st, Romeo Cortel Quieta, PH.D. and university professor was appointed as the new dean of the College of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD).\nBriefly\nDILC Sino-RP Friendship Room inaugurated\nVisual Arts\n\"Surprising\" Singapore by Bino C. Gamba\nVinluan exhibits in the Lion City.\nNestor Olarte Vinluan, two-time Gawad Chanselor para sa pinakamahusay na alagad ng sining awardee, could have set his residency in Singapore a year ago had not the SARS (Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome) epidemic spread like wild fire across Asia. Singapore was one of the countries hardest hit by the deadly virus. This time around, he was able to mount an exhibit at the Lion City without any glitch.  \nCinema\nFilm 101 : Behind the scenes... by Haidee C. Pineda\nSix renowned film directors talk about the art of filmmaking \nLights! Camera! Action!\nHappy Birthday Earth!\nWith one voice...\nVarious sectors fete Mother Earth.\nThe mood may be festive, but the call was serious : rehabilitate Earth!\nMusic\nTriumph of the great voice\nTenor\'s formidable voice reaches Vietnam and Thailand. \nAt first glance, he seems like an eccentric, burly man with fuchsia pink-dyed hair whose muscled arms and firm grip could crush your bones into pieces. \nResearch\nPhilippines\' western coast has high levels of EDC by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nEDCs are found in highly agricultural and major industrial areas\nDid you know that high levels of organochlorine pesticides (OCPs), phenols and phthalates exist along the Philippines\' Western Coast, including the Greater Manila Area?\nAssessing dyslexia in Filipinos by Riza A. Romero\nPsychologist develops test to assess dyslexia in Filipinos\nOne out of 10 Filipinos has Dyslexia, reports the local newspaper Philippine Daily Inquirer\nDoing what comes naturally* by Dr. Oscar M. Alfonso\nI asked to be allowed to say something because I would like to speak for Caring as well as for myself. But more like for Caring, because of her long association with CPA/NCPAG. And I cannot let Joe and Romy ride into the sunset as if I were entirely oblivious of this Parangal for them this evening. \nIn Memoriam\nNational artist Maceda, 87\nNational artist for music Jose M. Maceda passed away on May 5. He was 87. \nJose Maceda\'s lifelong quest for traditional Filipino music by Prof. Ruben D. F. Defeo\nHe was known for his improvisations that paved the way for new trends in composition. \nThere was certainly a European Air about him. A ubiquitous figure on campus-usually in white polo shirt, khaki pants and sandals-Jose Monserrat Maceda was more than a university institution. \nWe hear his music still*\nTwo deaths, two national artists, not one week\'s blink apart. If the country\'s cultural grandparents were leaves on a tree, May is the autumn of our loss. \nRebillon, 72\nAn abuse of power and breach of trust by Dr. Carlo A. Arcilla\nAssociate Professor of Geology\nCollege of Science \nDuring the Diliman Graduation Rites last April 25, 2004, President Nemenzo (again) administered his own version of \"Panunumpa\" to the 2004-graduating batch. \nSights and symbols\nEvery UPD graduation always has its own distinctive \"flavor.\" \nIsang hamon sa kapwa scholar\nApat, limang taon ang nakararaan nang una kang yumapak dito sa kampus. Manghang-mangha ka pa nga-ang lawak ng UP, ang daming puno, luntian ang kapaligiran, ang gaganda ng mga gusali. Humanga ka sa institusyon na tatayong pangalawang tahanan mo sa susunod na mga araw. \nUPD inks tie up with Nat\'l Defense, DOST\nThe MOU seeks to advance the country\'s military capability\nHeads of three government institutions met this June to sign a memorandum of understanding (MOU) that will boost the country\'s efforts to make the defense esctor self-reliant. \nOVCCA turns over vehicles to UPDP\nThe purchase was made possible by BCO.\nAt last! UPDP has new patrol cars.\nKudos to Benjie!\nUPD commends VIC guard.\nThe Office of the Vice Chancellor for Community Affairs recognized in May the prompt response of S.G. Benjamin Barba to a plea of a cell phone-snatching victim that led to the immediate arrest of a robbery suspect.\nConstituent universities celebrate UP\'s 96th Foundation Day\nOne in spirit and united even in cyberspace\nThe seven campuses comprising the UP System simultaneously marked the 96th founding anniversary of the University on June 18. Thanks largely to advances in information and communication technologies. \nUPD welcomes future centennial graduates\nCampus had 3,822 UPCAT qualifiers\nThe freshman assembly is an annual event to formally receive the campus\' newest batch of students. What distinguished it from the yearly rite were the honorees themselves-the freshmen who, in four years time, were to hopefully graduate in 2008, the University\'s Centennial. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(991, 'E2-0991AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XV, Number 1', '', '', 'February 10, 2005', 'Roman takes the helm as 19th UP President\nThe first woman president is the centennial president. \nIt\'s all system go. Today, the University of the Philippines (UP) makes its date with history as Dr. Emerlinda R. Roman assumes the top post as 19th President. Roman is the first woman president of the 97 year-old institution. Serving a 6-year term, she enjoys the distinction of being the centennial president since three years from now in 2008, UP will celebrate its 100 years of existence. \nThe women of Malolos \nBook Review\nProfile \nOutgoing helmsman\nSo many things can happen in six years - the length of service by a UP president. Outgoing University helsman Francisco \"Dodong\" Nemenzo looks back at the maelmstroms he faced, as he tried not merely to keep the boat afloat, but decide which course it would take, and steady its sails to that direction, however strong the winds may have been. \nAll in a day\'s work\nOn the 5-year watch of UPD Chancellor Emerlinda R. Roman (CERR), there has been relative quiet on campus : no discordant emotional debates over issues at the University Council meetings nor protest actions either. For at the heart of UPD\'s chancellor is a woman who seeks to set aside peripheral matters to address the more essential concerns. \nResearch\nThe new\"Nanay\" by Bino C. Gamba\nFemale OFWs tell how it is. \nThe government\'s inability to generate enough jobs and adequate income drives millions of Filipinos to work abroad and leave their families in search for greater monetary returns for their labor. \nBook review\nThe women of Malolos* \nFighting for right to education\nby Dr. Milagros C. Guerrero\nDepartment of History\nCollege of Social Sciences and Philosophy\n*A critique of the book, \"The Women of Malolos\" by Dr. Nicanor G. Tiongson, Ateneo de Manila University Press, 2004.\nThe period between 1850 and 1920, around which revolves Dr. Nicanor G. Tiongson\'s book is a particularly tumultuous one. Within this period took place the terror of 1872, the manifestation of 1888, the propaganda-reformist period, the Philippine revolution and the Filipino-American War. \nResolution of the University Council of the University of the Philippines Diliman on the Election of the Next University President \nProfessorial Chair Lecture\nRevisiting the 1946 fiscal crisis\nFormer National Treasurer Briones draws from the past to illumine the present-day fiscal crisis.\nIn August 2004, President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo announced the country was in fiscal crisis. Although the news did not come as a shock to most Filipinos, the admittance of the chief executive confirmed the people\'s fears that the Philippines was in dire straits. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
