(992, 'E2-0992AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XV, Number 5', '', '', 'September 7, 2005', 'Devotion, sacrifice, and accountable performance\nThe investiture of Dr. Sergio S. Cao as 8th UPD Chancellor\nBy Irwin Allen B. Rivera\n\"You who refused to work in other companies and teach in other schools share with me the enduring faith that UP is an institution worthy of devoting the best years of our lives.\" Said Dr. Sergio S. Cao in his speech at the investiture rites on September 7 at the UP Film Institute (see full text of the investiture address on page 1A)\nPresidential message\nAmong the University of the Philippines\' seven constituent universities, UP Diliman (UPD) is the biggest in terms of the number of students, number of faculty, number of degree-granting units and number of academic program offerings. As the largest campus, it deserves a most competent, dedicated and able leader who will lead this campus toward contributing to UP\'s aspiration to be a distinguished Filipino university in the 21st century. \nPaglilingkod at pananatili sa UP nating mahal* by Sergio S. Cao, Chancellor\nKagalang-galang na lupon ng mga rehente, presidente Emerlinda Roman, your excellencies, members of the diplomatic corps, mga presidente at pinuno ng ibang unibersidad at kolehiyo, mga piling panauhin mula sa loob at labas ng unibersidad, magandang hapon sa inyong lahat. Salamat sa inyong pagdalo sa aking investiture bilang ikawalong Chanselor ng UP Diliman. \nVoice of UP Diliman*\nBy Oscar M. Alfonso\n(Former member of the UP Board of Regents and retired UP Professor of History)\nIn the dusk of life, gifts of great moment come few and rare. Few come rarer thatn the singular honor and privilege accorded me today by Chancellor Sergio S. Cao of UP Diliman to present him during his investiture. Proof once more that pleasant surprises still lie in wait in late life. \n10-point agenda\nUPD action plan (2005-2008)*\nUniversity of the Philippines President Emerlinda R. Roman laid down her administration\'s plans and projects for the University\'s next six years in UP Plan (2005-2011). The President\'s plan has three major components : commemorating the UP Centennial, strengthening UP\'s stature as a center of excellence and culture, and transforming UP into an efficient university. \nOCES meets the press\nThe executive staff of UP Diliman (UPD) led by Chancellor Sergio S. Cao was formally introduced to members of the media on September 1, at a press conference held at Katre Restaurant on Scout Lascano along Tomas Morato Avenue in Quezon City.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(993, 'E2-0993AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XVII, Number 3', '', '', 'November-December 2007', 'BOR approves UPD Centennial Professorial Chairs and Faculty Grants by Chi A. Ibay\nSelection process for Chairs and grants is ongoing.\nOne hundred new professorial chairs and faculty grants, have been established for UP Diliman (UPD) following its approval by the Board of Regents (BOR) on August 22. \nNew knowledge is new power\nEnhanced grants yield promising new researches\nResearch is a major thrust at UP Diliman (UPD). Through the years, UPD faculty and researchers have made immense contributions to the upliftment of the Filipino society through their significant and strategic research outputs. \nEng\'g, Science on full throttle\nNational gov\'t sets aside nearly P2B to boost S&T.\nThe College of Engineering (CoE) and the College of Science (CS) are each getting a welcome shot in the arm as the national government pledged nearly P2 billion in resources to help increase the University\'s research and technology capacity. \nMaking sense of it all : anatomy of power rates\nThe power bill under scrutiny by Anna E. Regidor\nIn an era where energy and energy sources make or break entire economies and power has become as much a commodity as potable water, the generation and price of power is a major issue. \nPower to the people \nMaking Sariaya, Quezon the next tourist spot by Shirley S. Arandia\nWhat is the relationship among tourism, architecture, music, home economics and human kinetics?\nChristmas on Campus by Shirley S. Arandia and Anna E. Regidor\nFrom Quezon Hall to the UP Theater, campus guests and residents were treated to a dazzling array of festive activities\nMusic and dance came together to the tune of the Yuletide as UP Diliman (UPD) started off its Christmas celebrations with a twin bill extravaganza that pooled the University\'s most prestigious dance groups. \nIt\'s back, but where\'s the beef? by Chi A. Ibay\nThe Lantern Parade returns as people power.\nUP Diliman\'s annual parade of lanterns thankfully proceeded as scheduled on December 19, its comeback made even more anticipated, being right smack on the eve of the much publicized centennial of the University. \n2007 Christmas contest winners\nThe Office of the Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs announced the winners in the competitions held as part of the Christmas festivities at UP Diliman, a week after the Lantern Parade. \nFine Arts exhibit in NYC by Prof. Ruben D.F. Defeo\nImages of UP landmarks trigger alumni to take a trip down memory lane.\nThe nippy early evening weather outside was no match for the warm reception accorded the UP Landmarks Sketchbook Exhibition at the Philippine Center on Fifth Avenue in New York City, USA. \nNo joking matter \nYoung Ph.D. attempts to define Pinoy humor by Shirley S. Arandia\nWhy is Dolphy considered the \"King of Comedy?\" Why do we use markers like \"joke, joke, joke!\" even if we really want to speak our mind? Why do we find \"Hello Garci\" and Erap jokes so funny?\nMobile phones bring change in indigenous peoples by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nStudy shows cultural communities now have consumerist values with the advent of mobile phone use.\nThe mobile phone has successfully brought the indigenous peoples (IPs) closer to mainstream Filipino society and made it easier for the government to deliver services to them. The mobile phone also inadvertently introduced the IP to the consumerist values of the rest of society. \nICW applauds the birth of Likhaan\nJournal on contemporary Philippine literature launched on Writer\'s Night.\nIn a week that saw the College of Arts and Letters (CAL) lose two of its beloved professors, a birth in the family is a reliable way to lessen the gloom. \nPaalam\nNabahiran ng kalungkutan ang pagdiriwang ng Kolehiyo ng Arte at Literature (KAL) ng anibersaryo ng kanilang pagkatatag nang dalawa sa kanilang pinakapipitagang mga guro ang sabay na pumanaw noong Disyembre 5.\nEurope and Asia promote efficient lighting\n5 universities converge to develop curricula on energy efficiency by Anna E. Regidor\nEnergy efficiency is becoming an increasingly important concern in today\'s world. Rising oil prices and increasing energy consumption have reached greater heights than any other point in history.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(994, 'E2-0994AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XVIII, Number 1', '', '', 'January-March 2008', 'Lighting the way by Anna E. Regidor\nUP opens Centennial Year with an extravaganza\nFireworks, festivities and a symbolic flame. The University of the Philippines celebrated its centennial with a spectacle worthy of the 100-year wait. \nUP launches Centennial Lecture Series\n30 distinguished individuals share ideas on various concerns\nThe Office of the President has lined up a series of public lectures in various fields by distinguished scholars, academicians and personalities as a \"milestone activity and a vital component of the celebration of the University\'s 100th year of academic excellence and service to the nation.\"\nLaureate urges world gov\'t to achieve true humanity\nPhysicist Gross delivers first lecture at the UP Centennial Lecture Series by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nNobel laureate David Jonathan Gross espoused that every nation must now move towards a world government where internationalism is advocated. \nYou too can do it!\nCelebrated scientist exhorts the youth with his success story by Chi A. Ibay\nYes, even budding scientists can look forward to a hugely successful and rewarding career as internationally renowned scholars and researchers. The 2007 Harvard Scientist of the Year, Dr. Baldomero Olivera showed us how. \nThe UP Centennial kick-off in photos\nTaking charge\nNemenzo calls for reconstruction of education and a return to idealism by Anna E. Regidor\nReaction and revolution were the names of the game in the March 10 Centennial Lecture entitled \"Beyond the Classroom : Rebuilding a Damaged Nation\" as former UP president Dr. Francisco Nemenzo outlined his recommendations to improve the country\'s political conditions. \nReducing poverty in the Philippines\nLecture helps understand the reasons and create solutions by Bino C. Gamba\nReducing poverty can be realized through pro-poor development agenda by the national government such as scaling up investment in quality education and health, credit markets for education and small enterprises, an active population management program, sustained increase in labor demand coupled with producing highly-skilled workers and efficient social safety nets programs.\nDouglass North and the crisis of institutions*\nA casual glance at the Philippine dailies suggests that the country is a pit of institutional dysfunction by Raul V. Fabella, Ph.D. Former Dean, School of Economics\nManila, Philippines - A casual glance at the Philippine dailies suggests that the country is a pit of institutional dysfunction. The economy is growing but the growth is still largely externally driven by the overseas workers industry, which grew fortunately behind the government\'s back and beyond its grasp. In fact the most dynamic local sector, the BPO, grows precisely because it avoids government-provided services (ports and transport) and funnels its business into cyberspace courtesy of private telcos. \nKomedya sa Kampus\nUPD celebrates Diliman Month with First National Komedya Festival by Shirley S. Arandia\nIn celebration of the UP Centennial, the Office of the Chancellor, through the College of Arts and Letters (CAL) presented Komedya Fiesta 2008 : First National Festival from February 1 to 29, 2008 at the University Amphitheater. \nPreserving the past, sustaining a future\nCA inaugurates Museum of Filipino Architecture by Anna E. Regidor\nFrom the towering pyramids of Egypt to the quintessential Nipa Hut, one of the most concrete reflections of a culture is its architecture. At UP Diliman (UPD), often described as \"the Philippines in microcosm,\" a glimpse of the country\'s modern history can now be seen at the College of Architecture (CA).\nGawad Chanselor cash incentives increased, 13 honored\nAudience appreciates this year\'s more sober ceremony.\nUP Diliman\'s plum award just got better.\nCarrying on the tradition of excellence \nParangal sa mag-aaral rites emphasize learning beyond the classroom.\nThe UP education boasts a holistic development. A UP student must constantly strive to achieve both academic and non-academic excellence. \nAdieu and thank you!\nUPD fetes retirees and service awardees.\nIf there is a chance for any average employee to be recognized by the University, it is at the Parangal sa mga Retirado at Gawad Paglilingkod (PRGP), the annual program mounted by the UP Diliman administration to acknowledge the services and loyalty of its faculty, administrative staff (AS) and Research, Extension and Professional Staff (REPS).\nOn the qui vive for fundamentalism\nCentennial lecture figure in the month of women\nBy Bino C. Gamba\nFundamentalism, in varied forms, imperils the achievements and further growth of women as a sector in the country and in the world. This recaps the three lectures that Dr. Carolyn I. Sobritchea, former director of UP Center for Women\'s Studies (UPCWS), bring to the fore an important issue that has been hampering efforts to uphold gender equality and threatening the advancement of the emancipation of women. \nIn memoriam \nVictoria A. Bautista\nGaudencio T. Chan\nEmmanuel G. Gregorio\nCesar N. Padugar\nEditha P. dela Rosa\nRaquel R. Tuazon\nCarlos Perez Valino, Jr.\nRomeo S. Yumul\nArnel C. Zafra\nNEC turns 30\nCelebrating three decades of excellence in research and training\nNEC\'s the O.N.E. : working from the inside out\nUPD students shine at MACD 2008\nby Chi A. Ibay\nInventions of six student teams from the University of the Philippines Diliman (UPD) bagged the top prizes in the 2008 Microcontroller Applications Design Competition (MACD).', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(995, 'E2-0995AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XVIII, Number 3', '', '', 'July-September 2008', 'Briefly\nUP grads get 100% passing in dietitian licensure board\nGovernment salaries increased \nUPD Centennial Professorial Chair awardees named \n51 comprise first batch\nUP Diliman Chancellor Sergio S. Cao awarded the Centennnial Professorial Chairs to 51 faculty members during the University Council meeting held July 21. \nNewsmakers\nSmells like school spirit\nUP Pep win highlights the year UP hosts the UAAP.\n\"Tribo UP\" marched away with the spoils on September 7 as the UP Pep Squad clinched its second straight UAAP Cheerdance Competition (CDC) Championship title. \nUPAK brings home 2 silvers, 2 bronzes\nCaesar Saloma is 2008 outstanding scientist\nCS dean recognized for his contributions to photonics and signal processing\nDr. Caesar A. Saloma, dean of the College of Science (CS) and professor at the National Institute of Physics (NIP), is the recipient of the prestigious 2008 ASEAN Outstanding Scientist and Technologist (AOST) Award. \nAnother feather in the cap\nNIP professor honored for his contributions in S&T\nNoted scientist and National Institute of Physics (NIP) professor Dr. Henry J. Ramos received another accolade from the Department of Science and Technology (DOST). Ramos was named one of the \"50 Men and Women of Science\" during the DOST\'s Golden Anniversary celebrations at the Manila Hotel on September 10. \nA bevy of awards\nFaculty, alumni reap awards in literary tilts.\nThe year 2008 proved to be not just a celebration of the University\'s history, but also its brilliance as 41 faculty and alumni are feted in three of the country\'s most prominent awards. \nGrad student is UNAP outstanding youth leader\nAwardee cited for his support to young artists\nCarlito Camahalan Amalla, a student currently pursuing a Master of Arts in Art Studies at the College of Arts and Letters, is one of the five Outstanding Youth Service awardees of the United Nations Association of the Philippines (UNAP).\nCentennial Lectures\nKeeping activism alive\nSatur Ocampo believes the spirit of revolution stays aflame despite new charter. \nBy Anna Kristin Regidor\nThe University is known for its activism almost as much as its excellence. Even in today\'s globalized world, this spirit remains alive, said Rep. Satur Ocampo (Bayan Muna) in his Centennial Lecture on July 10 at the NISMED Auditorium.\nMapping out the path to enduring peace\nFormer president relates lesson learned in pursuing peace and development\nBy Albino C. Gamba\nSearching for answers\nBusiness icon raises questions and challenges UP\nBy Albino C. Gamba\nBusiness patriarch Dr. Washington Sycip posed straightforward questions to UP in the Centennial Lecture \"Questions for the Future of UP\" held September 3 at the National Institute for Science and Mathematics Education Development Auditorium. \nCentennial Lectures\nInternet age reporting and traditional values\nVeteran journalist defines the musts in the changing media landscape\nBy Chi A. Ibay\nThe Internet has brought about \"seismic shifts\" in the way news is produced, disseminated and used. However, news organizations that will succeed are those \"that embrace the possibilities offered by the new technologies without letting go of the values that have traditionally defined journalism : the defense of public interest, the discipline of verification and the provision of a forum for community dialogue.\"\nMaking a sense of peace\nIdea, intention and elements of the right to peace in the 1987 Constitution \nBy Chi A. Ibay\nAng UP bilang pamanang bayan\nMga kuwento sa likod ng mahahalagang monumento sa UP Diliman\nBy Floyd Padilla\nInformation Office\nCollege of Social Sciences and Philosophy\nNauna kang dumating nung umagang iyon sa AS lobby, kung saan napagkasunduan ng inyong grupo sa Kas 1 na magkita para talakayin ang nalalapit ninyong pag-uulat sa klase. Alas diyes ng umaga, mag-isa kang naghihintay at tanging kasama mo ang relo na nakapagkit sa dingding malapit sa may paanan ng hagdan patungo sa ikawalang palapag ng Palma Hall. \nCarillon tower : rebuilding a legacy by Roel M. Avante\nThe UPAA\'s Carillon Restoration Project gives new meaning to the phrase \"labor of love.\"\nOn August 1, 1952, the love of the UP Alumni Association (UPAA) for its Alma Mater paved the way for the 130-ft Carillon Tower - a structure that exemplifies the spirit of the alumni community. \nMSI wins prestigious international prize\nAward recognizes the Institute\'s contributions to the marine environment.\nThe Marine Science Institute of the University of the Philippines Diliman (UP MSI) is one of the two awardees of the Calouste Gulbenkian International Prize 2008.\nEngineering hosts research confab\nThe College heads consortium to map out the country\'s engineering research and development agenda.\nTwo heads are better than one. Or in this case, seven. \nDissecting power rates structure\nStudy tackles ways to save on electricity costs.\nPower rates could be reduced by at least P2 per kilowatt-hour (kWh). This was the gist of a forum eld at the Engineering Theater of Melchor Hall on August 4.\nNew academic heads assume posts\nAguirre is new SLIS dean; Barrios for the School of Statistics\nTwo new administrators assumed the top post in their respective colleges, following their appointments by the Board of Regents on August 29. \nLico is new campus architect\nThe Office of the Campus Architect (OCA) has a new office-in-charge in the person of Dr. Gerard Lico.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(996, 'E2-0996AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XVIII, Number 4', '', '', 'October - December 2008', 'Briefly\nUP artists\'/art scholars\' outstanding feats recognized through APS\nUPD Centennial Professorial Chair awardees named, part II\n29 comprise second batch; 21 receive centennial faculty grant. \nBy Chi A. Ibay\nTwenty-nine faculty members received the UPD Centennial Professorial Chair Award while 21 were awarded the Centennial Faculty Grant by Chancellor Sergio S. Cao on December 11. The awardees constitute the July 1, 2008 to June 30, 2009 cycle. \nEnhancing society\'s bioethic sensitivity\nDe Castro outlines help for the faceless and the voiceless.\nBy Floyd Padilla\nInformation Office\nCollege of Social Sciences and Philosophy\nIs donating an organ bad, even if one saves a life? This was one of the burning questions that confronted Dr. Leonardo De Castro of the Philosophy department following his Rafael Palma Centennial Lecture entitled, \"Bioethics from Below : Listening to the Disadvantaged and Vulnerable\" held last September 23 at the Palma Hall Room 207.\nForum to improve classroom performance\nAddressing one of the main problems plaguing Philippine public education was the main topic of Pagbabago sa Silid-Aralin : Kung Hindi Ngayon, Kailan? held at the Benitez Theater last December 2.\nMonochromed Memories makes a splash in Paris\nUNESCO celebrates UP Centennial\nBy Prof. Ruben D.F. Defeo\nMonochromed Memories : UP Landmarks Centennial Exhibition made a splash last quarter of 2008 at the Salle de Pas Perdus, Maison de l\'UNESCO, in Paris. As one of the activities to cap the UP centennial festivities, the exhibit afforded the international audience glimpses of a heritage educational environment in the Philippines.\nCentennial Lectures\nTaking on the IP question\nLeonen et al. argue for the indigenous and disadvantaged. \nBy Anna Kristine E. Regidor\nOurs is a nation marked by its diversity. Even on a geographical level, the 7,100 islands that make it up necessitates great and deep thought to equal and fair legal treatment for all the people that inhabit it, especially those who live in the peripheries of the mainstream.\nWhat\'s in store for UP in the 21st century?\nDiokno proposes strategies to face new challenges in higher learning.\nBy Chi A. Ibay\nThere are three things the Univresity of the Philippines must do to face the challenges of higher education in the 21st century. \nToday\'s Pinoy English is a result of gradual drift in language\nMalicsi says English in RP is changing. \nBy Floyd Padilla\nInformation Officer\nCollege of Social Sciences and Philosophy\nThe English language in the Philippines has continued to change ever since English has been used as the country\'s official language and the medium of instruction during the American colonial period. Dr. Jonathan Malicsi, Professor of Linguistics, identified some factors in the evolution of Philippine English, in his Rafael Palma Centennial Lecture on August 8, entitled \"Pinoy English : A Case of Language Drift.\"\nCentennial Lectures\nEducation redux\nBautista et al. discuss the challenges in reforming Philippine education by Anna Kristine Regidor\nA house is only as good as its foundations, and Philippine public education, one of the country\'s pillars, is in need of a reformat.\nExamining UP\'s role in RP\'s industrial policy\nMagpantay : poor funding stems from weak industry by Albino C. Gamba \n\"Since UP claims to be the best in the country, the training ground of our leaders and the source of our nation\'s economic planners, I would also like to examine the accountability of UP, if any, in the country\'s failure to develop the industry.\" - Dr. Jose A. Magpantay\nFaculty unleashed\nFun and frivolity during the holidays by Anna Kristine E. Regidor\nSometimes it\'s good to just let go. The University Theater became party central last December 15 when students and professors came together to celebrate the Centennial in the most hilarious way. \nFYI by Chi A. Ibay\nWhy the Lantern Parade was a no-see for many. \nIt was touted as the parade of the century, capping UP Diliman\'s year-long celebration of the university\'s centenary. With thousands packing the campus, participation was supreme and way beyond expectation. \nChristmas merriment, the UPD way\nA remarkable celebration to end the year and UP\'s centenary.\nUPD ushered in the Yuletide season on December 2 with the traditional rites of lighting the campus at the Oblation Plaza. As expected, the crowd started to flock at the venue as early as 5 in the afternoon, eagerly awaiting the event. \nNIGS professor honored\nLagmay wins PCASTRD outstanding R&D prize. \nThe University of the Philippines Diliman (UPD) re-affirmed its place as a leading producer of outstanding research and researchers with the recognition of National Institute of Geological Sciences (NIGS) professor Dr. Alfredo Mahar Francisco A. Lagmay\'s research by the Philippine Council for Advanced Science and Technology Research and Development (PCASTRD) last December. \nUPD teams dominate national programming contest \nUP bags top 3 spots in nat\'l programming tilt. \n(UP-ITTC)--Three UP Diliman student teams bagged the top three prizes in the Association for Computing Machinery -- 2nd Philippine National Inter-Collegiate Programming Competition (ACM ICPC Philippines 2008), besting 39 teams from 24 schools throughout the country who joined the national competition. It was held November 22 at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) in Basak, Cebu City.\nDemography paves way for \"population thinking\" in RP\nRaymundo says demography is one of the most technically sophisticated social sciences by Floyd Padilla, Information Officer, College of Social Sciences  and Philosophy\nDemography has made \"population thinking\" possible in the country and population scientist Dr. Corazon M. Raymundo. 3-term director of the UP Population Institute (UPPI), maintained that this phenomenon can be considered as the discipline\'s major contribution since its inception in the early 1960s. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(997, 'E2-0997AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XVIII, Number 4', '', '', 'July-December 2009', 'OCES reports on projects implemented\nPrograms and projects to take UPD into its 2nd century by Chi A. Ibay\nDr. Sergio S. Cao, chancellor of the University of the Philippines Diliman (UPD), reports on the projects, programs and initiatives of his administration from March 2005. \nModern teachers for the knowledge society\nMajor initiatives make the UPD faculty globally competitive.\nThe faculty is the university\'s greatest resource. \nUPEPP responds to challenges\nNew strategies assert UP\'s presence in the region. \nThe impressive socio-economic growth in Central Luzon has prompted the University to draw up a strategic plan for the UP Extension Program in Pampanga (UPEPP). To strengthen UP\'s presence in the region, Director Julieta Mallari has addressed the growing demand for quality education. \nSpanning the world\nCollaborations with international universities make UPD globally competitive by Chi A. Ibay\nInternationalization is a major policy of the UPD Administration.\nBearing fruit\nOpen Grant yields good crop of researches by Anna Regidor\nResearch, one of the University\'s core functions, took center stage in the last five years with the launching of the Open Grant and the Ph.D. Incentive Grant. \nPh.D. incentive awards carry on\nHelps new PH.D.s jumpstart their career\nWhile the Open Grant shone the spotlight on the more ambitious project, the Ph.D. Incentive Award (PIA) got nitty-gritty with the smaller researches that provide the building blocks for creative and groundbreaking output. \nLikhaan upholds tradition\nCreative Writing journal continues to be a dynamic platform for Philippine literature. \nAmong the myriad of publications that came out during UP\'s Centennial Year, few are more meaningful or more necessary than the UP Institute of Creative Writing (ICW)\'s centennial offering : Likhaan : The Journal of Contemporary Philippine Literature. \nGiving their due\nUPD provides counterpart funds for large-scale projects.\nGawad Saliksik sa wika\nFunds support research and use of Filipino.\nIn support of the Kahusayan sa Saliksik sa Wikang Filipino, the Office of the Chancellor (OC), under the administration of Chancellor Sergio S. Cao, allotted a P10 million endowment fund to the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Research and Development (OVCRD) in 2007. \nArts and culture get boost\nThey say art is the signature of a civilization. At UP Diliman arts and culture bloomed vibrant in the last five years by Anna Regidor\nInitiatives from every corner and in virtually every major aspect of development helped strengthen the University\'s prestigious and historically important arts programs. \nToyota Motors partners with UPD by Anna Regidor\nGT-Toyota Asian Cultural Center inaugurated.\nThe Centennial Year brought with it many surprises and blessings, but the biggest one would come to perhaps the unlikeliest unit : the Asian Center (AC). \nPrograms on student welfare\nMaking Isko life better.\nBy Haidee C. Pineda \nStudent welfare is a top priority of the UPD administration. As head of UPD, Chancellor Sergio S. Cao, through the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs (OVCSA) under the leadership of Dr. Elizabeth L. Enriquez, focused on key areas of student life on campus that needed immediate attention, namely - dormitories, health services and student activities. \nRevitalized DZUP airs Feb 1 by Haidee C. Pineda with reports from CMC Broadcast Communication Department\nNew transmitter strengthens DZUP 1602 from 1-kilowatt to 5-kilowatts.\nDZUP 1602, the official radio station of UPD, now has a new tower and transmitter that will allow its broadcast to reach Metro Manila, Cavite and Laguna, Bulacan and Pampanga, thanks to funds produced by the Office of the Chancellor (OC). \nA true academic haven by Haidee C. Pineda \nSecurity and aesthetics make UPD a solace for the mind, body and spirit. \nCampus security was high in the list of priorities of Dr. Sergio S. Cao when he assumed the chancellorship of UP Diliman in 2005. Early in his term, petty crimes were rampant in both the academic core and the residential areas at UPD, threatening the welfare and well-being of the campus\' constituents. \n30% discount for UPD employees at PGH\nDiscount availed only on confinement.\nUPD Diliman\'s faculty, REPS and administrative staff are now entitled to a 30 percent discount on room, board and laboratory fees upon confinement at the Philippine General Hospital (PGH), the country\'s 102 years old national tertiary referral center and teaching hospital of UP Manila. \nFaculty perks\nBenefits enhanced to retain UPD\'s most valuable resource.\nTwo new initiatives were rolled out by the UPD Administration to enhance the total compensation package of its professoriate for the period in review, namely sick lave benefits and study privileges for dependents. \nFaculty items created\nLow salary grade staff items converted to new faculty items. \nRegular items for faculty positions are a rare commodity at the University, the reality even made more ironic by the fact that the administrative personnel greatly outnumber the faculty. \nUP foundation day centennial commemoration June 18, 2008', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(998, 'E2-0998AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XIX, Number 5 (2 copies)', '', '', 'September 2011', 'Ushering in a new era by Anna Kristine Regidor\nPascual investiture promises innovation and invigoration\nIt was only 2 p.m., but all of the University Theater was abuzz with excitement in the afternoon of September 16 as it welcomed the guests at this month\'s biggest event : the formal investiture of UP\'s 20th president, Alfredo E. Pascual.\nPAEP blessed in pre-investiture rites\nA multi-sector group, headed by retired College of Arts and Letters professor Dr. Consolaction R. Alaraz, blessed UP President Alfredo E. Pascual in a quaint ceremony held at the Lagoon on September 12 in anticipation his investiture as 20th UP president on September 15. \nMaking UP a Great University*\nIsang mapagpala\'t mapagpalayang araw sa inyong lahat!\nAbout a year ago, I accepted my nomination to the UP Presidency in my desire to lead in the remaking of UP not only as a great Philippine university, but as a great Asian and global institution as well. \nConcert celebrates PAEP investiture\nIt was a night of celebration on September 12 at the UP Theater as 12 of UPD\'s best performing groups came together in honor of Alfredo E. Pascual\'s Investiture as the 20th UP President on Thursday, September 15. \nThe UP presidency through the decades\nIn honor of past UP presidents, the exhibit The UP Presidency Through the Decades opened at the Bulwagan ng Dangal (BnD) on September 14 to usher in the investiture of Alfredo E. Pascual as the 20th President of the University of the Philippines. \nUniversity Library launches PAEP\'s digital resource', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(999, 'E2-0999AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XX, Number 2 (4 copies)', '', '', 'July-August 2014', 'UPD has 2 new National Scientists \nBoth are marine scientists\nBy Albino C. Gamba Jr. \nPresident Benigno S. Aquino III conferred the rank and title of National Scientist upon Dr. Edgardo D. Gomez (Marine Biology) and Dr. Gavino C. Trono Jr. (Marine Botany), two UPD professors emeriti from The Marine Science Institute (MSI), on Aug. 12 at the Malacañang Palace. \nCMC honors Nora Aunor\nCited for excellence in film and TV performance\nBy Haidee C. Pineda, images by Leonardo A. Reyes\nPetite, dusky and humble; yet, she was the brightest star that afternoon. \nEli Guieb : Gawad Pambansang Alagad ni Balagtas\nKaalinsabay sa kanilang ika-40 taon, ang Kongreso ng Unyon ng mga Manunulat sa Pilipinas (UMPIL) ay ginawaran ng Gawad Pambansang Alagad ni Balagtas (GPAB) para sa Katha sa Filipino si Dr. Eulalio R. Guieb III noong Agosto 30 sa awditoryum ng Kolehiyo ng Komunikasyong Pangmadla (CMC). \n3 cagers on hoops, acads and life by Kevin Brandon E. Saure\nTheirs is a difficult dribbling of balls and ballpens.\nThe making of \"Bent\" by Haidee C. Pineda, image by Leonardo A. Reyes\n\"We\'re not broken, just bent.\"\n2 UPD alumni among TOSP 2014\nMa. Angela Teresa G. Sebastian of the College of Mass Communication (CMC) and Lancelot C. Yupingkun of the College of Engineering (CoE), are among the Ten Outstanding Students of the Philippines (TOSP) 2014. \nOn and off : 2 stages of Dulaang UP by Kevin Brandon E. Saure\nThe curtain opens. The lights fade in. A good show is on the roll. \nThe science of art by Chi A. Ibay, image by Leonardo A. Reyes\nFirst, he studied the oceans. Then he captured the land, its fascinating contours and its myriad creatures. \nMabini : the voice of the Philippines by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nHe is an underrated Philippine hero despite his progressive views on the Catholic Church, women\'s rights to vote, the rights of persons with disabilities and support for public education. \nNew insights into the Pinoy psyche by Mariamme D. Jadloc, images by Kevin Brandon E. Saure and Leonardo A. Reyes\nA new personality test reveals that people with the \"bahala na\" attitude have \"high emotional instability and are not used to planning their tasks and activities.\" In addition, \"init ng ulo\" or anger hostility \"borders between high emotional instability and concern for others,\" while \"pagkamatapat\" or sincerity straddles \"the ability to empathize and the tendency to be generally careful and cautious.\"\nNAST awards 5 UPD profs\nThe National Academy of Science and Technology (NAST) Philippines recognized five UPD professors for their outstanding contributions in the advancement of scienec and technology in the country. \nMaking buko water safe by Albino C. Gamba Jr. \nHow safe is your buko water?\nPredicting primetime revenue by Anna Kristine E. Regidor\nAdvertising is big business. A 30-second commercial on television can cost as much as P250,000 if aired during primetime (8-11 p.m.).\nTeatrong Mjlat : from relief to rehab by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nEight months after the onslaught of typhoon Yolanda (international name : Haiyan) in November 2013, a performing group at UP Diliman continues rehabilitation efforts in a very unique way.\nAlumni top PRC licensure exams\nUPD alumni topped the latest PRC (Professional Regulation Commission) licensure examinations for Geodetic Engineers, Nutritionist-Dietitans and Social Workers.\nThe Binder and his books \nText and image by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr.\nHe works in a discreet area in the third floor of the University Library at UP Diliman (UPD). His old, dependable desk is set amidst the sea of books and other printed materials stacked side by side and on top of each other on the book shelves, waiting for his hands to give them a new lease on life. \nUPD\'s timekeepers\nAmid the din of sounds on weekday mornings at UPD, two fill the air every 8 a.m., reminding one and all that the workday has officially begun. \nUPD recovers from Glenda by Anna Kristine E. Regidor, images by Leonardo A. Reyes\nIn the morning of Wednesday, Jul. 16, residents of UP Diliman (UPD) woke to howling winds and heavy rains. Typhoon Glenda was barreling through Metro Manila with winds of up to 185 kilometers per hour. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1000, 'E2-1000AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XX, Number 3 (4 copies)', '', '', 'September-October 2014', 'CMLT affirmed as 10th UPD Chancellor \nStudent performances highlight ceremony\nBy Anna Kristine E. Regidor, images by Leonardo A. Reyes\nThe University Theater was bursting at the seams in the afternoon of Oct. 17 : students mingled with diplomats and university officials in their academic regalia; two lines of the Rayadillo guards greeted guests as over 2,000 people watched noted medical anthropologist Dr. Michael Lim Tan\'s formal affirmation as the 10th Chancellor of UP Diliman (UPD). \n\"Selfie\" ang salita ng taon ni Haidee C. Pineda\nItinanghal ang \"selfie\" bilang salita ng taon matapos makakuha ng pinakamataas na boto mula sa mga kalahok ng \"Pambansang Kumperensiya sa Pagpapayaman ng Wikang Filipino at Sawikaan 2014 : Pagpili ng Salita ng Taon.\"\nTrans-boundary, before it is set in stone\nUPD debates on new GE program by Chi A. Ibay, image by Leonardo A. Reyes\nIt was to be a venue to craft a new General Education (GE) program fit for the first K-to-12 graduates, who will be UP Diliman\'s (UPD) freshmen in Academic Year 2018-2019. \nUPD holds 6th Paliwanagan by Albino C. Gamba Jr., images by Leonardo A. Reyes\nEight research projects were highlighted at the colloquium \"Paliwanagan sa UP Diliman\" on Oct. 3 at the NISMED (National Institute for Science and Mathematics Education Development) Auditorium. \nAgainst the flow : Ramos, up close and personal \nText and image by Albino C. Gamba Jr. \n\"Do not follow the path of a river because it causes the path of least resistance,\" said Dr. Henry J. Ramos \nBuilding Bridges, Creating Networks : Pakikpag-ugnayan*\nText by Michael L. Tan, images by Michael L. Tan and Leonardo A. Reyes\nHalos walong buwan na ang nakalilipas mula nang manungkulan ako bilang Tsanselor ng UP Diliman. \nQC as arts hub\nText and image by Kevin Brandon E. Saure\n\"Magnets\" for artists in the various disciplines abound within 5-kilometer radius of the Quezon Memorial Circle (QMC) in Quezon City, preliminary results of an inter-college research reveals. \nIIS preps for new home by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nThe Institute of Islamic Studies (IIS) did ground-making for the unit\'s new building in the Romulo Hall compound on Oct. 3. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1001, 'E2-1001AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XX, Number 4 (4 copies)', '', '', 'November-December 2014', 'Tatak UP\' and Pinoy traditions\nHighlights of the 2014 UPD Lantern Parade\nBy Haidee C. Pineda, images by Leonardo A. Reyes\nRain may have drenched the campus grounds in the afternoon of Dec.15 but this did not dampen the festive atmosphere of this year\'s most anticipated tradition in UP Diliman-the 2014 Lantern Parade. \nUP offers course on marine ecosystem by Albino C. Gamba Jr. \nNew Inter-CU grad program opens in Jan.\nThe University of the Philippines will offer a groundbreaking inter-constituent university (CU) collaborative graduate three program on the effective management and governance of the country\'s marine environment resources in January 2015.\nAbdulmari Asia Imao, 78\nDr. Abdulmari Asia Imao, beloved brother, father, and grandfather, a creative soul of the Bangsamoro, National Artist for the Visual Arts, peacefully joined Allah in the early morning of Dec. 16. \nUP\'s socialized tuition system in full swing\nBy Mariamme D. Jadloc, image by Leonardo A. Reyes\nA new financial assistance program for UP students, the Socialized Tuition System (ST-S) was implemented in the constituent universities in August 2014, coinciding with the first semester of UP\'s new academic calendar. \nStudents speak on the ST-S by Anna Kristine E. Regidor, image by Jefferson Villacruz\nHindi ka nagkikiskis ng bato para magluto. #BracketAKaNa.\nMay flush yung CR niyo? #BracketAKaNa. \nST-S at UPD by Haidee C. Pineda\nA total of 13, 820 students availed of the Socialized Tuition System (ST-S) at UP Diliman (UPD) in the first semester of Academic Year 2014-2015. \nDMAPS : a transdisciplinary approach to teaching disaster preparedness by Anna Kristine E. Regidor, image by Leonardo A. Reyes\nThree girls stand at the edge of the Sunken Garden wearing paper hats and singing their hearts out to the melody of Taylor Swift\'s \"Shake If Off.\" Instead of following the song\'s lyrics, the three are singing about how to prepare for earthquakes. \nLanguage experts at UPD for int\'l confab on nat\'l language by Haidee C. Pineda, images by Leonardo Reyes\nOver 1,000 languages educators across the globe gathered at UP Diliman (UPD) from Nov. 20 to 22 for the international conference \"Mother Tongue and National Language in the K+12 Curricular Enhancement as Framework for Development : An International Conference-Workshop.\"\nMapa draws plans for Stat\nBy Albino C. Gamba Jr., image by Leonardo A. Reyes\nThe creation of Research Laboratories (RLs) is the top priority of Dr. Dennis S. Mapa, dean of the School of Statistics (SS).\nSenate commends Gabriel for TOYP award \nBy Albino C. Gamba Jr. \nThe Senate of the Philippines honored Dr. Alonzo A. Gabriel of the College of Home Economics (CHE) on Dec. 15 for having been chosen by the Junior Chamber International (JCI) as one of the 2024 Ten Outstanding Young Persons of the World (TOYP).\nUPD preps for Christmas, opens with Pag-iilaw \nBy Anna Kristine E. Regidor, image by Leonardo A. Reyes\nThe street lights were dim Quezon Hall and its surrounding areas were shrouded in darkness in the early evening of Dec. 1\nEng\'g reclaims Karolfest crown\nBy Benito V. Sanvictores Jr., image by Kevin Brandon E. Saure\nThe Engineering Chorale of the College of Engineering (CoE) emerged as champion in this year\'s Karolfest, beating four other college choral groups in the inter-college choral competition for students and faculty/staff. This year\'s contest theme was \"Pasundayag Diliman : Pag-uugat at Pagyabong.\" \nA very jazzy Christmas by Anna Kristine E. Regidor\nWeather and the sudden change of venue did not deter the UP College of Music (CM) from making history, taking part of one of the best known choral works in classical music.\nUPD\'s Panecillo by Mariamme D. Jadloc, image by Jefferson Villacruz\nThe Panecillo de San Nicolas or San Nicolas is one of the oldest cookies in the Philippines.\nOf birds and men : why the Black Bittern did not die in vain by Chi A. Ibay, image by Jefferson Villacruz\nOn Nov. 9, a post in a social network site on the killing of a bird in the UP Diliman (UPD) campus went viral. \nFinding new meanings in children\'s stories by Kevin Brandon E. Sauro \nChildren stories tell so much more than good night and happy endings to kids\nWhen micro does macro : the UL Microform Section \nText and images by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nWhen you thought every information you need is in the web, think again. \nLatest Diliman journals now online \nThe current issues of the UP Diliman journals \"Humanities Diliman,\" \"Science Diliman\" and \"Social Science Diliman\" are now online.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1002, 'E2-1002AC', '', 'UPdate Diliman : the community newspaper of UP Diliman, Volume XXI, Number 5 (4 copies)', '', '', 'January to February 2015', 'UPD Month 2015\nCampus toasts the arts\nBy Anna Kristine E. Regidor, images by Jefferson Villacruz, Leonardo A. Reyes\nFebruary is always an exciting time as the community celebrates the achievements of its home-grown artists and cultural workers at UP Diliman Month. \nForeign experts at CMEAA 2015 by Pearlyn Manalo, NIGS\nLocal and foreign experts from different fields of the earth sciences gathered to discuss new findings and innovations in the international symposium \"Crust-mantle evolution in active arcs\" on Feb 12 and 13 at Sequoia Hotel in Quezon City.\nUPD-Dassault Systemes partnership for 3D design\n20 in 20 : the UP Diliman Month through the years by Chi A. Ibay, Images by Leonardo A. Reyes\nThe celebrations began in February 1995 as UP Diliman Week (UPDW). In 1999, the festivity was expanded to a month showcasing UPD\'s outstanding achievements in the various disciplines. \nUP International Center celebrates cultures by Kevin Brandon E. Saure\nThe participation of some 100 foreign students in the International Center\'s (IC) Festival 2005 made UP Diliman (UPD) a mini United Nations.\nUPD profs produce 9 books by Benito V. Sanvictores, Jr. \nNine books in varied topics such as cinema, culture, faith, family, history, language, literature, politics and theater will be released by UP Press in April. \n100M and counting by Mariamme D. Jadloc, image by Leonardo A. Reyes\nFilipino couples actually want only two to three children, a recent study by authors Clarissa C. David and Jenna Mae L. Atun, \"Factors Affecting Fertility Desires in the Philippines,\" revealed. \nUPD, LRU sign MOU\nUP Diliman (UPD) and Loei Rajabhat University, Thailand (LRU) entered into a 3-year memorandum of understanding (MOU) on Feb. 2 at the UPD Office of the Chancellor. \nUPD to launch balikUPDorm by Haidee C. Pineda, Images by Jefferson Villacruz\n\"Kung dormer ka, dapat sanay ka sa surot,\" a student dormer once said. \nChamps : UP Lady Jins and Poomsae teams by Albino C. Gamba Jr. \nCohesiveness and focus were the factors that contributed to the UP Taekwondo Women\'s Team and UP Taekwondo Poomsae Team in winning the championship titles in the University Athletic Association of the Philippines (UAAP) Season 77 Taekwondo Competitions.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
