(1029, 'E2-1029AC', '', 'UPdate Magazine. Volume 2, Numbers 1 (2 copies)', '', '', 'January-June 2015', 'Introduction by Benjamin A. Gonzales\nPantawid-gutom, pantawid-buhay by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nAla-sais pa lang ng umaga ay bukas na ang kanilang munting tindahan (food stall), handa nang punan ang mga gutom na tiyan ngunit kapos sa pera.\nFood trip by Jerwin Agpaoa. Images by Jefferson Villacruz and Kevin Brandon Saure\nAlong with UP Diliman\'s (UPD) rich academic history, liberal education and practice of perpetual inquiry and critique, food has eventually found its way into the university\'s identity. \nTasting the archipelago by Kevin Brandon E. Saure, image by Leonardo A. Reyes\nAnybody who had a chance to live at Kalayaan Residence Hall surely had a taste of the Pasalubong Festival (Pasafest).\nMerienda tayo! by Cecile Leah Bayaga. Image by Jefferson Villacruz\nFood is something that unites the Filipino people. As food-loving individuals, we are perceived to eat more than three meals a day. \nThe 4 M\'s of UFS : A conversation with Mtizi Reyes\nDr. Michael L. Tan in his message at his affirmation as 10th Chancellor of UP Diliman (UPD) on Oct. 17, 2014, focused on eight bridges as metaphors to his mission and vision for UPD. \nGood food, good service : The UP Pilot Food Plant Story by Djanna F. Cornago\nHave you ever wanted to send your famous home-made adobo sa gata or bagoong to your relatives abroad but feared that it might get damaged or spoiled along the way?\nLutong bahay sa Coop by Noel T. Pangilinan', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1030, 'E2-1030AC', '', 'UPdate Magazine. Volume 2, Numbers 2 (6 copies)', '', '', 'July-December 2015', 'Introduction by Jem Roque Javier\nSa edisyong ito ng UPDate Magazine, matutunghayan natin ang estado ng wika sa Unibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman at ang mga proyekto ng mga institusyon upang higit itong mapag-inam sa ikapagiging-angkop at kapaki-pakinabang tungo sa pagdaloy ng kaalaman, sa pamamagitan ng tunog, titik at senyas. \nEngineering in speech and language by Michael Gringo Angelo R. Bayona\nDecades ago, human-machine interaction existed mainly in the realm of science fiction. \nDeafness as ethnicity by Nestor T. Castro\nThe perceptions of cultural differentiation in the Philippines were traditionally reckoned through a combination of criteria, such as religion (e.g. Christian, Muslim, or \"pagan\"), domicile (e.g. concepts of highlander vs. lowlander, riverine or coastal peoples, sea-faring groups), phenotypic characteristics (e.g. Negrito vs. Mongoloid), and material culture (e.g. native costume, type of dwelling, musical instruments, weapons, customs and traditions, etc.). More important than these aforementioned factors, however, is the language that a particular group uses. Thus, varied communities are commonly referred as \"ethnolinguistic groups\"  instead of \"ethnic groups.\"\nSigns of the times by Marie Therese A. P. Bustos\nSaturday, 8:30 a.m. A flurry of conversations using hand, body and facial movements rushed past the College of Education (CEd) lobby as Mae Shiela Antenor, Morly Canta, Lisette Ann Dela Cruz, and Pearl Talens ran to Room 106.\nShifting paradigms by Jonathan C. Malicsi\nA prescription for teaching English as a foreign language.\nKritikal na imahinasyon : Panayam kay Rommel B. Rodriguez\nPanayam kay Direktor Rommel B. Rodriguez ng SWF \nSa pagtatapos ng panunungkulan ni Professor Emeritus Rosario Torres-Yu, bumuo ang Unibersidad ng Pilipinas (UP) Diliman ng isang Search Committee upang pumili ng susunod na manunungkulan bilang Direktor ng Sentro ng Wikang Filipino (SWF), ang tanggapang nangunguna sa pagtataguyod ng Pambansang Wika at susubaybay sa pagpapatupad ng patakarang pangwika sa Unibersidad. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1031, 'E2-1031AC', '', 'UPdate Magazine. Volume 3, Numbers 1 (2 copies)', '', '', 'January-June 2016', 'Panimula by Sir Anril P. Tiatco and Jem R. Javier\nHindi maitatatwa ng isang nag-aaral, nagtatrabaho o tumanda sa Unibersidad ng Pilipinas (UP) DIliman na ang Bulwagang Rizal, o mas kilala sa tawag na Faculty Center (FC) ang isa sa pinakabantog na gusali sa kampus. \nGunita at Panaghoy ni Bienvenido Lumbera\nAlaala ng FC by Amihan Bonifacio-Ramolete\nUnang naisip ni Carlos P. Romulo, Pangulo ng Unibersidad ng Pilipinas, na magtayo ng gusali para sa mga guro ng arts and sciences. \nRemarks at the inauguration of the Faculty Center by Salvador P. Lopez\nThis one is for the books by May Jurilla\nBooks in the Philippines generally tend to have short shelf lives. Our environment is host to many conditions that are not friendly to books, conditions that constantly threaten their survival. One of such is the frequency of fires. \nFaculty Center\nThe faculty, it has often been said, is the University\'s most important intellectual resource, being the vital cog in the University\'s business of imparting, and more importantly, instilling in the youth the love for knowledge. \nA home to National Artists, National Scientists and highly-acclaimed luminaries by Jose Wendell P. Capili\nBefore it was gutted by fire last Apr. 1, 2016, the Faculty Center (Bulwagang Rizal) was not just a university faculty. For many, it was Diliman\'s nerve center. \nGrieving for the UP Faculty Center by Randy David\nThough it is far from being an iconic structure, it is difficult to find another place in the University of the Philippines Diliman campus that is quite like the Faculty Center. Until it was gutted by fire last Friday morning, the FC, or Bulwagang Rizal, was the single biggest structure in the university to house faculty offices. \nFC by Michael Tan\nA security guard woke me up at around 1:30 a.m. last Friday, very calmly telling me, \"Sir, may sunog. Ang FC.\" (There\'s a fire. FC.) The words \"FC,\" Faculty Center, hit me like a shrill fire alarm. Not just a building, or rooms, FC was a place loved and cherished by several generations of UP communities. \nMula sa abo ng Faculty Center : Bangon CAL-CSSP!\nLimang oras ng pagtatanghal na pinamagatang \"Bangon CAL-CSSP\" ang ginanap sa harap ng Faculty Center, Abril 3, bilang pag-alaala sa nasunog na gusali at bilang panawagan para sa pagbangon. \nFC remembered\nMay 16 was a night of remembrance and beginnings at the Faculty Center (FC) as UP Diliman (UPD) held the \"Seremonya ng Pag-alaala at Parangal sa Lingkod Komunidad\" to open Linggo ng Parangal 2016. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1032, 'E2-1032AC', '', 'UPdate Magazine. Volume 4, Numbers 1 (6 copies)', '', '', 'January-June 2017', 'Panimula by Sir Anril P. Tiatco at Jem R. Javier\nA new direction for Philippine Studies by Michael L. Tan\nIn December 2015, I was in Shanghai for a Confucius Institute global conference and there was an entire session on the \"new SInology.\"\nSciences and Philippine Studies by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr.\nAn interview with Dr. Percival F. Almoro*, UP College of Science \nEconomics and Philippine Studies by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nAn interview with Dr. Orville Jose C. Solon,*Dean, UP School of Economics\nBusiness and Philippine Studies by Chi A. Ibay\nAn interview with Dr. Erik Paolo S. Capistrano,* UP Cesar E. A. Virata School of Business \nIslam and Philippine Studies by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nAn interview with Prof. Macrina A. Morados,* Dean, UP Institute of Islamic Studies \nThe Arts and Philippine Studies by Haidee C. Pineda\nAn interview with Prof. Leo Antonio C. Abaya,* UP College of Fine Arts\nAng Wikang FIlipino at ang Philippine Studies by Haidee C. Pineda\nPanayam kay Dr. Galileo S. Zafra,* UP Kolehiyo ng Arte at Literatura\nEngineering and Philippine Studies by Anna E. Regidor\nAn interview with Dr. Enrico C. Paringit,* UP College of Engineering\nPhilippine Studies/Pilipinolohiya : Pagtingin mula sa loob, para sa loob by Kevin Brandon E. Saure \nPanayam kay Dr. Zosimo E. Lee,* UP Kolehiyo ng Agham Panlipunan at Pilosopiya', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1033, 'E2-1033AC', '', 'UPdate Magazine. Volume 4, Numbers 2 (3 copies)', '', '', 'July-December 2017', 'Introduction by Sir Anril P. Tiatco and Jem R. Javier\nBody and sports by Marcus Jarwin Manalo\nAmong all the topics in this issue, the connection between body and sports is perhaps the most evident. \nTouch/Haplos by Octavio Paz (trans. Charles Tomlinson) Filipino trans. Michael S. Bernal\nThe body in faith and tradition by Ma. Christina S. Azarcon-Bolivar\n(Excerpts fromt he project \"Philippine Performance Archive : Ritual, Dance, Theater\" of the Emerging Interdisciplinary Research (EIDR) program of the UP Office of the Vice President for Academic Affairs.)\nOne cultural performance that largely involves the body is the \"Bulating\" of Boac, Marinduque.\nPrinciples of having a healthy diet (Push natin \'to mga Bes!) by Cecile Leah T. Bayaga\nMany may be unaware of it, but nutrition plays a significant role in one\'s life. And its significant effect will continue and depend on the foods they select and eat. \nBodies and/in performance research by Bryan L. Viray\n\"We only begin to understand our orientations, when we experience disortientation.\" - Merleau-Ponty\nFilipino bodies, public health and Philippine independence, 1901-1927 by Ma. Mercedes G. Planta\nThe political organization of a society and the anatomy of the body has been one of the earliest analogies for the body. Aristotle and medieval writers, for instance, compared the structure and function of political institutions with the organs and functions of the body, hence, the body politic. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1034, 'E2-1034AC', '', 'UPdate Magazine. Volume 5, Numbers 1 (4 copies)', '', '', 'January-June 2018', 'Introduksiyon by Jem R. Javier\nPride in people by Michael L. Tan\nThis was a difficult piece to write because these are just so many people to be proud of in UP Diliman (UPD). To give specific names here would risk missing out on many more so this article will be nameless, to honor all. \nPantasa, pag-ibig at pag-asa by Haidee C. Pineda\nMula sa isang kaswal na pagtatagpo, sila ay nagkuwentuhan; nagtugma ang mga gusto at hilig, nauwi sa pag-ibig, hanggang humantong sa isang malalim na relasyon. Sino ang mag-aakalang ang dalawang taong magkaiba ng personalidad ngunit iisa and adbokasiya ay magbubunga ng makabuluhang proyektong bayanihan para sa edukasyon at para sa bayan?\nFor crying OUTLawed! by Kevin Brandon E. Saure\nHow can an outlaw change the law?\nUnassuming guy to look up to by Bino C. Gamba\nDaniel Coquilla is a technician. His official designation is Movie Equipment Technician III, a movie projection operator at the UP Film Center\'s Cinema and Videotheque . Dansoy is a multi-awarded visual artist known for his comic top view representations of Philippine popular culture. Daniel Coquilla and Dansoy are one and the same person. He is one of UP Diliman\'s pride. \nThe last glassblower by Anna Regidor \nStepping into the Glass Laboratory of the Institute of Chemistry (IC) feels like traveling through a portal. One goes from the smooth cream colored ceramic tiles and open air of the hall into a small room that is more machine shop than laboratory. \nBLKD laban sa mga balakid by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nNang makita ang mga idolo sa kanilang pagra-rap \nNagsikap siyang maabot matagal nang pangarap\nSa kanyang kaisipan \'di niya agad naapuhap\nNa ang tatahaking landas ay ang pagra-rap. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
