(1048, 'E2-1048AC', '', 'AUN/SEED-Net\nFormat of Action Plan and Tentative SEED-Net Strategy Paper ', '', 'Jointly prepared by AUN/SEED-Net Secretariat & JICA Headquarter ', '2001', 'Introduction\nProcess of preparing action plan\nModel Contents of Action Plan\n1. Background\n2. Institutions Development Needs\n3. Objectives and Scope\n4. Inputs\n5. SEED-Net Activity Management Structure in Member Institution\n6. Coordination Arrangements\n7. Other Information\nExplanation of each heading \n1. Background\n1-1. Description of Industry Sectors\n1-2. Host Country Stratergy\n1-3. Member Institution\'s Development Strategy or Plan\n1-4. Prior and ongoing development activities and assistance\n2. Institution\'s Development Needs and Resources\n2-1. Situation of Your Institution\n2-2. Development issues mainly addressed by the framework of SEED-Net\n2-3. Institution\'s Resources Contributing to the SEED-Net\n3. Design of Action Plan\n3-1. Longer Term (in more than 5 - 10 years) Objective\n3-2. Short term (in less than 5 years) Objective of the Member Institution\n3-3. Direct Outputs\n3-4. Activities\n4. Inputs\n4-1. Member Institution\'s own resources\n4-2. Assistance from the Government to which the member institution belong\n4-3. Supports from Japanese Government through SEED-Net Secretariat \n4-4. Other resources\n5. SEED-Net Activity Management Structure in Member Institution\n6. Coordination Arrangements \n7. Other Information Required for the Preparation of SEED-Net Strategy Paper\n7-1. Situation of the Higher Engineering Education\n7-2. Documents Explaining Industrial Development of Your Country\n7-3. Available Resources of your Institution', 'Paper', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1049, 'E2-1049AC', '', 'Tentative SEED-Net Strategy Paper ', '', 'Jointly prepared by AUN/SEED-Net Secretariat & JICA HeadQuarter ', '2001', 'Introduction\n1. Background \n1-1. Evolvement of SEED-Net\n1-2. Rationale of establishment of SEED-Net\n2. The Tentative SEED-Net Strategy\n2-1. Longer Vision of the Network\n2-2. Network Purpose that should be directly attained\n2-3. Direct Outputs of the Networks\n2-3-1. Upgrade the standard of the engineering education\n1) Improvement of educational course of the member institutions\n2) Establishment of reciprocity system for credits\n3) Improvement of teaching skills and aids of teaching staffs \n2-3-2. Abilities of teaching and research staffs of member institutions are improved. \n1) Upgrading the qualifications and knowledge of teaching and research staffs of member institutions.\n2) Research activities of member institutions are promoted. \n3) Construction of an information network that disseminate latest academic information and technology. \n2-3-3. Stronger linkages between the industry sector and member institutions \n1) Model framework of industry and university liaison.\n2) IT-based continuing engineering education for the practicing engineers \n2-3-4. A databank, web-site and communication network will be constructed. \n1) Databank of academics of member institutions and supporting Japanese Universities. \n2) Establishment of web-site which links with the web-site of member institutions and provides research findings of member institutions.  \n3) Establishment of \"Chat rooms\" and \"Mailing lists\" in the field of studies through the internet. \n2-4. Inputs\n2-4-1. Japanese Government\n2-4-2. Member Institutions \n2-4-3. Other resources\n3. Organization of the AUN/SEED-Net (See ANNEX 3)\n3-1. Relationship between the AUN and SEED-Net\n3-2. Composition and Terms of the Steering Committee Members\n3-3. SEED-Net Secretariat\n3-4. Member Institutions\n3-5. Japanese Supporting University Consortium \n4. Member Institutions\n4-1. Brunei Darussalam\n4-2. Cambodia\n4-3. Indonesia\n4-4. Lao PDR\n4-5. Malaysia\n4-6. Myanmar\n4-7. Philippines\n4-9. Thailand\n4-10. Vietnam\n5. Supporting Committee & Universities in Japan\n5-1. Chairperson\n5-2. Committee Members ', 'Paper', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1050, 'E2-1050AC', '', 'Questionnaire to Universities on Southeast Asia Engineering Education Development Network (SEED-Net)', '', '', '', 'General Questions\n1. Name of University\n2. Year of Foundation\n3. Organization Chart\n4. Annual Report\n5. Degrees Offered\n6. Number of Currently Enrolled Students\n7. Number of Academic Staff \n8. Budget (Revenue and Expenditure)\nQuestions on Engineering Field \n1. Engineering Students\n2. Number of Engineering Academic Staff by Degree\n3. List of Engineering Academic Staff with Professional Qualifications, Research Interests and Topics. \n4. Exchange Program\n(1) Student exchange program\n(2) Credit exchange program (Credit transfer scheme)\n(3) Staff exchange program\n5. Distance/Continuing Learning Program\n6. Networks for Educational Exchange and Promotion\n7. Collaboration with the Industrial Sector\n8. Publications and Conferences\n(1) Publications\n(2) Conferences\n9. Tuition Fee\n(1) Per student per year\n(2) Per credit (or per course)\n10. Scholarship\n(1) In-house scholarship\n(2) Other scholarship\n11. Academic Calendar\n12. Staff Policies\n13. Problems to be tackled\nQuestions on SEED-Net\n1. Needs\n2. Benefits (Weaknesses you possess at present)\n3. Contribution (Strengths you possess at present)\n4. Implementation Structure\n(1) Implementation Structure\n(2) Counterpart Personnel Assignment\n(3) Budget Allocation\nQuestions on National and Industrial Development\n1. National Development Plan\n2. Industrial Policy and Legal Framework\n3. Statistics\n4. Human Resources of Engineers & Technicians\n5. Qualification System\nQuestions on Educational Development \n1. Relevance to National Development \n2. Educational Policy and Legal Framework', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1051, 'E2-1051AC', '', 'Answers to the Questionnaire', '', '', '', 'General Questions\n1. Name of University\n2. Year of Foundation\n3. Organization Chart\n4. Annual Report\n5. Degrees Offered\n6. Number of Currently Enrolled Students\n7. Number of Academic Staff \n8. Budget (Revenue and Expenditure)\nQuestions on Engineering Field \n1. Engineering Students\n2. Number of Engineering Academic Staff by Degree\n3. List of Engineering Academic Staff with Professional Qualifications, Research Interests and Topics. \n4. Exchange Program\n(1) Student exchange program\n(2) Credit exchange program (Credit transfer scheme)\n(3) Staff exchange program\n5. Distance/Continuing Learning Program\n6. Networks for Educational Exchange and Promotion\n7. Collaboration with the Industrial Sector\n8. Publications and Conferences\n(1) Publications\n(2) Conferences\n9. Tuition Fee\n(1) Per student per year\n(2) Per credit (or per course)\n10. Scholarship\n(1) In-house scholarship\n(2) Other scholarship\n11. Academic Calendar\n12. Staff Policies\n13. Problems to be tackled\nQuestions on SEED-Net\n1. Needs\n2. Benefits (Weaknesses you possess at present)\n3. Contribution (Strengths you possess at present)\n4. Implementation Structure\n(1) Implementation Structure\n(2) Counterpart Personnel Assignment\n(3) Budget Allocation\nQuestions on National and Industrial Development\n1. National Development Plan\n2. Industrial Policy and Legal Framework\n3. Statistics\n4. Human Resources of Engineers & Technicians\n5. Qualification System\nQuestions on Educational Development \n1. Relevance to National Development \n2. Educational Policy and Legal Framework', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1052, 'E2-1052AC', '31', 'Photos', '', '', '', '1. First Graduates in Geodetic Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines \nApril 4, 1939\n2. The First Chemical Engineering Senior Class \n- Rosalino Reyes Jr.\n- Cesar Concio, Jr.\n- Lim Yu Chin\n- Rogelio Reyes\nA New Building Takes Shape\nMain features : Power and Hydraulics Laboratories\nHydraulics Laboratory\n3. The Old Registration Routine\nThe College was now a no-man\'s land\n4. The Cyanidation and Flotation Pilot Plant in the Extractive Metallurgy Laboratory\n- Shop facilities under the department of mechanical engineering are : the Machine Shop (shown in the picture), the Welding & Forge Shop, the Wood and Pattern Shop, and the Foundry Shop.\n- The Batch Ore Dressing Laboratory. Ores from both the Philippine Iron Mines, and Hixbar Gold Mines, have been worked in this laboratory for developing the proper extraction method of the iron and copper ores, respectively. \n5. The \"Space Ship\" inside the hangar. \n6. Library Annex in construction. CO-OP Annex in the basement? \n7. The Tau Alpha silver jubilee affair was not without the distaff side. See above. \n8. The Gee Ees pasting the finishing patches of their Christmas lantern. \n9. The U.P. Loyalty and Arbor Day : A Freshman shows the boys how it\'s done \n10. The Ambuklao Dam will be the highest (131 meters) of its kind when completed. Present highest rock-fill dam is Salt Springs Dam in California completed in 1931, 100 meters high. Above, a view of the construction on the dam proper. \n11. The Be Way : a straight line is the shortest distance...\n12. The Civils at Caliraya\nInspection trips : excuses for excursions...\n13. The EE-Lites\nStill picture : photos and electrons...\n14. The girls\' volleyball team...a resolve to be a championship contender from hereon. \n15. The victory banquet held at Panciteria Moderna in honor of the Engineering intramural teams which garnered first place in football, first place in men\'s volleyball and second place in bastketball. Mr. Cristy Hernandez is the faculty athletic manager, and Eddie Enriquez, president of the Engineering Association, the student athletic manager. \n16. Students in IES 1 on laboratory tour. Professor T. Festin explaining the operation of the double-effect evaporator at the ChE lab. \n17. The College has now a photoelastic laboratory. It is a unit of the materials testing lab. \n18. Part of the crowd of students in the vicinity of the U.P. check point in the early morning of December 16. Buses and jeeps stalled on the roads as students hedged about them. One result of the demonstration : a longer Xmas vacation. \n19. The Engineering Elections. First in the campus. Keen contests...lively...orderly.\n20. Fraulein Soiree at Dean & Mrs. Ortigas\'s residence. Carmen Valencia, the prexy, is the second from right, first row. \n21. Melchor Hall', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
