(1071, 'E2-1071AC', '35', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman (3 copies)', 'UP Diliman', 'UP Diliman Information Office under the Office of the Chancellor', 'Abril-Mayo 2015', 'Marso 20-Abril 30\nTerraforming\n1F Galleries\nVargas Museum\nThe UP Vargas Museum, in cooperation with Art Informal and Box Plot, presents Terraforming, an exhibit of Mark Valenzuela\'s and Pablo K. Capati III\'s contemporary ceramics. \nAbril 5-11, 19-25\nNational Training of Trainers of Grade 4 Science and Mathematics Teachers for the K-12 Basic Education\nScience Teachers Training Center NISMED\nThe sessions for elementary school mathematics are designed to highlight teaching mathematics through problem solving. For elementary school science, the emphasis will be on teaching through inquiry.\nAbril 6-17\nTeaching Preschoolers and Early Graders in the Context of the K-12 Curriculum\nA seminar for preschool and primary teachers, administrators and tertiary level early childhood education (ECE) educators and organized by the Teaching in the Early Grades (TEG) area of the College of Education. \nAbril 7\nTragedy on Television : Aristotle\'s Revenge\nCollege of Mass Communication A101 \n5:30-7 p.m.\nWhile tragedy as a genre seems increasingly irrelevant to cinema, the recent trend in television serial dramas revolving around a central \"anti-hero\" makes contact with central tenets of classical tragic theory. Dr. Joel Mann views examples from the recent dramatic series Breaking Bad and Sons of Anarchy through the lens of Aristotle\'s poetics, though other series in the same vein will be up for discussion (e.g., Mad Men, The Sopranos).\nAbril 8-15\nBS Interior Design ID123 \nTable Setting Exhibit\nCHE Lobby\nCollege of Home Economics\n8 a.m.-5 p.m. \nAn open exhibit by the class of ID123 Decorative Arts and Soft Furnishings featuring table settings designed in various themes such as Filipino colonial-inspired breakfast and Mediterranean-style al fresco lunch. \nAbril 10\nTampisaw : An Interactive Exhibit\nPalma Hall Rm. 400\n12-3 p.m. \nTampisaw is part of the UP Tomokai\'s 24th year celebration of cultural exchanges between the Philippines and Japan.\nAbril 13-Mayo 11\n(Lunes-Miyerkules-Biyernes)\nSining Bulilit 2015\nGrade School Building\nUP Integrated School (UPIS)\n10:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m.\nSining Bulilit is an Art Enrichment Program that caters to two age groups : 6-8 years old and 9-11 years old. Young pupils are taught various art activities by Art Education graduate students of the College of Education.\nAbril 13-Mayo 22\n(Lunes-Miyerkules-Biyernes)\nReading Link : Beginning Reading Program\nUPIS Grade 3 to 6 Building\n8-10:30 a.m. \nThe Beginning Reading Program of Reading Link is designed for incoming Kindergarten (5.6 years old) to Grade 2 pupils who need more assistance to prepare them for reading. The program is handled by the faculty and graduate students of the Reading Area of the College of Education. \nAbril 13-Mayo 22\n(Lunes-Miyerkules-Biyernes)\nReading Link : Reading Enrichment Program\nUPIS Grade 3 to 6 Building\n8-10:30 a.m.\nThe Reading Enrichment Program of Reading Link is meant for incoming Grades 3 to 7 students. The program is facilitated by the faculty and graduate students of the Reading Area of the College of Education. \nAbril 13-17\nMining, Metallurgical and Materials (MMM) Engineering Days 2015\nThe MMM Days 2015 is the most anticipated week-long celebration of the 78th anniversary of the Department of Mining, Metallurgical and Materials Engineering (DMMME). This year\'s celebration also showcases DMMME\'s contribution to the society and promotes the department by organizing fun-filled activites. \nAbril 13-17\nCivil Engineering (CE) Days\nThe CE Days is the biggest and the most awaited annual institute-wide event attended by UP\'s civil engineering students and faculty. It is where students, instructors and professors are able to showcase their individual talents and where camaraderie and unity among the institute\'s constituents are built. \nAbril 14\nWeak or Strong State : The Implications of Self-organization in a Disaster-Prone Community in the Philippines\nCollege of Mass Communication A101 \n3:30 - 5 p.m.\nThe paper is an offshoot of an earlier study on the manifestations of self-organization in the community of Banaba, San Mateo, Rizal in their response to Tropical Storm Ketsana (local name Ondoy). \nAbril 14-17\nElectrical and Electronics Engineering Institute Days\nThe Electrical and Electronics Engineering Institute (EEEI) Days is a week-long event designed to promote camaraderie and community spirit among the EEEI student body, faculty and staff. Every year, the EEEI Day draws hundreds of EEEI students and faculty to participate in its unique and enjoyable events and gatherings. \nAbril 14-17\n2015 Summer Training-Seminar for Social Science Teachers \nCSSP Audio-Visual Room\nPalma Hall\nThe College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP) and the Social Science and Philosophy Research Foundation, Inc. (SSPRF) will be holding the 2015 Summer Training-Seminar for Social Science Teachers. \nAbril 15\nCLRG@50 Lecture Series : ICTs in Local Governments by Dr. Remigio D. Ocenar\nAssembly Hall\nNational College of Public Administration and Governance (NCPAG)\n2 p.m.\nThe CLRG@50 Lecture Series is held in celebration of the 50th anniversary of the NCPAG Center for Local and Regional Governance (CLRG). \nAbril 16\nMyanmar Planning : First-Hand Impressions (SURP 50th Anniversary Public Lecture Series)\nCariño Multi-Purpose Hall\nSchool of Urban and Regional Planning (SURP)\n6 p.m. \nThe talk is the fourth in the SURP 50th Anniversary Public Lecture Series and will be presented by Cesar B. Umali Jr. \nAbril 16-17\nISKOpreneur 2015 : Iskasaysayan\nUP Clark Courtyard\nUPD Extension Program in Pampanga \nISKOpreneur is an annual fair that showcases the entrepreneurial skills and innovative products of the senior Business Management students of UP Diliman Extension Program in Pampanga. \nAbril 17-Mayo 20\n(Lunes-Miyerkules-Biyernes)\nUP EDTEG Summer Fun\nClasses 2015\nK-12 Building\nKinder : 8-11 a.m.\nGrades 1-3 : 9 a.m. - 12 p.m.\nThe summer workshop for kids caters to Kindergarten (5 years old) to incoming Grade 3 kids who will be engaged in integrated developmentally appropriate literacy, arts, numeracy, science, music and physical activities facilitated by the faculty and graduate students of the Teaching in the Early Grades (TEG) area of the College of Education.\nAbril 17-Hulyo 17\n(Lahat ng Biyernes)\nManagement Development Program for Coops, NGOs and Trade Unions \nSchool of Labor and Industrial Relations (SOLAIR) \n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe certificate course in Management Development Program is designed to build the managerial, leadership and entrepreneurial skills primarily for cooperatives, NGOs and trade unions. \nAbril 17, 20-24\nSpeech and Theatre Fest 2015: SPECTRUM\nA SPECTRUM is a group of colors that can be separated from red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo and violet. These colors can be a byproduct of a prism. Just like a prism, the Department of Speech Communication and Theatre Arts produces different kinds of students passionate in different disciplines. This year\'s Speech and Theatre Fest aims to showcase what these disciplines are. \nAbril 18\nSocial Studies Education and the K to 12 Curriculum : Trends and Challenges \nBenitez Theater \nCollege of Education\n9 a.m. - 4 p.m. \nThe conference provides a venue to share best practices and present developments and results of research projects in Social Studies Education. It aims to promote collaboration and connection among scholars. educators and administrators in the field of Social Studies. \nAbril 20\nAyala Corporation - UP School of Economics Forum (AC-UPSE Economic Forum) : A Case for the Philippine Competition Law\nAyala Museum, Makati City\n3 p.m.\nThe AC-UPSE Economic Forum is a quarterly forum organized by the UPSE with support from a grant by the Ayala Corporation. The program encourages and publicly disseminates applied economic research on factors that promote sustained economic growth in the Philippines. Presentations involve a variety of topics affecting the Philippines and the world economy. \nAbril 20-25\nComputer Science (CS) Week\nA week-long event for the CS students, faculty and staff. \nAbril 21\nKorean War Films : From Unending War to the Peace Movement \nCollege of Mass Communication Auditorium \n10:30 a.m. - 12 noon\nThe paper represents the current research of Dr. John R. Eperjesi on the Korean War in both US and South Korean culture. \nAbril 21 \nAng Pagbabagong-bihis ng mga Aklat Pambata\nPanayam ni Eugene Y. Evasco\nPulungang Claro M. Recto, Bulwagang Rizal\nKolehiyo ng Arte at Literatura\n1-2:30 p.m. \nSa panayam na ito ni Dr. Eugene Y. Evasco, tatangkaing suriin ang mga bagong panitikang pambata sa anyo ng ebooks o kaya\'y picture book applications. Interactivity ang pangunahing pagtutuunan ng pansin sa mga tekstong ito. Tatalakayin dito ang natatanging uri ng mga \"aklat na may teknolohiya.\" Ibig sabihin, nakinabang ang mga aklat pambata sa mga pagbabagong dulot ng teknolohiya gaya ng animation, touch screen technology, musika at games. Sa huli, maglalatag ng tanong at hamon ang pag-aaral kung may tulong pa ang mga pagbabagong ito upang makapanghikayat ng mga mambabasa sa hanay ng kabataan. \nAbril 21\nAlimbukay : An Acoustic Cafe\nPalma Hall Rm. 400\n1-4 p.m. \nGuests will be served with free coffee and tea while Original Pilipino Music and Japanese cover bands entertain them with popular acoustic tunes. \nAbril 21-24\nEngaging in Advocacy Work : An Essential Skill for Social Development \nCSWCD Seminar Room \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nA College of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD) through the Research and Extension for Development Office (REDO) initiaterd training. \nAbril 24\nUPSE 50th Anniversary Fellowship Night : Bond for Gold \nSchool of Economics (SE) Auditorium\n6 p.m. \nA gathering of the UPSE alumni, students, faculty, staff and friends for a night of fellowship and renewal of camaraderie. This is held in celebration of UPSE\'s 50th anniversary. \nAbril 24\nUli-Uli : A Cultura Night\nSunken Garden\n6-9 p.m. \nAn evening of cultural performances and traditional games of Philippines and Japan. \nAbril 25\n\"Impact of Transatlantic Investment Treaties on Labor Relations\"\nSchool of Labor and Industrial Relations (SOLAIR) \n1-4 p.m.\nSOLAIR hosts the Annual Lecture Series featuring national and international experts from the academe, the government and the industry sectors. \nThe lecture impact of Transatlantic Investment Treaties on Labor Relations focuses on the extent to which corporations make use of the dispute settlement process of international investment treaties to challenge specific aspects of labor law (e.g. minimum wage).\nMayo 4\nParada ng Parangal\nAcademic Oval\n5 p.m.\nHudyat ng pagsisimula ng Linggo ng Parangal sa pamamagitan ng parada ng magpapatingkad sa mga tagumpay at karangalang inihatid ng iba\'t ibang yunit ng UP Diliman sa nakalipas na taon, habang sama-samang sasalubong nang buong-sigla at sigasig sa mga darating pang panahon. \nMayo 5\nChancellor\'s International Reception\nUP Theater Lobby \n5:30 p.m.\nAn annual event that brings together UPD officials and members of its international community, comprising of visiting students, faculty and researchers. With some members of the diplomatic corps in attendance, the event will also be the opportunity for UPD to promote its academic, research and extension programs. Highlights of the event are the performances by foreign students from Asia, Europe and the Americas. To be featured too are cultural presentations by UPD students. \nMayo 6\nParangal sa mga Mag-aaral\nGT-Toyota Asian Center \n2 p.m. \nIsang pagbibigay-pugay at pagkilala sa mga natatanging mag-aaral na nagpamalas ng katalinuhan at kagalingan sa kanilang mga gawaing pangmag-aaral. \nMayo 7\nParangal sa mga Retirado at Gawad Paglilingkod \nGT-Toyota Asian Center \n1 p.m.\nBilang pagpapahalaga at pasasalamat sa mga retirado at mga kawaning lubusang nag-aalay ng kanilang buong kakayahan sa pagtataguyod ng adhikain ng Unibersidad. \nMayo 8\nGawad Tsanselor\nInstitute of Biology Auditorium \n2 p.m. \nIsang hapon ng pagdiriwang at pagkilala sa kahusayan, tagumpay at serbisyo ng kaguruan, REPS, kawaning administratibo at mag-aaral ng Unibersidad ng Pilipinas. Pinakatampok na araw sa Linggo ng Parangal. \nMayo 4\nUP Diliman-wide Extension Colloquium\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\nCollege of Social Work and Community Development\n11 a.m.-5 p.m.\nA sharing of extension work and practices, perspectives, structrure and organization among UPD units to generate and enrich discussions for policy recommendations in line with the public thrust of the University.\nMayo 5-6\nAcademe Meets the Unions : Enhancing Labor Protection in Asia\'s Global Production Networks\nUniversity Hotel\n9 a.m.\nA workshop of leading Asian academics and researchers in the field of transnational global production networks (GPNs) in the Asia-Pacific region and the leading Asian labor voices advocating for social protection and labor rights throughout the GPN chain of production, particularly in the automotive, electronics/semiconductors and garments/textiles industries. \nMayo 7\nEvolution of the Philippine Working Class Struggle and Labor Movement \nBonifacio Hall\nSchool of Labor and Industrial Relations (SOLAIR) \n9 a.m. \nA forum in honor of Crisanto Evangelista organized by SOLAIR. \nThe forum gathers academics, labor historians and labor movement leaders to analyze and discuss the evolution of the Philippine working class struggle and labor movement. \nMayo 10-17\nThe 54th UP National Writers Workshop \nBaguio City\nAn annual literary workshop held every summer in Baguio City by the Likhaan : University of the Philippines Institute of Creative Writing (UP ICW). The fellows, associates and advisers of the UP ICW select 12 writers in mid-career to participate in this workshop.\nMayo 11-15\nA Basic Course in Urban and Regional Planning\nSchool of Urban and Regional Planning (SURP)\nThe SURP Training and Extension Division holds its second run of the training program A Basic Course in Urban and Regional Planning (ABC in URP). The training program is an introductory course on the basic concepts, processes and methodologies of urban and regional planning and provides updates on the latest planning approaches, tools and techniques. \nMayo 13\nCLRG@50 Lecture Series : Devolution by Nestor N. Pilar\nAssembly Hall\nNational College of Public Administration and Governance \n10 a.m. \nThe CLRG@50 Lecture Series is held in celebration of the 50th anniversary of the Center for Local and Regional Governance (CLRG) of the National College of Public Administration and Governance (NCPAG).\nThe lecture series aims to revisit the past issues and challenges on local governance as it relates to the present. Featured speakers are CLRG\'s past and present directors.\nMayo 14\nLearning Mathematics Through Origami\nDolores F. Hernandez Hall\nScience Teacher Training Center, NISMED, 2 p.m. \nLearning Mathematics Through Origami is a public lecture by Patsy Wang-Iverson, Vice President for Special Projects at the Gabriella & Paul Rosenbaum Foundation. Her work focuses on improving mathematics and science education by learning from practices around the world, including jugyokenkyuu (translated as lesson study) and origami. \nMayo 15 \nPaliwanagan sa UP Diliman : OVCRD Colloquium Series \nQuezon Hall\n3-7 p.m. \nA bi-annual activity of the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Research and Development (OVCRD).\nThe colloquium aims to create greater public awareness and appreciation of UPD\'s research and development initiatives and programs. \nMayo 20\nNeed for and Principle Contents of a National Transport Policy Act \n(SURP 50th Anniversary Public Lecture Series) \nCariño Multi-Purpose Hall\nSchool of Urban and Regional Planning (SURP) \n6 p.m. \nPresented by Dr. Primitivo C. Cal, it is the fifth in the SURP 50th Anniversary Public Lecture Series which commenced in January and will continue until October 2015. \nMayo 26-29\nEnhancing the Supervisor\'s Capability in Mentoring and Coaching \nCSWCD Seminar Room\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe 4-day, live-out training aims to enhance the knowledge, skills and attitudes of middle level supervisors in providing the needed support to improve the functioning of the supervisees. The focus is on making them proactive in intervening when there are performance gaps among the supervisees and systematically and purposively providing opportunities for their growth in their work. \nMayo 26-29\nData Analysis Using SPSS \n(Beginner\'s Course)\nComputer Laboratory\nUP Population Institute (UPPI)\nRoom 334, Palma Hall \nThe course is designed to provide an intensive introduction to the latest version of the Statistical Package for the Social Sciences (SPSS), now known as IBM SPSS Statistics. SPSS is a user-friendly Windows-based statistical software and a powerful and versatile tool for data analysis. The training combines lecture and hands-on laboratory sessions and involves an analysis of a subset of a large dataset. \nMayo 27-29\n2nd Training Workshop on Legal Research and Library Services Made Ready\nUP Law Library \nOrganized by the UP Law Library and the AASDI (Asosasyon ng Aklatan at Sinupan ng Diliman), the 3-day training workshop on legal research and library services uses informative and interactive discussions, networking sesssions and activities to allow participants to interact, inspire and learn from one another. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1072, 'E2-1072AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 1, Blg 3 (5 copies)', '', '', 'Hunyo-Hulyo 2015', 'Academic clusters organize faculty workshops on UPD GE framework\nHunyo 10\nArts and Letters cluster\n9 a.m. - 12 p.m.\nScience and Technology cluster\nNEC Audiovisual Room\n1-5 p.m.\nHunyo 11\nManagement and Economics cluster\nAIT Seminar Room\n8 a.m. - 12 p.m. \nSocial Sciences and Law cluster\nPalma Hall 207\n1 - 5 p.m. \nIn each workshop, the academic units concerned are expected to review and revise the General Education (GE) framework. This will entail looking at the context/rationale for revising the GE program, the philosophy/definition of general education, the pedagogy and different modes of inquiry for teaching GE courses, the capabilities that the GE program should develop among students, the system for classifying GE courses and the implementation scheme for the revised GE program. \nHunyo 15\nThe State of Penal Administration in the Philippines : Prospects for Reforms \nNCPAG Assembly Hall\n2 p.m.\nAnniversary Week\nIn celebration of the 63rd anniversary of the National College of Public Administration and Governance (NCPAG), the college is hosting a lecture \"The State of Penal Administration in the Philippines : Prospects for Reforms\" by Dr. Raymund E. Narag. Narag is an NCPAG alumnus and currently a visiting professor at the college. He obtained his Ph.D. from Michigan State University School of Criminal Justice in the United States as a Fulbright Scholar. \nHunyo 15-18\nHandling Children at Risk in UP Campus by UPD Security Personnel\nCSWCD Seminar Room\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe training is in line with the university\'s mandate of being a public service university providing various forms of public and volunteer service. This is also in support of UPD\'s vision for a safe, nurturing, shared, connected and sustainable spaces for its constituents. \nHunyo 17-19\nWorker\'s Institute on Labor Laws\nBonifacio Hall, SOLAIR\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe 3-day seminar covers a wide range of topics including : (a) legal rights of workers and management prerogatives; (b) allowable job contracting; (c) collective bargaining concepts, practices and issues; (d) unfair labor practices; (e) labor-management conflict resolution; (f) hours and conditions of work; (g) wages and wage-related benefits; (h) social welfare benefits; (i) just causes of termination of employment; and (j) resignation and retirement.\nHunyo 18\nPag-inog at Pagsulong : Ika-107 Kaarawan ng UP\nUniversity Theater\n7 p.m.\nIsang gabi ng pagtatanghal ng mga mag-aaral, guro at kawani ng Unibersidad ng Pilipinas-Diliman, sa direksyon ni Prop. Josefina Estrella.\nAng UP ay umiinog sa tatlong saligang adhikain : pagtuturo, pananaliksik at gawaing ekstensyon. Ang tatlong ito ang bumubuo sa kaibuturan ng tungkulin ng UP sa paglilingkod sa sambayanan. Kung kaya\'t marapat lamang na sa tuwing sumasapit ang kaarawan ng pagkakatatag ng Unibersidad ay balikan, pagnilayan at ipagbunyi ang ambag ng UP sa ikauunlad ng bansang Pilipinas. \nHunyo 18\n\"Nagsimula sa Puso\" digitally restored and re-mastered\nCine Adarna\n7 p.m.\nThe restored feature, shot in UP Diliman, premieres at the Cine Adarna of the UPFI Film Center in UPD at 7 p.m. on June 18, most fittingly as UP marks its 107th Foundation Day. \nHunyo 18\nTwelve Hundred Miles\nCollege of Mass Communication Auditorium \n3-5 p.m. \nTwelve Hundred Miles (2015, 44 minutes) is an experimental documentary by Joni Gutierrez which juxtaposes the footage from Beijing shot on June 4, 2014 with the Occupy Central protests in Hong Kong (HK) in the same year. It exhibits a perspective of a foreign student faced with an overwhelming need to understand the intricacies of HK-mainland relations. \nHunyo 25\nCapacity Building Seminar on Scholarly Research and Publication\n3/F UP College of Law Library\nEspiritu Hall\n7:30 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nResearch is integral for the growth of any profession as it anchors the established principles and serves to strengthen its foundations. It enforces, challenges, or in some cases, refutes established dogma and theories from which professional practice arises. \nThe seminar, organized by the UP Law Library and the AASDI (Asosasyon ng Aklatan at Sinupan ng Diliman), is designed and developed to assist Library Information System (LIS) professionals in conducting, writing and publishing their research. The (LIS) profession, like any other discipline, benefits from research as it learns which theories, principles and methodologies work, or do not. \nHunyo 26\nICT Skills and Innovations for Libraries \n3/F UP College of Law Library\nEspiritu Hall\n7:30 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nRapidly changing technology and evolving user needs and habits compel Library Information System (LIS) professionals to always be at the forefront of these developments to better understand and serve the library users. Improving the LIS professionals\' skills in the Information and Communication Technology (ICT) allows them to have more confidence in exploring the vast landscape the technology offers, while viewpoints from outside the profession enables them to have a fresh take on how the library and its services are seen externally. This renewed perspective, coupled with the improved ICT skills, help LIS professionals be more creative in designing and creating programs to improve the users experience in the library. \nUPD academic units\' recognition rites schedule\nHunyo 25\nHunyo 26\nHunyo 27\nHunyo 28\n104th UPD General Commencement Exercises\n\"Pag-uugat, Pag-uugnay, Pagyabong\"\nUPD Amphitheater\n7:30 a.m. \nSpeaker : Bro. Armin A. Luistro, FSC\nSecretary, Department of Education\nHunyo 28\nHunyo 29\nHunyo 30\nCall for papers for The 16th Biennial Symposium on Literature and Culture in the Asia-Pacific Region\nWhile all literatures explore the forbidden, this Symposium scheduled in November seeks to investigate its implications specifically for the literatures, cultures and perspectives of the Asia-Pacific region seen by scholars on and in the region. It invites research n impropriety in all its forms, from mischief and rule-breaking to crime, sin and subversion. It also celebrates writing itself as a dangerous or deadly habit, a form of deviant behavior, infiltration or transgression.\nHunyo 30 - Hulyo 3\nEnhancing the Supervisor\'s Capability in Mentoring and Coaching\nCSWCD Seminar Room\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe training is intended for supervisors of organizations involved in social development. The training course is designed to enhance the knowledge, attitude and skills of supervisors in providing the necessary support to improve the performance of their supervisees. It also aims to make the participants to be more proactive in intervening whenever there are performance gaps among their staff, thereby providing guidance and motivation for improvement of their work. \nHulyo 24\nTalasalitaan : Ulat sa CHED Memo Blg. 20 s2013 at Istatus ng Implementasyon ng Programang K-12 ng DepEd\n3/F SURP Building\n1-4 p.m.\nIsang panayam hinggil sa pinakabagong pangyayari sa implementasyon ng Commission on Higher Education (CHED) Memo Blg. 20 s2013 at ng Programang K-12 ng Department of Education. \nHulyo 24-28\n2015 National Science and Technology Week\nSMX Convention Center, Mall of Asia, Pasay City, 11 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nUP Diliman, through the Research Dissemination and Utilization Office of the Vice Chancellor for Research and Development (RDUO-OVCRD), participates in the 2015 National Science and Technology Week (NSTW) organized by the Department of Science and Technology\'s Technology Application and Promotion Institute (DOST-TAPI).', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1073, 'E2-1073AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 1, Blg 4 (3 copies)', '', '', 'Agosto-Setyembre 2015', 'Agosto 1-31\nBuwan ng Wika\nWikasabihan at Bugtungan sa Diliman\nPagpaskil ng mga kasabihang Filipino at mga bugtong sa palibot ng Academic Oval. Mayroong timpalak para sa mga mag-aaral ng UP Diliman na kailangang sagutin ang bugtong sa pamamagitan ng Facebook at text message. \nAklatang Bayan \nPagligid ng Aklatang Bayan ng Sentro ng Wikang Filipino (SWF) sa mga piling institusyon at kolehiyo sa UP Diliman para magbenta ng mga publikasyon ng SWF sa mababang halaga. \nPalihan ng mga Komite sa Wika\nPalihan at kumustahan ng mga kinatawan ng Komite sa Wika sa iba\'t ibang kolehiyo sa UP Diliman\nTalastagisan \nModernong balagtasan tampok ang mga pangkat ng Fliptoppers ng Tanghalang Bayan ng Kulturang Kalye (TABAKK) at mga pagtatangghal ng mga kultural na grupong mag-aaral ng UP Diliman. \nAgosto 1\nCollege of Human Kinetics (CHK) Community Recreation Program \nUniversity Gym\nThe Community Recreation Program is a sports and wellness extension class offering of the College per semester, where CHK faculty members and students share their expertise with the whole UP community.\nAgosto 5\nDulaang UP\'s 40th Theatre Season Launch\n20/20 Vision : Clarity, Originality, Perspective \nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater\n2nd floor, Palma Hall\n2 p.m.\nAgosto 5\n14 Silent Comics\n3/F South Wing Gallery, Vargas Museum \n4 p.m.\n14 Silent Comics is Manuel \"Manix\" Abrera\'s solo exhibition that presents silent comics (comics without dialogue). Characters from Philippine mythology like the manananggal, white lady, duwende and kapre are portrayed in a different light through stories that cast them as protagonists. They are either funny or philosophical, caught up in circumstances where they meet different creatures, mortal and otherwise. \nAgosto 5\nJorge Vargas : A Collecting Life : Opening of a new Permanent Exhibition \nLibrary and Archives, Vargas Museum\n4 p.m.\nThe exhibition presents three central themes in Jorge Vargas\'s practices of collecting : Kawilihan (Fascination), Kasaysayan (History) and Kasanayan (Discipline). \nAgosto 5\nBreeding Ground\n1F West Wing Gallery, Vargas Museum \n4 p.m.\nBreeding Ground focuses on the contested nature of land and how it is represented and appropriated. It presents the works of Fernando Amorsolo, Adjani Arumpac, Mark Maestro, Dominic Mangila and Jorge Vargas.\nAgosto 5\nHand Made Violence\n1F Lobby, Vargas Museum\n4 p.m. \nHand Made Violence is Bembol Dela Cruz\'s solo exhibition that presents confrontation with guns in two forms : first, in metal sheet with inscriptions in Braille; second, in painting. By asking users of unlicensed guns to describe their guns, Dela Cruz develops a \"cartographic sketch\" that makes the gun acquire a criminal face. \nAgosto 11\nA Nonparametric Option Pricing Model Using High Moments\nSchool of Statistics Auditorium \n4 p.m. \nThe colloquium presents the paper of Prof. Peter Julian Cayton on nonparametric model that includes non-Gaussian characteristics of skewness and kurtosis. The model is proposed based on the cubic market capital asset pricing model. \nAgosto 13\nKaligtasan, Kabuhayan, Karapatan : Mga Batang Manggagawa sa Tubuhan\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\nCollege of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD)\n8 a.m. - 3 p.m.\nOrganized by the UP Social Action for Research and Development Foundation, Inc. (UPSARDFI) of the CSWCD, the forum aims to disseminate the highlights of the research findings from the studies undertaken by the ABK3-UPSARDFI and University of St. La Salle Bacolod; gather feedback from the various stakeholders regarding implications of the research results; and identify recommendations for possible policy and program reforms to improve child labor conditions in sugarcane industry.  \nAgosto 13\nComparative Conundrum Between Nation-State and Muslim Governance\nA Public Lecture by Nassef Adiong, PhD\nConference Room\nInstitute of Islamic Studies\n9 a.m. - 12 p.m.\nThe study finds compelling points of contentions in comparing both nation-state and Muslim governance in terms of the 1933 Montevideo criteria (territoriality, citizenry, authority and sovereignty) including elements of history, constitution, Hallaq\'s moral predicament with modernity and difficulties with democracy, secularism, capitalism and nationalism. To go beyond this comparative conundrum, the study recommends to theoretically look into selected worldviews such as Alexander Wendt\'s proposal of a World State theory and various Islamicate civilizational analyses (i.e. from Khaldunian sociological perspective to Senturk\'s Open Civilization thesis) as alternative world orders in order to encompass an inclusive pluralist understanding of units of analysis in the international system/society (nassef.info).\nAgosto 22-Oktubre 10\nPottery Workshop\n(7 sessions, every Saturday)\nCollege of Fine Arts \n9 a.m. - 12 p.m. / 1:30 p.m. - 4 :30 p.m. \nAgosto 24-Oktubre 19\nPottery Workshop Batch 1\n(7 sessions, every Monday)\nCollege of Fine Arts\n9 a.m.-12 p.m. / 1:30 p.m. - 4:30 p.m.\nFacilitated by Prof. Romanlito Austria, the workshops aim to introduce students to basic hand-building technique in forming works and in using the wheel. \nAgosto 24-Oktubre 19\nCeramic Sculpture Workshop\n(7 sessions, every Monday)\nCollege of Fine Arts\n9 a.m. - 12 p.m. / 1:30 p.m. - 4:30 p.m. \nThis workshop familiarizes students with the nature, possibilities and processes involved in working with stoneware clay as a medium to create sculptural forms. Facilitated by Prof. Rita Gudiño, the workshop aims to provide opportunities for students to build skills and techniques in hand-building clay sculptures. \nAgosto 24\nInternational Humanitarian Law and Islamic Law on Armed Conflict and Humanitarian Affair\nConference Room\nInstitute of Islamic Studies \n9 a.m. - 12 p.m.\nOrganized by the Institute of Islamic Studies with speakers from the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), the public lecture discusses the Law on Armed Conflict with reference to the International Humanitarian Law and Islamic Law. The lecture explores both the simple and complex attributes of the law for better understanding of lawyers and non-lawyers alike. \nAgosto 24-Nobyembre 23 (Weekday Classes)\nAgosto 29-Nobyembre 14 (Saturday Classses) \nUPCM Extension Program\nThe UP College of Music Extension Program is a non-degree program of study that offers a set of music courses with the goal of providing comprehensive musicianship for youth, adults, musicians, and music educators who are not officially enrolled in the College of Music degree offerings. \nAgosto 25-28\nMandatory Continuing Legal Education\nUP Law Center\n8 a.m.\nThe Institute for the Administration of Justice is a research and training center for the improvement of the administration of justice. It actively formulates and conducts Continuing Legal Education programs (MCLE) for a member of the bar to hone their professional competence. It develops and conducts training programs on special areas of law on its own initiative or under special arrangements with other local and international organizations. \nAgosto 26-Setyembre 13\n#R</3J : A Multimedial Hallucination on William Shakespeare\'s Romeo and Juliet \nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater \n2nd floor, Palma Hall\nWeekday shows at 7 p.m.\nWeekend shows at 10 a.m., 3 p.m. and 8 p.m. \n#R</3J retells the star-crossed lovers\' narrative transforming Verona into a concrete jungle at the heart of Metro Manila - teeming with corruption, revolt, advertisements, sex, social media and condominium units. Destroy the city, the family, the government - even Shakespeare - but never destroy the will to love. \nAgosto 26-28\nThe College of Social Sciences and Philosophy and the Archaeological Studies Program\nCall for Participants\nConference on Cultural Heritage : Multidisciplinary Perspectives on Theory and Practice \nAugust 26-28, 2015\nPalma Hall, UP Diliman\nSetyembre 3-5\nOccupation and Liberation : An International Conference on the Pacific War in the Philippines\nGT-Toyota Auditorium\n8 a.m. \nThe conference aims to bring together scholars of World War II from both national and international communities in order to revisit and re-assess past studies done on the Pacific War in the Philippines; introduce new topics and approaches to the study of World War II; and develop an increased awareness and deeper appreciation for this particular period in Philippine history. \nSetyembre 5\nUAAP Season 78\nOpening Ceremonies \nSmart-Araneta Coliseum\n1 p.m.\nThe University of the Philippines (UP) is hosting the 78th season of the University Athletic Association of the Philippines (UAAP) for school year 2015-2016 with the theme \"Tumitindig, Sumusulong.\"\nSetyembre 5-18\nCombined Foundation and Advanced Certificate Course of the Paralegal Training Program on the Philippine Legal System and the Comprehensive Agrarian Reform Program, Laws, Rules, and Procedures\nMalcolm Hall\n9 a.m. - 6 p.m. \nThe UP Law Center, in coordination with the Department of Agrarian Reform, launches the first combined foundation and advanced certificate course of the Paralegal Training Program which focuses and specializes on the fundamentals of law in the Philippines and agrarian reform laws, rules and regulations. \nSetyembre 12-Nobyembre 28\nAsian Languages Extramural Classes 2015 Cycle 3 \nSetyembre 15-18\nParticipatory Monitoring and Evaluation of Social Development Projects\nSemimar Room\nCollege of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe four-day, live-out seminar workshop aims to equip social development practitioners with knowledge and skills to strengthen people\'s involvement, enhance their capacities and increase their confidence in the decision-making process. \nThe training also aims to enhance the understanding and capabilities of participants in developing appropriate participatory monitoring and evaluation systems for their respective community projects and programs. \nSetyembre 28-29\nDiliman-wide GE Conference \n8 a.m. \nThe outputs of the cluster workshops held in June and July this year will be presented and deliberated in the 2015 UPD GE Conference. \nThe conference aims to consolidate UPD\'s stand on the conceptual and operational design of the GE Program to be implemented alongside curricular changes in the respective degree programs of the different academic units. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1074, 'E2-1074AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 1, Blg 5 (2 copies)', '', '', 'Oktubre-Nobyembre 2015', 'Oktubre 1\nDEL Extramural Classes\n4th cycle 2015\nThe 4th cycle of the Department of European Languages (DEL) Extramural Classes will run from October to December 2015. Classes will be held on weekdays (2 hrs./session) and Saturdays (3 hrs./session).\nOktubre 2 \nSampling Design for Survey of Enterprises in the Philippines\nSchool of Statistics Auditorium \n4 p.m.\nThe colloquium presents the paper of Dr. Erniel Barrios on business surveys. \nBusiness surveys, according to Barrios\'s study, are very challenging for two reasons : the organizational structures of businesses are too complicated, thus it is often difficult to locate where the data is; and the distribution of some target variables like revenue is not normal but rather severely skewed. \nOktubre 2 \nPag-uugat at Pagsasanga : Antropolohiya Katambal ang Iba\'t ibang Larangang Akademiko\nPulungang Claro M. Recto \nBulwagang Rizal (Faculty Center) \n1-5 p.m.\nSa ikalawang handog na colloquium ng Departamento ng Antropolohiya, tampok ang mga piling gurong tagapagsalita, nilalayong baybayin ang ugnayan at kasaysayan ng disiplina ng Antropolohiya sa iba\'t ibang larangang akademiko at gawain, partikular sa Agham, Sosyolohiya at sa paglapat ng mga aplikasyon nito. \nOktubre 6\n#chooseright : Empowering Voters for Elections 2016 A public forum on voter\'s education\nNCPAG Assembly Hall\n1:30 - 4 p.m.\nThe forum is the first activity of the National College of Public Administration and Governance\'s (NCPAG) Center for Leadership, Citizenship and Democracy (NCPAG-CLCD) Election Series Project. NCPAG Dean Maria Fe Mendoza, Institute of Political and Electoral Reform Executive Director Ramon Casiple, and UP Political Science Prof. Grace Gorospe-Jamon of the UP Political Science Department will serve as resource persons. \nThe forum aims to contribute in facilitating discourse and analyses on national issues affecting the 2016 elections, provide a platform for discussion and dissemination of analyses to a wider audience, and help build awareness and capacity to make informed choices among the electorate especially the first time voters and the youth. \nOktubre 7\nDemocratization Advocates in Vietnam, 1990s-2014 \nA public lecture by Dr. Benedict J. Tria Kervliet\nSeminar Room, Hall of Wisdom, Asian Center 1:30-4 p.m.\nDr. Benedict J. Tria Kervliet will discuss how, \"beginning in the mid-1990s, public criticism of the Communist Party government in Vietnam spread to the point that by 2014 it became a prominent feature of the country\'s political scene. He is Professor Emeritus at the Department of Political and Social Change, School of International, Political and Strategic Studies, Australian National University. \nOktubre 7-25\nKing Lear / Haring Lear\nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater\n2/F Palma Hall\nWeekday shows at 7 p.m. \nWeekend shows at 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. \nThe play is set in the waning years of a Southeast Asian kingdom replete with appropriate music, movement, costumes and properties of the region without losing the themes, images and poetry of the playwright\'s supreme achievement. King Lear / Haring Lear is the epitome of how deceit and the love for the superficial can tragically bring families to ruin and great kingdoms to ashes. \nOktubre 8\nIndirect Fertility Estimation in light of International Labor Migration : Differentials across Selected Variables \nSchool of Statistics Auditorium\n4 p.m.\nThe colloquium presents the study of Michael Dominique del Mundo on the relationship of Migration and Fertility in the Philippines by focusing on the effect of spousal separation due to international labor migration on fertility. \nOktubre 8\nJosefino Chino Toledo\'s Misa Lingua Sama-Sama\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium \nCollege of Music\n7 p.m.\nFirst complete performance of Toledo\'s Misa Lingua Sama-Sama, a concert mass in Latin and Filipino featuring the UP Dance Company, UP Madrigal Singers, Aleron, UP Los Baños Choral Ensemble Technological Institute of the Philippines Choral Society, St. Scholastica\'s College Chamber Choir / Ateneo Glee Club Alumni, UP Manila Chorale, AUIT Chamber Vocal Ensemble. \nOktubre 8-9\nFuture Perfect : Cities at the Forefront of Change and Development \nEastwood Richmonde Hotel, Quezon City \n8 a.m. - 6 p.m. \nThe international conference showcases innovative approaches and reforms to city administration. It is organized by the UP National College of Public Administration and Governance in partnership with the Quezon City Government. \nOktubre 16\nThe Link between Expenditure on Contraceptives and Number of Young Dependents in the Philippines \nSchool of Statistics Auditorium\n4 p.m.\nProf. Michael Daniel Lucagbo used the Family Income and Expenditure Survey (FIES) 2009 data to examine the factors affecting the number of young dependents in a household, and focuses in particular on the household\'s level of contraceptive expenditure. \nOktubre 16\nMusic Culture Workshop with Dr. David Urrows\nCollege of Music\n3-5 p.m.\nThis event is part of the music colloquium series of the College of Music. The target audiences of this music culture workshop are doctoral students. Prior to the workshop, attendees will read two to three of the visiting scholar\'s most recently published research, and one or two discussants from the College may formally respond to them before the open forum. \nOktubre 17-18, 24-25 at 27-29\nUAAP Table Tennis Event \nSeason 78\nNinoy Aquino Stadium, Rizal Memorial Sports Complex, Malate, Manila\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe University Athletic Association of the Philippines (UAAP) Table Tennis Competition will be participated by the eight UAAP member universities. Both the UP men and women\'s team will try to regain the championships this season. The UP women\'s team was the UAAP Season 76 champions. \nOktubre 19\nGrants, Gigs and Gimmicks 2015\nAldaba Recital Hall\nUniversity Theater Complex \n2-4 p.m. and 4-6 p.m. \nThe UP Diliman Office for Initiatives in Culture and the Arts (UPD-OICA) invites registered UP Diliman student organizations (college-based or university-wide) to the third edition of the annual Grants, Gigs and Gimmicks 2015, a free orientation and workshop regarding the Financial Grants Program. \nOktubre 19-23\nThe 36th Asian Conference on Remote Sensing (ACRS 2015)\nCrowne Plaza Galleria, Quezon City\nThe Asian Conference on Remote Sensing (ACRS) is an annual international scientific conference in Asian cities with voluntary participation of the host country and researchers, educators, professionals and students from all over the world. This is the second time that the Philippines was chosen to host the ACRS, the first time was in 1988. \nOktubre 20-23\nEnhancing the Supervisor\'s Capability in Mentoring and Coaching \nSeminar Room\nCollege of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe seminar-workshop is an introductory skill-building course designed for program/project managers, senior community development workers, social workers and other social development practitioners with supervisory responsibilities. The content focuses on the concepts, principles and processes of supervision with special focus on mentoring and coaching functions utilizing appropriate methods and tools. \nOktubre 22\nUP SURP\'s 50th Anniversary Celebration and General Alumni Homecoming\nAng Bahay ng Alumni \n5:30 p.m. \nIn celebration of the 50th year of the UP School of Urban and Regional Planning (UP SURP), a series of activities will be held such as parade around the campus and groundbreaking of the new SURP building. This will be capped by the 50th anniversary celebration and general alumni homecoming at the Ang Bahay ng Alumni. \nOktubre 22-24\nNational Conference on Research in Teacher Education \nBenitez Hall (College of Education)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe National Conference on Research in Teacher Education (NCRTE) is conducted biennially by the UP College of Education since 1997. It has served as a venue for discussions on educational issues based on research findings. \nOktubre 23 \nConstructing Leading Economic Indicators for the Philippine Economy Using Dynamic Factor Models\nSchool of Statistics Auditorium \n4 p.m. \nThe study presents an alternative, and perhaps better, procedure to the Leading Economic Indicators System (LEIS) in nowcasting the movements of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) using the Dynamic Factor Models (DFM). This paper used 30 monthly economic indicators in capturing a common factor to nowcast movements of GDP via the DFM. \nOktubre 30\nCall for submission for UP Press Critical Essay Writing Contest \nOktubre 30 \nDemographic Sweet Spot and Dividend in the Philippines : The Window of Opportunity is Closing Fast\nSchool of Statistics Auditorium \n4 p.m. \nDr. Dennis S. Mapa\'s paper looks at the population structure of the country from 2010 to 2100, using actual census data from the Philippine Statistics Authority (PSA) and projections on future population from the United Nations (UN), to estimate the period when the country will experience the demographic window of opportunity. \nNobyembre 9\nLikha-Likas : Reconfiguring Music, Nature and Myth : A Symphonic Band Concert\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium \nCollege of Music \n8 p.m. \nThis is the UP leg of the weeklong 33rd Asian Composers League (ACL) Internationalo Festival and Conference. \nThe concert features the UP Symphonic Band under the baton of Prof. Rodney Ambat. The UP Symphonic Band will play new compositions of ACL member countries. \nNobyembre 10 \n(Re) Present! A Public Presentatio of Communication Research Student Papers \nCollege of Mass Communication\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThis whole-day event organized by the Department of Communication Research of the UPD College of Mass Communication showcases the research works of students and recent alumni of the Department. The morning session presents the research output of the Data Interpretation and Reporting class, while the afternoon session features student research papers that have been presented in international conferences. Topics covered by the student papers include health and wellness, leisure, film, politics, poverty, disaster, diaspora and the Filipino family. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
