(1075, 'E2-1075AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 1, Blg 6 (2 copies)', '', '', 'Disyembre 2015-Enero 2016', 'Disyembre 1\n\"Paano Lumakas ang Loob ng Mahiyaing Manok\"\nHall of Wisdom\nGT-Toyota Asian Cultural Center\n2:30 - 4 p.m. \nA public forum about \"Ang Mahiyaing Manok,\" a children\'s book that bagged the Encouragement Prize at the 2000 Noma Concours for Children\'s Picture Book Illustrations in Tokyo, Japan. The forum is free and open to the public. \nDisyembre 7\nPiano Music from Romantic Manila \nAbelardo Hall Auditorium \n6:30 p.m.\nAn evening of Filipino piano music from the 1860s to 1960s, to be performed by Israeli-American pianist Sally Pinkas, professor of music and pianist-in-residence at the Hopkins Center of Dartmouth College, Hanover, New Hampshire. \nDisyembre 10\nKRIZZMAZZ JAZZ at the Carillon\nThe Carillon Plaza\n6 p.m. \nThe UP Alumni Association inaugurates the Carillon Concerts Series at the Carillon Plaza with a concert by The UP Jazz Band, with conductor Prof. Raymundo Maigue and artistic director Dr. Ramon Acoymo. \nDisyembre 11\nTanglaw 2015 : Isang Pamaskong Konsyerto\nUP Theater\n3 p.m. and 7 p.m. \nAng konsyerto ay bahagi ng pagdiriwang ng ika-80 taong anibersaryo ng UP Filipiniana Dance Group (UPFDG). Lalahukan ito ng mga kasalukuyan at dating direktor at miyembro ng UPFDG. \nDisyembre 14\nParada ng mga Parol 2015\nAcademic Oval\n5 p.m.\nIto ang paligsahan ng pinakamagagandang parol ng mga akademiko at di-akademikong yunit ayon sa temang \"Dingas : Adhikaing Diliman, Adhikaing Bayan.\" Ipaparada ang mga parol paikot sa Academic Oval at magkakaroon ng palatuntunan sa Amphitheater. Ito ay tatampukan ng fireworks display. \nDisyembre 14\nMaskipaps : The Crossover\nSunken Garden\n9 p.m.\nIsang pangkomunidad na pagdiriwang ng UP sa pangunguna ng Beta Epsilon na dadaluhan din ng mga mag-aaral mula sa iba\'t-ibang pamantasan. \nEnero 8-9\nFor the Love of Death : Human Osteoarchaeology in Southeast Asia and the Pacific \nArchaeological Studies Program \nThe 2-day international conference aims to create an opportunity for researchers to present and discuss their latest work on archaeological human remains assemblages from across Southeast Asia and the Pacific. \nEnero 8-9\nWagas na Pag-aaruga : The Yaya Training Workshop\nAudio Visual Room\nCollege of Social Work and Community Development \n8:30 a.m. - 4 p.m. \nThis 2-day event aims to provie the Yayas the basics of child development that will enable them to facilitate appropriate activities as they interact with the children. Specifically, it focuses on how to : keep children stimulated through play; help children become more independent ; and deal with challenging behaviors of children. \nEnero 26-29\nEnhancing the Supervisor\'s Capability in Mentoring and Coaching\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\nCollege of Social Work and Community Development \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThis seminar-workshops is an introductory skill-building course designed for program/project managers, senior community development workers, social workers and other social development practitioners with supervisory responsibilities. The content focuses on the concepts, principles and processes of supervision with special focus on mentoring and coaching functions utilizing appropriate methods and tools. \nEnero 28\nHommage a\' l\'enfant : Isang Pagtatanghal sa Pista ng Sto. Niño\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium, College of Music 6-7:30 p.m.\nThe third week of January is significant to a number of communities because of the feast of the Holy Child. This event is commemorated at the University through an offering of music for and inspired by children. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1076, 'E2-1076AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 1, Blg 1 (3 copies) UP Diliman Month 2016', '', '', 'Pebrero 2016', 'Pebrero 1\nBodabil sa Kampus : Seremonya ng Pagbubukas ng Buwan ng UP Diliman\nUniversity Amphitheater\n6 p.m.\nHalaw mula sa bodabil, isang engrandeng programa ang isasaentablado sa may ampiteatro ng UP Diliman. Layunin ng seremonya ang ipagbunyi ang mga artista ng bayan hindi lamang bilang manlilikha ng obra maestra kundi bilang mga iskolar ng sining. \nPebrero 1-6\nPasalubong Festival (Pasafest) 2016\nPalma Hall and Kalayaan Residence Hall\nAn annual event celebrated in the Kalayaan Residence Hall, Pasafest showcases the dormers respective cultural identity through cuisines, cultural performances and innovative booths. \nPebrero 2-23\nUsapang Pambansang Alagad ng Sining\nBulwagang Recto\n2:30 p.m.\nIto ay serye ng lektura na katatampukan ng mga tala ukol sa buhay nila Lamberto Avellana, Manuel Conde, NVM Gonzalez at Severino Montano. Tatalakayin din sa mga lektura ang mga kabuluhan ng kanilang mga gawa sa kasalukuyang lipunang Pilipino.\nPebrero 2-5\nBIYABIT : Isang Pagtatampok ng Lahing Ala-eh sa Diliman\nAS Lobby and Tambayan Complex, Vinzons Hall\nA 2-part event which celebrates the culture and traditions of the province of Batangas : Tan-aw and Mual. \nTan-aw, a Batangueño word for glimpse, is a weeklong exhibit on the essence of the province where the largest balisong in the country, local handicrafts and some major products will be showcased. \nPebrero 3\nConde sa Dap-ay : Señorito\nCollege of Mass Communication Dap-ay\n7 p.m. \n\"Señorito,\" isang pelikula ni Manuel Conde. \nIto ay tungkol sa isang ama na umupa ng isang babae upang magpanggap bilang isang mayamang tao at gamitin ang kanyang karisma para baguhin ang maling pamumuhay ng kanyang lalaking anak. Habang nagtatagumpay ang plano ng ama, ang kanyang anak at ang inupahang babae ay tunay na nagka-ibigan, bagay na taliwas sa kanilang naging kasunduan. \nPebrero 4\nConde sa Dap-ay : Genghis Khan\nCollege of Mass Communication Dap-ay \n7 p.m.\n\"Genghis Khan,\" isang pelikula ni Manuel Conde.\nIto ay nagsasalaysay kung paanong gumawa si Temujin ng isang hukbo at napagtagumpayan ang pagkamit ng maraming lupain upang hirangin o bansagan na Genghis Khan, ibig sabihin ay \"haring walang katumbas.\" Sa kabila ng kanyang tagumpay, naging alipin siya ng kanyang pag-ibig sa anak na babae ng kanyang kalaban.\nPebrero 5\nPagpupugay : A Tribute to the National Artists\nPulungang C.M. Recto, Bulwagang Rizal \n5 p.m.\nUP Press, in partnership with the UPD College of Arts and Letters, re-launche the works of 13 National Artists of the Philippines. \nPebrero 6-20\nBasic Drawing and Painting Workshop 2016\n(3-sessions, every Saturday)\nCollege of Fine Arts\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nPebrero 7\nUPIS Centennial Fun Run : Bagong Siglo, Bagong Sigla : UPIS Takbo Pa!\nAcademic Oval\n4:10 a.m. \nThe fun run is a fund-raising activity of the UP Integrated School Parent-Teacher Association for the construction of the UPIS gymnasium. Participants get a chance to win an iPad Mini. \nThe activity is also in line with the centennial celebration of UPIS. \nPebrero 7-21\nHimigsikan\nCarillon Plaza\n5 p.m.\nAng Himigsikan ay ang taunang serye ng mga konsyertong handog ng UP Diliman sa komunidad sa bawat araw ng Linggo tuwing Pebrero. Sa taong ito, itatampok ang musika ng mga grupong hinubog o nakilala sa UPD. \nPebrero 10\nAvellana sa Arki : Badjao\nCollege of Architecture Amphitheater\n7 p.m. \n\"Badjao,\" isang pelikula ni Lamberto Avellana.\nKinikilala bilang \"pinakaunang mahusay na pelikula na naglarawan ng tradisyunal na kaugalian ng isang grupong minorya,\" tinalakay ng pelikulang \"Badjao\" kung paanong ang dalawang grupong naglalaban, ang mga Badjao at ang mga Moro, ay nakamit ang isang mapayapang kasunduan sa pamamagitan ng karanasan ng bagong kasal na pinuno ng mga Badjao at ng isang Moro na pinaglaban ang kanilang relasyon sa kabila ng mga pagtutol ng parehong grupo. \nPebrero 10-28\nTisoy Brown : Hari ng Wala\nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater\n2/F Palma Hall\nWeekday shows at 7 p.m.\nWeekend shows at 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. \nTisoy Brown : Hari ng Wala is Dulaang UP\'s third offering for its 40th Theater Season. Jose Estrella directs the play. \nPebrero 11\nTugs of War : Local Governments, National Government\nPCED Auditorium, School of Economics \n3 p.m.\nThe Ayala-UP School of Economics Forum on Tugs of War : Local Governments, National Government offers an economic perspective on the jurisdictional or functional conflicts among local governments or between local governments and national government under decentralization. The causes, consequences and conclusions of these conflicts will also be discussed. \nPebrero 11\nAvellana sa Arki : A Portrait of the Artist as Filipino\nCollege of Architecture Amphitheater \n7 p.m.\n\"A Portrait of the Artist as Filipino,\" isang pelikula ni Lamberto Avellana.\nIto ay base sa akda ni Nick Joaquin na itinuturing na \"pinakamahalagang dulang Pilipino sa English.\" Si Joaquin ay isang Pambansang Alagad ng Sining para sa Literatura. \nPebrero 13\nElevate 2016 : Utak at Puso\nUniversity Theater \n3 and 7 p.m.\nA dance concert of the UP Varsity Pep Squad, the project aims to present the different dance genres that the UP Pep Squad can do as well as to showcase the talents and creativity of the dancers and drummers of the squad. The concert also promotes school spirit. \nPebrero 15\nTUKLAS : A Look into Landscape Architecture\nNISMED Auditorium \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe seminar/workshop aims to give students more ideas on what landscape architecture is all about and how the profession can contribute in a community in terms of aesthetic qualities and how it introduces solutions to sustainable environment development through design. \nPebrero 15\nASEAN Youth Cultural Forum\nGT Toyota Auditorium \n9 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nWith a theme \"Locating the Filipino : Advancing Philippine Culture in the ASEAN,\" the forum seeks to address the current issue of the ASEAN integration and its implications on culture and the arts among UPD students, artists and cultural workers. \nPebrero 16-17\nMontano sa UP Theater Stage : The Ladies and the Senator\nUniversity Theater Stage\n3 and 7 p.m.\nIsang komedya ni Severino Montano tungkol sa pagbisita ni Anthony Maripal, isang Pilipinong senador na nasa Estados Unidos. Pinaghahandaan ng senador ang isang \'welcome party\' ng mga opisyal ng Filipino Women\'s Club ng Washington D.C. Ngunit bago pa man dumating ang senador, pinag-uusapan na ng kababaihan kung papaano pa nito nagagawang makapag-relaks samantalang sa Pilipinas ay may nakabinbin na kasong \'plunder\' laban dito. \nPebrero 16-19\nCarovana 2016\nUP Arki Buildings 1 and 2 and Amphitheater\nThe weeklong arts and music festival that include exhibit of student artworks, daily performances of ARKAIRA members and applicants, and a culminating activity with special performances of local bands. \nPebrero 19\nBawat Bata, Artista : Konsyerto ng UP Cherubim and Seraphim\nUniversity Theater Stage\n3 and 7 p.m.\nThe concert aims to showcase composition and arrangement of Philippine classics by well-known composers as well as works from the contemporary and popular repertoire. The concert will also feature works of National Artists for Music Lucio San Pedro and Ramon P. Santos.\nPebrero 20\nSpeech Cup 2016 PAMANA : Boses ng Pinalaya, Boses na Magpapalaya\nUP Film Institute \n1-5 p.m. \nSpeech Cup is an annual speech competition open to high school and college students nationwide. It serves as a venue for students to express themselves and their beliefs and principles through choral competition and oral interpretation. \nPebrero 20\nHaranafest\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium, College of Music\n3 p.m.\nHaranafest is an inter-college choral competition for students organized by the UPD Office of the Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs (OVCSA) and the University Student Council.\nThe theme of the inaugural Haranefest is \"Awit sa Pelikula.\" The official contest piece is \"Anak Dalita,\" theme song of the movie of the same title directed by National Artist for Film Lamberto Avellana. The choice of songs of the participating college choirs will be drawn from the theme songs of Filipino movies from the 1940s to the present. \nPebrero 22\nPagpapasinaya ng Selyo ni N.V.M. Gonzalez\nUniversity Theater, Lobby\n2 p.m.\nKasama ang National Commission for Culture and the Arts, pormal na pasisinayan ang espesyal na selyo tampok si NVM Gonzalez, Pambansang Alagad ng Sining Para sa Panitikan. \nPebrero 22\nWanderer in the Night of the World : A Dance Concert featuring the UP Dance Company\nUniversity Theater Stage\n4 and 7:30 p.m.\nIto ay isang konsyerto tampok ang UP Dance Company upang bigyang buhay ang mga tula ni NVM Gonzalez sa pamamagitan ng galaw at sayaw.  \nAng konsyerto ay sa direksiyon ni Angela Lawenko-Baguilat.\nPebrero 24\nN.V.M. Gonzalez\'s The Bread of Salt\nBulwagan ng Dangal\n3 and 7 p.m.\nHandog ng Teatrong Mulat ng Pilipinas ang isang palabas na papet na \"The Bread of Salt.\"\nSa direksiyon ni Amihan Bonifacio-Ramolete, dekana ng Kolehiyo ng Arte at Literatura, at mga disenyong papet ni Sig Pecho, layunin ng palabas na mas mapalapit sa mga batang manonood ang yaman ng wika at kultura ng Pilipinas na ipinamalas ni NVM Gonzalez sa kanyang akda. Isa rin itong pagkakataong makilalang maigi ng kabataan ang mahalagang teksto sa kasaysayan ng panitikan ng Pilipinas. \nPebrero 26\nSeremonya ng Pagwawakas : Panahon ng Luwalhati\nUniversity Theater\n7 p.m. \nIsang simple ngunit makabuluhang konsyertong katatampukan ng sayaw, poesiya at awitin ng mga kontemporaneong artista at obra maestra na sumisimbolo sa pangunguna ng UP sa pagpapatuloy ng mayaman at malalim na sining ng bayan.', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1077, 'E2-1077AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 2, Blg 3 (4 copies) UP Diliman 2016', '', '', 'Abril-Mayo 2016', 'Abril 3\nThe CentEEEnnial Run\nUP Academic Oval\n5 a.m.\nThe CentEEEnnial Run is a fund-raising activity of the UP Electrical and Electronics Engineering Alumni Association, Inc. The activity is also in line with the centennial celebration of the UP EEEI.\nAbril 4-15\nTeaching Preschoolers and Early Graders in the Context of the K to 12 Curriculum \nUP College of Education\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nA 10-day training workshop intended for administrators and professors who are handling courses in preschool and the early grades and teacher-practitioners of preschool and primary classes. \nAbril 6\nThe Dressing Room/Ang Dressing Room That Which Flows Away Ultimately Becomes Nostalgia/Ang Dressing Room Kung Saan Lubusang Pangungulila ang Dulot ng Panahon\nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater\n2/F Palma Hall\nWeekday shows at 7 p.m.\nWeekend shows at 10 a.m. and 3 p.m.\nThe Dressing Room/Ang Dressing Room is a tender and humorous drama about actors, the theatre, aging, surviving and moving on. Dr. Alexander Cortez directs the play. \nAbril 8\nThe Philippines and Thailand : A Reversal of Fortune? A Public Forum on Comparative Politics and Economic Development\nSeminar Room, GT-Toyota Asian Cultural Center, Asian Center\n2:30-4 p.m.\nUsing political economy, state-society and cultural lenses, the public forum examines how political factors link up to economic development. It also interrogates the narratives of economic growth and decline from different perspectives. \nAbril 8-13 at 15\nGawad Pangulo art and design competitions Awarding ceremony and exhibition of works\nGallery and Open Court \nUP College of Fine Arts (CFA) \n6 p.m.\nThe Gawad Pangulo held UP System-wide art competitions this February : the On-Your-Spot art competition, the Products UPGrade design competition and the Multimedia Competition. \nAbril 10-17 at 24; Mayo 8, 15 at 22\nBasic or Advance Drawing and Painting Workshop\nUP College of Fine Arts\n8 a.m.- 5 p.m. \nFacilitated by Prof. Yasmin Almonte, the 3-day workshop offers participants the chance to hone their skills in basic drawing and their choice of painting formats (portrait, still life, landscape, figure drawing, or abstract art).\nAbril 11-Hunyo 11\nUP Ceramic Studio Pottery and Ceramic Sculpture Workshops\nUP College of Fine Arts\nThe UP Ceramic Studio Extension Program offers 7-session workshops in ceramic arts to participants of all ages. \nAbril 11-15 \nTambulan sa Diliman XI\nUP College of Arts and Letters Grounds\nThe weeklong event serves as a venue for indigeneous peoples to share to the public their everyday realities and to shed light on pressing issues, such as on ancestral domains and cultural preservation, among others. Through creative workshops, cultural performances and a film showing activity, Kontra-GaPi hopes to surface the challenges that majority of these local communities experienced or are still experiencing and to inspire the general public to proactively respect and protect the rights of indigenous peoples. \nAbril 16\n3K UP: Takbo Para sa Kabataan, Kalikasan, Kinabukasan\nUP Academic Oval\n6 a.m.\nA run for a cause organized by the College of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD) administrative staff and faculty, together with Tatak CSWCD scholars, the UP CSWCD Student Council, UP CD Circle and JSWAP. \nAbril 16-Hunyo 18\nDepartment of European Languages Extramural Languages Extramural Courses 2nd cycle 2016\nCollege of Arts and Letters Building\nThe 2nd cycle 2016 of the Department of European Languages (DEL) Extramural Courses will run from 16 April to 18 June 2016. Classes will be held on weekdays (2 hrs./session) and Saturdays (3 hrs./session) \nAbril 18-Mayo 20\nSummer Fun Classes 2016\nSummer Fun is the annual summer program offered by the Teaching in the Early Grades Area of the College of Education. \nAbril 18-Mayo 14\nContinuing Education for Music Teachers (CEMT)\nUP College of Music\n8:30 a.m.-5 p.m.\nThe training is a post-baccalaureate summer certificate program (3 levels) offered by the UP College of Music Extension Program designed to address the need for music teachers to enhance their musical growth and teaching competencies. \nAbril 18\nThe Role of UP EEEI in the Philippine Innovation Ecosystem\nPLDT MLH (VLC), EEEI Bldg. I \n2:00 PM\nThe year-long lecture series aims to highlight the accomplishments of the EEE alumni, especially those who have been successful in their career in the Philippines. In addition, the lecture aims to instill the idea to undergraduate and graduate students that one does not need to find work opportunities overseas to have a successful career. \nAbril 19-30\nIndex 2016 : An Industrial Design Portfolio Exhibit\nCorredor and Foyer\nUP College of Fine Arts (CFA) \n5 p.m. \nThis annual exhibition showcases portfolio works by senior Industrial Design students from the D197 (Special Topics in Industrial Design) class of Dante Cruz. \nAbril 20\nBalik-tanaw sa mga Ambag ni Conkin sa Antropolohiya\nH. Otley Beyer Museum, Gusaling Palma \n2-5 p.m.\nBilang pagpupugay sa naging buhay ni Harold Conklin, ang Departamento ng Antropolohiya ay magkakaroon ng isang porum na magbabalik tanaw sa kanyang mga naging ambag sa Antropolohiya sa Pilipinas. \nAbril 20\nPelikula, Kasaysayan, at Lipunan : Pagmamapa at Kritika sa Tunguhin ng Sineng Filipino \nPanayam nina Prof. Nick Deocampo, Prof. Patrick Campos, at Choy Pangilinan\nCollege of Mass Communication Auditorium \n1-4 p.m. \nLayon ng panayam na talakayin at suriin ang kasalukuyang lagay ng sineng Filipino na may pagbibigay diin sa hindi maitatatwang hugpungan ng pelikula at lipunan. Sasalingin ng tatlong papel ng mga tagapagsalita ang mga usapin ukol sa pelikula, representasyon at bayani, kasaysayan ng pelikulang alternatibo, at dokumentaryo, kolektibong alaala at sineng politikal.  \nThe 2016 UP CMC Graduate Student Conference on Communication and Media Studies\nPlaridel Hall\n8:30 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe conference serves as a venue for graduate students who are interested in communication and media, to learn from each other through the presentation and discussion of their research papers. It also provides a space for students to share their experiences in graduate school and learn how to publish their papers. \nAbril 25\nBalangkas : a Symposium on Intensifying International Engagement\n3/F Melchor Hall\n9 a.m. - 5:30 p.m.\nThe Symposium on Internalization is intended to continue recognizing institutions, as well as individuals, who have been instrumental in moving forward the programs and activities that are in line with UPD\'s pursuit of international engagement. \nAbril 25-26\nUPD International Fair\n2/F Lobby, Melchor Hall\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe UPD International Fair is intended to continue recognizing institutions, as well as individuals, who have been instrumental in moving forward the programs and activities that are in line with UPD\'s pursuit of international engagement. \nAbril 26\nDigital Vigilantes : Online Shaming and Surveillance Culture in Top Gear Philippines\' Facebook Page\nCollege of Mass Communication Auditorium \n1-2:30 p.m. \nThe paper argues that the Top Gear Philippines\' Facebook page has transformed into a radically new site of \"crowdsourced\" forms of social norms and punishment for civic deviance and transgressions, and introduce coming greater capacities for negotiation, resistance, power and control in the digitally mediated surveillance society. \nAbril 26\nDigital Vigilantes : Online Shaming and Surveillance Culture in Top Gear Philippines\' Facebook Page\nCollege of Mass Communication Auditorium \n1-2:30 p.m. \nThe paper argues that the Top Gear Philippines\' Facebook page has transformed into a radically new site of \"crowdsourced\" forms of social norms and punishment for civic deviance and transgressions, and introduce coming greater capacities for negotiation, resistance, power and control in the digitally mediated surveillance society. \nAbril 26\nFamily picture : a study on the influence of news media on the voting public\'s perceived image of political dynasties in the province of Nueva Ecija. \nCollege of Mass Communication Auditorium \n3 - 4:30 p.m.\nThe paper aims to discover how the news media contribute to the voting public\'s formation of their perceived image regarding political dynasties in Nueva Ecija. \nMayo 14-Hulyo 16\nAsian Languages Extramural Classes (Cycle 2)\nUP Department of Linguistics \n8 a.m.- 5 p.m. \nIn line with the UP Department of Linguistics Extension Agenda, the Department undertakes extension activities with its goal of integrating linguistic knowledge into language pedagogy that focuses on the teaching and promotion of Asian Languages. \nMayo 16-20 \nLinguistics for Language Teachers \nUP Department of Linguistics \n9 a.m.-12 noon; 1-4 p.m. \nA one-week seminar based on a continuing linguistic research into the differences between unrelated languages (e.g., English and Filipino), and between language varieties (e.g., Philippine English and International English). It serves to make the participants appreciate that learning of a second language is, first and foremost, exposure to exemplars of that language. \nMayo 22-29\n55th UP National Writers Workshop\nUP Los Baños\nTwelve writers from different genres of poetry, fiction, creative non-fiction and drama present their works in progress, and talk about their craft, in this year\'s UP National Writers Workshop (UP NWW). The UP NWW is for advanced writers only. The fellows are accepted not only on the basis for their publications and awards but also for the potential of their current literary projects. \nMayo 26-28\nSEALS26\nThe Annual Meeting of the Southeast Asian Linguistics Society\nCentury Park Hotel, Manila \nAs a primary venue for exchange of linguistic ideas, the Southeast Asian Linguistics Society (SEALS) conference focuses on the language and linguistics of Southeast Asia, including the Austroasiatic, Austronesian, Hmong-Mien, Tibeto-Burman and Tai-Kadai families, and provides a venue for scholars to share their research. The SEALS conference regularly circumnavigates the globe and has met not only in the United States, but also Southeast Asia, Australia and Europe. \nMayo 31\nCall for Session Proposals for the SIMSEA Regional Symposium 2016\nThe SIMSEA Regional Symposium 2016 will focus on sub-themes and areas of research to meet the goals of sustainable development such as ocean health, productivity of marine ecosystems and sustainable livelihood; climate change and variability; weather extremes; disaster management and adaptation in the coastal zones; socio ecological dynamics of sustainable use of oceans, seas and coastal resources; coastal pollution, degradation and biodiversity loss; ocean policy and trans-boundary flows. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1078, 'E2-1078AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 2, Blg 4 (7 copies) UP Diliman 2016', '', '', 'Hunyo-Hulyo 2016', 'Hunyo 1 - Agosto 15\nGawad Rogelio Sicat 2016 : Timpalak sa Pagsulat ng Tula, Maikling Kuwento at Sanaysay\nUP Departmento ng Filipino at Panitikan ng Pilipinas\nAng Gawad Rogelio Sicat 2016 ay naglalayon na himukin ang mga mag-aaral na magpasa ng kanilang mga malikhaing akda at bigyang-gawad ang nagsisimulang manunulat na nagpapakita ng kahusayan sa pagsulat sa wikang Filipino. \nHunyo 1-3\nASIALEX 2016\nAdvancing Language Teaching with Lexicography and Corpus-Building Century Park Hotel, Manila \nThe 10th International Conference of the Asian Association for Lexicography (ASIALEX) aims to present the current trends and practices in lexicography and corpus-building, promote the use of lexicography and corpora in language learning and English Language Teaching (ELT), and to bring together lexicographers, linguists and language educators from different parts of Asia and the rest of the world. \nHunyo 6 - Hulyo 5\n2016 Ramadhan Program\nUP Institute of Islamic Studies (UPII) \n3:30-7:30 p.m.\nThe celebration of the holy month of Ramadhan is an annual program of the IIS that commenced in 2014. Every day from dawn to dusk during the month, more or less 1.6 billion Muslims around the world spend complete fast abstaining from food, drink and sex. Other malevolent acts are also prohibited during this month in order to avoid the inadvertent nullification of fasting. \nHunyo 7\nInclusiveness and Competitiveness : the Challenge for the Philippines\nRoom Ruby B, Crowne Plaza Manila Galleria, Ortigas Center, QC\n9 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nThe forum features the result of a 5-year project of an international research consortium working on a research programme about the phenomenon of the \"middle-income country trap.\" The heart of the research deals with factors that drive the success of firms who are able to survive, thrive in and withstands the competitive pressures of globalization despite the handicap of operating in high-cost environments. \nHunyo 9\nCHE Inauguration and Groundbreaking \nInauguration of the newly renovated CHE Gusali 2 and Ground Breaking of CHE Museum and the Department of Family Life and Child Development Center\nAlonso Hall, College of Home Economics \n8 a.m. - 12 noon\nThe UP College of Home Economics (CHE) will inaugurate the newly renovated Gusali 2 Building that houses five classrooms that could be turned into a multi-purpose hall. There will also be ground breaking of two new facilities, the CHE Museum and the Department of Family Life and Child Development with the Child Development Center. The newly designed and created CHE website will be launched on the same day. \nHunyo 14 - Disyembre\n(tuwing Martes at Huwebes)\nIntegrated Japanese 1\nAsian Languages Extramural Classes\nUP Department of Linguistics\n5:30 - 7:30 p.m. \nThe Integrated Japanese 1 (IJI) module is composed of the first 3 modules of the Japanese language series (1,2 and 3) offered in the UP Department of Linguistics Asian Languages Extramural Classes. \nHunyo 21\nRizal as a natural scientist\nRoom 104 Old IB Zoology Building \n3 p.m. \nIn celebration of the UP Natural Sciences and Research Institute\'s (NSRI) 52nd foundation day, UP\'s 108th foundation day and of the national hero\'s 155th birth anniversary, NSRI presents a lecture about Dr. Jose Rizal. \nHunyo 23\nPARA (!) SA LAHAT : Dahil sa Pag-arangkada para sa Karapatan, Walang Dapat Naiiwan\nPaglulunsad ng PRIDE Sticker Campaign sa mga Pampasaherong Dyip sa UP\nQuezon Hall Lobby\n8:30-9:30 a.m.\nBilang paggunita sa makasaysayang Stonewall Riots noong Hunyo 28, 1969 na naging batayan ng taunang Pride March, ilulunsad ng UP Center for Women\'s and Gender Studies ang PRIDE Sticker Campaign sa mga pampasaherong dyip sa UP Diliman. \nHunyo 26\nIka-105 Pangkalahatang Pagtatapos\nAmpiteatro ng Unibersidad \n7 a.m.\nAng tema sa taong ito ay \"Pumailanlang.\"\nAng pangunahing tagapagsalita ay si Pangulong Alfredo E. Pascual.\nHulyo 20-22\nPKSS-Korean Studies Workshop 2016\nMicrotel UP Technohub\nDiliman, Quezon City\nWith the purpose of encouraging Korean Studies scholars in the Philippines to produce research in the field, the workshop aims to help Filipino Korean Studies graduate-level students, researchers and scholars to develop their ongoing research works into publishable manuscripts for submission to journals in the country and/or abroad. The organizers hope that these research works would deepen the Filipino academicians\' awareness, understanding and knowledge of Korea and Korean Studies, and encourage them to challenge or integrate the concepts and ideas promoted by these researches as they develop their own Korean Studies curriculum and produce comparative research in their own institutions. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1079, 'E2-1079AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 2, Blg 5 (7 copies) UP Diliman 2016', '', '', 'Agosto-Setyembre 2016', 'Agosto 5\nGlobal Liquidity and Financial Vulnerability\nRoom 303, UP School of Economics \n4 p.m. \nThe study by Dr. Maria Socorro Gochoco-Bautista attempts to make a modest contribution to the literature on the relationship between global liquidity and financial vulnerability. It conducts a dynamic conditional correlation analysis to examine the relationship between global credit and risk, and regression analysis to examine how global liquidity, as seen in cross-border claims to the Asia-Pacific region or capital flows to the Philippines as a share of GDP interacts with the global factor, VIX, and affects stock market returns, bank leverage and the growth of domestic credit to the private sector in the Philippines. \nAgosto 8 - Setyembre 2 (Lunes-Biyernes)\n\"The Journey of Mankind : First Humans Out of Africa-The Hominids of Dmanisi, Georgia\"\nAlbert Hall Lobby \n9 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe exhibit is about a human evolution that took place 1.77 million years ago in Dmanisi, Georgia. The Dmanisi hominids are believed to be the first humans to have successfully left their native land and their story is one of adaptation, subsistence, survival and even compassion. \nAgosto 11\nEvaluating Fun and Enjoyment in Language Learning : New Trend in ELT Research\nBenitez Theatre\nCollege of Education\n10-11:30 a.m. \nThomas Lloyd, British Council Deputy Director for English for Education Systems East Asia, will be delivering the talk about fun and enjoyment in language teaching. \nAgosto 11 - Setyembre 15\nDancing The Shrimp\n(The Tactical Improvisation of Post Colonial Space Mix) \n1F Galleries, Vargas Museum\n4 p.m. \nThe exhibition features Jon Cuyson\'s new works of fragmented installations that combine painting, sculpture, sound, photography, performance and scenography. Cuyson transforms the entire ground floor of the Vargas Museum into a space in flux, slipping between abstraction, figuration, ready made, still life and movement. \nAgosto 12 - Setyembre 3\nLeft Wing - Right Wing : An exhibition of works by UP College of Fine Arts faculty\nCorredor and Foyer, Barlett Hall \n5 p.m. (Exhibit Opening)\nThe UP College of Fine Arts (UPCFA) holds its annual exhibit entitled \"Left Wing-Right Wing : An Exhibition of Works by the UPCFA Faculty.\" The title of the exhibit is a play on words alluding to the architectural location of the College\'s different departments as well as the wide spectrum and overlapping of diverse disciplines, fields and affinities within the College itself. \nAgosto 13-Oktubre 3\n(Tuwing Sabado at Lunes)\nUP Ceramic Studio Pottery and Ceramic Sculpture Workshops\nUP College of Fine Arts\nThe UP Ceramic Studio Extension Program offers 7-session workshops in ceramic arts to participants of all ages. \nAgosto 22\nPingkian : Student Colloquium on Public Service Initiatives\nCollege of Engineering Theater\n8 a.m.- 5 p.m. \nA conference of UPD student organizations that conduct public service progams in partnership with the different sectors of society such as people\'s organizations, non-government organizations, and basic and higher education institutions. \nIts objectives are to generate a general profile/typology of the public service work done by student organizations and to disseminate their best practices to the student population. The conference is open only for student organizations which have pre-registered at the UPD Office of the Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs. \nAgosto 24\nUP Gawad Plaridel 2016 Awarding and Lecture\nUP Film Center\n2-4 p.m.\nThe UP Gawad Plaridel is the sole award in UP given to outstanding Filipino media practitioners who have excelled in media (print, film, radio, television and new media) and have performed with the highest level of professional integrity in the interest of public service. \nAgosto 26\nTatak CSWCD : 50 Taon ng Wagas na Paglilingkod at Pakikilahok\nBulwagang Tandang Sora, CSWCD \n3-10 p.m.\nThe UP College of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD) is celebrating its 50th anniversary in August 2017. As a kick-off to the celebration, CSWCD will launch and announce, on August 26, the series of events and activities for the year-long golden anniversary celebration of the College. \nSetyembre 1-3\n9th International Conference on Teacher Education\nTheme : Teacher Agency and Educational Reform : Articulations, Conditions, Possibilities \nGT Toyota Auditorium, Asian Center \nThe International Conference on Teacher Education (ICTED) is a biennial event sponsored by the UPD College of Education. This year\'s conference foregrounds the theme of teacher agency, defined as the exercise of individual and collective power of teachers in the midst of challenging situations. It aims to create a forum for educationists, social scientists, policymakers and students to discuss the central question : In what ways can educational reforms support or constrain teacher agency, for what purpose, under what conditions and with what consequences?\nAgosto 30 - Setyembre 1\nWikang Filipino : Lunan ng Kaalamang Bayan, Lunsaran ng Makabayang Kamalayan.\nBalay Kalinaw\nAng UPD Sentro ng Wikang Filipino (SWF) sa pakikipagtulungan ng Opisina ng Tsanselor at ng iba pang organisasyon sa loob at labas ng Unibersidad ay ipagdiriwang ang Buwan ng Wika 2016.\nSetyembre 4\nUP College of Music \n100th Anniversary Grand Alumni Homecoming \nIsang Daang Taong Himig at Tinig!\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium \n1-5 p.m. (General Assembly and Cocktails),\n5:30 p.m. (Anniversary Concert)\nThe UP College of Music (UPCM) is celebrating its centennial year on Saturday, Sept. 4, 2016. The homecoming will begin with a registration followed by a General Assembly. The event will also reminisce the past 100 years of UPCM and a concert will cap the occasion. \nSetyembre 8-30\nA Visual Diary : Impressions and Reflections\nFirst one-man exhibition of Prof. Emmanuel Garalde\nCorredor and Foyer, Bartlett Hall\n6 p.m.\nThe exhibit marks Garalde\'s final year in serving UP. He has taught at the UP College of Fine Arts for over 43 years, dedicating his life to honing young artists by teaching and developing core courses and photography subjects. He served as College Secretary, Chairperson of the Department of Visual Communication and was a proponent of the CFA\'s Industrial Design program. He retired in 2013 and continued teaching as a Professorial Lecturer since then. \nSetyembre 8\n2nd Intercollegiate Voice Summit\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium\n7 p.m.\nThe most outstanding classical singers of the top music schools, conservatories and colleges in Metro Manila perform on the stage of the Abelardo Hall, in a repertoire of immortal operatic, sacred and art song ensembles. \nSetyembre 22-23\nVoices and Noises : Communication and Integration within and across ASEAN Communities\n2016 Communication Research International Conference\nCine Adarna, UP Film Center and UP College of Mass Communication\nThe 2-day international conference aims to create greater public awareness of the objectives, benefits, and challenges of the ASEAN integration and develop a regional platform for open discussion and sharing of information. \nSetyembre 23\nUP Carillon Concert Series\nInspirations in Literature and Music : An evening of great poetry and song\nCarillon Plaza\n6:30 p.m.\nThe UP Alumni Association will hold the third Carillon Concert Series with an evening of great poetry and song by immortal writers and composers. \nSetyembre 25\n23rd Inception Anniversary Fun Run\nUP Academic Oval\n5 a.m.\nThe College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP) Pahinungod and UP Manila Ugnayan ng Pahinungod will hold a fun run to celebrate the 23rd anniversary of the Ugnayan ng Pahinungod Program. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
