(1080, 'E2-1080AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 2, Blg 6 (5 copies) UP Diliman 2016', '', '', 'Oktubre-Nobyembre 2016', 'Oktubre-Disyembre\nThe 3rd UP Gawad Melchora \"Tandang Sora\" Aquino \nCall for Nominations\nThe UP Gawad Melchora \"Tandang Sora\" Aquino is the award bestowed to outstanding social development academics and/or practitioners or social development organizations. It honors individuals/organizations who/which have excelled in social work, community development or women development. The UPD College of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD) administers the award. Individuals/organizations who/which have excelled and provided exemplary service in social work, community development or women and development may be nominated. \nOktubre 3\n17th Faculty-Student Conference on Statistical Sciences\nShangri-la Hotel, EDSA\nThe Faculty-Student Conference on Statistical Sciences serves as a medium for the exchange of ideas between budding young researchers and seasoned academics in the field of statistical sciences, and as a venue for statistics students and faculty to disseminate their researches. It is an opportunity to explore different applications and areas of statistics, and experience limitless developments and discoveries in statistical sciences. \nOktubre 4\nBook Launching\nOctober 4, 2016 \n1:00 - 4:00 pm\nUP College of Home Economics Tearoom \nDiliman, Quezon City \nSoft Book Launching of the Introduction to Food Technology by the Food Science and Nutrition Department of the College of Home Economics\nThis event will launch the book \"Introduction to Food Technology\" written by Dr. Miflora Gatchalian, Dr. Sonia Y. De Leon and their co-authors. The two volumes of this book will be discussed in the event. There will also be a brief open forum during the launch. \nOktubre 5\nCall for proposals for the Southeast Asian Studies in Asia Conference \nThe Consortium for Southeast Asian Studies in Asia (SEASIA), of which the UP Asian Center is a member, will be holding the 2nd Southeast Asian Studies in Asia Conference (SEASIA 2017) on Dec. 16-17, 2017 in Chulalongkorn University, Bangkok, Thailand. \nOktubre 7-28\nSpatial Halo-Halo \nAn Exhibition of works by UPCFA, Department of Visual Communication\nCorredor, UPCFA Gallery, Bartlett Hall \n6 p.m.\nThe exhibit showcases art and design works of faculty members from the College of Fine Arts (CFA) Department of Visual Communication. Over the years, the exhibition has become a department tradition to showcase different creative practices and interests of the faculty of the Visual Communication and Industrial Design programs. More than 30 artists will be contributing their recent works, including ceramics, design, drawings, illustrations, painting, photographs, prints and sculptures. \nOktubre 10\nInnovating the Philippines\nThe UP EEEI Centennial Lecture Series\nPLDT Multimedia Lecture Hall (MLH/VLC) \n2 p.m.\nThe yearlong lecture series aims to highlight the accomplishments of Electrical and Electronics Engineering Institute (EEEI) alumni, especially those who have been successful in their career in the Philippines. The lectures are also geared to inspire students in pursuing their careers in the country. \nOktubre 10 \nFast Fashion : The Dark Sides of Fashion\nMain Exhibition Hall, Bulwagan ng Dangal \nGonzalez Hall\n6 p.m.\nThe UP College of Home Economics through the Department of Clothing, Textiles, and Interior Design in collaboration with Goethe Institute is holding an exhibit entitled Fast Fashion : The Dark Side of Fashion. First set up in Hamburg, Germany, the exhibit\'s main objective is to present the issues and concerns that emanate from the fast paced industyr of garments and textiles. It promotes the green concept and sustainability in fashion. \nOktubre 12-30\nDistrito de Molo\nThree one-act plays of Prof. Leoncio Deriada, directed by Prof. Tony Mabesa\nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater\n2nd Floor, Palma Hall\n7 p.m. (weekdays)\n10 a.m. and 3 p.m. (weekends)\nTres Hermanas de Molo - three old maids and their nanny call on the ghosts of the past and pray for repentance for thie freedom. Atlas de Molo - a statue of Atlas comes to life and changes the lives of two newly-weds in their ancestral home in Molo, Iloilo. Venus de Molo - a sculptor and a cruel patron recreates a famous statue but is shocked when they are visited by a local goddess of Molo. \nOktubre 13\nForum on the selection of the next UP President\nUP Cine Adarna\n9 a.m.\nThe Search Committee for the selection of the next UP President will hold a Forum on October 13 at the Cine Adarna, UP DIliman. \nTen nominees are officially vying for the position. They are Dr. Consolacion R. Alaras, Prof. Danilo L. Concepcion, Prof. Gisela P. Concepcion, J. Prospero E. De Vera III, Prof. Rowena Cristina L. Guevara, Dr. Orlando S. Mercado, Prof. Benito M. Pacheco, Dr. Roger D. Posadas, Prof. Caesar A. Saloma and Prof. Michael L. Tan. \nOktubre 14\nLaboratory Animal Workshop\nUP Natural Sciences and Research Institute \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe Biological Research and Services Laboratory of the UP Natural Sciences and Research Institute will be holding a workshop via a short lecture and hands-on session on the care and proper handling of mice, techniques in blood collection and drug administration, and sample collection. \nOktubre 14-17\nAmelia Lapeña-Bonifacio Writers Workshop\nUP Institute of Creative Writing Workshop on Speculative Fiction\nMicrotel, UP Technohub\n8 a.m.- 5 p.m.\nThe first Amelia Lapeña-Bonifacio Writers Workshop (ALBWW) will focus on Speculative Fiction. The works of 12 accepted fellows would be discussed and critiqued during four days of workshop sessions. The ALBWW is meant to complement the annual UP Writers Workshop, which has evolved to accomodate and mentor publised writers in mid-career. \nOktubre 17-21\nSpecial Course on Urban Transport Planning and Management (SCOUT)\nA basic course in transport planning\nCariño Multipurpose Hall\n3/F School of Urban and Regional Planning Bldg.\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe SCOUT is a 5-day program which provides an overview of transport planning, its systems, and how it is effectively assessed and managed. \nThe program is aimed at capacitating stakeholders in the local and national institutions in understanding transport planning and management in the Philippine context; likewise seeking to help improve physical and social machineries for the benefit of the community. In addition, the program identifies new challenges, directions and trends in transport planning, mobility management strategies, traffic impact assessment and transit-oriented development, among others. \nOktubre 20-22\nNational Electrochemical Energy Storage Workshop (CHED-PCARI Program)\nSmall Auditorium\nNational Institute of Physics\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nA 3-day workshop where concepts on energy storage and electrochemistry will be discussed such as how batteries and fuel cells work, how to improve their performance and how they are key in the world of renewable energy. \nOktubre 22\nMaglasig-lasig kitabi! : Peste Igal 2016\nGT Toyota Auditorium\n2 p.m. and 6 p.m.\nThe festival-concert enjoins audiences to partake of the rich performance traditions of the Sama-Bajau people of the Southern Philippines. It features igal and pansak, Sama-Bajau\'s traditional dances, and kulintangan ensemble music pieces from four performing groups from Semporna, Malaysia; Bongao, Tawi-Tawi; Apalit, Pampanga; and San Andres, Manila. \nOktubre 22\nIEmagineering for Nation-Building 2016 UP Industrial Engineering Alumni Association (UPIEAA) Symposium\nEngineering Theater\nMelchor Hall\n2 p.m.\nThe conference aims to fuel the nation-builder among engineers by tackling critical issues and unlocking opportunities in emerging technologies and to rediscover the engineer\'s role in transforming society. \nOktubre 22\nStreet bEats : The 51st UPSE Alumni Homecoming\nSchool of Economics grounds\n4-10 p.m.\nThe University of the Philippines School of Economics (UPSE) will be holding its 51st grand alumni homecoming with a theme Street bEats. There will be live performances by Juan Miguel Salvador of the Authority Band and DJ Galo Marquez. \nOktubre 24\nUPAA SURP Chapter General Assembly and Election\nUP School of Urban and Regional Planning \n6-9 p.m.\nThe UP Alumni Association (UPAA) School of Urban and Regional Planning (SURP) chapter general assembly and election is in line with the upcoming 51st founding anniversary of the UP SURP. \nThe UPAA SURP Chapter calls on its alumni to participate in the school\'s festivities. New members will be inducted into the chapter and honorary membership will be conferred to the individuals who served as deans of the School. A new set of officers will be elected during the assembly. Capping off the night will be a dinner celebration. \nOktubre 25-28\nSeminar Workshop : Participatory Monitoring and Evaluation of Development Projects\nSeminar Room\nCollege of Social Work and Community Development\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe training course aims to enhance the understanding and capabilities of participants in developing appropriate monitoring and evaluation systems for their respective community projects and programs. \nNobyembre 3-25\nBeyond My Body\nA solo exhibition of new works by Ambie Abaño\nCorredor, UP CFA Gallery, Bartlett Hall \nOpening reception November 8, 4:00 p.m. \nVisual artist and UP College of Fine Arts (CFA) faculty member Ambie Abaño remounts her solo exhibition, Beyond My Body, at the Corredor Gallery. Featuring large-scale prints on translucent textile and works on engraved Tanguile wood, the exhibition reflects on the temporal nature of the body and ponders on the essence of eternal selfhood lying within the deeper self : the spirit. In this exhibition, Abaño wields material binaries to represent dual states of being : images in engraved wood present the body in its various stages of deterioration, while images produced from layers of translucent tulle exemplify the ethereal qualities of the spirit. \nNobyembre 7\nThe Engineer\'s Advantage : Becoming a Visionary Entrepreneur\nThe UP EEEI Centennial Lecture Series\nPLDT Multimedia Lecture Hall (MLH/VLC) \nEEEI Bldg. I\n2 p.m.\nThe yearlong lecture series aims to highlight the accomplishments of Electrical and Electronics Engineering Institute (EEEI) alumni, especially those who have been successful in their career in the Philippines. The lectures are also geared to inspire students in pursuing their careers in the country. \nNobyembre 14-18\nSpecial Course on Urban and Regional Planning : A Basic Course in Urban and Regional Planning (SCURP : ABC in URP)\nCariño Multipurpose Hall\n3/F School of Urban and Regional Planning Bldg. \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe Special Course on Urban and Regional Planning : A Basic Course in Urban and Regional Planning (SCURP : ABC in URP) is a 5-day program that serves as an orientation-cum-introductory course on the basic concepts, processes and methodologies of urban and regional planning. \nNobyembre 15-18\nTraining on Community Organizing\nUP CSWCD Research and Extension for Development Office \nShort Courses\nSeminar Room\nCollege of Social Work and and Community Development\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe training is a 4-day course that aims to provide the participants with an overview of concepts, principles, processes and approaches in community organizing in the context of current realities. The phases of community organizing will be discussed as well as the essential skills needed. The course will facilitate the preparation of re-entry plans of the participants that they will use in their respective organizations. \nNobyembre 24\nEmpowering Entrepreneurs : The ISSI Journey\nA symposium in celebration of UP ISSI\'s 50th anniversary\nUP Institute of Small-Scale Industries (ISSI) \n1-4:30 p.m.\nThe event will showcase UP ISSI\'s 50-years worth of experience in providing training, consultancy, research and information towards the development and promotion of entrepreneurship in the country. It will also serve as a venue for information on business and on assistance that is available to entrepreneurs. \nNobyembre 25\n\"Kristiyanong Misyon at Antropolohiyang Pilipino\"\nPalma Hall 400\n1-5 p.m.\nAng Round Table Discussion 2016 ay ikatlong beses na paghahandog ng UP Departamento ng Antropolohiya bilang paghahanda nito sa nalalapit na sentenaryo sa taong 2017. \nAng tema ngayong taon, \"Kristiyanong Misyon at Antropolohiyang Pilipino\" ay naglalayon na talakayin ang naging ugnayan ng relihiyon at antropolohiyang Pilipino, partikular sa kung anong naging ambag ng mga Kristiyanong misyon sa pag-unlad ng disiplina ng antropolohiya sa Pilipinas. Ang mga tagapagsalita ay sina Dr. Melba Maggay, Dr. Hector Guazon at Dr. Prospero Covar. \nNobyembre 29\nTugSayAwit : Pagpupugay sa OPM mula sa Laybraryang Pinoy\nBulwagan ng Dangal, Gonzalez Hall \n6 p.m.\nA tribute to Original Pilipino Music (OPM), the concert will feature live performances by groups composed of The University Library staff. The event is staged in celebration of the Library and Information Services Month. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1081, 'E2-1081AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 2, Blg 7 (14 copies) ', '', '', 'Disyembre 2016 - Enero 2017', 'Disyembre 1-3\n5th International Conference on Asian Network for GIS-based Historical Studies (ANGIS)\nBalay Kalinaw Conference Hall \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nFocusing on Asian history and aiming to promote multidisciplinary approaches in exploring historical processes, the upcoming ANGIS Conference will serve as a venue for popularizing innovative methods such as digital visualization, analysis of data using time information system, and the use of Geographic Information Systems (GIS) in analyzing and interpreting historical data that are being undertaken by both academics and practitioners in the fields of history, geography, heritage studies, spatial analysis and modelling, visualization and GIS.\nDisyembre 2 \n\"Himig ng Diliman\"\nPag-iilaw 2016\nOblation Plaza\n6 n.g.\nAng seremonya ng pag-iilaw ngayong taon ay may temang \"Himig ng Diliman.\" Ang tema ay naglalarawan sa iba\'t ibang tunog at huni ng mga yunit ng kampus na kapag pinagsama-sama ay bumubuo ng isang magara at makabuluhang awitin. \nDisyembre 2\nMadrigal-Gonzalez Awards/Likhaan Journal 10 Launch/UP Writers Night 2016\nUP Institute of Creative Writing\'s Annual Writers Night Celebrations\nGT-Toyota Center\n4-10 p.m.\nLIKHAAN : The UP Institute of Creative Writing (UP ICW) celebrates Philippine writers with three consecutive activities. First is the awarding ceremony for the annual Madrigal-Gonzalez Best First Book Award. This year, the award will be given to a writer in Filipino who has just written his or her first book. This is followed by the launch of Likhaan Journal 10, an annual anthology of Philippine literature published by the UP ICW. This year\'s editor-in-chief is UP ICW fellow and UP Press director Dr. J. Neil Garcia. \nDisyembre 3 - 16\nSPATIAL TERRITORIES : Artistic form in the production of space \nBulwagan ng Dangal Museum\nSouth Wing Basement, University Library\nOpening cocktails on December 3\n4 p.m.\nThe UP College of Fine Arts\' MFA Program, under Prof. Katti Sta. Ana\'s FA 215 Class : Production of Space in Art Production, will hold an exhibit \"Spatial Territories.\"\nThe exhibit gathers 10 contemporary artists to produce spaces in the artists\' particular themes and mediums. All of them are forays into experiences of space - of miniature universes, virtual connections, memories, empowerment, disempowerment, grief, delight and confusion. \nDisyembre 10\n\'Sang Siglong Sigla! \nUP High, UP Elem, UP Prep, UPIS Grand Alumni Homecoming\nUPIS Grades 7-12 Quadrangle \n4 p.m.\nThis is the annual alumni homecoming of the UP Integrated School (UPIS) and all its progenitor schools - UP Elementary  School, UP Preparatory School and UP High School. This year\'s homecoming marks the centennial celebratio of UP High School which was established in 1916. UPIS Batch 1991 will be hosting the event.\nThe event is open to all alumni, teachers, former teachers and friends of UPIS, UP Elem, UP Prep and UP High. \nDisyembre 12\nKAPPanimad-on Round Table Discussion (RTD) Serye 2 : Sampaksaan sa Domestikong Problema at Panlabas ng Polisiya sa Ilalim ng Administrasyong Duterte\nPagtalakay sa mga Pananaw, Pag-unawa at Pagtaya ng Agham Panlipunan at Pilosopiya\nPavilion 2 Conference Room, Palma Hall \n8:30 a.m. - 12 : 30 p.m.\nLayunin ng KAPPanimad-on RTD 2 na mabigyan ng pagkakataon ang mga larang mula sa Kolehiyo ng Agham Panlipunan at Pilosopya (KAPP) na makapagbigay ng kanilang pananaw at gampanin sa administrasyong Duterte. Sa pagkamit ng layuning ito, magiging mas malinaw ang hangarin ng Kolehiyong mamulat, makapag-ambag at makisangkot sa mga lokal at pandaigdigang usapin. \nAng mga magiging tagapagsalita ay mula sa iba\'t ibang disiplina tulad ng Agham Pampulitika, Sosyolohiya, Pilosopiya at Antropolohiya. \nAng aktibidad na ito ay inorganisa ng Komite sa Indihinesasyon ng KAPP. \nDisyembre 14\nDreams Turned to Reality \nUPIS Field Demonstration / Street Dance Competition 2016\nUniversity Amphitheater \n6:30 - 11 a.m. \nThe event showcases the unity, creativity and dancing prowess of UPIS students : from Kindergarten to Grade 6 via a field demonstration; and the Grades 7-10 students via a street dance competition. The competition will be preceded by a parade of participants in full costume from the UPIS grounds to the amphitheater. \nDisyembre 14\nSingkwenta Filipino : Gabi ng Parangal at Paglulunsad ng 50 Aklat\nBalay Kalinaw, UP Diliman\n6 -9 n.g.\nAng gabing ito ay kulminasyon ng pagdiriwang ng ikalimampung taon ng pagkakatatag ng UP Departamento ng Filipino at Panitikan ng Pilipinas (DFPP). Magtitipon-tipon ang kaguruan ng DFPP, nakaraan at kasalukuyan, upang sariwain ang pagpupunyagi ng Departamento sa pagsusulong ng wika, panitikan, malikhaing pagsulat at araling Pilipino sa Unibersidad. \nDisyembre 15\nPagsulong ng Kabataan sa Katarungan para sa Karapatang Pantao (KKK) \nPagdiriwang ng Araw ng Karapatang Pantao 2016 ng UPIS\nUPIS Grade 7-12 Building\n9 n.u. - 12 n.t.\nSa kauna-unahang pagdiriwang ng Araw ng Karapatang Pantao, layunin na imulat ang buong paaralan sa mga usapin ng karapatang pantao hindi lamang sa kasalukuyan kundi sa naging pag-unlad nito sa kasaysayan. \nSa diwa ng Katipunan na nagsulong ng pambansang kasarinlan, nilalayon ng Departamento ng Araling Panlipunan at ng Kilusang Araling Panlipunan na buhayin ang pagsusuri at pakikisangkot ng mga mag-aaral ng UPIS sa mainit na usaping pambansa. \nAng tema ng pagdiriwang na ito ay \"Pagsusulong ng Kabataan sa Katarungan para sa Karapatang Pantao\" o KKK. Magkakaroon ng eksibit, tagis at talino, at Bayani ng Karapatang Pantao, mga patimpalak na sasalihan ng mga mag-aaral ng UPIS. Ang mga aktibidad para sa KKK ay bukas sa publiko. \nDisyembre 15\nUPIS Battle of the Bands 2016\nUPIS Grades 7-12 Quadrangle \n3 - 6 p.m.\nBattle of the Bands is a talent competition among bands whose members are all current UPIS students from grades 6 to 10. Bands are required to perform two songs. One of which must be an original composition based on a theme provided by the UPIS Student Council (a.k.a. Kamag Aral or KA). \nDisyembre 16\n\"Himig ng Diliman, Hagkan ang Gabi\"\nUPD Parada ng mga Parol 2016\nAcademic Oval \n4 p.m.\nMga akademikong yunit lamang ng Unibersidad ang kalahok sa Paligsahan ng mga Parol bagamat maaring gumawa at magparada ng parol ang anumang yunit at organisasyon sa Unibersidad. \nSa pamamagitan ng mga parol na ipaparada ng mga yunit, layuning ipaala-ala ang mga hamong pinagtagumpayan ng ating pamayanan at ang mga pagbubunying kalakip nito. Para patingkarin pa ang tema, binibigyan ng espesyal na halaga ang aspeto ng malikhaing paggamit ng ilaw sa mga parol. \nEnero 20-21\nUP ICW Teachers Seminar on Creative Writing and Malikhaing Pagsulat\nMicrotel, UP Technohub, Diliman, Quezon City\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nLIKHAAN : The UP Institute of Creative Writing (ICW) will be holding a two-day teachers\' training and seminar on Creative Writing and Malikhaing Pagsulat as a response to developments brought about by the implementation of the K-12 program. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1082, 'E2-1082AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 3, Blg 1 (7 copies) ', '', '', 'Pebrero 2017', 'Pebrero 1-28\nSansinukob : Isang Installation na Eksibit\nUP Lagoon and CMC Hill \n6 p.m. (Pasinaya) \nAng eksibit ay isang paglalahad ng pinagmulan ng sansinukob (universe) sang-ayon sa mga umiral at umiiral na kuwentong-bayan at alamat ng mga etnolinggwistikong pangkat ng Pilipinas. Sa pamamagitan ng eksibit mamamalas ang sinaunang etnoastronomiya at kosmolohiya bilang kaalamang-bayan ng mga kulturang Pilipino. ASng mga kaalamang-bayang ito ay hindi lamang humahanmgga sa kagyat na kapaligiran gaya ng lupa at tubig, kundi lumalagos din sa kalangitan at kabilang-buhay. \nPebrero 1 \nSeremonya ng Pagbubukas : K\'wentong Bayan, Kaalamang Bayan\nHarap ng Faculty Center \n6 p.m.\nAng mga k\'wentong bayan ay mga naratibong pasalita na nagpasalin-salin sa maraming henerasyon. Naririnig ang mga ito sa mga pangkomunidad na seremonya at ritwal at sa pang-araw-araw na paghuhuntahan at pagkukuwentuhan ng mga mamamayan. \nMadalas ang mga k\'wentong bayan ang nagpapaliwanag ng iba\'t ibang aspekto ng tradisyon, mga kalakaran at pati na rin kasaysayan. \nSa pagdiriwang ng Pambansang Buwan ng Sining, sasariwain ng UP Diliman ang mga k\'wentong bayan na kinalalakipan ng iba\'t ibang saysay, pukaw at kaalaman. \nPebrero 1\n2017 World Hijab Day\n\"UP-IIS Hijab Day and Interfaith Forum 2017 : Celebrating Women\'s Right in the Light of the Islam\"\nUP Balay Kalinaw\n1-5 p.m.\nThe event highlights the significance of hijab in the life of a Muslim woman as well as her rights in the light of Islamic teaching. The interfaith component of the program promotes respect and tolerance among people of different faiths. \nPebrero 2\nMaceda 100 : Cassettes 100\nRestaging of the \"Cassettes 100\" Event\nVargas Museum\n7 p.m. \nIn 1971, Cassettes 100 was performed at the lobby of the Cultural Center of the Philippines, where one hundred \'musicians\' weaved their way through an \'audience\' strolling around, each carrying a cassette player playing one of the hundred pre-recorded tracks of various Philippine instruments. \nThis restaging is a collaborative effort between the UP College of Music and the UP College of Engineering. \nPebrero 4, 11, 18 at 25\nMandatory Continuing Legal Education Saturday Course\n2/F Conference Room, Law Center \n8 a.m. - 6 p.m.\nMembers of the Integrated Bar of the Philippines not exempt under Rule 7 of Bar Matter 850 shall complete every three (3) years at least thirty-six (36) hours of continuing legal education activities approved by the MCLE Office. \nPebrero 7-9\nK\'wentong Bayan sa Pelikula\nUP Cine Adarna\n5 p.m. and 7 p.m.\nPebrero 7\n5 p.m. Ang Panggagahasa kay Fe\n7 p.m. Ploning\nPebrero 8\n5 p.m. K\'na the Dreamweaver\n7 p.m. Sayaw ng Dalawang Kaliwang Paa\nPebrero 9\n5 p.m. Hinulid\n7 p.m. Tuos\nPebrero 9-10\nThe Third World Studies Center in its 40th Year : An International Conference \nGT-Toyota Asian Center Auditorium, Asian Center\n8:30 a.m. - 6 p.m.\nThe Third World Studies Center (TWSC) gathers in this multidisciplinary conference its vast and resilient network of scholars and public intellectuals, academics and activists, advocates and bearers of unorthodox views from different parts of the globe. Dr. Alfred W. McCoy, Harrington Professor of History at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, is the keynote speaker and former TWSC directors will be featured in one of the plenary sessionsm while former TWSC visiting research fellows, contributors to Kasarinlan : Philippine Journal of Third World Studies, and members of the TWSC network will be presenting papers in 11 panels. Documentaries produced by student interns of TWSC and the University of Montreal will also be screened.\nPebrero 9\nDiwata ng Bayan\nIsang Dulang-Awit ng Ating Kasaysayan Tampok ang Natatanging Pagtatanghal ng Samahang Teatro ng Sinilangan\nTanghalang Nicanor Abelardo \n(CCP Main Theater)\n8 p.m.\nIsinulat bilang papuri sa alaala nina Gat Andres Bonifacio at Gregoria de Jesus, ang Dakilang Supremo at mandirigmang Lakambini ng Kataastaasan Kagalanggalangang Katipunan (KKK) ng mga Anak ng Bayan; at ng mandudulang \'sedisyoso\' na si Aurelio Tolentino ng KKK, gayundin sa kanyang mga kapanalig at kapwa alagad ng sining sa \'teatrong rebolusyonaryo\' noong digmaang Pilipino-Amerikano, at sa lahat ng mga bayani, bathala at bathaluman sa ating kasaysayan, mitolohiya at mga kuwentong-bayan. \nPebrero 10\nThe 5th UP Electrical and Electronics Engineers Alumni Association, Inc. (UPEEEAAI) Golf Classic\nAyala Greenfield Golf and Leisure Club, Calamba, Laguna\n8 a.m.\nThe UP EEEAAI invites all golf enthusiasts, UP alumni or otherwise, to join the 5th edition of the UPEEEAAI Golf Classic - the culminating activity of the UP EEE Institute centennial celebration and a fund raiser to help support the continuing scholarship and research programs of the UPEEEAAI. \nPebrero 10 at 24\nHimigsikan : Mga K\'wentong Bayan\nUP Carillon Plaza\n6 p.m.\nMga awiting-bayan na bibigyan ng bagong anyo sa pamamagitan ng kontemporaryong musika at interpretasyon. \nGaya ng nakagawiang anyo ng libangan tuwing hapon sa lilim ng mga puno, ito ay pagsasariwa ng mga awiting kinagisnan ng ating mga magulang at ninuno at sasaliwan ng makabagong tugtugan at areglo bilang pagpapamalas na maging ang mga awiting-bayan ay may kakayahang lumagos sa mga salinlahi at umagapay sa nagbabagong panahon. \nAng mga palabas ay libre at bukas para sa lahat\nPebrero 10 - Noel Cabangon\nPebrero 24 - Bayang Barrios \nPebrero 12 \nCOEXIST 2017 : Help Rebuild Libraries and Communities\nMelchor Hall/Academic Oval\n5 a.m.\nThe UP College of Engineering Library will be holding a Fun Run event to raise funds for the benefit of the Library\'s outreach program which will support a chosen beneficiary community. The activity intends to help rebuild libraries in the country that were affected by natural disasters. Moreover, it aims to promote the Library\'s \"I Love My Library Campaign\" to raise awareness on the importance of involving the community with the libraries. \nPebrero 15-28\nSi Faust at ang Dalumat ng Kasamaan : Isang Adaptasyon ng Akda ni Goethe\nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater, Palma Hall\nWeekdays shows at 7 p.m.\nWeekends shows at 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. \nFor its 41st Theater Season, Dulaang UP (DUP) presents Rody Vera\'s adaptation of Faust. The play opens in heaven where the devil, Mephisto, wagers with God that he can corrupt his most virtuous servant Faust. What follows in the play is a series of events that questions the preconceived notions of justice, rationality and morality. \nPebrero 15\nSagunja and Minhwa : Korean Traditional Painting Workshop\nAsian Center, Philippine and China Hall\n10 a.m. - 1 p.m. and 2-5 p.m. \nThe UP Korean Research Center (UP KRC), in partnership with the Korean Cultural Center (KCC) in the Philippines and UP Asian Center, organizes the \"Sagunja and Minhwa : Korean Traditional Painting Workshop\".\nSagunja, also called \"The Four Gracious Plants,\" is comprised of four elements - plum, orchid, chrystanthemum and bamboo. Minhwa is a Korean folk art that illustrates common people\'s freedom of expression and hope in carefree unconventionality. \nPebrero 17\n5th ERDT Congress\nSMX Convention Center, Pasay City\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe Engineering Research and Development for Technology (ERDT) Congress is a yearly event where researchers, ERDT scholars, visiting professors, industry, government, and other experts gather and get inspired by plenary lectures of highly distinguished professors and experts all over the world. The Congress also serves as a platform in setting directions for research and development. \nPebrero 17\nA Multidisciplinary Symposium on the Roots of Transcultural Philippine Music\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium\n1-4 p.m.\nThe articulation of Filipino modernities in the arts had two tendencies : 1) the middle-class elevation of the folk materials to \"high culture\" (e.g., use of balitao and kundiman in Western classical-art forms), and 2) the channelization of the Filipino folk-popular to wider audiences via the mass media, which was not isolated from the first tendency. \nThis symposium looks into these two tendencies, but give more space to the realm of the second in which vernacular Filipino literature, folk dances, Filipinized bodabil, and radio songs got broadcast audiences attuned to the emerging \"alternative Filipino modernities.\" This strand emerged during the formative years when capitalism and flow of images and ideas accelerated between 1898 and 1941.\nPebrero 18-19\nSita & Rama : Papet Ramayana\nInstitute of Biology Auditorium\n10 a.m. and 3 p.m. \nIto ay istorya ni Prinsipe Rama at ang pagpapalayas sa kaniya sa kaharian ng kaniyang amang si Haring Dashrata. Isinasaad din nito ang paglalakbay ni Rama sa kagubatan ng India kasama ang kaniyang asawang si Sita at ang kapatid na si Laksmana, pati ang kaniyang pakikidigma kay Haring Ravana dahil sa pagdukot nito sa asawa niyang si Sita; hanggang sa kaniyang pagbabalik sa kanilang kaharian matapos ang labing-apat na taon at pagkahirang bilang hari. \nPebrero 20-25\nCSSP Week\nAgham Panlipunan at Pilosopiya : Mapanuring Gabay sa Bayang Pilipino\nPalma Hall \n8 a.m. (everyday) \nThe College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP) Week celebrates the 33rd annual founding of the College since 1983. The celebration features a series of exhibits, workshops, roundtable discussions, panel discussions, public lectures and recognition events, together with a symposium, a faculty colloquium, a conference, a Zumba program, and an open house, led by the various offices, departments, institutes and centers of the College. \nPebrero 22 \nLate 19th Century Terremotos in Luzon : Scientific Researches, Post-Disaster Rehabilitation, and the Colonial State\nA Public Lecture by Kerby C. Alvarez \nCSSP Audio-Visual Room (Palma Hall 207) 2-4 p.m. \nThe lecture will present a historical study of earthquakes that devastated the island of Luzon in the late 19th century. It attempts to present a narrative of state-subject relations in Spanish-Philippines through the lens of hazards and disaster response. The public lecture is part of UP CSSP Week and presented by the UP Department of History. \nPebrero 22-28\nUP Engineering Week 2017\nEngineering Week or Eng\'g Week is the biggest and most awaited event of the College of Engineering. It is composed of night and day events organized by different organizations in the college. Over five thousand engineering students gather to participate in a variety of events ranging from simple games of chance to grand performances of talents and skills. \nPebrero 22\nSilakbo : Smoker Night 2017\nUP Film Institute \n7 p.m. - 12 a.m. \nContinuing its tradition of promoting creativity and critical thinking, SILAKBO : Smoker Night 2017 aims to attack, tackle, and criticize relevant social issues through a comedic play. This night event features Engineering-based organizations as they exhibit unique interpretations of their stands on the issues. This event also aims to showcase the holistic upbringing of UP engineering students who are not only excellent in their fields but are also proactive members of the society. As the first student-participated night even of the Engineering Week, Smoker Night propels the fighting spirit of each engineering student. \nPebrero 24\nSidlak : Tanghalan 2017\nEngineering Theater\nMelchor Hall\n5:30 - 8:30 p.m. \nNow on its second year, the Engineering Student Council brings SIDLAK : TANGHALAN 2017, an event where our faculty, administration, and staff can showcase their talents to the Engineering community and where the students can show their utmost appreciation outside of the classroom setup and have an avenue to celebrate them. With the theme of the Giant Lantern Festival, the event will present home-grown performers as they are the ones who truly light up the lives inside the college. This year, the event aims to be even more inclusive by welcoming unaffiliated engineering students to perform as well. \nPebrero 25\nJammeng\'g\nTBA\n6 p.m. - 12 a.m.\nJammeng\'g is a themed battle of the bands where different amateur bands hailing from various engineering organizations fight it out in a battle royal of musicality and artistic skills. Engineering students jam with them as they rock it out with all their hearts, eyeing the elusive prize. Bands are given the liberty to choose their songs of preference, as long as they comply with the theme of the year. On stage, they perform back-to-back with popular musicians of the day in front of a live audience in a raging party full of music and free-flowing drinks. \nPebrero 27\nAwitan\nHenry Lee Irwin Theater\nAteneo de Manila University\n6 p.m. - 12 m.n.\nAwitan is a prestigious university-wide choral competition open to all amateur choral groups of the different student organizations in UP Diliman. Since its conception in 1965, Awitan has serenaded the engineering community with a wide variety of Christmas and Themed chorale pieces. This year\'s pre-judging system is geared towards a bias-free evaluation of the participating groups via blind judging. Participating groups would have the opportunity to hear the comments and suggestions of the judges after their pre-judging performance.  \nPebrero 28\nIndakan\nUP Film Institute\n6 p.m. - 12 a.m.\nIndakan is a theme dance competition which aims to showcase the talents and creativity of amateur groups from various engineering organizations. Performances shall highlight the given theme through their dance choreograhy and music. This year, Indakan traces Filipino native roots as it features the diversity and richness of Filipino culture and tradition. The performers from the group category will take its audience around the country as they embody Filipino cultural dance and celebration through their performances that shall bring different Philippine festivals from the streets to the stage. \nPebrero 23\nSampaksaan sa K\'wentong Bayan : Pambansang Kumperensiya ng K\'wentong Bayan\nUP NISMED\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nAng Sampaksaan ay may pangunahing layunin na mailahad ang kasaysayan at kabuluhan ng mga k\'wentong bayan at kaugnayan ng mga mga ito sa pagbuo ng pambansang kamalayan. Layunin din ng kumperensiya ang makalikha ng dalumat hinggil sa k\'wentong bayan at mga mito gamit ang balangakas at/o modelong interdisiplinaryo. Ang kumperensiya ay libre at bukas para sa lahat. Ang mga dadalo ay tatanggap ng Certificate of Participation. \nPebrero 23 \n3rd UP Gawad Tandang Sora Recognition of Outstanding Social Development Practitioners or Social Development Organizations\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\n9 a.m.- 12 p.m.\nThe College of Social Work and Community Development bestows Gawad Tandang Sora to outstanding social development practitioners or social development organizations that excelled in social work, community development, or women and development. \nThe award is named after Melchora \"Tandang Sora\" Aquino, the \"Mother of the Philippine Revolution,\" whose life and deeds represent love of country and service to her fellow Filipinos. The awardee, like Tandang Sora, will be honored for a life of devotion to country and service to the Filipino people as a social development practitioner or as a social development organization. \nPebrero 23\nAral at Aksyon : A Forum on CSWCD Alumni in Action\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\n1-5 p.m.\nThe UP CSWCD Alumni Association will lead the forum that will showcase its outstanding alumni in various fields. In celebration of the College days, its alumni in government agencies, communities, local government units, NGOs and academe will share their insights to the CSWCD community. \nPebrero 24\nCSWCD Service Awards\nRecognition of Faculty, REPS and Administrative Staff for their Loyalty and Service to the College/University\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\n9 a.m.-12 p.m.\nPart of the annual celebration of the College of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD) days is the recognition of its faculty members, Research Extension and Professional Staff (REPS) and administrative staff for their loyalty and service to the College/University. For 2017, College-based student organizations will also be acknowledged for their support and service to the students and CSWCD\'s activities for the entire year. \nPebrero 25-26\nAng Unang Aswang ni Rody Vera\nTampok ang UP Dance Company\nArki Amphitheater\n7 p.m.\nBahagi ng pagdiriwang ng UP Diliman Month 2017 ang pagtatanghal ng orihinal na akda ni Rody Vera, Ang Unang Aswang, sa pamamagitan ng sayaw at galaw. Ito ay sa koryograpiya at direksiyon ni JM Cabling at sa pamamatnubay ni Prop. Angela Baguilat na parehong mula sa UPD Kolehiyo ng Musika. \nAng UP Dance Company, isa sa mga pitong opisyal na organisasyong pangtanghal ng UPD, ang siyang naatasang magbigay buhay sa dula. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
