(1083, 'E2-1083AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 3, Blg 2 (3 copies) ', '', '', 'Marso 2017', 'Marso 1\nCSWCD Golden Anniversary Lecture Series\nWhat is the Cutting Edge of Women and Development Studies?\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\n1-5 p.m.\nAs part of its year-long golden anniversary celebration, the College of Social Work and Community Development will be conducting lecture series featuring the expertise of its faculty from the Department of Women and Development Studies (DWDS). With its pioneering programs in women and gender studies in the Asia-Pacific region, the DWDS will provide relevant discussions on its academic program. \nMarso 1 \nCall for Nominations for the UP Gawad Plaridel 2017\nThe UP College of Mass Communication (UP CMC) is now accepting nominations for the annual UP Gawad Plaridel which recognizes Filipino media practitioners who have excelled in any of the media (print, radio, film, television and new media) and have performed with the highest level of professional integrity in the interest of public service. For 2017, the 13th UP Gawad Plaridel will be given to an outstanding television practitioner. \nMarso 1-5 \nSi Faust at ang Dalumat ng Kasamaan : Isang Adaptasyon ng Akda ni Goethe\nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater, Palma Hall\nWeekday shows at 7 p.m.\nWeekend shows at 10 a.m. and 3 p.m.\nFor its 41st Theater Season, Dulaang UP presents Rody Vera\'s adaptation of Faust. The play opens in heaven where the devil, Mephisto, wagers with God that he can corrupt God\'s most virtuous servant Faust. What follows in the play is a series of events that questions the preconceived notions of justice, rationality and morality. Neil Sese and Jack Yabut alternate in the title role of Faust while Paolo O\'Hara and Mailes Kanapi as Mephisto. Karen Gaerlan plays the innocent and pious Gretchen. The play is directed by Jose Estrella with an artistic team led by Sir Anril Tiatco, Jem Javier and Bryan Viray (dramaturgy), Barbie Tan-Tiongco (lights), Carlo Pagunaling (costume), Ed Lacson (set), JM Cabling (choreography) and Jon Lazam (sounds).\nMarso 2\nDulaang Engineering \nUP Film Institute\n6-11 p.m.\nThe event showcases the talent in theater production of the Engineering students through play performances that promote responsiveness on current trends and issues in the college, the university and the country. \nMarso 3\nSingkwenta! Samu\'t Saring Musika\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium\nUP College of Music\n6 p.m. \nIn celebration of 50 years of excellence and service, the Music Education Department of the UP College of Music invites everyone to its anniversary concert \"Singkwenta! Samu\'t Saring Musika.\" The concert highlights the resident groups of the department such as UP Rondalla, Musika Sophia Recorder Ensemble, Guitar Guild, JMEG Chorale, Cuerdas Comparsa String Ensemble with guest performers Profs. Mauricia Borromeo and Leticia Del Valle, Taytay Youth Philharmonic Orchestra, Talayan Children\'s Rondalla, NCCA Rondalla and the QMC Golden Nightingale Senior Citizen\'s Chorale. \nMarso 3\nMiss Engineering\nUniversity Theater\nMiss Engineering is the most awaited night event of Engineering Week. Male students from the College of Engineering, representing their organizations, compete in a grand pageant composed of photoshoots, video shoots, charity event, seminars, workshops, rehearsals and the pageant night. Each candidate will also portray a specific Philippine goddess or deity, while carrying the theme \"Self-Empowerment.\"\nMarso 4\nCall for submission of entries to The 2017 Amelia Lapeña-Bonifacio Literary Contest\nThis long running literary competition in English is open to all bonafide students of the University enrolled in the second semester AY 2016-17 excluding faculty members of the Department of English and Comparative Literature. \nMarso 4-5\nAng Unang Aswang ni Rody Vera Tampok ang UP Dance Company\nArki Amphitheater\n7 p.m.\nAng Unang Aswang ay isang pagtatanghal ng orihinal na akda ni Rody Vera sa pamamagitan ng sayat at galaw ng UP Dance Company, isa sa mga pitong opisyal na organisasyong pangtanghal ng UPD. Ito ay sa saliw ng koreograpiya at direksiyon ni JM Cabling at sa pamamatnubay ni Prop. Angela Baguilat na parehong mula sa UPD Kolehiyo ng Musika. \nMarso 4\nEngineering Week Afterparty\nCities Events Place, 30 Sgt. Esguerra Ave. Diliman, Quezon City\n7 p.m. \nThis is the awards night of the Engineering Week 2017, as well as the afterparty of the week-long event with the theme \"Sinulog\" or street party. \nThe Engineering community is invited to attend a night full of enjoyment and celebration of Engineering Week 2017. A short program will start the event to be followed by the awarding of the Top 10 and special awards by popular demand. The night will be capped with a party. \nMarso 10-27\nFlat to Functional \nAn exhibition of flat-pack, self-assembly furniture\nFoyer, UP Fine Arts Gallery, Bartlett Hall \n6 p.m.\nThe one-man exhibition by industrial designer and UP College of Fine Arts faculty member Tito de la Peña takes advantage of the digital design workflow and explores the use of the flat-pack model as a key design method. The show features recent furniture design prototypes for everyday use. Flat-pack furniture design offers practical solutions for people in need of affordable and almost ready-to-use goods. Through digital design development and production, it can now be implemented more quickly and at significantly less cost, providing people with more economical options for home furnishing needs. These products can be efficiently deployed to communities in disaster-affected areas and other offsite places. \nMarso 10-27\nReconfigurations\nA sculpture exhibition by UP College of Fine Arts faculty\nCorredor, UP Fine Arts Gallery, Bartlett Hall \n6 p.m.\nThis group exhibition of recent works by Roberto Feleo, Toym Imao, Paul Quiaño and Manolo Sicat explores the reinterpretation of figurative sculpture. It revisits the foundations of three-dimensional figuration as points for further creative exploration of the human form. The featured artists belong to different generations of sculptors and represent a diverse range of themes, media and practices in this field. All four are faculty members of the UP College of Fine Arts, handling core and major courses in materials and techniques in sculpture. A panel discussion wih the artists is scheduled on March 24, from 1 to 4 p.m. \nMarso 12-19\n56th UP National Writers Workshop\nBP International Makiling, Los Baños, Laguna\n8 a.m.-5 p.m.\nThe UP National Writers Workshop is an annual workshop catering to writers who have published or are on the brink of publishing a book, or have won an award. The 2017 fellows  are Arbeen Acuña (Fiction, Filipino), Christa De La Cruz (Poetry, Filipino), Zeno Denolo (Fiction, Filipino), Rowena Festin (Fiction, Filipino), Rogene Gonzales (Poetry, Filipino), Arvin Mangohig (Poetry, English), Arnie Mejia (Creative Non Fiction, English), Paolo Enrico Melendez (Creative Non Fiction, English), Charisse-Fuschia Paderna (Poetry, English), Wilfredo Pascual (Creative Non Fiction, English), Karren Renz Seña (Fiction, English), and Alvin Ursua (Poetry, Filipino). The works of these 12 fellows will be discussed and critiqued during a week-long series of workshop sessions, aimed at helping them further hone their craft. \nMarso 14\n38th Gabriel A. Bernardo Memorial Lecture\nUPD Main Library Lobby\n8:30 a.m. \nThe UP School of Library and Information Studies will be holding the 38th Gabriel A. Bernardo Memorial Lecture, with Prof. Iris Thiele Isip-Tan of the UP Manila Medical Informatics Unit as the guest speaker. Isip-Tan will be discussing the current state of health informatics in the Philippines and the role of librarians in health informatics. \nMarso 20-24\nSeminar Workshop : The Islamic Procedure in Inheritance and Family Cases at the Republic of the Philippines\nMicrotel, UP-Ayala Technohub\nCommonwealth Avenue, Quezon City\n8:30 a.m. - 8 p.m. \nThe UP Institute of Islamic Studies will be hosting 17 Justices from the Judiciary Department of the Kingdom of Thailand for a seminar workshop on Islamic Procedure in Inheritance and Family Cases. One of the highlights of the program is a courtesy visit to selected government offices including the Court of Appeals of the Philippine Judiciary. The event is in collaboration with the Research Association for Islamic Social Sciences, Inc. (RAIS), and the Office of the Judiciary in Thailand. \nMarso 21-24\nThe B.I.G. CSSP Career Fair\nBuild, Innovate, Generate : Pursue your passion, Serve the Nation!\nPalma Hall Lobby\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP) is holding the 6th annual CSSP Career Fair. Invited in this event are different non-government organizations, corporations, schools transitioning to the K-12 curriculum to offer CSSP majors and all UP Diliman students with socially relevant jobs and careers in line with their own courses-to emphasize the vital role both CSSP and UPD students play as nation-builders. A career talk by CSSP alumni will also be held on March 22 at the Palma Hall Room 400. \nMarso 21\nComparative Public Administration : Thailand and Philippines\nUP NCPAG Case Room\n1-4 p.m.\nThe UP National College of Public Administration and Governance (NCPAG) is holding a lecture on the comparison of public administration in Thailand and Philippines. Guest speaker is Dean Sida Sonsri. The talk is part of the lecture series featuring people who have been instrumental, or who have made significant contributons, in the advancement of the study of public administration in the Philippines and abroad and/or advocates of accountability, transparency, efficiency and responsible practice of public service and governance. \nMarso 21\nCSWCD Golden Anniversary Lecture Series\nTransformative and Transnational Social Work Practice\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\n1-5 p.m.\nAs part of its year-long golden anniversary celebration, the College of Social Work and Community Development will be conducting lecture series featuring the expertise of its faculty from the Department of Social Work (DSW). Recognized by the Commission on Higher Education as a Center of Excellence in Social Work, the DSW will be engaging its audience to an interesting topic on \"Transformative and Transnational Social Work Practice.\"\nMarso 25\nMicrobiology : Redefining Lives through Research, Development and Community Extension : A Cluster 2 Symposium\nInstitute of Biology Auditorium \nThe symposium targets to bring together researchers, scientists, faculty members, college students, entrepreneurs and even microbe enthusiasts in the fields of agriculture, environmental sciences, biotechnology, industrial microbiology and other related fields to communicate current research priorities and progress in these fields, and to identify new research approaches. It particularly aims to present the status of microbiology in the fields of agriculture, aquatic, environment and industry. \nMarso 25\nIhudyat! 2017\nUP Amphitheater \n4 p.m.\nIhudyat! 2017 is a festival of the finest marching bands of the Philippines. The Festival will feature the Citizen\'s Brigade Band of Dasmariñas Cavite, University of Luzon Drum & Bugle Corps, Philippine Air Force Band, Philippine Army Band, Philippine Coast Guard Band, Philippine Marines (Navy Fleet) Drum & Bugle Corps, and the UP ROTC Symphonic Band. \nMarso 31\nTalasalitaan 2017 : Ang Wikang Filipino sa Pagsulong ng Karapatan ng Kababaihan\nUP College of Law\n9-11 a.m.\nAng Talasalitaan ay isang regular na forum na isinasagawa ng Sentro ng Wikang Filipino (SWF)- UP Diliman na nagtatampok ng iba\'t-ibang paksa na may kaugnayan sa pananaliksik at pagtuturo ng wikang Filipino sa iba\'t ibang disiplina para sa lalo pang pagpapaunlad at pagsulong ng Palisi sa Wika ng Unibersidad ng Pilipinas. Ngayong Marso, magiging paksa ng Talasalitaan ang Ang Wikang Filipino sa Pagsulong ng Karapatan ng Kababaihan. Kasamang tagapagtaguyod ng SWF-UP Diliman ang iba\'t ibang organisasyon sa loob at labas ng Unibersidad tulad ng Gabriela Women\'s Partylist, UP Center for Women and Gender Studies, UP Diliman Gender Office at UP Portia Sorority ng UP College of Law. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1084, 'E2-1084AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 3, Blg 4 (4 copies) ', '', '', 'Mayo 2017', 'Ang Paglalakbay ng Pagpapaunlad ng Pamayanan \nCSWCD Golden Lecture Series\nBulwagang Tandang Sora\n2-8 p.m.\nAs part of the 50th Anniversary Celebration of the College of Social Work and Community Development, the Department of Community Development and the Community Development Society of the Philippines present \"Ang Paglalakbay ng Pagpapaunlad ng Pamayanan.\" Professors Elmer Ferrer and Maureen Pagaduan together with Prof. Emeritus Ka Lito Manalili, through a lecture, will share their experiences and expertise in the field of Community Development. A cultural and solidarity night floows right after the lecture. \nMayo 6\nAGORA 2017 : Arkichange\nMelchor Hall Theater\n1-4 p.m.\nAn annual event of the Architecture Student Council (ASC) since 2015, Agora serves as an avenue where peolle can exchange ideas through a multi-perspective view on Architecture and its related fields. This year, Agora focuses on how the present and future professionals in the field of architecture could own up their vital role and be able to contribute to the positive changes in our country. Representatives from the government, private architecture practitioners, private developers, non-government organizations and the academe will join the panel discussion for a holistic approach on the said topic. \nMayo 8\nTAMPISAW\nHuling HirEAT sa Tag-init\nAlonso Hall, College of Home Economics\n8 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nFood Science (FS) 178 Product Fair is an annual event organized by the 4th year BSt Food Technology students under the supervision of the FS 178 Faculty-in-Charge from the Department of Food Science and Nutrition, College of Home Economics. The event showcases various food products prototypes that were developed using High Impact Technology Solutions (HITS) equipment at the UP Diliman DOST Food Innovation Facility.\nMayo 8-12\nHARAYA 2017\nCollege of Architecture Complex \n8 a.m.-7 p.m.\nHaraya is an annual exposition of the UP Diliman College of Architecture. It showcases the outstanding body of works of its students, faculty and research associates, complimented by a series of activities geared towards the promotion of a collaborative environment between design students and professionals. The event is an open-house activity wherein everyone is welcome to view the students\' works. This grand exhibit is accompanied by different activities per day that are open to the public as well; such as presentation of best theses, presentation of faculty research, architecture and landscape architecture workshops, talks on career advancement, contests and social nights. \nMayo 8-22\nMultiple Modalities\nAn exhibition by the FA 222 graduate class under Prof. Josephine Turalba\nBulwagan ng Dangal, Main Hall\nUP Main Library\nSix artists from UP Diliman Master of Fine arts (MFA) program, in their FA222 : Studies and Exploration of Contemporary Methods and Approaches to Art Production class, explore non-habitual approaches to art production within their individual praxis in their show entitled Multifocal Modalities. The exhibit\'s highlights the artist\'s experimentations on various techniques, processes, media and modalities in production. \nMayo 12-27\nStill/Moving\nAn exhibition by the FA 215 class under Prof. Katti Sta. Ana\nBulwagan ng Dangal, Atelyer\nUP Main Library\nThe exhibition presents the end-of-semester output of four MFA students, namely, Weena Espardinez, Titat Ledesma, Annie Pacaña-Lumbao, and Manolo Sicat as they tackle problems in the creation of space in art making in FA 215 under Prof. Katti Sta. Ana.\nMayo 15-19\nCSSP-NSTP : Naglilingkod sa KAPPwa, Naglilingkod sa Bayan! \nIsang Linggong Eksibit\n1/F, Palma Hall Lobby\n8 a.m.-5 p.m.\nAng isang linggong eksibit na ito ay maglalaman ng mga larawan, poster at iba pang exhibit material na magtatanghal sa mga paglilingkod na ginawa ng mga mag-aaral ng National Service Training Program (NSTP) sa College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP) ngayong Ikalawang Semester, Akademikong Taon (AT) 2016-2017. Katatampukan ito ng pagbubukas ng eksibit mula sa unang araw at patimpalak para sa Natatanging Community Engagement Poster; at Natatanging Community Engagement Photo para sa mga klase sa umaga at hapon. Ang Parangal ay igagawad sa Programa ng Pagtatapos ng mga Mag-aaral ng NSTP sa CSSP. \nMayo 15\nCSSP-NSTP : Naglilingkod sa KAPPwa, Naglilingkod sa Bayan! \nPrograma ng Pagtatapos ng Mag-aaral ng NSTP sa CSSP 2016-2017\n1/F Palma Hall Lobby\n9 a.m. - 12 p.m. at 2-5 p.m.\nIto ay programa na naglalayong kilalanin ang matagumpay na pagtatapos ngayong Ikalawang Semestre Akademikong Taon 2016-2017 ng mga mag-aaral ng NSTP sa CSSP. Nakapaloob sa programa ang pagpapalabas ng video presentations tungkol sa paglilingkod-komunidad ng bawat klase; pagkilala at pasasalamat sa mga katuwang na organisasyon/komunidad sa pagsasakatuparan ng mga inisyatibo ng bawat klase sa CSSP-NSTP; paggagawad ng mga ispesyal na pagkilala sa mga klase; at ang mainit na pagtatanggap sa mga nagtapos bilang mga bagong kasapi ng National Service Reserve Corps. \nMayo 17\nSocial Development : Defining the Terrain, Exploring Pathways \n2017 CSWCD Golden Anniversary Conference\nBulwagang Tandang Sora, College of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD)\n9 a.m.-5 p.m.\nIn line with the 50th Anniversary Celebration of the CSWCD, the Social Development Program is conducting a conference entitled \"Social Development : Defining the Terrain, Exploring Pathways\" to look at Social Development as an academic discipline. The Conference aims to provide academicians, practitioners, policy makers and students a venue for sharing, understanding and networking knowledge and commitment towards disciplinal enhancement of social development. \nMayo 23\nBulawan : Konsiyerto para sa mga Iskolar ng Bayan\nCSWCD Concert Series\nConspiracy Garden Cafe\nVisayas Avenue, Quezon City\n8:30-11:30 p.m.\nBulawan : Konsiyerto para sa mga Iskolar ng Bayan is a kick-off cultural program designed to raise funds for the talented and deserving scholars of CSWCD. TUBAW Music Collective and other rising bands from the UP Diliman will perform. The soft launch for the grand concert scheduled on October 2017 will start on May 19 through an online campaign that will feature its scholars and various support groups. \nMayo 24\nEEE Technology Fair 2017 \nUP Professional Schools\nBonifacio Global City\n8 a.m. - 6 p.m.\nThe UP Electrical and Electronics Engineering Institute is hosting the first EEE Technology Fair 2017, with the theme, \"Enhanced Industry-Academe Collaboration to Support a Culture of Innovation.\" The event aims to engage state universities and colleges, government agencies and industry partners in advancing the Electrical, Electronics and Computer Engineering fields in the Philippines by setting the platform for collaboration. The Institute will showcase its research projects and will recognize the faculty, researchers and students in their efforts to make a difference for the Philippines. Invited inudstry partners and government agencies will also lay down the mechanisms for research collaboration and other forms of partnership. \nMayo 24-28\nIka-10 Palihang Rogelio Sicat\nTaunang Pambansang Palihan sa Malikhaing Pagsulat\nLeyte Park Resort Hotel, Tacloban City\nAng taunang Pambansang Palihan sa Malikhaing Pagsulat na ito ay itinataguyod ng Departamento ng Filipino at Panitikan ng Pilipinas ng UP Diliman, sa pakikipagtulungan ng Opisina ng Pangulo ng UP, Opisina ng Tsanselor ng UP Diliman, UP Tacloban, Sentro ng Wikang Filipino, City Mayor\'s Office ng Tacloban City at ni Bb. Karla Estrada. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1085, 'E2-1085AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 3, Blg 5 (5 copies) ', '', '', 'Hunyo 2017', 'Hunyo 1- Agosto 10\nA Man and His Relations\nA retrospective exhibition on the life and works of national Artist for Visual Arts Cesar Legaspi\nMain Hall, Bulwagan ng Dangal \nThe exhibition will feature artworks of Legaspi from the University Art Collection, works of Legaspi\'s peers from the Thirteen Moderns and the neo-realists, and archival materials. Cesar Legaspi was a pioneer of the neo-realist genre in painting; a prominent member of the Thirteen Moderns and is widely known for his contributions in Philippine Modern Art. He was awarded National Artist for Visual Arts in 1990. Legaspi graduated from the UP College of Fine Arts in 1936. The Bulwagan ng Dangal UP Heritage Museum endeavors to introduce Legaspi\'s art to a younger generation of UP students. \nHunyo 1-8\nUPCFA Studio Arts Thesis Exhibition\nUP College of Fine Arts\nThe Department of Studio Arts of the UP College of Fine Arts (CFA) will conduct a public viewing of thesis works by their graduating batch of students, ranging from paintings, sculptures, installation, video art and drawings. Thesis advisees of Professors Ambie Abaño, Benjamin Cabangis, Roberto Feleo, Marc Malto, Jonathan Olazo and Riza Romero will be exhibiting their art works at the UP Fine Arts Gallery (Corredor and Foyer), Amorsolo Hall, Theory Rooms, Bathalaman and RGEP Rooms. \nHunyo 1 at 14; Hulyo 4\nGender Sensitivity Training \nPara sa mga guro, REPS, kawaning administratibo at kawaning agency-hired ng UP Diliman\nSeminar Room, Diliman Gender Office (DGO)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nBilang pagpapatibay at pagtiyak na ang UP Diliman ay nananatiling makataong Kampus na may hustisyang pangkasarian, malaya sa diskriminasyon at pang-aabuso, isinasagawa ang Gender Sensitivity Training (GST) para sa mga guro, REPS (Research, Extension and Professional Staff), kawaning administratibo, mga security guard at janitorial workers. Bukas ito para sa mga empleyadong permanente, UP contractual at non-UP contractual. \nHunyo 2\nUP COE Undergraduate Project Competition 2017\nShowcasing UPD engineering\'s best undergraduate research projects\nMelchor Hall, UP College of Engineering Main lobby (demonstrations and exhibits) 5th floor, P&G Room (presentations and judging) 2-2:30 p.m. (demonstrations and exhibits) 2:30-5 p.m. (presentations and judging) Senior undergraduate students compete and vie for this year\'s best engineering undergraduate research project, as distinguished judges from the private sector, government, industry and academia share their expertise in deciding who deserves the grand prize of P50,000. \nHunyo 6-31\nLangueLounge : Forgetory by Jose Tence Ruiz\nAtelyer, Bulwagan ng Dangal, Main Library\nThe exhibit is a site-specific installation that is a meditation on the cult of glib and overwhelming information over truth. It works with image and meaning in relation to contemporary life and society. High backed chairs lined with red velvet are related to the image of high and honorable status, of luxury and comfort that is desired and possessed. Upon closer inspection, these honorable chairs turn out to be electric chairs, and what seems to be an opulent and elegant thing is an object of torture. The work calls for closer scrutiny on what is seen and heard, an encouragement to move out of places of comfort, conformity and complacency. LangueLounge : Forgetory was initially made for and exhibited at the ARTFair Philippines 2017 and was subsequently installed at the Far Eastern University as a center piece in Hudyat, an exhibition decrying the state of extra judicial killings and asserting the principle of human dignity. This third installation is a new iteration from previous exhibitions. \nHunyo 7\nA new look at Philippine export performance : a firm-level approach \nRm. 303, Encarnacion Hall, School of Economics 4-5 p.m.\nThis paper introduces a rich and novel database of the Philippine Statistics Authority (PSA) containing the universe of export and import transactions of all firms from 1991-2012, merged with all the manufacturing firm surveys since 1996. A new set of stylized facts is presented, pertaining to the drivers of export growth and patterns of trade, and including the dimensions of geographical location, size and firm ownership in the analysis. New firm typologies are developed, as the behaviour of individual exporting and importing firms can now be traced not only in terms of the entry, exit and survival, but also re-entry, permanent exit, and continuous or resilient survival. \nHunyo 16-Hulyo 7\nOnce More\nCorredor, UP Fine Arts Gallery, Bartlett Hall \n6 p.m. (Opening)\nThe exhibition brings together a batch of UP College of Fine Arts alumni from two decades ago, whose members have gone on to pursue full or part time art practice, education and other related fields. Participating artists are Kaye Anne Alba, Carina Altomonte, Erin Asuncion-Dionisio, Billy Atienza, Martin Caoile, Kathy Cuisia-Wu, Kim Dacanay-Mendoza, Patricia Perez Eustaquio, Pusongbughaw, Otto Hernandez, Jonathan Galicano, Philipp Ines, Lisa Ito, Kim Landicho, Liby Limoso, Lea Zoraina Lim, Elena Malgapo-Domingo, Josue Mangrobang Jr., Robby Mananquil, Winston Martinez, Jerry Morada, Bon Mujeres, Maria Rita Cecilia Pangilinan-Arenas, Chris Paulmino, Jaspher Penuliar, Eufemio Rasco IV, Alan Rapsing, Li-anne Roa-Patricio, Ria Suaverdez-Romero, Jiyas Suministrado-Morales, Riza Romero, Dave Salazar, Chelle Serrano-Tagle, Brian Sergio, Rodel Tapaya, Maan Villanueva dn MM Yu. \nHunyo 19\n[Linguistics Brown Bag] HOKAGLISH : The New Language of the Filipino-Chinese\nAVR (PH 207)\nCollege of Social Sciences and Philosophy \n9-11 a.m.\nWilkinson Gonzales, MA Candidate of the National University of Singapore will talk about the unique linguistic features of Hokaglish, i.e., Hokkien, Tagalog and English, also referred to as Salamstam (-oe) \'mixed speech\' or Lanang (-oe) \'our people speech\', a post-colonial Philippine contact language spoken generally in Metro Manila by local-born ethnic Chinese. \nHunyo 25\nIka-106 Pangkalahatang Pagtatapos \nAmpiteatro ng Unibersidad\n7 a.m.\nSa taunang Pangkalahatang Pagtatapos, iginagawad ng Unibersidad ang titulo sa mga mag-aaral na nagtapos ng kani-kanilang programa sa di-gradwado at gradwadong antas. Ito ay iba pa sa mga pagtatapos na ginagawa ng bawat kolehiyo o linangan ng UP Diliman. Ito ang ikatlong pagkakataon na gagawin ang Pagtatapos sa buwan ng Hunyo mula ng ilipat ang simula ng pasukan sa Agosto noong 2014. \nHunyo 29\n\'Walking Korea\' by Arirang Yurangdan\nMultimedia Room (PH 400)\nCollege of Social Sciences and Philosophy\n1-5 p.m.\nThe workshop brings Arirang Yurangdan\'s concept of \'Walking Korea\' which showcases Korean culture such as the Korean traditional music Gukak, calligraphy and traditional dance. As the Korean Culture Diplomatic Delegation, they travel around the world to share their culture and discover other cultures. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1086, 'E2-1086AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 3, Blg 6 (3 copies) ', '', '', 'Hulyo 2017', 'Hulyo 1-7\nTubig at Kalikasan : 6th Solo Exhibit of Prof. Johnny T. Reynoso\nFoyer, UP Fine Arts Gallery \nBartlett Hall\nThis 6th solo exhibition of UP College of Fine Arts (UPCFA) faculty member and photographer prof. Johnny T. Reynoso features his recent series of color photographs portraying the theme of water and nature : underscoring the connections and harmony between this vital element and the natural life that surrounds us. Reynoso\'s body of work often highlights the presence of nature and its vivid colors. This evident in his two coffee table books featuring his portfolio of photographs, titled \"Colors of Nature, Water of Life\" and \"In Retrospect : Water of Life 2\" released in 2014 and 2016, respectively. Reynoso is an Associate Professor at the UPCFA Department of Visual Communication. He started teaching in the college in 1987 on courses in Photography, Visual Design, Production Methods, Editorial Design, Graphic Workshop, Screenprinting, Research Methods and Graphic Thesis. \nHulyo 3-7\n9th Training Course on Road Safety Audit\nNational Center for Transportation Studies (NCTS)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe training, organized by NCTS, will use existing course materials and resources to maximize hands-on experiences and ensure internalization and retention of the concepts being presented. It provides an overview on principles and fundamentals of road safety, statistics/trends, causes and factors of crashes, road safety audit concepts, accident analysis and various road safety facilities. Basics of geometric design of highway sections and their applications together with intersection design elements are also presented. Target participants are municipal/city planners, municipal/city engineers, traffic engineers, transportation planners, and local and national government personnel involved in transportation and related functions. \nHulyo 4-27\n(tuwing Martes, Huwebes at Sabado)\nGender Sensitivity Training\nSeminar Room, Diliman Gender Office \nBenton Hall\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nBilang pagpapatibay at pagtiyak na ang UP Diliman ay nananatiling makataong kampus na may hustisyang pangkasarian, malaya sa diskriminasyon at pang-aabuso, isinasagawa ang Gender Sensitivity Training (GST) para sa mga guro, REPS, kawaning administratibo, mga security at janitorial personnel. Bukas ito para sa mga empleyadong permanente, UP contractual at non-UP contractual. \nHulyo 4-15\n(Martes, Huwebes at Sabado)\nBasic Vector Graphics Composition Workshop\nBartlett Hall\nUP College of Fine Arts (UPCFA)\n1-5 p.m.\nThe UPCFA will be opening slots for a 6-day workshop in Basic Vector Graphics Composition, to be facilitated by Studio Arts professor Riza Romero. Workshop schedules will be from 1 to 5 p.m. on July 4, 6, 8, 11, 13, and 15 (Tuesday, Thursdays and Saturdays). Vector graphics composition uses geometric primitives such as points, lines, curves and polygons based on mathematics to represent images in computer graphics. The workshop aims to introduce participants to vector-based graphic environment to give them an understanding of how mathematical equations are used to create images. \nHulyo 5\nFreshmen Orientation Program 2017 : Breed of new blood \nUP Film Center\n12-4 p.m.\nParent\'s Orientation Program : a pledge of support and allegiance\nSchool of Economics Auditorium\n12 - 4 p.m.\nThese programs aim to orient the freshmen and their parents with various university programs and services. \nHulyo 8-22\n(tuwing Sabado)\nDrawing and Painting Workshops\nBartlett Hall\nUP College of Fine Arts (UPCFA)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nFacilitated by Prof. Jamel Obnamia, the 3-day workshop emphasizes basic drawing skills in the student\'s choice of painting media (watercolor on paper, acrylic on canvas or oil on canvas). \nHulyo 15\nCall for papers for the International Conference Marking the Centennial of Philippine Anthropology\nThe conference aims to generate critical discussions that focus on institutional memories, historiography and analyses of issues and concerns in research, teaching and practice of anthropology in the Philippines in the last 100 years. Students, researchers and practitioners in anthropology and related disciplines are invited to submit paper and panel proposals that cover any of the following themes : Theory, Practice, Pedagogy and Ethics in Philippine Anthropology; Institutional Memories and Anthropological Traditions; Ancestors of Philippine Anthropology; Identity, Culture, Folklore and Heritage; Anthropology and Philippine Society; and New Directions for Philippine Anthropology. \nHulyo 21\nCall for papers for the 2nd Colleges and Universities Public Service Conference\nThe conference aims to provide a platform to effectively harness teaching and research for extension and public service, to provide a venue for scholarly discussions on lessons and best practices for continuous improvement, and to document innovative initiatives that highlight higher education institutions\' social responsibility and compassion. The conference is open to all disciplines with community engagements and public service initiatives. Programs with themes like service learning; student engagement; public service monitoring and reporting systems; knowledge-driven volunteerism; linkages of the university with communities, civil society, industries and government; and impact measurements of engagements are very welcome. \nHulyo 23-Agosto 6\n(tuwing Linggo)\nBasic or Advanced Drawing and Painting Workshop\nBartlett Hall \nUP College of Fine Arts (UPCFA)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nFacilitated by Prof. Yasmin Almonte, the 3-day workshop offers participants the chance to hone their skills in basic drawing and their choice of painting formats (portrait, still life, landscape, figure drawing or abstract art). Almonte is a summa cum laude graduate of the Universitgy of Northern Iowa\'s Master of Arts degree program and a magna cum laude graduate of the UPCFA\'s Painting program. \nHulyo 31\nCall for nomination for the 2nd Gawad Pangulo : Award for Excellence in Public Service\nThe Award seeks to recognize outstanding public service initiatives of various UP System units that exhibit compassion (malasakit) to the different publics that they serve. Nominations should belong to the five clusters : Arts and Letters and Communications; Science and Technology; Social Sciences, Management, and Law; Health and Allied Sciences; and Agriculture, Forestry, Fishery and Natural Resources Management. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1087, 'E2-1087AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 3, Blg 7 (4 copies) ', '', '', 'Agosto 2017', 'Agosto 7\nFreshman Welcome Assembly \nUniversity Theater\n1-5 p.m.\nThe program aims to welcome UPD freshmen by introducing them to their respective Deans as well as University Officials. \nAgosto 14-18\n19th Traffic Administration Course\nNational Center for Transportation Studies Bldg. \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe training gives an overview of what transportation planning is all about and its interaction with land use, introduction to traffic engineering and management. Basics of traffic impact assessment including rationale required analysis and components of the transportation system are also presented. Different traffic measures employed locally and internationally will be discussed as well as basic traffic safety information and education programs. Field work activity including data collection will be experienced by the participants for a more hands-on learning. Participants will also understand specific institutional issues and the possible legal arrangements in setting up the traffic regulatory unit including laws related therein. \nAgosto 15 - Setyembre 15\nCall for papers : Bodies in/and Asian Theatres\nThe Joint 2018 Asian Theatre Working Group Colloquium and International Federation for Theatre Research Regional Conference (IFTR-Asia) attempts to answer these general questions : What do we mean when we talk about bodies in Asian theatres and performances? What do we mean when we talk about Asian bodies in different performances outside the region? How does theatre affect the way we think about the bodies of Asians?\nAgosto 17-18\nSinelaysay : A Documentary Film Showcase\nRoom 400, Palma Hall\n10 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nFor six years now, the Third World Studies Center (TWSC) of the College of Social Sciences and Philosophy, UP Diliman and the Department of Political Science of Universite de Montreal produced documentaries that tell the stories of the lives and struggles of Filipinos at the unmarked margins of society. This year\'s showcase will premiere two new documentaries. \"Leaving Bodeng\" documents the last days of the about-to-be-evicted occupants of the iconic White Building in Phnom Penh, while \"Pag-baylo : Losing the Land to Solar Farms\" brings to light the deft maneuvers by big landowners to convert vast tracts of lands that are meant for distribution to its tenants into solar farms. \nAgosto 18\nWork-Life Balance IV\nSeminar Rm. \nUP Diliman Gender Office (UPDGO)\n9 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nLayunin ng Work - Life Balance IV na itaguyod ang malay sa kasariang talastasan sa pamamagitan ng mga impormal na lunan. Nag-oorganisa ang UPDGO ng mga aktibidad na naglalayong magbahagi ng kaalaman at kamulatan tungkol sa iba\'t ibang isyung pangkasarian. May libreng talakayan, sine, hilot at meryenda para sa mga kawani, REPS, guro at mag-aaral ng UPD. \nAgosto 18\nDepartment of Linguistics Research Colloquium\nPalma Hall Audio - Visual Room (Rm. 207) \n9 a.m. [Undergraduate papers]\n1 p.m. [Graduate papers]\nThe annual Research Colloquium serves as a venue for presenting findings of recent research projects done by graduate and undergraduate students of Linguistics to the general public, in order to forge collaborations among students, faculty and scholars of linguistics, language studies, as well as other related disciplines. \nAgosto 18 - Setyembre 1\nDissident Vicinities\nMain Hall and Atelyer\nBulwagan ng Dangal\n4 p.m.\nThe exhibition touches on how cultural work and production contributed to various arenas of struggle, from traditional venues to subaltern zone. It features works by Karl Castro, Nathalie Dagmang, Boy Dominguez and Leonilo Doloricon in collaboration with Tom Estrera, Voltaire Guray, Renz Lee, Henrielle Pagkaliwangan, Melvin Pollero, Iggy Rodriguez, Sining Lila, Aldrein Silanga, Pablo Baen Santos, Archie Oclos, Renan Ortiz, UGATLahi Artists Collective and Bagong Alyansang Makabayan. The exhibition is part of Condition Report, a collaborative art project with emerging young curators from Japan and Southeast Asia, and is supported by the Japan Foundation Asia Center. Responding to the theme \"What is Southeast Asia?\", the project consists of four collaborative exhibitions between January to March 2017 in Manila, Jakarta, Kuala Lumpur and Bangkok and 14 local exhibitions in 12 cities for the second half of 2017. Lisa Ito-Tapang curates the exhibit. \nAgosto 22\nNuclear Energy Forum\nConsiderations and Essential Information\nNovotel, Cubao, Quezon City\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe forum will discuss the plan of the present Philippine government to adopt or consider nuclear energy as potential solution in providing sustainable electric energy in the country. Its advantages such as the relatively competitive levelized cost of energy, low greenhouse gas and criteria air pollution footprint, and base load contribution will be presented. Concerns in using this energy source such as the complexity of the technology, multiple dimensions to be copnsidered, i.e. safety, security, safeguard as well as management of radioactive waste will also be tackled. The forum is organized by the National Engineering Center, the Engineering Research and Development for Technology (ERDT) and the UP Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. (UPERDFI).\nAgosto 22\nSpecial Lecture : Dr. Naonori Nagaya \nPalma Hall Audio-Visual Room (Rm. 207)\n10-11:30 a.m. The event is free and open to the public. \nAgosto 22-25\nPublic Administration in Changing Times : New Norms and Sustainable Reform\nMarco Polo Hotel, Ortigas Avenue, Pasig City\nIn celebration of the 65th anniversary of the National College of Public Administration and Governance, the College is holding an international conference on global issues, such as climate change, fiscal crises, human rights violations, international crimes, growing influence of supra-national institutions, disruptive technology, \'populist nationalism\' and changes in regional dynamics (i.e. Brexit), among others. \nAgosto 24-25\nMga Susing Salita : Pambansang Seminar sa Pagbuo ng Diskurso sa Konseptong Filipino\nAwditoryum ng Kolehiyo ng Edukasyon \n8 a.m.\nBilang bahagi ng pagdiriwang ng Buwan ng Wika 2017 sa UP Diliman (UPD), malugod na iniimbitahan ang mga guro, mag-aaral, manunulat at mananaliksik na dumalo at makiisa sa pambansang seminar. Sa pangunguna ito ng Sentro ng Wikang Filipino - UPD at pakikpagtulungan ng UP Departamento ng Filipino at Panitikan ng Pilipinas ng Kolehiyo ng Arte at Literatura, UP Departamento ng Linggwistiks ng Kolehiyo ng Agham Panlipunan at Pilosopiya, at UP Dibisyon ng Araling Wika ng Kolehiyo ng Edukasyon. Ito ang kauna-unahang pagkakataon para sa isang pambansang seminar na magtatampok sa pagbuo ng diskurso na hango sa konseptong Filipino. Gamit ang isang susing salita sa anumang wika sa Pilipinas, layunin ng seminar na paunlarin ang inisyal na mga ideya at konseptong nakapaloob sa piniling salita. \nAgosto 24\nThe Linguist Talks : Dr. Viveca V. Hernandez\nPalma Hall Audio-Visual Room (Rm. 207) \n9 a.m. \nThis brownbag session highlights the experiences of one of the pillars of the UP Department of Linguistics, Dr. Viveca V. Hernandez, as a fieldworker in various ethnolinguistic communities around the Philippines. Dr. Hernandez will share the issues, challenges, and rewards of actual field activities done for linguistics and cultural studies purposes, for the benefit of the future generation of field researchers. \nAgosto 24\nNanay talks\nPalma Hall Audio-Visual Room (Rm. 207)\n1-4 p.m.\nThis event invited scholars from the Department of Linguistics and the Department of Anthropology, who are also mothers, to share their experiences in rearing their child during their developmental and formative years. This roundtable discussion aims to gain insights into the language acquisition and learning of children, from the perspective of linguist/anthropologist-mothers. \nAgosto 25\nCSWCD Grand 50th Anniversary\nCollege of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD)\n9 a.m.-5 p.m.\nThe celebration of CSWCD\'s Grand 50th Anniversary will have a number of activities like Bicycle Campus Tour (9-10:30 a.m.), launching of Philippine Journal of Social Development 2017 Volume 9 (11 a.m.-12 p.m.), Lunch (12-1 p.m.) and Fellowship Time : songs, dances, games, and raffle (1-4 p.m.)\nAgosto 26\nCSWCD @50 Grand Reunion and Alumni Homecoming \nCSWCD Grounds\n3:30 - 10 p.m.\nJoin the College of Social Work and Community Development (CSWCD) in a night of song, dance and memories as they recall the 50 years of CSWCD in a Grand Reunion and Alumni Homecoming. \nThe College will recognize its Jubilarians and other graduates, and present the premiere of the CSWCD @50 video. \nAgosto 28\nLinguistics in Movies\nPalma Hall Audio-Visual Room (Rm. 207)\n9 a.m. - 3 p.m.\nA public screening of movies that highlight themes related to languages and linguistics. The event also serves as a venue for movie enthusiasts and linguistics and language studies scholars in order to engage in discussions on their disciplines and how they are relevant to and manifested in popular culture. \nAgosto 29\nPeminismong Babaylan\nNilalayon ng porum na talakayin ang lakas at kapangyarihan ng kababaihan sa perspektibo ng kalinangang Pilipino. Iniuugat sa mga babaylan ang taal na kapangyarihan ng mga Pilipina at ang mataas na pagpapahalaga sa kababaihan sa taal na pamayanang Pilipino. Tampok ang tagapagsalita na si Prop. Ma. Fe Buenaventura-Mangahas. \nAgosto 30\nNotes from the Field\nPalma Hall Audio-Visual Room (Rm. 207)\n9 a.m.\nIn this symposium, students of the recently conducted linguistic fieldwork will share their experiences in undertaking field activities for social science research. The presenters will present the research background, problems encountered and handled, and other pertinent notes in doing field research in their assigned sites outside the campus. \nAgosto 30\nLinguistic Mapping and Language Documentation\nPalma Hall Audio-Visual Room (Rm. 207)\nThis event presents the final outputs of the students of Linguistics 125 (Introduction to Field Methods) and Linguistics 121 (Linguistic Survey of the Philippines), under the supervision of faculty members of the Department of Lingustics, in collaboration with the Department of Geography. This serves as a platform where the presenters get to share with the public the results of their research on field activities and linguistic surveys through the soft launching of an interactive website where the visitors would be able to check out the languages spoken in specific localities in the country, alongside a brief profile of each of these languages. \nAgosto 31\nAsian Culture Fest : Writing Systems\nRoom 400, Palma Hall\n10 a.m. - 4 p.m. \nThe festival showcases the different writing systems of selected Asian languages in order to gain appreciation of how linguistic forms are expressed in a system other than the more commonly used Roman letters. This forum/workshop invites Asian language students, teachers and enthusiasts to experience the traditional and contemporary writing methods and techniques in the respective languages. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
