(1088, 'E2-1088AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 3, Blg 8', '', '', 'Setyembre 2018', 'Setyembre 2, 9 at 16\nDrawing and Painting Workshop\nBartlett Hall, College of Fine Arts\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nLearn the basic or advance techniques of drawing and painting landscapes, still life, portraiture, figure and abstracts through the study of the elements of art and principles of design. Prof. Yasmin Almonte, a summa cum laude graduate of the University of Northern Iowa\'s Master of Arts degree program and a magna cum laude graduate of the UP College of Fine Arts\' Painting program, facilitates the workshop. \nSetyembre 2-23\nRituals of Invasion and Resistance / Norberto Roldan\nVargas Museum, Ground Floor (GF) Galleries\n6-9 p.m. Opening Reception\nUP Vargas Museum, in cooperation with Silverlens, opens Norberto Roldan\'s exhibition titled \"Rituals of Invasion and Resistance\" at the GF Galleries of the museum. Roldan engages viewers with his past installations that reflect on belief systems, that are either religious, political or personal. \nSetyembre 2-23\nThe Arrow of Time in the Heart of the Sun / Ian Fabro\nVargas Museum, 3F Galleries\n6-9 p.m. Opening Reception\nThe exhibit focuses on Ian Fabro\'s skillful appropriation of various media to convey the intricacies of abstraction and the depiction of the human form. The bloodstained body and the suffering flesh hint at the internal struggle of humanity and the triumph over evil. The human is pinned downed literally and figuratively, awaiting redemption and enlightenment.\nSetyembre 3, 10 at 17\nDrawing and Painting Workshop\nBartlett Hall, College of Fine Arts\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nLearn the basic or advance techniques of drawing and painting landscapes, still life, portraiture, figure and abstracts through the study of the elements of art and principles of design. Prof. Yasmin Almonte, a summa cum laude graduate of the University of Northern Iowa\'s Master of Arts degree program and a magna cum laude graduate of the UP College of Fine Arts\' Painting program, facilitates the workshop. \nSetyembre 4 - 25\n(tuwing Lunes)\nGender Sensitivity Training\nSeminar Room, UP Diliman Gender Office\n1-5 p.m.\nBilang pagpapatibay at pagtiyak na ang UP Diliman ay nananatiling makataong kampus na may hustisyang pangkasarian, malaya sa diskriminasyon at pang-aabuso, isinasagawa ang Gender Sensitivity Training (GST) para sa mga mag-aaral ng UP Diliman bilang bahagi ng organization accreditation sa taong 2017.\nSetyembre 9, 16 at 23\nDrawing and Painting Workshop for Beginners\nBartlett Hall, College of Fine Arts \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nFacilitated by Asst. Prof. Jamel Joseph A. Obnamia, the 3-day workshop emphasizes basic drawing skills in the student\'s choice of painting media (watercolor on paper, acrylic on canvas or oil on canvas).\nSeptember 11 at 18\nLakad Gunita\nFirst Quarter Storm and Diliman Commune Memory Walk in UP Diliman\nCommune Memory Walk in UP Diliman\nPalma Hall (former AS) Lobby\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe First Quarter Storm of 1970 and the Diliman Commune of 1971 occured as a reaction to the worsening economic conditions of the time. These events displayed the response of a dissatisfied people who chose activism and militancy amidst threats of political persecution from the Marcos administration. Looking at the narrative and legacy of these events is crucial in producing a better understanding of the historical circumstances that ultimately led to the declaration of Martial Law in 1972. To celebrate the legacy of these student-led protests, the UP Department of History will conduct a memory walk which will revisit the key landmarks of activism within the UP Diliman campus. This is in cooperation with the College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP) and the Office for Initiatives in Culture and the Arts (OICA). \nSetyembre 19-22\nTraining on Participatory Monitoring and Evaluation of Development Projects\nSeminar Room, College of Social Work and Community Development\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe training course aims to enhance the understanding capabilities of participants in developing appropriate participatory monitoring and evaluation systems for their respective community projects and programs. The training is initiated and organized by the Research and Extension for Development Office of the UP College of Social Work and Community Development. \nSetyembre 26-28\nBatas Militar 2017 : Mga Hamon sa Demokrasya\nA seminar-workshop for teachers in basic and higher education institutions\nNational Institute for Science and Mathematics Education Development (NISMED) Auditorium\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nIn commemoration of the declaration of Martial Law in September 1972, the UP College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP) will hold a seminar-workshop aimed at helping improve the teaching of history, social studies and the social sciences (particularly on the issue of martial law), in various levels of education. This is in cooperation with the History Departments of Ateneo de Manila University and De La Salle University, with the support of the National Historical Commission of the Philippines and the Office for Initiatives in Culture and the Arts (OICA) of UP Diliman. \nSetyembre 26-29\n2nd Emission Inventory for Smaller Cities Training \nNational Center for Transportation Studies (NCTS) Building \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe training aims to identify the emission sources in the participants\' respective cities; develop an understanding of how computation of emission loading from different sources is conducted; and design a work plan for the establishment of emission inventories in their city. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1089, 'E2-1089AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 3, Blg 11 (6 copies)', '', '', 'Disyembre 2017', 'Disyembre 1-2\nUP Anthropology @ 100 : International Conference Marking the Centennial of Philippine Anthropology\nUP National Institute for Science and Mathematics Education Development (NISMED) \n8 a.m.\nThe Conference marks the culmination of the 3-year celebration of the UP Deparment of Anthropology of its 100 years of existence beginning in 1914 when general anthropology was taught at UP. In 1917, one of the earliest departments of anthropology in Asia was established in the country with Professor Henry Otley Beyer as the founding Chair. \nAlthough special attention is given to the institutional memory of the UP Department of Anthropology, the conference also brings together the various narratives of anthropological institutions in the country and presents different researches on the Philippines. The Conference celebrates, documents and interprets the legacy of Philippine anthropology cutting across geographies, academic traditions, personalities, and historical periods. \nDisyembre 1\nSession Avenue\nKick off celebration of Philippine radio\'s 100th year \nCarillon Plaza\n7 p.m.\nIsang on-ground music at cultural event na kung saan magsasama-sama ang mga home grown talent ng UP. Itatampok ang iba\'t ibang indie bands, solo artists, spoken word artists, manunula at iba pa. Magkakaroon ng open mic jamming session kung saan maari ring magtanghal ang mga tagapanood. \nDisyembre 2\nParangal sa mga Guro at Kawani ng UPIS\nUPIS Gymnasium\n7 a.m. - 2 p.m.\nThe event is a day of honoring and fellowship between the past and present UP Integrated School (UPIS) faculty, staff, students and alumni. This year, aside from the thanksgiving program and the special tribute for the retired UPIS faculty members, there will be a wellness fair that features free consultations with medical practitioners, nutrition consultants, wellness experts, massage services, and other health and wellness booths. \nDisyembre 4-5\nGender Sensitivity Training para sa OVCAA\nSeminar Room\nUP Diliman Gender Office (UPDGO)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nNagpapatuloy ang Gender Sensitivity Training (GST) ng Office of the Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs ngayong Disyembre bilang pagtalima sa Memorandum No. MLT-17-188 na inilabas ng Opisina ng Tsanselor hinggil sa GST. Tatalakayin sa GST ang ibayong pagsulong ng karapatan at kagalingan ng lahat ng kasarian, at ang oryentasyon ng bagong Anti-Sexual Harassment Code ng Unibersidad ng Pilipinas. \nDisyembre 4-5\nProblems and Opportunities in Achieving Competitiveness \nA series of talks reflecting on the NIMBB curriculum for the next 30 years\nNIMBB, National Science Complex\nDisyembre 4, 9:30 a.m. - 12 p.m.\nDisyembre 5, 11:30 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nThe National Institute of Molecular Biology and Biotechnology (NIMBB) has been producing excellent talent over the last 30 years. What lies ahead for the next 30 years? This series of talks aims to identify the key strengths, weaknesses, opportunities and threats that could inform a new curriculum. Invited speakers include Dr. William Padolina, President of the National Academy of Science and Technology, Dr. Luis Sison of the UP Technology Transfer and Business Development Office; and Dr. Gonzalo Serafica, Entrepreneur and Consultant to the United States Agency for International Development - Science, Technology, Research and Innovation for Development (USAID STRIDE). \nDisyembre 5-8\nMandatory Continuing Legal Education (MCLE)\nUP Law Center\n8 a.m. \nContinuing legal education is required of members of the Integrated Bar of the Philippines (IBP) to ensure that throughout their career they keep abreast with law and jurisprudence, maintain the ethics of the profession and enhance the standards of the practice of law. The UP Institute for the Administration of Justice actually formulates and conducts MCLE for IBP members to hone their professional competence. \nDisyembre 5\nThe Rohingya Conundrum : Its Significance for International Studies\nSeminar Room, UP Asian Center\n2-4 p.m. \nThis lecture will focus on three fundamental issues : the Rohingya conundrum, possible solutions and its implications in international studies. The conflict between Rohingya, a Muslim minority in Rakhine state in western Myanmar (Burma), and the Rakhine Buddhists has been an international concern since 2012 when violence first erupted in recent years. The protracted violence is a threat not only to Myanmar\'s internal peace and stability but also for the country\'s relations with the international community, particularly its immediate neighbor Bangladesh and the Muslim-majority countries in Southeast Asia, such as Malaysia and Indonesia, that have expressed concerns over the Rohingyas\' treatment in the past. \nDisyembre 6-8\nModule D : Predictive Analysis\nNational Engineering Center (NEC)\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThis course surveys the different algorithms for data mining specifically : classification, regression, feature selection, association and clustering algorithms for business analytics. Learn to utilize a data warehouse and the various data mining algorithms to aid in business decisions. Learn concepts such as problem types, data structure requirements, over and under fitting, and how to evaluate a business analytics model. Advantages and disadvantages of methods are discussed. \nDisyembre 6-8\n15th Asian Symposium on Medicinal Plants, Spices and Other Natural Products 22nd Natural Products Society of the Philippines Convention\nIntel Center of Science Innovation \nUP National Institute of Physics\n8 a.m.\nASOMPS (Asian Symposium on Medicinal Plants and Spices) is a scientific meeting which aims to strengthen and promote collaboration and cooperation between Asian  scientists in the fields of chemistry, pharmacology, pharmacy, biochemistry, botany and biotechnology of natural products to improve regional research potential and infrastructure in the region. The first symposium (ASOMPS I) was held in Peshawar, Pakistan in 1960. It was in ASOMPS VII held in Manila in 1992 that the conference title was modified to Asian Symposium on Medicinal Plants, Spices and Other Natural Products which recognized the extent of biodiversity from which natural products can be further developed. \nDisyembre 6-8\nASEANnale 2017 : 1st Film and Multimedia Competition and Exhibition\n2nd International Symposium on ASEAN Studies\nUP Asian Center\nThe competition encourages ASEAN higher education students to produce creative works in film and multimedia that are the narratives of their culture and personal experiences. The competition also gives honor to filmmakers and multimedia producers whose creative storytelling explores a range of human experiences that echoes the festival\'s theme \"Capturing the spirit of ASEAN in the Digital Times.\" There are three sub-themes for the film and multimedia competition - Diaspora, Democracy and Disaster. \nDisyembre 7-9\nUnpacking Asia : Emerging Issues in Politics, Security, and Foreign Policy\nA forum and exhibit\nJapan Hall, UP Asian Center\n1-8:30 p.m. (forum, Dec. 7) \n8 a.m. - 6:30 p.m. (exhibit, Dec 8-9)\nThe forum aims to promote awareness of Asian politics, and build constructive and informed dialogue on the various issues, perspectives, and methods used by states, security practitioners and diplomats in dealing with emerging challenges of the region. Twenty-one graduate students of Prof. Aileen Baviera will present their research findings via posters. The poster presentations are grouped into three panels : Security issues in the Asia-Pacific; International Relations of Southeast Asia; and Emerging Issues in Asian International Relations. Various facets of ASEAN and China\'s expanding role in Southeast Asia will be tackled, as well as the role of digital technology and cyber security in the region\'s domestic and international politics. \nDisyembre 7-8\nHandel\'s Messiah\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium\n6:30 p.m. \nThe UP College of Music presents George Frideric Handel\'s \"Messiah.\"\nThe annual concert features UP Concert Chorus, UP Singing Ambassadors, UP ARCO, UP Cherubim and Seraphim, UP Staff Choral Society, Dawani Women\'s Choir, Musika Sophia, Afro Latin Ensemble, UP Orchestra, Villancico Vocal Ensemble, MUPC 1-10 Chorus Classes of Prof. Janet Aracama and Dr. Beverly Shangkuan Cheng. Featured soloists are : Ervin Lumauag, tenor; Avelino Guande, Baritone; Stefanie Quintin, soprano; and Kyle Tingzon, countertenor..\nDisyembre 8\nWork-Life Balance V (WLB V)\nConference Room, UP Diliman Gender Office (UPDGO)/Office of Anti-Sexual Harassment \n9 a.m. - 4 p.m. \nAng gawaing ito ay bilang pakikiisa sa 18-Day Campaign Against Violence Against Women. Layunin ng WLB V na itaguyod ang malay sa kasariang talastasan sa pamamagitan ng mga impormal na lunan para sa kaalaman at kamulatan tungkol sa iba\'t ibang isyung pangkasarian. Magkakaroon ng libreng hilot, meryenda at talakayan para sa mga mag-aaral, guro, kawani at REPS ng UPD. \nDisyembre 8\nBig Data for Development (BD4D)\nA public lecture by Sriganesh Lokanathan\nCase Room, UP National College of Public Administration and Governance (NCPAG)\n2-4 p.m. \nLokanathan will talk about the potentials and challenges of big data for development, sharing examples from LIRNEasia\'s researches in Sri Lanka and Bangladesh. He will cover a range of topics like modelling of disease propagation, transportation and traffic, socio-economic activity and wellbeing, land use mapping, data access, privacy, marginalization, capacity requirements, and government engagement. The event is a joint initiative of LIRNEasia and the Center for Local and Regional Governance of UP NCPAG.\nDisyembre 8 - Enero 27, 2018\nPlace of Region in the Contemporary \nInitial project of the Philippine Contemporary Art Network (PCAN)\nUP Vargas Museum\n6 p.m. (Opening reception) \nUP Vargas Museum opens the first project of the Philippine Contemporary Art Network built through three nodes in a network : Knowledge Production and Circulation; Exhibition and Curatorial Analysis; and Public Engagerment and Artistic Formation. The project endeavors to activate a network to coordinate a range of interventions in contemporary art in the Philippines and to cast a sharper profile for it on an inter-local and trans-regional scale. Place of Region in the Contemporary was made possible through the support of Sen. Loren Legarda. \nDisyembre 9\nUPIS General Alumni Homecoming 2017\nUPIS High School Grounds\n3 p.m. - 12 a.m. (Dec. 10)\nThe University of the Philippines Integrated School (UPIS) will be commemorating its 101st anniversary as the unified institution of the UP High School founded in 1916, the UP Elementary School in 1936 and the UP Preparatory School in 1954. The 101st Grand Alumni Homecoming will welcome back to the institution more than 1,000 alumni who will be treated to a fun celebration night led by the Golden Jubilarians - UP High and UP Prep Class of 1967 and hosted by Silver Jubilarians - UPIS Class of 1992. \nDisyembre 15\n\"UP Diliman : Paaralan, Palaruan\"\nUPD Parada ng mga Parol 2017\nAcademic Oval \n5 p.m.\nPaligsahan ito ng mga pinakamagandang parol ng mga administratibo at akademikong yunit ayon sa temang \"UP Diliman : Paaralan, Palaruan.\" Ipaparada ang mga parol paikot sa Academic Oval at magtatapos sa isang palatuntunan sa Amphitheater. Ito rin ay tatampukan ng fireworks display. \nDisyembre 15\nMaskipaps : The Crossover\nUP Sunken Garden\n9 p.m.\nIsang pangkomunidad na pagdiriwang ng UP sa pangunguna ng Beta Epsilon na gaganapin pagkatapos ng Lantern Parade. Magtatanghal sa nasabing music festival ang iba\'t ibang banda at mga disk jockey. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1090, 'E2-1090AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 1', '', '', 'Pebrero 2018', 'Pebrero 1, 8, 15 & 22\nTaludturan : Poetry of the Body\nPalma Hall Lobby, Melchor Hall Lobby, Shopping Center, CMC Lobby\n3 p.m.\nTaludturan : Poetry of the Body is a 4-part public performance project which includes dance, movement and performance pieces lasting for around 10 minutes in selected venues around the UP Campus every Thursday of February. Each part explores the embodiment of the encounter and engagement with beauty, love, desire, revolt and death. It will be part of Kat(h)awan : UP Diliman Festival of Culture and the Arts 2018. The title \"taludturan\" means \"stanza\" specifically of a poem but it also evokes the craft of verse-making, recitation (turan) and movement. Indeed, some of the performances were inspired by poetic texts about the body. The performance, however, need not be secondary to a text as it can be the act of writing the poem and the poem itself. \nPebrero 1\nGuangxi (Connections)\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium\n7:30 p.m.\nAs the final activity for the commemoration of National Artist for Music Jose Maceda\'s 100th birth year/centenary, a special concert highlighting Maceda\'s three works that cover his whole career as a composer will be staged. The closing concert will involve around 80 musicians from the UP College of Music and Guangxi Arts University Traditional Orchestra of Taiwan/China to present Maceda\'s music and learn from one another about the various musical traditions of Asia. \nIndie Pa \'Ko Ready III\nBarrel House, Arayat St., Diamond Subdivision \nBalibago, Angeles City, Pampanga\n6-9 p.m. \nThe event is an annual music gig that promotes Original Pilipino Music and the local indie scene. Presented by the UP Musician\'s Guild, \"Indie Pa \'Ko Ready III\" will feature Psychomanagement and Chinita Phenomemon from UP Clark; Binge, Forestille and Mt. Lewis PH from Angeles City; and Sleepersecond and Goodbye Yesterday Hello Today (GYHT) from Manila. \nPebrero 3 - Marso 31\nLiving Architecture with special projects by Junyee and Indy Paredes\n1F Galleries, Vargas Museum\nOpening reception : 3 p.m.\n\"Living Architecture\" raises awareness of the relationship between architecture and the natural, social and cultural life of which it is part and to stimulate the creation of buildings that support these life processes. The exhibition does so by presenting projects from all over the world, which consciously relate to nature and to all human needs and thereby bring this attitude to an artistic expression. The 2018 exhibition at the Vargas Museum commissioned by Iona Stichting Foundation (Netherlands) is expanded with the site-specific works of Filipino artists Junyee and Indy Paredes. \"Living Architecture\" is the main presentation of the 2018 Arkitektura Festival. \nPebrero 6-9\nWorkshop on Historical Demography : Preparing & Analyzing Archival Data\nUP Population Institute Seminar Room\n3/F Palma Hall\n8:30 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThis 4-day workshop aims to gather local and international researchers in an interdisciplinary conversation to address the practical issues and concerns in the study of the different population histories of Philippine localities. The primary aim is to orient and capacitate workshop participants with the theories, methodologies, historical sources and new techniques in digital technology towards the advancement of local historical demography. Another is to coordinate the different and disparate research efforts across organizations with the Population Institute of the UPD College of Social Sciences and Philosophy, providing institutional leadership to standardize the methods being applied in the different studies under the Social History of the Philippine Population Initiative. The workshop is supported by the UP Office of the Vice Chancellor for Research and Development, the UP Office of the Vice President for Academic Affairs and the Demographic Research and Development Foundation. \nPebrero 6\nMs. UP Clark 2018 Coronation Night \nTeresa Hall, Angeles City, Pampanga \n6-9 p.m.\n\"Ms. UP Clark 2018,\" formerly known as Mr. and Ms. UP, is an annual event hosted by the UP Association of Economics Students (AES) of UP Clark. This year\'s theme, \"Ethnic : Unravel the Beauty of the Past,\" aims to showcase the rich culture of our ethnic tribes and to encourage Filipinos to help in their preservation. Contestants will be working hand in hand with the contest organizers in implementing a project that will benefit the ethnic community. \nPebrero 9\nSeremonya ng Pagbubukas : Karanasan ng Kat(h)awan \nUP Amphitheater \n5:30 p.m.\nBilang panimula ng \"UP Diliman Festival of Culture and the Arts 2018,\" tatalakayin ang katawan bilang paksa ng iba\'t ibang diskurso tulad ng pagnanasa, kaluwalhatian, \"masculine,\" \"female\" at \"queer gaze\" sa pamamagitan ng mga sayaw, \"spoken word poetry,\" at dramatikong pagbasa ng katha ni Gilda Cordero-Fernando. Tampok sa palatuntunan sina Rochelle Pangilinan ng Sexbomb, Masculados Does, Kare Adea, Dzeli Del Mundo at Orlando Oribiana. \nPebrero 10\nAsian Culture Fest 2018\nPalma Hall Parking Lot\n9 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nThe UP Department of Linguistics, with the support of The Japan Foundation Manila, is holding the Asian Culture Fest 2018. The event aims to introduce Asian cultures to Asian language students and the general public through games, food, costumes, dance, and other activities. The Department\'s language classes and student organizations will each set up a booth. \nPebrero 11\nCOEXIST : Help Rebuild Libraries and Communities 2018 \nColor Buddy Fun Run\nUP Academic Oval (Start)/Melchor Hall Finish) 4:30 - 5 a.m. (Registration and Assembly) 6 a.m. (Start of run) A fundraising activity for the benefit of the UP College of Engineering Library\'s outreach program which would support the rehabilitation of war-torn libraries in Marawi City. It also intends to promote the Library\'s I Love My Library Campaign to raise awareness on the importance of involving the community within the libraries. \nPebrero 13-15\nISKOLOR : Iba-ibang Kulay, Lahat Pantay-pantay\nUPIS Days 2018\nUPIS 7-12 Building\n7 a.m. - 8 p.m. \nIto ang taunang school fair na naglalayong maitanghal ang husay at talento ng mga mag-aaral sa pamamagitan ng iba\'t ibang gawain, gayundin ang mapagtibay ang ugnayan ng bawat miyembro ng paaralan. Batay sa adbokasiya ng tema ng pagdiriwang ngayong taon, pagtutuunan ang nga kulay bilang simbolo ng pagkakaisa at pagrespeto sa kapwa sa kabila ng magkakaibang pinagmulan, kasarian, paniniwala, relihiyon at iba pang aspeto. Sa mga nagnanais dumalo at makibahagi, may fair tickets na maaaring mabili sa mga nakasaad na petsa.\nPebrero 13-28\n(Com)modified Bodies in the Philippines : An Installation Exhibit\nAsian Center\nThe indoor exhibit includes \"the history of the beautiful in the Philippines,\" mundane rituals of everyday life, body modifications in the country and documentary films on body technologies. As each portrait tells their personal story, the gallery contemplates on motivations, processes, and beliefs around modification of the human anatomy : physiological and physical. Body alterations test the body\'s natural boundaries of how much pain it can endure. Each person\'s submission to pain and eventually relish the pleasure of their transformation is overwhelmed by the desire to make the body malleable to the shape of the ideal self. While each portrait unpacks a particular narrative, their altered bodies also complicate and interrogate body aesthetics and identity making. \nPebrero 13\nThe Chemical Youth Project\n3 p.m. Conference\n6 p.m. Film showing\nBased on a research collaboration of the Department of Anthropology, UP Diliman and the University of Amsterdam, it focuses on body sites and body technologies where the body is perceived as the target of social engineering, advertising and marketing. The event features the launching of the ethnographic study on body technologies conducted in the port areas of Southern Luzon and Indonesia and the premiere of the documentary film \"Sweet Medicine.\"\nPebrero 13-17\nUP Fair 2018\nSa Tugtog Mo\'y Buhay\nUP Sunken Garden\n6 p.m.\nThe biggest annual student-initiated activity in UP Diliman, this year\'s theme is \"Highlighting Resilience of the Filipino Spirit Through Progressive Change.\" The fair is a 5-day musical feast featuring established and budding local bands. \nPebrero 14\nPanawagan para sa Papel\nIniimbitahan ng Kolehiyo ng Arte at Literatura (KAL) ang mga gradwadong mag-aaral ng kolehiyo na magpasa ng abstrak sa ika-3 KAL Kolokyum ng Gradwadong Mag-aaral na gaganapin sa Abr. 7, 2018. Malawak ang saklaw na paksa ng kolokyum at hinihikayat ang kontribusyon mula sa iba\'t ibang larangan ng pag-aaral sa arte at humanidades. Ang pangunahing layunin ng kolokyum ay maglaan ng lugar sa mga gradwadong mag-aaral ng KAL upang magtipun-tipon at makipagpalitan ng kaalaman at karanasan patungkol sa mga partikular na disiplina na interes at mas malawak na komunidad ng gradwadong mag-aaral ng kolehiyo. \nPebrero 15\nMoving care between Japan and The Philippines : Policy, Theory and Experience \nA Forum and Roundtable Discussion\nSeminar ROom, UP Asian Center\n12:30-4:30 p.m.\nThis will discuss the relation between migration, regarded as the most intense source of social, cultural and historical linkage between Japan and the Philippines; and care, as one of the key aspects through which recent labor and family migration between Japan and the Philippines may be examined. The forum-roundtable will gather and highlight various perspectives from academics, government officials, migration brorkers and non-governmental organizations in order to examine care as a cultural ideology, a social and migration policy and a framework for evaluating shifts (and continuities) in Japan-Philippine relations. Organized by UP Asian Center, it is free and open to the public, but seating is on a first-come, first-served basis. \nPebrero 15-Marso 17\nBeyond Myself\nExhibition on Filipino Migrants\' Investments in Philippine Futures\n3F Galleries, Vargas Museum\nOpening reception : 3 p.m.\nThis feature works by Natalie Dagmang, Guhit Kulay HK and migrant workers in Hong Kong through the Voices of Women Media, with cooperative efforts from Scalabrini Migration Center Philippines, University of Hong Kong and Keele University. Co-presented by the Curating Development program of Goldsmiths, University of London, this explores various understandings of the idea of value and investment in moving and shifting contexts : value of people, images, objects and money in trans-border contexts. Specifically, it draws on and curates visual images produced mainly through a series of participatory art workshops with Filipinos living and working in London and Hong Kong. \nPebrero 15\nUPD One Billion Rising 2018\nQuezon Hall\n3 - 6 p.m.\nBumangon, lumaban, magkaisa!\nMuling magsasama-sama ang komunidad ng UP Diliman para sa taunang kampanyang \"One Billion RIsing (OBR).\" Ang OBR ay ang pambansang kampanya para labanan ang karahasan, partikular sa mga kababaihan. Sa ikalimang taon ng OBR sa UP Diliman, tangan ng komunidad ang tema ng pagbangon, paglaban at pagkakaisa. Ang OBR ay hudyat ng bisperas ng Buwan ng Kababaihan. Iniimbitahan ng Diliman Gender Office na lumahok ang lahat ng mga mag-aaral, guro, REPS, kawaning administratibo, pati na rin ang iba pang organisasyon at sektor na nasa loob ng UP Campus. \nPebrero 17\n28th Rockstruck Battle of the Bands\nIhawash, Angeles City, Pampanga\n5 p.m.\nAn interschool battle of the bands held annually by the UP Psychology Society (PsychSoc), it gathers amateur bands from UP Clark and other universities in Central Luzon universities, mostly in Pampanga. Ten bands will battle it out, on a night of fun and rock and roll, with songs from the \'80s. Each band will play two songs : one song is in line with the theme and a song of their choice. Part of the proceeds will go to UP PsychSoc\'s outreach programs. \nPebrero 19-23\n2nd Training Course on Road Works Safety\nNational Center for Transportation Studies (NCTS) Building\n8 a.m.- 5 p.m.\nThe UP NCTS, in cooperation with the Department of Public Works and Highways, offers this to provide a uniform approach to worksite traffic management through the use of standard signs and layouts that can be applied the most road work situations. Target participants are municipal/city and transportation planners, municipal/city and traffic engineers, and local and national government personnel involved in transportation and related functions. This is open to the public on a first-come, first-served basis. \nPebrero 19\nPatalasan\nUPDEPP Campus, Clarkfield, Pampanga\n1-4 p.m. \nThe event is an annual inter high school quiz bee that aims to foster social awareness, teamwork and friendly competition among local high schools, and promote UP Diliman - Extension Program in Pampanga (UPDEPP) and its various degree programs to the brightest students in the region. Hosted by Sigma Kappa Pi Fraternity and Sigma Delta Pi Sorority UPDEPP Chapter, the quiz bee is open to the public. \nPebrero 20-23\nBodies in/and Asian Theatres\nConference 2018\nAsian Theatre Working Group\nGT-Toyota Auditorium \nUP Diliman\nOn the occasion of \"Kat(h)awan\" [a contraction of katha (creative creation) and katawan (body)] or the celebration of the UP Diliman Month 2018 vis-a-vis the National Arts Month in the Philippines, \"Bodies in/and Asian Theatres\" invokes the Asian bodies and creative and critical entities. The international conference is envisioned to contribute to the study of the body, particularly its functions and placements in the different performances in the Asian region. This is in context of its peoples\' experiences, colonization, decolonization and globalization, albeit different modalities. The event is organized by the Asian Theatre Working Group, International Federation for Theatre Research (IFTR), UP Diliman, UPD Office for Initiatives in Culture and the Arts, College of Arts and Letters, Asian Center, Department of Speech Communication and Theatre Arts, UP Diliman Information Office and UP Theater Complex. \nPebrero 21 - Marso 11\nAng Dalagita\'y \'sang Bagay na Di-buo\nWilfrido Ma. Guerrero Theater\n2/F Palma Hall\nWeekday (Wed-Fri) shows 7 p.m.\nWeekend shows 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. \nDulaang UP brings to the Philippine stage Eimear McBride\'s haunting novel \"A Girl is a Half-formed Thing\" (Goldsmith Prize Award 2013) billed as \"Ang Dalagita\'y \'sang Bagay Na Di-Buo.\" Translated by Rody Vera, the play is based on Annie Ryan\'s stage adaptation of the critically-acclaimed novel, originally staged by The Corn Exchange Theatre Company in 2014. \"Ang Dalagita\'y \'sang Bagay Na Di-buo\" tells in fragmented, poetic and partly ambiguous language, the tragic life of a Girl, who has been repeatedly abused by her uncle, who loses her beloved brother, grapples with the wicked religiosity of her mother and increasingly finds herself in that corner of her life where no option is left. \"Ang Dalagita\'y \'sang Bagay na Di-buo\" is a harrowing piece that lays bare in no delicate terms, the appalling iniquity of sexual abuse and power. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1091, 'E2-1091AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 3 (3 copies)', '', '', 'Abril 2018', 'Abril 10\nLa Fashionista \nNature Couture : Connecting with nature to change the future\nTeresa Hall, Uni-chef\'s Catering\nAngeles City, Pampanga\n6 - 9 p.m.\nLa Fashionista is the annual fashion competition of the UP Clark Business Management Society where students can explore their talents infashion. This year\'s La Fashionista is about nature-based designs that are environment-friendly and promote connectivity and awareness to save the planet. Competing student designers will have their clothes modeled by their fellow students. \nAbril 11-13\nWorker\'s Institute on Labor Laws (WILL) Class 171\nIsabelo Delos Reyes Auditorium\nUP School of Labor and Industrial Relations (SOLAIR)\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe seminar will enable the participants to : acquire basic knowledge about labor laws and legislation of the country; apply the legal processes and techniques in their respective workplaces; and understand and share experiences and practices involving labor laws and industrial relations. \nAbril 11 - Mayo 14\nLawas\nSite-specific Installation Exhibit\nLawas is about three site-specific installations that examine representations of the body and shifting modes of perception. Featured artists are Agnes Arellano, Lee Paje and Mark Justiniani. Arellano\'s \"Project Pleiades 2,\" cast stone goddesses, four of seven of the open star cluster most visible to the naked eye at night will be situated in an area between UP Vargas Museum and UP Faculty Center; while Paje\'s \"Pagpamulak,\" stylized sculptures meant to mimic the body\'s intimate parts will be installed at the corner of Roxas Avenue and TM Kalaw St., Justiniani\'s \"Oasis\" is a structure likened to a navel, an invisible umbilical cord between heaven and earth. It will be constructed at the UP Lagoon area across UP Faculty Center. \nAbril 12\nUnderstanding population heterogeneity in demographic and human capital dynamics : How does population heterogeneity matter for the future population outlook? A public lecture by Dr. Samir K.C.\nPalma Hall Room 1314-1316\n10 a.m. - 12 p.m. \nAge and gender differentials are the two fundamental sources of population heterogeneity within a country that are considered in almost all demographic analysis. Recent researches demonstrated the importance of education (attainment) as a third significant source of population heterogeneity. Based on a series of publications and modeling studies, Dr. Samir K.C. and colleagues have also shown the significance of place of residence (urban or rural) and administrative regions as important sources of observable population heterogeneity. Samir K.C. is a professor and leader at the Human Capital and Development Pillar at the Asian Demographic Research Institute, Shanghai University, China. \nAbril 12-14\nISKOPRENEUR 2018\nUP Diliman Extension Program in Pampanga (UPDEPP) Clarkfield, Pampanga\n\"Iskopreneur,\" an annual bazaar organized by the Business Management seniors of UPDEPP, aims to develop the entrepreneurial skills of the students through the application of business management concepts in manning a physical store in a bazaar setting. This year\'s theme is \"Iskoprenotes : Playing a Harmonious Rhythm of Unity in Diversity.\" The students will embody the characteristics of the diverse genre of music through their costumes and booth aesthetics. The theme intends to send a message of \"unity in diversity.\" Despite of the divisiveness in race, culture, religion, gender and sexual orientation, people can work together towards one goal. The 3-day event will be filled with fun activities such as quiz bees, concerts and various competitions related to music. The event is open to the public. \nAbril 16 - 20\nInclusive Tourism in the City\nRoom 203, UP School of Labor and Industrial Relations (SOLAIR)\n8:30 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe 5-day workshop focuses on exploring the potential and challenges of inclusive development in tourism. It also aims to share ideas across a wide-range of disciplinary perspectives. Thematic discussions per day covers perspectives on : community and urban space; human rights and employment; culture; marginalized community; and the future. The workshop is a collaborative effort between the University of Strathclyde (United Kingdom) and UP Asian Institute of Tourism, together with the College of Social Sciences and Philosophy, College of Social Work and Community Development, SOLAIR and School of Urban Planning and Development. \nAbril 17\nMusika ng mga Filipino sa Radyo sa Panahon ng Kolonyalismong Amerikano \nA public lecture-concert of Prof. Elizabeth L. Enriquez\nTelevision Studio B, Media Center \nCollege of Mass Communication\n6-8 p.m.\nNaging mahalagang kasangkapan ang radyo upang mapalaganap ng mga Amerikano ang wikang Ingles at musikang kanluranin noong panahon ng kolonyalismong Amerikano sa Pilipinas. Ngunit nang buksan nila ang mga unang himpilan ng radyo sa bansa noong dekada 1920 at 1930, kinailangan nila ang mga mang-aawit at musikerong Filipino upang awitin at tugtugin ang mga himig nila sa himpapawid. Ito ang naging daan upang maisingit ng mga Filipino ang sariling awit at maging ang sariling wika sa kanilang mga programa sa radyo. Kaya bagama\'t naging popular ang jazz at iba pang banyagang musika sa pamamagitan ng radyo, pumailanlang rin ang kundiman at iba pang musikang maituturing na sariling atin, at maging mga bagong himig Filipino na may bahid ng kanluraning musika. May mag pagkakataon na sumahimpapawid ang ilang awiting taglay ang paglaban sa kolonyal na kondisyon. \nAbril 26 - 28\nTraffic Management Course for Traffic Law Enforcers (Level 1) \nNational Center for Transportation Studies (NCTS) Building\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe course provides training for personnel who are required to enforce traffic laws and regulations, allows enforcers to understand their role as a traffic enforcer and understand the different laws and regulations they are going to enforce. The program also covers the standard traffic signs and pavement markings - their meaning, and when and where to install them. Enforcers are also taught how to direct and control traffic in an intersection; administer traffic citation ticket and investigation; and recording and reporting of traffic incident. Target participants are traffic law enforcers and private traffic crash investigators, engineers, lawyers, safety officers and local and national government personnel involved in traffic management. Minimum degree requirement for participants is college level. \nAbril 27\nUniversity Student Council (USC) Elections / Halalan UPD 2018\nHalalanUPD2018 is the selection of leaders of elective positions in the University Student Council (USC). The elections aims to uphold the autonomous, democratic and representative character of the USC. The University Student Electoral Board is composed of the Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs as ex-officio Chairperson, two faculty members and two students. \nAbril 30\n13th Philippine Linguistics Congress Call for Abstracts\nThe Philippine Linguistics Congress focuses on the most current advances in the study of Philippine languages, and on the application of linguistic theory to other disciplines in the Philippines. The conference also looks into contemporary studies between Philippine languages and foreign languages. Abstracts dealing with theoretical, applied or experimental linguistic study on any Philippine languages are invited for presentation at the conference. Other topics include but are not limited to : Structural linguistics; Diachronic linguistics; Dialectology and Typology; Language documentation; Language education and learning; Language planning; Sociolinguistics; Psycholinguistics; Ethnolinguistics; Translation studies; Lexicography; Clinical linguistics; and Philosophy of language. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1092, 'E2-1092AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 5 (2 copies)', '', '', 'Hunyo 2018', 'Hunyo 1, 4-8\nFAMAS Rising at Cine Adarna\nYear\'s best with the country\'s oldest existing award-giving body\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n2:30 p.m., 5 p.m. and 7:30 p.m.\nThe UP Film Institute presents a selection of full-length, short and documentary features nominated for the Filipino Academy of Movie Arts and Sciences (FAMAS) Awards in time for the 66th Gabi ng Parangal honors night to be held on June 10 at The Theater, Solaire. \nHunyo 2 - Agosto 9\nParalegal Training Program\n14th Foundation Course\nMalcolm Hall\nTuesdays and Thursdays (5-8 p.m.)\nSaturdays (9 a.m.- 12 p.m.)\nThe Paralegal Training Program is an extension service and training program of the UP Law Center which aims to lay the foundation for the development and professionalization of paralegal work in the country. The Program was designed to provide participants with basic and practical knowledge of substantial legal concepts pertaining to government; the judicial system; civil, criminal and quasi-judicial procedure; jurisdiction of local government units; ethical standards of judges, lawyers and civil servants; and the rules, regulation and procedures of various administrative agencies. \nHunyo 2\nWorld Bicycle Day\n\"REQUITED\" Screenings\nCelebrating the first World Bicycle Day at the UPFI Film Center\nVideotheque, UPFI Film Center\n1 p.m., 3 p.m. and 5:30 p.m. \nIn celebration of the first official International World Bicycle Day this coming June 3, the UP Film Institute is screening \"Requited\" directed by Nerissa Picadizo. The film aims to put a spotlight on the long-distance biking culture of our country as seen through the characters of Matt (Jake Cuenca) and Sandy (Anna Luna) as they travel from Manila to majestic locations like Mt. Pinatubo Lake, Monasterio de Tarlac and Capas National Shrine. There will be a Q&A session with the director after every screening. \nHunyo 4 - 15\nDOST PHIL-LIDAR 1 Program and DILG LiDAR - GIS and Flood Disaster Management Training for Local Government Units (LGUs)\nGeodetic Engineering Theater, 4th Floor, Melchor Hall\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG) and the Department of Science and Technology (DOST) tapped the Phil-LIDAR Program to disseminate Light Detection and Ranging (LiDAR) products and to utilize and apply knowledge on open source geospatial processing tools, and come up with effective local government plans to more municipalities. Selected LGUs were asked to send representatives from their local DILG, Planning, Disaster Risk Reduction and Management (DRRM) and Engineering Offices. DOST and DILG Regional Offices were also invited. Covering 17 regions of the country, the training aims to expand the reach and power of GIS and LiDAR products in developing more proactive and responsive DRRM plans for the LGUs. \nHunyo 4 - 8\nTEC 2018\nTeaching Effectiveness Courses\nTeodoro Room, 3rd Floor, UP ISSI\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe TEC is a 5-day (40 hours) experiental course organized by the Office of the Advancement for Teaching (under the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs) leading to the design, development, try-out and revision of teaching plans. The activities are highly structured and cumulatively sequenced to achieve the intended learning outcomes (e.g., design of an effective teaching plan). The course is open to regular faculty, lecturers, teaching assistants and teaching fellows. Priority is given to new faculty members but more experienced faculty members who wish to be updated on teaching approaches may also join. The course is free of charge but pre-registration is required. Last minute/walk-in participants will not be entertained. \nHunyo 7\nRefugees and Immigration in the US\nPublic lectures by Dr. Claire Angelique Nolasco and Dr. Daniel Braaten\nRoom 207, Palma Hall\n9 a.m. - 12 p.m. \nAs the world faces a global refugee crisis and political debates take place over levels of immigration and immigration policy, two public lectures on refugees and immigration in the United States (US) are co-organized by the UP Department of Political Science and the UP Center for Integrative and Development Studies (CIDS) Program on Social and Political Change. Nolasco\'s lecture gives an analysis of US federal court jurisprudence to determine the legal rights of unaccompanied alien children in various stages of immigration enforcement proceedings. The lecture by Braaten explores how state capacity, state politics and the religious composition of federal states explain refugee resettlement patterns within the US. \nHunyo 13\nPerformance : Daloy Dance Company\nA collateral event in line with Lawas Public Art\nVargas Museum grounds (near CAL Lawn)\n6 p.m.\nDancers wearing animal masks will follow a trail around Agnes Arellano\'s work Pleiades through dance movements. Led by artistic director Ea Torrado, this performance by Daloy Dance Company is a collateral event in line with Lawas Public Art. This event is free to the public. Lawas is the public art component of the UP Diliman Festival of Culture and the Arts 2018. It features the works of Agnes Arellano, Mark Justiniani and Lee Paje at the CAL Lawn, Lagoon and Vargas Museum Sculpture Garden, respectively. Lawas may be viewed until August 2018. \nHunyo 14\nPagtatapos 2018\nUP Film Center\n2 p.m.\nAng UP Integrated School (UPIS) ay magdiriwang ng Pagtatapos 2018 na may temang \"Iskong Mahal ang Bayan, Manindigan para sa Katotohanan.\" Sa seremonyang ito, kikilalanin ang mga unang mag-aaral ng UPIS na magsisipagtapos sa ilalim ng K-12 Program ng Department of Education. \nHunyo 20\nAGHAMBAYAN\nA DOST-UP Science and Technology and Innovation Festival \nPhilippine International Convention Center, Pasay City\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nAGHAMBAYAN celebrates the scientific projects and accomplishments of the University of the Philippines (UP) that impact the seemingly ordinary challenges of daily living. The Department of Science and Technology (DOST) supports UP in these endeavors. Through this festival, UP and DOST hope to raise public awareness of the vaue of science and its role in improving the quality of life of ordinary Filipinos. There will be an exhibition of scientific works classified into four clusters : health and well-being, environment, food, and human resource and job creation. There will also be a conference with short panel discussions and breakout sessions that would expound on the policy implications, utilization and uses of scientific research and innovations that benefit the public. \nHunyo 21-22\nMicrosoft Excel Training : Intermediate Training Course\nCSRC Computer Lab 1 \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe UP Computational Science Research Center (CSRC) is conducting a two-day training on Microsoft Excel. Target participants are those who want to familiarize themselves with  Excel\'s terminology, screen components and most used functions, which are beneficial in making reports. \nHunyo 24\nIka-107 Pangkalahatang Pagtatapos\nUP Amphitheater\n7 a.m. \nSa taunang Pangkalahatang Pagtatapos, iginagawad ng Unibersidad ang titulo sa mga mag-aaral na nagtapos ng kani-kanilang programa sa di-gradwado at gradwadong antas. Ito ay iba pa sa mga pagtatapos na isinasagawa ng bawat kolehiyo o linangan ng UP Diliman. Ang tema sa taong ito ay \"Paglayang Minamahal.\" Ang pangunahing tagapagsalita ay si Senator Loren Legarda ng gagawaran ng titulong Doktor ng Batas (honoris causa). Ito ang ikaapat na pagkakataon na gagawin ang Pagtatapos sa buwan ng Hunyo mula ng ilipat ang pagsisimula ng pasukan sa Agosto noong 2014. \nHunyo 29\nChopin : Before and Beyond\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium\n7 p.m. \nFeaturing international concert pianist Albert Tiu in an evening of Chopin classics, the concert is the last offering of the Abelardo Hall Concert Series 1 of the UP College of Music. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
