(1093, 'E2-1093AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 6 (6 copies)', '', '', 'Hulyo 2018', 'Hulyo 2, 6-7\nFAMAS Rising at Cine Adarna\nYear\'s best with the country\'s oldest existing award-giving body\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n2:30, 5 and 7 p.m. \nThe UP Film Institute presents an extended screening of short and documentary features nominated for the 2018 Filipino Academy of Movie Arts and Sciences (FAMAS) Awards led by eventual winners : Best Documentary Film \"Yield\" directed by Victor Delotavo Tagaro and Toshihiko Uriu, Best Short Film \"Hilom\" by P.R. Patindol, and joint winners of the Grand Jury Prize for Short Films \"Aliens Ata\" directed by Glenn Barit and \"Dory\" by Beverly Ramos. FAMAS is an organization of prize-winning writers and movie columnists established in 1952. It is the oldest existing film industry award-giving body in the Philippines. \nHulyo 3 at 16\nIran\'s Film Festival\nVideotheque, UPFI FIlm Center\n1:30, 4 p.m. and 6:30 p.m.\nThe Cultural Section, Embassy of the Islamic Republic of Iran-Manila in partnership with the UP Film Institute proudly presents Iran\'s FIlm Festival. \nHulyo 3 - 27\nTumba Tumba Children\'s Museum of Philippine Art\nCANVAS - The Center for Art, New Ventures, and Sustainable Development\n1F and 3F Galleries, UP Vargas Museum \nTue - Sat, 9 a.m. - 5 p.m. except holidays\nThe exhibit is CANVAS\' proof of concept that transforms the Vargas Museum into a study of an actual operating children\'s museum complete with a museum shop. Three new CANVAS books for children, two of which written by Genaro Gojo Cruz and Eugene Evasco, were unveiled through the art of Arvi, Fetalvero, Jared Yokte and Jojo Barja. \"Abubot,\" a special show, features art works by Aze Ong, Sergio Bumatay III, Art Sanchez, Renz Baluyot, Liza Flores and more. Interactive installations by Elmer Borlongan, Pam Yan Santos and Daniel dela Cruz, two murals by Archie Oclos and a rainbow installation and a scale model presentation of the future site of the children\'s museum by the architectural firm Arkisens are also showcase in the exhibition. \nHulyo 3-27\nBridges : Marianao Ponce & Jorge Vargas\nIn cooperation with Museo ng Baliwag\n3F Sensorium, UP Vargas Museum \nTue-Sat, 9 a.m. - 5 p.m. except holidays\nThe exhibition explores the political roles of the two diplomats, Mariano Ponce and Jorge Vargas, during tumultuous times as the Philippines built its sense of nationhood and sought its independence in light of different forces amidst newly established governments. The exhibit engages the audience through its interactive and tactile activities in order to draw the youth to the relevance of history and the creation of a collective identity. This exhibition is part of the year-long programs of the Municipality of Baliwag and Museo ng Baliwag for the 100th Death Anniversary of Mariano Ponce. \nHulyo 5\nCineManunuri Film Festival\nVideotheque, UPFI Film Center\n1:30 and 4 p.m.\nManunuri ng Pelikulang Pilipino, Cinema Centenario together with the UP Film Institute present a selection of nominated and awarded films of the 41st Gawad Urian Awards. Featured at the Videotheque are the following : 1:30 p.m. \"Sorry for the Inconvenience\" directed by Carl Adrian Chavez, \"Gikan sa Ngitngit Nga Kinailadman\" by Kiri Dalena, \"Empyreus\" by Dennis Hubag, \"Redempsyon\" by Edmund Telmo and \"Caramel Child\" by Kim Timan; 4 p.m. \"Han-ayan\" by JL Burgos. \nHulyo 9\nBurning Issues in Korea, China, and Malaysia : Alternatives and Prospects for People\'s Movements \nUP CIDS Conference Hall, Lower Ground Floor\nAng Bahay ng Alumni\n1:30 - 5 p.m. \nThe event will examine current burning issues in Asia such as the Belt and Road Initiative, Chinese President XI Jinping\'s expanded powers, the US-North Korea summit and denuclearization in the Korean Peninsula and the return of Mahathir as Malaysia\'s leader. The discussion will be led by Asian Regional Exchange for New Alternatives (ARENA) fellows Lee Jung Ok, Ph.D. (Catholic University of Daegu, South Korea), Lau Kin Chi, Ph. D. (Lingnan University, Hong Kong), Margaret Jade Sit Tsui, Ph.D. (Southwest University, Chongqing, People\'s Republic of China) and Andrew Aeria, Ph.D. (Universiti Malaysia Sarawak, Malaysia). \nHulyo 16 - Agosto 11\nLinescapes : Aesthesizing Chaos of Urban Infrastructure\nMFA degree exhibition by Annie Dennise Pacaña Lumbao\nBulwagan ng Dangal, University Heritage Museum\n6 p.m. (opening)\nLinescapes is an MFA degree show that explores one\'s urban experience through art, technology, contemporary dance and counter-cartography. Here, the city and its chaos are expressed through photography, line drawing, moving image and new media, mapping connectivity. An introductory event is set on July 3 to 5, from 6 to 9 p.m. where a projection+performance entitled \"Waiting\" will be held at the UP Gateway commuter shed along the University Avenue. A Lost Frames screening+talk is also scheduled on August 10 at the Bulwagan ng Dangal at 3 p.m., coinciding with the artist\'s talk. \nHulyo 17-20, 23-28 at 30-31\nTOFARM Film Festival\nVideotheque, UPFI Film Center\n1:30, 4 and 6:30 p.m.\nThe UP Film Institute presents the full showcase of features from the first (2016) and last year\'s edition of the TOFARM Film Festival, the only advocacy-driven film festival in the country today, with entries showcasing the lives, journeys, trials and triumphs of the Filipino farmer. The first edition\'s line-up include \"Free Range\" directed by Dennis Marasigan, \"Kakampi\" by Vic Acedillo Jr., \"Pauwi Na\" by Paolo Villaluna, \"Paglipay\" by Zig Dulay, \"Pilapil\" by Johnny Nadela and \"Pitong Kabang Palay\" by Mariel Cariaga. The 2017 edition is comprised of \"Baklad\" by Topel Lee, \"High Tide\" by Tara Illenberger, \"Instalado\" by Jason Paul Laxamana, \"Kamunggai\" by Vic Acedillo Jr., \"Sinandomeng\" by Byron Bryant and \"What Home Feels Like\" by Joseph Abello.\nHulyo 20, 28; Agosto 4, 11, 18\nDigital Video Production Workshop\nUPFI Media Center Bldg. Film Studio \n1-6 p.m.\nTo be facilitated by award-winning director Milo Paz, the short course will discuss and apply pre-production, production and post-production management as well as the technical and creative functions of a digital video production crew. Paz\'s documentaries and short features were all recipients of the Gawad CCP para sa Alternatibong Video at Pelikula. He previously worked as an executive producer and director for GMA 7 and now regularly produces videos for NGOSs, government agencies and private institutions on important issues and advocacies. \nHulyo 28; Agosto 4, 11, 18 (4 na Sabado)\nFilm Acting Workshop\nUPFI Media Center Bldg. Room B4 \n1-6 p.m.\nThe course is designed to equip workshop participants with a fundamental understanding of the art of acting as applied to digital material such as film, TV, commercials and other digital content. The workshop is to be facilitated by TV and film character actor Rolando Inocencio. He teaches theater and film subjects at the Meridian International College and conducts workshops for Octoarts and Regal Films, among others. He has taken acting workshops under Ana Valdes-Lim, Noa Rotem, Kiara Pipino (Michael Chekov), John Maloney (Viewpoints) and Ron Burrows of Stella Adler Studio. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1094, 'E2-1094AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 7 (6 copies)', '', '', 'Agosto 2018', 'Agosto 1 at 2 \nAll Features from TOFARM Film Festival\nFull showcase from the festival\'s year 1 and 2 editions\nVideotheque, UPFI Film Center \nThe UP Film Institute (UPFI) presents the full showcase of features from the first (2016) and last year\'s edition of the TOFARM Film Festival, the only advocacy-driven film festival in the country today, with entries showcasing the lives, journeys, trials and triumphs of the Filipino farmer.\nAgosto 3\nFrancesco Conte\'s \"Filipinos in the Eyes of an Italian\"\nPanel discussion, project presentation, film screening and open forum on Filipino migrant workers in Italy\nConference Hall\nUP Center for Integrative and Development Studies (CIDS)\n2 p.m. \nIn this project, Francesco Conte depicts an in-depth portrait of Filipinos in Italy. The interviews in the film focused on Pinoys answering questions about what pushed them to move abroad and the challenges and fulfillments of living in Italy. This project will also contextualize and discuss the situation of Filipinos in Italy. \nAgosto 3 at 4\nSchool Opening Special with Slashed-Price Admission \nVideotheque, UPFI Film Center\nEnjoy full-length films at half the usual price at the campus cinema. Featured are the following : action-drama-historical Cinco De Mayo (La Batalla) directed by Rafa Lara; suspense-thriller Backstabbing for Beginners directed by Per Fly; and suspense-horror June directed by L. Gustavo Cooper. \nAgosto 4 - Oktubre 20 (12 Sabado)\nManagement Development Program\nIsabelo Delos Reyes Auditorium\nSchool of Labor and Industrial Relations (SOLAIR)\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe program is a short and comprehensive course to learn basic managerial and leadership skills in the application of technologies in management of organizations and enterprises. It is designed for cooperatives, non-government organizations, trade unions and similar organization like small and medium enterprises. \nAgosto 6-10\nTraining Course on Road Works Safety\nToyota Training Room, UP NCTS Building \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe UP National Center for Transportation Studies (NCTS), in cooperation with the Department of Public Works and Highways (DPWH), will offer Road Works Safety Course to provide a uniform approach to worksite traffic management by using the Road Works Safety Manual developed by DPWH. The program will train the participants to be competent in planning, organizing, directing and managing the flow of traffic through road works with the minimum delay and risk to other users. \nAgosto 7\nLinguistics Month 2018\nIn celebration of its 96th founding anniversary, the UP Department of Lingustics has prepared a roster of activities for the whole month of August that will showcase current research on the burning issues in Philippine languages and linguistics. The month-long celebration will kick off with a Department Welcome Assembly on Aug. 7, to be attended by Linguistics freshies, as well as new shiftee and transferee students. The annual Student Research Colloquium and Faculty Research Colloquium will be held on Aug. 14 and Aug. 17, respectively. On Aug. 18, the Department will hold the Asian Culture Fest, which will highlight the textile traditions of ethnolinguistic groups in the Philippines and in other Asian countries. The second installment of the Nanay Talks has invited experts that would talk about raising multilingual children, and will happen on Aug. 23. The Linguistics Month 2018 will conclude via the relaunch of The Archive, the Department\'s journal devoted to the study of Philippine languages and dialects, which will happen on Aug. 25. \nAgosto 8\nBook Launching of \'Twentieth Century Philippine Political Thinkers : Selected Readings\' Edited by Jorge V. Tigno\n2nd floor lobby, Palma Hall\n3 p.m. \nThe book is a collection of readings from 13 Filipino political thinkers of the 20th century. The thinkers include Maximo M. Kalaw, Onofre D. Corpuz, Pura Villanueva Kalaw, Ricardo R. Pascual, Remigio E. Agpalo, Felipe Agoncillo, Pedro L. Baldoria, Estrella D. Solidum, Jose P. Laurel, Renato Constantino, Claro M. Recto, Cesar A. Majul and Jose Maria Sison. A short essay written by Department of Political Science fauclty members introduces each thinker and reading. The contributors are Athena Lydia Casambre, Miriam Coronel-Ferrer, Perlita M. Frago-Marasigan, Jan Robert R. Go, Herman Joseph S. Kraft, Ruth Lusterio-Rico, Jaime B. Naval, Jalton G. Taguibao, Jorge V. Tigno and Jean Paul L. Zialcita. \nAgosto 10 at 11\nIAM4ME Digital Summit and Festival\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\nThe event aims to gather students of mass communication, media, arts, marketing, educaiton and psychology. The activities are : Digital Intelligence Summit (with digital citizenship, privacy management and digital footprint, critical thinking and fake new discernment, cyberbullying and digital empathy as topics); Screenings of advocacy movies; and YAEEHA DEMIC Awards (starting at 7:30 a.m.) on Aug. 11) to give recognition to exemplar digital educators, mentors, influencers and content. \nAgosto 10 - Oktubre 6\nTies of History : Art in Southeast Asia\nVargas Museum (UP Diliman), Metropolitan Museum of Manila and Yuchengco Museum (Makati City) \n5-9 p.m. (Opening Reception) \nThe Philippines organizes an exhibition of contemporary art in Southeast Asia in Manila to mark the 50th year of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN). The exhibit gathers 10 artists to represent the member-states of the organization. Taken from the ASEAN Declaration in 1967, the phrase \"ties of history\" may allude to the blessings and burdens of being together and being different in a region that is thought to be shared. The exhibition opens on Aug. 8 (Metropolitan Museum of Manila), Aug. 9 (Yuchengco Museum) and Aug. 10 (Vargas Museum) and will run until Oct. 6. The project is presented by the National Commission for Culture and the Arts through the Dalubhasaan Para sa Edukasyon sa Sining at Kultura with the support of the Office of Senator Loren Legarda. \nAgosto 14\nStudent Research Colloquium\nPalma Hall AVR (PH 207) \n1-4 p.m.\nThe colloquium is an annual Department event that aims to provide a venue for undergraduate and graduate students to share the results of their research while in their respective programs. For this year, the Colloquium will showcase the research projects of students in Linguistics 125 [Introduction to Field Methods] and Linguistics 225 [Field Methods in Linguistics], who did their fieldwork in the different ethnolinguistic communities in Baguio City during Midyea 2018. A multimedia exhibit that documents the field activities of the classes will also be launched. The Student Research Colloquium is part of the month-long celebration of Linguistics Month 2018, commemorating the Department\'s 96th founding anniversary. The event is free and open to the public.  \nAgosto 15\nApplication deadline : Gemino H. Abad Seminar-Workshop on Teaching Literature \nTraining teachers in junior and senior high school in discussing literary texts that are now being used in textbooks for our classrooms\nThe seminar-workshop aims to help establish a more standardized basis for literary discussion and analysis, as well as in choosing which works in both English and Filipino are most appropriate for inclusion in the school textbooks. In a bigger sense, the seminar-workshop aims to aid teachers in better educating the K-12 junior and senior high school students. The free 3-day workshop will be on Sept. 20-22, 2018. \nAgosto 15-18\nJapanese Film Festival at UP Film Institute\nEIGASAI 2018 : A Celebration of Collaboration and Diversity!\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n12:30 p.m., 2:45 p.m., 5 p.m. and 7:15 p.m.\nNow on its 21st edition, the Japanese Film Festival in the Philippines presented by The Japan Foundation, Manila in partnership with the UP Film Institute (UPFI), will showcase full-feature films of diverse genres selected for more than 100 screenings across five major cities nationwide. Films to be screened include : Chihayafuru Part 1-3, Tori Girl, When the Curtain Rises, Tora-san of Goto, Honnouji Hoterl, Of Love & Law, Survival Family, ReLIFE, Memoirs of a Murderer, Rudolf the Black cat, Let\'s Go, JETS! from Small Town Girls to U.S. Champions?! and Seven Samurai. \nAgosto 17\n\"Talastasan sa Kasaysayan : Ang Pampublikong Kasaysayan at Kamalayang Pangkasaysayan.\"\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe one-day conference on public history is in congruence with this year\'s History Month celebration with an overall theme \"Kasaysayan : Tuklasin, Mahalin, Palaganapin.\' Recognizing public history as an emerging field in the discipline, the conference primarily aims to provide an avenue for sharing and updating of knowledge on public history and its importance. Meanwhile, the more specific objectives are the following : to conduct a preliminary assessment of the state of public history in the Philippines; to identify the significance of public history in raising historical awareness and consciousness; and to understand the role of the public history in nation-building and in the fight against negative historical revisionism and disinformation. Aside from holding a one-day public history conference, other major events include the launch of the UP Department of History\'s website and a walking history tour (Lakad-Gunita). A forum on Martial Law will highlight this year\'s celebration of History Month (Buwan ng Kasaysayan 2018). \nAgosto 17\nFaculty Research Colloquium\nPalma Hall AVR (PH 207) \nThe annual Faculty Research Colloquium serves as a platform for the members of the faculty to share with the wider public their current research on Philippine languages. It aims to establish and strengthen networks of scholars of lingustics as well as other disciplines to improve their papers or form new research projects in Philippine languages and cultures. This year, the Department will showcase linguistic papers presented during the recently held Southeast Asian Linguistics Society Conference in Taiwan. The Faculty Research Colloquium is part of the month-long celebration of Linguistics Month 2018, commemorating the Department\'s 96th founding anniversary. \nAgosto 18\nAsian Culture Fest\nPalma Hall AVR (PH 207) \n9 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nAs part of their celebration of the Linguistics Month 2018, the Department will hold the Asian Culture Fest. The festival is an annual event showcasing the cultures of the different ethnolinguistic groups in the Philippines as well as the other Asian countries. This year\'s installment of the festival focuses on Philippine and Asian textile traditions. The main speakers for the event are Professor Emeritus Norma A. Respicio and Dr. Marilyn R. Canta. Respicio will talk about shared textile cultures among Philippine ethnolinguistic groups, while Canta will deliver a lecture on the connection between India and the Philippines in terms of textile tradition. Other invited exhibitors from Japan, Korea, Indonesia and organizations in the country that create indigenous woven products will also participate in the whole-day festival. \nAgosto 18\n2018 U.P. General Alumni Homecoming\n\"Mga Haligi ng Lahi\" \nAng Bahay ng Alumni\n3 p.m.\nThe UP Alumni Association (UPAA) will honor Distinguished Alumni Awardees as shining examples of \"Mga Haligi ng Lahi\" for having best exemplified the national university\'s ideals of service, excellence and leadership - with their outstanding accomplishments and services rendered to their communities and the nation which have brought glory to the Alma Mater. The homecoming will likewise feature the Jubilarians - members of Class 1958 (Diamond), Class of 1968 (Golden), Class of 1978 (Ruby), and Class of 1993 (Silver), who are preparing colorful and entertaining presentations. \nAgosto 20 at Setyembre 3\n2018 Orientation for New UP Diliman Faculty\nNational Center for Transportation Studies (NCTS) Toyota Room \n8 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nThe Office of the Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs (OVCAA), with the Office for the Advancement of Teaching (OAT), will be conducting an orientation program, which will cover academic and administrative policies and programs that UP Diliman faculty need to familiarize themselves with. While priority is given to new faculty members, other faculty members and faculty teaching associate/teaching fellows could be accomodated depending on the availability of slots. OAT, the coordinating office for the event, is requesting academic units to please send the list of suggested participants thorugh ovcaa.oatdiliman@up.edu.ph (Attention : Ms. Daizy Agao)\nAgosto 23-25\n10th International Conference on Teacher Education\nSeda Vertis North, Quezon City\nThe international conference is a biennial event organized by the UPD College of Education. The theme for this year is \"Educational Equity through inclusion.\"\nThis year\'s conference underscores the role of education as an agent for genuine social cohesion and equity which requires breaking barriers and narrowing gaps between and among learners, families, schools and other communities. It advances the view that inclusive education is all-embracing, and that it \"is a comprehensive process of which the diverse needs of all learners are addressed and responded to, regardless of their social, economic, cultural, linguistic, physical, or other contexts\" (UNESCO, 2013). The theme problematizes how inclusive education may be fostered through teacher education and professional development. \nAgosto 23\nNanay Talks : Raising Multilingual Children\nPalma Hall AVR (PH 207)\n1-4 p.m.\nNanay Talks is a roundtable discussion on topics regarding language acquisition and learning, particularly through the eyes of mothers who are also linguistics and/or language teachers. This year, the Nanay Talks has invited faculty members from the language departments within UP Diliman to talk about issues on raising multilingual children. Nanay Talks : Raising Multilingual Children is part of the month-long celebration of Linguistics Month 2018, commemorating the Department\'s 96th founding anniversary. \nAgosto 25\nJuan Balucas at ang Bayabas\nNational Heroes\' Day feature\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n4 p.m.\nInspired by the popular Juan Tamad tales that Filipino children grew up with and loved, the film is about a young boy\'s journey to save his fathe who has been mistaken to be Juan Tamad and is turned into stone by the mythical creature Ibong Adarna. The film is top-billed by Nourish Icon Lapuz, Archie Alemania, Rolando T. Inocencio, Peter Vallejos, Gabby Padilla, Brooke Chantelle Estillore, Ynahbel Moran, Randy De Silva, Rainier Morales and Bernard Laxa under the direction of Franco G. Arce. The film is packed with educational and cultural values as it conveys that \'Filipinos are not lazy\' as its overall statement. It has been rate \"G\" (General Audience) by the Movie and Television Review and Classification Board (MTRCB). \nAgosto 29-31\nWorker\'s Institute on Labor Laws (WILL) Class 173\nIsabelo Delos Reyes Auditorium\nSchool of Labor and Industrial Relations (SOLAIR)\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe seminar will enable the participants to acquire basic knowledge about labor laws and legislation of the country; apply the legal processes and techniques in their respective workplaces; and understand and share experiences and practices involving labor laws and industrial relations. \nAgosto 29\nUP Gawad Plaridel 2018\nAwarding and Lecture\nUP Film Center\n2 p.m. \nThe UP Gawad Plaridel is the sole award in UP given to outstanding media practitioners given to outstanding Filipino media practitioners who have excelled in media (journalism, broadcast-radio and television, film and new media) and have performed with the highest level of professional integrity in the interest of public service. This year\'s UP Gawad Plaridel recipient is Jessica Soho, a veteran broadcast journalist. She is cited for her pioneering work in broadcast investigative journalism and for her insightful and courageous coverage of Philippine and world news. She holds the distinction of being the most awarded broadcast journalist in Philippine history with 253 local awards and 32 international awards to date. She is the first Filipina recipient of the highly acclaimed George Foster Peabody Award for her documentaries on the illegal trade of kidneys and the harrowing plight of Filipino boxers and is also a 6-time recipient of the \"Most Trusted News Presenter\" award of Readers Digest Asia. \nAgosto 30 -31\nCuriosity, Adventure & Love\nNational Heroes\'Day feature\nVideotheque, UPFI Film Center\nAugust 30, 4 p.m.\nAugust 31, 7 p.m.\nThe documentary film weaves together three threads : the life of a 104-year-old American orphan who journeys to the Philippines alone in 1933 at age 18; the history of the country that she has witnessed and made her home over the last century; and the insights and wisdom on life of a woman whose indomitable spirit has evoked inspiration and awe for the thousands who have known her. Sitting alone in her 250-year-old Spanish colonial home, Jessie Lichauco\'s poetic soul draws comfort from the ebb and flow of the mighty river outside her window and protection from an ancient Banyan Tree while sharing stories of a life guided by fate, and where her innate sense of adventure, curiosity and compassion for others knows no boundaries. \nAgosto 30\nSecret Reunion\nKorean Arthouse Feature\nVideotheque, UPFI Film Center\n6:30 p.m.\nUP Korea Research Center, in partnership with UP Film Institute, will hold its 2nd Korean Arthouse Feature with a film entitled \"Secret Reunion\" (2010) directed by Hyun Jang. It is a story about a brotherhood between North Korean secret agent Ji-won and National Intelligence Service officer Han-gyu. In the midst of the ongoing peace talks on the Korean Peninsula, the film will make the viewers think about realistic yet humanistic pictures in this divided country. \nAgosto 31\nHonor : The Legacy of Jose Abad Santos\nNational Heroes\' Day feature\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n5 p.m.\nA full-length documentary biopic about the life and legacy of Filipino hero of World War II Chief Justice Jose Abad Santos. The story is weaved together through interviews with his descendants, top World II Philippine historians, official documents, and excerpts from articles written by Abad Santos\'s son, Pepito, who was with his father through his last days. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1095, 'E2-1095AC', '', '\"Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 8 (4 copies)\"', '', '', 'Setyembre 2018', 'Setyembre 3\nGender Sensitivity Training\nPara sa College of Home Economics \nSeminar Room\nUP Diliman Gender Office\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nBilang pagpapatibay at pagtiyak na ang UP Diliman ay nananatiling makataong kampus na may hustisyang pangkasarian, malaya sa diskriminasyon at pang-aabuso, isinasagawa ang Gender Sensitivity Training (GST) para sa mga guro, REPS, kawaning administratibo, mga security at janitorial personnel sa loob at labas ng kampus ng UP Diliman. Bukas ito para sa mga empleyadong permanente, UP contractual at non-UP contractual.\nSetyembre 3 at 10\nGender Sensitivity Orientation\nPara sa Student\nOrganization Accreditation\nVinzons Rooftop\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nUpang patibayin ang adbokasiya ng makataong kampus na may hustisyang pangkasarian, malaya sa diskriminasyon at pang-aabuso, at palawakin ang diskurso ng usaping pangkasarian sa hanay ng mga mag-aaral, isasagawa ang Gender Sensitivity Orientation (GSO) para sa mga organisasyong pangmag-aaral ng UP Diliman. \nSetyembre 6-8\nLib eFair 2018\nConnecting to Research Discoveries\nMain Library Lobby, Gonzalez Hall\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nA venue to gain insight into the improvement of academics and research in the UP community through online library resources, the University Library showcases trade booths of online databases, lectures on research productivity and exhibits on information literacy in conjunction with the UNESCO Literacy Day every September 8. This event is free and open to the public. Librarians from other organizations are also encouraged to attend. \nSetyembre 7\nPhilippine Music Suite : TUGMA, PADAYON and UP Dance Company \nAbelardo Hall\n6 p.m.\nThe performance is a restaging of the Philippine Music Suite featuring the music and dances of the Cordillera, the urban lowlands and Mindanao. This was first performed for the Guangxi ASEAN Music Festival at Guangxi Arts University in Guangxi, Nanning, China held from May 28 - June 3, 2018. \nSetyembre 10\nGender Sensitivity Training\nSeminar Room\nUP Diliman Gender Office \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nBilang pagpapatibay at pagtiyak na ang UP Diliman ay nananatiling makataong kampus na may hustisyang pangkasarian, malaya sa diskriminasyon at pang-aabuso, isinasagawa ang Gender Sensitivity Training (GST) para sa mga guro, REPS, kawaning administratibo, mga security at janitorial personnel sa loob at labas ng kampus ng UP Diliman. Bukas ito para sa mga empleyadong permanente, UP contractual at non-UP contractual. \nSetyembre 21\nExploratory workshop on \"Islam in Southeast Asia\"\nPublication opportunities for the BRILL\'s International Journal of Islam in Asia and Palgrave Macmillan\'s Islam in Southeast Asia book series. \nUP National Institute for Science and Mathematics Education Development (NISMED) \n8 a.m. - 5:30 p.m.\nThe international exploratory workshop on \"Islam in Southeast Asia\" concentrates on publishing selected peer-reviewed academic and policy works that focuses on theoretical, methodological, empirical, religious, spiritual and critical studies of Islam, including mundane praxes and day-to-day realities of Muslims (and their relations to non-Muslims) in Southeast Asia. It is organized and sponsored by the UP CIDS Islamic Studies Program, UP Office of International Linkages, UP Institute of Islamic Studies (UP IIS), Philippine International Studies Organization and UP IIS Graduate Students Organization. \nSetyembre 21\nGinoong Maria\nPremiere screening at UPFI\nCine Adarna, UP Film Institute (UPFI) \n7 p.m.\n\"Ginoong Maria,\" directed by Jon Red, is a black comedy inspired by true events. It is a fictional gangster tale and a parody of key figures in the current political arena. Dindo, now a family man, is being recruited back to a syndicate involved in the lucrative business of killing. He is torn between a personal ambition and his loved ones - wife and daughter. These imagined characters are set against the background of a more surreal scenario : a world of extrajudicial killings, fake news, misogynistic and corrupt leaders and fanatic followers. A curse that is yet to be broken. A nightmare that never sleeps. Everything is political. And everything is personal. \nSetyembre 22 at 23\nUPIS Leadership Camp\nUP Integrated School (UPIS) Building\n7 a.m.\nThe UPIS Leadership Camp is a 2-day camp for the recently elected officers of different organizations in UPIS. The camp aims to hone aspiring leaders and serving officials through lectures, discussions, workshops and mini competitions that target various skills essential to student leadership. This year, it focuses on two of the five UPIS core values-love and peace. It builds up from last year\'s camp which revolved around truth and justice, two other UPIS core values. \nSetyembre 22\nThe role of the State, Education, Community Outreach, Responsible Media, and Religio-Cultural Dialogues in Countering Violent Extremism (CVE)\nUP National Institute for Science and Mathematics Educaiton Development (NISMED)\n8 a.m. - 5:30 p.m. \nThe conference theme seeks to understand the ontologies, epistemologies, theories, studies, narratives, motivations, causes, effects and impacts of violent extremism, including exploring approaches, frameworks, solutions and mechanisms to counter it by utilizing the imperatives and significance of the state, education, sustainable community outreach programs, highly principled and responsible media, and inter/intra-faith or religio-cultural dialogues that promote religious pluralism, multiculturalism, respect for diversity, acceptance and tolerance. It is organized and sponsored by the UP CIDS Islamic Studies Program, UP Office of International Linkages, UP Institute of Islamic studies (UP IIS), Philippine International Studies Organization and UP IIS Graduate Students Organization. \nSetyembre 24-26\nKOTO TRANSFORMATION : Workshop and Concert of Transcultural Koto music and Artists\nAbelardo Hall, UP College of Music\nWorkshops and a concert with Tugtugang Musika Asyatika (TUGMA) and the Composition and Theory Department of the UP College of Music with Koto artists based in Australia, Thailand and Singapore. \nSetyembre 26 \nHIV 101 and Screening\nAn introductory talk about HIV and free screening for UPD community\nUP University Health Service Public Health Unit\n8 a.m. - 4 p.m.\nBehind Closed Doors : an uncensored talk about HIV \nA public lecture by Dr. Kate Leytritana\nUP University Health Service\nConference Room \n2-4 p.m.\nThe talk and screening will be held as public service of the UP University Health Service, as part of their month-long anniversary celebrations. It is in cooperation with LoveYourself Inc. From one per day, the current rate of new HIV cases daily has risen to 38, with increasing incidence in the younger age group. The activity will address the clamor of students, staff and faculty to obtain more information about HIV/AIDS, as a significant health concern. \nSetyembre 29\nJORNADA LEE\nPanel discussions on Spanish language teaching\nCAL Pavilion\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe event is a day-long discussion among Spanish didactic experts of issues related to Spanish language teaching. Organized by the Department of European Languages of the College of Arts and Letters. Panel discussions will tackle issues related to foreign language education policies in the Philippines, Spanish linguistics, Hispanic literature, and Spanish didactics. Speakers on the different topics include experts from UP, University of Santo Tomas, Instituto Cervantes de Manila, Western Mindanao State University, and the University of Cebu. \n', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1096, 'E2-1096AC', '', '\"Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 9 (5 copies)\"', '', '', '', 'Oktubre 3 \nCuriosity, Adventure & Love\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n2:30, 5 and 7:30 p.m. \nThe movie is about a woman\'s journey through a century of love, war and discovery. \nA young American woman leaves her country and all security behind, to begin an adventure in the Philippines that would witness the birth of a nation,a cruel war and occupation and reconstruction. \nOktubre 4-5\n16th Philippine-Spanish Friendship Day Conference\nMapping Spaces and Identities in Spanish Colonial Philippines\nNISMED Auditorium\n8 a.m. - 5:30 p.m.\nThe conference aims to interrogate the numerous ways that spaces and identities were mapped during the Spanish colonial period. The most obvious would be navigational maps that served not merely as geographic tools of exploration but also of conquest. The history, influence and legacy of cartography and the shift in the use of maps from simple navigation to long-term colonization remain rich areas of historical investigation. \nThe conference seeks to examine not the mapping spaces and identities per se but the various ways these were represented in concrete formats, such as cartographic maps, census or travel accounts, or even the demarcation of towns as recounted in founding documents. The annual Philippine-Spanish Frienship Day Conference is organized by the UP Department of History and the National Historical Commission of the Philippines. \nOktubre 4\nPassages\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium\n6:30 p.m.\nThe event celebrates UP Arco\'s 20th Year Anniversary and Reunion Concert. It is also to celebrate the passage of time and the beautiful music they have shared in 20 years. UP Arco, formerly the UP Chamber Orchestra, is one of the country\'s premiere orchestras that has distinguished itself in the careful study and performance of string orchestral music. In July 2015, UP Arco won the Silver Band Award (highest score in the string orchestra category) in the Bratislava International Youth Music Festival competition in Bratislava, Slovakia. In 2016, the group won the Gold Medal for the String Orchestra Category in the 2nd Music Festa Florence in Italy. The group was also given two Special Jury Awards - Best Musical Interpretation for their performance of Andante Festivo by Jean Sibelius and Best Female Soloist awarded to the group\'s concertmaster. UP Arco is under the baton of Prof. Edna Marcil Martinez. \nOktubre 5\n5th Interdisciplinary Book Forum : Sapantaha : Kalipunan ng mga Maikling Kwentong Spekulatibo at Imahinatibo \nPav. 1131, Palma Hall\n2:30 - 4 p.m.\nThe forum seeks to provide an academic venue in which to realize the imperative for dialogue and intellectual engagement across the various disciplines, which speaks directly to the Literature for Social Development (LSD)\'s core agenda. Being the center for the study and development of creative and, to a certain extent, critical writing in the UP System, the Likhaan is in a unique position to carry out such an important academic mission. The Interdisciplinary Book Forum is held once every semester and constitutes a vital component of the UP Likahaan\'s LSD. \nOktubre 10\nChange and Continuity in China\'s Foreign Policy\nA Public Lecture\nUP CIDS Conference Hall\nLower Ground Floor, Ang Bahay ng Alumni \n1:30 - 4 p.m.\nThe Strategic Studies Program (SSP) of the University of the Philippines\' Center for Integrative and Development Studies (UP CIDS), in partnership with the UP Diliman Department of Political Science, will hold a lecture on the emerging trends in China\'s foreign policy and its implications for Korea. The lecture is based on the findings of the studies conducted by SSP Research Fellows Dr. Meitling Li and Raisa E. Lumampao. The lecture is free and open to the public on a first-come, first -served basis. \nOktubre 15-16\nBergman in Spain\nIngmar Bergman screenings at UP Film Institute\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\nIn celebration of the centenary of Ingmar Bergman, the most iconic and influential Swedish filmmaker of all time, the Instituto Cervantes, in partnership with the Embassy of Sweden in Manila and the UP Film Institute, presents Bergman in Spain, one of the jewels stored in the 17th edition of Pelicula-Pelikula 2018, the largest Spanish Film Festival in Southeast Asia. \nOktubre 17-19\nBukluran : Exploring the Food Science and Nutrition nexus towards achieving the United Nation\'s Sustainable Development Goals (UN SDG) \nGusali 2, Alonso Hall \nCollege of Home Economics\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe 3-day event will serve as a platform for acquisition and exchange of new and existing ideas and information regarding the disciplines of food science and nutrition in achieving the UN SDG related to food security and availability. \nOktubre 19\nEnsuring a Square Meal : Women and Food Security in Southeast Asia\nBook Launch and Panel Discussion\nUP CIDS Conference Hall\nLower Ground Floor, Ang Bahay ng Alumni \n2 -4 p.m. \nThe UP CIDS Program on Social and Political Change, UP Department of Political Science and World Scientific will launch a book that aims to interlink women and food security at the household, community, national and transnational levels in the Southeast Asian region. The event will also hold a panel discussion joined by two of the book chapter authors, Dr. Jorge Tigno, Professor at the UP Department of Political Science; Dr. Thelma Paris, Senior Adviser (Gender Research) at Climate Change, Agriculture and Food Security in Southeast Asia; as well as the editor of the book, Dr. Theresa Devashayam, Associate Faculty at the Singapore School of Social Sciences. \nOktubre 19 - Nobyembre 16\nStasis and Mobility : Nasa Dugo Natin \'Yan?!\nBulwagan ng Dangal\n6 p.m. (Exhibit Opening)\nThe exhibition is an attempt to problematize the science of genetics through the visual arts. Genetics is the study of genes, genetic variation and heredity in living organisms. Colloquially, it refers to a unit of inheritance-such as physical traits passed on by parents to their children - color of the skin, hair, body-built and height. The exhibit also tries to answer the question : what is the relationship of genetics and culture? This is especially since both culture and genetics are considered two opposite poles in the same way many tend to perceive nature and culture as binary opposites. How do metaphysicians explain alterity and permanency : the self as the individual age changes and at the same time stays the same? The exhibit posits that the genetic make-up of the individual is both permanent and changing. \nOktubre 25-26\nColloquium on HIV/AIDS in Southeast Asia\nGT Toyota Auditorium\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nHIV/AIDS in Southeast Asia is an interdisciplinary and intercultural colloquium exploring the diverse processes by which HIV/AIDS is constructed as a cultural phenomenon. The colloquium presents two keynote speakers and up to 20 papers on various topics related to the theme. It also aims to bring together academics from different disciplinary backgrounds with the aim of developing a network of scholars working in this area. \nOktubre 26\nSawikaan 2018 : Salita ng Taon\nInstitute of Biology Auditorium \n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nAng Sawikaan ay isang masinsinang talakayan para piliin ang pinakanatatanging salitang namayani sa diskurso ng sambayanang Filipino sa nakalipas na taon. Isang popular ng kumperensiya ang Sawikaan at mainam na forum sa pagtalakay ng halaga ng wika sa mga pangunahing isyung kinakaharap ng bayan. Dadaluhan ito ng mga mag-aaral, guro, midya at mga akademikong sumusubaybay sa development ng wikang pambansa. Sa pagtutulungan ito ng Opisina ng Tsanselor ng UP Diliman (UPD), UP Diliman Information Office at ng Filipinas Institute of Translation (FIT). Ang FIT ay isang samahang pangwika na karamihan sa kasapi ay mga guro ng UPD. \nOktubre 30\nForum on Science, Technology and Society\nInstitute of Biology Auditorium\n1:30 - 5 p.m. \nIn celebration of the 200th anniversary of Mary Shelly\'s pioneering sci-fi novel \"Frankenstein,\" or the Modern Prometheus, a lecture-forum that gathers a cross-disciplinary panel discusses this early 18th century novel and the modern-day issues it anticipated. The forum aims to engage the UP community in discourses about the body and human consciousness, biotechnology and social responsibility, robotics, artificial intelligence and the perils of science ungoverned by ethical norms. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
