(1097, 'E2-1097AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 10 ', '', '', 'Nobyembre 2018', 'Nobyembre 3-13\nTOFARM Film Festival 2018\nSpecial Screening run at UPFI\n2, 5 and 7 p.m. \nUP Film Institute showcases all the six films of TOFARM Film Festival 2018 namely : Tanabata\'s Wife; 1957; Alimuom, Kauyagan; Mga Anak ng Kamote; and Sol Searching with three features each day for the duration of the screening program. This festival aims to uplift the farmers and their professional development. It is most worthy and significant since this is the only film festival that showcases the lives, journeys, aspirations, trials and tribulations - failures and successes of the farmers and other stewards of agriculture. \nNobyembre 3\nFilms by Carlo Enciso Catu\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\nUP Film Institute starts the month of November with a back-to-back screening of Carlo Enciso Catu\'s multi-awarded Ari : My Life with a King and the TOFARM Film Festival finalist Mga Anak ng Kamote. \nNobyembre 7-9\nPhilippine Research Conference on Tourism and Hospitality 2018\nFacing the Challenges of Overtourism\nHoliday Inn, Baguio City\nThe conference aims to examine the evolution of tourism development in rural and urban settings, and the implications of perceived and actual impacts of tourism on the environment, the economy and the social fabric. Through stand-up paper presentations, workshops, and keynote speeches, the conference will discuss a range of topics including resident perceptions and attitudes on tourism development, governance issues and policy options to address over-tourism and mitigate the negative impacts of tourism. The conference is organized by the UP Asian Institute of Tourism in cooperation with UP Department of Hotel, Restaurant and Institution Management. \nNobyembre 8-9\nWhat Now? A Hundred Years After World War I\nThe UP Center for International Studies (UPCIS), in collaboration with the French Embassy, UP Film Institute, and the Department of European Languages of UP College of Arts and Letters, will be holding a series of activities to commemorate the Centennial of the end of World War I. The activities wish to encourage discussion on the Great War topics and its contemporary implications, inviting students to participate in the discourse on one of history\'s most transformative events. \nNobyembre 8\nMarx Bicentennial Lecture Series No. 11\nA lecture by Dr. Francisco Nemenzo and Dr. Eduardo T. Gonzalez\nUP CIDS Conference Hall, Lower Ground Floor, Ang Bahay ng Alumni\n2 - 5 p.m.\nTo commemorate Karl Marx\'s 200th year, a group of academics and social movement activists have gathered to hold a series of lectures. For the Marx Bicentennial Lecture Series No. 11, former UP President Dr. Francisco Nemenzo will look at the early writings of Marx in his talk \"Marx before Marxism : The Philosophical Premises of Revolutionary Theory\" while Dr. Eduardo T. Gonzalez will talk about \"Navigating Contemporary Marxian Thought in the Age of Populism\".\nNobyembre 9\nRondalya Para Sa Lahat\nA celebration of rondalla music as an enriching and inclusive community music\nUP Abelardo Hall Auditorium\n3-8 p.m.\nIn celebration of the 51st anniversary of the Music Education Department of the UP College of Music, a workshop-concert highlighting rondalla music as an enriching and inclusive community music will be conducted. The event will also feature a lecture-workshop by Maestro Celso Espejo about managing and training a rondalla and a concert featuring performing groups mentored using the Celso Espejo Method namely : Talayan Rondalla, OB Montessori Center, Timoteo Paez Elementary School Rondalla, UP Rondalla, Celso Espejo Rondalla and the NCCA Employees\' Rondalla. \nNobyembre 12\nFilmmaking Masterclass with Italian Filmmakers\nUP Film Institute Media Center Bldg. Film Studio \n1-6:30 p.m. \nA 1-day Italian cinema masterclass that serves as the educational component of this year\'s edition of Italian Cinema : From Venice to Manila. Topics include new soundtracks to new horizons by Franco Eco; philosophy of an ordinary cinematographer by Davide Mancori; and FVX design by Paolo Bertola. Organized by the UP Film Institute, in partnership with The Philippine Italian Association, all masterclasses are free of charge. Certificates will be issued upon request. \nNobyembre 13\nOff-Campus Housing Fair\nIsabelo delos Reyes Auditorium\nUP School of Labor and Industrial Relations\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m.\nThe event aims to help UP employees think about their options on where to live and what to live in. Real estate developers will present residential options in Quezon City and nearby areas of Bulacan, Rizal and Laguna. Bank representatives are invited to present their home loan products and acquired assets. Pag-IBIG Fund is also invited to present their available loan programs and other services related to housing and to set up a Membership Assistance Booth. Interested employees may consult and interact with the representatives from the different property brands, banks and Pag-IBIG Fund. The event is open to all UP employees. The fair is organized by the Diliman Housing Ofice, under the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Community Affairs. \nNobyembre 14-16\n13th Philippine Linguistics Congress (13PLC)\nUP National Institute for Science and Mathematics Education Development (NISMED)\nThe Philippine Linguistics Congress brings together scholars interested in the study of Philippine languages and linguistics to discuss current research and recent advances in the field. The conference looks into the application of lingustics findings and theories to other related disciplines, as well as contemporary comparative studies between Philippine languages and other languages. The conference also seeks to promote collaboration and further research on Philippine languages and lingustics. It also serves as a venue for the discussion of langauge-related issues in the country. \nNobyembre 14\nYO! sa UP 2018\nCHRONO : TRAVERSE TOWARDS THE FUTURE\nSM Clark Cinemas \n6-9 p.m. \nYO! sa UP, hosted by the UP Triskelions Grand Fraternity and Grand Sorority, is celebrating its 30th year with the theme, Chrono : Traverse towards the Future. Witness dance groups of UP Diliman Extension Program in Pampanga go head to head in showcasing their dancing prowess in a hip-hop dance competition like no other. Prepare for robotic dance steps, galactic-inspired costumes, and eclectic sounds, all in a tangled array of futuristic aesthetic. \nNobyembre 16\nThe Cleaners\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n7 p.m.\nDirected by Hans Block and Moritz Riesewieck, the documentary film is about five \"digital scavengers\" among thousands of people outsourced from Silicon Valley whose job is to delete \"inappropriate\" content on the net. The film also divulges their struggles to come to terms with the new and diconcerting paradigm of the point of balance for social media to be neither an unlegislated space nor a forum rife with censorship. Evolving from a shared social vision of a global village to a web of fake news and radicalization, the film charts the rise and fall of social media\'s utopian ideology. \nNobyembre 17\nARIA\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n5 p.m.\nDirected by Carlo Enciso Catu, the film is about a love story set against the backdrop of the Huk guerrilla movement during World War 2. \nNobyembre 17\nGoing Back, Giving Back : 64 Years of Empowering People\nUP SOLAIR Grand Alumni Homecoming \nIsabelo Delos Reyes Auditorium\nUP School of Labor and Industrial Relations\n5-9 p.m.\nAll Diploma in Industrial Relations and Master in Industrial Relatons graduates are cordially invited to the UP SOLAIR Grand Alumni Homecoming 2018. Reminisce the UP SOLAIR experience, reconnect with your classmates, professors and staff, and meet new friends! \nNobyembre 21-23\nWorker\'s Institute on Labor Laws (WILL) Class 174\nIsabelo Delos Reyes Auditorium\nUP School of Labor and Industrial Relations\n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe seminar will enable the participants to : 1) acquire basic knowledge about labor laws and legislation of the country; 2) apply the legal processes and techniques in their respective workplaces; and 3) understand and share experiences and practices involving labor laws and industrial relations. \nNobyembre 22-23\nExamining Philippine Media : Texts and Contexts\nThe National Communication Research Conference 2018\nCine Adarna, UP Film Center\n7 a.m. - 6 p.m.\nThe 6th National Communication Research Conference (NCRC) examines our critical engagement with and consumption of the media within and across platforms. It features 65 papers selected through a blind review process as well as several plenary presentations on the conference theme of media monitoring as well as on pertinent concerns in communication and media research such as ethics, research dissemination, intellectual property and intellectual honesty. The NCRC, organized by the Department of Communication Research, in cooperation with the Philippines Communications Society, is a platform for students, faculty members and professionals to present and discuss their research papers before a community of scholars. \nNobyembre 23\nUP Writers Night 2018\nIn celebration of the 40th year of UPICW, Grand Homecoming of Fellows of the UP Writers Workshop\nUniversity Hotel\n4-11 p.m.\nAs part of its 40th year anniversary gala, the UP Institute of Creative Writing\'s (UP ICW) yearly gathering will pay homage to both the country\'s up and coming, and established writers. The grand homecoming will feature events like the 18th Madrigal-Gonzalez Best First Book Award, 40@40 and Likhaan 12 book launch. Expect a special evening filled with memories; to reminisce \"the good old days,\" and renew old friendships. Everyone is invited. Admission is free. \nNobyembre 24\nGinoong Maria \nSpecial screening at UPFI\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center \n7 p.m.\nThe film is a black comedy inspired by true events. It is a fictionalo gangster tale and a parody of key figures in the current political arena. Dindo, now a family man, is being recruited back to a syndicate involved in the lucrative business of killing. He is torn between a personal ambition and his loved-ones-a wife and a daughter. These imagined characters are set against the background of a more surreal scenario : a world of extra-judicial killings, fake news, misogynistic and corrupt leaders and fanatic followers. \nNobyembre 30\nSupremo\nSpecial screening at UPFI\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n1 p.m.\nThe screening of this bio-drama film by Richard V. Somes is to commemorate the 155th birth anniversary of Gat Andres Bonifacio. The film depicts events in history and exemplifies Bonifacio\'s sacrifice, passion and courage as the founder of the Katipunan. The Katipuneros called him Supremo, the supreme leader of Filipino revolutionaries. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1098, 'E2-1098AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 4, Blg 11 ', '', '', 'Disyembre 2018', 'Disyembre 1\nAng Pag-ibig Naghahari\nAbelardo Hall Auditorium\n7 p.m.\nThe concert is the final offering of the Abelardo Hall Concert Series\' Second Season. It will feature the UP Concert Chorus and Baihana. The UP Concert Chorus has been in various international tours and choral competitions and has won numerous festival awards including the Grand Prix at the 6th International Krakow Choir Festival in Poland, and was ranked \"Number 1 in the World\" for Folk Choral Performance at the 2012 Festival Internacional de Cantonigros in Spain. Formed in May 2008, Baihana has been garnering awards such as the \"Best Jazz Band\" at the Boy Katindig Songwriting Competition in 2012 and the \"Best Performance By A New Group\" at the 26th Aliw Awards in 2013. Backed up by the dashing Debonair District, the all-female vocal trio-Anna Graham, Krina Cayabyab and Mel Torre-enjoy executing playful arrangements of vocal harmonies and simply dive into any kind of music genre. \nWorld AIDS Day with Pusit\nIndie advocacy feature by Arlyn de la Cruz\nCine Adarna, UP Film Center\n7 p.m. \nThe UP Film Institute joins the commemoration of World AIDS Day through a special screening of Pusit. The film, directed by Arlyn de la Cruz, stars Jay Manalo, Kristoffer King, Roli Inocencio, Ronnie Quizon, Lehner Mendoza, Mike Liwag and Elizabeth Oropesa. Based on true accounts, the film is about a salon owner, an overseas worker, a model, a call center agent, a teenage boy, a son of a rich family, and a breadwinner raised by a single mother. The characters are connected and bonded both by hate, persecution and condemnation by a society that is blinded by its own guilt-a reality of the lives of persons living with HIV and AIDS. \nDisyembre 3\nFilm Screenings with Colombia\nUPFI Special Features\nVideotheque, UP Film Center\n2 and 4 p.m.\nThe UP Film Institute, in partnership with Embassy of Colombia in the Philippines, will showcase selected Colombian films, namely, Keyla (2 p.m.) and Mama (4 p.m.)\nKeyla is an adventure-drama about a young woman living on a Caribbean island searching for her father lost at sea. When her estranged family came to help, she must confront their dark past and this new family she never expected to embrace. The film is written and directed by Viviana Gomez Echeverry and starts Mercedes Salazar, Sebastian Enciso Salamanca and Elsa Whitaker Sanchez. Mama is about Victoria, a reserved and independent woman who apparently enjoys her loneliness. She receives an unexpected visit from her estranged daughter Sara. Sara requested Victoria to take care of her 7-year old daughter for a few days. This favor alters Victoria\'s life. \nDisyembre 4\nPython for Data Science and Analytics\nUP National Engineering Center\n8 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe 3-day course is a guide to learn the Python program for analyzing data, creating beautiful visualizations and utilizing powerful predictive analytic algorithms. Composed of lectures, hands-on exercises and real-world data case studies, the training gives an overview of how to use Python and Jupyter notebooks to extract, manipulate and present massive data for management decision-making. At the end of the training, the participants are expected to be confident enough to produce any type of business analytics analysis with Python. \nDisyembre 6\nTALASTASAN SA KASAYSAYAN \n\"Vietnam : The Chemical War\" \nSilid Balatik, Pavilion 2, Palma Hall\n2 p.m.\nThe UP Department of History, together with the Third World Studies Center, present a public lecture on history \"Vietnam : The Chemical War.\" \nSilid Balatik, Pavilion 2, Palma Hall\n2 p.m.\nThe UP Department of History, together with the Third World Studies Center, present a public lecture on history \"Vietnam : The Chemical War.\"\nProf. David Biggs from the University of California at Riverside will deliver a lecture on Vietnam War that will examine the history of the chemical war in Vietnam and the relation of scientific development, particularly in chemistry, at that time. The talk will also examine Vietnam War within a more global context of the post-1945 development of pesticides, the Green Revolution and military escalation in Southeast Asia. \nDisyembre 6\nMaking Policies Matter : Voter Responses to Campaign Promises (with P. Keefer and F. Trebbi)\nA public presentation by Julien Labonne and Cesi Cruz\nRm. 114, Encarnacion Hall\n4 -5 p.m. \nLabonne and Cruz\'s presentation looks into the different responses of voters to the campaign promises made by political candidates. Their analyses also show the impact of campaign promises to the distribution of vote shares. This seminar is organized by the Philippine Center for Economic Development and UP School of Economics and is open to the public on a first-come, first-served basis. \nDisyembre 8\nHonor : The Legacy of Jose Abad Santos\nUPFI Special Screenings\nCine Adarna, UP Film Center\n10 a.m., 1 and 5 p.m.\nShowcasing the life and legacy of the late Chief Justice Jose Abad Santos, the film uncovers his numerous virtues that guided him from his humble beginnings, to his scholarly achievements, and eventually to his ascent into prominence. \nThe film aims to inspire the younger generation by exposing them to the courageous, honorable and incorruptible nature of Jose Abad Santos - that they may emulate the same values in their own lives. His clean and upright public service record is one of the most outstanding in the history of Philippine governance. His love for the country was unparalleled-choosing death than siding with the Japanese Imperial Forces. His story is one that highlights patriotism, bravery and integrity in the face of overwhelming difficulty. \nDisyembre 8\nPamaskong Handog ng UP\nUP Amphitheater\n7 p.m.\nThe Philippine Philharmonic Orchestra (PPO) and UP\'s top soloists and choral groups will perform immortal orchestral selections, Christmas and inspirational music including Handel\'s Messiah, one of the grandest and best-known choral and orchestral works of Western music. More than 130 voices comprising soloists and UP choruses, under the musical direction of UP professor and Madrigal Singers choirmaster Mark Anthony Carpio, will be accompanied by the PPO under the baton of Dr. Herminigildo Ranera. \nDisyembre 8\nHonor : The Legacy of Jose Abad Santos \nUPFI Special Screenings\nCine Adarna, UP Film Center\n10 a.m., 1 and 5 p.m.\nShowcasing the life and legacy of the late Chief Justice Jose Abad Santos, the film uncovers his numerous virtues that guided him from his humble beginnings, to his scholarly achievements, and eventually to his ascent into prominence. The film aims to inspire the younger generation by exposing them to the courageous, honorable and incorruptible nature of Jose Abad Santos - that they may emulate the same values in their own lives. His clean and upright public service record is one of the most outstanding in the history of Philippine governance. His love for the country was unparalleled - choosing death than siding with the Japanese Imperial Forces. His story is one that highlights patriotism, bravery and integrity in the face of overwhelming difficulty. \nDisyembre 8\nPamaskong Handog ng UP\nUP Amphitheater\n7 p.m.\nThe Philippine Philharmonic Orchestra (PPO) and UP\'s top soloists and choral groups will perform immortal orchestral selections, Christmas and inspirational music including Handel\'s Messiah, one of the grandest and best-known choral and orchestral works of Western music. More than 130 voices comprising soloists and UP choruses, under the musical direction of UP profesor and Madrigal Singers choirmaster Mark Anthony Carpio, will be accompanied by the PPO under the baton of Dr. Herminigildo Ranera. The choral groups include the UP Cherubim and Seraphim, UP Concert Chorus, UP Singing Ambassadors, UP Staff Chorale and UP College of Music Chorus Classes. UPD\'s yearly Christmas include a Messiah staging, which culminates in a grand-scale performance of \"Hallelujah\". \nDisyembre 10-13\nUP CWGS 30th Anniversary Celebration\nFor its 30th anniversary, the UP Center for Women\'s and Gender Studies will be holding a week-long celebration with the theme #Kabog At 30 : Trailblazing in Equity and Equality. \nDecember 10\n5 p.m. Zumbabae : Patuloy na Pakikipaglaban para sa Karapatang Pantao at the UP CWGS Courtyard\nDecember 11\n2 - 5 p.m. Participatory Video Showcase at the UP CWGS Conference Room\nDecember 12\n3 - 5 p.m. Dakila Awards at the Balay Kalinaw\n5 - 9 p.m. UP CWGS Anniversary Night at the Balay Kalinaw\nDecember 13\n2 - 4 p.m. Review of Women\'s Studies vol. XXVIII Journal Launch at the UP CWGS Conference Room\nZumbabae and the Participatory Video Showcase are free and open to the public while the Dakila Awards, the UP CWGS Anniversary Night and the Review of Women\'s Studies vol. XXVIII Journal Launch are closed events. \nDisyembre 11-14\n2nd Philippine Symposium on Freshwater Biodiversity and Ecosystems (2nd PSFBE) \nFreshwaters are fragile and finite\nInstitute of Biology, College of Science\nThe symposium will gather international and Filipino specialists in limnology, freshwater ecology, biodiversity and conservation biology. Keynote speakers are Dr. Teodoro Herbosa (Executive Vice President of the UP System) and John Morse (Clemson University, USA). The symposium tackle issues that confront freshwater biodiversity and ecosystems, such as overexploitation, climate change and population growth. It will also highlight the overwhelming species - rich freshwater ecosystems. \nDisyembre 13\nUP Symphonic Orchestra Inaugural Concert\nUP Amphitheater \n6 p.m.\nThe concert will feature a program of both classical and contemporary orchestral works for the Christmas season, including selections of Christmas arrangements by National Artist for Music Ryan Cayabyab. Several pieces will also bring together a grand chorus representing the UP campuses of pioneering members of the UP Symphony Orchestra (UPSO). UPSO, under the musical direction of Prof. Josefino \"Chino\" Toledo, consist of 65 members exclusively from the UP community : alumni, students, faculty members and staff from all UP campuses. The Orchestra functions as training ground for both composers and musicians, and as representative of not only the University but also of the country in the worldwide stage. \nDisyembre 14\nPaglaot, Pagdaong\nUPD Parada at Paligsahan ng mga Parol 2018\nUP Academic Oval and UP Amphitheater \n5 p.m.\nParada at paligsahan ng mga pinakamagandang parol ng mga administratibo at akademikong yunit ayon sa temang \"Paglaot, Pagdaong.\" Ipaparada ang mga parol paikot sa Academic Oval at magtatapos sa isang palatuntunan sa Amphitheater. Ito rin ay tatampukan ng fireworks display. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1099, 'E2-1099AC', '', 'Ugnayan\nUnibersidad ng Pilipinas Diliman. Tomo 5, Blg 2 ', '', '', 'Abril 2019', 'Abril 1-27\nThe Nature of the Collection\n1F Galleries, UP Vargas Museum\nThe Nature of the Collection exhibits some of the most notable paintings of the American and Japanese period in the Philippines done by the first Filipino National Artist, Fernando Amorsolo. The exhibition dwells on Amorsolo\'s practice in portraiture and landscape as it intersects with the collecting practice of his patron Jorge Vargas. Seen together, the history of painting and history of a collection come together to define a time in Philippine art history through the careers of both Amorsolo and Vargas. Speaking to this condition of embodied nature and labor is the video work of Tanya Villanueva titled \"Safe Space, Sacred Space / How we work together.\" \nAbril 4\nThe Grammaticalization of Negative Stance Makers in Korean\nRm. 207, Palma Hall\n2-4 p.m.\nOrganized by the UP Department of Linguistics in cooperation with the UP Korean Research Center, this special lecture will be delivered by Dr. Kyou-Dong Ahn of the HanKuk University of Foreign Studies, Seoul, South Korea. \nAbril 4\nBird of Prey\nCine Adarna, UPFI Film Center\n7 - 9:30 p.m.\nRenowned wildlife cinematographer Neil Rettig embarks on what could be the most challenging assignment of his career : to find and film the rarest eagle on the planet. The documentary explores the vanishing world of the Great Philippine Eagle and reveals the people determined to save it. The award-winning feature-length documentary follows Rettig\'s return to the Philippines as he embarks on a grueling expedition alongside a small but devoted group determined to protect the eagle. Together, they answer the question : What will it take to save a species from extinction? \nAbril 6\nEngg Musika!\nA Benefit Concert for the Student Wellbeing (SWELL) Program\nDM Consunji Theater, UP Institute of Civil Engineering\n7 p.m.\nA benefit concert organized by the UP College of Engineering (UPCOE) and the UP Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. (UPERDFI), it aims to raise awareness and support for the SWELL Program to provide students with facilities and services for life coaching, peer support, meditation and relaxation - to overcome stresses and foster an outlook of optimism. The concert features Department of Science and Technology Sec. Boy de la Peña; Dean Divas - Usec Rowena Cristina L. Guevara; Aura Matias and Babylin de Leon; UPERDFI President Chato Calderon; Professors Rhod Gonzalez; Benito M. Pacheco; Glen Tabios, Ji Reyes; Sean Palmiano; UPCOE staff and many more. \nAbril 6\nEl Fin de la Guerra Civil (The End of the Civil War)\nVideotheque, UPFI Film Center\nInstituto Cervantes Manila in collaboration with the Embassy of Spain in the Philippines and the UP Film Institute present the following films : \"La Colmena\" (4:30 p.m.) and \"Pa Negre\" (6:30 p.m.). La Colmena (The Hive) : Based on a 1943 novel of the same title from Camilo Jose Cela, takes place in the cafe La Delicia narrating the lives of a wide variety of characters from all walks of life who are trying to survive in a poverty-stricken Madrid after the Civil War. Pa Negre (Black Bread) : In the harsh post-war years\' Catalan countryside, 11 year-old Andreu comes across the bodies of a man and his son in the woods. When the authorities try to pin the blame on his father, the boy find out the real killer. The experience opens Andreu\'s eyes to the world of adults who live on lies. The screenings are free and open to the public on a first-come, first served basis. \nAbril 11\nUniversity Student Council Elections/Halalan UPD2019\n8 a.m. - 7 p.m.\nHalalanUPD2019 is the selection of leaders of elective positions in the University Student Council (USC). The elections aims to uphold the autonomous, democratic and representative character of the USC. The University Student Electoral Board is composed of the Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs as ex-officio Chairperson, two faculty members and two student members. \nAbril 13\nTeaching Vocabulary in the Second/Foreign Language Classroom Using Japanese and Chinese Examples \nRm. 428, Palma Hall\n9 a.m. - 12 p.m. \nThe talk highlights the importance of vocabulary in language teaching. It presents various in-and-out-of-classroom activities to aid students in learning and remembering vocabulary words, and introduces non-textbook sources of vocabulary words and phrases that students can draw from. The event is free and open to the public, but priority will be given to language teachers. \nAbril 22-24\nWorker\'s Institute on Labor Laws (WILL) Class 175\nIsabelo Delos Reyes Auditorium, UP SOLAIR \n9 a.m. - 5 p.m. \nThe seminar enables the participants to acquire basic knowledge about labor laws and legislation of the country; apply the legal processes and techniques in their respective workplaces; and understand and share experiences and practices involving labor laws and industrial relations. Seminar fee is P9,000 inclusive of meals, copy of Everyone\'s Labor Code, certificate of completion. Payment can be made in cash or cheque, on or before seminar schedule. \nAbril 22 - Mayo 11\nJapanese for Kids & Teens\nPalma Hall Pavilion 1\nJapanese for Kids (8 y.o. - 12 y.o) :\nMon. - Fri., 1-3 p.m.\nJapanese for Teens (13 y.o. - 16 y.o.) :\nMon - Fri., 3- 5 p.m.\nThe Japanese for Kids & Teens are short-term summer courses designed to teach Japanese to our young language learners (preferably ages 8 to 16). These classes will meet for 15 days. A culminating activity with friends and families of students is scheduled on the last class day. \nAbril 23\nLa Fashionista\nSalvare : Wildlife Protection Through Innovative Fashion\nThe Encore at the Century Hotel, Balibago, Angeles City, Pampanga\n6 p.m.\nLa Fashionista is the annual fashion competition wherein students can maximize their talents related to fashion. This year\'s competition is all about bringing boundless creativity to encourage the preservation of the animal wildlife. The contestants will strut the runway and showcase pieces that feature the frolics and colors of the wild. Designers will create exquisite designs inspired by endangered species to promote awareness of their maltreated conditions while at the same time, being fashionable. \nAbril 27\nThe 5th CSSP Graduate Students Research Conference\nCSSP Wellness Center, Palma Hall Pavilion 1 \n8:30 a.m.\nThe CSSP Graduate Students Research Conference (GSRC) aims to bring together graduate students engaged in social science and philosophy research. CSSP GSRC is a venue where they can share insights and findings from studies conducted for their graduate courses, or from the theses or dissertations that they are currently working on. Dr. Peter Sy from the UP Department of Philosophy and Dr. Steven Rood, a fellow-in-residence at the Social Weather Stations and the former Philippine Country Representative of The Asia Foundation will be the conference plenary speakers. \nAbril 27\n2019 UP Korean Speech Contest \nRm. 400, Palma Hall\n1-5 p.m.\nA continuing tradition of the UP Department of Linguistics, the contest is on its 11th installment, commemorating the 70th anniversary of the bilateral relations between the Philippines and the Republic of Korea. The contest aims to promote the Korean language to UP students, as well as the students of the Asian Language Extramural Classes of the Department. It also aims to engage the students to think about and discuss the concept of \"unity\" using the Korean language. There are two categories for the contest : (1) for beginner learners, and (2) for advanced learners, including students who have been to Korea for an exchange program. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1100, 'E2-1100AC', '', 'Ugnayan Diliman. Recalibrate. Optimize. Engage. Vol. 2, No. 1 (10 copies)', '', '', 'Jan-Jun 2021', 'What\'s Inside\nNemenzo is 11th UPD Chancellor  by Anna Regidor\nIn a simple ceremony at the Quezon Hall steps, the campus witnessed the changing of its guard as Prof. Fidel R. Nemenzo, DSc took his oath of office as UPD\'s 11th Chancellor on Mar. 2, 2020. \nA right balance of sense and sensibility by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nKnown and appreciated for her critical mind and caring sensibility, Ma. Theresa T. Payongayong, PhD, professor of philosophy, is the newly-appointed UP Diliman (UPD) Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs (VCAA).\nSteward of UPD resources by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nWith UP Diliman\'s (UPD) vast array of assets, the Office of Vice Chancellor for Administration (OVCA) leads in being the effective and efficient steward of the university\'s physical, financial and human resources. \nIt\'s researcher\'s welfare first by Bino Gamba \nAs UPD\'s main policy-making and support body for research and development, the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Research and Development (OVCRD) plays a vital role in the continuing growth and nurturing in the life of the mind of the University. \nOVCSA : Providing students with safe and accessible support services by Haidee C. Pineda\nProf. Louise Jashil R. Sonido, an assistant professor at the College of Arts and Letters Department of English and Comparative Literature, was appointed as the new Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs (VCSA) on July 1, 2020. \nRe-imagining UPD as Academic Center of Excellence : Inclusive, diverse and public service-oriented by Fidel R. Nemenzo, DSc\nI have devoted all my life to UP. In all these years, I have had the privilege of learning from and collaborating with some of the best and most creative minds in the University, while mindful of the issues and challenges that our community faces every day. I have thought long and hard about the life and future of this University, and I treasure this opportunity to lead and shepherd the energy and talents of our faculty, REPS, staff and students toward realizing our ideals, values and dreams as Iskolar ng Bayan, Iskolar para sa Bayan. \nLeading the frontlines by Anna Regidor \nIt\'s hard enough starting a new job, but when that job entails leading the frontlines against a pandemic, the task becomes doubly difficult. \nOVCPD : Taking care of business by Chi A. Ibay\nBarely a year old, the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Planning and Development (OVCPD) has much of its work cut out. \nIn academic pole position by Mariamme D. Jadloc \nIn July 2020, Ugnayan conducted an email interview with Prof. Maria Vanessa Lusung-Oyzon, PhD, the new University Registrar appointed on Apr. 1. \nUPDIO : Stepping towards the future by Sir Anril P. Tiatco\nSince the establishment of the University of the Philippines Diliman (UPD) as a constituent university of the University of the Philippines System (UP) on Apr. 23, 1985, it has generated various publics, who have continuously motivated UPD administration to perform actively in relation to UP\'s mandate as the national university. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1101, 'E2-1101AC', '', 'Ugnayan Diliman. UP Diliman, our home. Vol. 2, No. 2 (17 copies)', '', '', 'Jul-Dec 2021', 'What\'s Inside\nIn living color - life in UP by Bino C. Gamba\nLiving in UP Diliman (UPD) is not at all blue.\nSaksi sa pakikibaka at pag-angat by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \n\"Taong 1976 nang lumipat ang buong pamilya namin dito sa UP Diliman (UPD),\" simula ng kuwento ni Clodualdo E. Cabrera na mas kilala sa palayaw nyang \"Buboy.\"\n\"Wanners,\" a pioneering community by Benito V. Sanvictores Jr. \nThe Cervanteses were among the first residents of the then flourishing UP Diliman (UPD) campus. \nTraditions from the past : growing up on campus in the \'70s by Bino C. Gamba\nThe UP exodus from Manila to Diliman brought not only learning and knowledge to the vast, cogon-dominated area, and rustic part of Quezon City but also families who would call UP Diliman (UPD) their home. \nDown Valenzuela Street, there lived Kiko by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nIn her article, \"The UP in our minds\" (\"Ugnayan\" Vol. 1, No. 1), anthropologist and UP professor Monica FA W. Santos said, \"Thus, while we can all collectively claim that we are from UP, being \'from UP\' can have various meanings because we inhabit UP in different ways.\"\nUPD and the Nemenzos by Bino C. Gamba \nFidel R. Nemenzo, DSc, the 11th chancellor of UP Diliman (UPD), is a third-generation Nemenzo. \nTagapagtanggol ng kalikasan by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nSino ba sa UP Diliman (UPD) ang hindi nakakakilala kay Fidel R. Nemenzo? \nMemories of an idyllic childhood by Anna E. Regidor\nBoth of Eduardo Francisco\'s parents were employees of the University Food Service.\nLiving in and leaving UP by Anna E. Regidor \nEduardo Santos and his family were one of the first UP employees to settle in Area 17, about three houses away from Purok Aguinaldo near Moresby Street (now C.P. Garcia Avenue). \nA walk down memory lane by Bino C. Gamba\nRomeo A. Sebastian cannot help but smile as memories flashed in his mind, while taking a trip down memory lane of the neighborhood and friends he grew up with at Village A on the UP Diliman (UPD) campus. \nThe Biodiversity Management Handbook by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nThe University\'s verdant spaces are home to many indigenous flora and fauna. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1102, 'E2-1102AC', '', 'Ugnayan Diliman. Walang Bibitaw. UP Fight! Vol. 3; Nos. 1-2 (3 copies)', '', '', '2022', 'What\'s Inside\nHistory makers by Photo spread \nJD endures by Bino C. Gamba\nHe made the winning three-point shot with 0.5 second left to play that ended the UP Fighting Maroons Men\'s Basketball Team (UPMBT) 36-year title drought in the University Athletic Association of the Philippines (UAAP). \nA valuable asset by Benito V. Sanvictores, Jr.\nA team player. A prized recruit.\nReenergized sports program by Bino C. Gamba\nUP Diliman (UPD) will have a new centralized sports office. \nKnowing his priorities by Benito V. Sanvictores, Jr. \nHaving a successful basketball career is the dream of Fil-Am Zavier V. Lucero, the 6-foot-7 forward of the UP Men\'s Basketball Team (MBT).\nGrateful by Mariamme D. Jadloc\nEvery time Carl Vincent C. Tamayo, UP Men\'s Bastketball Team (UPMBT) power forward, cried during the UPMBT\'s games at Season 84 of the University Athletic Association of the Philippines (UAAP), UP fans would also get emotional and fight the urge to hug him. \nWebb looks back by Anna Regidor\nIt\'s been an interesting journey for Noah Gabriel A. Webb\nUPMBT\'s roller coaster journey by Bino C. Gamba\nIn Season 85 of the University Athletic Association of the Philippines (UAAP), the UP Men\'s Basketball Team (UPMBT), being the defending champion, was the heavy favorites. \nUPMBT Season 85 by Photo spread ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1103, 'E2-1103AC', '', 'Ugnayan Diliman. UP Diliman : 2020-2023. Vol. 4; Nos. 1-2', '', '', '2023', 'What\'s Inside\nIntroduction by Ruth Jordana L. Pison\nWhen Fidel R. Nemenzo, DSc assumed his post as chancellor of the University of the Philippines Diliman (UPD) on March 1, 2020, he was prepared to move the University towards achieving its goals in the context of a volatile global economy and an extremely interconnected world.\nA distinctly Tatak UP education in a time of the pandemic by Loren Agaloos and Jean Aaron de Borja\nAcademic excellence has always been at the center of the University of the Philippines (UP) strength and pride. \nPromoting the well-being and dignity of the community by Catherine Regina H. Borlaza\nIn order for the UP Diliman (UPD) community to effectively fulfill its public mission, Chancellor Fidel R. Nemenzo emphasized the necessity of promoting the well-being and dignity of the community by creating nurturing and enabling environments essential for effective study and work; advancing gender equality and responding to the growing need for establishing reliable and holistic mental health services; and strengthening collaborations with different constituents within UPD, local and national agencies, and communities outside the campus in making UPD a safe space for all. \nDemocratic, efficient, and innovative leadership by Larissa Suarez\nIn the face of unprecedented, enormous challenges, the University has steadfastly maintained its commitment to academic excellence and the well-being of the UP community. \nSafe, smart and sustainable : A resilient UP Diliman campus by Jean Aaron de Borja\nOne of the many challenges that the UP Diliman (UPD) community had to face because of the COVID-19 pandemic was the preservation of the campus as a safe and resilient space amidst trying times. ', '', '', '', 'Nemenzo, Fidel R. \nCOVID-19 pandemic', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1104, 'E2-1104AC', '36', 'Dean Crisostomo A. Ortigas Correspondence / Letters', '', '', '', '', '', 'Brainy Bosses : More Scientists Leave Their Labs, Take Over Top Posts in Industry : Many Succeed But', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1105, 'E2-1105AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, May 18) Upgrade physics instruction in the Philippines. 273 Santa Teresa Street. Stanford, Ca', 'Dear Cris : Thanks for your good letter. I have just had a talk with the subject of our correspondence. He is very definitely interested in the possibility of helping you upgrade physics instruction in the Philippine high schools, and I am sure he would welcome a letter from you about the kind of activities that might be involved. Address him thus : Mr. Keith Harworth, 99 Victoria Drive, Atherton, Calif. USA. I do not have a copy of the information I gave you about Mr. Harworth but I think him competent to teach physics to either teachers or students, design fixed equipment for science departments, design apparatus for physics instruction, personally carry out all kinds of fabrication opreations, instruct shop personnel in the use of hand and machine tools, and do ordinary business or personnel management. If he comes to the Philippines he will bring a wife and a son of high school age. Mrs. Harworth has some training and experience in social welfare and she told she might like to pursue a master\'s degree in that field if it is offered at U.P. If Harworth gets into your field of work I think he should be on some kind of payroll, if only for regularity of status and administration. I think I told you that he does not exactly need to be paid. He is not wealthy by the standards of Philippine millionaires but he would be rated quiet well off by comparison with U.P. faculty standards. Mr. Harworth\'s chief occupation since the war has been the manufacture of an instrument which he invented and developed for detecting metal in the stomachs of cows. I am told that cows have a bad habit of eating barbed wire and other metallic tidbits. It doesn\'t inconvenience them but tends to reduce their milk production, so dairymen are continually calling on veterinarians to remove the foreign matter. So here is where Harworth\'s diagnostic apparatus come in. It is a sort of pocket-sized radar. Harworth is now tired of this business and looking for change. It he comes to the Philippines he will get one. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1106, 'E2-1106AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, April 29) Promotion and engagement of physics teaching. 273 Santa Teresa Street. Stanford, Ca', 'I presume that title is still ok; people call me professor even though I was fired three years ago on the theory that men become automatically senile at the age of sixty-five. Actually I was ready for a change and have had some interesting experiences since brushing off the chalk dust of Standard lecture halls. About six weeks ago I wrote to Professor Magno a letter which I thought might bring him some welcome aid, and which seemed at least worthy of a routine reply. Apparently it wasn\'t. I have now heard that you are engaged in the promotion and improvement of physics teaching so I feel that you might have some interest in the matter that I communicated to Magno. I am saving myself labor by enclosing here a carbon copy of the earlier letter. Please let me know if there is anything in it that you would like to follow up. Now I know that Americans are exasperating creatures to direct and work with, but I assure you that this fellow is a better-than-average American. Last night Mary Rose and I went to delightful party in the Orinda home of Don and Sally Hansen. You would have liked it. Other guests were the Bromleys, the Holloways, the Ganes, and the Ralph Smiths. You can imagine what the talk was about. Don played Philippine records and projected Philippine slides. Everybody suffered a little nostalgia. I am presently putting in several hours a day as a Consultant at Lockhead Space and Missiles, right here on the Stanford lands. I try to help them with the x-ray spectroscopy of space and have a laboratory in which to test out and use the instruments we devise for such work. When they drop me or the work gets uninteresting Mary Rose and I will try some more globe-trotting. Mary Rose sends greetings to Teresa. Sincerely, Paul Kirkpatrick.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1107, 'E2-1107AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, August 10) Memorandum for Mr. Gorgonio Velasco, Property Clark thru the Business Executive an', 'Ever since February 14, 1961, when the responsibility of handling the donations received from AID was transferred to our office, we tried our level best to reconstruct the records from the files received from the former project director, Dean Ortigas. Memorandum receipt were prepared and sent to you for signature, but up to the present same have not been returned. Your failure to cooperate with us greatly hampered the preparation of the liquidation report and final transfer of the properties to the University. Carlos Antonio, In-Charge, Property Division', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1108, 'E2-1108AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, August 14) 1st Indorsement ', 'Respectfully referred to Mr. Gorgonio Velasco, Property Clerk, College of Engineering, through the Dean, requesting prompt and immediate consideration of this memorandum of the Property Officer. The President of the University has given instructions to facilitate the turnover of all equipment and property received under ICA-NEC (AID) Projects. As of now, the remaining stumbling block for the finalization of this turnover is the uncooperation of the College of Engineering. Jose C. Campas, Jr. Business Executive', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1109, 'E2-1109AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, August 30) Report to the President of the University of the Philippines on the meetings of th', 'Prof. C.A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines Diliman, Quezon CIty. Sir : This will acknowledge the receipt of your letter dated August 23, 1962, together with a copy of your report to the President of the University of the Philippines on the meetings of the Advisory Panel of the SEATO Graduate School of Engineering held in Bangkok, Thailand, from August 6 to 14, 1962. Very truly yours, Rodrigo D. Perez, Jr. Assistant Executive Secretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1110, 'E2-1110AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, August 27) SEATO - Unclassified\nSeato Graduate School of Engineering \nReport of the Advisory ', 'Note by the Office of the Secretary-General\nThe following communication, dated August 14, 1962, from the Chairman, Advisory Panel of the SEATO Graduate School of Engineering, to the Secretary General is circulated for the consideration of the Council Representatives : - \"We have the honour to present, herewith, our Report, compiled according to the Terms of Reference transmitted to us. We take this opportunity of thanking you for your invitation to visit Bangkok, and for your hospitality and the courtesies accorded to us.\" ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1111, 'E2-1111AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, August) Report of the Advisory Panel of the SEATO Graduate School of Engineering, Bangkok, Th', 'Members of Advisory Panel\nReport of Advisory Panel\nA. Authority\nB. Terms of Reference\nC. Constitution of Panel\nD. Regular Programs\n1. Majors\n2. Type of Student\n3. Standards\n4. Present Numbers of Students\n5. Future Numbers of Students\n6. Faculty Staff\n7. Curricula\n8. Final Thesis Requirements\n9. Development of Further Options\n10. Location of Further Courses\nE. Teacher\'s Courses\nF. Student Welfare\nG. Special Programs\nH. Research\nI. Library and Publications\nJ. Finance\nK. Acknowledgements', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1112, 'E2-1112AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, July) SEATO Graduate School of Engineering, Special Report on Future Staff Needs', '1962-63\n1963-64\n1964-65\nThai Staff\nRobert M. Holcomb, Dean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1113, 'E2-1113AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, September) ', 'Dear Sigma Pi Sigma Member : Enclosed is your copy of The Radiations which gives you news of the recent activities of the Society and also an advance story on some of the serious problems we will consider at our seventh National Convention to be held at the University of Kansas on October 22-24. Your attention is called especially to the story on page three which will give you some further information concerning the current financial situation of the Society. You will note that last year members contributed more than $6,000 to the Society. Since these contributions accounted for about one-third of the Society\'s budget, such \"alumni dues\" are not only gratefully received, but are actually essential for the continued maintenance of our organization and services. It is the hope of the Executive Council that you will want to continue your support of Sigma Pi Sigma. Will you please send your contributions 1962-63 to the Headquarters Office as soon as possible. Your contribution, deductible for income tax purposes, will be used to support the publications of the Society as well as other services we are trying to provide for our chapters and members. You can also be of real help to our Society if you will provide us with up to date information concerning yourself. For this purpose a form and return envelope are enclosed. If you wish to receive a copy of the new edition of our Information Booklet, a membership card (wallet size), or a certificate of sustaining membership (for contributions of $5.00 or more), please indicate these items on the information form. A personal note from you would be greatly appreciated, too. Sincerely yours, Marsh W. White. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
