(1114, 'E2-1114AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, April) ', 'Dear Member : In October 1962 we sent you the enclosed letter and information form, together with an issue of The Radiations dated October 1962. You were asked to return the completed form so that we could update our files with your personal data. Unless we have made a clerical error we think you have not replied to our letter. We are most anxious to hear from you and to know that we have your correct address in our files. During the coming summer we hope to send you another issue of The Radiations, with recent news concerning the activities of the Society. Although we have no desire to annoy you with repeated communications we feel that we should at least go to this additional effort and expense to get in touch with you. So we urgently ask you to let us know whether you received our October communication. In December 1962 a special Post-Convention issue of The Radiations was issued. We will be glad to send you either or both of these recent issues, upon request. We think you will be particularly interested to read about the activities of the national convention held at the University of Kansas October 21-24. Some actions taken by this convention should be of lasting value to the Society and thus will increase the worth to you of membership in the organization. We will appreciate an early reply from you. Sincerely yours, Marsh W. White ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1115, 'E2-1115AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Insignia of the Society', 'Membership Plaque.\nCertificate of Membership (\"Shingle\")\nKeys and Lapel Buttons.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1116, 'E2-1116AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, September 20)', 'The Dean, College of Engineering, U.P. Diliman. Sir : This is in reference to the letter sent to me by Mr. Carlos Antonio, Dated August 10, 1962, coursed thru the Business Executive, thru the Dean, College of Engineering, U.P. which you have shown to me (Re-memorandum receipts for the dollar equipment received from abroad), for which I have the honor to inform you that the subject memo receipts were all accomplished except some six sheets which are still pending in the office of the Chemical Engineering Department for further verification of some missing items. This is to inform you further that the accomplished memo receipts were transmitted to Mr. Carlos Antonio thru Mr. A. Cabel last September 7, 1962. Very respectfull yours, Gorgonio R. Velasco, Property Clerk\n1st Indorsement\nSept. 24, 1962\nRespectfully forwarded to the Business Executive, University of the Philippines, for his information. Oscar Baguio, Dean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1117, 'E2-1117AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, October 29)', 'Mr. President, In accordance wtih your memorandum to facilitate the liquidation of all dollar aid commodities received under ICA-NEC counterpart projects, I would like to submit the following report. So far 13 projects have been inventoried, liquidated and transferred to the University. 10 projects have not been liquidated including the present U.P. Development Project for reasons hereafter stated. The following are various problems that are encountered in the process of liquidating the dollar commodities under these projects : 1. No complete records are available from the offices of the project directors of receiving units. 2. Responsible employees and officials who were then custodians of records of these properties are now either retired or are no longer in the employ of the University. It is difficult to get in touch with them and secure their assistance. 3. No complete records as to distribution of these commodities were made by former project directors or their assigned employees. 4. Some receiving units did not record properly the commodities they received. 5. Difficulties were encountered in locating records at NEC or at ICA. 6. NEC records are incomplete as found out by the U.P. team sent to NEC to reconstruct records. There are no receiving reports of recipient units available. 7. Some of the reconstructed invoices from NEC do not describe the books delivered. They only indicate the code numbers. 8. Some items, especially books, do not have unit prices. 9. Both from NEC and AID, only the total dollar values of PA\'s and PIO/C\'s of these commodities (supposed to be given to U.P.) are available but not the list of items under each PA\'s or PIO/C\'s. Without the list of items we cannot immediately proceed with the inventory. We have to reconstruct first the list of items under each PA or PIO/C. The liquidation of these properties is rendered very difficult by the fact that the Property Division was not involved in all the transactions. All the equipment coming under various projects from 1952 up to 1960 were delivered direct to the different units of the University through their respective project directors who took charge of distributing said items. In addition, all papers, documents, invoices, and other supporting papers were in the custody of the project directors who negotiated directly with NEC-ICA but did not furnish the Property Office with duplicate copies of the documents. The central administration of the University therefore has no record of such equipment. Considering the volume of these unliquidated dollar commodities and the scanty records available, coupled wiht the fact that all these project directors and some employees concerned are already out of the service of the University, may I take this occasion to request that additional personnel be appointed, specifically to carry out this liquidation work. The present personnel of the Property and of the Business Offices are not sufficient to carry out the job in a shorter time in spite of extra efforts on their part. Respectfully, Jose C. Campos Jr. Business Executive ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1118, 'E2-1118AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, November 16) Philippine Association of Science Teachers c/o Bureau of Public Schools, Manila', 'Prof. Cristostomo Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Quezon City. Dear Prof. Ortigas : A national conference and convention of science teachers sponsored by the Philippine Association of Science Teachers, the Bureau of Public Schools, the Bureau of Private Schools, and the UNESCO will be held in Manila on December 5-8, 1962. The theme is \"Improving the Teaching of Science for Developing the Skills of Inquiry and Creative Thinking.\" In this connection, the Board of Directors unanimously approved to invite you as a discussant in physics on the subjects : 1. How effectively do the present classroom procedures assist in developing the skills of inquiry and creative thinking? What are the earmarks of a good classroom procedure that develop critical thinking? How are the skills of inquiry and creative thinking developed in the new curriculum materials such as the PSSC, BSCS, CBA, etc.? 2. How effectively are we attaining our objectives in our choice and utilization of science equipment and facilities? This particular part of the program is scheduled on Thursday, December 6, 1962 from 3:00 to 5:00 p.m at the Manila High Schools, Intramuros. Knowing your keen interest in the promotion of science in the Philippines, it is hoped that you will not fail us and will accept this invitation. Your participation will, indeed, contribute immensely in shaping the course of thinking in the conference. Very truly yours, Aurelio Juele, Vice President for and in the absence of the President', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1119, 'E2-1119AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, April 16) Victorino Salcedo High School, Sara, Iloilo', 'Dean Crisostomo Ortigas, Physics Training Program, U.P. Diliman, Q.C. Dear Sir : With the school year 1962-63 over, I\'m hereby submitting an annual report of my work in the Victorino Salcedo High School in Sara, Iloilo as substitute Physics Teacher for Mrs. Lilia M. Tugbang. The Victorino Salcedo High School (VSHS) is a typical town high school with approximately a little more than 500 students enrollment. I was given 2 Physics and 2 Geometry classes in the fourth and third years respectively. From time to time I was made to substitute in teaching General Math and Arithmetic to first and second year students in cases where the subject teacher had to leave for athletic meets as coach. This lasted for a period of 2 to 3 weeks at most. In most instances, this practice disrupted some of our class activities in Physics. So I had to resort to remedial measures. Extra classes were held on Saturday mornings for the 2 Physics classes. And when I had just my regular load, my off periods were also utilized for Physics and Geometry. The first extra classes were actually basic Mathematics classes, inasmuch as 3/4 of the seniors could hardly add fractions nor do algebraic transposition. These extra classes paid off handsomely in the end. With the Math part minimized, the solutions of problems in Physics became easier to cope with. It is with extreme pleasure that I can look back to those Saturday classes when students came, not out of threats or fear of the teacher but out of a genuine desire to learn. Perhaps, to a large extent, this display of a willingness to learn, had accounted for my enthusiasm in teaching. In my student days in U.P., I had the good fortune of being under a professor who made me feel that coming to class was an enjoyable experience rather than a \"must\". I tried to make my students feel the same way that I felt when I went to that particular professor\'s class. To break the monotony of the day\'s lesson, I tried to inject humor and refresher songs in between periods and the class even performed some calisthenics to relieve cramped muscles. I have found out that these worked to advantage and the few minutes that is \"lost\" is actually on the over-all a \"gain\", for it made the students\' minds more receptive after the brief respite. The students were encourage to ask sensible questions which finally led them to associate daily occurences with physical principles being studied. In so doing, what otherwise seemed so theoretical and abstract began to take form and with it the analysis of the problems became clearer and easier to handle. As much as possible I introduced a new lesson with a demonstration experiement which led students to think on how it was done and why it gave out the results which they saw for themselves. At first they were apt to conclude that the experiment was form of \"magic\"; for example, why is it that water on a beaker spurts when a tuning fork is placed on the surface after being struck with a mallet? Later on however, they began to think of the results as effects explainable in the light of physical principles. And little by little by they began to know why earthen jars \"perspired\", why we see rainbow colors in gasoline-spotted roads, why natural occurences which we usually take for granted in the absence of a reliable explanation. To add variety to our class activities, we held outdoor experiments. Field trips were also organized. The most prominent of these was the educational trip we had in Iloilo City where we visited industrial plants, a radio station, a printing press and a university where students were shown the science facilities of the school. To reach Iloilo City at 8:00 A.M. we had to leave Sara as early as 3:00 A.M. and although the education trip was quite taxing, the group of 120 seniors and 8 faculty members that came back that evening of the same day were gratified to know a little bit more of the common knowledge of how coke is made, how newspapers are printed, how radio broadcasts come about and the like. My teaching experience in Sara was not without difficulties however. One of the pressing problems which I encountered was the lack of textbooks and reference materials. Roughly for every 4 to 5 students only 1 book was available. To top this, in our library, there was only 1 reference book for Physics and 2 obsolete laboratory manuals. To minimize the difficulty of teaching, I had to resort partly to outlining the course of study to the students. In this connection, a \"Borrow-a-Book\" program was initiated. Now this consisted of 3 reference books I took along from Manila plus the materials gathered in U.P. like Prof. Asperilla\'s \"Physics for Filipino Students\", Ralph Wilson\'s UNESCO experiments, and the PSSC materials. The students could borrow these books during the day or loan them for overnight and even week-end uses. To further offset the setbacks of inadequate textbooks, I finally resorted to utilizing the brighter students to tutor the weaker ones. The performance of the latter determined a certain percentage of the student-teacher\'s grade. To keep up the enthusiasm of the students, I gave out small prizes at the end of each grading period to the team whose marks improved best regardless of their previous grades. These measures however cannot altogether substitute for the inadequacy of books. Since it would be highly expensive to supply schools of this kind with complete texts, I think the problem will be diminished in size if efforts towards acquiring better reference materials will be revitalized. Aside from inadequate textbooks, another major problem which confronted me was the absence of essential laboratory apparatus. The school did not even have to its name a single thermometer or spring balance, to mention a few. We used improvised materials as substitute devices; e.g. we used milk and juice cans as beakers and overflow cans, oil cans with triangular cuttings at the sides as tripods, layers of sand, gravel, and charcoal and cotton placed layer by layer in bottles as filters and the like. What we could not possibly substitute for, we bought with funds coming out of the meager allowances of the students. I tried to make the students feel that this project was theirs as much as it was mine by trying to chip in a part of my salary in the same spirit in which the students gave away a part of their allowances. We were able to raise P60.00 and with it, we bought 2 thermometers, graduated cylinders, beakers, rubber tubing, wire gauzes, alcohol lamps and test tubes. Not one of these devices was broken or even marred by scratches at the end of the year. It just shows how much the students cared for them, fully knowing that the devices were theirs. These devices were left to the school as a donation of class \'63 for the use of the coming years. The school celebrated its \"Community Day\" (it should aptly be termed High-School Day) last Feb. 26. In this connection, the Physics and Geometry classes under me sponsored a joint exhibit of science projects. With the help of Peace Corps members stationed in the Sara Elementary School, I was able to secure a UNESCO book containing interesting projects which could be fashioned out of local and easily available materials. The projects meant work but the students looked to them with eagerness. My training in wood shop and welding and soldering did me much good, as students came to ask how parts of their devices could be joined best and what materials to use. After we labored till dusk in the school grounds to finish the projects as I forbade the students to bring home their projects since it would tempt them to let others do their projects and it would thus defeat the purpose for which they are being made. I must admit that the projects were launched wiht a bit of pessimism and agitation on my part since most of them were new to me in the sense that I\'ve never made them themself. But I tried to conceal from the students whatever misgivings I had and I must say in all modesty that what came out during the exhibits was beyond me. It was a fine exhibit, if I must say so myself. The students were able to make miniature electric buzzers, telegraph key and sounder, electric quizzers, elecric doorbells, steam engins, kaleidscopes, musical bottles, a weather house, hair hygrometer, a miniuature street lighting system, revolving lamps fashioned like an aquarium operating on the principle of convection currents and many more, including a fireless cooker, sundials, and the like. For the first time in the history of the school, an exhibit of that kind was put up. Townpeople and teachers from neighboring towns flocked the exhibit room and although the day left us, students and teachers alike, worn out with fatigue, I think I still have to meet a more rewarding experience. For one thing, that event taught me never to underestimate the ability of the young. Indeed they store a tremendous capacity for invention and quite a lot of amazing ingenuity. These projects were later on donated by the students to the science room of the school for posterity\'s sake. This year witnessed the absence of the national exams given to the fourth year high school students by the BPS. In its place, the Division Office of Iloilo gave instead a division test similar in type to that of the national exams. The highest score obtained by my students in Physics was a rating of 92% which tied with the highest score of the Iloilo Provincial High School for the first time. Comparison of medians obtained by the different public schools in Iloilo is not yet possible to this date as the results are still under the study committee. According to Mr. Jose Dator, science supervisor for the Division of Iloilo, the results will be released not later than the opening of the school year. Only then can I reliably comment on my students\' performance but I am optimistic about them. This about sums up the work I have done in the Victorino Salcedo High School. Whatever success I\'ve had in the projects I initiated, I owe mostly to the unselfish support of our lady principal, Miss Fortunata Alcantara, to the members of the faculty, to the students whose devotion I feel I\'ll find hard to meet again, to the generous townpeople of Sara who on every occasion of my needs lent a helping hand without much of fuss or ado and to the undeniable blessings and guidance of God. I have no regrets for having been assigned to Sara, although I must admit that I came to the place with great apprehension not knowing a single soul. And yet funny as it may seem, I left the place I hardly wanted to go to in the first place, with a feeling almost akin to pain, for it meant uprooting the roots I have steadily sunk through its grounds with the passing of days, weeks and months. But such is the nature of my job as a member of the Mobile Task Force. I can only look forward with the hope that my next assignment will have in store for me such fond memories that I now keep of the Victorino Salcedo High School of Sara, Iloilo. Respectfully yours, Lydia C. Lopez (Mobile Task Force 1962)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1120, 'E2-1120AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, January 22) ', 'Mr. President, Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, is due to retire in a month\'s time. My office cannot issue him clearance for his property accountability because as Project Director of NEC-Counterpart Projects from 1953-1959, he could not account for several items delivered to his custody. His failure to account for many of the equipment under NEC-ICA projects prevents the completion of the full inventory of all NEC-ICA property in the University of the Philippines. As a consequence, the formal turnover of these properties to the University cannot be done. On his own request, I recommend that Prof. Ortigas be authorized to deal with NEC-AID and assist Mr. Arsenio Talingdan in this unfinished work so that this matter may be concluded as soon as possible. Respectfully yours, Jose C. Campos Jr., Business Executive, Approved : Jan. 24, 1964. Carlos P. Romulo, President, University of the Philippines. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1121, 'E2-1121AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, February 3) ', 'Memorandum for : Mr. Arsenio P. Talingdan, Management Analyst and IBM Coordinator, University of the Philippines. On my recommendation, Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas was designated by President Romulo to confer with NEC-AID on the property accountability of various ICA projects. He is given full authority to negotiate with NEC-AID on this matter insofar as it concerns him as former Project Director. He shall keep you informed of developments working independently of your office. Jose C. Campos, Jr. Business Executive. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1122, 'E2-1122AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, March 4) 1st Indorsement ', 'Respectfully returned to the President, University of the Philippines, with the following comment : I am endorsing the recommendation of Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas to give him authority on condition that he works with Mr. Talingdan who was designated as Chairman of the U.P. Committee at a conference with NEC-AID personnel last year. This work on the liquidation of NEC-AID property was entrusted by the President to the undersigned in June, 1962. Personnel assigned to do this had no records or papers to start with because the Property Office had no records of NEC-ICA properties received by the University except those received when the Executive Vice-President was made Deputy Project Director. They had to reconstitute records from documents available only at NEC and ICA offices. Subsequently Prof. Ortigas turned over a partial list which was not complete. The inventory work was done with the sanction of the Dean and the assistance of personnel of the College of Engineering. The help of Prof. Ortigas was sought through the Dean but we did not hear from him until January, 1964 when he saw me at the Property Office and he was about to retire. I agree with Prof. Ortigas that it takes a technical man to gather all the data in this particular project. In the present case, his assistance if given early enough, would have facilitated matters. It was my own idea to draft Prof. Ortigas after his retirement and request for his voluntary services so that these projects could be liquidated. I had to do this without the knowledge of the Dean of the College of Engineering. Of the several NEC-ICA projects in the University, this is one of those which cannot be cleared because our personnel report shows the University cannot account for property worth some P600,000. I am glad to know that Dean Ortigas has finally taken an active part in the liquidation of this project to which only he holds the key. Jose C. Campos, Jr. Business Executive. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1123, 'E2-1123AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, January 6) ', 'Professor Crisostomo A. Ortigas (Thru the Dean, College of Engineering) University of the Philippines. Dear Prof. Ortigas : This is just a reminder of the provision of law [C.A. 186, Sec. 12 (e), as amended] regarding compulsory and automatic retirement which in your case will be on February 2, 1964--your 65th birthday anniversary. C.A> 186, Sec. 12 (e) provides : \"(e)...It shall be the duty of the employer concerned to notify each such employee under its direction of the date of his automatic separation from the service at least sixty days in advance thereof.\" Very truly yours, Onofre D. Corpuz, Secretary of the University ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1124, 'E2-1124AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, March 12)', 'The Chairman, National Economic Council, Manila. Attention : Mr. Simbulan, Fiscal Comptroller II, Dear. Mr. Simbulan : On behalf of the University of the Philippines, the undersigned hereby requests that a meeting amongst NEC, AID and UP be held at your earliest convenience for the purpose of taking action on the liquidation of counterpart projects in Diliman. When we left your  office on 6 February, we carried the impression that such a meeting might be held during the last week of March if UP can submit before 15 March an inventory approximating the value of dollar commodities received under different PA\'s and PIO/C\'s in Diliman projects. We are delivering to you today an inventory on Form 41-A in the amount of $1,275,969.98. This amount does not as yet include a large number of books, the numerous lists for which we are still processing. We are requesting that we be allowed to utilize March 14 (Saturday) and March 15 (Sunday) for completing booklists on Form 41-A as well as for segregating Industrial Pharmacy equipment from those of the Department of Chemistry, which are mixed up in PA 2283 and PA 3034 in this $1,275,969.98 inventory. The completion of book listing and rearrangement of PA 2283 and PA 3034 will be delivered to you on or before 19 March. Hoping that this request for a March meeting will meet with your approval, I am. Truly yours, C. A. Ortigas, Former Project, Director (1953-1959)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1125, 'E2-1125AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, May 5)', 'Mr. Crisostomo Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Diliman, Quezon City. Sir/Madam : Policy No....With reference to your letter dated reinsurance please be informed that action will be taken as soon as the item or information below is/are received in this Office and subject to the regulations of the System. () A complete statement of your service record on the enclosed form duly certified correct by your superior. Report of your physical and medical examination duly recorded on the enclosed form by any government physician who conducted the same. Certified true copy of approved appointment covering the change of your status from substitute to temporary, from temporary to permanent. () Certified true copy of either your birth or baptismal certificate () Information for Membership Insurance, 2 copies of which are herewith enclosed, duly accomplished by you. () Pay in cash an amount equivalent to 3% of your monthly salary or P...as your first premium payment and accomplish the enclosed letter of authorization for subsequent premium payments to be indorsed by your Collecting Officer. () Certified true copy of your approved appointment at P...per annum effective...() Immediate compliance herewith will be highly appreciated. Very truly yours, Ramon A. Diaz, General Manager', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1126, 'E2-1126AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, July 2) ', 'Dean Crisostomo A. Ortigas, University of the Philippines, Diliman, Quezon City. Dear Dean Ortigas : This is to extend to you an offer to work with us here at Central Philippine University in the development of our Science and Math teacher training program. Your designation would be Coordinator of Science and Math Teacher Training. In this connection, you would work in coordination with our existing teacher training program headed by Dr. Nelson. You would also work closely with the Director of Instruction, Dr. Ruiz. You would be free to develop this program in consultation with the Administration as you saw fit and within the financial limitations of the University\'s budget. You would also be asked to carry some teaching load with possible assignments in the Math and Physical Department and in the College of Engineering. May we request you to allows us to for the moment to hold in abeyance the question of compensation until we can think it through more fully. Your service would begin at the opening of the regular school year in August 1964. Sincerely yours, Joseph T. Howard, President', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1127, 'E2-1127AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, August 5) ', 'Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas, Central Philippine University/ Dear Prof. Ortigas : This is to notify you of your appointment as Teacher Training of Central Philippine University on the following terms and conditions : 1. You will perform the duties and responsibilities pertaining to your above-named office and take charge of such co-curricular and extra-curricular responsibilities as the Administration may assign to you, during the following periods : August 1, 1964 to June 30, 1965. Provided, that this appointment shall not become effective for each succeeding period, as specified above, unless you shall have presented to the Administration, within the month immediately preceding the starting date of said period, a medical certificate from the University physician, or his authorized representative evidencing your physical and mental fitness to continue handling the above-mentioned full-time responsibilities for the said entire period. 2. On the basis of the foregoing full-time services, you will receive a basic monthly salary of P600.00, payable in semi-monthly installments during the effective periods of this appointment. Should it become necessary, during the term of this appointment, to revise or change your basic monthly salary in accordance with existing University policies, the appropriate rider/s embodying the terms and conditions mutually agreed upon will be attached hereto as a part of this appointment. 3. You will be entitled to the following privileges : (a) Vacation pay, at your basic monthly salary rate, for the months of May and June, on the condition that you will have rendered continuous and uninterrupted full-time service during the entire school year; otherwise, such vacation pay shall be reduced in proportion to the length of service actually rendered during the said school year. (b) Insurance benefits, if you join the existing University group insurance plan. (c) Existing Social Security benefits. (d) Free tuition for your children, who are single and undergraduate, if they study in the University, in accordance with the following arrangement : one child, free tuition; the second child, 2/3 free tuition; the third child, 1/3 free tuition; thereafter, no free tuition. This number shall be increased to include an additional child, at free tuition, for each five years of your successful full-time service to the University. (e) With the written approval of the Administration, one-half free tuition for one subject of three (3) units if you pursue a graduate course or a professional law course; or free tuition for one subject of three (3) units if you pursue an undergradute course. The approval of this privilege by the Administration shall be based on the condition that the course you will take is in your field of work. (f) Hospital privileges at the Iloilo Mission Hospital in accordance with the existing agreement between said Hospital and the University. (g) Certain leaves with pay in accordance with the existing policies of the University, upon written approval by the Administration of a proper application therefore. 4. You will give full-time service to the University, agreeing not to teach in, or be connected with, any other school or to engage in outside business or occupation without the consent of the Administration. (5) You are expected to know and observe strictly the ideals and principles of the University, among which are : (a) High standard of personal conduct and moral character, in family relationships and in personal and business dealings with others. (b) Responsibility for efficient service, as shown by punctuality and regularity in office attendance and in making reports, efficiency in the performance of office and other responsibilities, and continued professional growth and attitude. (c) Unreserved loyalty to the Administration of the University and to colleagues, as expressed in the spirit of cooperation and in the interest of safeguarding the University\'s welfare, improvement and growth. 6. You are constantly to keep in mind the purpose of the University - \"mental and moral instruction, and the manual industrial training of young men and young women, under influences which strengthen Christian faith and build up Christian character.\" Your exemplary conduct in and outside the classrooms is a part of such influences. 7. This appointment will automatically terminate, without need of notice, at the expiration of the period specified in No. 1 of this appointment, unless sooner terminated by the Administration for any of the following reasons : your refusal or failure to comply with any of the obligations stated in No. 4; or your failure to observe the ideals and principles of the University, among which are enumerated in No. 5; or when a national or financial crisis does not permit the normal operation of the University or the department in which you are connected; or for any other justifiable cause. 8. This appointment may be terminated by resignation under exceptional circumstances and for good and valid reasons shown; however, no resignation will be considered unless it is submitted at least two (2) months before its date of effectivity, and it shall be always subject to the acceptance of the Administration to be given in writing. If the foregoing terms and conditions are acceptable to you, please indicate your acceptance of this appointment by signing your name on the proper space below and returning the original and a duplicate copy to the Office of the President. This appointment will not be complete as a contract unless the aforementioned copies duly signed by you, are received by our Office within 15 days from the date hereof. Sincerely yours, Joseph T. Howard, President', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1128, 'E2-1128AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, July 17) ', 'Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas, P-1, Area I, U.P. Campus Diliman, Quezon City. Dear Dean Ortigas, I\'m sure you have already received our telegram confirming that we are willing to make your base pay P600.00 per month. This will be flat rate compensation and anything over six units of teaching will be compensated at P60.00 per three unit subject which we pay for graduate level \"overloads.\" This will verify that your services will be directly under my office. The concept of \"Coordinator\" is that you will work with not under the Directors because your project will over-lap into several different fields. It also makes it possible for me to work out this appointment without clearing with the University Board of Trustees since their policy is that \"no administrative office may be appointed without official Board action.\" Not that I would anticipate their objections but they are not meeting until the last of August and I want this finalized now, if possible. As regards quarters, I\'m sorry that actions have already been taken which make the empty mission residences unavailable. One will be used by the Fulbright professor, one by the new classes we are opening in the Elementary (if they materialize), and the other by a visiting professor for the Seminary who is due in September. I repeat my regrets that none are available. Dr. Catedral was in the office this morning and said their place is still available if you are interested. Otherwise, we might be able to try to work out something with some other faculty member on the campus if you were interested. Your \"Two-phase\" development of the program sounds most acceptable to us. I should like to add that we would like for you to work with the \"follow-up\" program we plan for the NSDB students who were here this past summer. Also it is our hope that you might give us guidance and assistance in applying for Foundation grants which could be used to develop this program. We are aware that for the 1964-65 year this would be difficult as most organizations of this sort have already written their budgets for said year but we should like to be \"working on it\" all along with your experienced hand at the helm. May we be pleased to have your definite confirmation soon relative to your acceptance of the position of Coordinator of Science and Math Teacher Training. Looking forward to your early favorable reply, I remain. Sincerely yours, Joseph T. Howard, President ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1129, 'E2-1129AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, August 14) ', 'Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas, Central Philippine University, Iloilo City. Dear Prof. Ortigas : In connection with the contract which we are holding for you, we are requesting you to get a physical examination at Mission Hospital which according to our routine procedures requires the following : \"... a medical certificate from our University Physician stating that you have undergone a thorough physical and medical examination, including a chest x-ray (not just a flouroscopy) and that you have been found to be physically fit to assume full teaching and other responsibility.\" As soon as you can present this certificate, you will be eligible to receive your contract. Sincerely yours, Joseph T. Howard, President ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1130, 'E2-1130AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, September 28)', 'Dear Daddy : Ms. Asuncion sent two sets of mimeographed materials for your PSSC approach, prepared by Ed 282 under Prof. Abarilla, Summer 1964. Shall I send them to you?  Mitos and Sandy left Saturday morning at 1:30. I took them to the airport. Sulu and her brod were there also to see them off. Bunny is much better now. She is more cheerful now than last Friday. Ricci left U.P yesterday - she did not want to go home. Affectionately, Mamma ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1131, 'E2-1131AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, September 21) ', 'Dear Cris, I just got a letter from Suwarno, saying he couldn\'t get to Manila because of a Typhoon. His plane had to overfly HongKong and go direct to Bangkok - so no chance to go back to Manila. Thanks all the same - maybe another time you\'ll get together. Regards to Mrs. Ortigas. Sincerely, Bill', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1132, 'E2-1132AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, December 15) ', 'Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas, Central Philippine University, Iloilo City. I find your proposed TTTFC Project challenging and practical even exciting as I believe it is set up to meet a crying need and also to develop the potential of manpower in this country in a unique way. No such program exists in this part of the Philippines. Far from exceeding the bounds of CPU policy, you have given substance to her traditions and educational dedication by formulating this project. Ford Foundation thinks big! They are not interested in peanuts. You have thought big. I\'m sure you are prepared to give details if they are requested. Sincerely yours, Joseph T. Howard, President ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1133, 'E2-1133AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1965, February 1) ', 'Prof. Crisostomo Ortigas, Central Philippine University, Iloilo City. Dear Prof. Ortigas : I have already given you verbal notice of your appointment as Director of Research of Central Philippine University but I herewith quote to you the action of the Board of Trustees so that it might be a matter of record with you. Their resolution was as follows : \"CPUT 651.22-11 VOTED : That Prof. Crisostomo Ortigas be appointed Director of Research of Central Philippine University in accordance with the recommendation of the President.\" A job description of this position will be forthcoming and your assistance in its preparation will be greatly appreciated. This will also inform you that you are now an official member of the Administrative Commission of the University. Said Commission has regular stated weekly meetings at 7:00 in the Conference Room every Wednesday morning. You will be a valued and valuable member of said Commission, I am sure. We look forward to a happy and productive relationship with you as our Director of Research which, as I indicated to you verbally, will include the work you are already doing in connection with Math and Science Teacher Training plus other research development. Sincerely yours, Joseph T. Howard, President ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1134, 'E2-1134AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1965, February 1) ', 'Prof. Crisostomo Ortigas, Central Philippine University, Iloilo City. Dear Prof. Ortigas : I am herewith quoting the action of the University Board of Trustees at its most recent meeting relative to the program which you have been planning in connection with the preparation of high school physics teachers. Their action is as follows : \"CPUT 651.22-1 VOTED : To approve the recommendation of the Faculty Council to offer a One Year Training Program for holders of B.S. (Pre-Medicine), B.S. Chem, etc., to teach High School Physics which will entitle students to a Certificate in Teaching of High School Physics.\" This will therefore authorize you to proceed to make all of the necessary arrangements for having this course approved by the Bureau and also to get out the necessary publicity in connection wiht it. For the latter you will work through the Public Relations Office. For the former, I believe you have already begun negotiations through the Office of the Registrar. We anticipate that this will be a very helpful and useful program in our over-all setup here in the University. Sincerely yours, Joseph T. Howard, President', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1135, 'E2-1135AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, October 21) ', 'Prof. Crisostomo Ortigas, Central Philippine University, Jaro, Iloilo City. Dear Prof. Ortigas, I am pleased to inform you that the Madrigal Singers of the Conservatory of Music, University of the Philippines are coming to Iloilo City on 26 October 1964 to sing at the University of San Agustin Auditorium at 7:00 o\' clock in the evening. This presentation has been made possible by President Romulo\'s Committee on Culture whose purpose is to bring art closer to all groups of people. Iloilo College, University of the Philippines takes pleasure, therefore, in inviting you to this concert which will be the first of its kind in our City. The presentation is free because we would like the singers to reach as many as possible. Please do not hesitate to invite other friends and music lovers because I am sure they will enjoy this unique program. We look forward to seeing you during the program. Sincerely yours, Pedro E. Abelarde, Dean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1136, 'E2-1136AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, October 1)', 'Dear Dean Ortigas, I would like to inform you about the vehicle which you requested me to inquire for. Without official quotation, but prices quiet accurate, Toyota (Willys type) w4 wheel drive w/6cylinder, all steel body and tops cost P13,800.00, same brand Toyota canvass body and tops cost P11,000.00. Willys jeep 4 wheel drive 4 cylinder canvass cover cost P14,500.00, same brand 2 wheel drive canvass cover cost P10,800.00 all new can be bought from Delta Waters, and Embassy Waters dealer for Toyota & Willys. I have overheard that your set aside fund for this is P6,500.00 I doubt if we can afford to get a brand new one for that amount. I have a chinese friend, a long time one, who just acquire a new Mercedez Benz car, he is offering his 1 1/2 year own jeep to us. I have already drive that jeep many time, its very good running condition only it was already remodel for family use. They own a Auto Supply store thats why we can rest assure that all parts of said jeep are genuine willys. They are using it for their school children and for weekend outing sometimes. A four wheel drive, transmission and differential all new according to him, body, seat, paint still look new, we can of course inspect it anytime. They are giving me one month grace time to decide before they offer it for sale, They want P5,000.00 for it. Hope to hear from you sir, regards and best wishes to everybody encircle. Most sincerely yours, Enchong', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1137, 'E2-1137AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, October 30)', 'Government Service Insurance System Form', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1138, 'E2-1138AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, March 5)', 'Dean Crisostomo Ortigas, University of the Philippines, Quezon City. Dear Dean Ortigas : In reply to your query, I wish to say that it is my distinct recollection that all equipment and other articles given to the University during my term of office as president were under the direct responsibility of the officials receiving them. It is also the practice then that lists of the items were given to the Property Custodian so that he would know who had them and who was to be held accountable for any cases. Yours very truly, Vidal A. Tan, President', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1139, 'E2-1139AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, June 25) ', 'Professor C.A. Ortigas, Area, I, P-1, University of the Philippines Diliman, Philippines. Dear Professor Ortigas : Several weeks ago, I answered your interesting letter of May 25, 1962. As I am not now certain I addressed it correctly, I fear perhaps you are waiting for my reply. Let me know whether or not you have received my letter, for if you have not, I want to send you the information you requested. Yours very truly, Keith Harworth, 99 Victoria Drive, Atherton , California, U.S.A.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
