(1140, 'E2-1140AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, March 15) ', 'Prof. Melicio Magno, Department of Physics, University of the Philippines, Quezon City, Phil. Dear Professor Magno : Although we have not met I have followed your career for several years and often wonder about the progress of the work which you and your colleagues are not performing at the University of the Philippines. The present letter is prompted by this interest. I remember your Department as chronically understaffed and overworked; possibly the situation is better today, but if you are presently in need of qualified manpower you may be interested to read on. A friend and former student of mine - a male American forty-seven years of age - has decided to move with his family to the Philippines, even though he has no definite occupational plans. He is a little tired of the culture which has always surrounded him and he wants a change. He says California is getting overpopulated, overmechanized and overconventionalized, and he pictures the Philippines as a place where he might live a little more closely to nature, enjoy a change in the human environment, and experience some warm weather, which he likes. No, he is not running away from a bad past or anything of the sort; he is an individualist who finds it natural to respond to his drives and impulses. I may say that there is more than wanderlust to his promptings. He has always worked hard and is in a position to spend the rest of his life as he pleases, and what pleases him is not the life of leisure but the exercise of his considerable abilities in activities useful to other members of his species. A remunerative but essentially unproductive job would not now appeal to him in the least, but some project - perhaps poorly compensated - which could yield him the feeling of beneficial accomplishment is what will appeal to him. As to his job qualifications, he is practically a Ph.D. in physics, having completed the Stanford course work and research required for the degree. His dissertation has been written, accepted, and bound, and an approved abridgement of it may be found in the Physical Review. He does not possess the degree because war came along and prevented his taking the final oral examination. This is an original and resourceful man who has made most of his money manufacturing and marketing his own inventions. He is an expert machinist and is skilled at electronic design and repair. A quarter of a century age he had a job as teacher of physics at the University of Hawaii. He has never forgotten his enjoyment in this brief experience as a teacher, and I feel sure that he was a good one. He has given me permission to lay his qualifications before you, though he has little idea right now as to where in the Philippines he would like to live and work. Because of my interest in UP I should like to see him go there. He could bring you some skills and abilities which the Department once needed badly and which are not easy to find or afford in the Philippine market. Please let me know as promptly as possible if you would like to have this prospect communicate with you or if you would like to receive any more information about him from me. Do pass my warmest greetings to all of my old friends in the Department. Very sincerely yours, Paul Kirkpatrick', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1141, 'E2-1141AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, October 9) 1st Indorsement', 'Respectfully returned thru the Acting Business Executive, U.P. to Prof. C.A. Ortigas, Project Director CP Nos. 420, 530, 630, 730 & 830, with the information that the Inventory prepared by Mr. G. Velasco for these Projects were traced at the Property Division as follows : 1. CP No. 420 in one page with a total value of P16,265.75. 2. CP Nos. 430, 530, 630, & 830 in 17 pages with a total value of 88,242.99. 3. Dollar Commodities in 75 pages with a total value of $890,343.06. It is suggested that the letter be changed so as to state the above figures. It is also suggested that another letter be made to cover CP No. 892, the inventory of which has been prepared by the Property Division as follows : Furniture & Office Equipment valued at P22, 260.14; Books valued at 505.00; Miscellaneous valued at 39,196.36; Motor vehicle valued at P5,041.26; Furniture & Office Equipment valued at 13,580.14; Scientific Equipment valued at 26,840.48. L.S.B. Fernandez, Project Accountant. Noted : A.L. Nepomuceno, Chief Accountant ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1142, 'E2-1142AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Tentative Constitution of the Academy of Sciences & Humanities ', 'Article I - Aims and Objectives\nArticle II - Structure\nArticle III - Membership in the Academy \nArticle IV - Manner of Election\nArticle V - The Presidency\nArticle VI - The Vice - President \nArticle VII - Meetings\nArticle VIII - Administration\nArticle IX - Finance \nArticle X - Amendments ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1143, 'E2-1143AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, March 17) ', 'Dean Crisostomo A. Ortigas, University of the Philippines Diliman, Quezon City. Sir : I take pleasure in informing you of your appointment as Member of the Science Working Group under the Office of the President. The Science Working Group is composed of the following : Ledr Marcelino E. Calinawan, Jr., Chairman; Dr. Manuel V. Arguelles, Member; Dr. Joaquin Marañon, Member; Dr. Patrocinio Valenzuela, Member; Dean Crisostomo A. Ortigas, Member; Dr. Mariano P. Ramiro, Member; Dr. Mariano P. Ramiro, Member; Mr. Hugo Fernandez, Member; Mr. Manuel C. Herrera, Member; Mr. Dominador Reyes, Member; Mr. Ramon A.D. Hermano, Member (Executive Secretary). The group shall perform the following functions : 1. To recommend ways and means of effecting an integrated and coordinated science effort for the country; and 2. To recommend ways and means of promoting the active participation of private sectors in research and utilization of products of research. This group is hereby authorized to call upon any department, bureau, office, agency or instrumentality of the government including government-owned and controlled corporations, for such assistance or information as it may need in the performance of its functions. The group will submit its report and recommendations as soon as practicable, and thereafter shall cease to exist. On behalf of the President of the Philippines and on my own, permit me to express appreciation for the valuable service we hope you would extend to the Science Working Group. Very truly yours, Marcelino E. Calinawan, Jr., Chairman, Special Assistant to the President on Science Coordination', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1144, 'E2-1144AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, October 5) ', 'Mr. Crisostomo Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines Diliman, Quezon City. Dear Mr. Ortigas : I have the honor to inform you that, at the meeting of a Committee concerned with the launching of the Philippine Academy of Science and Humanities, you have been named member of a Special Committee to nominate the first members of the Academy. The members of this Special Committee are : Dr. Paulino J. Garcia, Chairman; Chief Justice Cesar Bengzon; Minister Emilio Abello; Mr. Eugenio Lopez; Mr. Herminigildo B. Reyes; Mr. Crisostomo Ortigas; Dr. Salvador Araneta; Mr. Carlos Fernandez; Mr. Jose P. Bautista. As Chairman of the Committee, I would like to invite you to a luncheon meeting at Minister Abello\'s Office at the Philam Life Building on Isaac Peral on Friday, October 13 at 12:15 p.m. On Wednesday, October 18, there shall be another luncheon meeting of a bigger committee to determine the final structure of the Academy. It shall be held at 727 Herran at 12:15 p.m. Enclosed herewith are the minutes of the first three meetings of the Academy, its Tentative Constitution and Criteria of Membership. Kindly fill up the attached form according to your good pleasure and have it sent to Miss Emerita S. Quito, Secretary of the Committee, c/o National Science Development Board, Port Area, P.O. Box 3596, or telephone 3-64-76 local 34. With assurance of my warm personal regards, I am. Sincerely yours, Paulino J. Garcia, M.D. Chairman', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1145, 'E2-1145AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, August 22) 1st Meeting. Minutes of the First Meeting of the Committee on the Proposed Philipp', 'Members present : Dr. Paulino J. Garcia, Chairman; Fr. Isidro Katigbak, O.P. represented by a Dominican Father; Fr. Horacio de la Costa, S.J.; Dr. Otley Beyer; Justice J.B.L. Reyes; Mr. Carlos Fernandez; Mr. Felix B. Bautista; Miss Emerita S. Quito, Secretary of the Committee. Others present : Vice-Chairman Casimiro del Rosario; Commissioner Florencio A. Medina; Commissioner Canuto G. Manuel; Dr. Arsenio C. Regala; Dr. Frank CoTui; Atty. Manuel C. Herrera. At 4:45 p.m. the Chairman, Dr. Paulino J. Garcia, called a meeting to order. Each provision of the tentative By-laws (see attached copy) was discussed. A Committee on Style was set up to put the By-laws in order. This Committee was made up of Justice J.B.L. Reyes as chairman, and of Fr. Horacio de la Costa, S.J., Atty. Manuel C. Herrera & Miss Emerita S. Quito as members. It was also agreed that Dr. H. Otley Beyer be consulted regarding the criteria of membership. Telegrams were to be sent to Dr. Detlev W. Bronk, President, National Academy of Science of the United States and Prof. T.M. Cherry, President, Australian Academy of Science for similar information. The meeting was adjourned at 6:45 p.m. Minutes of the Second Meeting of the Committee on the Proposed Philippine Academy of Science & Humanities, held on September 14, 1961 at 727 Herran. Members present : Dr. Paulino J. Garcia, Chief Justice Cesar Bengzon, Fr. Francisco Araneta, S.J. Dr. Antonio Isidro, Undersecretary of Education Jose Tuazon, represented by Dra. Liceria Soriano, Mrs. Geronima Pecson, Mr. Emilio Abello, Mr. Carlos Fernandez, Miss Emerita S. Quito. Dr. Paulino J. Garcia called the meeting to order at 4:15 p.m. and promptly requested Chief Justice Bengzon to preside. Each provision of the revised tentative By-laws (see attached copy) of the Academy of Science & Humanities was taken up. Some changes in the make-up of the Academy were effected viz. that the division of the Academy be left to the members to decide. The Committee agreed to meet on September 27, 1961 at a luncheon meeting at 727 Herran. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1146, 'E2-1146AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, September 27) Minutes of the Third Meeting of the Committee on the Philippine Academy of Scie', 'Members Present : Dr. Paulino J. Garcia, Chairman; Chief Justice Cesar Bengzon; Justice J.B.L. Reyes; Rev. Fr. Francisco Araneta S.J.; U.P. Vice President Antonio Isidro; Minister Emilio Abello; Dr. H. Otley Beyer; Mr. Jose P. Bautista; Miss Emerita S. Quito, Secretary of the Committee. Guests Present : Dr. Henri Marcel GAUSSEN, Member Correspondent de l\'Academie des Sciences de France; Dr. Lawrence Fuchs, Peace Corps. Others Present : Mrs. Rolsainda C. Garcia, Dra. Josefina Magno, Miss Josefina Constantino and Mr. Ramon Hermano. The meeting was begun by a short talk of Dr. Gaussen on the French Academy of Science, a copy of which is hereby attached. He was followed by Dr. Lawrence Fuchs who commented on the momentous occasion and thanked the Chairman for having invited him to be an \"eyewitness to history.\" The members of the Committee then proceeded to go over the revised Tentative Constitution of the proposed Academy. Dr. Isidro initiated steps to formalize the organization of the Academy so that it may not be duplicated by another group. A preamble was suggested by Fr. Araneta. A committee to nominate the first members of the Academy was set up. It is composed of : Dr. Pauline J. Garcia, Chairman; Chief Justice Cesar Bengzon; Crisostomo Ortigas; Hemenegildo B. Reyes; Salvador Araneta; Eugenio Lopez; Emilio Abello; Jose P. Bautista; Carlos Fernandez. An NSDR Committee to aid in making available data needed by this aforementioned Committee was set up by Chairman Garcia : Emerita S. Quito; Josefina D. Constantino; Rosalinda C. Valenzuela; Dolores Magnayo. It was also agreed that Universities be circularized in order that they may send in their suggestions. The next meeting was tentatively set for Wednesday, October 18, 1961. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1147, 'E2-1147AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, October 3) Memorandum\nTransfer of ownership of assets bought out of ICA-NEC funds', 'First Indorsement\nOctober 2, 1961 \nRespectfully forwarded to the Project Director, Prof. C. A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, recommending that the the transfer of ownership of assets bought out of ICA-NEC funds be requested immediately in order to close the accounts of this project. \nFRANCISCO NEMENZO\nActing Business Executive ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1148, 'E2-1148AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, September 29) ', 'Memorandum for : Prof. C.A. Ortigas, Project Director for CP#630 & 730\nCollege of Engineering\n(Thru the Acting Business Executive University of the Philippines) \nAs of this date the accounts of CP Nos. 630 & 730 are still open. It is therefore requested that this office be informed of the action taken on the following memorandum sent to that office on January 19, 1961 : \"The records of this office as of May 31, 1958, show that under the NEC-ICA Project CP Nos. 630 & 730 there were acquired Building, Office Furniture, Industrial Machineries & Implement, Technical and Scientific equipment and Miscellaneous equipment valued at P273,537.09. The said assets are in that College but they are still owned by the National Economic Council and Internatioanl Cooperation Administration until formally transferred to the University. It is therefore suggested that a request to transfer the ownership of the said assets to the University be sent to the National Economic Council and the International Cooperation Administration. A complete inventory on General Form No. 41 (A) should be attached to the request, duly certified by the Property Officer of that College. Prompt attention to this matter is requested so that the books of the Project may be closed as soon as those properties are formally transferred to the University.\" As the Project accounts remain open since 1958, it is very necessary that those properties be officially transferred to the university so that the project books may be closed. \nL.S.B. Fernandez, Project Accountant\nNoted by : A.L. Nepomuceno, Chief Accountant ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1149, 'E2-1149AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, September 29) ', 'Memorandum for Prof. C.A. Ortigas, College of Engineering CP 892 (Thru the Acting Business Executive University of the Philippines) As of the present date our accounts for CP 892 are still open. It is therefore, requested that this office be informed of the action taken on the following which was sent to that office on September 12, 1960 : \"At the meetings of the Project Accountants held on July 29 and August 11, 1960, at the National Economic Council and Budget Commission respectively, we were told verbally to advise the Directors of the Projects already terminated to make request for the transfer to the respective offices of the equipment acquired as aid from the International Cooperation Administration and National Economic Council. The Trial Balance of that Project under CP 892 shows the following asset value as of Oct. 31, 1958 : 1. Motor Vehicles & Accessories; 2. Furniture & Office Equipment; 3. Books; 4. Technical & Scientific Equipment; 5. Miscellaneous Equipment. Inventory lists which should tally with the above figures must be attached with the request to be made, one for the International Cooperation Administration and another for the National Economic Council offices. The Property Clerks of the recipient units should be required to present the inventories. Prompt action on the matter is of great importance as the Project has terminated on Oct. 31, 1958 yet, while the equipment remain ICA-NEC properties until officially transferred to the University. \nL.S.B. Fernandez, Project Accountant\nNoted : A.L. Nepomuceno, Chief Accountant ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1150, 'E2-1150AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, May 2) ', 'The Dean, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines Diliman, Quezon City. Sir : In compliance with the memorandum of the President dated February 17, 1961, copy herewith attached, I have the honor to submit herewith the inventory lists of ICA-NEC equipment, Dollar Portion, for the period from May 8, 1953 up to October 1, 1959, and the Counterpart Project, Peso Portion, for the period from June 30, 1952 up to December 31, 1959, broken down as follows : ICA-NEC---$890,343.06---P1,780,686.12 (75 pages 4 copies); Counterpart Project 420 Portion -- 16,265.75 (1 page 4 copies each); Counterpart Project 430 to 930 Portion (88,242.99 (17 pages 4 copies each) \nVery respectfully yours,\nGorgonio R. Velasco\nProperty Clark\n\n1st Indorsement\nMay 8, 1961\nRespectfully forwarded to the Deputy Project Director of NEC-ICA Projects, University of the Philippines\nOscar Baguio, Dean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1151, 'E2-1151AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, March 28) 3rd Indorsement', 'Respectfully forwarded to the Dean, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, inviting his attention to the attached comments of the President. You are requested to call the attention of Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas to the same. \nJose C. Campos, Jr. \nBusiness Executive', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1152, 'E2-1152AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, March 16) 1st Indorsement', 'Respectfully indorsed to the President, University of the Philippines (thru the Business Executive), without comments. \nThe communication affects official relation between this unit of this University with a foreign institution, and as such, by memorandum from the President\'s Office dated June 18, 1959, should have been coursed through the President.\nOscar Baguio\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1153, 'E2-1153AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, March 3) ', 'Sir : This is with reference to the recommendation by the National Science Development Board of Mr. Crisostomo Ortigas as a possible qualified nominee for membership in the Advisory Panel of the SEATO Graduate School of Engineering, Bangkok. The Constitution of the Advisory Panel requires the holding of a plenary meeting of the members once every year at Bangkok, or elsewhere, but specifies that expenses of the members incidental to the meetings will not be borne by either SEATO or the Graduate School. Before the name of Mr. Ortigas is offered by the Philippine Government for nomination to membership in the Advisory Panel, this Department would appreciate being informed if your College (or the University) could defray the travel expenses of Mr. Ortigas if he is appointed Philippine member of the Advisory Panel of the SEATO Graduate School of Engineering. An early reply is requested. \nVery truly yours, \nFor the Secretary of Foreign Affairs:\nRafaelita H. Soriano\nChief, SEATO Affairs Division', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1154, 'E2-1154AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, November 3) 1st Indorsement', 'Respectfully referred to the Property Clerk, thru the Dean, College of Engineering, U.P., inviting attention to the attached Memorandum No. 01-60 of the Chief Accountant, National Economic Council. It is therefore requested that a complete inventory as of October 31, 1960, and at the end of every quarter thereafter, of the dollar commodities received as aid from the U.S. Government be prepared on General Form No. 41 (A) and be forwarded thru this office to the N.E.C. Chief Accountant. The inventory of equipment should be separated from the inventory of the supplies, and the figures should tally with the figures on the Trial Balance dated October 31, 1960. \nL.S.B. Fernandez\nProject Accountant ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1155, 'E2-1155AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, September 16) ', 'Dr. Paulino Garcia\nChairman, National Science Development Board\nHerran, Manila\n\nDear Dr. Garcia : \n\nThis is in connection with your invitation for me to represent the University of the Philippines in the meetings of your Board. As I told you, I find it difficult to be present in your meetings on account of the number of engagements that I have to attend to. I am a member of ten boards and committees outside and chairman of one dozen or more committees within the University. But I thought I could be present once in a while in your Board, not however as a member but as a visitor perhaps. The reason is that the law, R.A. No. 2067, does not make a member. In its Section 5 it provides that the \"Board shall be composed of a chairman; a vice chairman...and the following members : the chairman of the National Research Council of the Philippines, the commissioner of the National Research Council of the Philippines, the commissioner of the National Institute of Science and Technology, the commissioner of the Philippine Atomic Energy Commission, the director of the Office of National Planning of the National Economic Council, a representative from the University of the Philippines to be designated by the President of the University, one member representing industry, one member representing scientific and/or technological associations or societies, one member representing agriculture, and one member representing education.\"\nFrom this provision it is quite clear that I have no right to be present as member of the Board because it would be the height of absurdity if I appoint myself as representative of the University. Strictly speaking, it is even illegal. \nHowever, I have decided to appoint Dr. Enrique T. Virata, Executive Vice President of the University of the Philippines as the representative of the University in the National Science Development Board. \nI have also designated Dean Crisostomo Ortigas to continue as our project director; and in this connection, the University of the Philippines Industrial Research Center, Project 2.1, needs the contemplated assistance for its full implementation. I hope you will give it your usual attentive and kindly consideration. \nCordially yours, \nV.G. Sinco\nPresident', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1156, 'E2-1156AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, August 12)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Quezom City. Dean Ortigas : I was very happy to meet you after the talk of Father Glover at U.P. Monday. On my return here, I looked for that book by Hopf which Father Glover recommended. Since we are not using it at present, we feel that it may be of help to you for the members of your very select group in Partial Differential Equations. By separate mail, I am sending this to you. Science is such an exacting disciplines and there is so much need of it in our modern world that every means of cooperating in the furtherance of science should be taken. I hope that you will find this book of some help to your interested class. I know that Father Glover before his departure yesterday for the States was concerned that you have access to this book. Sincerely yours, J.J. Hennessey, S.J. Director', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1157, 'E2-1157AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, July 30)', 'Dean Crisostomo Ortigas, National Science Development Board, Herran, Manila. Dear Dean Ortigas : In behalf of the National Committee on the observance of the National Science and Technology Week, please accept my deep appreciation and gratitude for your inestimable cooperation, without which the week would not have been as successful as it was. Believe me when I say that it is only through your unfailing assistance that the great task of scientific development can be pursued to its full realization. It is with profound optimism that I look forward to the prosecution of proposals made during the Week for scientific and technological advancement. I have high hopes that with our joint efforts, the significance of the week will be translated into tangible terms for science and country. Very sincerely, Paulino J. Garcia, M.D., Chairman, National Committee 1959 National Science and Technology Week', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1158, 'E2-1158AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, July 19)', 'Note for Dean Ortigas, Project Director, CP-6030-A\nThe amount of P653.00 being paid to Quezon City Motor Service is for the general repainting of the body, general reupholstery and change of window channels and broken door glasses. Carlos Antonio, In-charge, Property Division', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1159, 'E2-1159AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, January 25)', 'Dean Crisostomo Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Diliman, Quezon City\nDear Dean Ortigas : Please accept my deep thanks for the assistance and support you and your office readily extended the NSDB and the PAEC in connection with the laying of the cornerstone of the Philippine Atomic Research Center in Quezon City last January 22nd. In spite of the limited time allowed for planning and arrangements, the final ceremonies - thanks to you and many others - achieved its basic purpose, which was to convey to the public the significant role our reactor project would play in Philippine scientific growth. I can say in all sincerity that without your generous cooperation the complete success of the cornerstone - laying program would not have been possible. Sincerely yours, Paulino J. Garcia, M.D., Chairman', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1160, 'E2-1160AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, July 14)', 'Dr. Vincent G. Sinco, President, University of the Philippines Diliman, Quezon City, The Philippines\nMy dear Dr. Sinco : After a somewhat long business trip, I am back in Chicago and I hasten to express my deep appreciation for the many courtesies that you, Dean Ortigas, and Vice President Virata extended to me during my stay in The Philippines last March. Both Mrs. Gollong and I look back with pleasure to the evening we spent together and hope that it will not be too long before you revisit Chicago so that we may have the opportunity to entertain you and your wife. Upon my return to the States, I learned that ICA/Washington has contracted with the National Science Foundation for the provision of a Science Advisor to the National Science Development Board. From Washington, we learned that the initiation of the industrial research program needs to await the report of this advisor. We can only hope that this additional delay will be short so that, finally, the long-contemplated program at the University of the Philippines may be initiated. Because of your own intense interest in the program, we intend to keep you informed of developments as we learn about them here in the States. In turn, should certain aspects occur which you deem of interest to us, we would appreciate learning about them. Both Mrs. Gollong and I would like to extend our warmest personal regards to you and Mrs. Sinco. Sincerely, Paul B.W. Gollong, Director of International Research', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1161, 'E2-1161AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, July 14)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Diliman, Quezon City, The Philippines. My dear Dean Ortigas : You can imagine my surprise to learn upon my return to the States that in spite of the numerous conversations held between NSDB and USOM/Manila, ICA/Washington contracted with the National Science Foundation for the services of a science advisor to the NSDB. His short-term assignment, seemingly, will be for survey purposes, at the end of which a report will be issued. This, of course, is different from the understanding I had in my discussions with Dr. Garcia. Be that as it may, we have been informed that action on the industrial research program will be taken by ICA after issuance of the science advisor\'s report. This, of course, makes for additional delay. We can only hope that the delay will be short so that, finally, the long-discussed and long-awaited industrial research program at the University of the Philippines can be started. There isn\'t much we can do from this end except to keep abreast of developments. It really is a pity that the program, which could have been well under way, still is up in the air. It was good to see you and Mrs. Ortigas again. Both Mrs. Gollong and I look back with the fondest of memories to the time we spent together in the Philippines. Sincerely, Paul B.W. Gollong, Director ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1162, 'E2-1162AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, December 19)', 'Research Institute Has Plant for Extracting Oil From Bran : Patents Applied for Abroad : Millers Decide to Copy Prototype From Our Staff Reporter IN The Nation. Burma : Rangoon, December 19, 1958', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1163, 'E2-1163AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, November 28)', 'Survey Reveals Large Quantities of Brazilian Ore : High-Grade Deposits Are Available at Minimum Cost', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1164, 'E2-1164AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, November 3)', 'Dean C. A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Diliman, Quezon City, Philippines\nMy dear Dean Ortigas : Last Friday (October 31)  we had the very great pleasure of a visit by Dr. Sinco and Dr. Abelarde. This visit was doubly appreciated because both gentlemen had a very tight schedule and yet managed to take time off for a special visit to Chicago and to Technology Center. Their stay in Chicago, albeit brief, did permit us to show them the nuclear reactor and the general layout of the Center, as well as to have them meet various members of our staff, including Dr. H. A Leedy, Director, and Dr. C.E. Barthel, Assistant Director. In the evening, Mrs. Gollong and I enjoyed their company immensely. A lot of ground was covered in the short time and I do feel that the discussions were most helpful in presenting to the two gentlemen what the Armour Research  Foundation is and how it could be effective in the Industrial Research Center program. In turn, their visit permitted us to get a firsthand impression of their views as well as of Dr. Sinco\'s obvious outstanding abilities. It is thus that we thank you that you made the suggestion of such a visit as you did in your letter of October 4. Now we can only await developments from ICA. With warmest personal regards. Sincerely, Paul B.W. Gollong, Manager ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1165, 'E2-1165AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, November 18) ', 'Dr. Vicente G. Sinco, President, University of the Philippines, Diliman, Quezon City, Philippines. My dear Dr. Sinco : By now you probably have returned to the Philippines. We trust the Colombo meeting in Seattle was both fruitful and interesting. Certainly, the continued participation by the Member Nations in plans for the general development of the countries is very vital. It was indeed a pleasure to have you and Dr. Abelarde here although, perforce, your visit had to be brief. We hope that the quick glance at our Technology Center, coupled with the several meetings, gave you a picture of our mode of operations. As you know, these facilities and staff would be available in any joint undertaking on the Industrial Research Center program. It is now a matter of action on the part of the International Cooperation Administration as well as by pertinent Philippine government offices. Considering the many past delays, it is essential that action is taken at the earliest possible moment to initiate the program. We, of course, continue to maintain a close contact with Washington but seemingly, the basic final decision still rests in Manila. But in any case, if we can assist in some manner in bringing about the necessary action, we would be more than pleased to do so. May we ask that you be so kind as to extend our warmest personal regards to Dean Ortigas, Dr. Juan Salcedo, Dr. Ignacio S. Salcedo, and Dr. Clemente. Sincerely, Paul B. W. Gollong, Manager', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1166, 'E2-1166AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, October 14) ', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Diliman, Quezon City, Philippines. My dear Dean Ortigas : I had just returned from Washington, where I had met with ICA regarding the industrial research project in the Philippines, when your letter of October 4 arrived. At this point I must admit to a certain state of confusion in my mind. On one hand, Washington informs me that nothing will now be done on the Industrial Research Center program until such time that the survey requested by the NSDB has been carried out and the recommendations arising therefrom have been approved. Washington is just now approaching the U.S. National Science Foundation for its recommendations as to personnel that might be able to carry out the survey. It is not the intention of Washington to use a contractor for this work. On the other hand, I gather from your letter that there is no intent to hold up on the Industrial Research Center program nor that the NSDB intends to disturb the program, and that the survey program will go on apace. Where final action on the entire matter rests, I don\'t know. In any case, it does seem as if all we can do from this end is to await developments. It is only a pity that seemingly there are additional delays. One other thing that may be of interest to you. Although your letter seems to indicate that the Armour Research Foundation is under consideration by the National Science Development Board, Washington definitely is talking in terms of issuing a general bid request to eight or more organizations. In my estimation, this somewhat a pity because in all humility I do feel that over the course of the last seven years since we first became interested in the general state of industrial research in the Philippines, we have accumulated a wealth of information and experience in the Philippines which could be of such value in undertaking any program. Too, the cordial and strong relationship we have had the pleasure of developing over the several years could be of important service in the conduct of the program. Of course, should NSDB make a specific request for ARF, then USOM/Manila as well as Washington would enter into a negotiated contract with us. Do you think that NSDB would consider such a request, or have they already expressed such preference? With respect to the visit of President Sinco, it would indeed be a pleasure for us to see him here. Therefore, we are extending to him an invitation to visit us here at Technology Center during his stopover in Chicago, as per copy of our letter to him attached. Incidentally, you may be interested in reading the new brochure that we have just issued for this Department. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1167, 'E2-1167AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, September 12) ', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Diliman, Quezon City, Philippines. My dear Dean Ortigas : Imagine our dismay to learn this week from ICA/Washington that there is further delay in the Industrial Research Center program. Seeminly, your Government has requested that a survey first be conducted. This survey, according to our understanding, would deal with industrial research generally, the position of various Philippine entities within the overall program, etc. We are not quite certain of the full details, of course, but we are disappointed that there is a further delay, one which could well be for six months or more before the Industrial Research Center program is considered. Thus we wonder if you could shed further light on the matter so that we know what the present possibilities are for any kind of participation by the Armour Research Foundation. We might add here that we could very well conduct such a survey, especially in view of the fact that back in 1951 your Government first approached us with respect to such a survey. It was only because of certain political changes that program was not initiated. Too, as you know from our many discussions and from the material we have sent to you, we have conducted numerous similar surveys elsewhere, several of them leading to specific research centers. We, ourselves, favor the concept of one organization being responsible for not only the conduct of the survey, but also the implementation of the recommendations arising therefrom. We would very much appreciate hearing from you at your earliest convenience. Sincerely, Paul B. W. Gollong, Manager ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1168, 'E2-1168AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Biography of Dr. Christopher E. Barthel Jr., Assistant Director, Armour Research Foundation of Illinois Institute of Technology ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1169, 'E2-1169AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, November 26)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Quezon City, Philippines. My dear Dean Ortigas : Recently we have heard from Mr. C.D. MacGillivray, USOM / - Manila, regarding the Industrial Research Center. As you probably have heard, the responsibility for any assistance given by USOM to the Center, has been transferred from the Education Division to the Industry Division, where it properly belongs. Mr. MacGillivray said that he had a few talks with you on this matter and that he had a copy of the preliminary plans for the Center which look alright for a starting point. Further, it is our understanding that USOM has included in its tentative aid plan for fiscal year 1958 an adequate dollar figure for services such as we might provide. At present, the overall budget is now under consideration by the National Economic Council, as well as USOM\'s own Program Office, and it is difficult to say what the outcome will be. We hope that with your own intense interest in the program and the strong efforts you are making to implement it, a decision might soon be reached. If you feel that there is anything we can contribute to bring about action, please let us know. Warmest regards, Sincerely, Paul B. W. Gollong ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
