(1198, 'E2-1198AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1952, June 13)', 'Dr. C. A. Ortigas, Head, Department of Mechanical Engineering, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, Quezon City, Philippines. Dear Dr. Ortigas : Thank you for your letter of June 5 and the interest shown in the Armour Research Foundation of Illinois Institute of Technology and its Industrial Research Activities in numerous areas of the world. Perhaps the following brief resume, together with certain publications, covering the services, facilities and experiences of the Foundation, will give you the required material to be used by you in conneciton with the projected organization of the Research Center at the University of the Philippines. The Armour Research Foundation of Illinois Institute of Technology is a not-for-profit, non-endowed scientific organization established in 1936 to offer to industry and the public a confidential, impartial research and experimental engineering service. The sixteen years have seen a steady, continous growth in the activities of this non-governmental, public service organization until today it is one of the largest industrial research institutes in the United States. The Foundation has research appropriations estimated at a volume in excess of P9,000,000 for the current year and a full-time staff of over one thousand scientists, engineers and their assistants working in virtually every field of technology. The laboratories and operations of the Foundation in the many fields of science--ceramics, minerals, chemistry, metals, cellulose, physics, are just a few--have been continually supported by the research appropriations of the numerous industrial concerns, individuals, governmental agencies, trade associations and other organizations for which its services are performed. The investigations at the Foundation are conducted under what has become known as the Armour Plan for Industrial Research, in which the combined experience, thought, and effort of the entire scientific staff is brought to bear upon each problem for its earliest possible solution. The Foundation, through its International Division, has carried on industrial research programs in other countries since 1942, furnishing to other nations the same research and engineering service available in the United States. The Division is uniquely equipped with technicians already familiar with many of the specialized requirements and problems of research in other countries. To augment the usefulness of this background, the entire Foundation staff and facilities are available, as well as the Illinois Institute of Technology, one of the leading technological institutes in the Midwest, the Institute of Gas Technology, and the Central Research Laboratory of the Association of American Railroads, all located here at Technology Center. In addition, the Division has close and harmonious relationship with leading construction firms, engineering consultants, management consulting companies, and a multitude of manufacturing corporations, and can call on these specialized outside services when required. The Division has conducted broad techno-economic surveys of entire countries, determined specific ways to aid existing industries through research, assisted in utilizing indigenous raw materials, suggested new industries and future research possibilities, assisted in the establishment and operation of research and development laboratories in other countries. For example, the Division currently is assisting in the operation of an industrial research laboratory in Mexico City, which it established in 1946. The scientists at the laboratory are working on projects that will have significant effects on various phases of the economy of Mexico--projects covering work on tannin materials, fibrous projects, utilization of waste fiber, coal and charcoal, vegetable oils and fats. The Division also is currently carrying out fibrous and tanning materials research programs in Central America and in several of the Caribbean Islands and has been conducting a study for the United States Technical Cooperation Administration in selected South American countries on indigenous non-metallic construction materials. Under the Technical Cooperation Administration program it also is fulfilling research and engineering assistance requests from India and Pakistan in the industrial fields of refractories, foundries, cellulose and paper, small scale industries, and others. At the request of the Mutual Security Agency, the International Division recently conducted a survey of the status of the State Industrial Research Institute of Burma. As a result of the survey, the Division was asked to submit a proposal for the reorganization and expansion of the Institute. The proposal has already been accepted in principle. Of specific interest to you might be our work in the Philippines. Based on correspondence and a field trip to Manila by the writer, two proposals were prepared. One proposal, submitted to the Office of Economic Coordination, covers the services of the Foundation to cooperate with the Office of Economic Coordination in the furtherance of Philippine industrial projects. The other proposal deals with the reorganization and program development of the Institute of Science and Technology. Both proposals have been accepted in principle. To give you a more detailed picture of the Armour Research Foundation and the Illinois Institute of Technology, we are sending by third class airmal several pieces of literature : Annual Report, Ten Years of Progress, Export of Know-How, El Plan Armour, Mexican Report, and To Our Sponsors. If you require extra copies of these publications, pl;ease let us know. We are adding your name on our mailing list to receive our technical bulletins. The reports on the vairous Technical Cooperation Administration projects are confidential and have, as yet, not been released by our sponsor. However, if you require any other general information about our work under the various technical assistance programs, please do not hesitate to write us. Very sincerely yours, Paul B.W.Gollong, International Division ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1199, 'E2-1199AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1952, August 26) ', 'The Chairman, Philippine Council for United States Aid, RFC Building, Manila. Sir : I should like to inform you that Professor Crisostomo A. Ortigas is being recommended to you as our project director in connection with our PHILCUSA-MSA project entitled \"Improvement of the Instructional Facilities of the College of Engineering of the University of the Philippines\". Very respectfully, (sgd.) Vidal A. Tan, President ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1200, 'E2-1200AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1953, August 22)', 'The Chairman, Philippine Council for United States Aid, Manila. Sir : I have the honor to inform you that I am designating Professor Crisostomo A. Ortigas to act as Coordinator of the Stanford Univresity--University of the Philippines contract. Very respectfully, (sgd.) Vidal A. Tan, President', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1201, 'E2-1201AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1953, August 26) ', 'Dear Mr. Crucillo : In reply to your letter of August 24, 1953, concerning the designation of the Dean of our College of Engineering as Project Director of the combined counterpart projects Nos. 20, 30, and 65 for FY 1953-54, I should like to suggest that Professor Crisostomo A. Ortigas, Head of the Department of Mechanical Engineering, be designated as such instead of Dean of the College; because Professor Ortigas has been the one doing the work and is more familiar with the various projects. Furthermore, the present Dean of the College is contemplating to retire this semester and it would be better to relieve him of this responsibility. Sincerely yours, (sgd.) Vidal A. Tan, President ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1202, 'E2-1202AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1953, August 24) ', 'Sir : A copy of your memorandum circular dated August 7, 1953, designating certain members of the faculty as project directors of counterpart projects nos. 20, 30, 31 and 65 was received by this Office. Please be informed , however, that the counterpart budgets of Projects Nos. 20, 30 and 65 for FY 1953-54 have been consolidated into one counterpart budget for the Rehabilitation of the U.P. College of Engineering. PHILCUSA now considers these three projects as one project and desires that there should be only one project director. Under the new counterpart agreement which PHILCUSA has submitted to FOA, the Dean of the College of Engineering is designated project director of the combined counterpart project. Very respectfully, For the Executive Summary : Signed : Cornelio V. Crucillo, Technical Adviser (Coordinator of Projects) ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1203, 'E2-1203AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'V. Summary Description of Project and Project Activities\nA. Summary\nThis project proposal reccommends utilization of $630,000 of FY 1957 Technical Cooperation funds for a new project which undertakes: 1. to provide technical assistance in the establishment of an Industrial Research and Training Center in the University of the Philippines for a period of from three to five years; 2. to provide the necessary machineries and apparatus to equip the Industrial Research Center laboratories and the pilot plants assigned by R.A. No. 1606 to the University of the Philippines College of Engineering. It is proposed that this amount be expanded over a period of from 3 years to 4 years. The Technical Assistance is to be sought from outstanding research organizations in the United States, such as : The Armour Research Foundation, Arthur D. Little & Co., Inc. The Batelle Memorial institute. It is recommended that a team of 3 from these research foundations be imported to the Philippines to carry on what might be termed the 2nd and 3rd phases of what has already been done by the research team consisting of R.Norris Shreve, Raymond H. Ewell, and Thomas W. Adler, which was imported in the early part of 1956 to undertake a survey of industrial research and development in the Philippines in accordance with FR 4E200 dated May 13, 1954. About $130,000 is estimated to pay for these services (T.A.) and the remaining $500,000 will be spent for commodities as follows : $100,000 in the 1st year; $250,000 in the 2nd year; $150,000 in the 3rd year. B. Project Administration. The Dean of the College of Engineering of the University of the Philippines will serve as Project Director of this project. It is aimed to provide some pilot scale organization which will serve as a small scale model for the big Scientific, Engineering, and Technological Research Institution that is contemplated in R.A. No. 1606. Republic Act 1606 which became effective in August, 1956 provides for the establishment of an Industrial Research and Training Center in the University of the Philippines. Laboratory and pilot plant equipment as well as technical assistance will be needed for the implementation of RA 1606. C. Justirication for U.S. Assistance. Equipment needed for the Physics Laboratory and Industrial Research pilot plants and service laboratories is not available in the Philippines. Technical knowledge and skill necessary to set up and use such facilities must also be provided from U.S. aids. Thru and by the Quirino-Foster agreement, the Philippines and the United States under the leadership of the latter have launched a large scale economic and industrial development programme. The success or failure of this adventure is the responsibility of both governments. In the industrial research sector, the Philippines last month, approved Republic Act No. 1606 appropriating some 4 million pesos for financing 4 specific projects which by said act were assigned to the University of the Philippines. The peso resources set up by this Act need to be reinforced by dollar commodities and services not available in the Philippines. The resulting situation that will arise in the Philippines due to failure to receive U.S. aid for this industrial reserach program in the University of the Philippines would be comparable to the predicament of a ship that had been launched into a wide uncharted sea without the benefit of sufficient fuel, adequate crew and properly calibrated navigation instruments. The U.S. is in a position to supply the necessary reserve fuel in terms of dollar commodities; loan the additional crew in terms of technical assistance personnel ; and furnish the needed instruments. This aid needs to be extended immediately in view of the fact that the ship has been launched already - launched hopefully and jointly by the two governments. \nVI. Objectives of this Project\nA. Basic Problem \nAt the beginning of the UP-SU Contract it was found necessary to change the curriculum from 4 year to 5 year program. This was necessitated by a national law requiring all students in institutions of higher learning to take 12 credit hours in Spanish. There was a serious shortage of teaching staff which meant that every faculty member was overloaded. The College of Engineering had lost all its laboratory equipment during the war. Much new equipment had been ordered through the aid of PhilCUSA and MSA and was beginning to arrive for installation. Nearly all faculty members were young and had few years of experience. No graduate courses were possible or available and there was no time for the instructional staff to improve or do research work. \nB. Principal Objectives\nThe objectives of the contract members in Engineering was to aid in any way possible to improve the existing conditions : \n1. To help out in the teaching of technical courses;\n2. To revise the 4-year curriculum to a 5-year up-to-date curriculum; \n3. To emphasize and encourage the appointment of additional teaching staff;\n4. To train some of the young faculty men by offering graduate courses leading to a master\'s degree in engineering science. \n5. To encourage the establishment of an Industrial Research Center at U.P. (In October, 1954 an Industrial Research Center in the College of Engineering was established and was recently enlarged by the provisions of Republic Act 1606. )\nC. Expected Benefits and Significance to Philippine Development. \nThe College of Engineering is now equipped with excellent laboratories in most of the departments, and it is now possible to establish contact with industry in projects of research as well as technical aid. Laboratory equipment is essential to the teaching of good engineers. Cooperation with industry is also now developing rapidly and at the second Engineering Conference to be held in March, 1957 an advisory committee will be appointed to further this development. For the future it is vital to the continued growth of industry in the Philippines that a strong technical school be available for training technical personnel and for conducting the research and development necessary to the installation and day-by-day operation of the industrial plant of the nation. \nVII. Detailed discussion of progress to date and future work plans and schedules. \nA. Progress to Date\nIn the three years of operation of the UP-SU Contract in the College of Engineering, development of the college has been steady and marked. In all areas, staff, curricula, equipment, and morale, progress hsa exceeeded reasonable expectations for the short period of time of the operation of the contract. \nAll curricula in the college have been modernized and changed from inadequate four-year curricula to five-year curricula. In addition, a new curriculum in chemical engineering has been established and curricula in sanitary engineering and industrial engineering are being formulated. The growing recognition of the college by the Filipino community is reflected in the increased enrollment, from 628 engineering students in 1952-53 to 1080 students in 1955-56. In addition to the undergraduate courses, the college has substantially increased its offering of graduate courses leading to the Master of Science degree. The faculty of the College of Engineering has been increased from 23 in 1952-53 to 54 in 1955-56. Of these faculty members, 18 have been sent to the U.S. for at least one year of advanced study in their respective fields of engineering, thereby markedly increasing the general technical ability and training of the staff. In addition, the contact of these participants with the laboratories and research installations of the U.S. has created a capacity and interest in research that might otherwise not have developed. The laboratories for undergraduate instruction in engineering have been well-equipped during the three years of operation of the contract, with only the exceptions of the chemical engineering and hydraulics laboratories. The equipment for these two laboratories is on order and will be installed in the near future. In general, the value of laboratory equipment for the training of engineers can hardly be over-estimated, and the laboratories which have been provided through NEC-ICA aid have consequently become a predominant part of the courses work offered. The engineering library has been aided in the general program for library development and is at present excellent in all phases of engineering. Curricula in fields related to engineering or necessary to the training of engineers have been helped in the contract. Several of the faculty of the Departments of Geology, Physics, Chemistry and Industrial Pharmacy, and other related fields have been sent to the U.S. for advanced training as participants under the contract. The curricula and laboratories of the department have been modified and improved. Aid to the Department of Physics is contemplated for the coming year in the form of laboratory equipment for the teaching of undergraduates. \nProgress has been made in establishing mutual beneficial relations between the College of Engineering and the industriesof the Philippines. The creation of an Industrial Research Center in the College has served to acquaint industry with the activities of the college. At the same time the research center has successfully undertaken several research projects for both the national government and private industry, e.g. the model design of the spillway for the Ambuklao Dam. An annual engineering conference between the faculty of the College of Engineering and the engineers of industry has been inaugurated, the first such conference having been held in March, 1956. \nB. Current Work Plans\nPresent work plans of the College of Engineering are designed both to continue the progress made in developing the curricula and laboratories for undergraduate teaching and to extend rapidly the efforts of the staff in advanced studies and industrial research. Modern five year curricula have been instituted in all basic engineering fields in the past. In the present fiscal year, a five-year curriculum in the field of Industrial Engineering is also to be set up to meet the demand of Philippine Industry for trained graduates in this more specialized field. In addition, to provide technical training without the scientific emphasis necessary to the granting of the Bachelor of Science degree, the College of Engineering is instituting four-year curricula in the basic engineering fields. Those curricula are designed to fill the present void of technologists by giving a solid training in technical work to those incapable of or uninterested in the scientific aspects of the fields. The future Philippine industry will require many technicians skilled in the practical aspects of engineering, draftsmen, engineering assistants, and technologists, who need not be skilled in engineering theory and design. Laboratories for undergraduate teaching are progressing. Satisfactory laboratories have been developed in electrical engineering, mechanical engineering, civil engineering, geodetic engineering, and in mining and metallurgy. The chemical engineering laboratory is rapidly being equipped. Supplies and apparatus are presently being purchased and will be installed to a large extend during the present fiscal year. The hydraulics laboratory is also being equipped during this fiscal year. However, due to the delayed arrival of some equipment for the hydraulics laboratory, completion is not expected until fiscal year 1959.\nEmphasis is being placed on development of the faculty in the present fiscal year as in all previous years. The capabilities and advanced work of the staff are being extended through study in leading engineering colleges in the U.S. Six of the engineering faculty members are being sent to the U.S. this year for 12 to 18 months of graduate study. The graduate studies, advanced work, and research of the College in future years will be a direct result of the studies of these and former participants. \nIt is of course essential that the supporting fields to engineering physics, mathematics, chemistry, etc., be well equipped with the laboratories and staff for adequate and thorough undergraduate teaching. At the present thime the Department of Physics is almost completely lacking in laboratiory facilities and equipment. During this fiscal year a visiting professor from the Physics Department of Stanford University is cooperating with the faculty of the Physics Department at U.P. in determining the laboratory needs of the university. In the following section proposals are made to remedy the lack of these laboratories. \nIn addition, a participant in Physics is presently working toward the Ph.D. degree in the U.S. A participant in the field of petroleum geology is being sent to the U.S., this year for advanced study. \nTo further develop the teaching of fundamental sciences in the high schools., plans are being developed this year to attract recent science and engineering graduates into this work. Additional studies in education and science will be set up to train qualified instructors for the precollege schools. \nIn line with the primary objective of developing a principal center of industrial research at the University of the Philippines, emphasis is being placed during the present year on the institution of research and research facilities. Republic Act 1606 passed by the Congress of the Republic of the Philippines established the Industrial Research and Training Center in the university. Prior to the establishment of this Center, the Industrial Research Center in the College of Engineering was already in operation, and had performed several research projects for Philippine industry. Projects are now in progress in the Industrial Research Center, for example, studies in the utilization of coir dust sponsored by PHILCOA. During the present year, heavy emphasis will be placed on the continuation and completion of these projects, while at the same time planning for the design and equipping of the much expanded Industrial Research and Training Center will be undertaken. The faculty of the College of Engineering will be dream upon heavily for this purpose. \nOf the dollar commodities requested in this document for the College of Engineering, it is proposed to utilize during FY 1957 $70,000 in the purchase of laboratory equipment for the instruction of physics and $100,.000 for the partial equipping of service laboratories and facilities in the new Industrial Research Center would include \nAnalytical Chemistry Laboratiory\nInstrument and Apparatus Shop\nGlass-blowing Shop\nElectronics Shop\nMaterials Stores\nThese facilities are necessary to all engineering and scientific research, and should be made available at the earliest opportunity. It is proposed to equip the more specialized laboratories in the following fiscal years. \nDetailed lists of equipment for the service laboratories and shops are being prepared. \nIn addition, it is proposed to equip the coconut pilot plant specified in R.A. 1606 by the expenditure of $50,000 during the presnt fiscal year. \nC. Future Work Plans Utilizing Aid Requested in this PPA.\nWork plans for fiscal years 1958, 1959, and 1960 are to continue the development of industrial research facilities and the training of the staff of the College of Engineering. It is proposed to send up to 30 faculty members drawn from engineering and supporting fields to the U.S. for 12 to 18 months advanced study. To further advance the training of the faculty, specialized technicians from the U.S. are requested for periods of one or two years; during fiscal year 1958, 4 technicians FY 1959, 3 technicians, FY 1960, 3 technicians. Equipping of the basic laboratories in the Industrial Research and Training Center is projected for FY 1958 and 1959. During FY 1958 it is proposed to utilize $150,000 for obtaining equipment for the following laboratories and pilot plants : Physics Research, Chemical and Biochemical Research, General Engineering Research and Textile Pilot Plant. During FY 1959, it is proposed to utilize $100,000 to equip laboratories for advanced scientific studies in specific areas of the engineering and physical science fields. Detailed specifications of the equipment items required will be submitted when planning for these laboratories is complete. \nVIII. Explanation and Expansion of Financial Plan\nA. Summary of All Project Costs \nDollars (new costs) FY 1958 - $145,000 FY 1959 - $295,000 FY 1960 - $190,000\nPesos FY 1958 - P50,000 FY 1959 - P50,000 FY 1960  P50,000\nB. Requirements for U.S. Assistance\n1. Summary by Function\na. Dollar commodities : $100,000  $250,000  $150,000\nb. Contract Services : 45,000  45,000  40,000\nc. Participants (10 for every year at P3,000 / man year)\n2. Explanation of Requirements\na. The dollars will be required for technical assistance in control laboratories and for buying equipment for equipping these laboratories as well as the pilot plants.\nb. The pesos will be required to defray transportation, living allowances, housing, as well as clerical services and office equipment needed for the technical assistants. \nC. Requirements for Pesos\n1. New costs, Pesos  P50,000  P50,000  P50,000\n2. Source : It is intended that the pesos will come from R.A. No. 1606.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1204, 'E2-1204AC', '', 'Ortigas Memoranda Incoming ', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, May 27)', 'Memorandum No. 491\nTo : Prof. Agustin Pulido, Department of Chemistry\nMr. Hugo Funcion, Department of Chemistry\nMr. Adriano Cabel, Office of the Business Executive\nMr. Fidel Camañag, Office of the Business Executive\nPlease constitute yourselves into a committee to take an inventory of equipment in the Department of Chemistry. It is requested that the inventory be started as soon as possible and a report to the Office of the President be submitted not later than June 15, 1964. Carlos P. Romulo', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1205, 'E2-1205AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, April 27)', 'Circular No. 49\nTo : All employers and employees\nSubject : Sickness Notification System\nA Sickness Notification System is hereby adopted to expedite and facilitate the payment of daily sickness allowances to employees by employers, to minimize the incidence of overpayment of such allowances and to define the respective roles of the employee, the employer, and the Social Security System in the implementation of the sickness benefit provisions of the Social Security Act. \nEffective July 1, 1964, therefore, all employers and employees shall observe the following procedures in all cases of sickness for which reimbursement will be claimed from the System, to wit :\n1. As soon as the employee is unable to report for work by reason of sickness or bodily injury, he or a member of his family or his representative shall accomplish and file with his employer an \"Initial Notification of Sickness or Injury\" (SSS Form CLD-9 N.1, copy attached), Part II of which must also be accomplished by his attending physician. \n2. This Form CLD-9 N.1 shall be duly noted by the employer in the space provided therefor, must be sent by the employer to the Social Security System within 8 days from the start of the employee\'s absence. Postage in transmitting the Form CILD-9 N.1 shall be paid by the System. \n3. In the meantime, sickness allowances shall be advanced by the employer to the employee from the first day of confinement if caused by injury or acute disease, or from the eight day, if caused by a chronic disease. In any case, no sickness allowances shall be advanced until and after all company sick leaves with full pay to the credit of the employee are exhausted. \n4. Upon receipt of the accomplished Form CLD-9 N.1, the System\'s Medical Director or his representative shall return the duplicate copy thereof to the employer with the advice to continue paying sickness benefits to the employee for the period certified to by his attending physician, or to pay sickness allowances only for such period as may have been approved as reasonable confinement. The duplicate copy of said form shall be kept by the employer. \n5. In cases where the confinement of the employee would be prolonged beyond the period originally estimated by the physician in Part II of the Form CLD-9 N.1, the employee must file with his employer an \'Intermediate Medical Certificate\' (SSS Form CLD-9 N.2), duly accomplished by his attending physician, on or before the expiration of the original period of confinement. \n6. Form CID-9 N.2 shall likewise be duly noted by the employer in the space provided therefore, and transmitted to the System within 3 days from the last day of the original period of confinement estimated by the physician in Part II of the Form CLD-9 N.1.\n7. Payment of sickness allowances to the employee shall be continued for the period certified in Form CLD-9 N.2., unless the employer shall have been advised by the Medical Director, in returning to employer the duplicate copy of said form, to discontinue payment of sickness beyond the period that shall have been approved as reasonable confinement. The employer shall also keep the duplicate of this form together with the duplicate of the Form CLD-9 N.1. \n8. Upon the termination of the period of actual medical attendance as well as the recuperation period, the employer shall require the employee to submit to him a complete and final medical certificate (Part II, Form CILD-9) which will be submitted together with the Sickness Reimbursement Claim Form (Part I, Form CLD-9) and the duplicates of Forms CLD-9 N.1. and CLD-9 N.2. previously received from the System. \nForms will be available upon request from the Social Security System. \nUpon receipt of the notices, employers are enjoined to immediately take such steps as may be necessary to establish the veracity of the information furnished by the employee regarding his state of health, so that payment of sickness allowances may promptly be effected to the employee. Failure on the part of the employee to notify his employer in the manner prescribed in the foregoing shall be sufficient cause for the employer to withold payment of sickness allowances, unless the employee shall be able to sufficiently prove his confinement within the period of three months after his illness as provided in the System\'s Rules and Regulations or the employer had knowledge or should have had knowledge of such illness. In such a case, the employer must submit such proof to the System\'s Medical Director, and shall pay sickness benefits only for such period as may be approved by the Medical Director. In the same manner, FAILURE ON THE PART OF THE EMPLOYER TO TRANSMIT SUCH NOTICES TO THE SYSTEM\'S MEDICAL DIRECTOR, OR FAILURE TO TRANSMIT THE SAME ON TIME, SHALL GIVE RISE TO THE PRESUMPTION THAT A CLAIM FOR REIMBURSEMENT FILED SUBSEQUENTLY IS OF DOUBTFUL CREDIBILITY FOR WHICH THE SYSTEM DOES NOT GUARANTEE REIMBURSEMENT EITHER IN WHOLE OR IN PART. \nOn the other hand, NO REIMBURSEMENT WHATSOEVER SHALL BE MADE WHERE THE NOTICES ARE NOT SUBMITTED WITHIN THREE MONTHS AFTER THE EMPLOYEE RECOVERS FROM THE ILLNESS. \nIn no case, however, shall this notification system authorize employers to arbitrarily withhold or deny payment of sickness allowances to employees, where it appears that the employee have taken the steps required of them. \n(SGD) BERNARDINO R. ABES\nChairman, Social Security Commission & Acting Administrator, Social Security System\n\n', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1206, 'E2-1206AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, February 17)', 'Memorandum\nTo : The Dean, Department of Heads and Property Officers of\nThe College of Arts & Sciences\nThe College of Education\nThe College of Engineering\nThe College of Pharmacy\nThe College of Veterinary Medicine\nYou are hereby requested to extend full cooperation to the former project director in the united efforts to effect the transfer of title of NEC-ICA properties under C.P.\'s 30, 92 and 86. Professor C.A. Ortigas, former project director of C.P. 30 and C.P. 92, will brief you on the difficulties encountered in the liquidation of the aforementioned properties and explore with you possible courses of action which will bring about eventually the transfer of the title of the dollar commodities as well as the peso commodities to the University of the Philippines. \nFor the Acting President :\n(SGD) O.D. Corpuz\nAssistant Vice President\n(Administration)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1207, 'E2-1207AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1962, August 10)', 'Memorandum for\nMr. Gorgonio Velasco\nProperty Clark\nThru the Business Executive and \nThe Dean, College of Engineering\nEver since February 14, 1961, when the responsibility of handling the donations received from AID was transferred to our office, we tried our level best to reconstruct the records from the files received from the former project director, Dean Ortigas. \nMemorandum receipts were prepared and sent to you for signature, but up to the present same have not been returned. Your failure to cooperate with us greatly hampered the preparation of the liquidation report and final transfer of the properties to the University. \nCARLOS ANTONIO\nIn-Charge, Property Division', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1208, 'E2-1208AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, July 20)', 'MEMORANDUM for - \nProf. Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nDean Alfredo Morales\nDirector Carlos Ramos\nSubject : Disposition of Motor Vehicles acquired through ICA \nAttached please find the latest action of the Board of Regents on vehicles given by ICA to the University of the Philippines and used by certain Colleges or units together with the concurrence of ICA to this policy of the Administration. Accordingly, any vehicle in your present custody should be turned over to the Administration, to be kept, maintained, and operated under the supervision of the University Motor Pool available for use by any unit or any authorized person in the University. \nYour kind consideration of this request will be highly appreciated. \nJose C. Campos, Jr. \nSecretary\nBoard of Regents', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1209, 'E2-1209AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, July 15)', 'Excerpt from the Minutes of the 676th Meeting of the Board of Regents held on July 15, 1960\nIII. Matters recommended by the President : (The action of the Board is indicated following the corresponding item.)\nGeneral Administration\n1. Adoption by the Board of the policy of \'institutional ownership\' of all equipment, apparatus, machines, vehicles, and other properties given by the ICA, Rockefeller, United Nations, and other outside agencies to the University of the Philippines for the use of any of its colleges or units to carry out a particular project or program, to the effect that upon termination of the project or program, said equipment, apparatus, machine, vehicle and other property shall be subject to disposition by the General Administration in the manner most beneficial to the interest of the University with the view of its maximum utilization. \nBoard action: Approval.\nCertified Correct : \nJose C. Campos, Jr. \nSecretary\nBoard of Regents', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1210, 'E2-1210AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, June 29)', 'Dr. Antonio Isidro\nVice President for Academic Affairs\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\nDear Dr. Isidro :\nI understand a question was raised recently at a meeting in President Sinco\'s office relative to the status of equipment which ICA, under the Stanford Contract, has furnished to implement the U.P. projects. These items, of course still are the property of ICA and are expected to continue to serve the activities initiated under the project, when needed. \nHowever, to make full use of these items, ICA would interpose no objection to them being considered general University equipment for business purposes, provided the project activities are not handicapped when they need the services which said items provide. This would hold especially true where over-all University funds are being used to maintain, supply, or service this equipment. \nSincerely yours, \nC. Earle Hoshall\nChief, Education Division', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1211, 'E2-1211AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, May 3)', 'Memorandum for -\nProfessor Crisostomo Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\n\nYou may remain under the accrued leave status. \n\nV.G. Sinco\nPresident', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1212, 'E2-1212AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, April 25)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Diliman\nSir : \nPursuant to the brief conference at your office Thursday noon, the undersigned has the honor of requesting U.P. President\'s ruling on his LEAVE STATUS. He is programming his activities for next school year and finds that LEAVE STATUS has to be taken into account. Upon termination of his deanship, the undersigned assumed that he automatically remained on the cumulative leave basis because less than a year before (on 1 October 1959( the U.P. Board of Regents appointed him Professor and Head of the newly formed department of Engineering Sciences and the U.P. President ordered in Administrative Circular No. 5 Series 1959-60 dated 18 May 1960 that...\n4. All existing programs, like the UNESCO Physics Training Program, ICA-NEC programs and projects, shall remain under the direct management of Professor Crisostomo Ortigas until other arrangements are made. The undersigned shall assign any future program or project as he sees fit.\"\nOf the changes that have taken place during the school year 1960-61, two are relevant to the subject of this letter, namely; the appointment of a new head of the Department of Engineering Sciences and the transfer of the functions of the Vice President of Academic Affairs to the Executive Vice President. \nThe undersigned became aware of the first of these two while he was processing some requisition involving purchase of supplies for the Atomic Energy Laboratory sometime in October. The signature of Professor Dominador Ilio appeared over the title of \"Head, Engineering Sciences\". Upon inquiry he discovered the Prof. D. Ilio had been appointed to this position two months before. (This removes one reason for keeping the undersigned under the cumulative leave basis)\nUpon learning about the second change, I consulted with the Executive Vice President. The paragraph of Administrative Circular No. 5 quoted above was touched upon. It was arranged that the undersigned continue to discharge the function that he was discharging when he and Dr. Isidro were jointly operating C.P. 6030-A. This arrangement was later modified, however, when the services of Mr. Jose Juinio ceased to be available to him in January 1961 due to the termination of NSDB Project 2.1. The modification consisted in the release of the undersigned from prime responsibility in connection with dollar commodities. \nI am attaching pertinent excerpts from my service record in the belief that the President might wish to glance at it while formulating the reply to this letter. \nVery truly yours, \nC.A. Ortigas\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1213, 'E2-1213AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Excerpts from Prof. C.A. Ortigas Service Records\nAssistant Instructor in Mathematics (July 1, 1922)\nInstructor in Mathematics (July 1, 1924)\nInstructor in Hygiene, College of Medicine (January 1, 1926)\nAssistant Professor of Mechanical Engineering (February 15, 1927)\nAssociate Professor of Mechanics (July 23, 1945)\nProfessor and Head, Department of Mechanical Engineering (October 1, 1946)\nProfessor and Head, Department of Mechanics (January 1, 1950)\nProfessor and Head, Department of Mechanical Engineering (Again) (June 1, 1951)\nActg. Dean, College of Engineering (November 1, 1958)\nDean, College of Engineering (July 1, 1954)\nProfessor and Head, Department of Engineering Sciences (October 1, 1959)\nNo Statement (June 1, 1960)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1214, 'E2-1214AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, August 29)', 'Memorandum for : \nProf. Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nSubject : Disposition of Jeep Given to College of Engineering under Former (NEC-ICA) U.P. - Stanford Contract\nIn accordance with the resolution approved by the Board of Regents in its meeting held on July 15, 1960, whereby all vehicles given to the University under NEC-ICA programs which have been terminated should be turned over to the general administration so that said vehicles may be better utilized for the greater interest of the University, you are requested to turn over the jeep in your personal possession to the University motor pool through the Director of Physical Plant. \nYour early compliance with this memorandum will be greatly appreciated in view of the urgent need for the services of a jeep. \nV.G. SINCO\nPresident ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1215, 'E2-1215AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, August 31)', 'Received from Dean C. Ortigas, JEEP, PI-2701 (U.P. - STANFORD) in running condition without the following accessories : \n1. Spare Tire\n2. Cross Wrench\n3. Jack\nJHAN B. UY\nDirector', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1216, 'E2-01216AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, August 29)', 'MEMORANDUM FOR:\nProf. Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nSUBJECT : Disposition of Jeep Given to College of Engineering Under Former (NEC-ICA) U.P.-Stanford Contract\nIn accordance with the resolution approved by the Board of Regents in its meeting held on July 15, 1960, whereby all vehicles given to the University under NEC-ICA programs which have been terminated should be turned over to the general administration so that said vehicles may be better utilized for the greater interest of the University, you are requested to turn over the jeep in your personal possession to the University motor pool through the Director of Physical Plant.\nYour early compliance with this memorandum will be greatly appreciated in view of the urgent need for the services of a jeep.\nV.G. SINCO\nPresident ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1217, 'E2-1217AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, August 31)', 'Received from Dean C. Ortigas, PI-2701 (U.P. STANFORD) in running condition without the following accessories : 1. Spare Tire 2. Cross Wrench 3. Jack\nJHAN B. UY\nDirector ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1218, 'E2-1218AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, August 29)', 'MEMORANDUM FOR : \nProf. Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nSUBJECT : Disposition of Jeep Given to College of Engineering Under Former (NEC-ICA) U.P.-Stanford Contract\nIn accordance with the resolution approved by the Board of Regents in its meeting held on July 15, 1960, whereby all vehicles given to the University under NEC-ICA programs which have been terminated should be turned over to the general administration so that said vehicles may be better utilized for the greater interest of the University, you are requested to turn over the jeep in your personal possession to the University motor pool through the Director of Physical Plant. \nYour early compliance with this memorandum will be greatly appreciated in view of the urgent need for the services of a jeep. \nV.G. SINCO\nPresident ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1219, 'E2-1219AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, August 18)', 'MEMORANDUM FOR :\nProf. Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nProf. Alfredo Juinio\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nSUBJECT : Status of the U.P. Industrial Research Center and Its Personnel\nAt the conference held in the Office of the President last Tuesday, August 9, 1960, at which meeting the following were present : President Sinco, Dr. Virata, Dean Baguio, Prof. Ortigas, and the undersigned, the status of the U.P. Industrial Research Center was finally threshed out as follows : \n1. The U.P. Industrial Research Center, being a creation of the Board of Regents and financed by the Board, is a unit of the University with the Dean of the College of Engineering as its head; \n2. All personnel working under the U.P. Industrial Research Center must be appointed by the Board of Regents or by the President, as the case may be, upon recommendation of the Dean, College of Engineering;\n3. Any faculty member of the College of Engineering receiving appointment under the defunct National Science Board has no official standing with the U.P. Industrial Research Center unless they are appointed by the Board or by the President, as the case may be;\n4. Any research project financed by any outside agency, like the NSDB, to be conducted by the staff and personnel of the College of Engineering, must be carried out under the supervision of the U.P.I.R.C. Funds for such projects must be received by and coursed through the Office of the President and the President shall designate the proper University official authorized to make disbursements therefrom.\nThis memorandum is intended to clarify the status of some people in relation to the U.P. Industrial Research Center. It shall be understood that all projects heretofore conducted by the staff and personnel of the College of Engineering under some authority other than that of the Board of without confirmation by the Board, shall be placed under the U.P.I.R.C\nJose C. Campos, Jr. \nBusiness Executive ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1220, 'E2-1220AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, August 2)', 'MEMORANDUM FOR : \nDean Oscar Baguio, College of Engineering\nProf. Crisostomo A. Ortigas, College of Engineering\nDr. Enrique T. Virata, Executive Vice-President\nUniversity of the Philippines\nAs per instruction of the President, a conference on the status of the UP Industrial Research and Training Center and its personnel appointed by the National Science Development Board, will be held as follows : \nDate : Tuesday, August 9, 1960\nTime : 2:30 P.M.\nPlace : Office of the President\n2nd floor, Administration building\nYour presence is earnestly requested.\nJOSE C. CAMPOS, JR.\nBusiness Executive ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
