(1221, 'E2-1221AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, July 19)', 'MEMORANDUM FOR\nProf. Crisostomo Ortigas\nDean College of Engineering\nAt the conference held at the office of the President on July 14, 1960, at which occasion the status of the U.P.R.I.C. was threshed out, please be informed that pending the decisions of the Natural Science Development Board on your request for continuation of the project (under the auspices of the defunct Natural Science Board), the U.P.I.R. Center created by the Board of Regents in 1954, its personnel and activities are hereby placed under the Dean of the College of Engineering. Personnel of the U.P. Industrial Research and Training Center appointed by the Natural Science Development Board have no standing with the University until final clarification of the status of the abovementioned project by the NSDB.\nBy instruction of the President : \nJOSE C. CAMPOS, JR. \nSecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1222, 'E2-1222AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, May 18)', 'ADMINISTRATIVE CIRCULAR NO. 5\nSeries of 1959-1960\nTO : All Concerned\nRE : ADMINISTRATIVE RESPONSIBILITIES IN THE COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nIn view of the recent change in the administrative head of the College of Engineering, and in order to clarify the assignment of administrative responsibilities in the various aspects of the work and functions of the College, the following rules are hereby promulgated for the guidance of all concerned :\n1. Unless otherwise specified, the administration of all academic matters shall fall within the responsibility of the Dean of the College. \n2. The incoming Dean shall have the authority of recommending changes in the departments of the College. \n3. The U.P. Industrial Research and Training Center shall remain under the direct control of the present director. However, the assignment of the faculty members of the College to the Center or the use of the equipment of the College by the Center shall be arranged by the Dean of the College in consultation wit the Director of the Center. Any disagreement in this respect shall be submitted to the undersigned for final decision. \n4. All existing programs, like the UNESCO Physics Training Program, ICA-NEC programs and projects, shall remain under the direct management of Professor Crisostomo Ortigas until other arrangements are made. The undersigned shall assign any future program or project as he sses fit. \n5. Whenever the training of faculty members (in the Philippines or abroad) or the purchase of equipment for engineering instructional use is to be contemplated under any of the projects or programs stipulated in the immediately preceding section, the recommendation of the faculty member or the choice of equipment shall be made by the Dean of the College. In case of objection on the part of the program director concerned, the matter shall be elevated to the undersigned, whose decision shall be final. \n6. The Dean of the College is hereby empowered to issue such rules and regulations in implementation of the above regulations subject to the approval of the undersigned. \n7. Any aspect of administration in the College either adjunctive or integral, not covered by the above regulation, shall be submitted to the undersigned for definite ruling. \n8. Any existing rule or regulation in conflict with the above regulations shall be considered repealed by this administrative circular. \nV.G. SINCO\nPresident', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1223, 'E2-1223AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, September 16)', 'MEMORANDUM NO. 19\nSeries of 1959-1960\nSUBJECT : U.P. Radio Organization and Operation\nTO : Dean Crisostomo Ortigas and Professor Consuelo Fonacier\nFor the purpose of assuring adequate and efficient distribution of service in the maintenance and operation of the University of the Philippines Radio Station, the following arrangement shall henceforth be observed : \n1) The technical management, including mechanical maintenance, repairs, and technical operation of the equipment of the radio station, shall be under the direction and responsibility of the Dean of the College of Engineering and his staff. He shall see to it that the license granted to the University by the Government to operate the radio is properly observed; and shall also keep the station and necessary rooms and offices in proper condition. \n2. The direction and responsibility connected with the programs to be broadcast over the radio shall be assumed by the head of the Speech Department of the College of Liberal Arts and the staff of the Department. Furthermore, the head of the Speech Department or her authorized representative shall have the right to decide what persons may use the radio and at what time and to determine what matters, musical numbers, speeches, interviews, readings, and other subjects, shall be included in all programs for broadcasting. Appeals may be taken from their decisions to the President of the University. \nThe Radio Committee previously organized is hereby abolished. \nV.G. SINCO\nPresident', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1224, 'E2-1224AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, May 19)', 'MEMORANDUM\nTo the Dean\nCollege of Engineering\nSUBJECT : Research Projects\nIn compliance with your instructions, the following list of possible research projects that may be undertaken by this department during the incoming fiscal year is hereby submitted : \n1. Evaluation of Philippine Sands for Foundry Use \n2. Utilization of Laterite Ores\n3. Study of Philippine Manganese Ores for Battery Manufacture\n4. Natural Resins for Foundry and Other Uses \nThe last two items are proposed to be joint projects with the Chemical Engineering Department.\nPERFECTO K. GUERRERO\nAssociate Professor and Accounting Head', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1225, 'E2-1225AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, December 4)', 'MEMORANDUM FOR :\nDean Crisostomo Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nBy direction of Dean Ortigas, Chairman of the Committee created by the Executive Committee of the University Council in its meeting on November 27, 1956, to study the matter regarding scholarships, please be informed that there will be a meeting of said Committee on Saturday, December 8, 1956, at 10:00 a.m. in the Office of the Dean, College of Engineering.\nAttached are the Excerpts from the minutes of the 624th meeting of the Board of Regents and a copy of the Proposed Rules for non-U.P. sponsorships approved by the Committee on Student Progress. \nVICENTE BOBIS\nAssistant Registrar', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1226, 'E2-1226AC', '', 'Ortigas Memoranda Outgoing', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, July 27) ', 'MEMORANDUM FOR:\nThe President\nUniversity of the Philippines\nCampus\nIn connection with the Memo of the Secretary of the University dated 19 July 1960, the undersigned should like to request the holding of a conference for the purpose of modifying the tone of the last statement of the aforementioned Memo in view of the circumstances enumerated below, which appear unknown to the conferees at the time of the conferences. The statement referred to is \"personnel of the UP Industrial Research and Training Center appointed by the Natural Science Development Board have no standing with the University until final clarification of the status of the above-mentioned project by the Natural Science Development Board.\" It is feared that the tone of the last sentence might ruin the channels of cooperation amongst the various sources of assistance from which the U.P. Industrial Research Center created by the Board of Regents in 1954 has up to this time been drawing nourishment. \nThe operation of the UP Industrial Research Center from 1954 to 1957 was made feasible by reason of availability of TA\'s, dollar commodities and peso funds from C.P.\'s 30 and C.P.\'s 92. The first was known as the Rehabilitation of the College of Engineering : the second, the UP-Stanford Contract. When the UP-Stanford Contract was terminated in 1957, Mr. Arnold, Chief of the Office of Technical Services in Washington D.C., recommended the incorporation of TA and Commodities in CP 92 into CP 30. And so CP 30 condinued in 1958 as CP 830; in 1959 as CP 930. In 1960 this project was expanded to include administrative aspects of UP as recommended by the Hannah team into CP 6030-A. Throughout the duration of this CP 30 projects, the UP Industrial Research Center continued to receive assistance in the form of dollar commodities, NEC pesos and TA experts. \nIn 1958 the College of Engineering begun to receive assistance from the NSDB by virtue of the provisions of RA 1606 and RA 2067. This assistance has been given by NSDB Project 2.1 in the form of furnitures and office equipment, a P200,000 building, and personnel that peform various duties, such a : taking deliveries of dollar commodities that are still arriving under NEC-ICA counterpart projects, chemical analyses for industry-sponsored projects, installation of equipment; coordination and supervision of research activities, etc. In view of the foregoing, the statement to the effect that Project 2.1 personnel have no status in the University appears prejudicial to the continuation and expansion of the cooperation between UP and NSDB. \nIn the last two years the progress of the coordination projects centering around Industrial Research has reached a stage where the components from CP\'s 30, NSDB Project 2.1, and the support from industry have grown large enough to warrant consideration of forming an autonomous unit that could be operated with little help from the regular University budget. Perhaps this matter could be explored during the conference requested above. \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nNSDB Project 2.1', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1227, 'E2-1227AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'MEMORANDUM FOR THE EXECUTIVE SECRETARY\nNATIONAL RESEARCH COUNCIL OF THE PHILIPPINES\nQUEZON CITY\nIn compliance with your request of May 2, 1958, I am submitting hereunder the following information :\nI. Researches : None. \n2. Congresses or conferences attended : \n(a) May 1957 - U.S. - JAPAN Joint Atomic Industrial Forums\' Conference in Tokyo, Japan. \n(b) July 1957 - Colombo Powers Conference in Washington D.C. on Asian Regional Nuclear Center.\n(c) Oct. 1957 - International Atomic Energy Agency First General Conference in Vienna, Europe. \n3. Special work assigned to me as member of the Section : None\n4. Fellowships, academic honors or awards received : None\n5. Membership in professional organizations : Same as previously.\n6. Membership in learned societies : Same as previously. \n7. Additional data or information of interest to the NRC : \nAt present I am in charge of the establishment of an Industrial Research and Training Center in the University of the Philippines in accordance with R.A. 1606. \n8. List of special research laboratory equipment. \n9. A black and white copy of my photograph. \n10. Any comment or recommendation to best achieve the objectives of the National Research Council of the Philippines that you wish to submit for the consideration and proper endorsement of the Council. \nI urge that scientific agencies, specially newly created ones, make use of the \"brain power\" of NRC. \nC.A. Ortigas', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1228, 'E2-1228AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'NATIONAL RESEARCH COUNCIL OF THE PHILIPPINES\nQuezon City\nTO ALL MEMBERS AND ASSOCIATES OF THE NATIONAL RESEARCH COUNCIL OF THE PHILIPPINES : \nIn connection with the preparation of the annual report of the National Research Council of the Philippines, covering from February 25, 1957, to February 21, 1958, may we request you to please submit to the Office of the Secretariat the following data not later than May 20, 1958 : \n1. Researches of individual members and associates : \na. Researches presently undertaken --\nb. Researches completed and awaiting publication --\nc. Papers published, giving references, i.e. journal, volume, year, page, co-author, if any, etc. (Please send us a copy each of your available reprints.)\n2. National or international congresses or conferences attended or participated in by the members and associates : giving : \na. Name of congresses or conferences\nb. Date\nc. Paper read, if any,\nd. Important recommendations or resolutions adopted which have bearing on the Philippines\n3. Any special work assigned to a member or associate during the year and reference to the report submitted, if any. \n4. Fellowships, academic honors or awards received during the year. \n5. Membership in learned societies (indicate if officer at present). \n6. Membership in learned societies (indicate if officer at present).\n7. List of special research laboratory equipment. \n8. Any additional data or information of interest to the National Research Council of the Philippines. \n9. A black and white copy of your photograph, postcard size (for those who have not as yet provided the Council\'s office).\n10. Any comment or recommendation to best achieve the objectives of the National Research Council of the Philippines that you wish to submit for the consideration and proper endorsement of the Council. \nYour cooperation in this matter will be greatly appreciated. \nFOR THE CHAIRMAN OF THE COUNCIL : \nPATROCINO VALENZUELA\nExecutive Secretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1229, 'E2-1229AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, February 24)', 'MEMORANDUM\nTo : The President\nUniversity of the Philippines\nSubject : Second Progress Report\nAs a result of the first progress report submitted on 11 February pursuant to the 31 January letters to NEC and ICA authorizing the undersigned to deal with NEC-ICA in connection with the alleged dependence of his clearance on the liquidation of counterpart projects, the acting president issued on 17 February a memorandum requesting various deans and department chairmen and property officers to extend full cooperation to the undersigned. That memorandum yielded as of 21 February the following findings :\nAudio-visual Findings\n1. From interviews with persons who are in the know, the undersigned gathered that at a meeting held in June 1963 for the purpose of liquidating NEC-ICA properties at Diliman UP presented an inventory amounting to $600,000. ICA advised UP to present in the next few weeks an enlarged inventory and keep ICA informed from time to time of the progress of work. Up to last week ICA had not heard from UP. \n2. During the week ending 21 February the undersigned saw vast amounts of ICA commodities sitting conspicuously in the laboratories of Chemistry, Engineering, Industrial Pharmacy, and Physics valued at no less than $567,890, which were not included in the inventory which UP presented at that June meeting. Some of these equipment are large, - so huge that one of them cannot be housed in a small classroom; others, so small that several pieces of them can be contained in a lady\'s handbag. \nDocumentary Findings\n1. In October, 1961 the undersigned assembled an inventory valued at $890,000 covering ICA commodities that were received for the College of Engineering. Two years later, that is in June 1963, this College submitted an inventory of $600,252.31 - nearly one-third smaller. \n2. Records also show that the group handling this liquidation operation received inventories from Chemistry, Geology, and Physics not a part of which was included in that inventory submitted at that June meeting. \nComments\nIn view of the foregoing findings is it any wonder that the liquidation efforts repeatedly failed? Is it any wonder that outsiders ask: \"What is U.P.\'s conception of her obligations as a recipient of foreign aid commodities?\" etc. \nRepeated failures such as those that befell our liquidation teams may be attributed to insensibility on the part of some members of the teams, and to insufficient technical knowledge and inadequate experience. This conclusion is supported by the following examples : \n1. Disensibility. This team is used herein to indicate absence of the spirit which pervades the proverb : \"Do unto others what you would have them do unto you.\"\nIn the first half of the year 1963 department heads had to submit inventory lists for the second time because the lists that they submitted the first time had been mislaid. The persons that called for the lists did not seem to sense that there was anything wrong with it. A second example is the clearance of Dean Villa of the College of Dentistry. Up to 19 Feb. his clearance had not been issued for \"lack of man-power to check the equipment\" notwithstanding the fact that Dr. Villa by paying an outsider typist finished in November the list which the UP property office required of him for the purpose of checking his accountability. If the clearance clerks were not suffering from insensibility sickness the checking would have been done in November yet. \n2. Insufficient knowledge and inadequate experience. To know where to attack is essential to a successful execution of any operation. To know how much a shot misses a target is essential to the achieving of high hitting average. On the whole, the persons participating in the liquidation efforts did not know how to deploy their efforts and did not know how much nearer their weekly efforts carried them towards the ultimate goal. They did not know that PA 3064 had nothing to do with me; and that PA 2283 and PA 3034 were not part of my property responsibility in terms of my designation in August 1952 as project director. Team members have failed to come to know these after almost three years of assignment on the job! \nThe foregoing catalogue of inadequacies induces one to suggest that something analogous to \"blood transfusion\" is needed. Some one who possesses technical knowledge and experience is needed to remedy the malfunction of the liquidation machinery and render it operative. \nThere is no one in the service of the University at present whose experience is more valuable to the prosecution of liquidation efforts than that of the former project director\'s; and there is no one who possessses as much technical knowledge of the entire lot of commodities as he. He is, furthermore, impelled by strong motivation which stems from the following : -\n1. One\'s satisfaction in finishing what he started. The former project director initiated and completed most of the P.A.\'s (Procurement Authority).\n2. The belief that his participation in the liquidation of the projects will be vindicate those who made him serve as project director. He was appointed by former Speaker Jose Yulo who was then Chairman of PHILCUSA upon the recommendation of former UP President V.A. Tan. Former FOA Director Harry Brenn gave his concurrence to the appointment.  \nRecommendation\nIn view of the foregoing it is is requested that the authority granted to the former project director in 31 January be revised to incorporate the substance and bounds of the rough-draft which follows : -\n\"You are hereby commissioned to handle the UP part of the liquidation of NEC-ICA properties covered by the counterpart projects of which you were director effective to-day until 30 June 1964 or until the consumation of the transfer of the title to NEC-ICA properties from ICA to UP,- whichever is the earlier. In the discharge of your duties you will utilize to the maximum the cooperation of previous teams.\"\nC.A. Ortigas\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1230, 'E2-1230AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, February 20)', 'MEMORANDUM TO\nProf. Juinio\nProf. Koh\nProf. Yogore\nPursuant to the attached 17th of February memorandum of the Acting President and on behalf of that office, I should like to invite you to a brief meeting at the undersigned\'s office for the purpose of finding ways and means of discharging responsibilities intimated in the terms of said memorandum on the date and time indicated below : \nDate : Today, Thursday, February 20th \nTime : 10:30 A.M. \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1231, 'E2-1231AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, February 17)', 'MEMORANDUM TO\nDr. E.T. Virata\nActing President\nUniversity of the Philippines\nIn connection with the physical checkup of NEC-ICA properties to be commenced at once in Diliman simultaneously with the reactivation of the U.P. team at NEC for the reconstruction of some project records, I should like to propose for your signature the following memorandum addressed to the deans and department heads concerned.\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1232, 'E2-1232AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, February 11)', 'MEMORANDUM TO :\nDr. E.T Virata\nActing President\nUniversity of the Philippines \nSubject : LIQUIDATION OF NEC-ICA PROJECTS 30 & 92\nIn connection with your letter dated 31 January 1964 authorizing the undersigned to participate in the university\'s effort for liquidating NEC-AID properties, he submits the following summary of the action he has taken and the findings therefrom : \nI. Action and Findings\n1) In pursuance of a suggestion from the Business Executive, on 3 January I called on Mr. Arsenio Talingdan, who is coordinating above mentioned efforts. Mr. Talingdan confirmed the Business Executive\'s previous statement to the effect that the U.P. team assigned to perform the work required for the final turnover of NEC-ICA commodities had \"bogged down\". I gathered from what Mr. Talingdan said that the team assigned to gather records at NEC was withdrawn by their immediate superior. \n2) On 6 January I called at NEC to obtain first hand information that might enhance the effectiveness of my participation. NEC officials confirmed the fact that the U.P. team had asked NEC to furnish U.P. with a detailed list of NEC-ICA properties as previously mentioned by Mr. Antonio. According to NEC the problem involved in that request was solved right there and then. NEC informed the U.P. team that NEC is not in a position to furnish such list but that NEC is not in a position to furnish such list but that NEC would allow U.P. team to look at their files. NEC is not requiring U.P. to include detailed specifications in her inventory lists. For example, \"Electric motor\" would be enough description of an item; - it is not necessary to put \"rpm\", \"voltage\", and \"accessories\", etc. \n3) On the same day I called at AID to gather further information on the status of this liquidation efforts. I was informed at AID that the inventory of NEC-ICA property submitted by U.P. as of about six months ago represented only about 60% of the total value. According to the source of this information the U.P. team was advised to continue its work and keep AID informed of the progress from time to time. The same source stated that AID had not heard from U.P. since then. \nII. Further Findings\n1) The files of the former project director show that the inventory made before 1960 covering only equipment received by the College of Engineering up to 1958 amounts to more than 60% of total value of equipment received. \n2) The team engaged in this liquidation possesses only a very hazy image of the overall picture of the project. \n3) The vocabulary of the members of the team is seriously inadequate to the extent that in some cases they are not aware that a piece of equipment that they are looking for is lying at their feet or is within the reach of their fingers. \nIII. Psychological Observations \nThe following speculation may be relevant to the liquidation efforts : it appears that the slowness of the work of the U.P. team is due to the fear on the part of the property office to face, embrace or assume the responsibility involved in connection with the NEC-ICA property because they are unable to grasp what it is. \nRecommendations\nI. In order to achieve any progress, the team assigned at NEC should be reactivated as early as possible. \nII. Simultaneously a physical checkup of equipment in Diliman using records at the former director\'s files be made at the various departments that have received NEC-ICA equipment thru C.P.\'s 30 and 92. These departments are : Industrial Pharmacy, Chemistry, Physics, Geology, Zoology and Botany, including the entire Colleges of Education, Business Administration and Veterinary Medicine. The cooperation of heads and property officers of the various departments are badly needed for this phase of work. \nIII. That the former project director be commissioned to cooperate with the property office and heads of departments concerned. \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1233, 'E2-1233AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, May 13)', 'MEMO TO\nDr. E.T. Virata\nExecutive Vice President\nUniversity of the Philippines\n\nThis is to place on the records what I understood from our brief conversation last week regarding the extension of my participation in the liquidation of NEC-AID properties involved in various counterpart projects. The work has suffered some unavoidable delay particularly with respect to PA\'s 2283 and 3034 which were issued for Chemistry and Industrial Pharmacy in 1958. The Department of Chemistry has been helping us generously but there are still about P20,000 worth of commodities that cannot be located. Maybe about one-half of these are consumable and perishable commodities. \nI had a conference with Dr. Pulido this morning. It was agreed between him and myself that further work should be done in identifying these missing equipment with respect to the probability that several errors might have been committed in marking the properties in the Department of Chemistry. For instance, it is probable that some UP-purchased equipment were, by mistake, marked ICA, while some ICA-purchased equipment were, by mistake, marked UP. The basis of the speculation rests on the fact that there is a large number of equipment present in the Chemistry laboratories which are marked Philcuss but which do not appear in the shipping documents that were reconstructed from NTC records at NEC by a team of the Property Office.\nIn view of the above, it is recommended that the commission of the undersigned \"to handle the UP part of the liquidation of ICA properties\" be extended until July 31, 1964. \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1234, 'E2-1234AC', '', 'Ortigas Correspondence Outgoing', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, October 4) ', 'Dr. Paul R. Gollong\nManager, Armour Research Foundation\nIllinois Institute of Technology\n10 West 35th ST., Chicago 16\nIllinois, USA\nDear Paul : I apologize for the delay in replying to your letter of September 12. Weeks ago it was difficult to gauge what the authoritie involved on our side are intending to do about the industrial research program. Last week, however, indications began to take on an unmistakable pattern. \nIt is now certain that in making a request for an advisor on the general aspects of research, the National Science Development Board did not intend to disturb our industrial research center program. As a matter of fact, the NSDB recommended yesterday that the Project Director of the U.P. Industrial Research and Training Center be also the Project Director of the proposed contract with Armour Research Foundation. \nI want to tell you that your interest in our efforts to advance industrial research in the Philippines is very deeply appreciated by the undersigned as well as by his colleagues. \nPresident Sinco, the new president of the University of the Philippines, left last night by PAA for his six-weeks visit to the United States. He told me that he will be stopping by Chicago but did not know when. I suggested to him to get acquainted with key officials of the Armour Research Foundation, particularly with Dr. Barthel and Mr. Gollong. He will spend most of his time in Washington and New York. If you should wish to get in touch with him, maybe you could obtain his forwarding address from the Philippine Embassy in Washington or the Philippine Consulate in Chicago. \nOur warmest regards to Mrs. Gollong and you. \nVery sincerely, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1235, 'E2-1235AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, September 12)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City, Philippines\nMy dear Dean Ortigas :\nImagine our dismay to learn this week from ICA/Washington that there is further delay in the Industrial Research Center program. Seemingly, your Government has requested that a survey first be conducted. This survey, according to our understanding, would deal with industrial research generally, the position of various Philippine entities within the overall program, etc.  \nWe are not quite certain of the full details, of course, but we are disappointed that there is a further delay, one which could well be for six months or more before the Industrial Research Center program is considered. Thus we wonder if you could shed further light on the matter so that we know what the present possibilities are for any kind of participation by the Armour Research Foundation. \nWe might add here that we could very well conduct such a survey, especially in view of the fact that back in 1951 your Government first approached us with respect to such a survey. It was only because of certain political changes that program was not initiated. Too, as you know from our many discussions and from the material we have sent to you, we have conducted numerous similar surveys elsewhere, several of them leading to specific research centers. We, ourselves, favor the concept of one organization being responsible for not only the conduct of the survey, but also the implementation of the recommendations arising therefrom. \nWe would very much appreciate hearing from you at your earliest convenience. \nSincerely, \nPaul B. W. Gollong\nManager ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1236, 'E2-1236AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Biography of Dr. Christopher E. Barthel Jr., Assistant Director, Armour Research Foundation of Illinois Institute of Technology \nDr. Christopher E. Barthel, Jr., is assistant director of Armour Research Foundation of Illinois Institute of Technology, Chicago, one of the world\'s largest independent research organizations. \nBorn in Gonzales, La., in 1911, he received his B.S. and M.S. degrees in physics from Louisiana State University in 1932 and 1933, respectively, finishing the work with highest academic honors. After serving as an instructor of physics at Washington and Lee University, Lexington, Va., he pursued further graduate work at Iowa State College and received a Ph.D. degree from that institution in 1940. \nIn July, 1941, Barthel joined the staff of the Naval Ordinance Laboratory in Washington, D.C. He was placed in charge of the Magnetic Models Section, one of the largest and most active operations of the Laboratory, and later was appointed to a three-man committee for planning buildings, grounds, facilities, and equipment for a multi-million dollar permanent plant for the Laboratory.\nHe also served as personnel advisor to the officer-in-charge and as director of personnel for the Laboratory. After the war, Barthel led the research activities of a large number of scientists and engineers at the Laboratory, including the organization, staffing, and directing of research programs in the electronic computing and controls and acoustics fields. \nFor his diversified scientific and administrative activities with the NOL during the war he was awarded the Navy\'s highest civilian honor, the DIstinguished Civilian Service Award for outstanding contributions to the war effort. \nBarthel joined the staff of Armour Research Foundation in 1947 as assistant chairman of physics research, and five months later was appointed chairman of the department. He directed its operation and management until 1950, when he was appointed assistant director of the Foundation, to plan for and direct the recruiting of staff members, classification of positions and salary administration, and to serve as counsel to staff members on personal and professional problems. \nIn 1953 Barthel was appointed director of a program for the development of the Union of Burma\'s scientific and engineering research, under a new contract between that nation and Armour Research Foundation. Under his direction, legislation was prepared and passed by the Burmese parliament for the establishment of a research board to plan and administer scientific activities, a research council to advise the government, and the Union of Burma Applied Research Institute to conduct research aimed at the industrial and economic development of the country. \nHe also directed the formation of the Union of Burma Atomic and numerous other professional and honorary groups. In addition, he has served as president of the Chicago Technical Council; engineering advisor of the Encyclopedia Britannica; a member of the board of directors, chairman of the board, and president of the National Electronics Conference; member of the electronics committee of the Research and Development Board of the National Military Establishment, and chairman of the 1957 National Industrial Research Conference. \nBarthel edited two volumes of the Proceedings of the National Electronics Conference and has written numerous articles and given addresses on technical subjects, research management, personnel administration and Burma. \nBarthel resides with his wife and two children at 1135 Jeffrey Court, North, Northbrook, Ill. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1237, 'E2-1237AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, November 10)', 'Dr. Paul B.W. Gollong\nManager, Armour Research Foundation\nIllinois Institute of Technology\nTechnology Center, 10 West 35th Str\nChicago 16, Illinois\nMy dear Dr. Gollong : \nI have just opened your letter of November 3 informing me that President Sinco and Dr. Abelarde had made a brief visit at the Technology Center. I note with pleasure your last statement which expresses hopes that further development from ICA might be favorable. \nWith respect to your letter of October 14 the answer to which is delayed because I did not know really how to answer it, I wish to say that the gloom that it generated in me has just been dispelled by your November 3 letter. \nI shall take the liberty of showing your letter to President. Since when he arrives here in Diliman with special reference to \"President Since\'s obvious outstanding abilities.\" I am hoping that visit of President Sinco will give him additional enthusiasm to enlist ICA support for our industrial research activities in the U.P.\nWith warmest regards to you and Mrs. Gollong, I am\nVery sincerely yours, \nC.A. Ortigas\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1238, 'E2-1238AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, December 4)', 'Mr. Conrado P. Sevilla\nExecutive Vice President\nPhilippine National Bank\nManila\nDear Mr. Sevilla :\nThis is in connection with your daughter, Rosario E. Sevilla, who is now at Yale Medical Center. You will recall that Dr. Lara, you and I agreed yesterday that I shall send you a note with respect to Dr. Byerly\'s advise as to what your daughter should do in the United States for the purpose of preparing her for helping the Philippine Government in the future in its atomic energy program. Dr. Byerly, after hearing the background of your daughter, suggested that she get acquainted with techniques of using instruments and apparati that are required for atomic energy laboratory technicians. These apparati are as follows :\nPocket Dosimeter with Charger\nGlass Dosimeter and Computer-Indicator\nHand and Foot Counter\nIonization Chamber Type Monitor\nProportional Type Monitor Sensing Element\nGeiger-Mueller Tyoe Monitor\nElectroscope Charger and Indicator\nScientillation Type Monitor Sensing Element\nRemote Area Monitor\nAirborne Particle Monitor\nScaler\nRatemeter\nEtc.\nVery truly yours,\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1239, 'E2-1239AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, February 5)', 'Capt. Cesar Mamon\nCanlubang Sugar Estate\nCanlubang, Laguna\nDear Cesar :\nWe have some American visitors who are assisting the University of the Philippines in its rehabilitation and expansion. We are planning to visit you, with your permission, on Saturday, February 14, 1959. There will be between ten and fifteen in our party. \nThis team is headed by Dr. Thomas H. Hamilton, Vice-President Michigan State University. You have already met one of the members of this party, a physicist by the name of Dr. Paul Byerly, Jr., who was with us hen Miss Yulo played hostess to the party of Commissioner Graham of the U.S. Atomic Energy Commission. Dr. Hamilton is very much interested in agriculture and agricultural activities in the Philippines. \nI hope that you can make the arrangements for us to see the factory, the fields, the dairy, etc. \nThanking you very much for your kindness, I am \nSincerely yours,\nC.A. Ortigas\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1240, 'E2-1240AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, February 25)', 'Message for Philippinensian\nI am happy to note that \"The Dignity of Man\" has been chosen as the theme of the 1959 Philippinensian. To the staff of this publication - congratulations for this choice : \nThe dignity of man is not separable from the dignity of labor. The U.P. College of Engineering has always insisted that her students observe the dignity of labor - both manual and intellectual. The undersigned believes that efforts dedicated to the learning of new knowledge and the acquisition of useful skill shape the life of any student into a pattern within which he or she achieves the highest form of fulfillment of the noblest aspirations of mankind under any regime. \nC.A. Ortigas\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1241, 'E2-1241AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, January 27)', 'The Dean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Rizal\nDear Sir/Madam :\nWe have this honor to inform you that we need your message for the 1959 PHILIPPINENSIAN. This year\'s theme is \"The Dignity of Man\". In this connection, we would be extremely grateful if, in writing your message, you would lay particular emphasis on the relation of your college to this theme--how the graduates can work toward dignifying man, how they can dedicate themselves to the fulfillment of the nobler aspirations of man. \nLikewise, kindly send us a list of the Faculty of Instruction of your college with their respective degrees, honors, and schools attended. \nMay we expect your message before February 20, 1959?\nRespectfully yours, \nMIGUEL A. ENRIQUEZ, JR. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1242, 'E2-1242AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, March 17)', 'Dr. Jose C. Locsin\nChairman\nNational Economic Council\nManila \nDear Dr. Locsin : \nThe U.P. College of Engineering has a visitor who is very desirous of calling on you. He is Mr. Paul B.W. Gollong, Manager of the International Division of the Armour Research Foundation, who is stopping here in Manila for a few days on his way to review their operations in Burma in connection with the Institute of Applied Research of the Union of Burma which was established through contract between the Government of Burma and the Government of the United States. It is contemplated that the call, if granted, will take place on Wednesday afternoon, March 18. \nThe undersigned will deeply appreciate a reply at your earliest convenience, - by the bearer of this note, if possible.\nVery truly yours, \nC.A. Ortigas\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1243, 'E2-1243AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, April 20) ', 'President Teodoro Evangelista\nFar Eastern University\nQuezon Blvd., Manila \nDear President Evangelista : Pursuant to our discussion at the meeting of the National Science Development Board on April 10, 1959, Dr. Byerly contacted Dr. Brings on April 15, 1959. Dr. Brings expressed his desire to teach the course E.S. 201 (Advanced Mathematical Methods in Engineering), one of the courses in the University of the Philippines Atomic Energy Training Program leading to the degree of Master of Engineering (Atomic Energy). This course would meet from 4 to 6 P.M., Monday through Friday or other times as arranged between Dr. Brings and the students. The course will start on Monday, April 20, 1959 and continue for six weeks. \nUpon your concurrence of this matter, we will proceed to procure a temporary professorial lecturer\'s position for Dr. Brings for the Summer session. In addition, I have already sent a letter to the National Science Development Board for compensation for Dr. Brings. Approval of this interest for financing under Project 2.1 will provide compensation for Dr. Brings services. \nSincerely yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean\n(5 copies) ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1244, 'E2-1244AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, April 23)', 'Dr. Thomas H. Hamilton\nVice President for Academic Affairs\nMICHIGAN STATE UNIVERSITY\nEast Lansing, Michigan\nU.S.A.\nDear Dr. Hamilton : It is with deep gratitude that I hereby acknowledge receipt of the two reports on MSUO curriculum. These reports will certainly be of great help in the updating of our curriculum in line with the general education program. With warm regards, I am \nYours sincerely, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1245, 'E2-1245AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, April 17) ', 'Dr. C. A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\nDear Dean Ortigas : Please find enclosed two reports on MSUO curriculum. I hope you will find them helpful. \nSincerely, \nThomas H. Hamilton\nVice President ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1246, 'E2-1246AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, April 6) ', 'Dr. Thomas H. Hamilton\nVice President\nMichigan State University\nEast Lansing, Michigan\nU.S.A.\nDear Dr. Hamilton : I received this morning two envelopes each containing \"The Meadow Brook Seminars on Higher Learning\". Thank you very much for your thoughtfulness. The material that you sent at an earlier date referred to in your letter did not arrived at all. I wonder if it was different from the one that arrived this morning. I suspect that material might be the engineering program proposed for MSU-O. If it were, then it is something that we would like to have very much. Mrs. Ortigas as well as many of your friends here are in good health; they are joining me in extending to you their warmest. \nSincerely yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1247, 'E2-1247AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, March 23)', 'Dr. Thomas Hamilton\nVice President\nMichigan State University\nEast Lansing, Michigan\nU.S.A.\nDear Mr. Hamilton : \nThe work on the general education program in the University of the Philippines has reached such a stage that we in the College of Engineering feel optimistic about putting into effect in Diliman this coming June a 5-year B.S. program in engineering similar to the MSUO curriculum which was evolved from the seminars of distinguished educators represented by the President of the California Institute of Technology, a distinguished professor of Yale University, the Dean of Engineering of MIT, the Dean of Engineering of MSU, etc. \nI should like to renew my request for the above-mentioned materials. Thanking you in advance for your kind attention, I am \nYours truly,\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1248, 'E2-1248AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, June 12) ', 'Prof. Wyeth Allen, Chairman\nDepartment of Industrial Engineering\nCollege of Engineering\nUNIVERSITY OF MICHIGAN\nAnn Arbor, Michigan\nDear Professor Allen :\nI am sorry that we missed each other when you stopped by on your way home from Tokyo. Here\'s hoping that some day we shall see living a very active life with the young people on the Waseda contract. \nI will be glad to meet Dr. Schuck. I shall lookl out for him and inform him about your letter and my reply to you. \nWith best wishes, I am \nYours sincerely, \nC.A. Ortigas\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1249, 'E2-1249AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, April 22)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\nDear Dean Ortigas : Mrs. Allen and I stopped in Manila for a day and a half on our way home from Tokyo early this year in order to attend a University of Michigan affair. I was quite disappointed not to see you but I found out from out from your office that you were away at that time. \nAs you probably know, the Boy Scouts are having a big event in your country this summer and Dr. Arthur Schuck, Chief Executive in the United States, will attend. Dr. Schuck is a very good friend of mine and I have given him your name and hope that you have a chance to meet him. Anything you can do for him will be much appreciated. \nAs you probably know, when Professor Ericksen returned, I gave him a half time job helping take care of the Japanese professors who came on our Waseda contract. He is certainly a fine man on this kind of work and the men just love him. Some day, when you have a few minutes time, I would be interested in knowing how you are getting along with the Industrial Engineering Department. \nSincerely, ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1250, 'E2-1250AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, June 26)', 'Mr. Paul D. Summers\nDirector of I.C.A.\nManila\nDear Mr. Summers :\nI deeply appreciate your having given us a choice of three alternate dates, July 5, July 7, and July 13. Of these three, President Sinco indicated that he would be free on July 13. The time, however, that is being suggested by him is 5:30 p.m. The idea is that if we start 5:30 p.m. there would be longer time for conversation. He also indicated his desire to invite your two top men in the Education Division - Dr. Myers and Dr. Hoshall.\nPlease let me know if the time and date are acceptable to you so we could make arrangements for sending out invitations. \nSincerely yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS \nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1251, 'E2-1251AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, July 31) ', 'Mr. Gabino A. Mendoza\nExecutive Secretary\nPHILIPPINE CHAMBER OF TECHNOLOGY\n516 Roman Santos Building\nPlaza Goiti, Manila\nDear Mr. Mendoza : \nPursuant to your letter of July 25, I have the pleasure of accepting the invitation of the Philippine Chamber of Technology to join said Chamber as a regular member. Although at the present time I do not see how my joining the Philippine Chamber of Technology would help this Chamber, it is hoped that acquaintance with its operations will suggest ways and means for doing so in the near future. Please indicate further steps necessary toward becoming a regular member. \nYours sincerely, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
