(1252, 'E2-1252AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, July 25)', 'Mr. C.A. Ortigas\nDean, College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\nDear Mr. Ortigas : \nWe have your letter of July 22, 1959. In answer to your inquiry, kindly be informed that you were proposed for membership by the Chamber\'s Membership Committee itself, composed of Mr. Arturo V. Tanco as chairman and Messrs. Felix D. Maramba and Florencio Tamesis as members. Their proposal was circularized to all our members and approved by our Board of Directors. Since your membership proposal was made as it were, by the Chamber itself, it was thought that your invitation should be made by someone representing the Chamber as a whole. With regard to the category of membership that you have been invited to, kindly be informed that it was thought of our Membership Committee and of our Board of Directors that you would be invited to join as a regular member. We apologize for not having made the above clear in our original letter. And may I reiterate once again our hope that you shall accept our invitation. \nSincerely yours,\nGABINO A. MENDOZA\nExecutive Summary ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1253, 'E2-1253AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, July 22)', 'Mr. Gabino A. Mendoza\nExecutive Secretary\nPHILIPPINE CHAMBER OF TECHNOLOGY\n516 Roman Santos Building\nPlaza Goiti, Manila\nDear Mr. Mendoza : \nThis is to acknowledge receipt of your letter of July 18, 1959. After a cursory reading, I found the following lines which are relevant to your letter, namely lines 110 and 111 o page 4 of your By-Laws : \"..., shall he be invited in writing by the proposers.\" I am wondering if this had been deliberately over-looked by you when writing the above-mentioned letter.\nAlso on page 2 of your Constitution there are described different categories of your organization. I should like to be informed to what category of membership I am being invited, - whether sustaining or regular. \nThank you for kind letter, I am \nYours truly, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1254, 'E2-1254AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, July 18)', 'Engineer Crisostomo Ortigas\nDean, College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City \nDear Sir :\nIn the name of the Board of Directors of the Philippine Chamber of Technology, we are happy to invite you to join us in this Chamber as a member. \nA small group of technologists, a list of which is attached herewith, has pioneered in the organization of this Chamber with members from all lines of the technological profession, but limited to those who have successfully occupied responsible positions in the practice of their respective professions for at least 10 years. With the experience of such members not only in technology, but also in management, we have felt that this Chamber can contribute effectively in the development of our national economy. \nWe expected no overlapping in contributions or services with existing technological organizations, because ours would be generated from a broader point of view. There can be no confict with UTOP. As a matter of fact the creation of this Chamber was initiated and approved by UTOP. UTOP members are associations, each of which cover one particular technological profession. The members of this Chamber are individuals, and, they cover a wider variety of technological services. \nOur Constitutions and By-Laws provide that cooperation shall be the basis of our relationship with other technological societies, not competition. \nActual performance in the past couple of years has confirmed all our close expectations and we are satisfied. We have found many national issues and problems falling within the purview of the Chamber. We can see that the ways and system of technologists in the solution of problems, which are based on fundamentals, logic and facts, can contribute substantially in discussions of economic issues. \nSatisfied that the Chamber has a definite role to play in the development of our national economy, the members and our Board of Directors have decided to expand our membership, which is by invitation. You have been proposed for membership by the Membership Committee, and we are all happy to invite you to join us in this public service. \nEnclosed please find copies of our Constitution and By-Laws. May we request you, should you decide to accept our invitation, to kindly send us your curriculum vitae. Many thanks. \nVery truly yours, \nGABINO A. MENDOZA\nExecutive Secretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1255, 'E2-1255AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'ROSTER\n1958-1959', '\nMEMBERS OF THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS\nName\nFilemon C. Rodriguez - Civil Engineer\nArturo V. Tanco, Sr., - Mechanical & Electrincal Engineer\nGeorge L. Adamson - Chemist \nFelix D. Maramba - Agricultural Engineer\nManuel I. Felizardo - Mechanical & Electrical Engineer\nEduardo Taylor - Chemist\nBenito Legarda, Sr. - Chemist\nFlorencio Tamesis - Forester\nManuel Ayoardo - Mineral Engineer \nREGULAR MEMBERS\nBernardo Abrera - Mechanical & Marine Engineer\nMarciano Angeles - Mechanical & Chemical Engineer\nSergio Bayan - Civil Engineer\nCiriaco Coronel - Mechanical & Electrical Engineer\nEphraim Gochangco - Civil Engineer \nAndres Hizon - Civil & Geodetic Engineer\nCarlos Locsin - Chemist\nJoaquin Marañon - Chemist\nJose Mirasol - Chemist\nJuan Nakpil - Architect\nFernando Ocampo - Architect\nJose Paez - Civil Engineer\nHermenegildo B. Reyes - Electrical & Mechanical Engineer ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1256, 'E2-1256AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Constitution of the Philippine Chamber of Technology ', 'PREAMBLE\nWe, technologists of the Philippines, and others engaged in or specially dedicated in the technological advancement of the country as related to the improvement of social and economic life; recognizing that our country is underdeveloped in industry and in agriculture; recognizing further the necessity of an organized and concerted effort in the field of tehcnology in order to help the government and the country in successfully carrying out its scientific, industrial and agricultural development; in order to promote cooperation and understanding among ourselves; insure mutual assistance in the furtherance of our common undertakings; encourage and maintain the highest standards in the practice of technological professions; and help in the development of technical and vocational man-power, do hereby organize ourselves into a non-profit association and promulgate this Constitution : \nARTICLE I - NAME\nThe name of this association shall be the \"PHILIPPINE CHAMBER OF TECHNOLOGY\".\nARTICLE II - OFFICE AND SEAL\nSection 1. - Office. - The principal office of the Association shall be in the City of Manila, Philippines.\nSection 2. - Seal. - A circular seal with the words \"Philippine Chamber of Technology, Manila, Philippines - 1956\" shall be the corporate seal of the association which shall be in the custody of the Corporate Secretary. \nARTICLE III - PURPOSES\nThe objectives and purposes for which the association is organized are as follows : \na) To foster better understanding, relationship and cooperation among those engaged in the practice and advancement of technology, in solving their common problems. \nb) To unify into one strong and solid organization highly experienced technologists for the purpose of advancing the application of technological sciences in the development of industries and agriculture, and of developing sufficient and adequate technical and vocational man-power. \nc) To develop and maintain high standards of service and of ethics in the practice of technological professions and vocations, and to undertake, whenever called upon, services of arbitration and adjudication on cases involving technology and industrial management. \nd) To secure legislation as well as reforms and amendments to existing laws affecting their common interests and to accomplish the purposes of the association.\ne) To acquire, maintain and /or operate solely or in association with any institution and/or government agency, such service facilities as a pilot plant or plants, testing or research laboratories, etc., for the benefit of members of the association and for technological advancement in the Philippines. \nf) To establish, or to cooperate in the establishment and recognition of, standards of manufacture, design and construction, installation, assaying, testing, procedural methods, safety, and such other technical standards as may contribute to and promote :\n(1) progress in production and marketing\n(2) safety to life, health and prosperity\n(3) conservation and efficient utilization of natural resources\n(4) public confidence, and \n(5) orderly advancement in the development of our national economy. \ng) To cooperate and work with local or foreign Chambers, technological associations and other non-profit civic organizations pursuing objectives and purposes of the same or similar nature as those of the association.\nh) To acquire a land site for its office building by purchase, donation, lease or otherwise, and to construct thereon a building or buildings suitable for offices and other activities of the association.\ni) To promote such other objectives and purposes analogous or incidental to the above-mentioned purposes and objectives for the general progress and welfare of the Philippines and its inhabitants. \nARTICLE IV - MEMBERSHIP\nSection 1. - Membership. - Membership shall be classified into (1) Regular members, (2) Charter members, and (3) Sustaining members. \na) Regular members - These shall include all those persons who organized the association and those admitted into the association.\nb) Charter members - These shall be composed of those members who signed this Constitution previous to incorporation. \nc) Sustaining members - These shall include individuals, institutions, civic organizations, and commercial firms interested in technological advancement but otherwise ineligible for regular membership. \nSection 2. - Qualifications - Regular members shall possess all of the following qualifications : \na) Graduate with technological science degree from a credtable university or technical institute, or a technologist who is duly registered and licensed by government to practice his particular profession;\nb) Recognized success in the practice of his particular technological profession in responsible positions for not less than ten (10)( years;\nc) Good moral character, good personal business, and professional reputation, and possessed with the ideal of service as the basis of worthy enterprises.\nSection 3. Classification. The regular members of this association shall be classified in accordance with their respective technological professions. \nARTICLE V - BOARD OF DIRECTORS\nThe Philippine Chamber of Technology shall be goverrned by a Board of Directors composed of nine (9) members who shall be elected for a term of one year. \nARTICLE VI - AMENDMENTS\nAmendments to this Constitution may be proposed by the Board of Directors or by a majority vote of the members at any regular meeting but such proposed amendments may only be approved after each and every member shall have been furnished with written copies of the full text of the amendments not less than one (1) month previous to the next regular meeting and only after they have been fully discussed in said regular meeting. All the members shall be furnished with ballots on which they will vast their votes o the amendments within thirty (30) days after the date of the regular meeting in which the proposed amendments were discussed. An affirmative vote of two-thirds of all the Regular members shall be required to approve any amendment and to incorporate the same in this Constitution. Immediately after an amendment is thus approved, all members shall be notified accordingly in writing. \nAPPROVED AND ADOPTED, this 7th day of September, 1956, in the City of Manila, Philippines. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1257, 'E2-1257AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'By-laws of the Philippine Chamber of Technology', 'Article I - Name\nThe name of this association shall be the \"PHILIPPINE CHAMBER OF TECHNOLOGY\".\nArticle II - Office and Seal\nSection 1. - Office. - The principal office of the Association shall be in the City of Manila, Philippines. \nSection 2. - Sea;l. - A circular seal with the words \"Philippine Chamber of Technology, Manila, Philippines - 1956\" shall be the corporate seal of the association which shall be in the custody of the Corporate Secretary. \nArticle III - Purposes\nThe objectives and purposes for which the association is organized are as follows : \na) To foster better understanding, relationship, and cooperation among those engaged in the practice and advancement of technology, in solving their common problems. \nb) To unify into one strong and solid organization highly experienced technologists for the purpose of advancing the application of technological sciences in the development in the industries and agriculture, and of developing sufficient and adequate technical and vocational man-power. \nc) To develop and maintain high standards of service and of ethics in the practice of technological professions and vocations, and to undertake, whenever called upon, services of arbitration and adjudication on cases involving technology and industrial management. \nd) To secure legislation as well as reforms and amendments to existing laws affecting their common interests and to accomplish the purposes of the association. \ne) To acquire, maintain and/or operate solely or in association with any institution and/or government agency, such service facilities as a pilot plant or plants, testing or research laboratories, etc., for the benefit of members of the association and for technological advancement in the Philippines. \nf) To establish, or to promote the establishment and recognition of standards of manufacture, design and construction, installation, assaying, testing, procedural methods, safety, and such other standards as may contribute to and promote :\n(1) progress in production and marketing\n(2) safety of life, health, and property\n(3) conservation and efficient utilization of natural resources\n(4) public confidence, and \n(5) orderly advancement in the development of our national economy. \ng) To affiliate with local or foreign Chambers, associations, and other non-profit civic organizations pursuing objectives and purposes of the same or similar nature as those of the association. \nh) To acquire a land site for its office building by purchase, donation, lease or otherwise, and to construct thereon a building or buildings suitable for offices and other activities of the association. \ni) To promote such other objectives and purposes analogous or incidental to the above-mentioned purposes and objectives for the general progress and welfare of the Philippines and its inhabitants. \nArticle IV - Membership\nSection 1. - Membership. - Membership shall be classified into (1) Regular members, (2) Charter members, and (3) Sustaining members.\na) Regular members - These shall include all those persons who organized the association and those admitted into the association. \nb) Charter members - These shall be composed of those regular members who signed this Constitution previous to incorporation. \nc) Sustaining members - These shall include individuals, institutions, civic organizations and commercial firms interested in technological advancement but otherwise ineligible for regular membership.\nSection 2. - Qualifications - For eligibility to regular membership in the association, the proposed member must possess all of the following qualifications : \na) Graduate with technological science degree from a creditable university or technical institute, or a technologist who is duly registered and licensed by the government to practice his particular profession;\nb) Recognized success in the practice of his particular technological profession in responsible positions for not less than 10 years; \nc) Good moral character, good personal, business, and professional reputation, and possessed with the ideal of service as the basis of worthy enterprise. \nSection 3 - Classification. \na) The regular members of this association shall be classified in accordance with their respective technological professions.  \nb) The technological classifications shall be limited to the following : \n(1) Agriculture\n(2) Architecture\n(3) Chemistry\n(4) Civil Engineering\n(5) Electrical Engineering\n(6) Mechanical Engineering\n(7) Mineral Engineering\n(8) Surveying\n(9) Miscellaneous other technological professions\nc) The number of regular members under any one technological classification shall not exceed 20% of the total number of members of the association at any particular time. \nd) Minor classification under each technological classification may be created by the Board of Directors. \nSection 4. - Admission \na) No direct application for membership shall be considered. A new member may be proposed as provided for herein and, only after the proposal for his admission is approved by the Board of Directors, shall he be invited in writing by the proposers. \nb) No proposed member shall be considered for admission unless he is sponsored by three Charter members; provided that, after the second year of the association\'s existence, he may be sponsored by any three Regular members who have been such members for at least two(2) consecutive years.\nc) The admission of a proposed member shall be referred to all the regular members in writing and objections from regular members submitted in writing to the Board of Directors within 30 days from date of mailing the corresponding notice shall be considered before the Board takes action. A unanimous approval by all the members of the Board shall be required for the admission of a proposed member. \nSection 5. - Termination and Reinstatement of Membership. \na) Automatic termination - Any membership shall automatically terminate : \n(1) upon failure of the member to pay his semi-annual fee three months after it is due. \n(2) upon suspension of revocation of his professional license by the government\n(3) upon conviction of the member by any court of justice for any crime, immorality, or fraudulent transactions. \n(4) upon death or resignation of the regular member. \nb) Expulsion - Any member may be expelled by vote of five (5) members of the Board of Directors after charges are preferred against him under oath in writing and a fair hearing had upon the same before the Board of Directors :\n(1) when he makes improper and illegal use of the name of the Philippine Chamber of Technology for his personal material gain, or that of his family; \n(2) when he violates the code of ethics adopted by the corporation, provided however, that any member may be expelled for any other cause by the unanimous vote of all the members of the Board of Directors. \nc) Reinstatement - Any member, whose membership had been terminated for failure to pay his dues, for suspension or revocation of his professional license, or by virtue of court conviction under Section 5 :\n(1) may be reinstated by a vote of 5 members of the Board of Directors provided that, in the second case, the suspension or revocation of his professional license is lifted, and in the last case, a higher court of justice had reversed the decision of conviction, and provided, further, that, in all cases, he pays all fees and accounts in arrears up to the time of termination of his membership. \nSection 6. Honorary Membership - The Board of Directors may, upon approval by unanimous vote of all its members, confer an honorary membership in the association upon any individual who has made an outstanding achievement or contribution to advancement in the field of science and technology in the Philippines. \nARTICLE V - FEES AND PRIVILEGES\nSection 1 - Entrance Fee. An entrance fee of P100.00 shall be paid by each Chapter member previous to incorporation and each Regular member shall pay the same amount as entrance fee upon approval of his membership. \nSection 2 - Membership Fee. \na) Each Charter, Regular and Sustaining member shall pay a membership fee of P50,00 semi-annually payable in advance, provided that a new member, upon approval of his membership, shall pay this fee corresponding to the semester in which the membership was approved. \nb) The membership fee may be revised in the future upon approval by two-thirds (2/3) of all the regular members of the association. \nSection 3. - Privileges\na) Only Charter and Regular members are entitled to vote and be voted upon, without limitations. \nb) All members shall be entitled to all services and privileges that the association may provide for. For this purpose, each Sustaining member which is an institution or a corporation, shall designate as its representative, one of its executives who has discretionary powers within said institution or corporation. \nc) Sustaining members may participate in discussions and deliberations but cannot vote beyond committee levels and cannot be voted upon for any position above that of a committee member. \nARTICLE VI - BOARD OF DIRECTORS\nSection 1. - Membership. - The Philippine Chamber of Technology shall be governed by a Board of Directors composed of nine (9) members who shall be elected for a term of one (1) year. Immediately after their election, the members shall elect from among themselves, a Chairman, a First Vice-Chairman, Second Vice-Chairman, a Corporate Secretary, and a Treasurer; provided, however, that no director who had been elected and who had been elected and had served as Chairman in the last preceding two years, shall be re-elected Chairman. \nSection 2. - Election - The members of the Board of Directors shall be elected by secret ballot in a regular or special meeting of the association not later than in June of each year, provided, that there is a quorum in said meeting by a duly elected Nominating Committee. \nSection 3. - Nominating Committee. The Nominating Committee, to be composed of nine (9) members, shall be elected in a regular meeting not later than three months before date of election of the members of the Board of Directors. Each group of regular members present in this meeting belonging to one technological classification shall elect one member of this Committee from said technological classification.\nSection 4. - Qualifications of Nominees. A nominee shall be a Charter member or a Regular member of not less than two years membership and who must have previously served as Chairman of any committee or sub-committee. He must be a member in good standing and has no record of termination of membership for any cause. His written acceptance of the nomination and his affirmation that he will serve dedicatedly if elected, shall previously be secured. \nSection 5. - Tenure of Office. - All members of the Board of Directors and all officers appointed by said Board shall take office and assume their respective duties and responsibilities on the first day of July following their election or appointment, for one year or until successors have been elected and have qualified. \nSection 6. - Three (3) consecutive unexcused absences of any member of the Board of Directors shall automatically terminate the term of office of said member, in which case the Board of Directors shall elect in the next regular meeting a new member to replace him. \nARTICLE VII - OFFICERS\nSection 1 - The officers of the association shall be the following : \na) President, who shall be the one elected as Chairman of the Board of Directors;\nb) First Vice-President, who shall be the one elected as First Vice-Chairman of the Board of Directors;\nc) Second Vice-President, who shall be the one elected as Second Vice-Chairman of the Board of Directors;\nd) Treasurer, who shall be elected by the Board of Directors from among its members;\ne) Corporate Secretary, who shall be elected by the Board of Directors from among its members;\nf) Executive Secretary, who shall be elected, at the option of, and by the Board of Directors, who may or may not be a member of the association; \ng) Auditor, who shall be elected by the Board of Directors and who may or may not be a member of the association;\nh) Other officers and employees whose positions are created by the Board of Directors shall be appointed by the President with the approval of the Board of Directors. \nSection 2. - Compensation. - No member elected or appointed to any office or position in the association except that of Executive Secretary, shall receive any compensation. The salaries and compensation of officers and employees shall be fixed by the Board of Directors. \nARTICLE VIII - STANDING COMMITTEES\nSection 1. - Major Committees. To attain the purposes and objectives of the association, there shall be created the following standing major Committees : Committee on Club Affairs, Commitee on Industrial Development, Commitee on Agricultural Development, Committee on Technical Man-Power Development, Commitee on Community Development, Committee on Fuels & Power Development \nSection 2 - Minor committees may be created by the Board of Directors under each major committee in Section 1, which shall include Membership Committee under the Committee on Club Affairs, to be composed of Charter members and/or Regular members whose qualifications shall be the same as those for nominees for the Board of Directors in Article VI, Section 4. \nSection 3. - Each major committee shall be headed by a member of the Board of Directors, provided however, that the Corporate Secretary shall be designated as the Chairman of the Committee on Club Affairs. \nARTICLE IX - DUTIES OF OFFICERS\nSection 1. - President. - The President shall be the executive officer and the only spokesman of the association. He shall preside at all meetings of the association and of the Board of Directors. He shall be responsible for the execution of all policies, resolutions, and actions of the Board of Directors and of the membership in meetings of the association. He shall direct the activities of the association towards the attainment of its purposes and objectives in accordance with its Constitution and By-Laws and with the specific policies and resolutions of the membership and of the Board of Directors. He shall sign all checks and approve all disbursements of funds of the association. \nSection 2. - First Vice-President. - The First Vice President shall act as President in case of inability, sickness, absence or any otehr temporary disability of the President and shall perform such other duties as may be delegated to him by the President. \nSection 3. - Second Vice-President. The Second Vice-President shall act as President in case of inability, sickness, absence or any other temporary disability of both the President and the First Vice-President and shall perform such other duties as may be delegated to him by the President. \nSection 4. - Corporate Secretary. - The Corporate Secretary shall be the custodian of all records, papers, and other documents of the association; he shall take minutes and prepare resolutions at all meetings of the members and of the Board of Directors; he shall perform such other duties and functions as may be delegated to him by the President or by the Board of Directors in the execution of the policies and of all resolutions of the Board of Directors and of the membership of the association in the furtherance of the objectives of the association. \nSection 5. - Executive Secretary - The duties of the Executive Secretary shall be those of the Corporate Secretary which are delegated to him by the Board of Directors thru recommendation of the Corporate Secretary. \nSection 6. - Treasurer. The Treasurer shall be the financial officer of the association and as such he will be the custodian of all funds and properties of the association; he shall countersign all checks and disbursements funds of the association. The Treasurer shall make an annual report of the finances of the association and such other reports as the Board of Directors may require him to make. \nSection 7. - Auditor. The Auditor shall audit and examine the receipts of all monies and disbursements of funds of the corporation and shall see to it that disbursements are properly carried out in accordance with these By-Laws, and with the resolutions of the Board of Directors and of the membership of the association. The Auditor shall make an annual report to the Board of Directors and the members of the association of the state of finance of the association and such other reports as the Board of Director may require of him. \nARTICLE X - PERMANENT VACANCIES \nSection 1. - Members of the Board of Directors. - In case of death, removal, resignation or permanent vacancy for any cause in the membership of the Board of Directors, the same shall be filled by the Board of Directors, provided that such new member shall hold office only until the expiration of the term of the Director he has replaced. \nSection 2. - President. - In case of death, removal or resignation of the President, the First Vice-President shall take over the office and assume the duties and responsibilities of President. \nSection 3 - First Vice-President. In case of death, removal or resignation of the First Vice-President or of his assumption of the office of the President, the Second Vice-President shall take over the office and assume the duties and responsibilities of the First Vice-President. \nSection 4. - Second Vice-President. In case of death, removal or resignation of the Second Vice-President or of his assumption of the office of the First Vice-President, the Board of Directors shall immediately elect a new Second-President from among its members after which a new member shall be elected to fill the vacancy left in the membership of the Board of Directors, who shall hold office only until the expiration of the term of office of the member elected to the Second Vice-Presidency. \nSection 5. - Any permanent vacancy created in any office of the association shall be filled in immediately either by the Board of Directors or by the President with the approval of the Board of Directors, as the case may be, in exactly the same manner as is stipulated in these By-Laws for that office. \nARTICLE XI - MEETINGS\nSection 1. Regular meetings. There shall be regular monthly meetings of the association to be held on the first Saturday of each month at 12:30 p.m. in the principal office of the association, or at such other day, time and place within the City of Manila as may be fixed by the Board of Directors. \nSection 2. Board meetings. The Board of Directors shall hold regular meetings every month on the second Monday of each month at the principal office of the association or at any place and at such time of the day as the Board of Directors may decide. \nARTICLE XII - SPECIAL MEETINGS\nSection 1. A special meeting of the membership of the association or of the Board of Directors may be called by the Corporate Secretary oat the instance of the President or at the instance of any 3 Directors, or at the instance of any 10 members, who shall so inform the Corporate Secretary in writing, provided that, all the members of the association or the members of the Board of Directors, as the case may be, shall have been notified not later than 10 days previous to the date of the meeting. \nARTICLE XIII - PUBLIC AFFAIRS\nSection 1. - This association shall not endorse or recommend any candidate for public office and shall not discuss at any meeting the merits or demerits of any such candidate. \nARTICLE XIV - AMENDMENTS\nAmendments to these By-Laws may be proposed by the Board of Directors or by a majority vote of the members at any regular meeting but such proposed amendments may only be approved after each and every member shall have been furnished with written copies of the full text of the amendments not less than one (1) month previous to the next regular meeting. All the members shall be furnished with ballots on which they will cast their votes on the amendment within 30 days after the date of the regular meeting in which the proposed amendments were discussed. An affirmative vote of two-thirds (2/3) of all the Regular members shall be required to approve any amendment and to incorporate the same in these By-Laws. Immediately after an amendment is thus approved, all members shall be notified accordingly in writing. \nApproved and adopted this 31st day of August, 1956, in the City Manila, Philippines', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1258, 'E2-1258AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, August 12)', 'Mr. Roel Ortigas\nXavier University\nCagayan de Oro City\nMisamis Oriental\nDear Roel : \nWe have had some interesting visitors in the last term; - all of them physicists of considerable renown. One of them was a Jesuit father who lectured on Quantum Mechanics. He gave an excellent performance. He is here on special tour of the National Bureau of Standards on the subject of propagation of waves. He returned to the United States yesterday but he will be back next year to help establish an observatory at Loyola Heights. \nThe new calendar year of the UP, end to end, is undergoing some revisions on account of the congestion of students\' subjects which stems from the fact that its length is only 160 days a year as against the old which was 200 days long. The revision will consist in the addition of one more than term which will result in 204-day calendar. In spite of the congestion, however, many students preferred the end to end calendar to the old calendar as it prevents them from procastinating. \nHow is your Hamilton performing? It seems somewhat slow when we got it from the repair shop; - about one minute a day I think. \nWe are still having Fathers O\'Brien and Ortiz at least once a week. \nAffectionately yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1259, 'E2-1259AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, August 25)', 'Fr. Francis Glover, S.J.\nRadio Propagation Physics Division\nNATIONAL BUREAU OF STANDARDS\nBoulder, Colorado \nU.S.A.\nDear Fr. Glover :\nI have just received an air-mail envelope containing the Iospherical Radio Propagation. I am grateful to you for your thoughtfulness and promptness in supplying my needs. Last week I received from Fr. Hennessey the Introduction to Differential Equations in Physics, which I have found very useful in my course, Engineering Science 202, Mathematical Methods in Engineering. \nI hope to be able someday in the near future to reciprocate. I look forward with anticipation to the time when you will be spending your life in the Philippines as our \"next door neighbor.\"\nSincerely yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1260, 'E2-1260AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, August 20)', 'Dr. C. A. Ortigas\nDean, College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\nDear Dr. Ortigas\nWhen I had the pleasure of meeting you last week at the Physics Department, you mentioned that you were interested in a book that would give something about the propagation of radio waves. At that time I think I said something about a book that is put out here at the National Bureau of Standards. This is not the best in the field, but I must say that I found some of the chapters rather helpful, and the references do give a good introduction to the field. I hope that you find it useful. \nPermit me to say how much I enjoyed my brief stay at U.P. last week and how much I look forward to being able to return to the Philippines and to be your \"next door neighbor\" in the years to come. I personally feel that science and technology has a big role to play in the economic development of the Philippines, and I am quite interested in making whatever small contribution I can to this worth-while effort. \nSincerely yours, \nFrancis Glover, S.J.\nRadio Propagation Physics Division', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1261, 'E2-1261AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, December 3)', 'The Honorable Jose E. Romero\nSecretary of Education\nManila\nDear Mr. Secretary :\nThis is to acknowledge receipt of your letter of December 1, 1959, on the subject \"restudy of the merits of the application of her Harvardian Colleges as a University.\" I am happy to serve in the Committee to make the aforementioned restudy. \nAwaiting further details of this assignment, I am \nYours truly,\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1262, 'E2-1262AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, December 1) ', 'Dean Crisostomo Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\nDear Dean Ortigas : \nMrs. Barbara Yap Angeles of Davao City filed an application for the accreditation of her Harvardian Colleges as a University. In an investigation made by the Director of Private Schools, his report was adverse to the application. Mrs. Angeles has impugned this report on several grounds which you will find in the records among them, prejudice on the part of those who prepared the report. She also claims that the deficiencies pointed out by the investigators have been remedied. It is, therefore, desired by this Department that a new set of investigators be appointed to make a thorough review of this case. \nIn a speech delivered by His Excellency, the President of the Philippines, at the Far Eastern University on January 29, 1959, he said the following : \n\"How this constitutional guarantee to freedom of education may find more flesh in the development and operation of private institutions of higher learning is the challenge that should be met and exploited today, in response to our pressing need for good men and true, alive and alert to our responsibilities and potentials as a free people.\n\"...We might have the University of the Philippines to serve as touchstone in the enforcement of this system. Until such a system is developed and established, I am afraid we shall continue to be tolerant with the operation of a government agency of manifestly limited resources and the application of what is generally deplored as an educational straight-jacket.\"\nWe have, therefore, thought of appointing the following as the new committee to restudy the merits of this application and we have decided that this committee should compose of the following:\n1. Dean Alfredo Morales, Graduate College of Education, U.P.;\n2. Dean Crisostomo Ortigas, College of Engineering, U.P.;\n3. Prof. Juan Canave, College of Education, U.P.\nThis Department would deeply appreciate it if you could take this assignment and advise the Secretary on this matter. \nFurthermore, we are also considering new criteria for the accreditation of Universities, and in time will appoint a committee to study this matter and in line with the policy enunciated by the President inthe above-mentioned sppech, we will designate members of the U.P. Faculty to this committee, of whom you will be one. \nKindly acknowledge receipt of this letter and I hope you will formally accept this designation. \nTruly yours, \nJOSE E. ROMERO\nSecretary of Education', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1263, 'E2-1263AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, January 6)', 'Dr. Paul B.W. Gollong\nDirector of International Research\nArmour Research Foundation of Illinois Institute of Technology\n10 West 35th Street, Chicago 16\nIllinois, U.S.A.\nMy dear Paul:\nI was indeed very happy to hear from you again. Please accept our best wishes for you and Mrs. Gollong for the New Year; - also for the prosperity of the ARF.\nI am still hoping, but with my fingers crossed, that the key people in our country that have anything to do with industrial research would eventually see the wisdom of placing the Industrial Research Center under the University of the Philippines. This is of course a wish that has a very small probability of being fulfilled, since at the present moment the big shots of the Industrial Research Center activities under the National Institute of Science and Technology.\nWhen are you coming to Manila again? Please don\'t forget to look us up. Mrs. Ortigas joins me in sending our warmest regards to the Gollong family. \nVery sincerely yours,\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1264, 'E2-1264AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, December 30)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\nThe Philippines\nMy dear Dean Ortigas:\nRecently, a copy of Dr. William Watson\'s report, \"Science in the Philippines, 1959\", weas sent to me. After reading it thoroughly, I must come to the same conclusion reached by Dr. Watson; namely, that he did not have sufficient information on the Philippines prior to his field work nor enough time on the assignment to develop a really thorough and encompassing report on science and the Philippines. I understand that he will return so that this initial work can be expanded. \nIt is interesting to me to read that Dr. Watson makes quite clear the role that the U.P. Industrial Research Center must play. With this further verification of the need for such a center, I hope that the long-planned program eventually will get under way. \nPlease accept my best wishes for a most healthy and satisfying New Year.\nSincerely, \nPaul B.W. Gollong\nDirector of International Reseearch', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1265, 'E2-1265AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, January 11)', 'MESSAGE\n(to the 1960 Philippinensian)\nCongratulations to you, candidates for graduation in 1960!\nThe diploma each one of you will receive is an evidence of your academic achievement. The College of Engineering is proud of you. Your Alma Mater succeeded in providing you with sufficient skill for solving problems in engineering sciences and in imparting some experience in designing. There is another form of pride that we feel and that is the one which stems from the conviction that we have contributed to the formation of your moral character and your ideals during the critical period of your maturity. All these are sources of satisfaction to your professors. \nThe undersigned wishes you success in the endeavor that you will pursue during the remainder of your life in this world.\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1266, 'E2-1266AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1959, December 28)', 'Third Floor, Student Union Bldg.\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Rizal\nDecember 28, 1959\nThe Dean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Rizal\nDear Sir : \nThe 1960 Philippinensian is coming out on or before Commencement Day. Work is going on full-blast and all materials are just about in. A certain number of your students is graduating this year. And your message traditionally and most fittingly serves as anchor of the roll of graduates from your college. It shall be a deep debt of the present staff of the university yearbook if you could provide us with your message not later than January 10, 1960. \nThe theme of the 1960 Philippinensian is \"Filipinism as a University Tradition\".\nI remain\nRespectfully yours,\nJOSE MA. SISON\nExecutive Editor ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1267, 'E2-1267AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, May 6)', 'Dr. Paulino Garcia\nChairman, National Science Development Board\nHerran, Manila\n\nDear Dr. Garcia : \n\nThis letter is being written in acknowledgment and in pursuance of a telephone message received from Executive Vice President Virata yesterday to the effect that \"Chairman Garcia desires that turn-over ceremonies for the Textile Engineering and Pilot Plant Building be held.\" Dr. Virata further suggested that I contact you in connection with this matter.\n\nThe undersigned was very glad to hear that decision on this matter has ultimately been reached. He is looking forward to a conference with you or your representative at your earliest convenience to discuss details of these ceremonies. He should like to suggest, however, that the ceremonies be held after June 13 on the ground that his time at present is limited by the pressure of preparations for the coming registration as well as for the opening of the Golden Jubilee Celebration of the College of Engineering which will start on June 12. We at the U.P. are speculating that the Chairman of the NSDB might wish to include the turn-over ceremonies as part of the all-year round Golden Jubilee Celebration. \nVery truly yours,\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1268, 'E2-1268AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1960, July 5)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Diliman\nSir : \n\nIn connection with our recommendations for the renewal of the appointments or promotions of Arturo A. Ramos as Field Engineer, Juanito L. Eugenio as Asst. Research Engineer, Francisco R, Mateo as Technician Clerk and Aramenio Infante as Laboratory Helper, the undersigned should like to submit herewith the resulting FY 1960-undersigned should like to submit herewith the resulting FY 1960-1961 budget at the U.P.I.R.C. (Marked Annex A) together with supporting data showing that said budget will be defrayed entirely from income expected to be received from funds advanced by project sponsors barring interferences from force majour. \nAnnex B (Yearly Income from 1 July 1955 to 31 December 1959) indicates that the yearly incomes tend to increase. This Annex B together with Annex C (Income Statement from 1 June 1959 to 31 May 1960) and Annex D (Income Statement from 1 June 1959 to 31 May 1960) and Annex D (Income for June 1960) provide a basis for expecting an income of more than P40,000 for FY 1960-1961. If the monthly income remain equal to that in June throughout FY 1960-1961 the income for that fiscal year will be 12 x P4,476.00 or P53,712. In any case, should force majeur upset our extrapolation the deficit can be adequately covered from a sizable reserve accumulated between 1955 and 1960 shwon in Annex E (Statement of Accumulated Cash Balance as of May 31, 1960)\nAnnex F (Plantilla of Personnel of U.P.I.R.C) shows that four categories of compensation are involved in the operation of U.P.I.R.C. These are : \n(a) Additional compensation for the directorate defrayed by funds from the National Science Development Board by virtue of R.A. 2067. \n(b) Regular salaries defrayed from UPIRC income; and those defrayed by NSDB.\n(c) Honorarium for Senior Research Engineer, Associate Research Engineer, and Research Technician holding special appointment entitling them to compensation on the hourly basis for services rendered to projects sponsored by industry or sister institutions.\n(d) Wages paid to emergency or contingent labor hired expressly for the projects.\nVery truly yours,\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDirector, U.P.I.R.C', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1269, 'E2-1269AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, April 7)', 'Mrs. Rafaelita H. Soriano\nChief, SEATO Affairs Division\nDepartment of Foreign Affairs\nPadre Faura St., Manila \n\nDear Madam :\nThis has reference to your letter dated March 3, 1961 in connection with the recommendation by the National Science Development Board of Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas as a qualified nominee for membership in the Advisory Panel of the SEATO Graduate School of Engineering, Bangkok.\nThe answer of the President of the University to the question as to whether the University could defray the travel expenses of Prof. Ortigas should he be appointed Philippine member of above-mentioned Advisory Panel is that there are \"no funds for the purpose.\"\nAn early reply to your letter was not possible due to necessary references we had to make. \nVery truly yours,\nOSCAR BAGUIO\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
