(1270, 'E2-1270AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, May 3)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines\nSir :\nPursuant to the brief conference at your office Thursday noon, the undersigned has the honor of requesting U.P. President\'s ruling on his LEAVE STATUS. He is programming his activities for next school year and finds that LEAVE STATUS has to be taken into account. \nUpon termination of his deanship, the undersigned assumed that he automatically remained on the cumulative leave basis because less than a year before (on 1 October 1959) the U.P. Board of Regents appointed him Professor and Head of the newly formed department of Engineering Sciences and the U.P. President ordered in Administrative Circular No. 5 Series 1959-60 dated 18 May 1960 that...\"4. All existing programs, like the UNESCO Physics Training Program, ICA-NEC programs and projects, shall remain under the direct management of Professor Crisostomo Ortigas until other arrangements are made. The undersigned shall assign any future program or project as he sees fit.\" \nOf the changes that have taken place during the school year 1960-61, two are relevant to the subject to this letter, namely; the appointment of a new head of the Department of Engineering Sciences and the transfer of the functions of the Vice President of Academic Affairs to the Executive Vice President. \nThe undersigned became aware of the first of these two while he was processing some requisition involving purchase of supplies for the Atomic Energy Laboratory sometime in October. The signature of Professor Dominador Ilio appeared over the title of \"Head, Engineering Science\". Upon inquiry he discovered the Prof. D. Ilio had been appointed to this position two months before. (This removes one reason for keeping the undersigned under the cumulative leave basis). \nUpon learning abou the second change, I consulted with the Executive Vice President. The paragraph of Administrative Circular No. 5 quoted above was touched upon. It was arranged that the undersigned continue to discharge the function that he was discharging when he and Dr. Isidro were jointly operating C.P. 6030-A. This arrangement was later modified, however, when the services of Mr. Jose Juinio ceased to be available to him in January 1961 due to the termination of NSDB Project 2.1. The modification consisted in the release of the undersigned from prime responsibility in connection with dollar commodities. I am attaching pertinent excerpts from my service record in the belief that the President might wish to glance at it while formulating the reply to this letter. \nVery truly yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1271, 'E2-1271AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, October 4) ', 'Dear Prof. Nemenzo :\nHere\'s the letter in compliance with your endorsement. If you believe the style should be changed let me know; - or just go ahead and make the necessary modification. \nThe Forms No. 41 (A) have been with Mr. Antonio for sometime already ready for this request.\nCAOrtigas', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1272, 'E2-1272AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, October 11)', 'The National Economic Council\nPadre Faura St., Manila\n(Thru Proper Channels University of the Philippines)\nSir :\nThe undersigned, Project Director of C.P. No. 892 respectfully requests, hereby, the transfer to the University of the Philippines the assets acquired thru the above-mentioned projects. General Forms No. 41 (A) covering said assets are herewith enclosed.\nVery truly yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nCP. No. 892', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1273, 'E2-1273AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, October 11) ', 'The National Economic Council\nPadre Faura St., Manila\n(Thru Proper Channels, University of the Philippines)\nSir : \nThe undersigned, Project Director of C.P. No. 892, respectfully requests the transfer to the University of the Philippines the assets acquired through the above-mentioned project. General Forms No. 41 (A) covering said assets are herewith enclosed.\nThese documents cover the following \n1. Furniture & Office Equipment valued at P22,260.14\n2. Books valued at 505.00\n3. Miscellaneous valued at 39,196.36\n4. Motor vehicle valued at 5,041.26\n5. Furniture & office equipment valued at 13,580.14\n6. Scientific Equipment valued at 26,840.48 \nVery truly yours,\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProject Director, CP No. 892', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1274, 'E2-1274AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, October 11) ', 'The National Economic Council\nPadre Faura St., Manila\n(Thru Proper Channels, University of the Philippines)\nSir : \nThe undersigned, Project Director of C.P. Nos. 420, 430, 530, 630, 830, respectfully requests the transfer to the University of the Philippines the assets acquired through the above-mentioned projects. General Forms No. 41 (A) covering said assets are herewith enclosed.\nThese documents cover the following: \n1. CP No. 420 in one page with a total value of P16,265.75\n2. CP Nos. 430, 530, 630 & 830 in 17 pages with a total value of 88,242.99\n3. Dollar Commodities in 75 pages with a total value of $890,343.06\nVery truly yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProject Director \nCP Nos 420, 430, 530, 630 & 830 ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1275, 'E2-1275AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1961, December 5)', 'Dr. Jose C. Locsin, President\nINTERNATIONAL CONGRESS ON RIZAL\nP.O. Box 3398, Manila \nDear Dr. Locsin : \nThe undersigned desires to thank you for your letter of 25 November notifying him of his election as Delegate to the International Congress on Rizal, and to express his disappointment over the unfortunate fact that the said letter was delivered to him only on 5 December, - five days after the deadline for acceptance, and to acknowledge the honor of having been thought of as deserving to be a delegate to the said Congress. \nIn closing, I should like to place my humble self at your disposal for performing any chore that you may wish to undertake in connection with your responsibilities in the Centennial Commission. \nVery truly yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1276, 'E2-1276AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, January 28) ', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Campus\nDear Mr. President :\nIn compliance with your lettert dated 16 January (and received 22 January by the undersigned), I am submitting herewith the affidavit mentioned therein, - duly notarized.\nThis affidavit departs from the draft inclosed with said letter,- the departure having been made in the interest of accuracy. \nVery truly yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1277, 'E23-1277AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, January 25)', 'REPUBLIC OF THE PHILIPPINES\nQUEZON CITY\nI, Crisostomo A. Ortigas, of legal age, married and residing at UP Campus, Diliman, after being duly sworn to in accordance with law, depose and say :\nThat from the year 1953 up to the year 1959 I was the project director of a number of NEC-ICA counterpart projects in the Diliman units of the University of the Philippines;\nThat as such project director, I received certain equipment under the terms of counterpart Projects listed as follows : \n(A) Rehabilitation of the U.P. College of Engineering including Geology, Chemistry, Physics, Industrial Pharmacy, bearing CP Nos. 20, 65, 430, 530, 630, 730, 830, 930;\n(B) The University of the Philippines - Stanford University Contract involving the Colleges of Business Administration, Education, Engineering, Main Library, Physics, and Geology, bearing CP No. 492, 592, 692, 792, 892;\n(C) The Electronics Training Project bearing CP No. 7103.\nThat the equipment received by me under the terms of the above enumerated projects as of 1959 were properly distributed to the Colleges of Business Administration, Education, Engineering, Liberal Arts, Main Library, and Pharmacy in pursuance of the terms of project agreements. \nThat the equipment received by the responsible officers of the aforementioned colleges and units. \nThat sometime in 1959 Dr. Vicente G. Sinco, the then incumbent president took over abruptly the authority on and the responsibilities pertaining to project directorship;\nThat on account of unavoidable time lag between approval of agreement on the one hand and implementation on the other, commodities continued to arrivel well beyond 1959;\nThat I am not fully acquainted with the procedures followed by the project director in distributing commodities that were received by him since he took over the responsibilities;\nThat I am aware that copies of inventories for NEC-ICA have been in the state of preparation since 1959 under the direction of the UP property officer and that I have extended unqualified cooperation in said preparation. \nIN WITNESS THEREOF, I have hereunto set my hand this 25 day of January, 1963, in the district of Diliman, Quezon City. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1278, 'E2-1278AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, January 16)', 'Prof. Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nU.P. College of Engineering\nDiliman, Quezon City\nDear Prof. Ortigas :\nThe records of the University show that certain project items from the NEC-ICA were received by you as project director and which items you distributed to the various units of the University pursuant to the terms of the Project. Under date of October 8, 1962, a communication was received from the NEC-ICA inquiring as to the manner of disposition of the said project items and asking for copies of inventories of said properties. \nThe records of the University, however, show that the project directors, including yourself, failed to make any inventory or record of the properties you received and distributed. \nTo prevent my being misunderstood, I wish to ask you to execute and affidavit to the effect that you received in fact the said equipment and had accordingly distributed the same to the respective units entitled under the terms of the Project to receive them. This way, you will assist me in meeting my responsibility with respect to such properties. \nAttached is a draft of the affidavit requested. \nVery truly yours,\nCarlos P. Romulo', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1279, 'E2-1279AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, April 3)', 'University of the Philippines\nPHYSICS TEACHERS TRAINING PROGRAMME \nQuezon City\n\nDean Patrocinio Valenzuela, Vice-Chairman\nUNESCO Commission of the Philippines\n\nDear Dean Valenzuela :\n\nIn response to our note of March 4 and in accordance with our subsequent conversation in connection with the said note I am submitting to you the following comments :\n\nThe report of Dr. Ralph C. Wilson, specialist in science education, dated January 1959 embodies most of the findings of the three other specialists that preceded him. The recommendations of Dr. Wilson as well as those of the other three touch on similar or related ideas such as training of teachers, apparatus and teaching aids, curriculum and teaching materials, etc. The paucity of materials and inadequacy of the preparation of the teachers particularly those assigned to teaching physics classes have been underscored in Prof. Wilson\'s report as well as in the abstracts of the reports previously prepared by the specialists that preceded him. The undersigned has not come across any refutation of the findings of the UNESCO specialists; it appears that their observations are adequately justified. In particular they are borned out by my personal experience with the Bureau of Public Schools teachers that have enrolled in the NEC-AID physics teachers training program in the University of the Philippines at Diliman during the last three years. This conclusion has been amply corroborated by other teachers, officials and citizens who feel deep concern with our education system. \nThe UNESCO specialists that have come for science education assistance were not familiar with our way of life and the idiosyncrasies of our people. Therefore their recommendations can be no more than suggestive in nature. However, I hasten to add, that the report deals with problems that are so urgent in nature that the sequel step should be undertaken by us without further delay. \nI believe that UNESCO Philippines with the active cooperation of the Bureau of Public Schools, University of the Philippines, together with moral and financial support of the National Science Development Board and the National Economic Council is in a very strong position to push through a dynamic plan that can start operating for producing physics teachers in adequate number not later than August 1964. This prediction is based on the experience which we have acquired in connection with the NEC-AID physics teachers training program at the University of the Philippines. The undersigned further believes that a significant advantage will be gained by an early move on the part of the UNESCO Commission to take advantage of this physics teachers training program by employing it as a launching pad for mounting a large scale Five-Year Physics Teachers Training Program designed to make the universities produce physics teachers in sufficient number starting right away. \nThe urgency of the Five-Year Plan mentioned above may be underscored by repeat here again that less than five per cent of teachers teaching physics in the Bureau of Public Schools are physics trained. Furthermore, the universities in the Philippines are not producing physics teachers and no signs are visible that physics teachers in adequate number will be produced in the next ten years. THe undersigned hereby offers his humble services to collaborate with an ad hoc group formed by UNESCO to formulate details of the Five-Year Plan referred to above. \n\nYours sincerely,\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProgramme Management ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1280, 'E2-1280AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, October 24)', 'MR. JOSEPH F. BRONBERGER\nConference Chairman, The Third International Accelerator Conference \nHigh Voltage Engineering Corporation\nBurlington, Massachusetts\nU.S.A.\nDear Sir : \nThis is to acknowledge your kind invitation to The Third International Accelerator Conference for which I am thankful. I regret to inform you, however, that arrangements for my attendance failed. \nPlease inform me how one may acquire copies of papers presented as well as the cost of such acquisition. \nThank you again for inviting me and best wishes for the success of the conference. \nVery truly yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS \nProgramme Management & Prof. of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1281, 'E2-1281AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, October 11) ', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman Campus\nManila \nPhilippine Islands\nDear Dean Ortigas :\nWe are pleased to send you the second printing of the Accelerator Conference program for the November meeting in Boston. As you can see, a number of papers have been added including a special session on Research with Electron Accelerators. \nAs of this date, we have not had a reply from you and wondered if our original invitation went astray. If you are planning to attend, would you please return the enclosed registration card. Because the hotel facilities are limited, it will be necessary to limit the number of participants to 500. We now have approximately 300 regisrations.\nIf you wish to stay at the Hotel Somerset, please mail the second enclosed card for your room reservation. A special rate of $12.00 per single occupancy and $17.00 per twin occupancy has been arranged with the hotel for the moderate accomodations. \nContrary to our previous announcement, there will not be a charter flight to this conference. The number of people who expressed an interest in it did not meet the minimum number for the flight. Most people are taking advantage of the 14-day excursion rate which becomes effective with all airlines after October 1. The rates under this plan are substantially reduced from the normal fare. The only requirement is that the traveler must be away at least 14 days and not more than 21 days. We recommend that you inquire about this plan. \nRegistration will take place at the Hotel Somerset beginning Sunday, November 10. There will be a get-acquainted cocktail party at the hotel for late Sunday afternoon, November 10. Further details about this party and the other social events will be available at the Conference Registration Desk. \nWe are looking forward to a very successful conference with you. \nVery truly yours, \nJoseph F. Bromberger\nConference Chairman ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1282, 'E2-1282AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, October 24)', 'MR. PAUL B.W. GOLLONG\nSpecial Technical Adviser\nResearch and Evaluation Division Centre for Industrial Development\nUnited Nations\nNew York, U.S.A.\nDear Paul :\nI am glad to hear from you particularly about your new connection with the United Nations. I wish you success in this new activity. \nThe deanship of the College of Engineering is now handled by one of our colleagues, Prof. Oscar Baguio and you probably have heard that President Sinco was retired in accordance with the laws of the land in 1961. \nI am no longer participating in the activities of the National Science Development Board and the U.P. Industrial Research Center. My responsibilities in connection with the agencies terminated as soon as Prof. Baguio took over in 1960. However, my interest in your work remains as intense as ever. Please let me hear about you and about your work from time to time. Please remember me to Mrs. Gollong and our mutual friends. Mrs. Ortigas sends you her warmest regards. \nSincerely,\nC.A. Ortigas\nProgramme Management & Prof. of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1283, 'E2-1283AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1963, October 8)', 'My dear Dean Ortigas, \nI thought you would like to know that I have accepted an appointment with the United Nations Secretariat in New York as Special Technical Adviser with the Centre for Industrial Development, which is the unit responsible for the research and field activities of the United Nations in the field of industry. I am hopeful that through my work at the Centre - which is actually an expansion of that which I carried out at the Armour Research Foundation - we will see each other from time to time. \nCordially yours, \nPaul B.W. Gollong\nSpecial Technical Adviser\nResearch and Evaluation Division\nCentre for Industrial Development ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1284, 'E2-1284AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, January 6)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines\nThru the Executive Vice President\n\nDear Mr. President :\n\nThis letter concerns the Physics Teachers Training Program and my impending retirement which will take place on 2 February 1964. The letter is being written because of some peculiar aspects of the contents of the training program. The undersigned has been involved in its operation (management and instruction) since 1960 at which time it was known that said program would phase out at the end of the school year 1964. The peculiar aspects referred to above may be summarized as follows : \n\n1) The materials being used for the physics course of the Bureau of Public Schools teachers enrolled under this program are those prepared by the Physical Science Study Committee (PSSC) of the United States. The undersigned is now teaching this course due to shortage of manpower in the Department of Physics. \n\n2) Another peculiar aspect of the program is handling of Education 299 (Seminar) by the undersigned due to unavailability of professors. In Education 299, the goal is for the teachers under training to complete an adaptation from PSSC materials that would be suitable for use in their classes when they return to their posts. An analogous adaptation was prepared by a previous group of teachers last summer. That adaptation has generated considerable interest in high schools in the Philippines both private and public. This year\'s adaptation is expected to be superior to last summer\'s adaptation because about three times as long a period is available for the incubation requirements of modernized concepts and new approaches which characterized the training program.\n\nShould UP find itself confronted with delay in arranging for the takeover of these two courses, the undersigned stands ready to continue handling these two courses until the end of this semester or until his replacement is found, whichever is the earlier. \n\nYours truly, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\n(Programme Management)\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1285, 'E2-1285AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, January 8)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines\nThru the Executive Vice President\n\nDear Mr. President :\n\nIn connection with any compulsary and automatic retirement which will go into effect on 2 February 1964 (about three weeks from now) I should to bring to your attention, for the purpose of seeking advice and soliciting help, a bottleneck which holds up the processing of my retirement papers at the Property Office. Mr. Antonio, officer-in-charge of the office believes that he cannot sign my clearance papers until an inventory of dollar aid commodities received from USA is completed in the form satisfactory to NEC. Further , he said he cannot proceed to make this satisfactory inventory list until NEC furnishes his office with a detailed list of the names of the equipment. I learned about this in a conference with Mr. Antonio and his assistant yesterday. They also made me understand that they do not expect that the NEC list is forthcoming, and that they cannot take another step forward in the absence of such list. \nI became involved in the dollar commodities from USA because at the time that most of the equipment for Engineering, Education, Business Administration, Industrial Pharmacy, Geology, Chemistry and Physics were coming in, I was the project director of USOM-NEC projects at Diliman, by designation by Dr. Vidal A. Tan, then U.P. President. \nIt appears that the delay mentioned above will last for several years (perhaps forever in the event that the two parties do not agree on a course of action.) I therefore beg of you to find an avenue of action by which Mr. Antonio\'s objections may be waived.\nShould my services be deemed of any value to you for the purpose of breaking the impasse between our property office on the one hand and the NEC counterpart personnel on the other, I stand ready to give them. \nYours respectfully, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences  ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1286, 'E2-1286AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, March 16)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines\nCampus\n \nSir : \n\nThese comments are being submitted in compliance with your order of 11 March, which was received 13 March. \nI. Records Were Not Lacking.\nThe following quotation from the Third Progress Report, which will be ready by Palm Sunday, should dispel all doubts regarding availability of ample records at the Business Executive\'s office : \"Using no other records than those in the possession of the property office earlier than 1963, the task of assembling an inventory covering dollar commodities in the numerous P.A.\'s under C.P. 20, C.P. 30, C.P. 65, and C.P.\'s 430, 530,...930 got under way on 29 February 1964. On 13 March, 1964 an inventory exceeding $1,275,000.00 was completed and submitted to NEC. A meeting amongst NEC, AID, and UP has been scheduled to be held on 31 March tentatively. \nII. Dr. Herrera, Mr. Velasco, Mr. Talingdan\nThe Business Executive mentioned the roles played by Dr. Herrera, Mr. Velasco and Mr. Talingdan in the two previous liquidation efforts. I am withholding my comments on these until after interviews with these three gentlemen. In the meanwhile I limit myself to wondering why I, who has been eager all the time to participate in the liquidation efforts was not invited to join then or earlier; and to speculating why those three clearks allegedly assigned to Dr. Herrera too six months to find out that there were no records to start with. \nIII. 1952-1953 vs. 1953-1959\nThe absence of commodities received by Chemistry, Geology and Industrial Pharmacy from the June 1963 $600,000.00 inventory casts doubts on the existence of \"complete records of 1952-1953 operation in the property office\" as claimed by the Business Executive. In any case it became apparent in 1953 that the efforts involved in handling increasing volumes of dollar commodities were beyond the capabilities of our property office. It was decided therefore that this office enter the operation at the time the end-user is opening the crates at which time memorandum receipts are to be prepared. [Representatives of property and/or auditing offices witness the opening of crates].\nThe end-user acknowledges accountability to UP by memo receipts; and accountability to the project director, by Form 131. UP acknowledges accountability to NEC-ICA via Form 131 executed by the project director. \nIV. Property Responsibility and Jurisprudence\nResponsibility for the vast amounts of incoming properties loomed high in our thoughts in 1953. The principle that was adopted in connected with this problem may be outlined as follows : \n1) UP as a recipient of foreign aid is accountable to NEC, which in turn is accountable to USOM, Manila. USOM, Manila is accountable to ICA, Washington.\n2) In each of the above institutions there is a network of accountability peculiar to its organizational pattern. \n3) In UP the pattern of network accountability to NEC-ICA may be described as follows : \na) The project director answers to NEC on behalf of UP. In answering UP\'s accountability the project director depends on the property office, which is supposed to hold memo-receipts for equipment, etc. \nb) In the event that such a memo receipt had not been duly accomplished or had been mislaid, the project director and/or the property office representative seek the assistance of the end-users. The P.A. number under which the equipment had been procured serves as a guide as to who is the end-user of the equipment in question. The end-user exhibits the equipment or proves its existence by some other means. \nc) The end-user is doubly accountable; first to the property office, via memorandum receipt; and the second to the project director via Form 131. However when either of these two accountabilities is satisfied, the other is also satisfied automatically. In any case the ultimate criterion for the satisfaction of accountability is the physical existence of the property under consideration. Thus when a professor satisfies the accountability to the property office for a piece of equipment such as a Diesel Engine, the accountability of any other person to any other officer in connection with the Diesel Engine is automatically satisfied. \nd) The accountability of the project director is incidental to his function; i.e., it automatically ceases as soon as someone else takes over his functions. Otherwise, the situation would be incongruous in the sense that many people would still remain accountable for properties in C.P.\'s 430, 530, ....930 since at one time or another, Dr. Sinco, Dr. Virata, Prof. Campos, Dr. Tentamatay, etc. served as project directors. \nYours truly, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1287, 'E2-1287AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, March 3) ', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Campus\nSir : \nIn pursuance of the reservation stated in my letter of 20 Feb, 1964 to the effect that I rejected the proposition \"that the failure of U.P. to obtain the title to ICA equipment is due to the failure of C.A> Ortigas to account for many ICA equipment received while he was project director\" I hereby renew my request in writing that the remaining 50 percent of my cumulative leave be released and that a deed of clearance be issued to me on the ground that all such equipment had been previously acounted for at least once; some, twice; and others, thrice. The following facts and precedents show that all ICA equipment in question had been duly accounted for by their custodians and end-users. \nFacts and Precedents\n(1) When Dr. Jose Feliciano, head of Geology Department died his ICA property accountability passed on to Dr. Mateo Tupas. When Dr. Arsenio Gonzales succeeded Dr. Tupas he assumed property accountability, which included equipment from P.A.\'s 2265, 3029, 3047 and 6518. Thus Dr. Gonzales considers himself accountible for ICA properties received by Geology department thru the project director. \n(2) When Prof. Enrique Ostrea relinquished the headship of Mining department to Prof. Roman Ramos the latter assumed property accountability including the ICA property purchased for the mining department thru P.A.\'s 2265, 3029, 3047, and 6518. This accountability passed on to Dr. Perfecto Guerrero who succeeded Prof. Ramos. Thus like in the Geology department the property responsibiulity has been accounted for twice. \n(3) When Dr. Amando Clemente, head of Chemistry department retired his property accountability passed on to Dr. Salcedo, who in turn passed it on to Dr. Tentamatay, and finally to Dr. Pulido who now assumes the property accountability for ICA equipment received by Chemistry department thru P.A.\'s 2283, 3034 and 3049. Thus properties were accounted for thrice in this case. \n(4) Part of the properties received thru P.A.\'s 2283, 3034 and 3049 were properly accountability of Dean Valenzuela and this accountability passed on to Dr. Alfredo Santos as a matter of course. \n(5) Similar transfers ran smoothly as mattesr of course for properties procured for Engineering. Thus property accountability of C.A. Ortigas as former project director is a myth particularly because these equipment are here in our laboratories. The department heads say they are here and I believe them because I have seen most of them with my own eyes.\nConclusion\nA team of historians employed to process the records will draw the following conclusions :\n(1) \"The failure of the 1961 liquidation efforts for the transfer of the title to NEC-ICA properties to U.P. was due to the failure of the project director at that time Dr. V.G. Since to account for said property. The project director then did know what should be done and failed to recognize the fact that he did not know. \n(2) The failure of the second liquidation efforts made in 1963 failed because U.P. submitted an inventory, which was nearly $300,000 lower than the inventory submitted in 1961. [The writer of this letter believes that President Romulo present Project Director is not aware of this decrease].\n(3) The 1964 efforts being exerted now stand on excellent chance of succeeding because of the participation of C.A. Ortigas, who is familiar with most of the properties involved in the counterpart projects being liquidated. The records indicate that he was invited to participate in this third efforts but was excluded in the first and in the second.\"\nIn the foregoing I have not only demonstrated that property accountability is the responsibility of the heads of the departments using the equipment but have also located and identified the causes of the failure of the liquidation efforts in 1961 and in 1963. \nTherefore I reiterate that U.P. cease to hold up my clearance. \nVery truly yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1288, 'E2-1288AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, March 23)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Campus\n\nSubject : Third Progress Report \n\nDear Mr. President :\n\nOn 6 March 1964 the undersigned was commissioned \"to handle the UP part of the liquidation of NEC-AID properties...\" To prepare himself for the obligations anent this commission he consulted records at all levels. Amongst his findings there are two which should be cast in sharp focus and rendered in bold relief because they affect reputations of individuals as well as the integrity of the state university. The enumeration of these findings is hereunder placed after the statement of performance in order that their bearing on the liquidation efforts may be discerned rightly. \nPerformance\nUsing no other records than those in the possession of the property office earlier than 1963, the task of assembling an inventory covering dollar commodities in the numerous P.A.\'s under CP 20, CP 30, CP 65 and CP 430, 530...930 got under way on 29 February 1964. On 13 March 1964, an inventory exceeding $1,275,-000 was completed and submitted to NEC. A meeting amongst NEC, AID and UP has been scheduled to be held on 31 March tentatively. [The preceding paragraph was quoted in advance on 16 March in response to President Romulo\'s request for comments on the letter of the Business Executive].\nOn 19 March additional sheets of For 41-A coveirng over $26,000 worth of ICA books and periodicals were forwarded to NEC. Recognition is hereby recorded in favor of Mr. Fidel Camaniag of the property office, who contributed about 30 per cent of these additional materials. \nAt the present time we are in the midst of segregating equipment in PA 3034 and PA 2283 into two groups; namely the Chemistry group and the Pharmacy group. PA 3034 and PA 2283 represent about $200,000 issued in FY 1951-1952 and FY 1952-1953 to CP 30. I was not the project director of this counterpart project; I believe Dr. Virata was the project director. \nFindings\nThe findings referred to in the first paragraph of this report may be classified under two headings; namely, inability to read the score and propensity to make untrue statements. The following illustrations are presented. \nI. Inability to read the score. \nDuring the months of January and February four persons in the various offices of the Business Executive informed the undersigned on different occassions in a tone of finality that the UP team who had been going to NEC to gather records needed to continue going there before they could construct the list of items for which he was being held accountable. For the purpose of safeguarding the reputation of other employees of said offices, I hereby record the names of the aforementioned persons as Professor Jose Campos, Jr.; Business Executive; Mr. Arsenio Talingdan, Management Analyst and IBM Coordinator; Mr. Carlos Antonio, In-charge Property Division; and Mr. Adriano Cabel, Chief Inventory Section. The behaviour of these four officers of the UP proves that they did not know the score of the liquidation efforts in June 1963 and proves further that they had not learned how to read the score from June 1963 to January 1964. For as stated in the first paragraph of this letter the inventory for $1,275,000 of ICA commodities was based on the records that had been in their hands earlier than June 1963.\nThe Business Executive was right in saying that money was wasted in sending the UP team to NEC in the sense that they spent time gathering records for PA 2265, PA 3029, PA 3047 and PA 6518 and perhaps PA 2324, which records have been always in the files of the College of Engineering (not in Ortigas\' file). Again an example of inability to read the score. \nOne more illustration. On 14 August 1962 Prof. Campos wrote : \"As of now, the remaining stumbling block for the finalization of this turnover is the uncooperation of the College of Engineering.\" The real stumbling block as recently revealed is the ICA property that went to Chemistry and Industrial Pharmacy in 1952 and 1953.\nII. Propensity for Untrue Statements\n(a) On 9 March the Business Executive wrote that the property office had complete records of the commodities received in 1952 and 1953. However, on 29 October 1962 he wrote : \"All the equipment coming under various projects from 1952 up to 1960 were delivered direct to the different units of the university thru their respective project directors who took charge of distributing said items.\"\nIt is obvious that the two statements mentioned above cannot be both true. Since I was not a project director during FY 1952 and FY 1953 I requested in writing for a loan of the \"complete records\" that was referred to in 9 March statement because such records would be useful for the segregation of ICA Chemistry commodities from the ICA Pharmacy commodities. Mr. Cabel of the property office informed my emissary that there were no other records than the PA 2283 and PA 3034 and PA 3049 folders, which were obtained from NEC around 1962.\n(b) On 4 March 1964 the Business Executive wrote : \"This work on the liquidation of NEC-AID was entrusted by the President to the undersigned (Prof. Campos) in June, 1962. The help of Prof. Ortigas was sought thru the Dean but we did not hear from him until January 1964...\" This statement is false. I never heard from the Business Executive nor from the Dean. \nRecommendations\nThe inability to read the score together with the propensity for untruth amy be only a mechanism of defense which results from a face-saving struggle for survival. If this be the case then the sooner assistance is extended to Prof. Campos, Mr. Talingdan, Mr. Antonio and Mr. Cabel either separately or collectively the better it will be for the university. For this purpose, I recommend that : \nI. A corps of technical assistance volunteers (TACV) be constituted immediately to guide the above enumerated persons in the performance of their duties in connection with NEC-AID properties. The nucleus of thsi corps shall include the present project director or deputy director of C.P.\'s 6030, 6130, 6230 and6330, the former project director of C.P. 20, C.P. 30 and C.P. 65, and the former project director of C.P.\'s 430, 530...930. (The above mentioned nucleus involves so far only two persons : President Romulo or Vice-President Virata and Prof. Ortigas).\nII. To enable this TACV to render assistance quickly and effectively the Business Executive shall furnish said TACV with copies of the lists of NEC-ICA properties covered by the transfer of accountability in the following cases : \n1. Geology Department \n(a) From Dr. Feliciano to Dr. Tupas\n(b) From Dr. Tupas to Dr. Gonzales\n2. College of Pharmacy\n(a) From Dean Valenzuela to Dean Santos\n3. Physics Department\n(a) From Prof. de la Cruz to Dr. Magno\n4. Chemistry Department\n(a) From Dr. Clemente to Dr. Salcedo\n(b) From Dr. Salcedo to Dr. Tentamatay\n(c) From Dr. Tentamatay to Dr. Pulido\nYours truly, \nC. A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1289, 'E2-1289AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, April 6)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Campus\nDear Mr. President :\nLast month the undersigned submitted a request for the issuance of a deed of clerance in his favor on the basis of precedents. He maintained then as he continues to maintain now that it is not right for the Business Executive\'s office to hold him responsible for NEC-ICA properties that had been accounted for by end-users to the satisfaction of the B.E.\'s office during the years prior to President Romulo\'s regime. Without retreating from this position he hereby renews that request on the basis of justice. \nSeen from the affirmative side of the proposition that foreign aid is mutually beneficial to U.S. and R.P. as conceived in the Quirino-Foster Agreement signed by President Quirino on behalf of R.P. and Mr. William C. Foster representing President Harry S. Truman on 14 November 1950 the University of the Philippines is honor-bound to acknowledge its accountability to AID-NEC for properties received under counterpart projects operated by her. The Business Executive must have become acutely aware of his inability to account for NEC-AID properties last June when AID informed UP that UP\'s accountability exceeds by far the $600,000 inventory that UP was submitting for consideration at that time. Instead of requesting my assistance right there and then he abandoned the liquidation efforts for seven months; and in January 1964 he held up my clearance. This is an act of injustice; becauase the paucity of their inventory was the consequence of the negligence of his office. If the B.E. has asked me to help him at the time that President Romulo assigned to him the task of liquidating the NEC-ICA counterpart projects which President Sinco had taken over, the title to the properties would have been transferred to UP within the summer of 1963. How is this estimate arrived at? ANSWER : In less than three weeks in March, an inventory covering all PA\'s under CP 20, CP 30, CP 65, CP 430, 530, 930 was assembled in Form 41-A. In other words, the work that the B.E.\'s office neglected to do during four years of Tan regime, the entire Sinco regime and the first year of Romulo regime could have been made up within one summer last year or earlier. \nIn view of the foregoing, I hereby again reiterate in the name of fair play that the commander-n-chief of the University of the Philippines grant my previous request, which is detailed as follows : \n(1) Release the second half of my commutation leave; and \n(2) Issue a deed of clearance in my favor. \nYours truly, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1290, 'E2-1290AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, May 14)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Campus\n\nDear Mr. President :\n\nI shall be at the Central Philippine University from 15 May to 27 June for the National Science Development Board - Asia Foundation - supported summer institute for upgrading high school physics teachers in the Visayas. This information is being furnished in connection with my participation in the liquidation of NEC-AID equipment, which operation is not yet completed; the delay being caused by difficulties encountered in the location of and accounting for some $20,000 worth of commodities received under PA 2283 and PA 3034. \nThe personnel of the chemistry department started to trace the whereabouts of the above mentioned articles in April, but the problem still remains unsolved. There are about $20,000 worth of commodities duly acknowledged to have been received by the University but they cannot be located in the premises of the Department of Chemistry. Perhaps one-half of these are supplies and perishables. On the other hand, there are many pieces of equipment in the Department of Chemistry which are marked with ICA-PHILCUSA emblems and bear PHILCUSA property numbers, but these equipment do not appear in the original invoices and shipping documents. \nIn a conference between the head of the chemistry department and the undersigned yesterday, it was agreed that an ad hoc inventory team consisting of members from the chemistry department and members from the Business Executive\'s office to match records against existing equipment in the chemistry laboratories which bear the markings of PHILCUSA or FOA but whose names and descriptions do not appear in the original invoices might find the key to the solution of this ticklish problem. It is probable that some pieces of equipment purchased by the University of the Philippines\' money were wrongly labelled PHILCUSA while some pieces of equipment donated by AID were labelled erroneously as UP Property. This suggested solution is a simple operation but is difficult to get it started, hence this appeal to the commander-in-chief of the University.\nRecommendation\nI. It is recommended that an ad hoc committee such as described above consisting of two members from chemistry and two from property and supply office be formed and instructed to start the work soon. The lists of equipment referred to are in the possession of Dr. Pulido and the details of the operation of this team had been threshed out by Dr. Pulido and myself to the extent that my physical presence in the premises will not be needed in the next six weeks. It is also recommended that the commission of the undersigned \"to participate in the liquidation operation\" be extended to July 31, 1964 inasmuch as there are still other things to be done with respect to other procurement authorizations. \nII. It is further recommended that the University of the Philippines put her records straight with respect to the involvement of various UP personnel in the counterpart projects. Permit me to illustrate : - As indicated in one of his letters to the President the Business Executive was under the impression that the undersigned was the project director of CP 30 (Rehabilitation of the School of Chemistry) the counterpart project to which were issued PA 2283 and PA 3034 in Fiscal Years 1952 to 1953. We have been informed by the AID-Education Division that the director of said project was Executive Vice President Virata from the time it was established to the time that part of the project was incorporated wiht CP 430 (Rehabilitation of the UP College of Engineering) which went into effect legally in October 14, 1953 when pertinent documents were signed by the director of USOM and the Chairman of PHILCUSA. Dr. Vidal A. Tan, then UP President, recommended Prof. C.A. Ortigas to be the project director of CP 430 (Rehabilitation of the UP College of Engineering) on August 26, 1953. True copies of the letter of President Tan to Mr. C.V. Crucillo, Mr. Crucillo\'s letter, and that of the Agreement on the Rehabilitation of the UP College of Engineering are hereto attached. \nThe undersigned respectfully requests that the University of the Philippines request AID and/or NEC for further documentation that might help the various offices of the University to obtain a clear picture of the liquidation problems. \nYours truly, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1291, 'E2-1291AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1953, August 26)', 'Sir : \nA copy of your memorandum circular dated August 7, 1953, designating certain members of the faculty as project directors of counterpart projects nos. 20, 30, 31 and 65 received by this Office. Please be informed, however, that the counterpart budgets of Projects Nos. 20, 30 and 65 for FY 1953-54 have been consolidated into one counterpart budget for the Rehabilitation of the U.P. College of Engineering. PHILCUSA now considers these three projects as one project and desires that there should be only one project director. Under the new counterpart agreement which PHILCUSA has submitted to FOA, the Dean of the College of Engineering is designated project director of the combined counterpart project. \nVery respectfully, \nFor the Executive Secretary : \nSigned : CORNELIO V. CRUCILLO \nTechnical Adviser\n(Coordinator of Projects) ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
