(1292, 'E2-1292AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1953, October 14) ', 'COUNTERPART PROJECT NO. 430\nAGREEMENT ON THE REHABILITATION OF THE U.P. COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\n1. Description of Project :\nTo afford a better coordination and a more effective implementation of all activities aimed at the rehabilitation and improvement of the educational facilities and instructional staff of the U.P. College of Engineering, the Mining School Rehabilitation (Counterpart Project No. 20), the Rehabilitation of the U.P. College of Chemical Engineering (Counterpart Project No. 30) and the Improvement of the Instructional Facilities of the U.P. College of Engineering (Counterpart Project No. 65), have all been merged into one under this project. \nDuring FY \'54, activities will be directed towards the acquisition, receipt and installation of needed laboratory equipment and towards the construction of a chemical engineering laboratory building. This laboratory building will house the bigger pieces of laboratory equipment now causing congestion in their present locations. The engineering laboratory building provided for in the Improvement of the Instructional Facilities of the U.P. College of Engineering (Counterpart Project No. 65) is expected to be completed by the end of the second quarter. In view thereof, large machinery and equipment will have to be installed. \n2. Financing : \nBudgetary requirements of this project will be financed by withdrawals from the Counterpart Fund-Special Account, in conjunction with regularly appropriated funds of the U.P. College of Engineering, and counterpart funds provided for the Improvement of Instructional Facilities of the U.P. College of Engineering Project (Counterpart Project No. 65), the budget for which will expire on September 30, 1953. The University of the Philippines will provide P100,000 out of its regular funds to cover its share in the cost of the chemical engineering laboratory building. \n3. Counterpart Project Budget\nThe counterpart budget for this project will be for the period July 1, 1953 to June 30, 1954, in the amount of P345,000 as shown in detail in the attached budget of expenditures. These funds will be used for payment of obligations incurred prior to the effective date of this agreement. \n4. Operating Procedure :\nAn initial release of funds to the Dean, College of Engineering, U.P., in the amount of P90,000 for the first quarter (July 1 to September 30, 1953), is authorized at the time of approval of this agreement. \nSubsequent releases of funds will be made by PHILCUSA in accordance with need and upon submission of monthly financial reports by the project director in accordance with the provisions of Section 6 hereof. \nFunds released to the project director will be deposited in the Philippine National Bank in a current account designated \"University of the Philippines (Counterpart Project No. 430).\"\nWithdrawals will be made by checks signed by the project director designated by the President of the University of the Philippines and countersigned by the comptroller of the University. \nNo obligations will be incurred subsequent to June 30, 1954. \nPayment of outstanding obligations will be made within 60 days from June 30, 1954. Any funds then remaining will be returned to PHILCUSA and deposited in the Counterpart Fund-Special Account. \nA final report on the project will be submitted to PHILCUSA and to the USOM Comptroller not later than 90 days after June 30, 1954. \n5. Property Acquisition and Disposition\nAll items of equipment and/or furniture and fixtures acquired with counterpart funds will be properly labelled with the joint FOA/PHILCUSA emblem, and a permanent record of each item showing the cost, location, vendor\'s name and procuring voucher number will be maintained. All equipment acquired by the project and all supplies not consumed will be turned over to PHILCUSA upon completion of their use or completion of this project for such utilization or disposition as PHILCUSA and FOA/STEM determine. \nProperties and funds of this project will be subject to physical examination and the books of accounts and other records including property records being maintained by the project director will be subject to audit and examination by PHILCUSA and the FOA Mission Controller, at such reasonable times as they may desire to make such examination. \n6. Reporting Procedure :\nMontly reports of receipts, disbursements and outstanding obligations or commitments, on forms prescribed by FOA/PHILCUSA, together with a trial balance, will be submitted by the project director to PHILCUSA and to the FOA Mission Controller not later than 10 days following the close of each month. Complete instructions for the preparation of these reports are contained in the Manual \"Reporting Requirements for Counterpart Fund Projects\", copy of which was furnished each project director and accountant. The \"Reporting Requirements\" are hereby made a part of this agreement by reference. \nQuarterly reports of project progress and status will be submitted by the project director to PHILCUSA and to the FOA Mission not later than the 15th day following the close of the quarter.\n7. Date of Effectivity\nThe effective date of this agreement is the first day of the budget period. \n(SGD). HARRY A. BRENN\nDirector, USOM\n(SGD). PLACIDO L. MAPA\nChairman, PHILCUSA', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1293, 'E2-1293AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, May 14)', 'Fourth Progress Report\nThe President\nUniversity of the Philippines Campus\n\nDear Mr. President :\nI shall be at the Central Philippine University from 15 May to 27 June for the National Science Development Board- Asia Foundation supported summer institute for upgrading high school physics teachers in the Visayas. This information is being furnished in connection wiht my participation in the liquidation of NEC-AID equipment, which operation is not yet completed; the delay being caused by difficulties encountered in the location of and accounting for some $20,000 worth of commodities received under PA 2283 and PA 3034. \n\nThe personnel of the chemistry department started to trace the whereabouts of the above mentioned articles in April, but the problem still remains unsolved. There are about $20,000 worth of commodities duly acknowledged to have been received by the University but they cannot be located in the premises of the Department of Chemistry. Perhaps one-half of these are supplies and perishables. On the other hand, there are many pieces of equipment in the Department of Chemistry which are marked with ICA-PHILCUSA emblems and bear PHILCUSA property numbers, but these equipment do not appear in the original invoices and shipping documents. \n\nIn a conference between the head of the chemistry department and the undersigned yesterday, it was agreed that an ad hoc inventory team consisting of members from the chemistry department and members from the Business Executive\'s office to match records against existing equipment in the chemistry laboratories which bear the markings of PHILCUSA or FOA but whose names and descriptions do not appear in the original invoices might find the key to the solution of this ticklish problem. It is probable that some pieces of equipment purchased by the University of the Philippines\' money were wrongly labelled PHILCUSA while some pieces of equipment donated by AID were labelled erroneously as UP Property. This suggested solution is a simple operation but it is difficult to get it started, hence this appeal to the commander-in-chief of the University. \n\nRecommendations\n\nI. It is recommended that an ad hoc committee such as described above consisting of two members from chemistry and two from property and supply office be formed and instructed to start the work soon. The lists of equipment referred to are in the possession of Dr. Pulido and the details of the operation of this team had been threshed out by Dr. Pulido and myself to the extent that my physical presence in the premises will not be needed in the next six weeks. It is also recommended that the commission of the undersigned \"to participate in the liquidation operation\" be extended to July 31, 1964 inasmuch as there are still other things to be done with respect to other procurement authorizations. \n\nII. It is further recommended that the University of the Philippines put her records straight with respect to the involvement of various UP personnel in the counterpart projects. Permit me to illustrate : - As indicated in one of his letters to the President the Business Executive was under the impression that the undersigned was the project director of CP 30 (Rehabilitation of the School of Chemistry) the counterpart project to which were issued PA 2283  and PA 3034 in Fiscal Years 1952 to 1953. We have been informed by the AID-Education Division that the director of said project was Executive Vice President Virata from the time it was established to the time that part of the project was incorporated with CP 430 (Rehabilitation of the UP College of Engineering) which went into effect legally in October 14, 1953 when pertinent documents were signed by the director of USOM and the Chairman of PHILCUSA. Dr. Vidal A. Tan, then UP President, recommended Prof. C.A. Ortigas to be the project director of CP 430 (Rehabilitation of the UP College of Engineering) on August 26, 1953. True copies of the letter of President Tan to Mr. C.V. Crucillo, Mr. Crucillo\'s letter and that of the Agreement on the Rehabilitation of the UP College of Engineering are hereto attached. \n\nThe undersigned respectfully requests that the University of the Philippines request AID and/or NEC for further documentation that might help the various offices of the University to obtain a clear picture of the liquidation problems.\n\nYours truly, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1294, 'E2-1294AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1953, August 26)', 'Sir :\nA copy of your memorandum circular dated August 7, 1953, designating certain members of the faculty as project directors of counterpart projects nos. 20, 30, 31 and 65 was received by this Office. Please be informed, however, that the counterpart budgets of Projects Nos. 20, 30 and 65 for FY 1953-54 have been consolidated into one counterpart budget for the Rehabilitation of the U.P. College of Engineering. PHILCUSA now considers these three projects as one project and desires that there should be only one project director. Under the new counterpart agreement which PHILCUSA has submitted to FOA, the Dean of the College of Engineering is designated project director of the combined counterpart project. \nVery respectfully, \n\nFor the Executive Secretary :\nSigned : CORNELIO V. CRUCILLO\nTechnical Adviser\n(Coordinator of Projects) ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1295, 'E2-1295AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, April 6)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Campus\n\nDear Mr. President :\nLast month the undersigned submitted a request for the issuance of a deed of clearance in his favor on the basis of precedents. He maintained then as he continues to maintain now that it is not right for the Business Executive\'s office to hold him responsible for NEC-ICA properties that had been accounted for by end-users to the satisfaction of the B.E.\'s office during the years prior to President Romulo\'s regime. Without retreating from this position he hereby renews that request on the basis of justice. \nSeen from the affirmative side of the proposition that foreign aid is mutually beneficial to U.S. and R.P. as conceived in the Quirino-Foster Agreement signed by President Quirino on behalf of R.P. and Mr. William C. Foster representing President Harry S. Truman on 14 November 1950 the University of the Philippines is honor-bound to acknowledge its accountability to AID-NEC for properties received under counterpart projects operated by her. The Business Executive must have become acutely aware of his inability to account for NEC-AID properties last June when AID informed UP that UP\'s accountability exceeds by far the $600,000 inventory that UP was submitting for consideration at that time. Instead of requesting my assistance right there and then he abandoned the liquidation efforts for seven months; and in January 1964 he held up my clearance. This is an act of injustice; because the paucity of their inventory was the consequence of the negligence of his office. If the B.E. had asked me to help him at the time that President Romulo assigned to him the task of liquidating the NEC-ICA counterpart projects which President Sinco had taken over, the title to the counterparts would have been transferred to UP within the summer of 1963. How is this estimate arrived at? ANSWER : In less than three weeks in March, an inventory covering all PA\'s under CP 20, CP 30, CP 65, CP 430, 530,...930 was assembled in Form 41-A. In other words, the work that the B.E.\'s office neglected to do during four years of Tan regime, the entire Sinco regime and the first year of Romulo regime could have been made up within one summer last year or earlier. \nIn view of the foregoing, I hereby again reiterate in the name of fair play that the commander in chief of the University of the Philippines grant my previous request, which is detailed as follows : \n(1) Release the second half of my commutation leave; and \n(2) Issue a deed of clearance in my favor \nYours truly, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nProfessor of Engineering Students. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1296, 'E2-1296AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, July 14)', 'Dr. Joseph T. Howard\nPresident, Central Philippine University\nIloilo City\n\nDear Dr. Howard : \nThis is to reply to your offer to the undersigned to join Central Philippine University as \"Coordinator of Science and Math Teacher Training.\" I understand that an employment such as stated in your letter is customarily covered by a contract. It is therefore suggested that the following three points be spelled out in the contract : \nI. Manner of Compensation : This question is being mentioned first because on 2 July we agreed to hold it in abeyance and recently I heard that you were about to write me about it. It has come to my knowledge that directors, deans, etc. in Central Philippine University are given flat-rate compensation as dean or as director and an additional compensation for teaching assignments depending on the number of units carried. May I say that this system is to my liking because it will enable me to limit my teaching load to the extent that my performance as coordinator may be maintained at peak levels? \nII. Relationship Between the Coordinator on the one hand and Directors on the other. This point has particular reference to the clause \"you will be free to develop this program in consultation with the Administration as you saw fit and within the financial limitations of the University\'s budget.\" As regards this mandate, I propose that it be stated in the agreement that the Coordinator of Science and Math Teacher Training will be responsible to the President only and not subject to \'overrule\' by any CPU Administration officer other than the President. \nIII. Quarters. The undersigned hereby requests that he be provided living quarters in one of the mission houses at a rate to be determined by Central Philippine University. The living quarters may be part of a house or the whole house. He strongly believes that his work as coordinator can be best performed if he lives within the campus and in a house which will provide an academic atmosphere. I have been in some of your mission houses and there I felt this kind of atmosphere. \nCOMMENTS\n(Not part of agreement)\nTwo Phases. The Science and Math Teacher Training Program may be divided into two phases, namely : the development phase and the operation phase. At the present time there is no science and math teacher training program in CPU; therefore the work must start with planning and development. During the undersigned\'s tour of duty with NSDB Summer Institute at Central Philippine University last summer a one-year curriculum designed to convert holders of B.S. pre-medic into physics teachers was drafted by Dr. Cathedral, Prof. Sornito and the undersigned. Perhaps this curriculum will provide the starting point of the development of the Science and Math Teacher Training Program. One encouraging aspect of this one-year curriculum is the inclusion of four courses (two in mathematics of 3 units each; and two in physics of 3 units each) which were offered in the NSDB Summer Institute. Complete syllabi for these four courses could be worked out during 1964-65 while they are being taught; - as a start in the implementation of the program. \nSincerely yours, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1297, 'E2-1297AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, July 30)', 'The President\nUniversity of the Philippines Campus\nDear Mr. President : \nThis morning, officials of NEC, AID and UP held a meeting at the Board of Regents room. The undersigned attended this meeting upon the invitation of the U.P. Business Executive. \nOne of the items discussed was the transfer from AID to UP of the dollar commodities that were acquired under Procurement Authorizations issued during the time when the undersigned was Project Director. The transfer was not made during this meeting; - there are things yet to be done by NEC and ICA on the one hand and the University of the Philippines on the other. It was apparent from the pace of the deliberations during the meeting that the undersigned\'s assistance to the early transfer of these commodities is still needed. In view of this, I hereby request that my commission to participate in the liquidation efforts be extended until such efforts are terminated. \nTruly yours, \n\nC. A. ORTIGAS \nProfessor of Enginering Sciences ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1298, 'E2-1298AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, September 17)', 'General Carlos P. Romulo\nPresident, University of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\nDear Mr. President :\nIn view of the fact that Dr. Virata has already been issued clearance by the University of the Philippines as revealed to Mrs. Ortigas by Mr. Antonio of the Business Executive Office the undersigned, who retired six months earlier, hereby requests that a clearance be issued to him likewise. \nIt will be recalled that the Business Executive held up my clearance because of his state of helplessness with respect to the liquidation of NEC-AID dollar commodities, which were issued to UP from 1951 to 1960. This situation gradually cleared up to the extent that by July 30, 1964 it was accepted that the remaining mess lay in the dollar commodities requisitioned for chemistry department and the College of Pharmacy and Geology department before the middle of 1953. The project director of the counterpart projects up to then was Dr. Virata, which can be verified from the records of AID. The Business Executive erroneously held me accountable for these commodities because the progressive percentage receipts for commodities from these (pre-1953) projects were constantly and consistently carried in my quarterly and annual reports to NEC since FY 1954 in accordance with the form prescribed by that office.\nAt any rate the impediments to the issuance of clearance were the Chemistry-Industrial Pharmacy \"mess\". These impediments vanished when clearance was issued to Dr. Virata. Believing that I am entitled to an equally fair treatment, I reiterate my request that UP issue my clearance at its earliest convenience so that I may be relieved of inconvenience which has been forced upon my way of life since 2 Feb. 1964. \nVery truly yours,\n\nC.A. ORTIGAS ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1299, 'E2-1299AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, October 28)', 'Dean Francisco Nemenzo\nCollege of Arts and Sciences\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dean Nemenzo :\nThis is a follow-up of our conversation last Friday (23 Oct. 1964). \nI am convinced that the delay of my clearance stems from the absence of earnest concern and enlightened sensibility on the part of the preceding Business Executive coupled with the lack of competence on the part of UP officials that former President Sinco placed in the offices that he created and accentuated by the fear of said offcials to bring the matter to the attention of the President lest the seriousness of their incompetence be discovered. \nThe facts of the matter may be summarized as follows : I was retired on 2 Feb. 1964. My clearance has been held up since then by Business Executive Jose Campos, Jr., who unjustly alleged that the repeated failures of his attempts to secure the title to dollar equipment obtained from ICA thru various counterpart projects was due to my inability to account for properties received by the UP under my tour of duty as project director. \nThe records now available in the University at NEC and ICA show that properties received thru procurement authorizations (PA\'s) issued in the counterpart projects of which I was project director have been accounted for. It is true that there are properties that have not been duly accounted for but these were requisitioned in counterpart projects which other persons were directing, or helping to direct. Some of these persons are still in the payroll of the University. Among them may be mentioned Dr. Enrique Virata, Dr. Augusto Tenmatay, Mrs. Lolita Asuncion, Prof. Enrique Astrea, Prof. Roman Ramos, and Prof. Arsenio Gonzales. \nIt might be relevant to mention at this moment that the work of adjusting prices of properties and pin-pointing continuing responsibilities for existing equipment is going very slowly of lack of attention on the part of the officials using said equipment. Now this failure to adjust prices and pin-point responsibilities by the mere process of signing memorandum receipts is not a legitimate reason for holding up the clearance of a professor who has retired nine months  before and who was expended a large part of this nine months helping UP straighten out the confusion in its liquidation efforts without any compensation. I am pouring out these sentiments to you in the belief that as Acting Business Executive you might be able to cause this case to be given due attention. \nLet me mention further that Dr. Jose Feliciano, Dr. Amando Clemente and Dr. Ignacio Salcedo had been cleared of accountability for these dollar equipment for which I am being now unjustly held accountable. This action automatically transfers the accountability of the equipment to the property officers of the University, who issued the clearances to these gentlemen? May not this transferred responsibility be the real reason why they are holding up my clearance? If this is so then they are guilty of a serious misbehavior. \nI understand that GSIS has sent to UP a request for my clearance. I wonder if the GSIS request has reached you already. This appears to be a proper stimulus for following up my case. \nSincerely yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1300, 'E2-1300AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, October 30)', 'HON. GIL PUYAT\nMember, Board of Regents\nUniversity of the Philippines\n\nDear Sir : \n\nThis is an appeal to you as member of the Board of Regents to intercede for Mr. Crisostomo A. Ortigas so that he may secure his clearance from the University of the Philippines. \nBy virtue of the Retirement Law he was retired from the service on February 2, 1964. A requirement for the release of retirement gratuity is a statement of clearance from the University of the Philippines (Form 420) and which has been signed by the Dean of the College of Engineering, the U.P. Librarian, the Legal Officer and heads of other units recommending the issuance of clearance. The Property Custodian of UP, has, however, up to this time refused to sign this form. Prof. Jose Campos, past Business Executive, in a letter to the President, explained that Mr. Ortigas could not be given his clearance because he \"failed to account for NEC-ICA equipment issued to him.\" \nI shall attempt to explain the background of this stinging remark of the Business Executive. \nFrom 1953 to 1959, Mr. Ortigas was Project Director of NEC-ICA sponsored projects for the rehabilitation of the College of Engineering. As such, dollar commodities were sent directly to him for him to distribute to end users such as the Department of Geology and Department of Chemistry. The heads of these units in turn acknowledged the receipts of these commodities in proper documents and thus assumed responsiblity for them. Reports of the disposition of the commodities were periodically sent to the sponsoring agencies and copies of these reports were sent to the Property Division, U.P. \nIn July, 1960, Mr. Ortigas was furnished a copy of a letter of Prof. Jose Campos, then Secretary of the Board of Regents, to Dr. Jose Locsin, Chairman of NEC. In this letter he notified Dr. Locsin that in accordance with the policy laid down by the Board of Regents, the President of the University of the Philippines was to be the Project Director of all NEC-ICA projects. The letter terminated Mr. Ortigas\' duties as Project Director. \nShortly after this, NEC-ICA projects were terminated and U.P., NEC and AID tried to negotiate for transfer of the assets to the University of the Philippines. But up to now no such transfers have been accomplished becauase of discrepancies in the inventories of the three agencies involved. \nIt is on the strength of this failure that the clearance of Mr. Ortigas is being withheld. So Mr. Ortigas requested the President to allow him to reconstruct the inventory of this equipment. The President allowed him to do this and by March, 1964, Mr. Ortigas was ready with an inventory that was submitted to NEC. \nIn July, 1964, Mr. Ortigas was invited by Prof. Campos to sit at a meeting of NEC, AID and UP representatives. At this meeting the three agencies again differed in their inventory values. NEC submitted the smallest, UP next and AID the biggest. UP was sixty-two thousand dollars ($62,000) behind AID. Mr. Ortigas requested AID representative to identify in terms of document numbers the missing items. But up to now nothing has been heard from AID.\nThe situation has reached an impasse. It is improbable that these three offices, the NEC, AID and UP will ever be able to reconcile their records with one another. They have been trying to do this the past three years. The difference in the figures may be due to accounting systems or interpretations of items. For instance, part of the sixty-two thousand dollars ($62,000) difference in AID and UP records is an amount of thirty-five thousand dollars ($35,000) for the Graduate College of Education. Dr. Antonio Isidro, not Mr. Ortigas, was involved in the College of Education. The UP Property Custodian upholds the opinion that there should be no clearance until AID accepts our inventory report. \nWe believe that the problem needs the intervention of high authorities of the University. This is a question that transcends the scope of the Property Custodian. For it is not a matter of the Property Custodian having found missing equipment. The question involves differences of inventory values which is quite distinct from a physical check up of equipment. \nMr. Ortigas has written a number of letters to the President requesting for the release of his clearance statement. But he appears to be waiting for the recommendation of the Property Custodian. \nThank you for your very kind attention. \nVery truly yours,\nTERESA Z. ORTIGAS\n(Mrs. Crisostomo A. Ortigas)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1301, 'E2-1301AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, October 30)', 'HON. ENCARNACION ALZONA\nMember, Board of Regents\nUniversity of the Philippines\n\nDear Sir : \n\nThis is an appeal to you as member of the Board of Regents to intercede for Mr. Crisostomo A. Ortigas so that he may secure his clearance from the University of the Philippines. \nBy virtue of the Retirement Law he was retired from the service on February 2, 1964. A requirement for the release of retirement gratuity is a statement of clearance from the University of the Philippines (Form 420) and which has been signed by the Dean of the College of Engineering, the U.P. Librarian, the Legal Officer and heads of other units recommending the issuance of clearance. The Property Custodian of UP, has, however, up to this time refused to sign this form. Prof. Jose Campos, past Business Executive, in a letter to the President, explained that Mr. Ortigas could not be given his clearance because he \"failed to account for NEC-ICA equipment issued to him.\" \nI shall attempt to explain the background of this stinging remark of the Business Executive. \nFrom 1953 to 1959, Mr. Ortigas was Project Director of NEC-ICA sponsored projects for the rehabilitation of the College of Engineering. As such, dollar commodities were sent directly to him for him to distribute to end users such as the Department of Geology and Department of Chemistry. The heads of these units in turn acknowledged the receipts of these commodities in proper documents and thus assumed responsiblity for them. Reports of the disposition of the commodities were periodically sent to the sponsoring agencies and copies of these reports were sent to the Property Division, U.P. \nIn July, 1960, Mr. Ortigas was furnished a copy of a letter of Prof. Jose Campos, then Secretary of the Board of Regents, to Dr. Jose Locsin, Chairman of NEC. In this letter he notified Dr. Locsin that in accordance with the policy laid down by the Board of Regents, the President of the University of the Philippines was to be the Project Director of all NEC-ICA projects. The letter terminated Mr. Ortigas\' duties as Project Director. \nShortly after this, NEC-ICA projects were terminated and U.P., NEC and AID tried to negotiate for transfer of the assets to the University of the Philippines. But up to now no such transfers have been accomplished becauase of discrepancies in the inventories of the three agencies involved. \nIt is on the strength of this failure that the clearance of Mr. Ortigas is being withheld. So Mr. Ortigas requested the President to allow him to reconstruct the inventory of this equipment. The President allowed him to do this and by March, 1964, Mr. Ortigas was ready with an inventory that was submitted to NEC. \nIn July, 1964, Mr. Ortigas was invited by Prof. Campos to sit at a meeting of NEC, AID and UP representatives. At this meeting the three agencies again differed in their inventory values. NEC submitted the smallest, UP next and AID the biggest. UP was sixty-two thousand dollars ($62,000) behind AID. Mr. Ortigas requested AID representative to identify in terms of document numbers the missing items. But up to now nothing has been heard from AID.\nThe situation has reached an impasse. It is improbable that these three offices, the NEC, AID and UP will ever be able to reconcile their records with one another. They have been trying to do this the past three years. The difference in the figures may be due to accounting systems or interpretations of items. For instance, part of the sixty-two thousand dollars ($62,000) difference in AID and UP records is an amount of thirty-five thousand dollars ($35,000) for the Graduate College of Education. Dr. Antonio Isidro, not Mr. Ortigas, was involved in the College of Education. The UP Property Custodian upholds the opinion that there should be no clearance until AID accepts our inventory report. \nWe believe that the problem needs the intervention of high authorities of the University. This is a question that transcends the scope of the Property Custodian. For it is not a matter of the Property Custodian having found missing equipment. The question involves differences of inventory values which is quite distinct from a physical check up of equipment. \nMr. Ortigas has written a number of letters to the President requesting for the release of his clearance statement. But he appears to be waiting for the recommendation of the Property Custodian. \nThank you for your very kind attention. \nVery truly yours,\nTERESA Z. ORTIGAS\n(Mrs. Crisostomo A. Ortigas)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1302, 'E2-1302AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, October 30)', 'HON. HERMENEGILDO R. REYES\nMember, Board of Regents\nUniversity of the Philippines\n\nDear Sir : \n\nThis is an appeal to you as member of the Board of Regents to intercede for Mr. Crisostomo A. Ortigas so that he may secure his clearance from the University of the Philippines. \nBy virtue of the Retirement Law he was retired from the service on February 2, 1964. A requirement for the release of retirement gratuity is a statement of clearance from the University of the Philippines (Form 420) and which has been signed by the Dean of the College of Engineering, the U.P. Librarian, the Legal Officer and heads of other units recommending the issuance of clearance. The Property Custodian of UP, has, however, up to this time refused to sign this form. Prof. Jose Campos, past Business Executive, in a letter to the President, explained that Mr. Ortigas could not be given his clearance because he \"failed to account for NEC-ICA equipment issued to him.\" \nI shall attempt to explain the background of this stinging remark of the Business Executive. \nFrom 1953 to 1959, Mr. Ortigas was Project Director of NEC-ICA sponsored projects for the rehabilitation of the College of Engineering. As such, dollar commodities were sent directly to him for him to distribute to end users such as the Department of Geology and Department of Chemistry. The heads of these units in turn acknowledged the receipts of these commodities in proper documents and thus assumed responsiblity for them. Reports of the disposition of the commodities were periodically sent to the sponsoring agencies and copies of these reports were sent to the Property Division, U.P. \nIn July, 1960, Mr. Ortigas was furnished a copy of a letter of Prof. Jose Campos, then Secretary of the Board of Regents, to Dr. Jose Locsin, Chairman of NEC. In this letter he notified Dr. Locsin that in accordance with the policy laid down by the Board of Regents, the President of the University of the Philippines was to be the Project Director of all NEC-ICA projects. The letter terminated Mr. Ortigas\' duties as Project Director. \nShortly after this, NEC-ICA projects were terminated and U.P., NEC and AID tried to negotiate for transfer of the assets to the University of the Philippines. But up to now no such transfers have been accomplished becauase of discrepancies in the inventories of the three agencies involved. \nIt is on the strength of this failure that the clearance of Mr. Ortigas is being withheld. So Mr. Ortigas requested the President to allow him to reconstruct the inventory of this equipment. The President allowed him to do this and by March, 1964, Mr. Ortigas was ready with an inventory that was submitted to NEC. \nIn July, 1964, Mr. Ortigas was invited by Prof. Campos to sit at a meeting of NEC, AID and UP representatives. At this meeting the three agencies again differed in their inventory values. NEC submitted the smallest, UP next and AID the biggest. UP was sixty-two thousand dollars ($62,000) behind AID. Mr. Ortigas requested AID representative to identify in terms of document numbers the missing items. But up to now nothing has been heard from AID.\nThe situation has reached an impasse. It is improbable that these three offices, the NEC, AID and UP will ever be able to reconcile their records with one another. They have been trying to do this the past three years. The difference in the figures may be due to accounting systems or interpretations of items. For instance, part of the sixty-two thousand dollars ($62,000) difference in AID and UP records is an amount of thirty-five thousand dollars ($35,000) for the Graduate College of Education. Dr. Antonio Isidro, not Mr. Ortigas, was involved in the College of Education. The UP Property Custodian upholds the opinion that there should be no clearance until AID accepts our inventory report. \nWe believe that the problem needs the intervention of high authorities of the University. This is a question that transcends the scope of the Property Custodian. For it is not a matter of the Property Custodian having found missing equipment. The question involves differences of inventory values which is quite distinct from a physical check up of equipment. \nMr. Ortigas has written a number of letters to the President requesting for the release of his clearance statement. But he appears to be waiting for the recommendation of the Property Custodian. \nThank you for your very kind attention. \nVery truly yours,\nTERESA Z. ORTIGAS\n(Mrs. Crisostomo A. Ortigas)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1303, 'E2-1303AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, November 11) ', 'Dean Vicente Abad Santos\nOfficer-in-Charge\nU.P. President\'s Office\nDear Dean Abad Santos : \nAttached herewith is the statement of \"clearance\" issued in favor of Crisostomo A. Ortigas by Mr. Carlos Antonio. The last sentence in this document, \"This certification does not include the NEC-AID commodities transferred to the University through him as Project Director\" nullifies the purpose for which the statement has been issued. It is no clearance at all. \nThere has been no transfer of commodities through Mr. Ortigas as Project Director. No transfer has been made because no agreement has been reached as to the value of the equipment. \nThe equipment received by Mr. Ortigas for the University as described in his documented reports have been found and located by a team appointed by Mr. Antonio himself. The heads of the different units have already acknowledged the existence of such equipment. \nThe reservation made by Mr. Antonio in his statement of clearance seems to be caused again by the fact that AID has not accepted our reports. We reiterate again athat his failure to reach an agreement should not be held against Mr. Ortigas. This was the basis of our appeal to Regent H.R. Reyes and Regent Encarnacion Alzona which was endorsed to you. \nAt our conversation last Thursday, November 5, 1964, it was my understanding that at a conference you called where the Dean of the College of Engineering, the Accountant, the Auditor, the Property Custodian and Regent Alzona were present, it was agreed that the report of Mr. Ortigas was to be accepted by the University and that was to be made the basis of the inventory of NEC-ICA equipment received by Mr. Ortigas. \nMay I appeal to you to please straighten out this matter of clearance? It has dragged on and on - nine months now! We have suffered already too many indignities being shoved from office to office; being charged with neglect which cannot be substantiated.\nVery truly yours, \nMRS. CRISOSTOMO A. ORTIGAS', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1304, 'E2-1304AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, November 24)', 'Dr. Carlos P. Romulo\nPresident\nUniversity of the Philippines\nThru the Business Executive\n\nDear sir : \nThis letter is on behalf of Professor Crisostomo A. Ortigas (retired, February 2, 1964), who is now in Central Philippine University at Jaro, Iloilo. \nThe purpose of this letter is to appeal to you for the release of a property clearance statement in favor of Mr. Ortigas. This has been pending for the tenth month now. The clearance is being withheld on account of problems encountered by the Property Division with respect to the liquidation of dollar commodities received by the University from the National Economic Council and the International Cooperation Administration now Agency for International Development (AID). \nMr. Ortigas was director of some NEC-ICA projects from 1952 to 1959. In 1960 such a designation was transferred to the President, University of the Philippines. \nOn May 2, 1961, the property clerk of the College of Engineering, Mr. Gorgonio Velasco, submitted to the Dean, College of Engineering, inventory lists of ICA-NEC equipment, dollar portion, for the period June 30, 1952 to December 31, 1959, broken down as follows : \nICA-NEC...$890, 343.06 -- 75 pages, 4 copies each Counterpart Project 420 peso portion...P16,265.71. Counterpart Project 430 to 930 peso portion..88, 242.99 (Engineering File #7.011-A)\nIn March, 1964, an inventory covering all Procurement Authority papers under counterparts 20, 30, 65, 430, 530...930 was assembled in Form 41-A.\nThe Property Division, therefore, had ample time to study these inventory lists, to check if not to honor them. \nWe therefore request, Mr. President, that (a) The University accept the inventory list submitted by Mr. Ortigas, and (b) The deed of property clearance in favor of Mr. Ortigas.\nVery truly yours, \nTERESA Z. ORTIGAS\n(Mrs. Crisostomo A. Ortigas) ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1305, 'E2-1305AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1964, December 29)', 'Rev. Brother A. Philip\nDe La Salle College\nGreen Hills, Mandaluyong\nDear Brother Philip :\nThis letter has been composed in pursuance of the suggestion made by Dean Waldo S. Perfecto last week. That suggestion was, I believe, unavoidable in view of the large number of conversations that have been between De La Salle top brass and the undersigned; - three with the Provincial, two with the President, two with the Academic Vice - President, two with the Chairman of Natural Science, and one with the Chairman of Physics. Dean Perfecto suggested that I write down a resume version of my interpretation of those pleasant conversations. I gather that De La Salle College is inviting me to join her staff on the hope that my experience and qualifications will help her attain some of her immediate goals in connection with her desire to see a stable and dependable Philippines. My concept of a fruitful role at De La Salle College is indicated by the block which I have inserted in the chart that Dean Perfecto furnished me. That chart, which now bears the insertion, is inclosed herewith. Said insertion is intended to indicate that the Coordinator of Science and Mathematics Teacher Training is directly responsible to the President (solid line) and has indirect relationships (dotted and dashed lines) with the Deans of the Graduate School and of Engineering as well as the Chairmen of Physics, Mathematics, and Natural and Engineering Sciences. This role is like that of my present position at Central Philippine University where I am under contract from 1 Aug 1964 to 30 June 1965 as Coordinator of Science and Mathematics Teacher Training with six units of teaching a semester. Central Philippine University has no Vice - President but employs instead a Director of Instructional Services to whom all deans report directly. The accompanying brochure illustrates the pattern of collaboration amongst Dean of Graduate Studies (Nelson) and the Dean of Education (Herradura), the Coordinator of Science and Mathematics Teacher Training.\nIn as much as Rev. Brother C. Richard had previously indicated to oversee the preparation of a proposal by De La Salle College, may I request that in drafting her proposal to the undersigned De La Salle College include the following items; namely, job description, initial and terminal dates of employment and rate of compensation? May I further request that such a proposal be mailed before February 1965 to : Professor Crisostomo A. Ortigas, Central Philippine University, Iloilo City?\nWith best wishes for the New Year, I am \nSincerely yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nInc : Administration Flow Chart with INSERTION\nTwo Central Philippine University brochures', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1306, 'E2-1306AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1965, February 17)', 'Dean Waldo S. Perfecto \nAcademic Vice President\nDe La Salle College \n1501 Taft Avenue\nManila\n\nDear Dean Perfecto : \nThis is to acknowledge receipt of your letter dated February 13 as well as the telegram which preceded it by a couple of weeks. I share with you the expectation for some more exchanges of views in the near future. \nCentral Philippine University has recently created the Office of Director of Research and put me in it without prejudice to my continuing as Coordinator of Science and Mathematics Teacher Training. Wish me good luck. \nSincerely yours, \nC.A. Ortigas\nDirector ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1307, 'E2-1307AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1965, February 22) ', 'Dr. Patrocinio Valenzuela\nExecutive Secretary\nNational Research Council of the Phil. \nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City\nDear Dr. Valenzuela :\nThis is to acknowledge receipt of the Addenda of the 26th February, 1965 Annual Meeting of the Charter and the Regular Members of the National Research Council of the Philippines and the accompanying registered documents. I regret to inform you that my duties at Central Philippine University require my absence from the said meeting. \nYours truly, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDirector ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1308, 'E2-1308AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'College of Engineering\nM E S S A G E\n(Philippinensian \'55) \nTo the class of 1955 : Congratulations and best wishes. The success you are about to achieve will form a firm foundation of your future. You owe this good fortune to the government of the Philippines. Consequently the Filipino people are entitled to a goodly measure of the fruits of your endeavors. In order to be of assistance to the five-year program of economic development you need to nourish the urge to serve your country. The University of the Philippines has given you the training and she expects you to cherish that urge. \nIn cherishing such an urge you are setting a living example to peoples of other countries - peoples who constitute the elements amongst which World Peace should reign. \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1309, 'E2-1309AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, June 12) ', 'Mr. Patrick J. Selak\nManager, Nuclear Engineering Department\nKAISER ENGINEERS\nKaiser Building\nOakland 12, California\nU.S.A.\nDear Mr. Selak : \nI was very happy to get a package from you and was delighted to take possession of its contents. I want to thank you very much for this thoughtfulness of yours as well as for the value of its contents. \nWe are waiting word from Washington with respect to their action to our nuclear reactor program. Our Congress recently passed a bill repealing the old law creating the Philippine Nuclear Commission which you heard about while you were here in Manila. We are very hopeful that everything will proceed smoothly. \nMrs. Ortigas joins me in sending you our warmest regards to you and your family not excluding the kids. \nSincerely yours, \nC.A. ORTIGAS \nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1310, 'E2-1310AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, October 24)', 'Dr. C.E. Barthel, Jr.\nAssistant Director, ARF\nTechnology Center\n10 West 35th Street \nChicago 16, Illinois \n\nDear Dr. Barthel :\n\nThank you for your letter of 17 September 1956. A few days before your letter arrived 6 copies of your proposal for assistance to our industrial research center were received - with profound gratification. It will take some time before we can get action on this matter; in any case we will let you know as soon as something develops. \nMr. Gollong dropped me a note indicating that he intends to stop by on his way back. We are looking forward to seeing him and talking to him about our local problems. \n\nSincerely yours,\n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
