(1311, 'E2-1311AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, September 17)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nIndustrial Research Center\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\n\nDear Dean Ortigas : \n\nSomewhat belatedly, I am acknowledging your letter of August 24, in which you requested information on the cost of consultation services which might be provided the Industrial Research Center by the Armour Research Foundation. In spite of the delay in writing you, Mr. Gollong and I have been at work preparing a draft of a plan of service to the Center. This draft is nearly completed and it will certainly be in the mails within a few days.\nThank you very much for your letter of August 24. We continue to hope that we shall be working with you in the not-too-distant future.\n\nCordially yours, \n\nC.E. Barthel, Jr. \nAssistant Director  ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1312, 'E2-1312AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, August 24)', 'Dr. C.E. Barthel, Jr.\nAssistant Director, ARF\nTechnology Center\n10 West 35th Street \nChicago 16, Illinois \n\nDear Dr. Barthel :\n\nThank you for your letter of 7 August 1956. This reply was purposely put-off hoping that the research bill would become law -- and the hope was fulfilled yesterday.\nThe first problem we have concerns control laboratories in which, I believe, your institute can help us. The question that arises naturally is : How much will the consultative services cost us? Proposals which do not carry cost estimate will not be acted upon by our superiors here. \n\nWe are looking forward to welcoming Mr. Gollong. \n\nCordially yours, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1313, 'E2-1313AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, August 7)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\n\nDear Dean Ortigas : \n\nI was indeed delighted to receive your letter of August 1st in which you announced that your law-making bodies had approved the research bill designed to give strong support to the development of research and technology in the Philippines. Science and technology are growing at such a rapid rate at the present time that no country can afford to lag. In my humble opinion, therefore, the decision of your law-making bodies will have a profound effect on the development of the economy of your fine country. \n\nOf course, I was equally delighted to hear that your group had convinced the Standford group that technical assistance for the support of an expanded research center should be sought from the Armour Research Foundation rather than from the Stanford Research Institute. You know of our intense enthusiasm for research in general and for the Philippines in particular, and we at the Foundation continue to hope that we shall have an opportunity to assist in the not-too-distant future in the development of science and technology in the Philippines. \n\nMr. Gollong, Manager of our International Department, plans to be in Manila sometime in January, 1957. He will certainly want to speak with you then about possible ARF assistance to your research center. In the meantime either Mr. Gollong or I will welcome the opportunity to provide you with any information that you might require to assist you in the initiation of a program of ART participation in the expansion of your research center. \n\nAgain please convey my warmest greetings to my friends in your College of Engineering and elsewhere in the University.\n\nCordially yours,\n\nC.E. Barthel, Jr. \nAssistant Director ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1314, 'E2-1314AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, August 1)', 'Dr. C.E. Barthel, Jr. \nAssistant Director\nArmour Research Foundation of Illinois Institute of Technology \n10 West 35th Street\nChicago 16, Illinois\n\nDear Dr. Barthel :\n\nThe day your letter of 20 July arrived was a happy one for us. The research bill we spoke about during your short visit at our campus was passed by our law-making bodies. It is now awaiting the approval of President Magsaysay, who we believe will not veto it inasmuch as he certified to its urgency for the special session. \n\nThe members of the Stanford group and our group have been talking about possible technical assistance from ICA as well as aid in the form of dollar commodities. I think our group have convinced the Stanford group that technical assistance should be sought from ARF rather than from SRI. \n\nWith warm regards, I am\n\nYours cordially, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean \n\nP.S. Dean Valenzuela is sending his best regards and is saying that he had already sent you by surface mail some of the bulletins of the National Research Council. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1315, 'E2-1315AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, July 20) ', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\n\nDear Dean Ortigas : \n\nI am so very enthusiastic about the value of scientific and engineering research on the economy of a nation that my discussions with you and your colleagues on June 26th were indeed a pleasant occasion for me. These discussions and others which I held with members of the United States Operations Mission to the Philippines, and with the staff of the Institute of Science and Technology, indicate conclusively that the Government of the Phlippines also recognizes the value of research to its development. The details of the planning for your Industrial Research Center seem to be well under way and we of the Armour Research Foundation wish you outstanding success in your program. I am sure that my visit with you on June 26th convinced you of the sincere and continued interest of the Armour Research Foundation in the development of science and engineering research in the Philippines and we hope that we shall have an opportunity to serve in your country in the near future. \n\nAgain, it was certainly a pleasure to meet with you and your people at the time of my short visit to Manila. I hope that you will be so kind as to convey my greetings to Dean Valenzuela and to Professor Ericksen. \n\nCordially yours, \n\nC.E. Barthel, Jr. \nAssistant Director', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1316, 'E2-1316AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, June 27) ', 'Dr. Paul B. W. Gollong\nManager, A.R.F.\n10 West 35th Street\nChicago 16, Illinois\n\nDear Dr. Gollong :\n\nThank you for your letter of 20 June and a copy each of \"Partners in Research,\" English version and Spanish version of the draft agreement, etc. Your letter arrived late in the forenoon of Tuesday, 25 June, and Dr. Barthel showed up early in the afternoon. Our \"conference\" lasted at least five hours and we enjoyed every minute of it. The antecedents of the pronoun \"we\" include Dean Valenzuela of the College of Pharmacy, Dr. Santos (Professor of Industrial Pharmacy), and Prof. Eriksen (Head of the UP-Stanford Contract professors). I wonder if Dr. Barthel enjoyed the conference as much as we did. He was accompanied by Mr. Alder (ICA staff/Manila) and his son. The Alders left Dr. Barthel to our mercy within the first hour. \nDuring that day, 25 June, the Senate of the Philippines was discussing the Research Bill which will provide ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1317, 'E2-1317AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, June 27) ', 'Dr. Paul B.W. Gollong\nManager, A.R.F.\n10 West 35th Street\nChicago 16, Illinois \n\nDear Dr. Gollong : \nThank you for your letter of 20 June and a copy each of \"Partners in Research,\" English version and Spanish version of the draft agreement, etc. Your letter arrived late in the forenoon of Tuesday, 25 June, and Dr. Barthel showed up early in the afternoon. Our \"conference\" lasted at least five hours and we enjoyed every minute of it. The antecedents of the pronoun \"we\" include Dean Valenzuela of the College of Pharmacy, Dr. Santos (Professor of Industrial Pharmacy), and Prof. Eriksen (Head of the UP-Stanford Contract professors). I wonder if Dr. Barthel enjoyed the conference as much as we did. He was accompanied by Mr. Adler (ICA staff/Manila) and his son. The Alders left Dr. Barthel to our mercy within the first hour. \nDuring that day, 25 June, the Senate of the Philippines was discussing the Research Bill which will provide us with funds for expansion of research operation in our College. The copy of this bill, which we furnished Dr. Barthel will be considerably altered only in wording but not in spirit. Many minor amendments were proposed by enthusiastic senators and most of them were accepted. \nWe learned a lot from reading the published report as well as from the briefing which Dr. Barthel so generously gave us. \nYours truly, \nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1318, 'E2-1318AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, June 20)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\n\nDear Dean Ortigas :\nIn view of your interesting letter of June 12th, we cabled our Dr. C.E. Barthel to make certain to see you during his all-too brief stopover in the Philippines. By now he will have had the pleasure of seeing you and discussing with you mutual points of interest. We will be anxious to have Dr. Barthel\'s report upon his return to Chicago. \nMeanwhile, we are pleased to send you copies of a draft agreement, both in English and in Spanish, similar to the ones we used in the Mexico, Colombia and Burma programs. Naturally, each contract must be tailored to the specific use and to the indigenous conditions. Obviously, we could not send you a direct copy of our agreement with Burma, but we believe that the enclosed draft is indicative of the type generally used. \nFurther, we are enclosing a copy of \"Partners in Research\", which sets forth the methodology of operation of the Foundation, together with a reprint on the operation in Mexico and a copy of a recent newsrelease on the Colombia opreations.\nPlease be assured of our continued interest in assisting in the creation of an effective research program in the Philippines. If we can aid in any fashion, please do not hesitate to let us know. \nSincerely, \n\nPaul B.W. Gollong\nManager ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1319, 'E2-1319AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, June 12) ', 'Mr. Paul B.W. Gollong\nManager, Armour Research Foundation of Illinois Institute of Technology\n10 West 35th Street, Chicago 16\nIllinois, U.S.A.\n\nDear Mr. Gollong : \n\nThank you for your 5 June letter and the three enclosures : Burma Applied Research Program, ARF Research Reactor and AMA Getting the Most From Research and Engineering. We are making preparations for contacting Dr. C.E. Barthel Jr. \nThere is considerable interest among our legislators to appropriate a sizeable amount of money for research during this coming special session which is scheduled to start 20 June. A copy of your agreements with Burma might help us draft a reasonably effective program of research in the Philippines. Would you be so kind as to suggest a quick way of getting such copy?\nThank you in advance. \n\nSincerely yours, \n\nC.A. Ortigas\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1320, 'E2-1320AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1956, June 5)', 'Dean Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon, Philippines\n\nMy dear Dean Ortigas : \n\nFrom our mutual friend, Dr. Ignacio S. Salcedo, we have learned that he kindly transmitted certain correspondence and material to you that we had send to him. Because of the study tour that he made in the United States and because of his association with the University of the Philippines, we felt that the material might be of use to him and to the University. \n\nSince we sent him this material, we have accumulated certain other brochures which we think might be of use to the University, particularly to the Industrial Research Center, of which you are a Director. The brochures deal with research and engineering and with our research reactor which was recently dedicated. \n\nWe continue to believe that the Armour Research Foundation may be of assistance to the Industrial Research Center of the University of the Philippines, as it has been to other similar institutes elsewhere in the world. Most indicative of the type of service we can render is the program in Burma, in which we are providing advice and assistance in the areas of research administration, project conduct, program development, and like activities related to the expansion and strengthening of the local Institute. Believing that the details of this particular program may be of interest to you, we are pleased to send you a copy of the Burma Report. The Government of the Union of Burma kindly has permitted us to make limited distribution of this report. \n\nIncidentally, our Dr. C.E. Barthel, Jr., Director-General of the Burma Institute will be in Manila the latter part of June. We hope that he has the opportunity of seeing you and discussing with you his activities. \n\nSincerely, \n\nPaul B.W. Gollong\nManager ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1321, 'E2-1321AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1955, December 13)', 'Mr. Wenceslao Trinidad\nSuperintendent, Maria Cristina\nFertilizer Plant\nIligan City\n\nDear Mr. Trinidad : \n\nIt is indeed a pleasure to inform you that our return trip from your very hospitable \"guest house\" to Manila was negotiated very smoothly and we enjoyed every kilometer of it. Our party stopped for a few minutes at the Forest Reservation in Itinao to enjoy its cool and refreshing atmosphere and at Cagayan de Oro to read the historical market of the Capitol building relating to the laying of the corner stone by President Quirino. We arrived in Cebu on schedule. Mr. Rodriguez of the CEPOC entertained us at the guest house until it was time for us to go to the airport. Our plane landed in Manila on schedule. \n\nProfessors Eriksen, Bromley, and Festin join me in saying \"Thank you again.\"\n\nPlease extend our warm regards to Mr. Pascual, Mr. Serrano, Mr. Flores, and the other boys. \n\nYours sincerely, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS \nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1322, 'E2-1322AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1955, December 13) ', 'Mr. Edergisto Rodriguez\nGeneral Supertendent, CEPOC\nCebu City\n\nDear Mr. Rodriguez :\n\nOur plane took off on schedule and landed on the dot - a very uneventful trip. \nProfs. Eriksen, Bromley, and Festin join me in saying. \"Thank you again for your hospitality.\" Please extend our warm regards to Mr. Parungao and Mr. Cabreros. \n\nSincerely yours, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1323, 'E2-1323AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1955, December 14) ', 'Mr. Filemon Zablan\nGeneral Manager\nNATIONAL POWER CORPORATION\nBonifacio Dr. Port Area\nManila\n\nDear Mr. Zablan :\n\nWe enjoyed every minute and every kilometer of our visit to Iligan City. The men at the Power Plant, Fertilizer Plan, and the guest house were very hospitable and solicitous of our comfort. \nOn behalf of our party (Profs. Eriksen, Bromley, Festin and myself). I thank you for the courtesy and hospitality.\n\nSincerely yours, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1324, 'E2-1324AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1955, December 16)', 'Dr. Patrocinio Valenzuela\nCollege of Pharmacy\nUniversity of the Philippines\nCampus\n\nDear Dean Valenzuela :\n\nI am sorry to report to you my failure to contact the Alumni Association at Cebu. The president of the Cebu Chapter is in the U.S. However, I met Mr. Cabreros in CEPOC.\n\nAs regards our visit to Iligan, I am happy to say that we met most of our U.P. alumni at the Fertilizer Plant, Steel Plant, and the Power Plant, and the Carbide Plant. Our alumni there are completely out of touch with the U.P. I think it might be a good idea to send them the Collegian and the Campus Journal regularly. These and other U.P. publications will establish good public relations with our alumni.\n\nThe journey was uneventful. Prof. Festin and I left Manila at 6:30 A.M., Friday, 9 December by PAL Convair, which landed on schedule (9:00 A.M.) at Cagayan de Oro where we transferred to another plane for Iligan, to join Profs. Eriksen and Bromley who left Diliman the previous Monday. The four of us left Iligan by National Power car at 6:20 A.M. Sunday to return to Cagayan de Oro to catch the plane to Cebu. The automobile made the distance in three hours over a considerably bumpy road. Our plane arrived in Cebu at noon Sunday. We spent Sunday afternoon looking for U.P. alumni in vain. Early Monday morning we left for a visit to CEPOC, where Mr. Rodriguez entertained us at the guest house. Soon after lunch we left for home and arrived here in Diliman about half past six. \nI repeat the journey was uneventful but we enjoyed every minute and every kilometer of it. \n\nSincerely yours,\n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1325, 'E2-1325AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1955, April 18)', 'Philippine Association of Civil Engineers\nQuezon City\n\nATTN : Mr. Ambrosio R. Flores, Chairman\nCommittee on Seminars and Publications\n\nGentlemen : \n\nYour 16 April letter requesting me to write on \"Progress and Trends of Engineering Education\" is deeply appreciated. I regret to say that the above article holds no interest for me. However, I shall be glad to contribute to your First Semestral Publication an article on \"A Proposed Program for Engineering Education.\" Please let me know at your earliest convenience if this counter-proposal is acceptable to you. \n\nSincerely yours, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1326, 'E2-1326AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1955, April 16)', 'Dean Crisostomo Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering, U.P.\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nMy dear Dean Ortigas : \nIn the name of the \"PHILIPPINE ASSOCIATION OF CIVIL ENGINEERS\" known as \"PACE\", I am requesting your help in writing an article about the \"Progress and Trends of Engineering Education in the Philippines and other countries\". This article will be published as one of the main features of the First Semestral Publication of the above-mentioned organization to be issued this, coming June. \nAs the Dean of the College from which most of the leading members of this engineering group come from, we look up to you for a full-hearted cooperation. The article should be due about the end of May to give us time to arrange the magazine set up.\nKindly notify the undersigned if you can prepare the article we are earnestly requesting, and we will certainly appreciate any other advice or suggestions you may have to make this maiden issue and succeeding ones a success. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nAMBROSIO R. FLORES\nChairman, Common Seminars and Publications ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1327, 'E2-1327AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1954, November 16) ', 'Dean Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Sir : \n\nWe are now working on the Philippinensian \'55 because of our desire to issue the university annual as early as week after commencement exercises. \nThe theme of the 1955 Philippinensian is \"Dedication of the UP Youth to the Cause of World Peace\". We, therefore, forward this request for your graduation message which we hope will primarily center on the aforementioned theme. \n\nWe would greatly appreciate it if you could send us your message on or before December 10, 1954. \n\nThank you. \n\nRespectfully, \n\nARTURO C. MOJICA\nAssociate Editor \n\nMESSAGE \nTo the class of 1955 : Congratulations and best wishes. The success you are about to achieve will form a firm foundation of your future. You owe this good fortune to the government of the Philippines. Consequently the filipino people are entitled to a goodly measure of the fruits of your endeavors. All that you need to do to be of assistance to the five-year program of economic development is to nourish the urge to serve your country. The University of the Philippines has given you the training and she expects you to cherish such an urge.  ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1328, 'E2-1328AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'M E S S A G E\n(Philippinensian \'55)\n\nTo the class of 1955 : Congratulations and best wishes. The success you are about to achieve will form a firm foundation of your future. You owe this good fortune to the government of the Philippines. Consequently the Filipino people are entitled to a goodly measure of the fruits of your endeavors. In order to be of assistance to the five-year program of economic development you need to nourish the urge to serve your country. The University of the Philippines has given you the training and she expects you to cherish that urge. \nIn cherishing such an urge you are setting a living example to peoples of other countries - peoples who constitutes the elements amongst which World Pleace should reign. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1329, 'E2-1329AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, March 16) ', 'Mr. R.L. Waterfield\nHereford, Swinely Road\nAscot, Berkshire\nEngland\n\nDear Mr. Waterfield : \nThe other night I met Mr. Amber, who gave a talk at a B.A.A. gathering over which you presided in 1956 in England. \nI should like to greet you and congratulate you on your election to the presidency of the famous B.A.A. I was hoping that you and Loyd (hope this is not far from the correct spelling of your companion\'s name in 1929 solar eclipse expedition) would show up in the Philippines to observe the total eclipse last year. \nWith warmest regards, I am\n\nYours truly, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1330, 'E2-1330AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, April 1)', 'Mrs. Luz B. Magsaysay\nShaw Boulevard\nMandaluyong, Rizal\n\nDear Mrs. Magsaysay :\n\nA few weeks ago, Mr. Gollong, the writer of this enclosed letter was visiting us in Diliman, Quezon City. He spoke very highly and very appreciatively of the leadership of the late President Magsaysay. Now he is conveying through the undersigned his deep sense of loss over the tragic accident. I am therefore forwarding this letter to you as a token of appreciation on my part of the sympathy expressed by the Armour Research Foundation. \n\nVery truly yours,\n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean\n\nEncl : letter of Dr. Gollong', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1331, 'E2-1331AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, March 22)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nDirector\nIndustrial Research Center\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\n\nMy dear Dean Ortigas : \n\nAs member of the Western Society of Engineers, I receive the publication, \"Midwest Engineer.\" Catching up on my reading, I found the November issue particularly interesting. Believing you too will find the article, \"The Peacetime Development of Atomic Energy\" pertinent, I\'m enclosing the magazine. \n\nMay I also add our expression of sympathy. To all of us here, the death of your beloved President came as a personal sense of loss. It will be most difficult to find a national leader of that stature again.\n\nSincerely, \n\nPaul B.W. Gollong\nManager ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1332, 'E2-1332AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, April 2)', 'Dr. Paul B.W. Gollong\nManager, Armour Research Foundation\nTechnology Center, 10 West 35th St. \nChicago 16, Illinois\n\nDear Dr. Gollong : \n\nThank you for the Midwest Engineer and of the Tagaytay print. The print, indeed evokes pleasant memories. General Nichols\' article on Atomic Energy is very interesting. \n\nI deeply appreciate your sharing with us our sense of national loss of our beloved president. I have taken the liberty of forwarding your March 22nd letter of condolence to Mrs. Luz B. Magsaysay.\n\nSincerely, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1333, 'E2-1333AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, March 25) ', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nDirector\nIndustrial Research Center\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines \n\nMy dear Dean Ortigas :\n\nShortly after mailing my last letter to you, the print arrived of the photograph taken at Tagaytay. The picture certainly evokes most pleasant memories.\n\nSincerely, \n\nPaul B.W. Gollong\n\nDear Dr. Gollong : \n\nThank you for the Midwest Engineer and of the Tagaytay print. The print, indeed evokes pleasant memories. Generl Nichols\' article on Atomic Energy is very interesting. \nI deeply appreciate your sharing with us our sense of national losso of our beloved president. I have taken the liberty of forwarding your Mar. 22 letter of condolence to Mrs. Magsaysay.\nSigned, CA', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1334, 'E2-1334AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, October 2) ', 'Mr. Eliseo Mendoza\nPresident, Natural Science Club\nPhilippine Normal College\nTaft Avenue, Manila\n\nDear Mr. Mendoza, \n\nI have for acknowledgment your letter of 30 September requesting for an autobiography and picture. I am deeply honored for having been chosen as one of the subjects of your project - the compilation and dissemination of outstanding scientists. However, I do not have on hand a written autobiography, so I am sending to you instead a copy of my Curriculum Vitae.\nHoping that this will serve your purpose, I am\n\nVery truly yours, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1335, 'E2-1335AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, September 30)', 'Dean Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering, U.P.\nQuezon City\n\nDear Sir : \nWe, the students of the Philippine Normal College, presently taking Natural Science 2 under Prof. Garzon, would like to request that you kindly furnish us at your earliest convenience your autobiography together with your picture. We are planning to compile the autobiographies and pictures of the first one hundred outstanding Filipino scientists as a part of our class project. \nReally, there is a felt need in pushing through this project because according to Prof. Garzon, who was one of the members of the Screening Committee on Science Talent Search, which was sponsored by the National Science Board through the cooperation of the Bureaus of Public and Private Schools, the University of the Philippine and the Philippine Normal College, the students who were interviewed were totally ignorant about the splendid achievements of our Filipino scientists. They blamed the local newspapers and magazines for not publishing their work and the seeming apathetic attitude of our institutions with regard to this matter. \nSpurred and motivated by the observation and comment of our professor, our class thought of this project in order that we might be able to disseminate in one way or another our outstanding Filipino scientists. May we, therefore, enlists your whole-hearted cooperation and support in order to make our project a reality?\nHoping for your kind attention and help regarding our request. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nNATURAL SCIENCE CLASS\nIII-G2\n\nBy:\n\nEDISEO MENDOZA\nPresident, Natural Science Club\n\nCONTENTS NOTED : \n\nDIONISIO P. GARZON\nProfessor, Natural Science ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1336, 'E2-1336AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, August 15)', 'Dr. Paul R. Hanna, Coordinator\nPhilippine Department of Education Contract\nUniversity of the Philippines Contract\nPost Office Box 1468\nStanford, California\n\nDear Paul : \nThank you for yours of 7 August and the enclosure. I am sharing the pride which you must be feeling from the rapid progress being made by SRI. \nTeresa and I are sending our best and warmest regards to Mrs. Hanna and you. \n\nCordially yours, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1337, 'E2-1337AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, August 7)', 'Dean Crisostomo A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman\nQuezon City, Philippines\n\nDear Cris :\n\nAttached is a bulletin published by the Pacific Gas and Electric Company which describes the opening of the new Stanford Research Institute buildings. I thought you\'d be interested.\n\nWe send you our best regards. \n\nCordially yours,\n\nPaul R. Hanna\nCoordinator   \n\nDear Paul :\nThank you for yours of 7 Aug and the enclosure. I am sharing the pride which you must be feeling from the rapid progress being made by SRI.\nTeresa and I are sending our best and warmest to Mrs. Hanna and you. \n\nCordially yours, \n\nC.A. Ortigas', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1338, 'E2-1338AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, June 23)', 'Dr. Paul B.W. Gollong\nManager, Armour Research Foundation\nTechnology Center\n10 West 35th Street \nChicago 16, Illinois\nU.S.A.\n\nDear Dr. Gollong :\nYour letter of June 12 revived my bright hopes for the future of the Industrial Research Center in the University of the Philippines. I was afraid that by this time you might have lost your interest in participating in the bids for Technical Assistance to our Research Center. Let me wish you good luck. I should have said let us wish ourselves good luck for your good luck in this project will also be a piece of good luck for us. \nMy sincere and best regards for you. \n\nSincerely yours,\n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1339, 'E2-1339AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1958, June 12)', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City, Philippines\n\nMy dear Dean Ortigas :\n\nYou can imagine my delight in learning from your letter of May 14 that action finally has been taken on the industrial research program. I, personally, must admit that at times I lost hope that anything would ever result out of the concerted efforts of our friends in the Philippines and of ourselves. It is, of course, some seven years since the initial interset in an industrial research program was expressed,. \n\nWe understand from conversation with Washington that bid requests for the program will shortly be issued. Although we do not know whether our own bid will be suitable, we deeply hope so, especially in view of the close interest we have for so long maintained with Philippine developments in this area.\n\nMy best and warmest personal regards. \n\nSincerely yours, \n\nPaul B.W. Gollong\nManager ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1340, 'E2-1340AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, December 2)', 'Congratulations to Tau Alpha on its twenty-fifth anniversary. It is a matter of first-hand knowledge to the writer that members of Tau Alpha have developed and cherished remarkable loyalty to one another.\nThis loyalty can be a potent factor in the development of high norm of conduct amongst the citizens of the Republic of the Philippines. The members of the Tau Alpha Fraternity possess the ability for utilizing this loyalty to enhance the usefulness of the University to the growth of the Filipino Nation. I hereby urge the resident members and the Alumni members of Tau Alpha to put up a performance that can be classified under a category that may be termed nation-wide rather than merely frat-limited. \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1341, 'E2-1341AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, November 25) ', 'The Tau Alpha Fraternity\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nNovember 25, 1957\n\nThe Dean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\n(Thru the Fraternity Adviser)\n\nDear Sir : \n\nThe Tau Alpha Fraternity is celebrating the twenty-fifth anniversary of its foundation this year. To commemorate this occasion, we intend to publish a souvenir programme. In this connection, we shall be honored it you can give us a message together with a photograph of your good self for inclusion with the abovementioned publication. \nHoping for a favorable reply to our request, I am \n\nVery respectfully yours, \n\nCESAR B. BAUTISTA\nGrand High Alpha\n\n1st Indorsement\n27 November 1957\n\nRespectfully forwarded to the Dean, College of Engineering, University of the Philippines, requesting for a message for the souvenir program of the Tau Alpha Fraternity. \n\nFELISBERTO G.L. REYES\nAdviser', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1342, 'E2-1342AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, November 26)', 'Dean Crisostomo Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\n\nDear Sir :\n\nThe TAU ALPHA FRATERNITY will celebrate its 25th anniversary on Saturday, December 7, 1957. A reunion of all alumni members is being planned and in this occassion, we would like to show to them the different equipments and laboratories of our college. As a matter of fact, most of the alumni are eager to observe the progress of the college since last they were here. There is also a plan of putting up, along the lobby, an exhibit of different products and machineries. We plan to hold this exhibit from Saturday, December 7, to Friday, December 13. \n\nIn this connection, we would like to ask your permission for the use of the college building and the opening of the different laboratories on the said day. \n\nWe pray for your kind consideration.\n\nRespectfully yours, \n\nCesar B. Bautista\nGrand High Alpha \n\nApproved :\n\nProf. Felisberto G. Reyes\nFaculty Adviser ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1343, 'E2-1343AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, August 26)', 'Dr. Paul B.W. Gollong\nManager, Armour Research Foundation\nTechnology Center, 10 West 35th St.\nChicago 16, Illinois\nU.S.A.\n\nDear Dr. Gollong :\n\nI have received your letter about the Conference to be sponsored by the Stanford Research Institute and the Time International Magazine together with the materials enclosed therewith. I inquired from ICA and NEC but they did not seem to be familiar with this project. So I asked Mr. Fernandez of the Industrial Development Center to help me contact the different offices involved with the request that he communicate with them directly and extend your invitation to each of them on behalf of the Armour Research Foundation. I believe that this was the most efficient way of letting these different companies hear of your hospitality. \n\nBest regards to you, Dr. Bartel, Dr. Nelson, Dr. Cieflo and others who were so kind to the undersigned during his visit in your laboratory.\n\nCordially yours, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1344, 'E2-1344AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, May 7)', 'Dr. Paul B. W. Gollong\nManager, Armour Research Foundation\nTechnology Center, 10 West 35th St. \nChicago 16, Illinois\nU.S.A.\n\nDear Dr. Gollong : \n\nThank you for your letters of 3 May and 22 April about Dr. Humphreys and Dr. Ewell respectively. \nI shall look forward to seeing Dr. Humpreys in our Campus and shall congratulate Ray as soon as I can get around to it. \nThings are going slow about the pesos from the National Science Board although moral support from NEC and ICA/M has been repeatedly indicated. \n\nSincerely, \n\nC.A. ORTIGAS\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1345, 'E2-1345AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, May 3)', 'Dean C. A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\n\nMy dear Dean Ortigas :\n\nShortly, Dr. R.F. Humphreys, Assistant Director of the Armour Research Foundation is leaving for Burma to advise on the Atomic Energy Program of that country. En route, he will stopover in Manila, arriving June 5th on PAA Fllight No. 833. He will stay at the Manila Hotel until the 7th and then proceed on to Burma. \n\nAlthough his stay will be brief, I believe that a meeting with you would be most interesting. Thus, I have asked him to contact you upon his arrival. A brief biography on him is enclosed. \n\nSincerely, \n\nPaul B.W. Gollong\nManager ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1346, 'E2-1346AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1957, April 22) ', 'Dean C.A. Ortigas\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City, Philippines\n\nMy dear Dean Ortigas : \n\nIn the \"C & EN\" issue for April 15th, I see that Ray Ewell has been named Vice Chancellor for Research and Professor of Chemistry at the University of Buffalo with the appointment effective in September, 1957. As you know, Ray, formerly Assistant Director of the National Science Foundation, has been a Consultant to the India Ministry of Commerce and Industry in New Delhi under The Ford Foundation. I thought you might be interested in this news. \n\nBest regards, \n\nPaul B.W. Gollong ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1347, 'E2-1347AC', '37', 'Atanacio, Edgardo C. \nDean, College of Engineering\n1997-2004', '', '', '', 'Chapter 1 : Industry Restructuring\nGoals and Constraints\nRange of Restructuring Models\nPrerequisites for Effective Competition\nModel 1\nModel 2\nModel 3\nUS History of Industry Restructuring\nPower Pools or Bilateral Trading\nISO VS. TRANSCO\nMarket Power\nConclusion\n\nChapter 2 : Independent Power Production and Competitive Bidding\nThe Goals for an IPP Program\nRelationship to Electric Utility Industry Restructuring\nRisks and Rewards\nPower Purchase Agreements (PPA)\nCompetitive Bidding Issues\nDealing with Contingencies\nRenegotiations\nConclusion\n\nChapter 3 : The Economic Justification for Utility Regulation\nTheory of Price in Competitive Markets\nTheory of Price under Monopoly Conditions\nNatural Monopoly\nObjectives of Economic Regulation\nPublic Goals of the Electric System \nElectric System Public Purpose Mechanisms\n\nChapter 4 : Institutional Framework and Process\nBackground\nFunctions and Responsibilities of a Regulatory Commission\nKey Characteristics of a Regulatory Commission\nIndependence of the Commissioners\nCommission Staff\nCommission Process\n\nChapter 5 : Cost-Based Ratemaking\nObjective of Rate Setting\nMechanics of Traditional Rate Setting\nElements of Rate Setting\nRate Design : Pricing for Regulated Services\nObjectives of Rate Design\nEmbedded Costs\nMarginal Cost Pricing\n\nChapter 6 : Licensing the Utility\nLicenses\nLicenses as a Supplement to Regulation\nAddendum\n\nChapter 7 : Market Prices, Subsidies and Public Policy Goals\nMarket Prices\nPublic Policy Goals\nDiscounts and Economic Development Rates\n\nChapter 8 : Performance-Based Regulation\nComponents of a PBR\nSetting the Goals\nPBR Structure\nAZ Factors\nThe Strength of the Incentives\nSharing Mechanisms\nFuel Adjustment Clauses\nGetting the Numbers Right\nConclusion\n\nChapter 9 Environmental Issues\nBackground\nWhat are the Environmental Impacts of Electricity Production?\nWhat Steps Can Regulators Take to Reduce Environmental Harm?\nMethods of Internalizing Environmental Costs\nCap and Trade Approaches\nEconomic Decisions that have Environmental Impacts\nConclusion\n\nChapter 10 : Consumer Protection Issues\nProviding Consumer Protection\nThe Need for Consumer Protection\nConsumer Policy Protection\nThe Obligation to Provide Reasonable and Adequate Service\nEstablishing Standards\nEnforcement of Consumer Protection\n\nChapter 11 : Integrated Resources Planning (IRP)\nHistory and Purpose of IRP\nGoal and Need for Capturing IRP\nNew Resources\nMarket Forces in the IRP Process\nConclusion\n\nResources for Further Information\n\nFinancing Resources ', '', 'Best Practices Guide : Implementing Power Sector Reform \nPrepared for :\nEnergy and Environment Train', 'The United States Agency for International Development\'s (USAID) Global Center for Environment, Energy and Environmental Training Program has developed the Best Practices Guide Series to provide technical information on the topics of power sector reform and regulatory practices. This series of guides is adapted from coursework that was designed to develop technical leadership capacity in energy development and greenhouse gas emissions reduction that are both friendly to the environment and beneficial to economic growth. This guide is for regulatory staff members, members of regulatory bodies government officials and professional interested in or working on establishing or restructuring the power sector, particularly those involved with regulation or establishing or restructuring regulatory functions. It provides regulatory decision-makers and professionals with enhanced knowledge and procedures necessary to start up and run an efficient and effective regulatory body. Through a contract with the Energy Group at the Institute of International Education (IIE), USAID\'s contractor for the Technical Leadership Training Program, The Regulatory Assistance Project (RAP) has prepared the Best Practices Guide : Implementing Power Sector Reform. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1348, 'E2-1348AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Report ', 'Project to establish virtual centers for technological innovation (VCTI)\nSub-study : Strengthening o', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1349, 'E2-1349AC', '', 'The Hanoi University of Technology', '', 'Hanoi', 'June 1997', '', '', '', 'The Hanoi University of Technology (HUT) was established in 1956. Over the last 40 years, HUT has been continuously growing and making considerable contributions to the industrialisation and modernisation process of the country. \nA large number of scientists and highly qualified engineers, who obtained various academic degrees of BE, MSc and Ph.D. at HUT, have been working effectively in various fields of political, cultural and social life, and science & technology development throughout the country. The obvious achievements in training and research undertaken at HUT and their application to production activities, have contributed significantly to the flourishing national technologies. \nOver the last decade, Vietnam has embarked upon a radical and comprehensive process of economic and social reform. Based on 40 years of tradition, HUT has been creative and dynamic in this process and has become a centre of excellence. It should continue to contribute more and more to socio-economic development, industrialisation, and modernisation of the country. \nThe development of HUT has been linked with strong support from the Government, great efforts by HUT staff and students from generation to generation, and especially with wholehearted assistance from international organisations and individuals. Our friends and colleagues in the world have supported us not only in building up infrastructure and facilities but also in teaching staff development. Over the years, international co-operation programmes have brought to the university effective staff with high academic standards and competence in training, research, and management activities, which has accelerated the process of integration of HUT into the university community within the region, and all over the world. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1350, 'E2-1350AC', '', 'Proceedings of the Professor Ma. de Castro Memorial Lectures / Edited by Benito M. Pacheco, Vibrametrics, Inc. and Victor A. Pulmano, University of the Philippines-Diliman ', 'University of the Philippines-Diliman ', '', '10/10/2000\nEdsa Shangri-La Hotel, Mandaluyong City ', 'Table of Contents\nPreface\nReminiscences\nSalvador F. Reyes, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nAlfredo L. Juinio, UP Engineering Research & Development Foundation, Inc. \nFelipe F. Cruz, FF Cruz & Co.\nMarino M. Mena, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nEdgardo G. Atanacio, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nReynaldo B. Vea, Mapua Institute of Technology\nAlfredo R. Austria, DMCI Holdings, Inc. \nRomeo L. Manlapaz, UP BS ChE 1960\nEdna Zapanta Manlapaz, La Vista, QC\nElsie I. Opinaldo, UP NEC Philippine Engineering Information Services\nRodolfo N. Ferrer, R N Ferrer & Associates\nEfren H. Sison, E.H. Sison Engineers Co.\nLeopoldo V. Abis, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nDaniel J. McNamara, S.J., Manila Observatory\nSelected Papers by Jose Ma. de Castro\nIntroducing a Computer System into the Civil Engineering Company\nThe 1985 Mexico Earthquakes : Their Implications for Metro Manila\nPreparing for the Big One in Metro Manila : A Proposed Program of Lifeline Preparedness\nLoad Resistance Factor Design Philosophy\nImplications of Welded Beam-Column Joint Failures During the 1994 Northridge Earthquake\nAnalysis & Design of Soil Nail System : Derivations \nTechnical Papers\nKey Elements to Consider in Revising the Codes of Ethics of Filipino Engineers by Manuel C. Belino, De La Salle University\nThe 1997-1998 El Niño Episode and Metro Manila\'s Water Supply by Reynaldo B. Vea, Mapua Institute of Technology\nComputation of Nonlinear Wave Field in Reflective Harbors by Eric C. Cruz, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nUsing Tensorial Biomorphometrics in Quantitative Growth Analysis of Prenatal Rat Eyes by Andre S. Publico, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nEffects of Chemical Composition and Diameter of Binders on the Interfacial Transition Zone in Concrete by Nathaniel B. Diola, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nCommercial Production of 10,000 psi Concrete for the Pacific Plaza Towers Project by Francis C. Felizardo, Oliver S. Elec, Jose R. Ofilan, Jr. and Maricor M. Cervera, Union Cement Corporaton, Unicon PHINMA Concrete Corporation \nGraphical Post-Processing of Finite Element Analyses by Mark H. Zarco, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nTechnique for Calculating Vertical Soil Stresses Underneath Foundations with Curved Boundary by Victor A. Pulmano, University of the Philippines-Diliman\nGreen\'s Functions for Clamped Beams by Salvador F. Reyes, University of the Philippines-Diliman', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1351, 'E2-1351AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Introducing a Computer System into the Civil Engineering Company by Jose Ma. de Castro ', 'Three case studies of engineering design/consultancy firms are discussed, to provide practical insights to civil engineering firms who are planning to computerize. It is observed that top management persons must be conversant with computer solutions of engineering problems. At least one full-time engineer must be detailed to the program development. The firm must choose the software first and then the computer system. Because the computer field is changing so rapidly, the system must be chosen that would pay for itself in three to five years. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1352, 'E2-1352AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The 1985 Mexico Earthquakes : Their Implications for Metro Manila by Jose Ma. de Castro', 'The paper presents initial information available regarding the 1985 Mexico earthquakes : the tectonic setting, the geotechnical characteristics of Mexico City, the types of structures that were damaged, and the types of foundations. A comparison is made with the setting of Metro Manila. Some recommendations are given from the structural engineering point of view, to help prevent similar damage from taking place in the Philippines. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
INSERT INTO `records` (`id`, `accessionNo`, `boxNumber`, `title`, `placeOfPublication`, `publisher`, `dateOfPublication`, `descriptionContent`, `type`, `paper`, `abstract`, `keywords`, `filePath`, `fileName`, `accessLevel`, `status`, `dateEncoded`, `updatedAt`) VALUES
(1353, 'E2-1353AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Preparing for the Big One in Metro Manila : A Proposed Program of Lifeline Preparedness by Jose Ma. ', 'The concept of lifelines is reviewed. To define the setting, both the political makeup of Metro Manila and its geotechnical condition are first reviewed. Among the lifelines considered are : transportation, water, energy and communication lifelines. A plan to provide reasonable assurance that these lifelines are functional after the major earthquake event is proposed. Roles of different entities, both government and private, are suggested. The proposed preparedness plan is discussed in two parts : post-earthquake activities, and development of public policy in anticipation of a major earthquake. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1354, 'E2-1354AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Load Resistance Factor Design Philosophy by Jose Ma. de Castro ', 'The publication by the American Institute of Steel Construction of the specifications for Load Resistance Factor Design (LRFD) signaled the acceptance of LRFD as a co-equal of the traditional Allowable Stress Design (ASD) in the design of steel structures and indicated that, in time, LRFD would be the predominant design method for structural steel. Although LRFD has already been in use as strength design for reinforced concrete since 1956 in the USA, and since 1986 in the Philippines (first adopted in the 3rd Edition of the National Structural Code of the Philippines for buildings), the philosophy behind the LRFD method of design is not yet fully appreciated by the local structural engineering profession. Because of the many implications of LRFD both for the practitioner and for building code writers, this paper presents a brief discussion of the philosophy and background of the LRFD method of design. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1355, 'E2-1355AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Implications of Welded Beam-Column Joint Failures during the 1994 Northridge Earthquake by Jose Ma. ', 'Contemporary wisdom states that a welded steel moment frame (WSMF), connected by means of Uniform Building Code (UBC) standard prequalified welded connections, is a superior structural system because of the ductility provided and is thus relatively invulnerable to earthquake damage. The 17 January 1994 Northridge Earthquake quickly proved that such frames were not only not invulnerable but were instead very susceptible to damage. This paper provides a catalog of different types of damage found in WSMF\'s, discusses some possible causes, and then presents some solutions proposed by different organizations and entities in the United States, some of which had been tested in laboratories under simulated earthquake loading. Finally, different implications are examined. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1356, 'E2-1356AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Analysis & Design of Soil Nail System : Derivations by Jose Ma. de Castro ', 'The block of soil-nailed material is assumed to act as a rigid body for external forces. The retained soil is assumed to have a horizontal surface, with surcharge loads that are uniformly distributed. Earthquake forces are not explicitly considered. Both the external stability of the soil-nailed block, and the internal stability of the nails against pullout from the soil, are considered in the derivation of required nails. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1357, 'E2-1357AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Key Elements to Consider in Revising the Codes of Ethics of Filipino Engineers by Manuel C. Belino', 'This paper gives a preliminary analysis of the five (5) Codes of Ethics of Filipino Engineers and enumerates some key elements that must be considered in revising these Codes. The key elements are : underlying principles, scope and form, marginally relevant elements, and concerns for contemporary issues. The concerns for contemporary issues include promotion of safety, health and public welfare; concern for the environment; respect for intellectual property rights; and, liberalization of professional services. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1358, 'E2-1358AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The 1997-1998 El Niño Episode and Metro Manila\'s Water Supply by Reynaldo B. Vea ', 'The Metropolitan Waterworks and Sewerage System (MWSS), the water franchise for the Metro Manila area, had to implement several measures to cope with the effects of the El Niño episode on the quantity and quality of the water supply. An explanation of the El Niño phenomenon is given as well, to emphasize the need of incorporating this knowledge into the process of strategic planning for water supply development. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1359, 'E2-1359AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Computation of Nonlinear Wave Field in Reflective Harbors by Eric C. Cruz ', 'A computational model is presented that applies to waves in harbors of any shape. A set of equations for nonlinear dispersive wave evolution is used with a damping term for energy dissipation at structure discontinuities and boundary conditions on the velocities at structure faces to model the coupled interior and exterior wave fields. The boundary condition is developed using a volume flux resolution method and allows for alternate ways of prescribing the condition for the direction of the reflected wave. The effect of structure damping is shown by a diffraction simulation and the applicability of the boundary condition for partial reflection is verified by comparing with the result of a laboratory experiment. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1360, 'E2-1360AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Using Tensorial Biomorphometrics in Quantitative Growth Analysis of Prenatal Rat Eyes by Andre S. Pu', 'Developments in geometric morphometrics, image acquisition, and geometrical information extraction technologies have made the invetigations of forms and form changes in biological intra- and inter- population settings increasingly practical. Presented in this paper is a reference-frame invariant morphometric method for handling, not only landmark data, outline data or interlandmark distances representation, but also the more general cases of multiboundary and zoned biological structures. Form change is considered as a large deformation of continuum from an initial to a final configuration. The kinematics is modeled as displacement funtions that satisfy the Laplace equation subject to Dirichlet boundary conditions. These problems are solved using the boundary element method. Growth analysis of prenatal rat eyes by this tensorial biomorphometrics obtained results that agree with documented qualitative descriptions.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1361, 'E2-1361AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Effects of Chemical Composition and Diameter of Binders on the Interfacial Transition Zone in Concre', 'The effects of chemical composition and the diameter of binders on the ITZs (Interfacial Transition Zones) between model aggregates and mortar were investigated. To achieve variety in binder chemical composition, three types of cement : ordinary Portland, high alite, and high belite cements were used together with fly ash and blast furnace slag. Limestone powder and ordinary Portland cement were sieved and classified into three diameter ranges for the investigation of the influence of binder diameter. It was found that the amount of C3S + C3A in the binder affects the formation of ITZ. Also, it was shown that the presence of fine reactive particles does not necessarily lead to improvement in ITZ or mortar properties. The effect of diameter of binder and some ways of improving the ITZ and mortar strength are also discussed. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1362, 'E2-1362AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Commercial Production of 10,000 psi Concrete for the Pacific Plaza Towers Project by Francis C. Feli', 'From August 1998 to April 1999, more than 12,000 cu.m. of 10,000 psi (10K) concrete was succesfully delivered to the Pacific Plaza Towers (PPT) Project, the first Philippine project to specify 10K concrete. Although producing high strength concrete is a technical challenge, the raw materials for producing 10K concrete are readily available. Moreover, the ideas behind its mix design, production and performance measurement are both simple and accessible to concrete producers with a good technical organization. The PPT Project proved that reliable and cost-effective 10K concrete is now available in the Philippines. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1363, 'E2-1363AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Graphical Post-processing of Finite Element Analyses by Mark H. Zarco', 'A procedure for post-processing finite element results is presented. The procedure uses graphic entities to generate mesh, contour and vector plots in data exchange format (DXF) for viewing and further processing using cad software. An algorithm for generating contour plots from finite element analyses results is also presented. The contour plotting procedure ues an interpolation scheme that is consistent with that assumed by the finite element formulation. In cases where the physical quantity being plotted is discontinous across element boundaries, a global smoothing procedure is employed to obtain the required nodal values. Illustrative examples are presented to demonstrate the capabilities of the proposed procedure. The resulting post processing procedure is general enough to apply to wide range of problems, and provides a convenient means of generating graphical representations of finite element analysis results. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1364, 'E2-1364AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Technique for Calculating Vertical Soil Stresses Underneath Foundations with Curved Boundary by Vict', 'A simple computational technique is proposed for evaluating the vertical soil stresses underneath foundations with curved boundary. By parametric mapping of the local and Cartesian coordinates which define an eight-node square domain and an eight-node domain with curved boundary, respectively, the integral expression of the Boussinesq solution over a loaded domain with curved boundary is transformed into an expression which can be easily integrated using the Gaussian integration scheme. Numerical example is presented to demonstrate the performance of the proposed technique. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1365, 'E2-1365AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Green\'s Functions for Clamped Beams by Salvador F. Reyes ', 'In the analysis of frames using general-purpose commercial software, obtaining the value of the bending moment function M(x) and transverse shear V (x) at any section x of a non-prismatic beam or a beam subjected to uncommon combinations of loading can be cumbersome and not too accurate. To provide an alternative, this note derives Green\'s functions for bending moment and shear in the clamped beam with or without a hinge release at some point on the axis. The task of finding shear and bending moment functions under any loading condition is reduced to a straightforward numeric integration process that may be easily implemented on currently available personal computers. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
