(1493, 'E2-1493AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'FAG INNOVATION AWARD 2002', 'FAG INNOVATION AWARD 2002\nFAG KUGELFISCHER FOUNDATION\n\nExamples of themes\nProduct Innovation\n- Development of physical / mathematical models for describing the kinematics and dynamics in rolling bearings. \n- Tribology in rolling contact\n- Reaction layer formation in rolling or sliding contacts when applying suitable EP lubricants. \n- Inspection technique for determining the lubricant life cycle\n- Mechanisms of material fatigue in rolling contact\n- New methods in analysis and diagnostics of rolling bearing damage\n- Surface layer coating of rolling bearing companies\n- Cage stress in roller bearings\n- Criteria of minimum loads in large rolling bearings\n- Vibration diagnostics for the determination of rolling bearing life cycles\n\nEnhanced Manufacturing\n- New methods in ring manufacture\n- Cycle-time dependent heat treatment of rolling bearing rings\n- New methods in grinding and honing technology\n- New findings with regard to the flexible small lot production\n- Self-learning factory - Conditions and factors\n- New methods in the machining of hardened materials\n- New surface techniques for metal surfaces\n\nMarket Strategy\n- Marketing of commodities and services with industrial commodities\n- Pricing of services with industrial commodities\n- International pricing of industrial commodities considering the Internet as a new distribution channel\n- The Internet as a new distribution channel for industrial commodities in classical multi-channel companies / Utilization of the Internet for integrating sales partners in the classical multi-stage sales system. \n- Cooperation with companies from foreign industrial segments (i.e. industrial insurance companies) for marketing preventive maintenance services for large-size bearings (paper mills, steel mills, etc.)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1494, 'E2-1494AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2002, October 25) ', 'National Center for Transportation Studies\nUniversity of the Philippines, Diliman 1101 Quezon City\nTelephone Nos. : (632) 929-04-95, (632) 920-53-01 locals 5516, 5258, 5807\nFacsimile No. : (632) 929-5664 or 929-44-03\n\nPROF. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nDean, College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City \n\nDear Dean Atanacio : \n\nThe National Center for Transportation Studies (NCTS), a unit of the University of the Philippines, will be conducting the fifth offering of the \"Executives\' Forum on Urban Environment and Transport Development Management (EXETRAM V) from November 18 to December 13, 2002 under its Third Country Training Programme. This training course which will be attended by senior transportation officials from various government agencies in the Asia Pacific region is a project of the Government of the Philippines and the Japanese Government through the Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA).\n\nThe purpose of EXETRAM is to provide the participants from Asia-Pacific countries with an opportunity to improve their knowledge and techniques in the field of transportation development management. Participants of this course will be coming from Bangladesh, China, India, Indonesia, Laos, Nepal, Papua New Guinea, Sri Lanka, Vietnam and the Philippines. \n\nIn this regard, we would like to invite you to do the honor of introducing Chancellor Emerlinda R. Roman who is invited to deliver the main address during the opening ceremonies scheduled on November 18, 2002 (Monday), 6:00 o\'clock in the evening at the quadrangle of the National Center for Transportation Studies. \n\nPlease find herewith the draft copy of the ceremony programme and the General Information brochure of EXETRAM.\n\nThank you for your attention and we look forward to your favorable response. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\n\nRICARDO G. SIGUA\nDirector ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1495, 'E2-1495AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '1998 Outstanding Architect of the Year', 'A brief biography of Architect Philip H. Recto \n1998 Outstanding Architect of the Year\nawarded by the Professional Regulation Commission (PRC) \nRepublic of the Philippines during the Philippine Centennial Year Celebration\n\nArchitect Philip H. Recto was born in Manila on July 24, 1947. He obtained his Bachelor of Science degree in Architecture from the University of the Philippines where he was a College Scholar and ranked 2nd place in the graduating class of 1970. A diligent student, he was also the Vice-President of the College of Architecture & Fine Arts Student Council.\nArch. Recto\'s early professional training included an apprenticeship with the office of Felipe M. Mendoza & Associates where he accumulated a wealth of practrical experience, especially in detailed contract documentation; and then with the renowned firm of Leandro V. Locsin & Associates where he honed his design prowess while participating in significant projects such as the Cultural Center of the Philippines. \nIn 1971, just a month after passing the board examinations, Arch. Recto obtained his first major commission - an integrated textile knitting factory project in Singapore. Due to the varied technical nature of the project, Arch. Recto decided that a move to the island-state for the duration would be valuable as it would allow him to devote full-time to the project and also serve to expand his professional horizons in the global scene. Thus began a 5-year stay in Singapore where he gained invaluable experience in the design and supervision not only of industrial buildings but also modern high-rise office buildings, residential condominiums, schools and churches. \nAfter completion of the textile factory project and desiring to broaden his experience in other building types, Arch. Recto joined Ang Kheng Leng & Associates, one of the oldest and biggest architectural firms in Singapore with branch offices in Kuala Lumpur & Penang, as an executive architect. There he was entrusted with many prestigious projects, including the 50-storey International Plaza, the tallest building in Singapore at the time. At this high point in his professional career and equipped with considerable foreign experience and professional maturity, Arch. Recto decided to return to the Philippines and set up practice on his own turf. \nHaving returned to Manila at the end of 1975, Arch. Recto set up an architectural partnership with long-time classmate and good friend, David SyCip, Jr., early the following year. In 1978, he established his own professional practice where he went on to carve a niche in the design of functional, no-frill condominium buildings, school buildings and high-rise office buildings. \nSince the beginning, Arch. Recto has always believed in honesty, integrity and diligence as the foundation of service in gaining clients\' trust and confidence; and he has inculcated such values in his associates and staff. His unblemished record and high ethical conduct are hallmarks in the building industry today. \nA well-known personage, Recto served as President of the United Architects of the Philippines (UAP) Makati Chapter for two terms (1983 & 84); Chairman of the 11th Architects\' National Convention in 1985; and UAP National Vice-President in 1987. He was a member of the 1984 Inter-Professional Conference Committee which undertook detailed review of UAP Document 301 - General Conditions; and was the head of the committee that prepared UAP Document 700 - Standard Forms for Architectural Practice, both used extensively by practicing architects today. \nA prolific interest, Recto has designed numerous landmark structures ranging from first-class office towers to compact, high-rise residential buildings, among which are the PSBANK Tower in Makati; the Philippine National Oil Co. (PNOC) Bldg. in Fort Bonifacio; the 54-Storey One San Miguel Avenue in Ortigas Center; Sunette Tower, Primetown Century Tower and Century Citadel Inn, all in Makati; the State Investment Trust Bldg. in Ortigas; Gedisco Tower in Manila and the JG Summit Corporate Tower in Mandaluyong City. Other notable works include Manila Electric Co. (Meralco) Training Centre in Antipolo; SM City in Xiamen, China; Byron EDSA Hotel in Mandaluyong City; Faith Academy Campus Redevelopment in Cainta; Biblical Seminary of the Philippines in Valenzuela; Hope Christian High School in Manila; Grace Bible Church in Nagtahan; Steniel Manufacturing Plant in Cagayan de Oro City and the Toyota Showroom & Service Center in the Manila Bay reclaimed area. \nRectos\' outstanding achievement in the field of design was recognized when the rank of Fellow was bestowed upon him by his peers in 1986. This is the highest rank in the professional organization of architects. Later, he was invited to be a life member of the exclusive ASEAN Association for Planning & Housing representing the Philippines. He also received numerous awards for his meritorous services to the architectural profession. Dubbed \"Designer par excellence\" by Construction Magazine (March 1989), his name was acknowledged in VIP\'s in the Philippine Business (1988), Business & Professionals in the Philippines (1988-1989), ASEAN Who\'s Who and Who\'s Who of the World (1998).\nWhen Philippine Centennial Year was celebrated in 1998, Arch. Philip Recto received one of the highest recognitions for a Filipino architect - the prestigious \"Outstanding Architect of the Year\" award from His Excellency, President Fidel V. Ramos, and the Professional Regulation Commission (PRC), the government agency mandated to license and regulate the practice of Filipino professionals, including 14,000 architects. \nA well-respected professional, Arch. Recto is also generous in sharing his expertise with various government agencies. He was appointed by former President Corazon C. Aquino as a Trustee of the Philippine Technological Council in 1987. He sat as a member of the National Building Code Review Committee (Architecture Sub-committee) at the Department of Public Works and Highways, and acted as a Consultant to the Construction Industry Authority of the Philippines on the formulation of Uniform General Conditions for Private Construction Contracts. He is a founder and director of the Society of Philippine Accredited Consultants and served as Chairman of the Architecture Committee of the Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry. He is a sought-after resource speaker on topics concerning high-rise building design, the National Building Code and architectural practice. \nAside from professional organizations, Recto is actively involved in several religious, educational and civic organizations. He is the Chairman of the Board of Palawan Hope Christian School; a board member of Hope Christian High School, Manila; a deacon of United Evangelical Church of the Philippines and a Paul Harris Fellow of the Rotary Club of Manila. \nArch. Recto is married to Ester Chiong whom he met in the course of their respective businesses. Prior to their marriage in 1977, Ms. Chiong was a top business executive at a well-established property development company. Today, she is Philip Recto\'s supportive partner in managing the family\'s business affairs. Arch. & Mrs. Recto are both devout Christians who believe in the importance of incorporating Christian values and teachings into all aspects of daily life. They generously support a variety of Christian ministries. \n- By Mary B. Holland\nPS BANK TOWER\nThis architecturally-acclaimed 28-storey office building houses the head office of Philippine Savings Bank, one of the country\'s largest banks and a member of the Metrobank Group. Situated in a location which can be seen from almost all directions, the elegant building\'s multi-faceted design presents an interesting view and becomes a converging sculptural focal point from all angles. Crowning this impressive building is a space frame structure serving as the communication tower. Illuminated at night, it presents a spectacular sight which is visible for miles and makes it a familiar landmark in Makati City. \nONE SAN MIGUEL AVENUE\nLocated at the gateway to Ortigas Center, this 54-storey office building is one of the tallest buildings in the country. With its dramatic exterior in a unifying combination of glass, granite and aluminum, this imposing structure incorporates the country\'s first double-deck passenger elevator. Sky terraces grace the intermediate floors and the rooftop features a skylounge and roofdeck gardens. Two radio rooms occupying the topmost part of the building with powerful communication antennae complete the prestigious archiectural landmark. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1496, 'E2-1496AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, October 31)', 'Society for the Advancement of Technology Management inthe Philippines\n\nDean Edgardo G. Atanacio\nDean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines, Diliman\n1101 Quezon City\n\nDear Dean Atanacio, \n\nGREETINGS!\n\nWe are pleased to report to you the activities of our organization since the last General Membership Meeting in February 1999. \n\n1. ASEAN Automotive Project. We have submitted our final report on our year-long engagement with the Australian Pacific Economic Corporation Committee (AUSPECC) last August 2000. This project is a regional study of the ASEAN Automotive Industry with SATMP as project leader. The results of the study can be viewed through www. asean-auto.org, a web-site that SATMP developed and maintains. Limited copies of this report may be requested from the SATMP secretariat. \n2. NRE Contest. As part of our mandate to advocate environment - friendly technologies, the Philippine National Oil Company engaged our services to manage a nation-wide contest on New and Renewable Energy System. This almost year long engagement culminated with the awarding of prizes to the winners last May 2000. We are happy to report that the Department of Energy would extend commercial funding support to the three winners of the contest. The results are posted on our web site. SATMP produced a souvenir CD to document the contest. Copies of the CD may be requested from the SATMP secretariat. \n3. Analysis of Technical Options for Mitigating Environmental Emissions from the Urban Transport System in Selected Asian Countries. SATMP is part of six-Asian-megacity study on greenhouse gas mitigation being coordinated by the Asian Institute of Technology based in Bangkok. The project is ongoing and will be completed mid-2001. \n4. DAP Yearbook on Technology, Competitiveness and Economy. The Development Academy of the Philippines (DAP) has engaged SATMP\'s services to manage the development and publication of DAP\'s Yearbook which henceforth will be an annual activity. The project started this year and will run through 2001. \n5. Technology and Exports Competitiveness. The Philippine Exporters Confederation of the Philippines (PHILEXPORT) has engaged our services to undertake several studies on the above subject, viz. IPR, Innovation, Technology Management, etc. The results were published in a compendium by SATMP and PhilExport. Limited copies of this report may be requested from the SATMP secretariat. \nIn addition to the above, SATMP has also conducted local seminars/workshops as part of our advocacy agenda on technology management (see attached list of policy forum and conferences). \nWe look forward to be ablt o expand to other technology related activities in the coming years. But as before, the strength of the organization depends on your continuous support. \nEnclosed are membership renewal form and statement of membership dues for your updating. Thank you and best wishes.\n\nSincerely, \n\nMAGDALENO B. ALBARRACIN, JR. D.B.A.\nPresident ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1497, 'E2-1497AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'FAG Innovation Award 2002', 'FAG Kugelfischer Foundation\n\nThe FAG Kugelfischer Foundation announces the INNOVATION AWARD 2002 valued at a total 25,000 euro. It rewards outstanding treatises in the subjects areas of product innovation, enhanced manufacturing and market strategy', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1498, 'E2-1498AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1999, August 2)', 'Engr. Edgardo Atanacio\nDean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Engr. Atanacio :\n\nFurther to your meeting with Dr. Pura Flor D. Isleta regarding a possible assistance as consultants in maintaining NICU and PICU equipment, you are invited to attend a brain-storming meeting with the PGH-OETS Engineer, the Chair of the Department of Pediatrics, the NICU/PICU heads, and the representatives of ARCI. ARCI is the non-government organization which is upgrading the PGH NICU & PICU. The meetings are scheduled on August 9 at 2:00 p.m. and August 12 at 8:30 p.m. at the Philippine General Hospital\'s 2nd Floor Director\'s Conference Hall. \n\nThank you for your kind acceptance of this invitation. \n\nVery truly yours,\n\nCARMELO A. ALFILER, MD\nChair\n\nNoted :\n\nPERLA D. SANTOS OCAMPO, MD\nChancellor', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1499, 'E2-1499AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, February 22) ', 'Dean Edgardo G. Atanacio\nMelchor Hall\nCollege of Engineering\nDiliman, Quezon City\nPhilippines\n\nDear Dean Atanacio :\n\nPlease be informed that monies are now available for the DOMINADOR I. ILIO MERITOROUS SERVICE AWARD In ENGINEERING. \nFor the funds to be released, a written request has to be made through : \nDr. Antonio S. Racela \nExecutive Director\nFriends of UP Foundation in America\n912 Burning Tree Drive\nKansas City, MO 64145\n\nPhone : (816) 942-7533\nFax : (816) 942-8393\nemail : friends@kctera.net\n\nFor records purposes, please indicate in your letter if an awardee has already been chosen and the criteria used for the selection. Also, will the awardee receive the award only for year 2000, or is it renewable for the same awardee and for how long?\n\nIf you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact Dr. Racela or myself. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nMacArthur Delos Reyes/\nJosefina Parras Delos Reyes\n1300 Rustric Trail\nParma, Ohio 44134-4860\n(440) 845-75001', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1500, 'E2-1500AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1999, June 4) ', 'Professor Edgardo S. Atanacio\nDean\nCollege of Engineering\nU.P. Diliman\n\nDear Dean Atanacio : \n\nThe Administrative Personnel and Fellowships Committee (APFC) during its meeting held on 27 May 1999 deliberated on your recommendation for the change of status from temporary to permanent of Mr. Jose Marie Lim as University Research Associate II, Salary Grade 14 : \n\nThe Committee recommends that Mr. Lim be promoted to University Researcher I, Salary Grade 16 in view of his having acquired the M.S. in Chemical Engineering as soon as you can identify a vacant item for him. Meanwhile, the Committee endorsed your recommendation for a change of status from temporary to permanent as University Research Associate II. \n\nMay we request your advice/comments soonest so we can act on your recommendation accordingly. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nPERLA E. LEGASPI\nVice-Chancellor for Administration and Chairman, APFC ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1501, 'E2-1501AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Dear Sir :\n\nGreetings!\n\nThe U.P. College of Engineering is known for consistently producing a successful crop of graduates every year. This coming April, the Engineering graduates of 2001 will proudly enter the next phase of their lives along with the responsibility of carrying on the college\'s tradition of excellence. As in the past years, the Engineering Student Council will be producing a yearbook to serve as a reminder of their stay in the University of the Philippines. \n\nWe would then like to ask you to write a message for this year\'s yearbook, Inhinyero 2001, to serve as inspiration and encouragement to the new graduates. Your wisdom and invaluable advice will truly be appreciated by the students who have looked up to you during their stay in the university.\n\nWe would like to thank you in advance for being part of our college lives. May God bless you. \n\nYours truly,\n\nJenm Gamboa\nHead, Write-up Committee\nInhinyero 2001', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1502, 'E2-1502AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, April 16) ', 'Dean Edgardo G. Atanacio\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dean Atanacio :\n\nThe National College of Public Administration and Governance, University of the Philippines, (NCPAG-U.P.), together with the Institute for Aerospace Survey and Earth Sciences (ITC) in the Netherlands, is instituting a new area of specialization, Spatial Information Management, in the Master of Public Administration degree Program. This program will be implemented with the support of the U.P. College of Engineering (Department of Geodetic Engineering), the College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (Department of Geography), the School of Urban and Regional Planning (SURP), and the National Center for Transport Studies (NCTS). This new specialization aims to develop a corps of decision makers, administrators, and technical personnel knowledgeable in the theory and practice of Public Administration and Governance, and in the application of information and communications technology (ICT), specifically, Geographic Information Systems (GIS) to their work as public servants. The GIS technology will provide the government and society with an effective platform for addressing public administration concerns in hazard and disaster management, fiscal administration, land administration, public service delivery, election administration, national security, environmental security, and public information management, among many other applications.\n\nThe new course program has secured the approval of the Scientific Council of the ITC. Meanwhile the proposal is now undergoing the curricular approval process in the University and we hope to start in the second semester of Academic Year, 2001-2002. The MPA-SIM Program initially targets to accept a maximum of twenty students. The SIM specialization requires students to complete a total of thirty-nine (39) units within a two-year period. Students who have successfully defended their thesis proposals would be given an opportunity to stay for a maximum of three months at the ITC in the Netherlands where they will write and defend their theses. \n\nIn this connection, may we invite you to a roundtable discussion on the MPA-SIM program on April 25, 2001 (Wednesday), 9:00 AM, at the Dean\'s Conference Room, National College of Public Administration and Governance, University of the Philippines. This roundtable discussion will hopefully provide a basis for determining the needs of government in terms of spatial information management so that a more responsive MPA-SIM Course can be provided by the NCPAG.\n\nWe hope that you will help us bring the curriculum closer to your particular need as an institution. We are intent on making the program strategy appropriate for developing the capacity of your staff to better meet challenges of our increasingly technological world. \n\nTruly yours,\n\nLEDIVINA V. CARINO\nDean', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1503, 'E2-1503AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 25)', 'Prof. Edgardo Atanacio\nDean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City 1101\n\nDear Sir : \n\nAttached herewith is a copy of the proposal of DLRC to establish a Computer Classroom and Review Center at the College of Engineering. As mentioned in the proposal we will need a 4 bay classroom or two regular size rooms. The creation of the center will greatly benefit engineering students as this geared towards the improvement of the services offered by DLRC1. \n\nWe are hoping for your favorable response to our request. \n\nSincerely yours,\n\nJaime Y. Hernandez Jr. \nDLRC Faculty Coordinator ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1504, 'E2-1504AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Proposal for the establishment of a DLRC Computer Classroom and Review Center at the College of Engineering, University of the Philippines Diliman Campus\n\nProject Description\n\nGoal : To establish a self-sustaining, non-profit computer classroom and review center at the College of Engineering in U.P. Diliman.\n\nObjective : \n1. To give underprivileged students opportunities to utilize the benefits of technology.\n2. Tutor students on computer basics, as well as in their academic subjects free of charge.\n\nMethods : \nHow : The center will offer several services such as low-cost computer rental on word processing, computer software, internet, and printing. Free tutorials from our student volunteers, will help students with computer and internet literacy. We will also offer free tutorials from our volunteer faculty members in various academic subjects. \n\nWhen : With the approval of the Dean of the College of Engineering and U.P. Administration, and the availability of startup funds, we hope to open the center on the second semester of school year 2001-2002.\n\nWhere : The center will be established at the College of Engineering. \n\nOur Staffing and Administration\n\nDLRC Core Group :\n\nDLRC Director : \nDr. Lydia R. Arcellana\n\nDLRC Faculty Coordinator : \nProf. Jaime Hernandez Jr. \n\nGuidance Counselors : \nClaribel Amihan\nRosalinda de Mesa\n\nU.P. Faculty Volunteers :\nRonald John Galiza\nKristine Joy Carpio\nGiovanni Tapang\nKhrisna Alcantara\n\nStaff : \nMary Jane V. Cenas\n\nStudent Assistants :\nRich de Guzman\nMelinda Mejia\nSarah Jane Mandaing\nMarizelle Ramos\n\nVolunteer Student Leaders : \nBoni Lou Arensoi\nFrederick Ryan Domingo\n\nEvaluation Procedures\nWe have plans to implement the following evaluation procedure : \n1. The DLRC Core Group will meet quarterly to review the following :\nA. Financial records, time sheets, expenses, and pricing models to determine if we are charging the least amount for our services to students. \nB. Random surveys administered to students to determine the effectiveness of our tutoring program.\n2. If required by the U.P. administration or major donor, an independent audit will be conducted and the results made available to any concerned party. \n\nCommunication\n\nWe will make available a semi-annual report detailing our progress, as well as an annual report from the DLRC director. \n\nOrganizational Information\nThe Diliman Learning Resource Center (DLRC) is directly under the Office of the Vice-Chancellor for Student Affairs (OVCSA). The DLRC exists with the following purpose and objectives : \nPurpose Statement :\nTo promote academic excellence among UP students (particularly freshmen and sophomore students) in a caring and nurturing environment.\n\nObjectives :\n- To promote academic excellence by training students to analyze problems, ask right questions, arrive at solutions and become self-reliant\n- Encourage students to identify and maximize their potential and thus help them find their niche in society.\n- To provide opportunities for the students to discern their values and evaluate these in terms of their benefit to self and society.\n\nDLRC maintains two centers : DLRC1 is situated at the 3rd floor of the National Engineering Center (NEC) building and DLRC2 is at the back of the Kamia Residence Hall. At present, DLRC1 occupies a two bay classroom which is normally used for peer tutorials and as study center for students. The present demands of U.P. education, especially engineering students, require much use of computers and computer applications. This proposal is given in order to enhance the service provided in DLRC1 to U.P. students. \n\nOur Needs, Your Opportunity\nStartup funding inthe amount of 2,000,000.00 pesos. This amount will cover the expenses for 30 computers, tables and chairs, 2 printers, internet equipment, multimedia projector, a copying machine, air-conditioning equipment, computer software and the renovation of a 4 bay classroom (2 bays for the computer classroom & 2 bays for the review center). The breakdown is given in the supplemental information as part of this proposal.\n\nThank you again for your consideration of this proposal. Should you need more information. please do not hesitate to contact us. \n\nOur address : \nDiliman Learning Resource Center\nKamia Residence Hall\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City 1101\nTel. No. 920-5301 loc. 6665', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1505, 'E2-1505AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, February 5) ', 'DR. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nDean, College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dean Atanacio : \n\nThe College of Mass Communication in cooperation with the U.P. Diliman Office of Initiative for Culture and the Arts is pleased to announce the 3rd U.P. DILIMAN FILM AND VIDEO FESTIVAL this February. The festival is a competition that aims to promote independent film and video production among students from various schools, colleges and universities in the country. Students may submit entries in four categories, namely, NARRATIVE, ANIMATION, EXPERIMENTAL, and DOCUMENTARY. A trophy and cash prize awaits the winner : 1st Prize is P5,000; 2nd Prize is P3,000 and 3rd Prize is P2,000.\nIn this connection, we would like to solicit your help in encouraging your students to join this festival. Entries may be in 16mm film or VHS Video formats not exceeding 45 minutes in running time and must have been produced not earlier than February 1, 2000. The deadline for submission of entries is on February 19, 2001 at 5:30 pm at the Film and AVC Department of the UP College of Mass Communication. For further details please call PLDT # 920-6863 or UP Trunkline 920-5301 up to 99 local 4639 and look for Fortune. \nEnclosed are the poster, contest rules, and entry forms. The entry forms may be photocopied should you run out of it. \nThank you very much.\n\nVery truly yours, \n\nDR. GIGI JAVIER ALFONSO\nChair, Organizing Committee\n3rd UP Diliman Film and Video Festival', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1506, 'E2-1506AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The 3rd UP Diliman Film and Video Festival Competition Mechanics\n1. Entries must be student works completed not earlier than February 1, 2000.\n2. Entries must have been completed while the filmmaker/video director was enrolled as a student in their respective schools and universities.\n3. Entries should be in the following formats : \nFILM : 16mm\nVIDEO : VHS\n4. Running time for all entries must not exceed 45 minutes. \n5. All works must strictly be independent works and not produced for commercial screening or commercial circulation. \n6. Each participant is allowed to submit only one (1) entry in each category.\n7. Each entry can only be submitted in one (1) category.\n8. Each entry reel or tape must contain only one (1) title. \n9. Categories are the following :\nNarrative (Short Feature)\nExperimental\nAnimation\nDocumentary\n10. Entries must include the following :\na. Duly accomplished entry form (original or a facsimile/xerox). Include the following information :\nTitle of film/video work\nDate Production Started\nDate Production Completed\nName of school and College or department of origin\nProducer (s)\nScroptwriter (s)\nEditor (s)\nProduction Designer (s)\nOther production staff\nCompetition Category\nFilm or Video\nFilm or Video Format (see #9)\nSound Format (Magnetic, Optical or silent in case of Film entry)\nRunning Time or duration of film/video work (in case of Film entry please include number of film reels) \nShort synopsis of film/video work\nComplete address of filmmaker or group rep\nConforme (signed by person submitting)\nConforme (signed by owner of film/video rights) \nb. Synopsis of entry\nc. One (1) 5x7 inches (5R) or 3x5 inches (3R) production stills of the entry. \n11. Awards for the winning entries shall be given to the filmmaker/video director indicated in the entry form. For joint directorial works, the group must assign a single representative to act on its behalf. All official communications shall be addressed to this representative. The Organizers shall not be liable for any controversy regarding the sharing of awards among the members of the group. \n12. The decision of the Board of Judges is final. The Board of Judges reserves the right not to give awards in any category should no entry merit it. In the case of ambivalence, the jurors shall decide the category of the entry. \n13. Cash prizes for the categories NARRATIVE, EXPERIMENTAL, ANIMATION and DOCUMENTARY are as follows :\n1st Prize : P5,000.00 plus trophy\n2nd Prize : 3,000.00 plus trophy\n3rd Prize : 2,000.00 plus trophy\n14. Entries must be submitted not later than 5:30 PM FEBRUARY 19, 2001 at the Film and AVC Department of the College of Mass Communication.\n15. Winners shall be notified by mail or telephone. All winners are enjoined to be at the awards ceremonies ON February 28, 2001 at 2PM at the UP-CMC Auditorium.\n16. The UP-OICA and UP-CMC reserves the right to exhibit the entries, winning or not, during the festival week. The UP-OICA and UP-CMC also reserves the right not to screen entries it deems unsuitable for public screening. \n17. Winning entries shall be archived and filed by the UP-CMC Film and AVC Department in its collection/library.\n18. Entries may be picked up starting March 30, 2001. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1507, 'E2-1507AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 22) ', 'University of the Philippines Diliman\nQuezon City\nEXECUTIVE COMMITTEE OF THE UNIVERSITY COUNCIL\n\nFOR : Members\nExecutive Committee\n\nFROM : LUDENDORFFO T. DECENTECEO\nMember-Secretary\n\nThe Executive Committee of the University Council, UP Diliman will meet on Wednesday, 7 February 2001 at 1:30 p.m., at the Conference Room of the Office of the University Registrar to take up matters which were originally scheduled for the January 17, 2001 meeting. \n\nThank you very much. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1508, 'E2-1508AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 24) ', 'Prof. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nDean\n\nSubject : Engineering Canteen\n\nDear Dean :\n\nAttached please find the final version of the Proposed Canteen Layout for your approval. The concessionaire submitted the layout yesterday. It included the suggestions of the College Food Service Committee members and the Office of Campus Architect (OCA) in a meeting held with the concessionaire on 9 January 2001. Through a verbal request to OCA Officer-in-Charge, Mr. Cesar Bravo, OCA is now evaluating the technical specifications.\n\nIn the same meeting, the concessionaire was requested by the committee to start operation temporarily to service the canteen needs of the college without rental from 12-20 January 2001. It was agreed that utilities and other risks during the temporary operations is the responsibilities of the concessionaire. The PBAC agreed on the request in a PBAC meeting held on 9 January 2001. \n\nCanteen 3 started operations on 22 January 2001 except for the air-conditioning. The specification is still being prepared. \n\nThank you and Mabuhay po kayo!\n\nVery truly yours, \n\nFERDINAND G. MANEGDEG\nChair\nCollege Food Service Committee ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1509, 'E2-1509AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 16) ', 'PROF. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nDean, College of Engineering\nUNIVERSITY OF THE PHILIPPINES\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Prof. Atanacio,\n\nI am pleased to inform that the Philippine Nuclear Research Institute is currently receiving the mission of Dr. Takeo Onchi, a Technical Consultant of the Nuclear Safety Research Association of Japan, under a technical exchange program with the Japanese Government from 4 January to 24 February 2001. He will advise the PNRI on Nuclear Safety. Dr. Onchi is an expert in material research technology and has several papers on the degradation and corrosion of materials subjected to heat especially those used in power and research reactors operations. \nIn connection with his mission, Dr. Onchi would like to visit laboratories doing materials analysis and testing in the country. In this regard, may we request that Dr. Onchi be allowed to visit your laboratory in the afternoon of 25 January 2001. \nOur Mr. Alejandro J. Mateo, Head of Inspection and Enforcement, Nuclear Regulations, Licensing and Safeguards Division, will provide any further information you may need regarding the visit.\n\nThank you very much for the kind attention you would give the matter, \n\nWith best regards,\n\nVery truly yours,\n\nALUMANDA M. DELA ROSA, Ph.D.\nActing Director', 'Philippine Nuclear Research Institute (PNRI)', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1510, 'E2-1510AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 10)', 'Prof. Edgardo G. Atanacio\nDean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines Diliman\n\nDear Dean Atanacio :\n\nThe U.P. is a participating university in a lecture series with the theme \"Filipino Spiritual Culture and Globalization\" sponsored by the Carmelite Sisters of St. Therese in Quezon City. \nOn Wednesday, January 17, 2001, 10:00 a.m., at the Lyceum of the Philippines Father Eliseo Mercado, OMI President of Notre Dame University in Cotabato City will deliver a public lecture on \"Social Cultural Cleavages and the Peace Process in Southern Philippines.\"\nWe are inviting you and your faculty to this lecture by an important figure in the peace process in Mindanao.\nPlease get in touch with my office (929-1288) if you need transportation to go to Lyceum.\nHappy New Year!\n\nYours truly, \n\nJOSE N. ENDRIGA\nVice President for Public Affairs  ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1511, 'E2-1511AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 12) ', 'Prof. Anastacio Atanacio\nDean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\n\nDear Dr. Dayrit,\n\nGreetings!\n\nIn behalf of our client EMC Philippines, we would like to propose an initiative to conduct a free seminar discussing The BASICS OF STORAGE to selected 3rd and 4th year Computer Engineering students. Schedule of seminar will depend on the availability of the students for the month of January 2001. \nStorage is now a critical component in the Information Technology infrastructure. This seminar will be most beneficial to your students since this will serve as a valuable primer as they take that big step towards the professional world of IT. \nEMC Corporation, based in Hopkinton, Massachusetts, is the world\'s leading provider of enterprise storage systems, software and services. EMC is the recognized time-to-market leader in delivering advanced storage and retrieval and information management and protection technologies to companies whose success depends on information. \nPlease expect a call from our office to follow-up on this matter. Should you wish to reply sooner, you may call us at 890-3766/897-7088 or you can also e-mail us at dominguez@pacific.net.ph\nThank you and we are hoping for your favorable response. \n\nSincerely, \n\nMARIE PAGADUAN\nAccount Executive ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1512, 'E2-1512AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 3) ', 'Dr. Edgardo Atanacio\nDean\nCollege of Engineering\nU.P. Diliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dr. Atanacio : \n\nAs a follow up to the agenda item on affiliate faculty which we discussed in our 05 December 2000 meeting, may we have a list of your faculty who may be invited to join the CIS as affiliates?\nAs you will recall we agreed that a faculty affiliate should have an MA degree, done or is interested to do multidisciplinal research, and can at least read the language of the country of his/her research.\nWe hope to come up with a potential list to be presented at our meeting in March.\n\nSincerely yours, \n\nConsuelo J. Paz, Ph.D.\nOfficer-in-Charge ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1513, 'E2-1513AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 4) ', 'Dean Edgardo Atanacio\nCollege of Engineering \nU.P. Diliman\n\nDear Dean Atanacio : \nThe Academic Personnel and Fellowships Committee (APFC) during its meeting held on December 7, 2000 deliberated on your recommendation for the original appointment of Mr. JOSE DON DE ALBAN as Lecturer 1, effective November 13, 2000 until May 31, 2001. \nThe Committee took note of his failing marks. Nonetheless, we have decided to endorse his appointment because classes have already started, but for the 2nd semester 2000-2001 only. We would like to suggest that you monitor his performance as a faculty during this period. Renewal of his appointment shall be subject to evaluation of his teaching performance. \n\nTruly yours, \n\nAMELIA P. GUEVARA\nChairperson, APFC', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1514, 'E2-1514AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 4) ', 'Dean Edgardo Atanacio\nCollege of Engineering \nU.P. Diliman\n\nDear Dean Atanacio : \nThe Academic Personnel and Fellowships Committee (APFC) during its meeting held on December 7, 2000 deliberated on your recommendation for the original appointment of Mr. JOSE MARIO DIAZ as Instructor 2, effective November 13, 2000 until May 31, 2001. \nThe Committee took note of his failing mark in ES 12 which the Committee considers very much related to the engineering sciences curriculum. Nonetheless, we have decided to endorse his appointment because classes have already started, but for this 2nd semester 2000-2001 only. We would like to suggest that you monitor his performance as a faculty during this period. Renewal of his appointment shall be subject to evaluation of his teaching performance. Thank you.\n\nTruly yours, \n\nAMELIA P. GUEVARA\nChairperson, APFC', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1515, 'E2-1515AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2001, January 4) ', 'Dean Edgardo Atanacio\nCollege of Engineering \nU.P. Diliman\n\nDear Dean Atanacio : \nThe Academic Personnel and Fellowships Committee (APFC) during its meeting held on December 7, 2000 deliberated on your recommendation for the original appointment of Mr. ERICKSON MIRANDA as Instructor 1, effective November 13, 2000 until May 31, 2001. \nThe Committee took note of his failing mark in CS 160 which the Committee considers very much related to the computer science curriculum. Nonetheless, we have decided to endorse his appointment because classes have already started, but for this 2nd semester 2000-2001 only. We would like to suggest that you monitor his performance as a faculty during this period. Renewal of his appointment shall be subject to evaluation of his teaching performance. Thank you.\n\nTruly yours, \n\nAMELIA P. GUEVARA\nChairperson, APFC', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1516, 'E2-1516AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'TO : Prof. Edgardo Atanacio\nDean\n\nFROM : Michelle B. Napolis\nSocial Affairs and Special Projects Committee\n\nRE : Christmas Contributions\n\nI am pleased to inform you that the contributions from the faculty for the gifts to be given to the Administrative Personnel has amounted to P28,000.00. Attached is the breakdown of the said contributions from each department.\n\nThe acquired amount will be used to purchase 80 pcs. of Purefoods Fiesta Ham approximately 1 kilo each and will be distributed on Thursday December 21, 2000. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1517, 'E2-1517AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, December 15) ', 'PROF. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nDean, U.P. College of Engineering\n\nDear Dean Atanacio, \n\nI would like to endorse for approval the request of our Mining Engineering faculty for amendment in the implementation plan of the CHED Center of Development Grant of ONE MILLION PESOS for Mining Engineering in a letter dated December 13, 2000. After getting quotations of the equipment listed in the Annual Plan (see attached Plan - Revision no. 4 dated April 13, 2000) under capital outlay for the first year of implementation, a realignment is deemed necessary considering that the cost of certain items have been underestimated, and some are even no longer affordable because of the current dollar to peso exchange rate. \n\nThe proposed amendments are attached to this letter (see also proposed Plan Revision No. 5 dated December 15, 2000). Also attached is a quotation of the cost of the items to be purchased under the proposed revised plan. If this amendment merits your approval, we seek permission to have the RIVs of these equipment prepared immediately. \n\nThank you very much. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nALBERTO V. AMORSOLO, JR. Ph.D.\nChairman, MMME Department ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1518, 'E2-1518AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, December 15) ', 'PROF. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nDean, U.P. College of Engineering\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dean Atanacio,\n\nWe would like to inform you about the sentiment of the faculty members of the MMME Department in connection with the request of the U.P. Engineering Society to put up a tambayan along the corridor wall which is between the IE Department and the MMME Department. \n\nIn a consultation with the Department faculty members during our last regualr meeting dated December 13, 2000, they unanimously voted against putting up a tambayan by any organization in that area. One of the main reasons cited is the anticipated increase in the noise level reaching our Department which they believe will deleteriously affect the efficient performance of their jobs such as course preparation work considering that our Department is not sound-proof. They also point out that tambayans along the corridor make the area congested and narrows the space intended for people to walk through, especially during the times that a lot of students congregate there. A safety issue was also cited by Dr. Mena. \n\nWe understand the dilemma of the U.P. Engineering Society, however, in view of the reasons cited, we are not in favor of their choice of location for their new tambayan. We therefore propose that a more appropriate area be located for their transfer. To quote one of my staff, lobbies and corners are okay for the purpose but not corridors. \n\nThank you very much.\n\nVery truly yours, \n\nALBERTO V. AMORSOLO, JR., Ph.D.\nChairman, MMME Department ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
