(1519, 'E2-1519AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, December 20) ', 'Prof. Edgardo G. Atanacio, Dean\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dean Atanacio : \n\nThis is in connection with the Philippine Engineering Journal (PEJ), which is a published by the U.P. Engineering Research and Development Foundation, Inc. (UPERDFI) for the National Engineering Center. I recently was informed that the UPERDFI reduced the amount of it direct assistance for the publication of the PEJ from P120,000.00 to P60,000.00 effective 1999. Unfortunately, this amount of financial assistance is not sufficient to enable to the PEJ to come out with two issues per year. While in the last year there has been in delay in the release of the PEJ, this has mainly been due to the slow rate at which the PEJ receives articles, which I mentioned on a number of occasions to the College Executive Board. We have been able to solve this problem by more aggressively seeking out potential contributors of articles while still maintaining the quality the articles included in the PEJ. I also foresee that this will not be a problem in the near future, given the new university guidelines on faculty promotions that have publication requirements. In addition, we have also undertaken steps to streamlining the typesetting and proof reading process such that a given issue of the PEJ can be made ready for distribution within a month after all articles have been received. \n\nBecause of the abovementioned efforts, we have been able address the delay in the release of issues of the PEJ. We recently released the December 1999 that was charged versus the UPERDFI\'s direct assistance for 2000. The June 2000 issue is already at the printers, with the December 2000 issue to follow shortly. However, the balance of 2000 direct assistance provided by the UPERDFI is not sufficient to cover the publication cost of these two issues since each issue costs approximately P40,000.00 to publish. The foundation has advised us to charge these issues versus our 2001 allocation, which will be in sufficient to publish the two issues. At this point, we anticipate that we will be able to release both the June and December 2001 on schedule as we already have articles for these two issues. \n\nFor this reason, I would like to ask your assistance in requesting the foundation for additional financial assistance in the amount of P100,000.00 to cover the costs publication of the next four issues of the PEJ (June and December 2000, and June and December 2001). This amount is over and above the P60,000.00 in direct assistance the UPERDFI has already allotted for the PEJ.\n\nMay I also request from the UPERDFI, through your representation, that the level of direct assistance be restored to P120,000.00 per annum, in enable the PEJ to release two issues of the journal per year. \n\nHoping for your favorable response to this request. \n\nSincerely, \n\nDr. Mark H. Zarco,\nFaculty-in-charge, PEIS', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1520, 'E2-1520AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, December 13) ', 'Dr. Edgardo G. Atanacio \nExecutive Director\nNational Engineering Center\nU.P. Diliman\nQuezon City \n\nDear Director Atanacio :\n\nPlease be informed that the search for U.P. Alumni Awardees for the year 2001 is now open. We would like to enlist your support by submitting qualified nominees for the various categories of awards. \n\nThe categories are : \"Most Distinguished Alumnus and/or Alumna Award (s)\", \"Outstanding Professionals Awards\", \"Community Service Awards\", \"Lifetime Distinguished Achievement Award\", UPAA Service Awards\", and the \"Outstanding Alumni Chapter Award\", \"UPAA Service Awards\", and the \"Outstanding Alumni Chapter Award\" (one each for locally-based and foreign based UPAA Chapters). \n\nThe deadline for the submission of nominations is MARCH 15, 2001. Mailed entries must be postmarked not later than MARCH 15, 2001. Only properly accomplished nominations will be accepted by the UPAA Search Committee. Nominations sent through fax or e-mail will not be entertained. For details, please see attached papers. \n\nNominations may be made by any individual or organization. Members of the UPAA Board, UPAA Search Committee and UPAA Committee on Alumni Awards are not qualified to nominate or be nominated for the awards. \n\nEnclosed are copies of the criteria and nomination form which may be replicated.\n\nThank you for your continuing support.\n\nVery truly yours, \n\nGARI M. TIONGCO\nChairman\nUPAA Search Committee for U.P. Alumni Awards ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1521, 'E2-1521AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, December 12) ', 'For : Prof. Edgardo G. Atanacio\nDean\nCollege of Engineering\nUP Diliman \n\nDear Dean Atanacio:\n\nGreetings!\n\nThe Civil Engineering Department has submitted its recommendation of at least a one step promotion for all its members. We would like to respectfully point out that the additional documentation of promotion justification which was requested by your good office last December 7, 2000 and which have duly submitted actually indicates that the requested promotion for the undersigned is for more than one step. These recommendations are made on the strength of the justifications provided. Thus we, the undersigned hope for your appropriate action on this matter. \n\nThank you for your kind attention. \n\nRespectfully yours, \n\nCrispin E. D. Diaz\nAsst. Prof.\nCivil Engineering Dept. \n\nNathaniel B. Diola\nAsst. Prof. \nCivil Engineering Dept. \n\nRicardo G. Sigua\nAssoc. Prof. \nCivil Engineering Dept. \n\nNoted : \n\nVictor A. Pulmano\nChairman\nCivil Engineering Dept. \n\nEric C. Cruz / Alfredo B. Junio / Alan T. Tan\nAcademic Personnel Committee\nCivil Engineering Dept. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1522, 'E2-1522AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, December 12) ', 'Dr. Emerlinda R. Roman\nChancellor\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dr. Roman :\n\nWarm greetings!\n\nIn reply to your communication with REF No. ERR - 00-632, we are pleased inform you that the Commission has acted favorably on your recommendation of Dean Edgardo Atanacio as member of the AUN/SEED Net Steering Committee.\n\nEnclosed is the official letter of nomination.\n\nVery truly yours, \n\nESTER A. GARCIA\nChairman  ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1523, 'E2-1523AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, December 12) ', 'Prof. Dr. Panitan Lukkunaprasit\nAUN/SEED Net Executive Director\nDepartment of Engineering\nFaculty of Engineering\nChulalongkorn University\nBangkok 10330, Thailand\nFAX : (662) 251-7304\n\nDear Prof. Dr. Panitan :\n\nGreetings from the Commission on Higher Education!\n\nCongratulations to your appointment as AUN-SEED Net Secretariat\'s Executive Director. \nWith reference to your communication number 362/2000, we are pleased to note the success of the preparatory meeting relative to the AUN-SEED Net Project and the information about the Net\'s secretariat to be located at the Faculty of Engineering, Chulalongkorn University.\n\nAs agree upon and requested by the convenors, the Commission nominates Dean Edgardo Atanacio of the College of Engineering, University of the Philippines as member of the AUN/SEED Net Steering Committee.\n\nBest regards\n\nVery truly yours, \n\nESTER A. GARCIA\nChairman ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1524, 'E2-1524AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, November 27) ', 'OFFICE OF THE CHANCELLOR\n\nMEMORANDUM NO. ERR-00-186 \n\nFOR : Dean Rosario Torres-Yu, Arts and Letters\nDean Christopher Espina, Architecture\nDean Armando Malay, Jr., Asian Center\nDean Elvira Zamora, Business Administration\nDean Raul Fabella, Economics\nDean Edgardo Atanacio, Engineering\nDean Raul Pangalangan, Law\nDean Maragtas Amante, Labor and Industrial Relations\nDean Rhodora Azanza, Science\nDean Elizabeth Ventura, Social Sciences and Philosophy\nDr. Consuelo Joaquin-Paz\n\nSUBJECT : Center for International Studies Coordinating Council Meeting\n\nWe are pleased to inform you that the Board of Regents, in its 1146th meeting held on October 20, 2000, approved the establishment of the UP Diliman Center for International Studies. Attached for your information is the official notice from the Secretary of the Board of Regents. \nProviding overall policy direction to the Center is the Coordinating Council which shall be composed of deans of units closely affiliated with the concerns of the Center. Your unit has been identified to be part of the Coordinating Council. It is in this connection that I am inviting you to the first meeting of the Council which will be held on Tuesday, December 5, 2000 at 9:00 o\' clock am at the Chancellor\'s Conference Room.\n\nThank you. \n\nEMERLINDA R. ROMAN ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1525, 'E2-1525AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, October 20) Excerpt from the Minutes of the 1146th Meeting of the Board of Regents held on 20', 'UNIVERSITY OF THE PHILIPPINES\nQuezon City\n\nExcerpt from the Minutes of the 1146th Meeting of the Board of Regents held on 20 October 2000\n\nVI. POLICY MATTERS FOR APPROVAL OF THE BOARD  \n\nF. Proposal to Establish the U.P. Diliman Center for International Studies\n\nOverview\n\nThis report proposes the creation of a Center for International Studies in U.P. Diliman that will bring together existing area and international studie at the Asian Center (AC), College of Arts and Letters (CAL), College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP), and other units with related offerings. The goal of the Center is to promote reserach on the cultures and the interrelatedness of the social and economic systems of countries in Asia, America, and Europe. In the future, depending on the need and faculty resources, the Center may offer degree programs at the undergraduate and graduate levels. \n\nRationale\n\nAn international studies program is important for its cotribution to the wealth of knowledge and to the development of well-rounded, cosmopolitan citizens. Area studies imply intimate knowledge of a given country\'s or region\'s cultural foundations arising from basic research in the history and culture, social movements, civil society, foreign relations, and migration patterns of the world\'s major civilizations. \n\nMoreover, area studies help advance national development goals. The conduct of Philippine foreign policy, for instance, benefits a great deal from the availability of a large pool of university-based specialists who can provide expert analysis in various areas of concern (e.g., culture, politics, economics, science and technology) about individual countries or a regional grouping of countries.\n\nThe Philippines is increasingly being integrated with the rest of the world not only economically but also socially, politically and culturally. Such integration, however, is not always smooth and to enable this ongoing transformation to serve development goals. It is important to have a good understanding of the determinants, processes, and consequences of rapid globalization. To do this, teaching and research in international studies, whether basic or policy oriented, undertaken by a core of country and subject specialists, are indispensable.\n\nU.P. Diliman is well placed to provide the required teaching and research, not necessarily by creating new programs, but by integrating and strengthening existing area and international studies programs in the Diliman campus. These programs have had a long history. At present, however, they are scattered in various units and departments, resulting in high overhead costs and low synergy. A little introspection will show that n amalgamation can lead to scale economies in the use of faculty time and financial resources and to more focused academic programs.\n\nAs globalization proceeds, economic and technical cooperation between developed and developing countries, anchored on human capital buildup and technology transfers, gathers strength. In this regard, the developed countries have seen it fit to assist the developing ones in capacity enhancement through support education, training and research. U.P. Diliman will be in a strong position to attract some funds for the purpose, which are in the form of official development assistance and grants from private foundations, if it has in place a world-class international studies program. \n\nAim/Vision\n\nThe Center for International Studies shall be a leading source of knowledge of the countries of the world, to enable the Filipino to gain this knowledge and meaningfully relate to the outside world. \n\nObjectives\n\n1. To conduct multi/interdisciplinary cross-cultural research. \n2. To become a resource center for information on different countries. \n3. To grant degrees on studies of specific countries in order to train and develop experts/specialists on countries of the world. \nThe offering of degree programs is not foreseen in the immediate future. Nevertheless, the institution of any degree program shall follow the procedure prescribed by the University. \n\nResearch Agenda\nThe various fields of specialization of affiliate faculty members define the research agenda. Faculty research is mandatory. Research work has, at the minimum, a credit load equivalent to three units of teaching every semester. \nAs a further incentive to research, a fund in support of academic research must be established at the Center. The fund should be sufficiently large to finance local research expenses of the faculty, including a reasonable honorarium. \n\nThe incentive structure is designed to encourage publication in professional journals, both here and abroad. Invitation to join the Center and subsequent promotion rest heavily on the publication record of the faculty. \n\nOrganization\nProviding overall policy direction to the Center is the Coordinating Council, the chairperson of which is the Diliman Chancellor. The Council shall be composed of the deans of the College of Arts and Letters, College of Social Sciences and Philosophy, Asian Center, School of Economics and other units closely affiliated with the concerns of the Center.\n\nIt must be emphasized that the Center will not have its own complement of permanent faculty members. Rather, the Center will be open to faculty affiliates who will be assigned or detailed to the Center on a temporary or part-time basis. The idea is for the faculty to maintain their own disciplinal identity and to be assigned to the Center on a temporary basis. \n\nA director shall head the Center. S/He shall be assisted by coordinators, the number of which will depend on the number of area studies that are ready to be implemented. In the immediate term, for example, coordinators for a Southeast Asian Studies Program and a European Studies Program will be designated. \n\nOrganization\n\nProviding overall policy direction to the Center is the Coordinating Council, the chairperson of which is the Diliman Chancellor. The Council shall be composed of the deans of the College of Arts and Letters, College of Social Sciences and Philosophy, Arts and Letters, School of Economics and other units closely affiliated with the concerns of the Center. \n\nIt must be emphasized that the Center will not have its own complement of permanent faculty members. Rather the Center will be open to faculty affiliates who will be assigned or detailed to the Center on a temporary or part-time basis. The idea is for the faculty to maintain their own disciplinal identity and to be assigned to the Center on a temporary basis. \n\nA director shall head the Center. S/He shall be assisted by coordinators, the number of which will depend on the number of area studies that are ready to be implemented. In the immediate term, for example, coordinators for a Southeast Asian Studies Program and a European Studies Program will be designated. \n\nBudgetary Requirements\nU.P. Diliman shall source the funding requirements of the Center from its own budget. \n\nIn estimating the budgetary requirements, the following guidelines will be observed:\n\n1. Personal services\n\nCharges against this item shall include th following :\n- honoraria and RATA of faculty administrators\n- salaries and honoraria of substitutes of faculty members who will be detailed to the Center\n- honoraria of faculty doing work for the Center\n\n2. MOOE\n\nCharges against this item shall include, among others, utilities expenses, security and janitorial services, office rent, etc.\n\n(Please see Appendix 1 for the full text of the Proposal and an estimate of budgetary requirements for the first five years.)\n\nBoard action : Approval\n\nCERTIFIED CORRECT : \n\nMARTIN V. GREGORIO\nSecretary of the University\nand of the Board of Regents', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1526, 'E2-1526AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Proposal to Establish the UP Diliman Center for International Studies ', 'Overview\nThis report proposes the creation of a Center for International Studies in UP Diliman that will bring together existing area and international studies at the Asian Center (AC), College of Arts and Letters (CAL), College of Social Sciences and Philosophy (CSSP), and other units with related offerings. The goal of the center is to promote research on the cultures and the interrelatedness of the social and economic systems of countries in Asia, America, and Europe. In the future, depending on the need and faculty resources, the Center may offer degree programs at the undergraduate and graduate levels. \n\nRationale\n\nAn international studies program is important for its contribution to the wealth of knowledge and to the development of well-rounded, cosmopolitan citizens. Area studies imply intimate knowledge of a given country\'s or region\'s cultural foundations arising from basic research in the history and culture, social movements, civil society, foreign relations, and migration patterns of the world\'s major civilizations. \nMoreover, area studies help advance national development goals. The conduct of Philippine foreign policy, for instance, benefits a great deal from the availability of a large pool of university-based specialists who can provide expert analysis in various areas of concern (e.g., culture, politics, economics, science and technology) about individual countries or a regional grouping of countries. \n\nThe Philippines is increasingly being integrated with the rest of the world not only economically but also socially, politically and culturally. Such integration, however, is not always smooth and to enable this ongoing transformation to serve development goals, it is important to have a good understanding of the determinants, processes, and consequences of rapid globalization. To do this, teaching and research in international studies, whether basic or policy oriented, undertaken by a core of country and subject specialists, are indispensable. \n\nUP Diliman is well placed to provide the required teaching and research, not necessarily by creating new programs, but by integrating and strengthening existing area and international studies programs in the Diliman campus (see Appendix A for details). These programs have had a long story. At present, however, they are scattered in various units and departments, resulting in high overhead costs and low synergy. A little introspection will show that an amalgamation can lead to scale economies in the use of faculty time and financial resources and to more focused academic programs. \n\nAs globalization proceeds, economic and technical cooperation between developed an developing countries, anchored on human capital buildup and technology transfers, gathers strength. In this regard, the developed countries have seen it fit to assist the developing ones in capacity enhancement through support education, training, and research. UP Diliman will be in a strong position to attract some funds for the purpose, which are in the form of official development assistance and grants from private foundation, if it has in place a world-class international studies program. \n\nAim/Vision\n\nThe Center for International Studies shall be a leading source of knowledge of the countries of the world, to enable the Filipino to gain this knowledge and meaningfully relate to the outside world. \n\nObjectives\n\n1. To conduct multi-interdisciplinary cross-cultural research.\n2. To become a resource center for information on different countries. \n3. To grant degrees on studies of specific countries in order to train and develop experts/specialists on countries of the world. \n\nThe offering of degree programs is not foreseen in the immediate future. Nevertheless the institution of any degree program shall follow the procedure prescribed by the University. \n\nResearch Agenda\n\nThe various fields of specialization of affiliate faculty members define the research agenda. Faculty research is mandatory. Research work has at the minimum a credit load equivalent to three units of teaching every semester.\n\nAs a further incentive to research, a fund in support of academic research must be established at the center. The fund should be sufficiently large to finance local research expenses of the faculty, including a reasonable honorarium. \n\nThe incentive structure is designed to encourage publication in professional journals, both here and abroad. Invitation to join the center and subsequent promotion rest heavily on the publication record of the faculty. \n\nOrganization\n\nProviding overall policy direction to the Center is the Coordinating Council, the chairperson of which is the Diliman Chancellor. The Council shall be composed of the deans of the College of Arts and Letters, College of Social Sciences and Philosophy, Asian Center, School of Economics and other units closely affiliated with the concerns of the Center. \n\nIt must be emphasized that the Center will not have its own complement of permanent faculty members. Rather, the Center will be open to faculty affiliates who will be assigned or detailed to the Center on a temporary or part-time basis. The idea is for the faculty to maintain their own disciplinal identity and to be assigned to the Center on a temporary basis. \n\nA director shall head the Center. S/He shall be assisted by coordinators, the number of which will depend on the number of area studies that are ready to be implemented. In the immediate term, for example, coordinators for a Southeast Asian Studies Program and a European Studies Program will be designated. \n\nBudgetary Requirements\n\nUP Diliman shall source the funding requirements of the Center from its own budget. \n\nIn estimating the budgetary requirements the following guidelines will be observed :\n\n1. Personal Services \n\nCharges against this item shall include the following :\n- honoraria and RATA of faculty administrators\n- salaries and honoraria of substitutes of faculty members who will be detailed to the Center\n- honoraria of faculty doing work for the Center\n\n2. MOOE\nCharges against this item shall include among others utilities expenses, security and janitorial services, office rent, etc. \n\nFor an estimate of budgetary requirements for the first five years, please refer to Annex A. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1527, 'E2-1527AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'An International Studies Agenda for UPD ', 'Introduction\nThe following report represents the fruition of an \"idea whose time has come\" : the integration, rationalization and coordination of area/international studies in UP Diliman. Its analyses and recommendations are made with the end in view of putting UPD at par with other prestigious universities in Asia and the world through the institutionalization of area/international studies programs as a distinct field of intellectual endeavor. \n\nIt is an incontrovertible fact that the University is the pioneer in the Philippines in the field of area studies (i.e. Asian Studies) : in 1955 was created the Institute of Asian Studies, a non-degree granting establishment for research and which 1958 was \"upgraded\" into the Asian Center. But with the proliferation of other area-studies programs (e.g. French, or European, the latter being under the wing of the UCIDS), a certain tendency to stagnate has set in. The relevance of certain courses, if not of whole programs, is sporadically under question. There is no coordination among the various programs existing or proposed to be put up. Not least, the problem of the acceptability of area-studies has lingered in the minds of a number of faculty members in the \"established\" disciplines. Thus the full potential of area-studies is not tapped by the university which was among the first in Asia to venture in that field. \n\nYet the age of globalization has brought great winds of change upon the national community, and with it comes the urgent challenge for UPD to be regionally and internationally relevant. This does not mean that we should adopt area/international studies programs indiscriminately and uncritically just to keep up with current trends, but it means that UPD should make efficient use of its bountiful multidisciplinary faculty resources, and further develop country experts to make it a center for the learning of culture, society, history, economic activity and political processes of, at least initially, its immediate neighbors. Well-developed and productive area/international studies centers are hallmarks of the great modern university; no nation with aspirations to greatness can afford to be ignorant of its partners in either trade or simple diplomatic relations. Indeed, it has been rightly said that one gains better knowledge of one\'s own society after intimate contact with a foreign one. \n\nThe best time to embark on this project is now, with the new millennium\'s psychological and ideological climates auguring a more open atmosphere for this field of learning than ever before. It will not be effortless, to be sure, and \"disciplinal inertia\" plus budgetary constraints will create an impression of resistance. But there is growing local demand for expertise in country-or area studies, and several foreign governments and foundations are only waiting to be asked to help set up appropriate programs. UPD should realize that it has so much yet-untapped intellectual resources that could make area international studies one of its major offerings. \n\nI. Status Report\nA. Existing courses/programs :\n1. Disciplinal based\n1.1. Comparative literature courses - CAL\nThese include courses on European as well as Asian literature\n1.2. Master in International Studies - Political Science, CSSP. This degree is more oriented towards international relations. \n1.3. Courses on features of various countries in the departments of History, Geography, Linguistics, Political Science, Psychology, Philosophy and Demography - CSSP \n1.4. Art Studies : Asian and Chinese - CAL\n1.5 Economics in Asia - School of Economics\n1.6 Language structures of Japanese, Chinese, and Bahasa in Indonesia - Linguistics, CSSP\n\n2. Area based\n2.1 MA Asian Studies (China, Japan, Korea) - Asian Center\n\n3. Language based\n\n3.1. B.A. in different European languages - CAL\n3.2. B.A. Linguistics, Plan C : Linguistics at Wikang East Asia (Japanese/Chinese/Korean) - CSSP\n\nB. Existing research/data base building/networking\n\n1. Film : CMC\n2. Gender : SOLAIR and Women\'s Study Center\n3. Music : CM\n4. Public policy : NCPAG\n5. International relations and security : Area and Strategic Studies : Japan Program - Law Center\n6. Earthquake engineering (Japan) : College of Architecture\n\nC. Initiatives and Programs\n1. Area Studies\na. Area Studies Council - 1994\nThis council was set up afer several meetings and a workshop conducted in previous years. It consisted of the VC for Academic Affairs, the VC for Student Affairs, Director of the Office of Instruction, the deans and directors of CSSP, CAL, AC, ILS, SURP, CPAD, SE and 2 other representative of CSSP and AC. \nThe duties of the council were to : \n1. advise the Chancellor on matters pertaining to Area Studies; \n2. develop an Area Studies program;\n3. coordinate studies and research;\n4. collect and retrieve knowledge to enrich area studies\nb. The documents show that Area Studies :\n1. \'encompasses studies, researches and expertise in the language, society, culture, particular country and/or region. The systematic learning of the language in its cultural context will be given priority\";\n2. \"aims to develop expertise in area studies for the development of basic knowledge, the formulation of national policy and the creation of an enlightened and patriotic citizenry\"; \n3. intends to conduct \"the training of selected scholars\";\n4. intends to study cultural areas - (this was not explained fully).\nc. European Studies\n1. CAL - Proposed a European Studies minor for the existing BA European Languages (for both Plan A and Plan B) \"to provide European language students an opportunity to know about the continents, cultural, social and political diversity\" and...Produce students proficient in at least one European language other than English...conversant with the culture and political and social institutions of not just one European country, but of the entire continent as well...\" Required number of courses will be 27 of the total 141 units required for BA European Languages Program as follows : \n\n6 units Comparative Literature\n3 units Art Studies\n3 units History (Kas 102)\n3 units Geography (Geo 151)\n9 units Political Science\n3 units Music or Fine Arts\n\n2. CSSP - Plans are underway for a \"...multidisciplinary approach to the study of social/human problems, and complementary to existing special area/topic, degree, research, training, extension programs and course offerings in various Units of the University,... of area coverage (North/East/South/West/Central European countries) and a comparative perspective - with particular reference to the Philippines and Asia...\"\n\n- Special projects : Research and resource collection - research on the influence of Europe upon the Philippines and comparative studies of European and other countries. Initial plan - Country Profiles Project \"...projects require joint participation among at least two European Union countries and two developing countries...\"\n\nd. Southeast Asian Studies\n1. CSSP - proposal under study\n2. Linkage with Southeast Asian Studies Regional Exchange Program (SEASREP)\n\nA number of the faculty have collaborated or benefited from one or more of its components which are : \n\nTeaching SEAS at the undergraduate level\nPost-graduate training\nLanguage training\nStaff development\nCollaborative research\nConferences\nPublications\nInstitutional development\nLibrary resource development\nAdministrative networking\n\n3. Chinese Studies\nProposals were made for : \n1. Chinese Studies Resource Office - \"...to develop and promote 1) research and publication, 2) library resources, 3) intra- and inter-university linkages and exchanges pertinent to the mutual understanding of the Filipinos and Chinese peoples...\"\n(This was one of the recommendations of the conference/workshop held on October 25-26, 1993, sponsored by the Chiang Ching-Kuo (CCK) Foundation). \n2. Task Force on Chinese Studies (1998) - reiterated the establishment of a Chinese Studies Resource Office \"to enable the UP to institutionalize a framework of bringing together on an organized, regular and permanent basis, scholars, academic and professionals in the field of Chinese Studies from various disciplines.\" It proposed setting up \"a core group composed of research fellows, an advisory panel and a physical office\".\n\nf. Korean Studies \n\nA Korean Studies committee was formed in 1995 which held an Interaction Conference between the College of Arts and Letters and Han Nam University sponsored by the Korea Foundation.\nIn a letter to Dr. A. T. Torres then VCAA, the Vice President of Korea Foundation Mr. Young-Mo expressed their intention to support a teacher for the Korean language and the hope that courses on Korean culture, history and literature would be offered in the future. He mentioned the Foundation\'s program which included grants for institutional efforts to develop Korean Studies in terms of visiting professors, fellowships and book and reference materials. \nA few members of the faculty have gone to Han Nam University. This activity did not prosper because the program was for undergraduates, was too short for gaining knowledge, and the support given was not adequate. \n\ng. Japanese Studies\n\nThe documents show that the proposed BA Japan Studies was meant \"to develop an understanding of Japanese society and culture as part of the liberal education orientation of the University and as a contribution to the human resource requirements of a globalizing world.\" After a long period of discussions, and meetings of successive committees which were established to study the viability of the program, it was decided to propose 2 tracks (A and B) to be managed by CSSP and CAL.\n\nRequired number of units : 147\n\nTrack A\nCourses\nGE courses - 42\nmandated course (PI 100) - 3\nlanguage courses - 36\ncore courses (required for both tracks) - 33\nmajor courses - 18\nPre-requisites - 6\nelectives - 9\n                 147\nTrack B - Arts and Letters\nGE courses - 42\nmandated course (PI 100) - 3\nLanguage courses - 36 \ncore courses - 33\nmajor courses - 33\nelective -3 \n                    150\n\nThe curricula were discussed at a 3/147 UC Special Meeting on 2.26.99. The decision was to reconvene the committee to study the newly instituted courses for Japanese in the Department of Linguistics and make the necessary changes in the proposed Japanese Studies curriculum. \n\nPresently, both proposals track A and B with the necessary changes have been passed by the respective College Assemblies and resubmitted to the VCAA Office. \n\nh. American Studies\n\nA Committee on American Studies proposed a BA American Studies curriculum in 1996. The program \"...aims to provide basic knowledge of the United States of America as a nation, to enable the students to interpret trends in American society, politics, economy, industry, and technology. It also aims to develop an appreciation of American literature and the arts and to broaden the perspective of students on regional and global affairs supportive of Philippine nation building.\"\n\nThe committee last met in November 1996 to discuss the curriculum and request the members representing their various colleges to propose to their respective units, the possibility of offering the new courses listed in the curriculum. The proposal stipulated a total of 141 units, with 42 GE courses, PI 100, 33 core courses (18 to be instituted), and 63 other courses in American Studies (18 to be instituted). \n\nII. Proposed General Framework for Strengthening International Studies \nAs shown by the preceding status report on existing and planned efforts towards building expertise and amassing knowledge of other countries, UPD has still a lot of ground to cover. \nThe greatest effort taken to date is initiating discussions on an Area Studies Program. Apparently one reason for the failure in implementing the program can be the indecision on the scope of the \'area\' concept. \nArea Studies implies the study of a group or groups of countries which are in some way identified together either geographically, linguistically, culturally, economically or by religion. Also, such studies could proceed on a disciplinal approach. Therefore studies along these lines would necessarily be comparative in nature and would demand experts on the countries involved. \nThe documents show that the program aims, among other things to \"...develop expertise in Area Studies for the development of basic knowledge.\" This contradicts the notion of area studies, if this means basic knowledge of the people and culture of the specific countries of the area. \nThe discussion/proposal did not clearly spell out what was meant by \'cultural area\'. It seems that this has to evolve out of the commonalities of the countries to be studies as an area. \nThe other proposals/initiatives except that of Japan Studies are still in the initial stages of planning. \nThe BA Japan Studies proposal is so far nearest the stage of implementation and this is the greatest and most immediate problem right now. Although the CSSP and CAL are supposed to take care of the admission to and graduation of students, no unit/body has been given the responsibility of coordinating the tracks. This problem will be compounded should the other proposals (Chinese studies, Korean studies, etc.) go for establishing a degree especially since these proposals are multi/interdisciplinary. It is necessary therefore to come up with a general framework for strenghthening and coordinating studies of other countries and the areas into which they cluster. \n\nSUMMARY OF BUDGETARY REQUIREMENTS\nCENTER FOR INTERNATIONAL STUDIES\n\nPersonal Services   356,488     856,488     856,488     1,230,000     1,230,000\nPersonal Services  106,488    106,488     106,488     230,000     230,000\nPS Lumpsum 250,000     750,000     750,000     1,000,000     1,000,000\n\nMOOE  500,000     1,000,000     1,000,000     1,000,000     1,000,000\nEquipment Outlay 200,000                                  250,000\nTOTAL  P1,056.488     1,856,488     2,056,000     2,230,000     2,230,000', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1528, 'E2-1528AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, December 4) ', 'Edgardo Atanacio\nDean \nCollege of Engineering\n\nDear Sir : \n\nGreetings!\n\nThis is to file an official complaint against Mr. Donato Dela Cruz, our professor in ChE 133, Process Equipment Design I. Until now we have yet to receive our final grade for that subject. There was only a sheet of paper in which he signed his name and listed the names of those that passed. \n\nListed below are instances, which serves as grounds for our complaint :\n\n1. No classcards yet. \n2. Delayed posting of the second part of the list of those that passed. Some of us could have finished the enrollment on the first day if not for that. We had to go back for three days to find out the results to no avail. \n3. Left us hanging in the middle of the semester, since he had to work. We were supposed to have make-up classes on Saturdays but there he would never show up for any reason at all. There was no notice that we won\'t be having classes. \n4. Excessive absences. \n5. He crammed the fourth exam into a three-hour lecture, which ended late at night, and to think he would still arrive late. The fourth exam was just 2 days away. \n6. He moved the exam to a later date to October 20 when the last day of finals was supposed to be October 19. That was the time when there was no electricity, and the rooms were dark. Also he arrived about an hour late, and he still had not photocopied the exams, which was a total waste of time. \n7. Always arrives late on the day of the exams or make-up classes. \n8. Always goes back on his word : \na) He told the class that we will be having just 3 exams since he was going on leave, then changed his mind and changed it back to 4.\nb) We waited for our class standings/exemption list for the finals but he never showed up and said some time later, that no one was exempted from the finals. \nc) The second part of the list of students that passed, in which he said a particular date, but it never came. Then he said tomorrow, and we waited, and there was still no list. It came three days later. \n\nWe hope this letter will reach you to shed more light upon the nature of our complaint. Your utmost cooperation and attention will be highly appreciated. \n\nSincerely yours, \n\nJayme Maniti\n\nIsabella Yap\n\nSarah Jane Legaspi', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1529, 'E2-1529AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, November 20)', 'Asean University Network\n\nOur Reference Number : 362 /2000\n\nH.E. Professor Easter A. Garcia\nChairperson\nCommission on Higher Education\n5/F DAP Bldg., San Miguel Avenue\nOrtigas Center, Pasig City 1605\nMetro Manila, Philippines\nFax : (632) 637 3571\n\nExcellency,\n\nSubject : Southeast Asia Engineering Education Development Network (SEED-Net) \n\nKindly refer to our letter dated October 3, 2000, reference number 285/2000 which we informed you about AUN/SEED-Net Project and its Preparatory Meeting to discuss the Project details and plans for the implementation of the project.\n\nWe would like to inform you that the AUN/SEED-Net Preparatory Meeting was successfully held at Chulalongkorn University, Thailand during November 16-17, 2000 participated by the Rectors, Deans of the Faculty of Engineering and/or Representatives of the universities selected by your ministry.\n\nDuring the Meeting, the following two issues have been endorsed :\n1) Location of AUN/SEED-Net Secretariat to be located at Faculty of Engineering, Chulalongkorn University\n2) Prof. Dr. Panitan Lukkunaprasit, a professor of Civil Engineering, Chulalongkorn University, to be the AUN/SEED-Net\'s Executive Director\n\nFollowing the agreement and acknowledgment on the Project details and implementation plan, the Meeting further requested each ministry responsible for higher education to nominate one dean of engineering faculty in each country as a member of the AUN/SEED-Net Steering Committee. The term of deans of engineering faculties in the Steering Committee shall be initially staggered into one-and two year periods. The responsibilities of the Steering Committee include formulation of policies, approval of proposals, evaluation of activities, managing and generating fund, and etc. \n\nTherefore, we would highly appreciate your kind nomination of a member of the AUN/SEED-Net Steering Committee by mail to the newly appointed AUN/SEED-Net Secretariat\'s Executive Director by December 29, 2000 at the following address :\nProf. Dr. Panitan Lukkunaprasit\nAUN/SEED-Net Executive Director\nDepartment of Civil Engineering\nFaculty of Engineering\nChulalongkorn University\nBangkok 10330, Thailand\nFax : (662) 251 7304\n\nFor further information, kindly refer to the Minutes of AUN/SEED-Net Preparatory Meeting as attached. \n\nPlease accept, Excellency, the renewed assurances of my highest consideration.\n\nSincerely yours, \n\nAssoc. Prof. Supachai Yavaprabhas, Ph.D.\nAUN Executive Director\n\ncc : 1. De La Salle University\n- Dr. Sevillano Olano, Jr., Dean of College of Engineering\n2. University of the Philippines System\n- Dr. Emerlinda R. Roman, Chancellor - UP Diliman ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1530, 'E2-1530AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(2000, November 24) ', 'Republic of the Philippines\nDepartment of Trade and Industry\nCONSTRUCTION INDUSTRY AUTHORITY OF THE PHILIPPINES\n4/F Jupiter 1 Building, 58 Jupiter St., Bel-Air Village, Makati City, 1209, Philippines\n\nHON. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nExecutive Director\nNATIONAL ENGINEERING CENTER\nUP Campus, Diliman\nQuezon City\n\nDear Sir : \n\nThe CIAP shall launch its Action Agenda and present its proposed specific action plans for each action agenda item in pursuit of the Construction Industry Strategic Plan for the 21st Century (CI21) on December 04, 2000, 1:00 p.m. at the Makati Shangri-La, Ayala Avenue, Makati City. \n\nThe CI21 is a framework of the orderly and accelerated growth of construction based on the shared industry vision of \"Global players in a global environment.\" It was formulated in mid-1998 through a series of consultation meetings with representatives from various industry associations to set the long-term direction for all concerned sectors. The intent of CI21 is for CIAP, government agencies involved in construction, and industry associations, to use it as the basis for drawing up their own Action Agenda an/or plans and programs for the specific construction industry sectors within their areas of concern. \n\nBased on the CI21 and the CIAP mandate, the CIAP Action Agenda and proposed specific action plans seek to address the following three (3) major challenges : \n- Upgrading of Construction Capabilities and Resources;\n- Enhancing Quality and Efficiency; and\n- Ensuring Professionalism and Social Responsibility\n\nThe proposed strategies and action points will be presented during the launching to government and private participants from the various sectors of the construction industry. The participants shall be given time after the launching to comment on the proposed CIAP Action Agenda and to rank each item according to urgency and importance. These will be consolidated for discussion and finalization in a workshop to be held in January of next year. A plenary session in February 2001 is also set for the signing of agreements on specific responsibilities and commitments under the CIAP Action Agenda and Specific Action Plans. \n\nIn this regard, we are pleased to invite you to grace the occasion as one of our special guests as well as one (1) officer/member from your agency to participate and/or represent your office in the forthcoming workshops to discuss the CIAP Action Agenda on Upgrading of Construction Capabilities. \n\nFor confirmation and other queries, please don\'t hesitate to call us at Tel. Nos. 896-18-31, 896-18-33 and Fax No. 896-45-69.\n\nWe look forward to your presence and participation. \n\nVery truly yours,\n\nKATHRYN JOSEPHINE T. DELA CRUZ\nOfficer-In-Charge ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1531, 'E2-1531AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1998, January 9)', 'Republic of the Philippines\nOffice of the President\nCOMMISSION ON HIGHER EDUCATION\nRegion IX, Zamboanga City\n\nThe Chairman\nMeralco Award for Engineering and Applied Sciences\nSecretariat, Corporation Communication\nMeralco, Ortigas Avenue\nPasig City\n\nSir, \n\nWe are sending herewith the Nomination form and other supporting documents of Mr. Carlos A. Abarro and Arch. Domingo A. Abarro III for consideration to the Annual Meralco Award for Engineering and Applied Sciences. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nBernabella LL. Panganiban\nOIC, Chief', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1532, 'E2-1532AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Republic of the Philippines\nWestern Mindanao State University\nZamboanga City\nPhilippines\n\nACHIEVEMENTS\n\nOutstanding contribution to Socio-Economic Development\n\nMr. Carlos Anselmo A. Abarro, Jr. could be given the credit in improving the Wood Wool Cement Bonded Board construction material, (DOST-Los Banos, introduced the material thru its Transfer Technology Program) by re-discovering the weed PALO VERDE (Scientifically known as Piper Arborecens) and using its excelsior as one of the main components/ingredients in producing Wood Wool Cement Bonded Board which his firm G.C. Enterprises is producing and marketing under the name ZAMBOARD (featured in 1996 Land Bank of the Philippines calendar).\n\nThis product Zamboard was submitted and tested by DOST Los Banos, Laguna (refer to xeroxed letter-result sent by Mr. Arturo A. Pablo, Chief, Composite Products Development, Forest Products Research and Development Institute, DOST, College, Laguna dated 24 May 1995 to Mr. Carlos A. Abarro, Jr.) and accredited by AITECH, Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council, Makati Avenue, Makati City (refer xeroxed copy Inter-Agency Committee Accreditation Certificate No. 95-005 / R1 dated 24 March 1997 signed by Chairman, Dionisio Dela Serna) and likewise, found to be one of the better Wood Wool Cement Bonded Boards available in the market today. \n\nZamboard is an alternative construction material that is economical and practical in low-cost and marginalized housing. Thru, innovative design, use and construction the budget conscious residents of Zamboanga City, the neighboring provinces and cities in Region IX are benefitting by using Zamboard in their house renovation, constructing low-budget houses as well as medium-cost structures and buildings. \n\nBy :\n\nDr. Alfredo A. Ducanes\nDean for Research \nWestern Mindanao State University ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
