(1533, 'E2-1533AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1998, January 07)', 'Republic of the Philippines\nWESTERN MINDANAO STATE UNIVERSITY\nZamboanga City\nPhilippines\n\nAchievements \nOutstanding contribution to Socio-Economic Development\n\nWhile Mr. Carlos Anselmo A. Abarro, Jr. improved, produces and market Zamboard (Zamboanga Wood Wool Cement Boards), Arch. Domingo A. Abarro III (Dean, College of Architecture, Western Mindanao State University, Normal Road, Zamboanga City) his elder brother, had designed, used and experimented extensively thru actual projects the construction material, Zamboard and thus, proving the material to be very promising, which could be used 80 to 90 per cent in structure components specially in low-cost housing projects as well as medium to high budget cost structure (refer to his paper, entitled : Zamboard, a very promising construction material, presented in November 1996, @The  4th International Conference for Civil Engineering, Diamond Hotel, M.M.  \n\nZamboards usage was first limited to walls, ceiling, and partition but thru Dean Abarros\' creativity and technical know-how in architectural design, materials and construction the board can presently be used as roofing material, fascia boards, base boards, panels for panel and flush doors, 2nd floor base flooring as well as furniture and furnishings for homes and offices, while being affordable, aesthetically appealing, functional and structurally sound still environment friendly.\n\nThe Zamboard project Sites (listed below) will attest to his findings and prove the principles applied in architectural design, use and construction which is benefiting the residents / builders of Region IX as well as some other provinces and cities. \n\nZamboard Project Sites : (Please refer to pictures)\n\n1) Zamboard Model Office / House, #36 Varela Street, Zamboanga City\nOwner : G.C. Enterprises, # 36 Varela Street, Zamboanga City\nTel. Nos. 991-1949 /991-3620\nFax No. (062) 991-3309\n\n*Featured in the 1997 DBP Calendar (September)\n*Featured in the 1996 Land Bank Calendar (February)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1534, 'E2-1534AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Republic of the Philippines\nWESTERN MINDANAO STATE UNIVERSITY\nZamboanga City\nPhilippines\n\n2) Carmen Subdivision @Upper Pasonanca, Zamboanga City (Low to middle-low housing)\n\nOwner : Anvaland Development Corporation, Canelar Street, Zamboanga City\nTel. No. 993-2566\n\n3) Kristina Homes @ Talon-talon, Zamboanga City\n(Low, middle-low to high housing) \n\nOwner : Commercial Lending House, La Purisima Street\nZamboanga City\nTel. no. 991-5403\n\n4) Office Furniture / Furnishings \nZamboanga City Ecozone and Free Port Authority Office\n2nd Floor, Security Bank Building, Veterans Avenue, Zamboanga City\nTel. no. 991-3151\n\n5) Middle-low Model Houses (on-going)\nXavier Estates, Km. 5 Upper Balulang\nCagayan De Oro City\n\nOwner : East Pacific Investros Corporation\nTel. nos. (088) 858-8784\n858-8785\nTelefax (088) 727646, 72975\n\nSubsidiary of : A Brown Company, Inc. \n\nBy : \n\nDr. Alfredo A. Ducanes\nDean for Research \nWestern Mindanao State University', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1535, 'E2-1535AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Zamboard \nA VERY PROMISING CONSTRUCTION MATERIAL\n\nARCHITECT DOMINGO A. ABARRO III\n\nABSTRACT\n\nThis paper is about Zamboard, a very promising alternative construction material which is made of 60% cement and 40% Palo Verde Weed mixed with suitable accelerator into two feet by eight feet panels, thickness varying from 8 mm to 50 mm. A transfer technology from DOST at Los Banos, the author in coordination with G.C. Enterprises (manufacturer) has a first information in experimenting with the product and putting its inherent characteristics, uses and other special features into actual use in search for a lower costing material for low cost and marginalized housing. Principles are discussed and introduced to show the real potential of the product and its eventual use for the benefit of the construction industry and its ultimate beneficiary, the house owner. \n\n1. INTRODUCTION\n\nAs the millennium fast approaches the 21st century, the population of the Philippines as well as that of the world has increased tremendously. Such is likewise the case, of the need for more of one of the basic necessities of man, SHELTER. More so when we look at the great disparity between the rich and poor wherein the latter is found wanting of the very basic need, coupled with the scarcity of raw and inexpensive materials caused by misuse, wanton destruction of our natural environment in the guise of so called \"modern development\" introduced by uncaring, ignorant, irresponsible, and materialistic, profit-oriented impostors pretending to be the real professionals. \n\nThus, a search for an alternative construction material that would meet the following criteria :\n\n1.1 Ease of production, less expensive (than existing ones) but possesses far superior qualities and characteristics. \n1.2 Uses waste materials that are abundant. \n1.3 Environment friendly\n1.4 User friendly with existing tools and equipment and methods of construction\n1.5 Flexibility in terms of use and application.\n1.6 Long-lasting / stand the abuse of time and the natural elements. \n1.7 Best used for low-cost and marginalized housing but with expensive home applications through innovative, creative designs and construction methods.\n\nAlas, Zamboanga Boards (Zamboard for short) is it!\n\n2. ZAMBOARD (ZAMBOANGA CEMENT BONDED BOARD) DEFINED\n\nZamboard is made of shredded wood fibers of excelsior of Palo Verde (Scientifically known as Piper Arborecens, which grows well in lowlands as well as uplands as Zamboanga Peninsula with elevation up to 600 meters above sea level. It grows rapidly and adaptable to a wide range of soil condition, ease in plantation establishment and suitable to various and uses are salient characteristics of this weed) bonded with ordinary cement, water and a suitable cement accelerator, cold pressed under low pressure and ambient temperature. Its surface dimensions 610 millimeter wide by 2440 millimeter long and in various thickness from 8 millimeter to 50 millimeter.\n\n3. HISTORICAL DEVELOPMENT\n\nWood cement composite product have been known in Europe for so many years. The Heraklith Company of Austria claims to be the original patentee of the so-called wood wool building slab. The company obtained its first patent of the material as early as 1808. \n\nIn Germany, the first wood wool products was introduced in the market in 1921. It had wood wool from spruce, a member of the pine family as its main raw material and soil cement, its main binder. \n\nWood wool industries have been well established in many European countries from many years. In Britain, the wood wool buildings slab industry was already established long before the second world war. The slabs were used mainly as structural insulating roof decking materials. Years later other countries like Netherlands, France, and Switzerland develop the product and were marketed successfully over the world as DURAPANEL. before the second world war. The slabs were used mainly as structural insulating roof decking materials. Years later other countries like Netherlands, France and Switzerland develop the product and were marketed successfully over the world as DURAPANEL.\n\nIn Asia in the early sixties, countries like Australia, Japan, Malaysia, and Singapore have already adopted the manufacture of the board until they shifted into high grade finished boards. \n\nWood wool or cement bonded board was introduced in the Philippines druing the 1980\'s through the Department of Science and Technology (DOST) at Los Banos, Laguna which introduced the technology and the resulting product to some manufacturers in Luzon using rice stalks, rattan shavings, saw dusts and rice husks as raw materials with a short-lived success due to unavailability of the mentioned raw materials in volume quantity. My brother, Carlos Anselmo A. Abarro, Jr., a graduate of U.P. College of Agriculture at Los Banos, was introduced to the technology and product when he mated to his Alma Mater in seach for new business opportunitiesa after the family logging TLA (timber license agreement) expired and with a Lease Agreement for 500 hectares of logged-over area for Agro-industrial ventures good for 25 years. He readily accepted the technology transfer in 1995 and started searching for the raw material that would suit and give the desired qualities of a wood wool board. In the process of searching he re-discovered the great potential of the weed Palo Verde which abounds and rapidly grows in our logged-over area. Produced in our factory situated at Pamacutan, Zamboanga City, tested and tried in the laboratories of DOST at Los Banos (refer to MECHANICAL PROPERTIES OF ZAMBOARD) our new product was born and renamed Zamboanga Board or just Zamboard. \n\n4. MATERIAL COMPONENTS\n\nThe main components of this product is wood and cement. Wood is lightweight and can be easily machined while cement is incombustible, rigid when cured, resistant to rot, fungi and is highly resistant to dimensional changes when exposed to humidity. \n\nAny wood materials except hard wood can be a potential raw materials for the product. The latest discovered species of weed which has a high potential value is the Palo Verde of scientifically known as Piper Arborecens. This small evergreen tree abound in Zamboanga City particularly in Barangay Pamacutan, Sinubong, Patalon, Labuan, Limpapa, La Paz, Baluno, and Bunguiao, and it is now being utilized for the manufacture of ZAMBOARD as one of it\'s main ingredients, it is produced commercially in Zamboanga City by the Abarro\'s G.C. Enterprises and the first manufacturer to use the Palo Verde weed. \n\n5. ZAMBOARD MANUFACTURING PROCESS\n\nProcesses involved : \n\n5.1 Cutting and shredding\n5.2 Soaking\n5.3 Drying\n5.4 Mixing\n5.5. Mat-forming\n5.6 Pressing\n5.7 Clamping\n5.8 Curing and conditioning\n5.9 Trimming\n5.10 Finishing\n(REFER TO FLOW PROCESS IN THE PRODUCTION OF ZAMBOARD)\n\n6. CHARACTERISTICS AND USES\n\nZamboard has a desirable characteristic, relatively lightweight, water resistant, fire resistant and decay resistant. It is durable enough to withstand adverse water conditions such as typhoon, earthquakes and heavy rains, thermal insulating acoustic properties. It can be saved, to the high humidity, the board can be used as exterior walling paneling, and as partitions in rooms with high relative humidity.\n\n6.1 CHARACTERISTICS\n\n6.1.1 Termite free\n6.1.2 Fire retardant\n6.1.3. Asbestos Free\n6.1.4. Water resistant \n6.1.5. Earthquake resilient\n6.1.6. Thermal insulator\n6.1.7. Acoustic Properties\n6.1.8. Rot, fungi, and Vermin proof\n\n6.2. OTHER FEATURES\n6.2.1. Nailable\n6.2.2. Paintable\n6.2.3. Sawable\n6.2.4. Plasterable\n6.2.5. Sanderable\n6.2.6. Practically workable using ordinary carpentry tools\n6.2.7. Glutable\n\n6.3 USES\n6.3.1. Ceiling panels\n6.3.2. Walling (exterior and interior)\n6.3.3. Partitions\n6.3.4. Furniture\n6.3.5. Doors (panel and flush doors)\n6.3.6. Cabinet/closets flooring\n6.3.7. Toilet wall tiling\n6.3.8. Fascia board\n6.3.9. Baseboard\n6.3.10. Ceiling eaves\n6.3.11. Furniture/Furnishing \n6.4. MECHANICAL PROPERTIES\nTHICKNESS (mm)   DENSITY (Kg/m)     MODULES OF RAPTURE (MPa)     BRITISH STANDARDS (MPa)    REMARKS\n8                                 850                             8.30                                                   2.0                                                  Passed\n12                               800                             6.00                                                   2.0                                                  Passed\n19                               750                             5.20                                                   2.0                                                  Passed\n25                               700                             4.80                                                   2.0                                                  Passed\n\n7. CONSTRUCTION APPLICATIONS \n\nHaving the rare privilege to design and make use of our new product, Zamboard, I was able to discover that it is a promising alternative construction material to existing ones such as concrete hollow block (for exterior and interior walling) plywood (for interior, exterior sidings, ceiling, eaves, fascia as well as parapet walls a furniture) and more importantly scarce wood. \n\nTaking advantage of its inherent, positive physical characteristics (termites free fire retardant water resistant, earthquake resilient, thermal insulator, acoustic properties and rot/fungi/vermin proof) and other desirable features such as nailable, sawable (using ordinary carpenter\'s saw), gluable, plasterable and sanderable. The designer can come up with new innovative and creative design and construction methods that can lower the cost of existing low and marginalized cost of housing at the least. In bringing down the cost of low and marginalized shelters the designer/builder should be working on 3 very important areas : \n\n7.1. Innovative Design\n\n7.1.1. Principles of Duality as well as multi-purpose use of areas and spaces come into play (i.e. Sala by day, dining area during meal and sleeping area by bedtime)\n7.1.2. Maximum use of all available spaces i.e. Added useable area due to conversion of dropped ceiling to attics. \n7.1.3. Down scaling of house components without violating existing rules and regulations with respect to safely and comfort (i.e. Regular stairs to spiral staircase) \n7.1.4. Proper placement of sizing of fenestrations such as doors and windows and ventilation for better light and cross ventilation that would result to energy-saving and cost-cutting (i.e. Less usage of artificial lights and electric fans and the like)\n\n7.2. Use of inexpensive materials with special characteristics and desirable features to the maximum and to designer\'s advantage which is synonymous to the use of Zamboard (refer to Table I - Recommended Uses of Zamboard as to Density and Thickness and Table II - Comparative Cost Analysis of Zamboard with other materials)\n\nTable I. Recommended Zamboard uses with respect to thickness/density (1996)\n\nTHICKNESS                                                                                                                                                                           Remarks/Prevailing Price Zamboanga City as \n(2\' X8 Zamboard)     Density               USES                                                                                                                      of September 1996\n8 mm                          High Density     Interior wall, Ceiling board, Furniture, Flush/cabinet doors and sidings                                                  P120.00 per panel\n12 mm                        High Density     Interior part wall, Ceiling board, Furniture, Cabinets/doors panel                                                             P160.00 per panel\n19 mm                        High Density     Fascia board, Furniture, Cabinets/panel doors, Interior/part. Walls Baseboards                                   P215.00 per panel\n25 mm                        High Density     Flooring, Exterior Wall, Interior walls/part, Fascia board, Kitchen counter, Panel door, Base board    P270.00 per panel\n50 mm                        High Density     Exterior wall                                                                                                                                                         P390.00 per panel\n                                     Low Density      Interior wall                                                                                                                                                          P290.00 per panel \n                                                                 Flooring\n\nTable 2 Comparative cost analysis of Zamboard with other construction material (1996)\n\nType of construction materials     Material Cost           Zamboard Savings      Remarks\nExterior walls (18 sq. meters)       P12,480.00 (L&M)                                          Labor cost-lesser due to use of 2\' x 8\' panel. Thickness of plasters is less   \n1. CHB 4\' thk                                     P10,286.00 (L&M)                                         (1/2\' thk) no need to plaster interior surface - just paint textured effect finish\n2. Zamboard 2\' thk. Low density                                      117.6%\n\n\nInterior/partition wall \n(7.50 sq. meters)\n1. Zamboard 8mm thk                     P1,256.00 (L&M)        22.7%                          Labor cost the same, other desirable characteristics; textured finished   \n 2. Ordinary plywood 1/4\'in. thk     P1,625.00 (L&M)                                             surface thermal and acoustic qualities, homogenous\nFlooring (36 sq. meters)                                                                                             Material T&G labor-more expensive, Zamboard and marine plywood labor \n1. Zamboard                                      P6,750.00 (M)             50%                             cost the same Underside of Zamboard can serve as ceiling of ground floor. \n25 mm thk\n2. T&G 1\"x4\"x10\"                               13,520.00 (M)\n3. Marine plywood                             13,910,00 (M)\n3/4\"thk\nCeiling (63.2 sq. meters)                   \n1. Zamboard 8mm thk                      P240.00 (plywood) size       savings in terms of additional characteristics     Superior due to inherent qualities of \n                                                                                                                                                                                                    termite / Vermin proof, Thermal and \n2. Ordinary plywood 1/4\" thk           P280.00 per piece                                                                                                      acoustic qualities\nFascia board\n1. Zamboard                                       P430.00                         22%                                                                                      Longer lasting - Algae/fungi free/\n19mm thk                  \n2. Lumber\n1\"x10\"x10\"                                           P440.00                                                                                                                      Rot/vermin proof, paintable \n\nL&M : Labor and material cost\nM : Material cost only\n7.2.1 Using 1\" thick high dense on 2\" thick low dense Zamboard panels for exterior walls (non-load bearing) instead of 4\" concrete hollow blocks with properly placed and situated reinforcing bars will cut the cost by a minimum of 15% due to lesser cost of the materials and resulting reduced size of foundation, ease of construction (being panels) not to mention lesser labor cost and savings from having thinner plaster work on surfaces (minimum 1/2\", maximum 3/4\" in thick plastering), interior surface of 2\" thick panels could just be painted without plastering hence having a textured effect in vogue nowadays. Using 1\" thick high dense panels will results to using smaller dimension wooden window jambs (from 2\"x 4\" maximum to 1\"x 3\" minimum) and door jambs from 2\"x 4\" maximum to 2\" x 3\" minimum). \n7.2.2. Zamboard 1\" thick high dense for second floor or attics instead of T&G or plywood will also contribute to lower the cost plus if designed creatively the under surface of the panel can serve as the ceiling of the ground floor (considering the textured and acoustic qualities of Zamboard) cutting the cost more (no ore ceiling and ceiling joists).\n7.2.3. Thermal/insulator quality and acoustic quality of our material enables us to use attics as second floor for bedrooms even in highly urbanized area (concrete jungle) where heat is a major problem not to mention the added space at a minimum cost. \n7.2.4. Zamboard will cost lesser in the long run for as it ages it will last longer for it is 60% concrete, 40% Palo Verde, termite proof, fire retardant, water resistant, earthquake resistant, rot/fungi/vermin proof thus it can be best use as fascia, interior and exterior walling. \n7.2.5. Rough texture and patterns formed on the surface of Zamboard can save the owner from using expensive textured paints - the surface and it is serves as the texture itself when finished with ordinary latex paint. \n7.2.6. When painted with water proofing paints, it can be used as roofing material as well as tiling (for walls) material for toilets. Used as roof shingles it is ideal for beach houses where rust-free roofing is desired with thermal control coming as a bonus. \n7.2.7. Versatile - can be used with steel, concrete and wood construction\n7.2.7.1. As a furniture material, its natural look, plain painted or textured painted is a head turner. \n7.2.7.2 Zamboard is not just for the poor, the more expensive homes can use where its qualities and characteristics can be used to its full advantage (ie. Fascia - water-resistant, vermin/fungi/rot proof, textured ceiling).\n7.2.7.3. Zamboard\'s limitations - not to be used in areas where you want to have a very smooth surface finished as the final finish; it has limited bending angle and a little heavier than plywood of the same thickness and size.\n7.3 Innovative Construction Methods \nLow cost houses could be constructed like Lego, using pre-fabricated components such as Zamboard panels with innovative attachments, supports and reparations resulting to faster construction. Principles of quality and multi-purpose come into play-walls become dining tables, bed during the night, flooring as ceiling (underside of panel floor) roofing as walling (attic design) resulting to a truly low-cost shelter for the multitude who need it most. \n8. CONCLUSION\nZamboard or wood wool cement board is one of today\'s technological development substitute building material to improve traditional low cost housing construction. It is a versatile housing construction material that can be used in dry construtions, as sheathing in timber framed construction, in wet construction as a substitute for concrete hollow block (CHB). The board has many uses, but foremost among these are for walls and ceiling. \nThe advantage of Zamboard is that, it is lightweight and can be easily handled, eliminating the need for any special on-site equipment erection and utilization. Transporting is easy too, due to the small size of the panel. It is adaptable to any building design and is totally impervious to termites. Ultimately, at a very much lesser cost considering its inherent qualities and desirable features, one can design and build shelter for the pauper and the king with creativity and innovation. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1536, 'E2-1536AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1995, May 24) ', 'Republic of the Philippines\nDepartment of the Science and Technology\nFOREST PRODUCTS RESEARCH & DEVELOPMENT INSTITUTE\nCollege, Laguna 4031\n\nMr. Carlos A. Abarro, Jr. \nManager\nZamboard Woodwool Cement Board\n36 Dr. S.T. Varela St.\nZamboanga City 7000\n\nDear Rocky : \n\nThank you for sending at once the shredding machine. Director Bello would like first to test the machine before sending it to Candon, Ilocos Sur. \nHerewith are our corrections in your printed Zamboard brochure. \n\n1. The comma (,) after the word Zamboard should be replaced with the word (is) to read Zamboard is the housing component...\n2. The available sizes should be presented as follows : \nAvailable sizes\nThickness     Width      Length\nmm (inch)     mm (ft)   mm (ft.)\n8 (5/16)         610 (2)    2440 (8)\n10 (3/8)         610 (2)    2440 (8)\n12 (1/2)         610 (2)    2440 (8)\n19 (3/4)         610 (2)    2440 (8)\n25 (1)             610 (2)    2440 (8)\n50 (2)             610 (2)    2440 (8)\n3. The Physical and Mechanical Properties column should be placed at the back page of the brochure. The word modules should be modulus, and the board thickness and densities for the mechanical and physical properties should be consistent as follows : \nMechanical and Physical Properties\nA. Mechanical Properties\nThickness     Density     Modules of Rupture     British Standards 1975-1105     Remarks\n(mm)              (kg/m3)   (MPa)                              (MPa)\n6                     1000         10.52                               2.0 (min)\n8                      850             8.30                               2.0\n\nThickness     Density      Modulus of Rupture     British Standards 1975-1105     Remarks\n(mm)              (kg/m3)    (MPa)                              (MPa)\n10                   820             6.20                                2.0                                                  Passed\n12                   800             6.00                                2.0                                                  Passed\n19                   750             5.20                                2.0                                                  Passed\n25                   700             4.80                                2.0                                                  Passed\n50                   680             3.60                                2.0                                                  Passed\nB. Physical Properties\nThickness     Density     24-hour thickness swelling (%)    British Standards 1975-1105 (%)     Remarks\n(mm)             (kg/m3)     \n6                     1000          2.1                                                    2.5                                                          Passed\n8                      850           2.3                                                    2.5                                                          Passed\n10                    820           2.0                                                    2.5                                                          Passed\n12                    800           2.2                                                    2.5                                                          Passed\n19                    750           1.9                                                    2.5                                                          Passed\n25                    700           2.0                                                    2.5                                                          Passed\n50                    680           2.2                                                    2.5                                                          Passed\n\nVery truly yours,\n\nARTURO A. PABLO\nChief, Composite Products Development ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1537, 'E2-1537AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'ALEJANDRO MELCHOR, JR.\nExecutive Secretary\n\nSecretary Melchor was born in Manila on May 1, 1930. He currently resides in Wack-Wack Subdivision, Mandaluyong, Rizal with his wife, the former Rosario M. Panganiban and his children; Alejandro III, Michael, Elizabeth, and John. \nHe completed all his formal schooling in the United States, ie., grade school, high school, and college. He started college as an engineering student at the University of the Philippines. He was subsequently appointed a cadet at the Philippine Military Academy in Baguio. From there he went to the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md., where he graduated in 1952. He is also a graduate of various service schools both here and abroad. \nSecretary Melchor\'s record of government service has included economic planning, development and programming work at the Program Implementation Agency and the Presidential Economic Staff, establishing of our economic information reporting system, review and control of foreign-funded projects, negotiation of various loans with foreign financing institutions, assignment with the Asian Development Bank as temporary alternate Director, service in various special missions abroad, e.g., UNCTAD, bilateral negotations, attache duty in Washington, D.C., and line, staff and command assignments, both ashore and afloat. He was also Director of Studies of the UNDP - financed Transport Survey which culminated in the preparation of feasibility studies for major highway projects for which the World Bank has committed financing. Mr. Melchor has also taught mathematics at Far Eastern University, marine engineering at La Salle College and lectures at the National Defense College, the Philippine Executive Academy, and the U.P. Institute for Economic Development and Research. \nAmong Secretary Melchor\'s awards and decorations are a Presidential Award for his services as Deputy Overall Committee Chairman for the 7-Nations Manila Summit Conference, the Navy Command Badge, the Distinguished Service Star with anahaw leaf cluster, the Bronze Cross, the Military Merit Medal, the Military Commendation Medal, the Administrative \"E\" Award as an Executive Officer and the Operations \"E\" Award as a Commanding Officer. \nPrior to his appointment as Executive Secretary on February 8, 1970, Secretary Melchor was concurrently serving as Undersecretary of National Defense and Deputy Director General for Operations, Presidential Economic Staff; Chairman, PES-DND Computer Center; Presidential Action Officer for Foreign Loan-Funded Projects; and member of the Board of the National Power Corporation. He continues to hold the last three positions and serves, in addition as Chairman, Power Development Council; part-time Governor, Development Bank of the Philippines; and Alternate Governor, International Bank for Reconstruction and Development. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1538, 'E2-1538AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Melchor Alejandro Sr.\n1900-1947\n- appointed as Mathematics instructor \n- assistant professor at the COEng\n- served as College Secretary in 1930\n- head of the Dept. of Engineering of PMA in 1936\n- assigned to the Engineering Board at Fort Belvoir.\n- served as undersecretary of National Defense\n- member of the Philippine delegation to the UN Conference in San Francisco in 1945\nEducation\n- Took graduate courses at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology\n- B.S.C.E\n- Born in Ibajay, Capiz on August 9, 1900\n- Member of the UP Board of Regents\nDied on September 5, 1947\nParents : Juan Melchor\nCaridad Salmero\n- graduated in CE with highest honors in 1924\n- a brilliant mathematician, he become the head of the Mathematics Department of the PMA.\n\n1963 UP Alumni Engineers homecoming. The Engineering Bldg. was officially named Melchor Hall in honor of he late Col.Alejandro Melchor, engineering alumnus, former member of the engineering faculty and the UP Board of Regents, Secretary of National Defense in the Phil. Cabinet in exile during WWII, and a researcher whose studies on portion bridges contributed significantly in winning the war for the Allied Forces. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1539, 'E2-1539AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Melchor, Alejandro\n\nUP Engineer v. 3, no. 2 November 1955 p. 10-21\nUP Engineer v. 3 no. 3 February 1956 p. 20-22\nUP Engineer v. 5 no. 4 April 1958 p. 13-17', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1540, 'E2-1540AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Melchor Jr. \nborn on May 1, 1930\n\n- government official\n- development banker\n- naval officer\n\nmarried to Rosario Panganiban, year 1953\n4 kids - 3 sons, 1 daughter\nParents - Alejandro, Melchor Sr.\nCatalina Barza\n- Executive Director - ADB - International Fund for Agricultural Development\n- governor, DBP\n- chairman- president, Phil. Aerospace Devt. Corp. \n- Exec. Sec. Rep. of the Philippines \n- Undersecretary of National Defense\n- Deputy Director General; Presidential Economic Staff\nTitles & Honors : Recipient, Navy Command Badge\nDistinguished Service Star (w/ Anahaw Cluster)\nBronze Cross\nTitles & Honors :\nMilitary Merit Medal\nAdministrative \"E\" Award as an Executive Officer;\nOperations \"E\" Award as a Commanding Officer\nGrand Cross of Merit, - Federal Republic of Germany\nCross of San Carlos, Republic of Columbia\nCross of Diplomatic Merit, Republic of Korea\nSchooling - US - grade school to HS and Naval Academy Training\nUP Eng. Student when he passed examinations for cadet at PMA subsequently he enrolled at the US Naval Academy in Anapolis, Maryland graduating in 1952.\nExtensive Record of Government Service\n- economic planning and development with the Program Implementation Agency and later with Presidential Economic Staff\n- loan negotiations with foreign banks and financing institutions\n- special missions abroad for the government \n- attached duly in Washington D.C.\n- Director of Studies of UNDP financial projects \n- Executive Secretary in Malacanang\n- Undersec of National defense\n- Deputy director general of PES\n- Chairman of National Computer Center\n- Presidential action officer for foreign loans funded projects\n- Board member, National Power Corporation\n- Appointed by President Marcos Exec. Sec. on Feb 3, 1970', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1541, 'E2-1541AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'The University Council\n\nThe University Council is composed of the President of the University and of all instructors in the University holding the rank of professor, associate professor or assistant professor. Meetings ordinarily are held on the first Saturday of each month during the school year, but the same may be held at such other times as the exigencies of the service may require. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1542, 'E2-1542AC', '39', 'ILIO, DOMINADOR\nFaculty, College of Engineering ', 'ILIO Notes on Alejandro Melchor Sources ', '', '', '', '', 'The University Council', 'The University Council\n\nThe University Council is composed of the President of the University and of all instructors in the University holding the rank of professor, associate professor or assistant professor. Meetings ordinarily are held on the first Saturday of each month during the school year, but the same may be held at such other times as the exigencies of the service may require. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1543, 'E2-1543AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Mechor, Alejandro, pp. 343', 'Melchor, Alejandro., government official, development banker, naval officer; born May 1, 1930, Manila; married to Rosario Panganiban, 1953; four children; BS, U.S. Naval Academy; parents, Alejandro Melchor, Sr. and Catalina Barza. \n\nExecutive Director, Asian Development Bank, International Fund for Agricultural Development; governor, Development Bank of the Philippines; previously Executive Secretary, Republic of the Philippines; Undersecretary of National Defense; deputy director general, Presidential Economic Staff. \n\nTitles & Honors : Recipient, Navy Command Badge; Distinguished Service Star (with anahaw cluster); Bronze Cross; Military Merit Medal; Administrative \"E\" Award as an Executive Officer; Operations \"E\" Award as a Commanding Officer; Grand Cross of Merit, Federal Republic of Germany; Cross of San Carlos, Republic of Columbia; Cross of Diplomatic Merit, Republic of Korea. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
