(1547, 'E2-1547AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Alejandro Melchor, Jr., pp. 243', 'Executive director of Asian Development Bank, part-time governor of Development Bank of the Philippines, and chairman-president, Philippine Aerospace Development Corporation. Born in Manila on May 1, 1930; married to Rosario M. Panganiban; three sons and one daughter. \n\nEarly schooling in the United States, from the grade school to high school and naval academy training. U.P. engineering student when he passed examinations for cadet at Philippine Military Academy. Subsequently, he enrolled at the US Naval Academy in Annapolis, Maryland, graduating in 1952. Graduate also of various service schools in US and the Philippines Foreign leader grantee, 1972. \n\nExtensive record of government service includes economic planning and development with the Program Implementation Agency; later, with Presidential Economic Staff; loan negotiations with foreign banks and financing institutions; special missions abroad for the government; attache duty in Washington, D.C. director of studies of UNDP financed projects. Prior to his appointment as executive secretary in Malacañang, variously undersecretary of national defense and deputy director general of Presidential Economic Staff; chairman, National Computer Center; Presidential acton officer for foreign loans funded projects; and board member, National Power Corporation. Appointed by President Marcos Executive Secretary on February 3, 1970. Among his awards : Navy Command Badge, Distinguished Service Star, Bronze Cross, Military Merit Medal, Military Commendation Medal. \nOffice : ADB, Roxas Blvd, P.C.\nResidence : Wack Wack Subdivision, Mandaluyong, Metro Manila ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1548, 'E2-1548AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Alejandro Melchor, Jr., pp. 118-119 ', 'Alejandro Melchor Jr. \nOffice Address : Philippine Consulate Union of Soviet Socialist Republics, Moscow, USSR\nBirthdate : May 1, 1930 in Manila\nCivil Status : Married to Rosario M. Panganiban\nChildren : Four\n\nEDUCATION\nStudied in the United States from Elementary to High School\nBegan pursuing an Engineering degree at the UP but entered the Philippine Military Academy instead\nGraduated from the US Naval Academy, Maryland, 1952\nForeign Leader Grantee, 1972\n\nCAREER BACKGROUND\nEconomic analyst and consultant, Economic Planning and Development, Program Implementation Agency\nConsultant Presidential Economic Staff \nLed Philippine Delegations to special government missions abroad (including loan negotiations)\nFormer attache, Washington, D.C.\nDirector, Studies of UNDP-financed projects\nFormer undersecretary, Department of National Defense\nFormer Deputy Director-General, Presidential Economic Staff\nPast Chairman, National Computer Center\nFormer Board Member, National Power Corp. \nFormer Executive Secretary to President Ferdinand Marcos\nPrior to his appointment as Philippine Ambassador to the Soviety Union August, 1986, he was Executive Director, Asian Development Bank, Part-time Governor, Development Bank of the Philippines, and Chairman/President, Philippine Aerospace Development Corporation. \n\nAWARDS AND RECOGNITIONS\nNavy Command Badge\nDistinguished Service Star\nBronze Cross\nMilitary Merit Medal\nMilitary Commendation Medal\nOther awards and commendations\n\nIN THE PUBLIC\'S EYE\nA distinguished figure in both business and goverrnment, Amb. Melchor is likewise no novice in the diplomatic field. His experience as attache in Washington was actually a \"test-the-water\" stint for a more challenging post- the ambassadorship to the USSR. With his exceptional skills in protocol, finance, military strategy and human relationships, we could only expect the best out of Philippine-Soviet relations. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1549, 'E2-1549AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Inventory of Melchor Memorabilia of Merci Melchor for loan to Prof. Ilio for the August 9, 2000 Alej', '1. military uniform\n2. six (6) academic pins\na. American Society of Civil Engineers\nb. National Society of Professional Engineers\nc. American Military Engineere\nd. UP Astronomical Society\ne. Phil Kappa Phi\nf. UP Beta Epsilon original pin\n3. Fort Sentinel PMA publication with cover portrait of Colonel Alejandro Melchor, CE as First Dean Corps of Professors\n4. \"Col. Alejandro Melchor\" one-page write up with photo\n\nReceived by :\n\nProf. Dom Ilio\n14 Malusog St., UP Village  QC\nTel. 4351246\n23 July 2000', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1550, 'E2-1550AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Office of the Command Historian\nPhilippine Military Academy\nFort del Pilar, Baguio City (2000, July ', 'Col Alejandro Melchor\nList of Items :\n1. Diploma of Merit dtd 21 Nov 1962\n2. Photo of Col Melchor at Fort Benning, Infantry School; Awarding of ribbons to two hundred and six Combat Veterans\n3. Picture of Col Melchor together with members of the Phil Rehabilitation Commission (1944)\n4. 18 different medals awarded to Col Melchor\n5. Photo of Col Alejandro Melchor\n6. Clippings abot Col Melchor\n7. Newspaper Photo Clip of Col Melchor together with MGEN Eichelberger and others aboard a rowboat crossing a lake during West Point Point Manoeuver\n8. Citation : Most distinguished UP Alumnus, March 1949\n9. Photo of Col Melchor together with his family\n10. Photo of Col Melchor together with an American Officer\n11. Editorial Notes together with photos of his family at the Melchor Hall lobby\n12. Col Melchor togethe with other members of the Philippine Delegation\n13. Painting of Col Alejandro Melchor by Amorsolo\n14. Photo of \"World\'s Biggest Floral Sundial\"\n\nReceived by :\n\nProf. Dom Ilio\n23 July 2000', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1551, 'E2-1551AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Melchor Hall (College of Engineering)', 'The late Col. Alejandro Melchor was one of the most outstanding engineering alumni of the University. In 1925, a year after he received his civil engineering diploma, he was appointed mathematics instructor, first in the College of Liberal Arts and then at the College of Engineering where he rose to assistant professor in 1927 and served as college secretary in 1930. \nMelchor was named head of the department of engineering of the Philippine Military Academy in 1936. In this position, he worked closely with Gen. Douglas MacArthur and Lt. Col. Dwight Eisenhower in preparing the Academy\'s four-year curriculum. \nHe took graduate courses at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and was later assigned to the Engineering Board at For Belvoir. During the war he served as undersecretary of national defense in the government-in-exile of the Commonwealth. He was a member of the Philippine delegation to the United Nations Conference in San Francisco in 1945. \nMelchor was born in Ibajay, Capiz, on August 9, 1900. He was a member of the U.P. Board of Regents at the time of his death on September 5, 1947. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
