(1561, 'E2-1561AC', '40', 'SLISNET', '', '', '', '', 'E-mail', '(1997, January 8) ', 'Date : Wed, 8 Jan 1997 11:41:09 +0100\nFrom : Torrijos Delia <dtorrij@mozart.inet.co.th>\nTo : web-slisnet@enssibhp.enssib.fr\nSubject : Re : web-slisnet; discussion list for students; best wishes \n\nI have forwarded your message to the Institute of Library Science, Univ. of the Philippines, through the College of Science Library of the same University for information and action for her to relay this to the newly appointed Dean of the UPILS, Dr. Josephine Sison, so that she can in turn send SLISNET the new e-mail address where she can be contacted pending the repair of the communication system in the University. \n\nI think your idea is good. We should ask the students what topics or discussion focus they consider useful. UPILS can get the information and send them to you.\n\nBest regards, \n\nD.E. Torrijos\n\nOn Tue, 7 Jan 1997, DOROTHY WILLIAMS wrote : \n\nThe e-mail of 22 December talked about setting up a discussion list for students. I agree that discussion lists for students need to have a focus and purpose. Maybe we are not the people to suggest what the focus should be. Why not ask students for ideas? Before the discussion lists are set up the Schools could ask their senior students to identify themes which they think are important for either their own future careers or of current professional cocnern generally. The chosen theme (s) would be those which are suggested by most students. \n\nHappy New Year!\n\nReply to : \nDr Dorothy Williams\nSchool of Information and Media\nThe Robert Gordon University\nE-mail : D.WILLIAMSON@RGU.AC.UK\nTel : 01224-262956\nFax : 01224-262969', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1562, 'E2-1562AC', '', 'Philippine Association for Scientific Conservation of Cultural Property, Inc. ', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'PHILIPPINE ASSOCIATION FOR SCIENTIFIC CONSERVATION OF CULTURAL PROPERTY, INC. 128-13th Avenue, Cubao, Quezon City, Philippines\n\nPASCON is a non-stock and non-profit corporation under the laws of the Republic of the Philippines. \n\nOBJECTIVES\n\n1. To encourage the conservation of our country\'s cultural property, both movable and immovable such as important works of art, antiques, artifacts, historical structures, etc.;\n2. To promote, develop and disseminate knowledge in cultural conservation;\n3. To upgrade the field of conservation science; \n4. To promote and establish linkages among conservators and other individuals doing related work within the country and other parts of the world;\n5. To act as a clearing house or coordinating body for the various institutions and individuals engaged in the restoration and preservation of cultural materials; \n6. To collect documents, manuscripts, books and other publications and audio-visual materials on conservation, catalogue them and make them available to the reading public;\n7. To publish the PASCON Journal and PASCON Newsletter which shall contain vital information, current issues and studies in the field of conservation; and,\n8. To promote greater awareness of the significance and value of preserving our cultural and historical heritage. This will be done by means of public lectures, workshops, symposia, course offerings and published essays.\n\nFUNCTIONS\n\n1. Conduct and support interdisciplinary scientific research as they apply to conservation and to those who work for it.\n2. Undertake the publication of scientific, educational and cultural materials.\n3. Raise funds from popular support and/or conduct fund-raising activities, projects and campaign programs. \n4. Receive and take possession of, and use the proceeds and income of money deposits, trust funds, stocks, bonds, and other securities of any individual, organization, association, agency, corporation or foundation, domestic or foreign, as set aside for the purpose of the corporation.\n5. Fund totally or partially support, any government or private activity, project or program in the field of conservation.\n6. Conduct training programs, seminars, workshops, courses and conferences on conservation and related fields, directly or through an established recognized educational institution, school or training organization.\n7. Give awards, prizes, certificates, plaques, citations, or scrolls of honor, for distinction, outstanding service, and achievement in conservation and related fields. \n\nCOMPOSITION\n1. Professional working in conservation laboratories and museums. \n2. Professionals who are deemed acceptable by reason of some special contribution to conservation science. \n3. Professionals in other fields of discipline who have interest in conservation, e.g. architects, engineers, artists, history researchers, archivists, librarians, etc. \n4. Students taking courses in Museology, Archaeology, History, Anthropology, Arts, Chemistry, Geology, Architecture, and other fields of the natural sciences. \n\nPASCON shall be responsible for the creation, operations and coordination of the following :\n1. Committee on Professional Growth\n2. Committee on Trainings\n3. Committee on Publications\n4. Committee on Special Projects\n5. Committee on Finance\n6. Committee on Membership\n\nPASCON has three (3) operating branches in Manila, namely :\n1. Materials Conservation Center\nNational Historical Institute\nT.M. Kalaw, Manila\nContact Person : Engr. Nimfa T. Rubias\nConservator II and Head, MCC\nTelephone No. : 58-19-21\n\n2. Chemistry and Conservation Laboratory\nNational Museum\nOld Congress Building\nP. Burgos St., Manila\n\nContact Person : Mr. Mauro T. Alvarez\nMuseum Researcher II, CCL\nTelephone No. : 47-69-50\n\n3. Casa Manila Museum\nIntramuros Administration\nJuan Luna cor. Real St.,\nIntramuros, Manila\n\nContact Person : Ms. Amelita E. Mendoza\nSr. Historical Site Dev\'t. Officer, CMM\nTelephone No. : 49-67-93', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1563, 'E2-1563AC', '', 'ISISPHIL', '', '', '', '', '', '(1989, June 13) ', 'Dear Yoly, \n\nSubject : CDS/ISIS Users\' Group General Assembly \n\nThe UPILS is organizing the ISISPHIL (Philippine CDS/ISIS Users\' Group) General Assembly to be held on 21-23 June 1989 at the UPNEC Audio-Visual Room. During the meeting, the draft ISIPHIL Resolutions are expected to be voted upon to formalize the group and select the new members of its Steering Committee. The other main feature of the meeting is the distribution of Version 2.3 of CDS/ISIS.\n\nInasmuch as the University is represented by the UP Diliman Main Library, the official representative has been nominated by the University Librarian (Diliman). On the other hand, due to the sheer size of the University, we feel that users who acquired their ISIS through the Library should have the opportunity to attend the meeting. We therefore invite you to participate in this gathering. The registration fee is P300.00 if you will attend the General Assembly & Overview and P100.00 if you will attend the General Assembly only.\n\nEnclosed is the Registration Form. Please fill it in and return to us not later than Friday, 16 June. Payment of the fee may be made during registration at 8:30 a.m., June 21.\n\nThank you and looking forward to hearing from you!\n\nYours sincerely,\n\nROSA M. VALLEJO\nDean\n\n*includes cost of lunch, snacks and hand-outs.\n\nMrs. Yolanda Granda\nLibrarian\nUNIVERSITY OF THE PHILIPPINES DILIMAN\nEngineering Library\nMelchor Hall\nDiliman, 1101 Quezon City', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1564, 'E2-1564AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1991, May 5) ', 'Mrs. Yolanda C. Granda\nLibrarian\nUniversity of the Philippines\nEngineering Library\nMelchor Hall\nDiliman, 1101 Quezon City\n\nDear Mrs. Granda :\n\nWe, the ISISPHIL Steering Committee \'90, are happy to announce the holding of the annual ISISPHIL General Assembly on 22 June 1991 at the Asian Institute of Management, Paseo de Roxas, Makati.\n\nBeing a licensee of the UNESCO-generated Micro-CDS/ISIS software, your institution is invited to send your representative/s and participate in the proceedings of the ISISPHIL General Assembly.\n\nPart of the program will be the presentation of some of the best CDS/ISIS applications and utilities developed in the Philippines and abroad. In this regard, if your institution has developed specific applications which you may want to share with the rest of the ISISPHIL members, please send it/them to any of the Steering \'90 members together with the Registration Form on or before May 31, so we can include them for demo during the assembly.\n\nDetails of participation requirements can be found in the attached Registration Form. May we request that this be returned to us not later than May 31, together with your payment.\n\nThe Philippine Council for Health Research and Development (PCHRD), in cooperation with the Technology Application and Promotion Institute (TAPI), will also like to invite you to to a week-long training course in Health Research Database Management Using the Mini-micro CDS/ISIS Software : Designer and Operator Levels. This will be held on June 17-21,1991 at the Phil. Women\'s University, Taft Avenue, Manila. The course fee is P3,500.00 per participant. More details about the training are outlined in the attached leaflet.\n\nThank you and see you there! \n\nVery truly yours,\n\nVINA CRUZ\nChairperson', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1565, 'E2-1565AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1990, May 25)', 'MRS. YOLANDA C. GRANDA\nLibrarian\nUniversity of the Philippines\nEngineering Library\nMelchor Hall\nDiliman, 1101 Quezon City\n\nDear Mrs. Granda :\n\nWe, the ISISPHIL Steering Committee \'89, are happy to announce the holding of the annual ISISPHIL General Assembly on 28-29 June 1990 at the De La Salle University, Taft Avenue, Manila. \n\nBeing a licensee of the UNESCO-generated Micro-CDS/ISIS software, your institution is invited to send your representative/s and participate in the proceedings of the ISISPHIL General Assembly and avail of the giveaways that will be distributed to each member-institution during the assembly.\n\nThe two-day assembly will be highlighted\n\n\nDetails of participation requirements can be found in the attached Registration Form. May we request that this be returned to us not later than May 31, together with your payment.\n\n\nThank you and see you there! \n\nVery truly yours,\n\nMIMI OLYMPIA\nChairperson', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1566, 'E2-1566AC', '', 'CONSAL', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Eighth Congress of Southeast Asian Librarians\nc/o THE NATIONAL LIBRARY OF INDONESIA\nJalan Salemba Raya 28A, P.O. Box 3624, Jakarta - Indonesia\nTel. 3101411, 3101472, 3103553\nFax. 3103554; Telefax 62875 IA\n\nOur ref : 105/CON.VIII/90\n\nSubject : Invitation\n\nMr. Ruben A. Garcia\nDean, College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\nPhilippines\n\nDear Mr. Ruben A. Garcia\n\nOn behalf of the Organizing Committee of the Eighth Congress of Southeast Asian Librarians, we would like to invite you to participate in this activity. \n\nThe Congress will be held on 11-14 June 1990 and will take place at Sahid Jaya Hotel in Jakarta. \n\nAbout 500 participants from Asean and non-Asean countries, as well as local librarians, take part in this congress.\n\nThe 8th CONSAL will discuss three main topics, which are : \n\na. Library and Information services in Southeast Asia\nb. Application of automation to handle information network\nc. Preservation and conservation\n\nWe, herewith, send you a CONSAL Newsletter and Enrollment form for your perusal.\n\nThank you for your attention. \n\nYours sincerely,\n\nPaul Permadi\nSecretary\nOrganizing Committee ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1567, 'E2-1567AC', '', 'CONSAL NEWSLETTER ', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'CONSAL NEWSLETTER\n\nSecond Announcement on 8th CONSAL\n11-14 June 1990\nJakarta, Indonesia\n\nConference theme : New Challenges in Library Services in the Developing World\n\nThe Committee keeps imagining that 8th CONSAL will be carried out sooner than expected. Hectic days are becoming more routine than usual as the moment drew alarmingly closer and closer. Preparation would have seemed to run into a collision course had it not been tackled totally by all the Committee members, especially by the staff of the National Library who volunteered for duty at the Secretariat. \n\nOffice hour has never been enough for doing all the administrative work, even when it has been extended to overtime. And how time does flow. Only a month and a half remains before the D-day. In any case, the Committee is confident that everything will go smoothly as expected. Should there be any deficiencies, however trivial it may be, it is indeed unavoidable for such a gathering as colossal at this one. \n\nThe Committee estimates that about 400 participants will take part during the four-day conference. Naturally, most of the librarians and information specialists will come from countries in the Southeast Asia region, but the list at the Secretariat shows that no less than 20 non-ASEAN registrants will be involved, either as speakers or plain participants. It demonstrates that CONSAL is, a matter of fact, the assembly for librarians to strengthen and increase the already well-established regional cooperation, particularly in Southeast Asia.\n\nThe ASEAN librarians have met seven times since it was first held in 1970, to discuss and to share experiences from various perspectives of library matters, incorporating the most \"traditional\" topic, like cataloging and classification, to complex issues such as online bibliographic cooperation using the computer. The latter, as often encountered and conversed in international forums like CONSAL, is unmistakably growing more and more dominating. And the eighth convention, to be held next June, will not likely eliminate that very question, although information technology will not be the only subject to discuss. \n\nAs it has been indicated in the first 8th CONSAL circular, the Committee looks forward to receiving papers on the strategy to meet new challenges in library services, as well as those on relevant topics within the range of education and training on librarianship, manpower development, and information exchanges. Besides, there is also a topic which is recently becoming actual among librarians and archive specialists, that is, library conservation and preservation. In fact, it has become one of the priorities in the program of the National Library of Indonesia, which is evident by the establishment of the National Preservation Center and by the continuing support of several developed countries on the program. \n\nIn this second newsletter, the publisher presents the 8th CONSAL Executive Board membres (except Brunei Darussalam which is not a member yet). The names of several important figures of the Government, who act as patron and advisers, also appear in addition to the Executive and Organizing Committees of 8th CONSAL. Of significance too is a more detailed tentative program of the Congress. It is also worthwhile to note that the Congress is expected to be officially opened by President Suharto at the State Palace. This another confirmation of how keen the President\'s interest is in librarianship and all of its aspects, including book publishing and reading habit. His concern in these affairs had already been expressed earlier in his address on 11 March 1989, that was during the opening ceremony of the National Library building. \n\nNotice to all participants : Please be aware that all registration forms must be filled out and submitted to the 8th CONSAL Secretariat no later than 19 May 1990, whether the fee has been paid or not. Failure to do so may result in the participants\' names not being listed as attendees to the opening ceremony at the State Palace. However, the payment of the fee may be done prior to the start of the Congress (Sunday, 10 June 1990). Just a reminder, formal attire is compulsory on the occasion of the opening. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1568, 'E2-1568AC', '', 'CANDIDATES FOR GRADUATION', '', '', '', '', '', 'Candidates for Graduation\n1st semester, 1987-88\nWITHOUT DEFICIENCY\nGRADUATE', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1569, 'E2-1569AC', '', 'Minutes of the 256th Engineering Faculty Meeting\nHeld on June 17, 1987, Room 410, Melchor Hall ', '', '', '', '', '', 'Minutes of the 25th Faculty Meeting held on 17 June 19897 at MH 410 (GE CONFERENCE ROOM)', '(1) The meeting was called to order at 1:30 p.m. with Dean R.A. Garcia presiding. \n(2) Approval of minutes of the 255th Faculty Meeting\nThe minutes of the 255th faculty meeting held on 09 March 1987 were approved as presented. \n(3) Introduction of New or Returning Faculty Members\nThe CE Department introduced Mr. Joseph Raymond V. Flora, BSCE magna cum laude 1987 as a new faculty member. \nThe following were introduced as returning faculty members : \nME Department : \nDr. Ibarra E. Cruz, returning from special detail with PNOC-ERDC\nProf. Rodolfo Casiple returning to full-time status \nES Department : \nProf. Angel A. Alejandrino, returning from special detail with NHRC\n(4) Business Arising from the Minutes\na) Attendance \nDr. G.T. Marzan remarked that there seems to be more members absent than present in faculty meetings. He stated that something should be done about attendance to meetings. \nb) Candidates for Graduation who have Cleared their Deficiencies.\nAs requested in the previous meeting, a list of candidates for graduation as of the end of second semster 1986-87 who have cleared their deficiences is included in pages 3 and 4. All of the candidates except for Mr. Enrique Manzano have cleared their deficiencies. Mr. Manzano\'s candidacy will be discussed at this meeting. \nc) Reiteration of the UPAA and UPAE Homecoming and Reunion Activities\nThe faculty was reminded that the UPAA Homecoming and Reunion Activity will be held on Saturday, 20 June 1987 8:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. at the Manila Hotel while the corresponding activity for UPAE is scheduled on Saturday, 11 July 1987, 6:30 p.m. at Valle Verde Country Club. Tickets for the UPAA affair cost P200 and for UPAE, P100.\nd) UPAE Fourth 500 Life Members\nIt was announced that the life membership fee in the UPAE will still be P300 up to July 11, 1987. Those who register will now be part of the \"fourth 500\" life members. \n(5) Candidates for Graduation\na) Without Deficiencies\nThe lists of candidates for graduation without deficiencies for undergraduate and graduate levels were approved as presented. \nb) With Deficiencies\nThe lists of candidates for graduation with deficiencies for undergraduate and graduate levels were approved provided that they removed their deficiencies on or before 22 May 1987 with the exception of the following two candidates for BSChE whose names were withdrawn : Gener J. Lopez and Marissa R. A. Villanueva. \nMs. E.M. David reported that they have not been able to clear their deficiency with her as of May 22, 1987. \n(6) Change of Grade/Status\nThe following changes of grade or status were approved by the faculty : \nName of Student\n1. Widodo\n2. Jimenez, Hector\n3. Frondoza, Christine\n4. Vilvestre, Ingemar\n5. Forteza, Carlos C. \n6. Gargantos, Gilbert C. \n(7) Other Matters\na) Revision of Curricula to Remove Spanish\ni) BS Mechanical Engineering\nDr. MV. Hernandez, Jr. reported that of the 12 units originally alotted to Spanish, their department will use only six units for technical courses so as to compensate for the additional units due to the new General Education program. The total number of units becomes 174 units. \nThe six units will be used as follows : \n- require ME 176 (3 units)\n- include another elective with departmental approval\nThis proposal was approved by the faculty. \nii) BS Metallurgical Engineering\nDr. M.U. Ordillas, Jr. stated that the 12 units originally alotted to Spanish will be used such that there will be: \n- 3 units foreign language\n- 9 units electives\nHe also proposed that EM 10 be moved from its present place in the second semester of the fourth year to first semester of the fifth year. \nA discussion ensued during which Dr. Pacheco stated that 3 units of foreign language are not sufficient and Dr. Hernandez agreed that it is difficult to learn of foreign language in 3 units. Dr. Hernandez also added : now that some General Education units can be reduced, why add some more?\nDr. Ordillas answered that the three units of foreign language are meant to develop reading comprehension. Dr. Gopez added that based on his experience in teaching an experimental course in French in Technology it is possible for students to learn to read a foreign language in three units. Prof. M.T. Escoto, Jr. also stated that learning another foreign language could be beneficial. \nDr. Pacheco said that with the growing volume of reading material in English, there would be little time for engieners or engineering students to read material in another language.  \nDean Mena suggested that the proposal be changed instead to 12 units department approved electives. \nAfter an informal conference with MetE Department staff members, Dr. Ordillas modified his proposal to 9 units department approved electives together with the proposal to move EM 10 to the first semester of the fourth year. This was approved by the faculty. \niii) BS Mining Engineering, Industrial Engineering, Geodetic Engineering\nThe faculty approved the proposals to replace 12 units of Spanish with 9 units department approved electives in BSEM, BSIE, and BSGE. The proposals were given by the respective department chairmen. \niv) BS Chemical Engineering\nDr. Wilfredo Jose gave copies of the proposed revisions to the BSChE curriculum. After some discussion it turned out that some of the revisions such as Change in Course Title and Change in Curriculum Requirements were not directly related to the abolition of Spanish. These changes cannot be made due to the proviso that at least three years after a curriculum revision is done, there should be no changes. (The BSChE curriculum was recently revised). \nAccordingly the BSChE revisions which were approved by the faculty were :\n- replacement of Spanish with 9 units of deparment approved electives \n- institution of ChE 197 Special Topics, credit 3 units, may be repated for a maximum of 6 units\nThe Secretary was requested to check whether the BSChE curriculum required EE 3 and for EE 6 and 7. \nv) BS Civil Engineering\nProf. U.P. Ignacio, Jr. stated that the CE Department proposes to increase the number of units of CE 110, CE 131 and CE 132 from two to three units and add 6 units of department approved electives to replace Spanish. This proposal was approved by the faculty. \nvi) B Computer Science\nProf. Francisco stated that since consensus of the Computer Science Committee and additional approval by the College of Science are needed for the BCS revisions the ES Department will present its proposal for conditional approval by the faculty. \nOnly 9 units will be used as follows : \n- requirement of a second special problems course (3 units)\n- splitting of CS 195 (3 units) into two courses; CS 191 (3 units) and CS192 (3 units)\n- addition of another elective ( 3 units)\nThere were no objections to the proposal. \nvii) BS Electrical Engineering\nDr. E.F. Abaya reported that the EE Department was not yet ready with a proposal. For the information of the body he added that the Department intends to use only 9 units of the 12 units originally alotted to Spanish.\nb) Request for \"Special Faculty Meetings\"\nDr. Pacheco and Dr. S.F. Reyes suggested that informal faculty meetings be held to discuss other matters for which ordinarily there would be no time during regular meetings. Dr. Pacheco suggested institutional self-examination as a possible theme in one meeting. Dr. Reyes suggested that these \"special\" meetings be held regularly. Dr. Hernandez suggested that a discussion paper be presented at each of these meetings. \nIt was decided that the meetings be held every second Wednesday of each month with the first meeting being held on 8 July 1987, 2:30 p.m. Dr. Pacheco was requested to present a paper on \"Institutional Self-Examination\" at this meeting. \n(8) The meeting was adjourned at 3:00 p.m.\n\nADOLFO JESUS R. GOPEZ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1570, 'E2-1570AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1987, November 3)', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\n23 November 1987\n\nMEMORANDUM\n\nFor : All FACULTY MEMBERS\nCollege of Engineering\n\nFrom : The College Secretary\n\nThe 257th faculty meeting of the College of Engineering will be held on WEDNESDAY, 25 NOVEMBER 1987, 2:30-4:00 p.m. at MH 410. The agenda is as follows : \n\n(1) Approval of the minutes of the 256th meeting held on June 11, 1987;\n(2) Business arising from the minutes: \n(3) Approval of the candidates for graduation as of the end of the First Semester 1987-88;\n(4) Action on Requests for Change of Grade;\n(5) Curriculum Change Proposal (EE Dept.);\n(6) Proposal to revise procedures on the Waiver of Maximum Residence Rule Requirements;\n(7) Telecommunication Research and Service Institute Proposal;\n(8) Other matters. \n\nROMEO G. SOLIS', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1571, 'E2-1571AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'CURRICULAR REVISIONS OF BACHELOR OF COMPUTER SCIENCE DUE TO THE NEW RULE ON SPANISH SUBJECTS ', 'CURRICULAR REVISIONS OF BACHELOR OF COMPUTER SCIENCE DUE TO THE NEW RULE ON SPANISH SUBJECTS \n\n1) Removal of twelve units of Spanish from the curriculum. \n2) Reduction on the total number of units by 3 to eliminate the need to require a summer session in the program. \n3) Increase in the number of units of electives by 3. \n4) Inclusion of 6 units of one foreign language in the list of electives.\n5) Requirement of a second CS 198 : Special Problems course (requiring a total of 6 units of CS198)\n6) Revision of the CS 195 : Software Engineering course into two courses by \na) Institution of a Course\nCS 191 : INFORMATION SYSTEMS DESIGN\nFeasibility Study. Systems analysis and design. Construction and management of information systems. Documentation. Prerequisite : Junior Standing. Credit : 3 units. \nb) Change in Number, Description, Prerequisite and Credit\n\nFrom CS 195 : SOFTWARE ENGINEERING \nMetholodogies for requirements analysis. Software design, implementation and maintenance. Testing techniques. Software system documentation guidelines. Prerequisites : Fourth Year Standing. Credit : 3 units (2 hrs. lecture., 3 hours lab.)\n\nTo CS 192 : SOFTWARE ENGINEERING\nImplementation of a software project using the techniques of requirements analysis, design, testing and maintenance. Performance evaluation. Prerequisite : CS 191. Credit : 3 units (1 hr. lect., 6 hrs. lab.)\n\nNOTE : In the last curricular revision approved by the university Council on 14 February 1987, CS 62 : Software Design and Development was revised to CS 195. The instructors of CS 62 believe that it should be a 6 unit course. It was not revised into two subjects then because there was no room for an additional subject in the program revision. \n\nPROPOSED REVISION OF THE B.S. ELECTRICAL ENGINEERING CURRICULUM\n\nRATIONALE \nIn the light of the removal of the 12-unit Spanish language requirement, two lecture courses and one laboratory course are proposed to be added to the E.E. curriculum to strengthen its Electronics and Computer foundation. The two lecture courses proposed to be required are now being taught as electives in the present curriculum. \nIn order to satisfy the 15 unit E.E. elective requirement in the present and proposed curricula, two new courses are proposed for institution. In addition, an existing Special Projects course is proposed to be taken as an elective for up to 6 units. \nThese changes will effectively reduce the total units of the curriculum from the present 182 to 176, the former total before the institution of compulsory General Education courses. \n\nSUMMARY OF CURRICULUM CHANGES\n1. Courses are removed from the curriculum as follows :\nSpan. I\nSpan. II\nSpan. III\nSpan. 20\n\n2. Two existing courses are added to the curriculum as follows : \nEE 123 - Electronic Circuits II\nEE 162 - Switching Theory and Digital Logic Design\n\n3. One laboratory course is instituted and added to the curriculum to accompany EE 123 as follows : EE 124 - Electronics Laboratory III\n\n4. One existing laboratory course, EE 122, is reduced by one (1) unit to accomodate the institution and addition of EE 124. \n\n5. Two courses are instituted to serve as Electives as follows : \nEE 177 - Wire Communications\nEE 178 - Wireless Communications\n\n6. Up to 6 units of EE 198 (Special Projects) will be allowed as Electives.\n\n7. The total number of units is decreased from 182 to 176. \n\nI. REVISION OF UNDERGRADUATE COURSES\n(Change in number of units/credit)\n\nEE 122 ; ELECTRONICS LABORATORY II\nFrom : 2 units (6 hours lab.)\nTo : 1 unit (3 hours lab.)\n\nEE 198 ; SPECIAL PROBLEMS\nFrom : 7 hours a week (1 class, 6 lab.); credit 3 units\nTo : 7 hours a week (1 class, 6 lab); credit 3 units may be repeated for a maximum of 6 units\n\nII. INSTITUTION OF UNDERGRADUATE COURSES\nEE 177 : WIRE COMMUNICATIONS. - Telephony and telegraphy. Terminal equipment. Switching techniques. Traffic engineering. signalling systems. Wire transmission characteristics. \n\nPrerequisite : EE 171\nCredit : 3 units (3 hours lecture)\n\nEE 178 : WIRELESS COMMUNICATIONS. - Radio wave propagation. Antennas. Transmission lines and waveguides. Cavity resonators. Radio link design. Satellite communications. \n\nPrerequisite : EE 171\nCredit : 3 units (3 hours lecture)\n\nEE 124 ; ELECTRONICS LABORATORY III. - Construction, performance measurements and behavior analysis of pulse, waveshaping, timing and digital circuits. \n\nCorequisite : EE 123\nCredit : 1 unit (3 hours lab.)', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1572, 'E2-1572AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Changes, Cancellation, Additions in the schedule of classes, 2-87-88\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nRegistration\n2nd Semester, 1987-88\nTues. 20 Oct. - Fri. 23 Oct.\n8:00-12:00; 2:00-4:00\nFaculty Assignment \nInstruction for Registration\nSecond Semester, 1987-1988\nTues., 20 Oct. - Fri., 23 Oct\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\nSchedule of Classes\nSecond Semester, 1987-1988\n(Undergraduate)\nDepartment of Chemical Engineering\nDepartment of Civil Engineering\nDepartment of Electrical Engineering\nDepartment of Geodetic Engineering\nDepartment of Mechanical Engineering \nDepartment of Mining and Metallurgical Engineering', '', 'INSTRUCTIONS FOR REGISTRATION', 'INSTRUCTIONS FOR REGISTRATION\nSecond Semester, 1987-1988\nTues., 20 Oct. - Fri., 23 Oct.\n1. Go to your assigned adviser. Your adviser will write the subjects you are to enroll in . The student shall verify that the schedule of the subjects has no conflicts. Conflicts of schedule are not allowed. Never add or cross out a course in your registration forms without the consent of your adviser. \n2. After the U.P. Form 5-A is signed by your adviser, write your Student No. and your Enlistment Priority Number (EPN) at the upper right hand corner of your Form 5-A. Your EPN is the last three digits of your student number written in the reverse order. (For example, if the student number is 85-14093, the EPN is 390). Then go to 3rd floor classrooms (West Wing) for CS, ES, GE, EM and Met E classcards (classcards in ChE, CE, EE, IE and Me subjects may be obtained from the appropriate departmental office) and/or enlistment. Enlistment for non-engineering subjects will be done at Melchor Hall on Tuesday, 20 Oct. 1987. From Wed., 21 October onward, enlistment will be done at the Colleges where subjects needed are offered (see bulletin boards for enlistment schedules). All classcards must be filled out completely before they are presented for checking. \n3. Register in P.E. if you have not yet completed the required number of units. \n4. Secure the U.P. Form 5 at the 2nd floor lobby. Fill up the form and have it signed by your adviser. \n5. Proceed to the checkers at the 2nd floor lobby for checking and turn in your U.P. Form 5-A. \n6. Male students including aliens should register at the Dept. of Citizen Military Training. \n7. Present the U.P. Form 5 and CMT registration papers to the assessors at the 2nd floor lobby for assessment of fees. Special assessment - those with fees for billing, go to the first floor of the Office of the University Registrar, Benton Hall. \n8. Go to the Institute of Small Scale Industries Bldg. for the payment of fess. See that your U.P. Form 5 and classcards are stamped \"REGISTERED\".\n9. Register for library privileges at the Eng\'g Library. \n10. Deadline for submission of classcards to your instructors is on Nov. 3, 1987 (or one day after the last day for late registration). If you do not see your instructor before this day, have your classcard transmitted to him by the department chairman. \n\nPayment of tuition and other fees may be made in CASH, MANAGER\'s or CERTIFIED CHECKS only. Personal checks are not acceptable. \n\nADOLFO JESUS R. GOPEZ, Dr.-Ing.\nCollege Secretary\n\nLast day for GRADUATING STUDENTS\nto file application for graduation\nMonday, 16 November 1987', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1573, 'E2-1573AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'INSTRUCTIONS TO CANDIDATES FOR GRADUATION, SECOND SEMESTER, 1988-1989', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nINSTRUCTIONS TO CANDIDATES FOR GRADUATION, SECOND SEMESTER, 1988-1989\n\n1. Submit the attached application form fully accomplished to the Administrative Staff Office not later than Monday, 16 November 1987 (LAST DAY FOR GRADUATING STUDENTS TO FILE APPLICATION FOR GRADUATION). Your name will not be included in the list of candidates for graduation to be submitted to the Registrar\'s Office if you fail to submit the accomplished form.\n\n(See back - SOME GUIDELINES IN CONNECTION WITH GRADUATION)\n\n2. Submit also the following not later than Monday, 25 Jan. 1988 : \n\na. CMT Certificate of Completion or Exemption (for men only). \nb. PE Certificate of Completion for those whose Student No. starts with 80- or 81-. If your Student No. start with 82-, check first with the undersigned if your grades in PE are complete. If your grades in PE are not complete, secure also PE Certificate of Completion from SPEAR.\nc. Mine & Mill Practice Certificate for EM students and Mill Plant Practice Certificate for MetE students. \nd. Substitution papers if there are any. \n\n3. WATCH BULLETIN BOARDS FOR NOTICES FOR GRADUATING STUDENTS.\n\n4. PERTINENT PARTS OF ACADEMIC CALENDAR FOR GRADUATING STUDENTS\nLast day for graduating students to clear their deficiencies - M, 25 Jan. \n(See Item 4, Some Guidelines in Connection With Graduation)\nLast day for submitting grades : \nGraduating students - W, 24 Feb\nAll other students - M. 14 March\nFaculties meet to approve graduation - M, 29 Feb\nUNIVERSITY COUNCIL MEETING TO APPROVE GRADUATION OF 2ND SEMESTER GRADUATES - M, 21 March\nBOARD OF REGENTS MEETING TO CONFIRM GRADUATION - TH, 24 March\n\nCHECK WITH THE UNDERSIGNED YOUR CHANCES OF GRADUATING STARTING MARCH 2, 1988. DON\'T GO FOR A VACACTION NOT UNTIL YOU HAVE CHECKED WITH THE UNDERSIGNED. CLEARANCE FOR GRADUATION WILL ALSO BE SIGNED STARTING MARCH 2. \n\nPACIFICO G. BALANGUE\nStudent Records Examiner\n\n11-3-87\nUNIVERSITY CLEARANCE FORMS are available at Registar\'s Office \n\nSOME GUIDELINES IN CONNECTION WITH GRADUATION\n\n1. Students who have completed all requirements for graduation (academic as well as non-academic) within the semester and who have applied for graduation accordingly, are listed as candidates for graduation as of the end of that semester. \n2. If, however, some graduation requirements are fulfilled beyond the end of the semester concerned, then the student becomes a candidate for graduation as of the end of the succeeding semester. \n3. Definition of end of semester : \n3.1 The first semester and the summer session end on the day immediately preceding the first day of advanced registration for the second semester and for the first semester, respectively. \n3.2. The second semester ends on Commencement Day.\n4. All candidates for graduation must have their deficiencies made up and their records cleared not later than five weeks before the end of the last semester, with the exception of those in academic subjects and work in Physical Education and Military Science, in which the student is currently enrolled during that semester. \nThe attention of graduating students should be called early enough on their graduation deficiencies including possible deficiencies in CMT and Physical Education. Regarding Physical Education, please be reminded that there are appropriate Physical Education classes in the University even for the physical defective students. Students should be reminded of their deficiencies in CMT and Physical Education even before their senior year.\n5. The authority requested by the University Registrar from the University Council to add to the list of candidates up to a specified deadline refers only to students whose graduation had already been approved by the faculty. The names of these students, however, might not have been included in the list submitted to the University Council because of some deficiencies. These deficiencies pertain only to those cases where requirements had been completed before the end of the semester but the grades or results of which were inadvertently misplaced or not yet sent to the Office of the University Registrar. These requirements may be subjects already passed, removals, oral examinations, comprehensive examinations, theses and/or dissertations.\n6. A fine on late application for graduation every semester of summer term is imposed as follows : P10,00 after the deadline and additional fine is P1.00 every working day thereafter, but not to exceed 30 working days. After the 30 working days shall have elapsed, no more applications will be entertained for that semester or term. \n7. No student shall be conferred any title or degree who fails to pay the required graduation fee within the specified period set by the University Registrar. Such student may, however, upon his request and payment of the necessary fees, be given a certified copy of his credentials without specifying his completion of the requirements toward any title or degree. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1574, 'E2-1574AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'TRANSFER, SHIFTING AND ADMISSION POLICIES (adopted by the Executive Committee, 18 September 1985)', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nTRANSFER, SHIFTING and ADMISSION POLICIES\n(adopted by the Executive Committee, 18 September 1985)\n\na) Transfers, shifting and admission for 2nd Bachelor\'s degree will be allowed in both the first second semesters subject to availability of slots.\nb) Transfers from other schools into all BS Engineering programs are allowed only if the quotas are not filled up.\nc) Foreign students may apply for transfer to any BS Engineering program subject to the availability of slots.\nd) Eligibility for transfer to U.P. from a local or foreign school shall be decided by the University Registrar based on University Rules and Regulations.\ne) Students of other UP units wishing to shift to any BS Engineering Program must have studied at least two semesters and earned at least 33 units in their original unit. To be considered for shifting a student must have no failing grade, or \"4\" in Mathematics, Physics and Chemistry courses. Admission of students is subject to the availability of slots in the quotas. \nf) Shifting from other U.P. units is not allowed for students who have finished their third year. \ng) Shifting within the College of Engineering is allowed subject to the approval of the Departments concerned.\nh) Transfer or shifting to the B.S. Computer Science program are not covered by these policies.', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1575, 'E2-1575AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'LAST THREE YEARS OF THE FIVE-YEAR CURRICULUM LEADING TO THE DEGREE OF BACHELOR OF SCIENCE IN CHEMICA', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1576, 'E2-1576AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City \n\n11 June 1987\n\nMEMORANDUM\n\nFor : ALL FACULTY MEMBERS\nCollege of Engineering\n\nSubject : 256th ENGINEERING FACULTY MEETING\n\nFrom : The College Secretary \n\nThe 256th faculty meeting of the College of Engineering will be held on WEDNESDAY, 17 June 1987, 1:00 - 2:30 P.M. at MH 410 (GE Conference Room). The agenda is as follows :\n\n(1) Approval of the minutes of the 255th meeting held on 9 March 1987, 1:00 - 2:30 P.M. at MH 410 (GE Conference Room). The agenda is as follows : \n\n(1) Approval of the minutes of the 255th meeting held on 9 March 1987 :\n(2) Business arising from the minutes :\n(3) Approval of candidates for graduation as of the end of Summer 1986 :\n(4) Action on Requests for Change of Grades : \n(5) Other matters\n\nADOLFO JESUS R. GOPEZ\n\n(1) The meeting was called to order at 1:55 p.m. with Dean Garcia presiding. \n(2) The minutes of the 254th faculty meetinf held on 10 December 1986 were approved as presented. \n(3) Business arising from the minutes : \nIt was announced that the curricular revisions proposed in 253rd meeting have now been approved with modifications by the University Council \n(4) Candidates for graduation as of the end of the second semester 1986-87 without deficiencies:\nThe lists of candidates for graduation without deficiencies in the graduate and undergraduate divisions were approved as presented.\nCommenting on the short list of undergraduate students, Prof. M.B. Escoto, Sr. said that these students were probably those who did not make it at the end of the first semester. Mr. P.G. Balangue, Student Records Examiner stated that Mr. Joseph R.V. Flora, BSCE magna cum laude, MR. Abdulrahman I. Macapundag, Jr., BSCE and Mr. Ryan Alan B. Celis, BSME are bona fide second semester graduates. \nThe Secretary opined that the early final examinations for graduating students and early submission of the list as requested by Registrar has not really increased efficiency. \n(5) Candidates for graduation as of the end of the second semester 1986-87 with deficiencies. \nProf. U.P. Ignacio, Jr., CE Department Chairman stated that the following should be removed form the list of undergraduate students since their grade in CE 24 is already \"5\".\nPage 3 - 12 - Joel G. Macaraeg\nPage 3 - 13 - Michael S. Miranda\nPage 3 - 17 - Antonio B. Prado\nPage 4 - 28  - Lawrence A. Yu\nThe case of each of the following undergraduate students were reviewed by the body because their \"INC\", NIL or n.g.y. were for semesters long past the one-year period for consideration. \nPage 2 - 20 - Peter E. E. Torres - Phys. 73.1. Inc. 1-84-85 Comments/Action : Mr. Torres has a note on file regarding his grade. The Secretary was requested to send a letter to the NIP Director to clear the matter up. \nPage 5 - 16 - Enrique M. Manzano - EE 81 Inc. 1-85-86 - His instructor Mr. D. Alcasid stated that Mr. Manzano has not completed his requirements before the required cut-off date (23 Oct \'86). Mr. Manzano\'s name was withdrawn from the list. \nPage 9 - 27 - Roberto J.R. Jimenez - IE 32 Inc. 2-84-85 - Mr. E. Gonzales was his instructor. Mr. Jimenez could not have taken the next subjects if he had not completed IE 32. Perhaps, Mr. E. Gonzales has not yet submitted his Report of Completion Grade. \nPage 9 -28 - Lianie E. Jose - ES 15 Inc. 1-85-86 - Mr. Balangue reported that Mr. C. Gonzales will submit Ms. Jose\'s grade. It seems that although Ms. Jose completed the requirements before Oct. 23, 1986, Mr. C. Gonzales was not able to immediately submit the Report of Completion Grade. \nPage 10 - 35 - Patrick V.G. Lena - IE 32 Inc. 2-84-85 - Same case as Mr. R.J. R. Jimenez\nPage 11 - 5 - Raul R. Ganaden - COmm. II n.g.y. - It was asked why Mr. Ganaden is taking this subject at such a late stage. Mr. Balangue replied that Mr. Ganaden had an \"INC\" in Engl. II which lapsed and he had to re-enroll in the subject. \nPage 11- 50 - Aureen K. Uy Psycho II NIL 1-82-83 Ms. Uy is already taking Psycho 140 so she should already have a grade in Psycho 11. The Secretary was requested to write a letter to the Department of Psychology regarding the matter. \nPage 12 - 15 - Artemio I. Sumague, Jr. Span 20 n.g.y. 1-83-84 Mr. Balangue reported that Mr. Sumague\'s grade has already been received by the Secretary\'s Office. \nPage 12 - 16 - Fidel P. Vista, Jr. - Speech I n.g.y. 1-83-84 - Mr. Balangue reported that Mr. Sumague\'s grade has already been received by the Secretary\'s Off. \nThe list of undergraduate students who are candidates for graduation with deficiencies as of the end of the second semester 1986-87 was approved as amended with conditional approval for Ms. Llanie E. Jose. \nThe list of graduate students who are candidates for graduation with deficiencies as of the end of second semester 1986-87 was approved as presented. \n(7) Requests for Change of Grade/Status\nThe following requests for change of grade/status were approved by the faculty. \n1. ALINEA, Ma. Mercedes - ChE 62 - 2.0 - 1.75 - 2-86-87 - R. David\n2. DIMAANO, Jose Nelson - CE 21 - 5.0 - DRP - 1-86-87 - U. Ignacio\n3. MARAMBA, Tomas III - ChE 62 - 2.25 - 2.0 - 2-86-87 - R. David\n4. PIMENTEL, Caroline - ChE 62 - 2.0 - 1.75 - 2-86-87 - R. David\n5. TANCO, Martin K. - ES 12 - 5.0 - DRP - 1-85-86 - G. Quelapio\n6. YAP, Jimmy - EE 3 - 2.25 - 2.0 - 2-85-86 - D. Baltazar\n7. ZETA, Sheila Rose - ChE 31 - 3.0 - 2.25 - 1-86-87 - W. Jose\n(8) Introduction of New Faculty Member\nProf. LD.L. Francisco ES Department Chairman introduced Mr. Gatmahal Johann C. Ochoco, BS (Civil Engineering) magna cum laude, 1986 to the body as a new instructor in engineering sciences. \n(9) Other matters\na) West Wing Ground Floor\nIt was announced that the installation of the grills on the ground floor, West Wing is being undertaken to improve the security of the area since the whole ground floor of the West Wing now contains offices. \nDr. S.F. Reyes states that exits must be provided for particularly in cases of emergency. Dean Garcia reminded Dr. Hernandez of the need to construct a fire exit for the ME Department.\nProf. F.G.L. Reyes requested that the poor of the CE department be repaired. \nb) UPAA and UPAE Homecoming\nIt was announced that the UPAA Homecoming will be held on April 4, 1987, at the Manila Hotel (tickets P200 each with lunch and free year book) while the UPAE Homecoming will be held on July 11, 1987 (tickets P100 each for dinner).\nc) UPAE \"Third 500\" Plaque and College Recognition Rites  \nThe Dean invited everyone to attend both the College Recognition Rites and the unveiling of the \"Third 500\" Plaque of the UPAE on Sunday, April 5, 1987. The Recognition Rites will start at 1:30 p.m. at the Lobby while the unveiling will follow at 3:30 p.m. \n(10) The meeting was adjourned at 3:45 p.m. \n\nADOLFO JESUS R. GOPEZ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
