(1577, 'E2-1577AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Department of Mining and Metallurgical Engineering \nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City \n\nI. INSTITUTION OF COURSES\n1. Met E 210; ADVANCED METALLURGICAL THERMODYNAMICS. Application of thermodynamic principles in prediction of stable phases. Activity considerations. \n\nPrerequisites : Met E 17\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n2. Met E 213; RATE PROCESSES. Heat and mass transfer, kinetics and mechanisms of reactions in metallurgical systems. \n\nPrerequisite : Met E 132\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n3. Met E 217; MINERALS INDUSTRY ANALYSES. - Microeconomic and macroeconomic analysis of the minerals industry. Market conditions, structure and price formation of major mineral commodities. Government regulations and global trends affecting the mineral sector. \n\nPrerequisite : Eco. 11\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n4. Met E. 218; PROCESS SYNTHESIS. - Metallurgical process synthesis, flowsheet development and associated economic analysis. \n\nPrerequisite : MET E 136 or consent of instructor 3 hours a week (class) credit 3 units\n\n5. Met E 235; PHYSICAL CHEMISTRY OF STEELMAKING. - Design and control of iron and steelmaking processes, with emphasis on blast furnace, basic oxygen furnace, and electric furnace. Application of deoxidizers, vacuum and inert gas processes for product purification. \n\nPrerequisite : Met E 134 or consent of instructor \n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n6. Met E 257; DEFORMATION PROCESSING - Fundamentals of plastic deformation processing. Forging, rolling, extrusion and drawing. Tools and equipment. \n\nPrerequisite : Met E 147 or consent of instructor \n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\nII. CHANGE IN COURSE NUMBER AND CREDIT\nFrom : Met E 200 : Special Problems\nTo : Met E 298; SPECIAL PROBLEMS\nCredit 3 units; may be repeated for a total of 6 units\n\nIII. CHANGE IN COURSE DESCRIPTION AND PREREQUISITE\n1. Met E 232; ADVANCED EXTRACTIVE METALLURGY II. -\nFrom : Production of refining of one or more of the common metals. Special problems in roasting, smelting, refining, pyro-metallurgical and electro-metallurgical processes. \nPrerequisites : Consent of instructor.\nTo : Problems in roasting, smelting, and refining. Pyro-and electro-metallurgical processes. \n\nPrerequisites : Met E 134 or consent of instructor. \n\n2. Met E 241 : ADVANCED PHYSICAL METALLURGY\n\nFrom : Electron theory of metals, the nature of solid solutions, intermetallic compounds, solid state transformations. Mechanism of plastic deformation, creep, fatigue, rupture of metals. \n\nPrerequisite : Met E 47 or consent of instructor\n\nTo : Electron theory of metals, theory of crystal binding, solid solutions and compound formation. Phase stability. Solid state phase transformations. Microstructures and mechanical properties. \n\nPrerequisite : Met E 147\n\nIV. CHANGE IN COURSE NUMBER AND TITLE : \n1. From : Met E 290; SEMINAR\nTo : Met E 296 : GRADUATE SEMINAR\n\nV. CHANGE IN COURSE TITLE AND PREREQUISITE\n1. Met E 221;\nFrom : MINERAL DRESSING PRACTICE. \nPrerequisite : Met E 27 or consent of instructor\nTo : ADVANCED MINERAL PROCESSING I. \nPrerequisite : Met E 127\n2. Met E 222;\nFrom : ADVANCED MINERAL DRESSING\nPrerequisite : Met E 27 or consent of instructor\n\nTo : ADVANCED MINERAL PROCESSING II. \nPrerequisite : Met E 127\n\nVI. CHANGE IN COURSE TITLE, DESCRIPTION AND PREREQUISITE :\n1. Met E 243;\nFrom : HEAT TREATMENT OF STEEL - Physical metallurgy of plain carbon and alloy steel. Time-temperature-transformation diagrams and their interpretation. Concepts of hardenability. Effects of alloying elements. Industrial heat treatment practices. \n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\nTo : HEAT TREATMENT of FERROUS ALLOYS - Types of ferrous alloys. Interrelationships among composition, microstructure, service requirements and mechanical properties of ferrous alloys. Industrial heat treatment practices. Special alloys. \n\nPrerequisite : Met E 146\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\nIX. ABOLITION OF COURSES\n1. Met E 202 : NUCLEAR METALLURGY\n2. Met E 242 : PRINCIPLES OF METALLOGRAPHY\n3. Met E 233 : ADVANCED CYANICATION\n4. Met E 234 : ADVANCED PRODUCTION METALLURGY OF STEEL \n\nDEPARTMENT OF MINING AND METALLURGICAL ENGINEERING\nCollege of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nQuezon City \n\nSUMMARY OF GRADUATE COURSES\n\nI. COURSES OF A GENERAL NATURE\n1. Met E 210; ADVANCED METALLURGICAL THERMODYNAMICS. Application of thermodynamic principles in prediction of stable phases. Activity considerations.\nPrerequisite : Met E 17\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n2. Met E 213; RATE PROCESSES. Heat and mass transfer, kinetics and mechanisms of reactions in metallurgical systems. \nPrerequisite : Met E 132\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n3. Met E 217; MINERALS INDUSTRY ANALYSES. - Microeconomic and macroeconomic analysis of the minerals industry. Market conditions, structure and price formation of major mineral commodities. Government regulations and global trends affecting the mineral sector. \nPrerequisite : Eco. 11\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n4. Met E. 218; PROCESS SYNTHESIS. - Metallurgical process synthesis, flowsheet development and associated economic analysis. \nPrerequisite : Met E 136 or consent of instructor \n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n6. Met E 296 : GRADUATE SEMINAR\nCredit 1 unit per semester; maximum 3 units\n7. Met E 298 : SPECIAL PROBLEMS\nCredit 3 units; may be repeated for a total of 6 units\n8. Met E 300; THESIS\nCredit 3 to 6 units\nII. COURSES IN EXTRACTIVE METALLURGY\n1. Met E 221; - ADVANCED MINERAL PROCESSING I. - Technology of mineral beneficiation, current plant procedures, operating controls, plant research, metallurgical accounting, materials inventory and economic recoveries. \nPrerequisite : Met E 127\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n2. Met E 222; ADVANCED MINERAL PROCESSING II. - Special topics in flotation and comminution theory, mineral physics, thermal decripitation, use of radioactive tracers and ion exchange resins. \nPrerequisite : Met E 127\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n3. Met E 231 : ADVANCED EXTRACTIVE METALLURGY I - Theory, operation and economics of modern industrial hydrometallurgical processes, including electroplatingm electrowinning, and electrolytic refining.\nPrerequisite : Met E 132\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n4. Met E 232; ADVANCED EXTRACTIVE METALLURGY II. - Problems in roasting, smelting and refining. Pyro and electro-metallurgical processes.\nPrerequisite : Met E 134 or consent of instructor - 3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n5. Met E 235; PHYSICAL CHEMISTRY OF STEELMAKING. - Design and control of iron and steelmaking processes, with emphasis on blast furnace, basic oxygen furnace, and electric furnace. Application of deoxidizers, vacuum and inert gas processes for product purification.\nPrerequisite : Met E 134 or consent of instructor \n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\nIII. COURSES IN MATERIALS\n1. Met E 241 : ADVANCED PHYSICAL METALLURGY - Electron theory of metals, theory of crystal binding, solid solutions and compound formation. Phase stability. Solid state phase transformations. Microstructures and mechanical properties. \nPrerequisite : Met E 147\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\n2. Met E 243; HEAT TREATMENT OF FERROUS ALLOYS - Types of ferrous alloys. Interrelationships among composition, microstructure, service requirements and mechanical properties of ferrous alloys. Industrial heat treatment practices. Special alloys. \nPrerequisite : Met E 146 or consent of instructor 3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\n\nIV. COURSES IN METALS FORMING\n1. Met E 251; METAL CASTING. - Metallurgy of cast metals. Unit foundry operations. Sand testing and control. Melting and casting practices. Manufacture of special cast metals and alloys. \nPrerequisite : Met E 147\n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units. \n\n2. Met E 257 : DEFORMATION PROCESSING - Fundamentals of plastic deformation processing. Forging, rolling, extrusion and drawing. Tools and equipment.\nPrerequisite : Met E 147 or consent of instructor \n3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1578, 'E2-1578AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '255th Engineering Faculty Meeting', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City \n\n2 March 1987\n\nMEMORANDUM\n\nFor : ALL FACULTY MEMBERS\nCollege of Engineering\n\nSubject : 255th ENGINEERING FACULTY MEETING\n\nFrom : The College Secretary \n\nPlease be informed that the 255th Engineering Faculty Meeting will be held on MONDAY, 9 MARCH 1987, 1:30 P.M. at MH 410 (GE Conference Room). The agenda will be :\n\n(1) Approval of the minutes of the 254th meeting held on 10 December 1986;\n(2) Business arising from the minutes;\n(3) Approval of candidates for graduation as of the second semester 1986-87;\n(4) Action on Requested for Change of Grades;\n(5) Other matters. \n\nADOLFO JESUS R. GOPEZ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1579, 'E2-1579AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'CANDIDATES FOR GRADUATION\nFirst Semester, 1986-87\nUNDERGRADUATE\n', 'WITHOUT DEFICIENCY \nADDITIONAL LIST\nFor the degree of Bachelor of Science (Electrical Engineering) : (3) \n1. Luis Joseph A. Cortez\n2. Jehmel C. Ofreneo\n3. Joel Raymond S. Ramos\n\nWITH DEFICIENCIES\nI. For the degree of Bachelor of Science (Chemical Engineering) :\nName \n1. Romel G. Cortez - Ch.E. 45 - \"4.0\" - 1-86-87\n2. Angela A. Layco - E.E. 4 - \"5.0\" - 1-86-87\n\nII. For the degree of Bachelor of Science (Electrical Engineering) :\n1. Roger S. Chua \nResidency, 1st Semester, 1986-87\nPE Cert. of Completion\n2. Angela A. Leyco\nE.E. 81 - Inc. - 1-85-86\n\nNote : Deficiencies as of 8:00 a.m., Wednesday, 10 December 1986\n*With pending request for a change of grade ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1580, 'E2-1580AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'MINUTES OF THE 254TH ENGINEERING FACULTY MEETING \nHELD ON DECEMBER 10, 1996, ROOM 410, MELCHOR HALL ', '(1) The meeting was called to order at 2:20 p.m. with Dean Garcia presiding.\n(2) The minutes of the 253rd faculty meeting held on 15 October 1986 were approved with the following corrections :\na) Prof. M.T. Escoto Jr. was on special detail in Japan as USPS-NSTA researcher at the time of the meeting. \n(b) Delete the words \"by the faculty\", in terms 6 and 8 of the minutes. \n(3) Business arising from the minutes\na) Item 3 (a) \nThe Secretary announced that Mr. J. Ofreneo already has a grade in EE 81. \nb) Curricular Revisions\nDr. Pacheco reported on the progress of the curricular revisions. For the Biotechnology course ChE 202 microbiology and biochemistry are now prerequisites. He also reported that in the revisions of the B.S. (Metallurgical Engineering) program due to the general education program the abolition of MetE 155 was not approved because U.P. Baguio still requires it in their curriculum offerings. \nHe requested the Chairman of the C.E. Department to write to the School of Urban and Regional Planning regarding the institution of CE 245, in order to get feedback from that school.\nc) Request for extension of residence by Gerardo A. Remulla \nThe Secretary informed the body that Mr. Remulla\'s request for extension of residence has already been approved by the Chancellor U.P. Diliman. Mr. Remulla is presently enrolled in Shop 4. \n(4) Candidates for graduation as of the End of the First Semester 1986-87 without deficiencies\nThe list of candidates for graduation without deficiencies in the graduate and undergraduate divisions were approved. It was ascertained that candidates for graduation with honors were not underloaded during their period of residence. In Item VII-13 the words \"cum laude\" should be underlined. \n(5) Candidate for Graduation as of the End of First Semester 1986-87 with deficiencies\nBefore action on this list was made the Secretary requested action on the request for change of grade in EE 4 of Mr. F. Kiunisala III from 5.0 to 3.0 made by his instructor, Mr. A. Echevarria. After the reading of Mr. Echevarria\'s request the faculty approved the change of Mr. Kiunisala\'s grade in EE 4 from 5.0 to 3.0.\nThe faculty approved the list of students for graduation with pending deficiencies as of the end of the first semester 1986-87.\n(6) Requests for Change of Grade/Status\nThe following requests for change of grade/status were approved by the faculty. Mr. Echevarria\'s request regarding Mr. Kiunisala\'s grade in EE 4 is included in the list. \nName of Student\n1. Henson, Marie Elaine - ES 13 ULZ12 - 5.0 - * - 2-85-86 - C. Gonzales\n2. Kiunisala Frederick - EE 4 - 5.0 - 3.0 - 1 - 86-87 - Echevarria \n3. Ledesma, Lovelita - ChE 61 - 2.5 - 2.25 - 1-86-87 - E. David \n4. Limos, Rommel Jason - ChE 43 - 5.0 - 3.0 - 1-86-87 - A. Escoto\n5. Neores, Diosdado L. - CS 31 - 2.5 - 2.0 - 1-86-87 - M. Vencio \n6. Patricio Claribelle - CS 31 - 2.75 - 2.25 - 1-86-87- M. Vencio\n7. Thalla, Primavera - CE 11 - 4.0 - 2.5 - 1-86-87 - G. Zabat\n8. Trinidad, Ma. Jennifer - CE 11 - 2.5, 4.0 - 1-86-87 - G. Zabat\n9. Ulanday, Ma. Cecilia - ES 13 - 4.0 - 3.0 - 2-85 -86 - C. Gonzales\n*Cancelled\nMr. Marcial T. Ocampo\'s request for the change of grade of Ms. Jocelyn C. Flores on the basis of absences which should be excused was read to the body by the Secretary. Mr. Ocampo argued that because three of Ms. Flores\' absences were due to her employment her grade should be changed as follows : \n(11 + 3) = 14 = 30% Attendance\n90 = 27% Group Work\n90 = 36 % Final Exam\n93% = 1.50\n(old grade = 1.75)\nIt was pointed out that Ms. Flores present average is 2.05 and that if this change of grade is approved. She will be able to graduate with a masters degree. Dr. Pacheco stated that the change of grade is not due to any error on the part of the lecturer. Ms. Flores was still absent whether her absences were excused or not. Dr. Marzan said that Mr. Ocampo is still requesting the change of grade. Dr. Jose argued that this change of grade does not really affect Ms. Flores\' graduation since she is enrolled in the second semester 1986-87 anyway. Dr. Pacheco answered that if this change of grade is approved, Ms. Flores will drop her present enrollment. He also said that if this request is approved similar requests must be approved in the future. \nDr. M.G. Mena moved for disapproval of Mr. Ocampo\'s request for change of grade. Prof. M.T. Escoto, Jr. seconded Dr. Mena\'s motion. The faculty voted for disapproval of Mr. Ocampo\'s request with 20 voting for disapproval none voting for approval and the rest abstaining. \n(7) Introduction of New Faculty Member\nMr. Francis Felizardo, BS (Civil Engineering) magna cum laude 1985 was introduced to the body as a new instructor in civil engineering. His appointment was effective 1 December 1986. \n(8) Other Matters\na) The Secretary announced that the Team on Graduation Affairs of the Engineering Student Council was requesting the faculty members to go to MH 203 for picture taking this afternoon (10 December 1986) at 4:00 p.m. \nb) It was announced that the minimum contributions for the College Christmas Party scheduled on 18 December 1986, 3:00 p.m. at the 2nd floor lobby are : \n(i) Professor  P80\n(ii) Associate Professor  P70\n(iii) Assistant Professor  P60\n(iv) Instructor  P50\nThese contributions are needed to subsidize gift bags for administrative personnel.\nc) It was announced that the ACES GP\'s Comp. Soc., EMC 2 Gamma Sigma Pi and the Engineering Student Council are participating in the coming lantern parade (December 18)\n(9) The meeting was adjourned at 3:20 p.m.\n\nADOLFO JESUS R. GOPEZ ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1581, 'E2-1581AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'CANDIDATES FOR GRADUATION\nSUMMER 1986', 'CANDIDATES FOR GRADUATION\nSUMMER 1986\n\nADDENDA\nWITHOUT DEFICIENCY\n\nMASTER OF ENGINEERING\nElectrical Engineering : (1) Julius S. Algabre\nBlk. 2, Lot 93, Midland Villlage, Ma-a, Davao City\nB.S.E.E., University of Mindanao, Davao City, 1978\n\nDIPLOMA IN INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING\n1. Juancho Pablo S. Calvez\n13-A, Baco St., Quezon City\nB.S.Met.E., Mapua Institute of Technology, 1983\n\n2. Ma. Theresa R. Nazal\n99-A, Col. B. Serrano Road, Quezon City\nB.S. Statistics, University of the Philippines, 1983\n\nADDENDA\nWITHOUT DEFICIENCY\nUNDERGRADUATE\n\nFor the degree of Bachelor of Science (Metallurgical Eng\'g) :\nAs of the end of Summer, 1985 (June 1, 1985) :\n1. Joel C. Manumbas', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1582, 'E2-1582AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'CANDIDATES FOR GRADUATION\nSummer 1986\nWITHOUT DEFICIENCY\nUNDERGRADUATE', 'I. For the degree of Bachelor of Science (Civil Engineering) \n1. Edgar G. Ramos\nII. For the degree of Bachelor of Science (Electrical Engineering) :\n1. Edwin L. Allenegui\n2. Joel T. Reyes\nIII. For the degree of Bachelor of Science (Industrial Engineering)\n1. Manuel G. Mozo, Jr.\n2. Ma. Judith M. Tabuzo\nIV. For the degree of Bachelor of Science (Mechanical Engineering) :\n1. Angelo V. Dalumpines\n2. Enrico G. de Guzman\nWITH DEFICIENCIES\nI. For the degree of Bachelor of Computer Science\n1. Emmanuel M. Miranda\n2. Edwin E. Santos \nDeficiencies\nSpan 20. - no grade yet - Sum. 86\nCMT Certificate\nPE Certificate\nCMT Certificate\nII. For the degree of Bachelor of Science (Civil Engineering) 1. Robert U. Alcaraz - CMT Certificate\n2. Arturo B. Fernando - CMT Certificate\n3. Dantes S. Manuel Jr. - CMT Certificate\n4. Alexander T. Pil - Econ. 11 - no grade yet - Sum. 86\nIII. For the degree of Bachelor of Science (Elect. Engineering)\n1. Lou N. Arriola - Hum I - Inc. 2-85-86\nEE 81 - Inc. - 1-85-86\nPE Certificate\nCMT Certificate\n2. Roger S. Chua - EE 81 - Inc. 1-85-86\nPE Certificate\n3. Ferdinand O. Geluz - EE 81 - INC - 1-85-86\nPE Certificate\nCMT Certificate\n4. Ray E. Gonzales - EE 81 - Inc. - 1-85-86\nCMT Certificate \n5. Manuel J. Henares, Jr. - Residence Summer 86\nEE 81 - Inc. - 1 - 85- 86\n*As of the end of the second semester, 1985-86 (April 20, 1986)\n**As of the end of the first semester, 1985-86 (Oct. 25, 1985)\nIII. For the degree of B.S. (Elect. Eng\'g)\n6. Rodrigo A. Laguisma \nResidence Summer 86\nEE 81 - Inc - 2-84-85*\nEE 135 - Inc - 2-85-86) one is\nEE 173 - Inc. - 2-85-86) extra\n7. Jehmel C. Ofreneo - EE 81 - name not in the list - 1-85-86\n8. Mario Eusebio I. Pangilinan - Residence Summer 86\nEE 81 - Inc. 1-85-86\nPE Certificate\n9. Leopoldo L. Santos - EE 81 - Inc. 2-85-86\nEE 163 - Inc. 2-85-86\n10. Francisco R