(1588, 'E2-1588AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'PROPOSED REVISION OF THE GENERAL EDUCATION PROGRAM ', 'Appendix E, page 1\nPROPOSED REVISION OF THE GENERAL EDUCATION PROGRAM\nI. ORIENTATION AND OBJECTIVES OF THE REVISED GENERAL EDUCATION PROGRAM\nThe Revised General Education Program shall be oriented towards the development and promotion of a liberal, scientific, and humanistic Filipino culture. The Program\'s objectives are : \n1.1. To broaden the intellectual and cultural horizons of students by developing in them an awareness of the environment and a deeper insight into and understanding of man and man\'s achievements that would enable them to appreciate their Filipino, Asian, and human heritage. \n1.2 To cultivate among students a capacity for clear and independent thinking that is critical but open-minded, scientific but holistic, logical and rational, but imaginative and humanistic. \n1.3. To develop the students\' capabilities to evaluate, integrate, synthesize, and even modify knowledge as well as to discriminate between values, purposes, and ends to that they could make choices and decisions with freedom and responsibility and with universal ethical values and humanist ideals in mind. \n1.4. To develop the communication skills, whether in speech or in writing, that would enable the students to express themselves clearly, coherently, effectively, and if possible, eloquently. \n1.5 To foster a nationalist commitment that would promote the cause of attaining a truly free, democratic, just, self-reliant, and progressive Filipino society. \n\nII. COURSE REQUIREMENTS OF THE REVISED GENERAL EDUCATION PROGRAM\n\nThe Revised General Education Program shall consist of 60 units of courses distributed as follows : \n2.1 Humanities Requirements\nEnglish and/or Filipino - 12 units\nHumanities I - 3 units\nSpeech I - 3 units \nForeign Language - 12 units\nSubtotal - 30 units\n2.2. Natural Sciences and Mathematics Requirements \nMathematics I - 3 units\nNatural Science I - 3 units\nNatural Science II - 3 units\nScience and Society I or Environmental Issue - 3 units\nIntroduction to Computers - 3 units\nSubtotal - 15 units \n2.3 Social Science Requirements\nSocial Science I - 3 units\nSocial Science II - 3 units\nSocial Science III - 3 units\nSocial Science IV - 3 units\nPhilosophical Analysis - 3 units\nSubtotal - 15 units\nTOTAL - 60 units\nIII. REVISION OF GENERAL EDUCATION COURSES\n3.1 CHANGE OF COURSE TITLE \nFrom : PHILIPPINE HISTORY AND INSTITUTIONS I\nTo : SOCIAL SCIENCE I. PHILIPPINE HISTORY AND INSTITUTIONS\n3.2 CHANGE OF COURSE TITLE AND DESCRIPTION\nFrom : MATHEMATICS I. MATHEMATICS FOR GENERAL EDUCATION. \nFundamental principles of mathematics; applications. \nTo : MATHEMATICS I. Survey of the concepts, methods and applications of mathematics.\n3.3 CHANGE OF COURSE NUMBER, TITLE, AND DESCRIPTION\nFrom : NATURAL SCIENCE I. FOUNDATIONS of PHYSICAL SCIENCE I. - Basic principles and the philosophical, cultural and social aspects of physics, astronomy and meteorology. \nTo : NATURAL SCIENCE I. Foundations of physics and the earth sciences.\nPrerequisite : Mathematics I. \nCredit : 3 units\nIV. INSTITUTION OF GENERAL EDUCATION COURSES\n4.1 SOCIAL SCIENCE II. ASIA AND THE WORLD. Survey of world civilizations with special focus on the civilizations that developed in Asia.\nCredit : 3 units\n4.2 SOCIAL SCIENCE III. SOCIETY AND CULTURE. - An analytical study of the institutions, processes, and practices in Philippine society.\nCredit : 3 units\n4.3 SOCIAL SCIENCE IV. POLITICAL ECONOMY. - Principles, theories and practices with particular emphasis on the Philippine experience.\nCredit : 3 units\n4.4 SCIENCE AND SOCIETY I. The nature, logic and structure of science and its interrelationships with society from a historical perspective; science and technology in the Philippines\nPrerequisites : Natural Science I and II (for their equivalent) and senior standing\nCredit : 3 units\n4. INTRODUCTION TO COMPUTERS. Computers in society; introduction to computer programming. \nCredit : 3 units (2 lect., 1 lab.)\nV. PROPOSED ABOLITION OF A GENERAL EDUCATION COURSE\n5.1 Natural Science 3 FOUNDATIONS OF BIOLOGICAL SCIENCE \na. With the exception of the tool courses, the G.L. courses may be taken by students during their 3rd, 4th or 5th years. \nb. Any combination of English and/or Filipino may be taken provided that at least 3 units of a literature course in English or Filipino must be part of the combination. \nc. Under the present las, 12 units of Spanish are required, but if the Spanish law is repealed, the 12 units of foreign language requirements would be determined by each department according to the needs of its degree program.\nd. May be replaced by Mathematics 11 or 17\ne. May be replaced by any of the introductory disciplinal courses in physics, geology, and meteorology.\nf. May be replaced by any of the introductory disciplinal courses in biology, botany, zoology and chemistry.\ng. Choise is to be specified by each department. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1589, 'E2-1589AC', '', '', '', '', '', '1. Rationale\n2. Nature and Objectives of the NTI\n2.1 Nature of the NTI\n2.2. Objectives of the NTI\n3. Programs and Services of the NTI\n3.1 Educational and Training Programs\n3.2. Research Programs\n3.3 Extension services \n4. Organizational Structure of the NTI \n4.1 Administration\n4.2 The Advisory Board\n4.3 The NTI Divisions\n5. Staffing of the NTI\n5.1 Regular Technical Staff \n5.2 Supplementary Academic Staff \n5.3 Auxiliary Academic Staff\n5.4 Technical Support Staff \n5.5 Administrative Support Staff \n6. Facilities of the NTI\n6.1 Infrastructure\n6.2 Facilities and Equipment\n7. Financial Resources of the NTI\n7.1 1985-1986 NTI Budget\n7.2 Projected Sources of Funds\n8. Appendices', '', 'PROPOSAL FOR THE ESTABLISHMENT OF THE NATIONAL TELECOMMUNICATIONS INSTITUTE ', 'Proposal for the Establishment of a NATIONAL TELECOMMUNICATIONS INSTITUTE in the University of the Philippines\n1. RATIONALE\nNational Development. The accelerated pace of industrialization and agricultural modernization during the last decade has called for a rapid expansion of telecommunication services in the country. Being essential to the country\'s economic development, telecom facilities must undergo major improvement and expansion. Such upgrading has been programmed to be undertaken by both the government and the private carries and it will include the integration of telecommunication backbone routes, upgrading of transmission and switching facilities, and expansion of service coverage, and the introduction of new services. \nManpower Needs. In light of the country\'s developmental thrust, a greatly increased demand for trained engineers, managers, and technicians who will plan, design, construct, install, manage, operate, maintain and upgrade these facilities has been recognized by the government and industry leaders. In fact, the managerial and technical manpower requirements of the sector have already been identified and characterized in a study conducted by A.D. Little Consultants for the Ministry of Transportation and Communications (MOTC). In addition, the U.P. Foundation, Inc. also completed a study for the Ministry to establish a National Telecommunications Manpower Development Program which will provide th aforementioned manpower needs. Likewise, a 1984 UNDP/TTU survey team has confirmed that the urgent need for training will be answered through a National Telecommunications Institute. \nAt present, the manpower supply and demand gap in the telecommunications sector is being exacerbated by the outflow of experienced personnel who are lured by higher paying jobs abroad. Furthermore, the existing educational and training programs are deemed inadequate to meet present and future manpower needs. They are basically uncoordinated among themselves as well as with the sector\'s requirements. \nCoordinated Nationwide Manpower Development Program. To come up with the engineering, technical managers and technicians in step with the industry\'s needs, it will be necessary to establish a broad-based educational and training program involving the industry, the national government, the University of the Philippines and other technical institution all over the country. \nR&D and Local Manufacture. The International Telecommunications Union (TTU), a UN agency, constituted in 1983 an Independent Commission for Worldwide Telecommunication Development. One of the Important recommendations coming from the commission is that developing countries, with the assistance of the industrialized countries, 1) establish R&D institutions as \"sources of higher technological, supervisory and managerial training...\" and 2) carry out equipment development and manufacturing activities in support of their equipment requirements.\nTo this end, NTI sees applied R&D for telecommunications as one of its vital tasks. Technical assistance from Japan and other industrial nations will be sought in pursuit of the goal of local manufacture. \nFuture Asian Telecommunications Center. Over the long term, the same expertise and physical resources which are used to train Filipinos may be made available to the Asian community as well as the rest of the Third World as a center for graduate education and applied research. It is envisioned that with the collaboration of other units of the university the NTI can be the Philippine counterpart of the Asian Institute of Technology in the field of telecommunications. \nSince the U.P. is the leading engineering institution in the country and has the support of both the government and the private sector, it is hereby proposed that the National Telecommunications Institute (NTI) be put up in U.P. Diliman. The NTI will coordinate with the U.P. Electrical Engineering Department to provide the training opportunities, research and extension services in telecommunications and its allied fields. \n2. NATURE AND OBJECTIVES OF THE NTI\n2.1 Nature of the NTI\nInitially, the NTI is to be organized out of the present staff and facilities of the U.P. and of the Butel\'s Telecommunications Training Institute (TTI). It is expected that later, this activity will involve the training centers of PLDT and AFP COMMEL. NTI will coordinate its programs with telecommunication companies and various government agencies. Initially, training will be carried out by jointly offering the courses and sharing the facilities and staff of the centers. As a center of excellence in telecommunications, the NTI shall provide instruction, undertake research activities and provide extension services in the field of telecommunications and related areas. As such, it shall : \n2.1.1 Accord research and extension service as much importance as teaching\n2.1.2 Take a leading role in the development of Philippine telecommunications through the development products, processes, services and the continuing training of personnel\n2.1.3. Attract, retain and nurture highly qualified staff by providing the proper environment, facilities and incentives thereby ensuring external services, quality research outputs and training results. \n2.2 Objectives of the NTI\nAn expanded and improved national telecommunication network will only be possible with more qualified manpower. The NTI will, therefore, serve as the national center of excellence for the acquisition, dissemination and application of knowledge in the field of telecommunications. Specifically, it will work towards the attainment of the following objectives :\n2.2.1 To provide the telecommunication industry and government with competent manpower in the various specialties of telecommunications for the successful implementation of the country\'s telecommunication development plans through extensive continuing education and training programs. \n2.2.2 To conduct applied technological research and development activities in all areas of telecommunications and its related fields. \n2.2.3 To assist colleges and universities, and technical schools in developing instructions and instructional materials.\n2.2.4 To provide extension services related to national scientific and technological development.\n2.2.5 To assist the U.P. Department of Electrical Engineering to provide quality undergraduate and graduate education in telecommunications, including broadcasting and the application of electronics and computers in communications. \n2.2.6 To provide the industry and the government with experts in telecommunications and related areas, especially to identify appropriate technology to import/adapt, and/or to evaluate those being brought/introduced here.\n2.2.7 To establish an industry data bank and information system.\n3. PROGRAMS AND SERVICES OF THE NTI\nIn pursuit of its objectives, the NTI shall carry out applied research and development programs and offer the following services : \n3.1 Educational and Training Programs\n3.1.1 The initial thrust of NTI will be towards the rapid upgrading of technical manpower in the industry. Thus, the Institute will also offer short-term intensive courses leading to certificates in some specialized telecommunication subjects including : \n- Telephony\n- Outside Plant Engineering\n- Inside Plant Engineering\n- Cable Splicing\n- Line Construction\n- Station Installation and Maintenance\n- Central Office Equipment Installation\n- Telegraphy\n- Radio and Carrier courses\n- Digital Communication\n\nOther countries will be instituted later when the NTI shall have enlarged its instructional staff.\n\n3.1.2 The NTI shall assist the College of Engineering in offering top-quality undergraduate and graduate programs leading to the following degrees :\n- B S Electrical Engineering (major in Telecommunications Engineering)\n- M S Electrical Engineering (major in Telecommunications Engineering)\n- M S Industrial Engineering or Masters in Business Administration (major in Telecom Administration and Management)\n\nThe NTI shall also give assistance for the production of educational materials to complement its mission, e.g. textbooks, primers, manuals, films. \n\nThis assistance shall be in the form of NTI staff who shall be allowed to lecture in the college, use of NTI facilities, and through the provision of scholarships, fellowships, research and training assistance. \n\nOver the long term, the NTI shall extend assistance to other engineering and technical schools in the country. \n\n3.2 Research Programs\n\nThe opportunities for doing meaningful applied research in telecommunications, electronics and computers are especially significant in light of country\'s present economic situation. The NTI shall undertake basic and applied research, the latter being directed at meeting the country\'s needs in the following areas :\n\nTelecommunications. This will include research work in all aspects of telecommunications as well as related fields. Studies on the problems of the industry will also be done. Research and development activities in telecommunication may be concerned with the following specific technologies : \n- Local Area Networks for office or Factory Automation\n- Locally developed and built teletype/telex machines\n- CAD Computer programs for telecomm design\n- Teaching Aids - e.g. PCM trainers, transmission line simulation, multiplex equipment\n- Microprocessor-based communications test equipment - e.g. data analyzers, transmission line test sets\nApplied Electronics. This area covers such aspects of electronic technology as computers, consumer electronics, educational and industrial equipment as these may relate to communications. \nTechnology and Public Policy. There will also be research activities on the effects/impact of telecommunications and related technologies on society and public policy. \n\n3.3. Extension Services \n\nIn keeping with the mission of transmitting university skills and resources to the country at large, the NTI shall also render various types of related extension services such as the following : \n- Consultancy\n- Technology Assessment and Forecasting \n- Industrial Contract Research\n- Public Policy Advising\n- Technical Information\n- Continuing Education\n- Industrial Services\n- Engineering Support\n\n4. ORGANIZATIONAL STRUCTURE OF THE NTI\n\nThe NTI shall adopt the organizational structure shown in diagram A.\n\n4.1 Administration\n\nThe NTI shall be governed by the rules and regulations of the University of the Philippines. However, policies, plans and program directions will be formulated by the Advisory Board.\n\nThe chief executive officer of the NTI shall be the Executive Director who shall be appointed by the President of the University of the Philippines upon recommendation of the members of the Advisory Board. The Executive Director shall have a term of five (5) years. \n\nThe Executive Director shall be assisted by an Associate Director and by the Assistant Directors of the four (4) major divisions - Administrative, Extension and Support Services, Research and Training. \n\n4.2 The Advisory Board\n\nThe NTI shall have an Advisory Board which shall fulfill the following functions : \n\n4.2.1 To set the policies and program directions\n4.2.2 To help in assessing programs and performance\n4.2.3 To help in generating resources for its various programs\n4.2.4 To help in developing linkages with various Philippine and external institutions and agencies. \nThe NTI\'s Advisory Board shall be composed of representatives from the following entities : \n- University of the Philippines \n- Ministry of Transportation and Communications\n- National Telecommunications Commission\n- National Economic Development Authority\n\nThe NTI Executive Director shall be an ex-officio member of the NTI Advisory Board. THe Minister of Transportation and Communications shall be the Chairman of the Advisory Board. \n\n4.3 The NTI Divisions\n\nThe four (4) major NTI divisions are as follows : \n\n4.3.1 Administrative. This division shall manage and coordinate all non-academic affairs of the NTI such as providing internal and personnel services. It shall regulat finances, make budget allocations, and handle the procurement of supplies and equipment needed by the Institute. \n4.3.2 Extension and Support Services. This division shall be responsible for the continuing education programs, for industrial and related services, for the technical information system of the NTI, and for providing consultancy services. \n4.3.3 Research. This division shall take charge of all research and development activities as in equipment R&D in the industry and related fields as well as assist in the development of course materials for use in training. \n4.3.4 Training. This division shall undertake all the educational and training programs of the NTI. It shall also handle student affairs and provide counselling. \n\n5. STAFFING OF THE NTI\n\nThe initial instructional, research and extension services staff of the NTI shall be composed of faculty members of the EE Department of the University of the Philippines, trainors from the training centers of BUTEL, AFP COMMEL and PLDT and lecturers from the industry. The service of expatriate experts shall be obtained through bilateral and multilateral assistance. \n\nEventually, the NTI shall have an expanded staff consisting of the following categories : \n\n5.1 Regular Technical Staff \n\nThis will be composed of regular faculty members and researchers with the minimum qualification of an MS degree (or its equivalent in work experience) for those who will handle the advanced level subjects and carry out applied research work. These staff members may hold joint appointments with the College of Engineering. Another group of the regular staff will be made up of technical trainors whose qualifications shall include an engineering degree and/or extensive industrial experience. \n\n5.2 Supplementary Academic Staff \n\nThis will be composed of non-regular teaching and/or research staff members who shall supplement NTI\'s regular technical staff from time to time. The members of this staff shall have the same minimum qualification as the regular technical staff. They may be research fellows, visiting professors, professorial lecturers or adjunct researchers. \n\n5.3 Auxiliary Academic Staff\n\nThis will be composed of full-time graduate students of the NTI with appointments as Teaching or Research Assistants, and with corresponding teaching, research or extension service duties. \n\n5.4 Technical Support Staff\n\nThis will be composed on non-technical personnel with some technical training and appointments such as research technician, laboratory technician, computer technician, electronic technician, laboratory attendant, machinist, draftsman, technical librarian, carpenter, etc. \n\n5.5 Administrative Support Staff \n\nThis will be composed of non-academic personnel with appointments such as administrative officer, administrative assistant, senior clerk, accountant, property custodian, messenger, clerk-typist, etc. \n\n6. FACILITIES OF THE NTI\n\nThe initial facilities of the NTI shall consist of the present facilities that can be jointly used at the training centers of PLDT, BUTEL, AFP COMMEL and at the U.P. College of Engineering. The latter organizations have signified their willingness to permit equipment, instruments, and space necessary for the conduct of training to be made available to the Institute. \n\nHowever, to carry out its expanded programs effectively, the NTI will need the following infrastructure, facilities and equipment : \n\n6.1 Infrastructure\n\nIn addition to the existing TTI facilities in Valenzuela, Bulacan, the proposed NTI complex requires the construction of the following buildings/facilities : \n- Training center\n- Administrative building\n- Library\n- Multi-purpose hall \n- Housing\n- Sports/recreational area\n- Motor pool\n\nIt is expected that a 10-hectare site can be found in the U.P. Diliman Campus, either in the proposed commercial-office complex north of Marcos Avenue or in the south section of the campus adjacent to the Science Community Complex. \n\n6.2 Facilities and Equipment\n\nThe NTI will also require the following types of facilities and equipment : \n- Aerial cable plant\n- Underground plant\n- Subscriber plant\n- Tools and equipment for outside/inside plant\n- Central office equipment\n- Transmission system\n- Telegraph/telex/data system\n- Data communications equipment\n- Broadcasting equipment\n- Office equipment\n- Shop equipment\n- Teaching aids\n\nSome of these facilities are already in the Telecommunications Training Institute, except for the data communications and broadcasting equipment, office and shop equipment and with the administration of TTI by U.P. would ease the start up of NTT\'s operations. \n\n7. FINANCIAL REQUIREMENTS AND RESOURCES OF THE NTI\n\nIn order to make an immediate and substantive impact on its sectors the education, training, extension-service, and research activities of NTI will require a substantial amount of funds, facilities and personnel. The projected initial working budget of NTI is outlined below (section 7.1). The corresponding sources of support have also been identified (section 7.2). ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1590, 'E2-1590AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, August 22) Special Meeting ', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nMEMORANDUM\n\nFor : MEMBERS OF THE FACULTY\nCollege of Engineering\n\nFrom : The Secretary\n\n1. A special meeting of the faculty of the College of Engineering will be held on WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 28, 1985 at 1:00 p.m. at Rm. 410 (G.E. Conference Room).\n2. The agenda is as follows : \na) Discussion of the General Education Program;\nb) Discussion on the establishment of the National Telecommunications Institute (NTI);\nc) Other matters.\n3. Copies of the NTI proposal and some materials on the GE program are with the department chairmen.\n4. You are urged to discuss both the GE program and the NTI proposal at the department level prior to the faculty meeting. \n\nADOLFO JESUS R. GOPEZ, Dr_Ing. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1591, 'E2-1591AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, March 27) Minutes of the 246th Engineering Faculty Meeting Held on March 27, 1985, ROOM 410, ', '(1) The Dean called the meeting to order at 2:20 p.m.\n(2) The minutes of the 245th faculty meeting were approved as presented. \n(3) Business arising from the minutes : \n(a) It was pointed out that the suggestion as listed under Item 4 of the minutes (the faculty should be furnished with the list of candidates well before the meeting so that these candidates can be approved en masse during the meeting) cannot be implemented for this meeting due to lack of time, since the date of faculty meeting was advanced two weeks to accommodate the early graduation this year. \n(4) The faculty approved the candidates for graduation as of the end of the second semester, 1984-85. The following candidates, who carried 14 units of load for one semester, were recommended for honors : Jocelyn de Luna (B.S.Ch.E) and Stella Maris Fajardo (B.S.I.E)\n(5) The faculty approved the following requests for change of grades : \nName of Students\n1. Eduardo D.R. Bondoc - Shop 4 - 5.0 - 3.0 - 1st Sem. 84-85 - B. Malabed\n2. Josef Isidro - C.E. 53 - 4.0 - 3.0 - 1st Sem. 84-85 - G. Zabat\n3. Anson Lee - C.E. 53 - 2.5 - 1.75 - 1st Sem. 84-85 G. Zabat\n(6) The Dean reported that he already forwarded to the Office of the Chancellor the official comments of the College of Engineering on the proposed revised General Education Program as discussed and agreed by the College Executive Committee.\n(7) In connection with the coming Diamond Jubilee celebration an open house is scheduled for June 10-13, 1985 by each department. The open house will feature exhibits of faculty research work and student projects. The alumni reunion will be on June 13, 1985. \n(8) Other matters : \n(a) Dean Mean invited the faculty to the get-together for our graduates on April 14, 1985 at 1:30 p.m. This affair will be held at the second floor lobby.\n(b) It was agreed that the faculty should be reminded of the importance of proper filling out of the dropping slip, especially the \"class standing\". This information is valuable for future decisions on students graduating with honors. \nThere being no further business the meeting was adjourned at 4:00 p.m. \n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1592, 'E2-1592AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, June 28) The 247th meeting of the faculty of the College of Engineering ', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nMEMORANDUM\n\nFor : Members of the Faculty\nCollege of Engineering \n\nFrom : The Secretary\n\n1. The 247th meeting of the faculty of the College of Engineering will be held on WEDNESDAY, JUNE 26, 1985 at 2:00 p.m. at Room 410 (G.E. Conference Room) \n2. The agenda is as follows : \n(a) Approval of the minutes of the 246th meeting on March 27, 1985;\n(b) Business arising from the minutes;\n(c) Approval of the candidates for graduation as of the end of Summer, 1985;\n(d) Approval of requests for change of grades;\n(e) Other matters.\n\nMIGUEL D. ESCOTO\nSecretary ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1593, 'E2-1593AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Summer 1985\nCandidates for Graduation', 'Addenda\n\nCANDIDATES FOR GRADUATION\nSummer 1985\n\nWITHOUT DEFICIENCY GRADUATE\n\nMASTER OF ENGINEERING (ENGINEERING EDUCATION) : \n1. Carmencita E. Vidamo\nBangkal Diversion Road, Talomo Dist., Davao City\nB.S.Ch.E., University of Mindanao, Davao City, 1977\n\nWITH DEFICIENCY\nUNDERGRADUATE\n\nFor the degree of Bachelor of Science (Industrial Engineering) : \n1. Gertrudes C. Tanay - PI 100 - Inc. - 1-84-85', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1594, 'E2-1594AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, March 21) ', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines \nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nMEMORANDUM FOR : Members of the Faculty\nCollege of Engineering\n\nFROM : The Secretary\n\n1. The 246th meeting of the faculty of the College of Engineering will be held on Wednesday, March 27, 1985 at 2:00 p.m. at Room 410 (G.E. Conference Room).\n2. The agenda is as follows : \na) Approval of the minutes of the 245th meeting on December 12, 1984;\nb) Business arising from the minutes;\nc) Approval of the candidates for graduation as of the end of the 2nd Semester, 1984-85;\nd) Approval of requests for change of grades; \ne) Report on the College\'s stand on the G.E. program;\nf) Report on the Diamond Jubilee celebrations; \ng) Other matters. \n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1595, 'E2-1595AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, December 12) Minutes of the 245th Engineering Faculty Meeting held on December 12, 1984, Room', '(1) The Dean called the meeting to order at 2:20 p.m.\n(2) The minutes of the 244th faculty meeting were approved as presented. \n(3) Business arising from the minutes : \n(a) On Item 3 (b) : With regards to the Physics enrolment Dr. Liongson pointed out that some 30 students in Computer Science were not able to get classcards. According to Prof. Mayor the enrolment in Chemistry courses is the larger problem this time. \n(b) On Item (5) : In connection with the coming diamond jubilee of the College the Dean announced that the kick-off ceremonies to launch the jubilee will be held on January 23, 1985. At this time pledges of the alumni for the College will be presented. \nVarious committees to take charge of the various activities during the year have already been formed. \n(4) The faculty approved the candidates for graduation as of the end of the first semester 1984-85. It was suggested that in the future the faculty should be furnished with a list of the candidates well ahead of time and that these candidates will be approved en masse during the meeting. \n(5) The faculty approved the following requests for change of grades : \n1. GAERLAN, Roland U. - E.S. 12 - 1.5 - 1.5 - 1st sem. 84-85 - L. Regalado\n2. LOPEZ, Gener J. - ChE. 31 - 5.0 - DRP - 1st sem. 84-85 - W. Jose\n3. ZARCO, Mark Albert H. - C.E. 53 - 4.0 - 1.5 - 2nd sem. 82-83 - S. Reyes\n\n(6) It was agreed that future faculty meetings will be held on FRIDAYS. There being no further business the meeting was adjourned at 3:00 p.m. \n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
