(1596, 'E2-1596AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1985, February 7) Discussion of the proposed revision of the General Education program', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nMEMO FOR : Members of the Faculty\nCollege of Engineering\n\nFROM : The Secretary\n\n1. There will be a meeting of the faculty of the College on Thursday, February 14, 1985, at 2:00 p.m. at Room 410 (G.E. Conference Room) Melchor Hall. \n2. Item of the Agenda : Discussion of the proposed revision of the General Education Program (see attached)\n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary\n\nTHE FACULTY OF ARTS AND SCIENCES\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDr. Irene R. Cortes\nChairman, University Curriculum Committee\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nThrough : Dr. Paz G. Ramos, Vice-Chancellor for Academic Affairs, U.P. Diliman and Dr. Emeteria P. Lee, University Registrar, U.P. Diliman\n\nDear Dr. Cortes : \n\nOn behalf of the Arts and Sciences Council which is responsible for reviewing and recommending the institution, revision and abolition of General Education courses, we would like to recommend the adoption of the attached proposal for a Revised General Education Program which was approved by the Faculty of the former College of Arts and Sciences on August 31, 1983 and endorsed by the Arts and Sciences Council during its 3rd Meeting on January 4, 1985. \n\nWe would appreciate it if this curricular proposal could be taken up by the University Curriculum Committee during its meeting on January 14, 1985. \n\nPABLO K. BOTOR, Dean, College of Arts and Letters\nROGER POSADAS, Dean, College of Science\nLESLIE E. BAUZON, Dean, College of Social Sciences and Philosophy\n\nCOLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines \nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nPROPOSED REVISION OF THE GENERAL EDUCATION PROGRAM\n\nI. PROPOSED ORIENTATION AND OBJECTIVES OF THE REVISED GENERAL EDUCATION PROGRAM\n\nThe Revised General Education Program shall be oriented towards the development and promotion of a liberal, scientific, and humanistic Filipino culture. The Program\'s objectives are : \n1.1. To broaden the intellectual and cultural horizons of students by developing in them an awareness of the environment and a deeper insight into and understanding of man and man\'s achievements that would enable them to appreciate their Filipino, Asian, and human heritage. \n1.2. To cultivate among students a capacity for clear and independent thinking that is open-minded but critical, holistic but scientific, imaginative but logical and rational. \n1.3. To develop the students\' capabilities to evaluate, integrate, synthesize, and even modify knowledge as well as to discriminate between values, purposes, and ends so that they could make choices and decisions with freedom and responsibility and with universal ethical values and humanist ideals in mind. \n1.4. To develop the communication skills, whether in speech or in writing, that would enable the students to express themselves clearly, coherently, effectively, and if possible, eloquently. \n1.5. To foster a nationalist commitment that would promote the cause of attaining a truly free, democratic, just, self-reliant, and progressive Filipino society. \n\nII. PROPOSED COURSE REQUIREMENTS OF THE REVISED GENERAL EDUCATION PROGRAM\n\nThe Revised General Education Program shall consist of 54 units of courses distributed as follows : \n\n2.1 Humanities Requirements\nEnglish and/or Filipino - 12 units\nHumanities I - 3 units\nSpeech I - 3 units\nForeign Language - 12 units\nSubtotal - 30 units\n\n2.2. Natural Sciences and Mathematics Requirements\nMathematics - 3 units\nNatural Science I - 3 units\nNatural Science II - 3 units\nScience and Society I or Environmental Issues - 3 units\nSubtotal - 12 units\n\n2.3. Social Sciences Requirements\nSocial Science I - 3 units\nSocial Science II - 3 units\nSocial Science III - 3 units\nSocial Science IV - 3 units\nSubtotal - 12 units\nTOTAL - 54 units\n\nIII. PROPOSED REVISION OF GENERAL EDUCATION COURSES\n3.1 CHANGE OF COURSE TITLE\nFROM : PHILIPPINE HISTORY AND INSTITUTION I\nTO : SOCIAL SCIENCE I. PHILIPPINE HISTORY AND INSTITUTIONS \n\nFROM : INTRODUCTION TO ASIAN CIVILIZATIONS\nTO : SOCiAL SCIENCE II. INTRODUCTION TO ASIAN CIVILIZATIONS\n\n3.2 CHANGE OF COURSE TITLE AND DESCRIPTION\nFROM : MATHEMATICS I. MATHEMATICS FOR GENERAL EDUCATION - Fundamental principles of mathematics; applications.\nTO : MATHEMATICS I. -- Survey of the concepts, methods, and applications of mathematics. \n\n3.3 CHANGE OF COURSE NUMBER, TITLE AND DESCRIPTION\nFROM : NATURAL SCIENCE I. FOUNDATIONS OF PHYSICAL SCIENCE I. Basic principles and the philosophical, cultural and social aspects of physics, astronomy and meteorology. \nTO : NATURAL SCIENCE I. Foundations of physics and the earth sciences. \nPrerequisite : Mathematics I\nCredit : 3 units\nFROM : NATURAL SCIENCE 2. FOUNDATIONS OF PHYSICAL SCIENCE II. The basic concepts of inorganic, organic, and biological chemistry; the basic principles of earth sciences. \nTO : NATURAL SCIENCE II. Foundations of chemistry and the life sciences. \nPrerequisite : Natural Science I\nCredit : 3 units\n\nIV. PROPOSED INSTITUTION OF GENERAL EDUCATION COURSES\n4.1 SOCIAL SCIENCE III. PHILIPPINE SOCIETY AND CULTURE. An analytical study of the institutions, processes, and practices in Philippine society. Credit : 3 units\n4.2 SOCIAL SCIENCE IV. THE PHILIPPINE POLITY. Principles, theories and practices. Credit : 3 units\n4.3 SCIENCE AND SOCIETY I. The nature, logic and structure of science and its interrelationships with society from a historical perspective; science and technology in the Philippines. \nPrerequisites : Natural Science I and II (or their equivalents) and senior standing. Credits : 3 units\n\nV. PROPOSED ABOLITION OF A GENERAL EDUCATION COURSE \n5.1 Natural Science 3 : FOUNDATIONS OF BIOLOGICAL SCIENCE \n\nADOPTED BY THE FACULTY OF THE COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCES DURING ITS MEETING HELD ON 31 AUGUST 1983. \n\nReport of the Committee on a System-Wide General Education Program\n\nAfter studying and reviewing past studies and programs on the subject, the Committee on a System-Wide General Education Program decided to \"start anew in a manner of speaking, to steer clear of the various special concerns which naturally stem from academic prejudices, ideological interests as well as personal biases and insecurities. Thus oriented, the Committee hoped it could be creative rather than reactive, integrative rather than specialized and isolated. It could cover global rather than narrow areas of thought, and address the total person of the learner rather than a limited number of his faculties. \n\nCONCEPT\n\nGeneral education, as conceived of by the committee, has no intention of providing the learner with any one specific orientation or philosophy or ideology. It means rather to expose him to alternative, even competing, view-points and methodologies, upon which he can make analytics differentiations and whose significance and worth as well as inadequacies and limitation he can examine and evaluate in the light of universally accepted principles. It aims to place the student in the midst of problematic settings and situations that will call into play the exercise of his total powers, such as mentioned in the list of objectives, and his use of wide-ranging data and information available from relevant fields of knowledge, and areas of human endeavor in historical perspective. It intends to bring him to a conscious exercise and practice of available cognitive styles and strategies to seek answers to questions and solutions to problems, and even hit upon new knowledge, while integrating for himself forms and interpretations, theories and explanations, decisions and policies in his studies in the arts and sciences. \n\nIn short, the committee\'s conception of general education lays stress on how to think, feel, and do integratively, not what to think, feel, and do in isolated and piecemeal fashion. \n\nGeneral education should train students to be able to learn how to learn and to think of themselves as individuals and as members of society. \n\nUnder this concept, general education is that component of a university education that helps the student actualize his potentials as a thinking, doing, and feeling individual and member of society by heightening his awareness, consciousness, and exercise of the various modes of apprehending reality in all its complexity, diversity, relativity and flux. \n\nOBJECTIVE\n\n1. Cultivating and integrating the intuitive and analytic faculties. \n2. Developing the abilities to discriminate between what is unique, particular, and/or concrete, on the one hand and what is general and abstract, on the other, as well as to perceive the relationship between them. \n3. Developing side by side the participant\'s sense of involvement and the observer\'s critical detachment. \n4. Developing recognition and appreciation of the interaction between what is visible and what is inward. \n5. Instilling appreciation and respect for process and the dynamic continuities and discontinuities of the past, the present, and the future. \n6. Deepening and strengthening the individual\'s relationship with himself, with others, with the physical world, and the cosmos. \n7. Developing a sense of and appreciation for the underlying connection between and among the empirical, logical, moral and aesthetic domains. \n8. Developing a sense of wholeness in all of human endeavor.\n\nOutside of the enumerated objectives, themselves values basic to general education, no specification is made of values and attitudes. The committee is of the opinion that, in learning how to perceive and structure the reality both within and outside him, the learner is at the same time grasping, - in fact, more genuinely - the values and attitudes that characterize the fullness of human dignity, his full worth as a person. the committee stands by the view that the full worth of a person lies in his freedom as well as the fullest possible exercise of all his faculties. Freedom is envisioned as much a goal as a climate for learning which it is incumbent upon the university and the classroom to provide. It is the kind of freedom that allows the full exercise of one\'s rational powers in self-teaching, self-learning, self-thinking. It assures that the individual will be free to act judiciously and responsibly, as, in the process of growing and unfolding, he is released from the tyranny of unexamined impressions, naive preconceptions, irrelevant compulsions, and blind caprice; he is freed from mindless involvement in a problem by its transformation into a solution; he is liberated from the entrapment of mere facts to a perception of them in the light of some structured meaning. For it is only through this liberating process that he can be clear-seeing enough to grasp truth. It is this clear-eyed discernment of the truth which, in turn, will render him humble, honest, and far-seeing. And above, and best of all because then unhampered by the lettesr of self-interest, critical and fearless. \nThe integrative purpose of this conception is evident in the alignment of persistent dichotomies in thinking and behaving, which, under the listed objectives are seen as continuous and interacting. Broken down, the entire conception may be grouped under three categories. \nThe Over-all Concept : \n1. thinking, feeling, doing (willing)\n2. individual and member of society\n3. various modes of apprehending reality\n4. reality in all its complexity, diversity, relativity, and flux.\nThe Learner : \n1. thinking, feeling, doing\n2. intuitive, and analytic faculties\n3. participant\'s sense of involvement and observer\'s critical detachment\n4. relationship with himself, with other men, the physical world, and the cosmos\nThe Object of Learning : \n1. the unique, particular, and/or concrete, on the one hand and the abstract and general, on the other; the relationship between them \n2. interaction between what is visible and what is inward\n3. appreciating, and respecting process and the dynamic continuities and discontinuities of the past, the present, and the future\n4. connection between and among the empirical, logical, moral, and aesthetic domains\n5. a sense of wholeness in all of human endeavor\nRECOMMENDATIONS\nI. Courses\nA. Tool Courses - 12 units\nEnglish or Filipino - 6 units\nSpeech - 3 units\nPhilippine History - 3 units \nThe above-mentioned tool courses are existing courses in the current G.E. program. The committee feels however, that they should be restructured so as to be supportive and reinforce the concepts and objectives of general education as stated in this report. \nB. Natural Sciencews and Mathematics - 9 units\nG.E. Mathematics - the nature, logic and structure of Mathematics and its interrelationship with society from a historical perspective - 3 units\nG.E. Natural Science I and II - the nature, logic and structure of natural sciences and their interrelationship with society from a historical perspective - 6 units\nI. Physics and the Earth Sciences\nII. Chemistry and the Life Sciences \nC. Social Sciences - 9 units\nPhilosophical Analysis\nLogic, epistemology and ethics - 3 units\nG.E. Social Science I - Social Change : Theories and Models of Social Change : An interdisciplinary course with inputs from the various social science disciplines - 3 units\nG.E. Social Science II - Researches and case studies on social change - 3 units \nD. Humanities - 9 units\nG.E. Humanities I - Images of Man and Reality in Literature, Comparative Study of the Various Perceptions of Man and Reality as Reflected in Selected World Masterpieces through the Ages - 3 units\nG.E. Humanities II - The Arts - Images of Man and Reality as reflected in the masterpieces of art in the world - 3 units\nG.E. Humanities III - Perceptions and Values in the Discourse, Methods, Products, and Results of the Arts & the Sciences - 3 units\nE. Practicum - 3 units\nG.E. Practicum - Development of sensitivity to people, responsiveness to their needs, and critical awareness of social realities\nTotal Number of Units - 42 units\nIII. Administration\nCreation of a System-Wide General Education Center \nThe Committee strongly recommends the creation of a General Education Center under the Office of the University President. We believe that general education has primacy over all aspects of education and therefore is deserving of centralized concern, decision-making, research and implementation.\nThe functions of this proposed General Education Center are : \n1. Selection and appointment of a core faculty.\n2. Recruitment and development of faculty members.\n3. Curriculum development. \n4. Preparation of instructional materials and teaching aid. \n5. Monitoring and evaluation. \n6. Research\n7. Organizing and sponsoring workshops, seminars and conferences\n8. Publications\n\nThe proposed organizational structure of the General Education Center is as follows :\nDirector\nAdministrative Staff\nFaculty\nServices\nTraining \nCurriculum\nMonitoring\n\nThere are three anticipated problems of the Center : \n1. Faculty incentives\n2. Faculty status : Permanent or affiliate (e.g. loyalty to mother unit)\n3. Funding\n4. Physical plant and facilities \n\nMembers of the Committee\nProf. Ines Belleza\nDepartment of Mathematics\nCollege of Arts & Sciences\nU.P. Diliman\n\nAssoc. Prof. Ponciano Bennagen\nDepartment of Anthropology\nCollege of Arts & Sciences\nU.P. Diliman\n\nAssoc. Prof. Lourdes de Castro\nDepartment of Humanities\nCollege of Arts & Sciences\nU.P. Visayas\n\nProf. Concepcion Dadulfalza\nDepartment of English\nCollege of Arts & Sciences\nU.P. Diliman\n\nProf. Horacio R. Estrada\nDepartment of Pharmacology\nCollege of Medicine\nU.P. Manila\n\nProf. Edelwina Legazpi\nDepartment of Humanities\nCollege of Arts & Sciences\nU.P. Los Baños\n\nProf. Ruben Umaly\nDepartment of Zoology\nCollege of Arts & Sciences\nU.P. Diliman\n\nFor the Committee : \n\nHORACIO R. ESTRADA, M.D.\nChairman\n\nMINUTES OF THE SEVENTH MEETING OF THE COMMITTEE OF VICE-CHANCELLORS FOR ACADEMIC AFFAIRS, Tuesday - 27 November 1984, Law Library Conference Hall, 9:30 - 11: 35 a.m. \n\nPresent : Vice-President for Academic Affairs Irene R. Cortes\nVice-Chancellor Paz G. Ramos\nVice-Chancellor Higino A. Ables\nVice-Chancellor Leopoldo L. Lazatin\nVice-Chancellor Lydia G. Ledesma\n\nAlso present : \nVice-President for Planning and Finance Raul P. de Guzman\n\nMatters discussed : A. The minutes of the previous meeting (25 October 1984) was approved without any corrections made. \nB. The system-wide General Education Program\nAfter carefully considering and deliberating on the various proposals of the four autonomous universities and the Horacio Estrada Committee on the G.E. program, the members of the Committee agreed to adopt the following as a minimum requirement for G.E. Courses in each of the four autonomous universities of the UP system with the corresponding number of units per course; without  prejudice to an autonomous university\'s prescribing additional course :\nI. Tool courses - 9 units\nEnglish/Pilipino - 6\nSpeech I - 3\n*Additional subject depending upon the discretion of each of the autonomous universities.)\nII. Natural and Mathematical Sciences - 9 units\nMathematics I - 3 \nNat. Sci. I** - 3\nNat. Sci II** - 3\n(Science and Society - 3)\n*Additional subject depending upon the discretion of each autonomous university. \n**Course description is left to the individual autonomous universities. \nIII. Social Sciences  - 12 units\nSoc. Sci. I - 3 \nSoc. Sci. II - 3\nPhil History - 3\nPhilosophical Analysis - 3 \nIV. Humanities  - 6 units\nG.E. Hum I - 3 \nG.E. Hum II - 3\n(G.E. Hum III - 3)\n\n*Additional subject based on the discretion of the autonomous universities)\n\nV. Electives \n\nCourses/Seminars** - 6\n**To be specified by each autonomous university. \n\nTotal No. 42 units\n\nInclusive of Spanish subjects would depend on the repeal or non-repeal of the Spanish Law which requires students who need to take any type of board examinations to comply with a maximum of 12 units of Spanish subjects. \n\nA move which the autonomous universities can take for the repeal of the Spanish Law is to pass resolutions making the Spanish subjects optional. Then it is up to the administration of the UP system to take the appropriate step/s. The repeal is a complicated matter since it will affect other specific provisions of the Spanish Law as well as the policies pertaining to professional organizations. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1597, 'E2-1597AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, December 6) The 245th meeting of faculty of the College of Engineering ', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nMEMORANDUM\nFor : MEMBERS OF THE FACULTY\nCollege of Engineering\n\nFROM : The Secretary\n\n1. The 245th meeting of the faculty of the College of Engineering will be held on WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 12, 1984 at 2:00 p.m. at Room 410 (G.E. Conference Room).\n2. Business arising from the minutes;\n3. Approval of candidates for graduation as of 1st semester 1984-85;\n4. Requests for change of grades;\n5. Other matters. \n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1598, 'E2-1598AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, July 2) Memorandum to the members of the Faculty ', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nMEMORANDUM\n\nFOR : MEMBERS of the FACULTY \nCollege of Engineering\n\nFROM : The Secretary\n1. Please be informed that the 243rd meeting of the faculty of the College of Engineering will be held on THURSDAY, JULY 5, 1984 at 2:00 p.m. at Room 410 (G.E. Conference Room).\n2. The agenda is as follows : \na) Approval of the minutes of the 242nd meeting on March 30, 1984;\nb) Business arising from the minutes;\nc) Approval of the candidates for graduation as of the end of Summer, 1984;\nd) Plans for the Diamond Jubilee Celebration of the College(*);\ne) Improvement/Expansion of College Library and the laboratory facilities;\nf) Other matters. \n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary\n\n(*) The College of Engineering was established on June 13, 1910. Suggestions from the faculty will be most welcome, specifically on : a) theme of the celebration; b) activities that will encourage participation of alumni, faculty and students. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1599, 'E2-1599AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, March 30) Minutes of the 242nd Engineering Faculty Meeting held on March 30, 1984, Room 410, ', '(1) Dean Mena called the meeting to order at 2:50 p.m. The minutes of the 241st meeting of the faculty were approved as presented. Dr. Panlasigul suggested that the following be put on record : candidates for graduation who may have cleared their deficiencies just before the meeting will not be automatically transferred to the \"CLEAR\" is authorized to make this transfer after appropriate verification of the students\' record.\n(2) Business arising from the minutes : \n(a) On Item 4 : The graduation of Mr. Tito R. Flores, a candidate for the B.S. Met. E., was approved by the graduation committee, provided that this case does not become a precedent. \n(b) On Item 6 : Dr. Pacheco informed the faculty of the action of Cluster C of the Curriculum Committee on the following curricular matters : \n*Approval of the institution of Energy 101 & Energy 197.\n*Approval of the changes in prerequisite for E.S. 26 and C.S. 51. \n*On the proposed E.E. curriculum, the Dept. Chairman of E.E. is requested to : \n-- prepare the rationale for the proposed revisions;\n-- justify the need to institute so many E.E. courses;\n-- shorten the description of some courses.\n*Approval of the revised curriculum on : B.S.I.E., B.S.Met.E., M.S.I.E., and Diploma in I.E.\n*The B.S. Mining E. curriculum was not yet discussed.\n*The proposed M.S. in Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering still has to pass thru the Vice-President for Planning & Finance. \n(3) The faculty approved the candidates for graduation as of the end of the second semester, 1983-84. \n(4) The following requests for change of grade were likewise approved by the faculty : \nABSTRACT OF REQUESTS FOR CHANGE OF GRADES APPROVED BY THE ENGINEERING FACULTY IN ITS 242ND MEETING HELD AT RM. 410 MELCHOR HALL LAST MARCH 30, 1984. \nName of Students               Course     From     To      Sem/Yr     Faculty\n1. ALLENEGUE, Edwin         E.E. 69     4.0         3.0     2-83-84     C.B. San Juan \n2. LEGASPI, Dante E.           C.E. 11     2.0         1.5     2-83-84     V. B. Zabat\n3. LEYRAN, Eugene R.S.      C.E. 54     4.0         3.0     2-83-84     V. B. Zabat\n4. VIGILAR, Gregorio            C.E. 60     2.0         1.5     2-83-84     J. de Castro\n(5) Other matters :\n(a) The Dean reminded the faculty advisers that they should not allow students to enroll in more than 6 units this coming Summer Session. \n(b) The faculty discussed the proposed increase in tuition fees in the University. The following are the comments/reaction of the faculty : \nSome questions posed : \n1) What is the probability of this increase being adopted by the University?\n2) What will the University do in case of mass action against the increase? \n3) How do the new rates compare with those of the private schools?\n4) Are children of faculty and personnel still eligible to enjoy tuition fee discounts?\nSome comments : \n1) Before we can comment we should see the whole picture first.\n2) The increase should be graduated over a length of time. \n3) Some sort of double taxation-- we already pay our income tax according to brackets and now the tuition benefits are also bracketed. (i.e., tuition fee discounts diminish as the income bracket increases. \n4) Use NET income instead of GROSS income to specify the category. \n5) The rationale for the increase is to maintain academic excellence. The expected net yield of P18M is a small percentage compared with the national subsidy; therefore we cannot expect a quantum improvement in academic excellence. \n6) A suggested approach : subsidize the student with free tuition but must serve the government after graduation; those not willing to serve the government must pay the full tuition. \n7) Tuition fee discounts should not be granted outright to graduate students; financial assistance should be based on intellectual ability. The income tax return is misleading. Some graduate students may have low income but may be sons of millionaires. \n\n(6) There being no further business the meeting was adjourned at 4:05 p.m.\n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1600, 'E2-1600AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Candidates for Graduation\nSecond Semester, 1983-1984\nWITHOUT DEFICIENCY\nGRADUATE ', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1601, 'E2-1601AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, March 27) Memorandum to the members of the Faculty', 'COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nMEMORANDUM\n\nFOR : Members of the Faculty\nCollege of Engineering\n\nFROM : The Secretary \n\n1. Please be informed that the 242nd meeting of the faculty of the College of Engineering will be held on FRIDAY, MARCH 30, 1984 at 2:30 p.m. at Room 410 (G.E. Conference Room).\n2. The agenda is as follows : \n(a) Approval of the minutes of the 241st meeting on December 14, 1983 and continued on January 18, 1984;\n(b) Business arising from the minutes;\n(c) Approval of the candidates for graduation as of the end of the second semester, 1983-84;\n(d) Requests for change of grades;\n(e) Other matters. \n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1602, 'E2-1602AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1984, January 18) Minutes of the 241st Engineering Faculty Meeting Held on December 14, 1983 and Ja', '(1) Dean Mena called the meeting to order at 2:15 p.m. The following new members of the faculty were introduced :\nCh.E. - Mr. JOAQUIN E. SAN DIEGO\nC.E. - Ms. OLIVIA MARIA LAI REYES\nReturnees, from Met/Mining : Dr. ADOLFO GOPEZ\nDr. MANOLO MENA\nNew Engineering Librarian : Ms. YOLANDA GRANDA (vice Mrs. Lopez-retired). \n(2) The minutes of the 240th meeting held on July 6, 1983 were approved with the following correction : Mr. Victorino Zabat is added to \"Present\" list. \n(3) Business arising from the minutes :\n(a) On Item 4 : Mr. Ong was a probable candidate for graduation with honors as of the end of summer, 1983. However his \"INC\" in E.E 81 was not cleared on time. \n(b) On Item 6 : On the assessment of the effect of the new class schedule additional data will be gathered for the second semester; feedback from the students will also be obtained. \n(4) The faculty approved the candidates for graduation as of the end of the 1st semester, 1983-84. \nThe faculty also discussed the case of Mr. Tito R. Flores, a candidate for the B.S. Met. Eng\'g who was recommended by the faculty for graduation as of the end of the 2nd semester, 1982-83. However, the University Registrar objected since Mr. Flores finished only 55 units in U.P.; this is less than 50% of the total units for the B.S. Met. E. program. This student has a B.S. degree in Mining from St. Louis University when he applied to our Met.E. program. He validated some courses and re-enrolled those courses which he did not succeed in validating. He finished the requirements for the B.S. Met. in two years. It was pointed out that Mr. Flores finished 55 units out of the total of 98 units required from the 3rd to the 5th years. \nDr. Pacheco pointed out that this case may be a dangerous precedent since students may take the first two-year courses in another school and then apply in U.P. for the last years of the program. \nProf. A. dela Cruz said that in future cases we should be careful at the admission stage. After some discussion Dr. Ordillas moved that Mr. Tito Flores be recommended for graduation as a special case. In the votation two are \"against\" and the rest are \"in favor\". \n(5) The following requests for change of grade were approved by the faculty : \nNAME OF STUDENT\n1. CAMBA, Willie -  C.E. 53  - 4.0 - 3.0 - 1-83-84 - Victorino Zabat\n2. LAO, Willen S.  - E.S. 21 - 1.75 - 1.5 - Sum. 82 - 83  - Jesus Ignacio\n3. MANGALILE, Reynaldo  - E.E. 72  - 3.0 - 2.5 - 1-83-84  - Alfonso Aguilar\n4. PIMENTEl, Aurelio - E.E. 36 - 2.0 - 1.5 - 1-83-84 - Christian San Juan\n5. TOLENTINO, Andres Fe - C.E. 21 - 3.0 - 2.5 - 1-83-84 - Fernando German\n\n(6) The faculty considered the following curricular matters :\n(a) Institution of two courses in Energy : \nEnergy 101 : Introduction to Energy Engineering\nEnergy 197 : Special Topics \nFaculty Action : Approval  \n(b) Change in Prerequisite : \nFor E.S. 26 : Computer Programming\nFrom : E.S. 21 or equivalent \nTo : Math 55\nFor C.S. 51 : Numerical Methods and Analysis \nFrom : C.S. 12 and Math 55\nTo : Math 55 and C.S. 11 or equivalent \nFaculty Action : Approval \n(c) Proposed B.S.E.E. curriculum : \nDr. Viray explained that the proposed revised E.E. curriculum satisfies the need to incorporate the technological advances in computers, communication, instrumentation and controls. \nProf. F.G.L. Reyes asked why E.S. 13 is deleted from the program. Dr. Viray said that in actual practice this course is not needed; another reason for removing E.S. 13 is to make room for E.E. 13 : Introduction to Electrical Engineering so that the second year students who take this course will already have a sense of belonging to the College. \nFaculty Action : Approval of B.S.E.E. curriculum \n(d) Proposed B.S.I.E. curriculum : \nProf. F. dela Peña explained that the present I.E. curriculum dates back to 1978 and now there is a strong need to revise the curriculum. \nThe main features of the proposal are : \n- emphasis on methods engineering and use of statistical analysis\n- redistribution of subject content in sequential courses\n- reduction in number of required electives\n- rearrangement of courses in the different year levels to expose the student to the engineering program as early as possible\n- renumbering of courses according to the proposed University numbering system\nAt this point the Dean declared a recess (4:15 p.m.); continuation of the meeting was set for January 1984. \nThe continuation of the 241st faculty meeting was held on January 18, 1984. Dean Mena called the meeting to order at 2:15 p.m. Dr. Wilfredo Jose, a returnee from the Ch.E. Dept. was introduced. \nThe faculty approved the following requests for change of grade : \nNAME OF STUDENT\n1. TI, Nelson Lim - C.E. 53EF - 2.5 - 2.0 - 1-83-84 - V. Zabat\n2. REX, Rey R. - E.S. 12PW2 - 1.25 - 1.0 - 1-83-84 - F. Aniban\n3. KHO, Stephen U. - E.S. 12PW2 - 1.5 - 1.0 - 1-83-84 - F. Aniban\n4. PALMA, Elsa -- E.S. 201K - Drp. 2.0 - 2-82-83 - M. Pascual\n5. FAJARDO, Stella R. - I.E. 42UV - 2.25 - 1.75 - 1-83-84 - A. dela Cruz\n\nDiscussion of the B.S.I.E. curriculum was resumed. \n\nFaculty Action : Approval of B.S.I.E. program. \n(e) Proposed B.S. Met. E. curriculum : \nDr. Ordillas presented the proposed revised Met. E. program. \nFeatures of the new curriculum are : \n- balanced consideration of the four major branches of metallurgy : minerals engineering, extractive metallurgy, adaptive metallurgy, and physical metallurgy. \n- increased emphasis in investigative and computational skills\n- reduction in laboratory units form 93 to 81\n- reduction in Chemistry and Geology requirements \n- separation of laboratory courses from lecture courses (except in design courses)\n- rearrangement of courses to introduce the student to metallurgical engineering earlier\n\nAfter discussion it was agreed that the footnotes for the social science courses should be uniform for the different curricula being presented.\n\nFaculty Action : Approval of the B.S. Met. E. curriculum \n(f) Proposed B.S. Mining E. curriculum : \nMr. Forado Serrano presented the new Mining curriculum. The main features of the curriculum are : \n- institution of courses on specialized areas of mining technology\n- inclusion of courses in computer programming and statistics needed for new mining courses.\n- change in course description of retained mining courses to reflect up-to-date mining engineering practice\n- increased number of electives required\n- reduction in Chemistry and Geology requirements\n- rearrangement of courses to introduce the student to the mining engineering program earlier\n\nFaculty Action : Approval of B.S. Mining Engineering program\n\n(g) Proposed M.S.I.E. / Diploma in I.E. : \nThe I.E. Dept. proposes a two-tiered approach to the I.E. graduate program : the Diploma program and the masteral program. Non-I.E. baccalaureatte degree holders will be trained in the basics of I.E. and after completion of required courses will be awarded a diploma. These required courses are graduate courses and problem-oriented. Holders of the Diploma will be eligible for admission to the masteral program. For the Diploma program the grade-point requirement and the maximum residence (3 years) should be indicated.\nThe masteral program will allow for specialization in the following fields : Production Systems, Operations Research, and Information System. The student may choose a thesis or a non-thesis option.\nFaculty Action : Approval of Diploma & masteral programs in I.E. \n\n(h) Proposed master\'s program in Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering :\n\nProf. Vea presented the proposal for this new program. Among the things he discussed are : \n- the need for the masteral program - to develop the capability in ship design and construction in order to support the need for a strong interisland shipping fleet\n- assessment of the potential demand for graduates of the program\n- resource requirements of the program when fully operational\n- institution of new courses (14 courses) / sample programs \n- financing - proposed sources are the regular budget and the shipyard fund \nThe proposed start of the program is in the second semester, 1984-85.\n\nFaculty Action : Approval of the master\'s program in Naval Architecture & Marine Engineering \n\n(7) There being no further business the meeting was adjourned at 3:45 p.m.\n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1603, 'E2-1603AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1983, December 9) Members of the Faculty ', 'University of the Philippines\nCOLLEGE OF ENGINEERING \nDiliman, Quezon City \n\nMEMORANDUM FOR : Members of the Faculty\nCollege of Engineering \n\nFROM : The Secretary\n\n1. Please be informed that the 241st meeting of the faculty of the College of Engineering will be held on WEDNESDAY, December 14, 1983 at 2:00 p.m. at Room 410 (G.E. Conference Room). \n2. The agenda are as follows : \n\na) Approval of the minutes of the 240th meeting on July 6, 1983;\nb) Business arising from the minutes\nc) Approval of the candidates for graduation as of the end of the first semester, 1983-94;\nd) The case of Mr. Tito R. Flores : student was recommended by the faculty for graduation (B.S. Met. E.) as of 2nd Sem. 82-83. University Registrar objected; Mr. Flores finished less than 50% of the total units required for Met. E. Mr. Flores finished B.S. Mining at St. Louis University.;\ne) Requests for change of grade.\nf) Approval of the following revised curricula : \nB.S.E.E.\nB.S.I.E\nMaster\'s Program, I.E.\nB.S. Met.E.\nB.S. Min.E.\ng) Institution of a masteral program in Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering;\nh) Other matters. \n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nSecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1604, 'E2-1604AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1983, July 6) Minutes of the 240th Engineering Faculty Meeting held on July 6, 1983 at Room 410, Me', '1. Dean Mena called the meeting to order at 2:45 p.m. The following new members of the faculty were introduced : \nCh.E. : Ms. Rosalinda Lontok\nE.S. : Prof. Rey Vea (returnee)\nG.E. : Mr. Benedicto Legaspi\nI.E. : Mr. Godofredo Dolor\nMs. Sheila Perez\nMet/Mining : Mr. Eduardo Mayor (returnee)\nM.E. : Mr. Jesus A. San Mateo\nMr. Alfredo Diaz\nMr. Romeo Soriano\nReturnees : \nDr. Manuel Hernandez\nMr. Alex Paran\nMr. Gino Bautista\n\n2. The minutes of the 239th meeting held on April 5, 1983 were approved with the following correction : Prof. F. T. dela Pena should be transferred to \"Members Present\" list. \n\n3. Business arising from the minutes : \n(a) On Item 3 : Mr. Demetrio P. Crisostomo was cleared for graduation as of the end of Summer, 1983. Mr. Virgil P. Estrada was cleared for graduation as of June 3, 1983. \n\n4. The faculty approved the candidates for graduation as of the end of Summer, 1983. In this connection Dr. Pacheco informed the faculty that Mr. Aristeo G. de Gracia is recommended posthumously for the degree Master of Engineering (Industrial Engineering). Mr. Jose L. One (E.E.) will probably graduate with honors (still has INC. in E.E. 81). \n\n5. The Dean presented to the faculty the proposed University rules on scholastic delinquency. After discussion of the proposals the faculty agreed to recommend the following : \n\n(a) the University Council Committee on Student Progress should inquire if all units have their own scholastic rules as per Art. 389 of the University Code (The faculty of each college or school shall approve suitable and effective provisions governing undergraduate delinquent students.)\n\n(b) Further study by the Committee should be made particularly on the basic framework/premise that was adopted for the existing univesrity scholastic delinquency rules. \n\nThe faculty will submit its recommendations based on additional information regarding the above items. \n\n6. The faculty made a preliminary assessment on the effect of the new class scheduling. Does the new system attain its objectives, such as : (a) maximum utilization of classrooms, (b) students may possibly go to classes 4 days instead of 5 days a week?\n\nA survey made in the College for the first semester, 1983-84 shows that : (a) there was a reduction in the use of some classrooms, although there was an increase in the use of some rooms at NEC. (b) there is no marked change in the number of days that the students go to classes.  \n\nDr. Garcia made the following suggestions : \n(a) take the average percentage utilization of all classrooms by each day (Monday, Tues, Wednesdays, etc.) rather than by room to room comparison.\n(b) take into account the number of students (size of class) using a given classroom\n(c) get a feedback from the students\n\n7. The faculty approved the request for a change of grade by Prof. Ulpiano P. Ignacio, Jr. for Mr. Marvin Garbo CE 24 from \"4.0\" to \"3.0\", 2nd semester, 1982-83.\n\n8. There being no further business the meeting was adjourned at 4:00 p.m. \n\nMIGUEL B. ESCOTO\nCollege Secretary\n\nMr. Celso G. Santos, Jr. a BSIE candidate is the only candidate cleraed of his deficiency. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1605, 'E2-1605AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Proposed Undergraduate Courses to be Instituted ', 'Energy 101 : Introduction to Energy Engineering. - Energy resources, conversion, uses and conservation. Prerequisite : Senior standing. 3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units\nEnergy 197 : Special topics. Credit 3 units, may be repeated for a maximum of 6 units\n\nREVISION OF COURSES\nChange in Prerequisite\nE.S. 26 COMPUTER PROGRAMMING \nFrom : Prerequisite : E.S. 21 or equivalent\nTo : Prerequisite : Math 55.\nC.S. 51 NUMERICAL METHODS AND ANALYSIS\nFrom : Prerequisite : C.S.12 and Math 55\nTo : Prerequisite : Math 55 and C.S. 11 or equivalent', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1606, 'E2-1606AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Proposed Increases in TFD/GIA Benefits and Tuition Needs', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1607, 'E2-1607AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'A. Institution of Undergraduate Courses \nB. Change in course description & pre-requisite.\nC. Change in course description. \nD. Change in course title and Course description. \nE. Change in course title, course description and number of units.\nF. Change in course number & course description. \nG. Change in course number, course description and pre-requisite. \nH. Abolition of undergraduate Courses \nI. Course taken from another unit/department deleted from BSGE Curriculum\nJ. Course taken from another department included in BSGE Curriculum ', '', 'SUMMARY OF PROPOSAL FOR REVISION OF BSGE CURRICULUM ', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1608, 'E2-1608AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'I. Justification for the Revision\nII. Salient Features of the Proposed Curriculum \nPROPOSED FIVE YEAR CURRICULUM LEADING TO THE DEGREE OF BACHELOR OF SCIENCE IN MINING ENG\'G\nI. Abolition of Courses\nII. Institution of the New Courses\nIII. Change in Course Number, Title, Description and Prerequisite\nIV. Course Taken from Another Unit Deleted from BSEM Curriculum\nV. Course to be Taken from Another Unit Included in BSEM Curriculum \nSUMMARY OF CHANGES IN BSEM CURRICULUM \nSUMMARY LIST OF COURSES OFFERED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF MINING AND METALLURGICAL ENGINEERING ', '', '(1983, November 29) PROPOSAL TO REVISE THE CURRICULUM LEADING TO THE DEGREE OF BACHELOR OF SCIENCE I', 'SUMMARY OF UNDERGRADUATE COURSES IN MINING ENGINEERING TO BE OFFERED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF MINING AND METALLURGICAL ENGINEERING \n\nE.M. 10; PRINCIPLES of MINING. History importance and characteristics of the minerals industry. Principles of mineral exploration including geology, geochemistry, geophysics, sampling, prospect drilling and statistical evaluation. Principles of mine development for both underground and surface operations. Brieg introduction to mining methods. Prerequisite : Preceded or accompanied by Geol. 11. 3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units. \n\nE.M. 36; UNDERGROUND MINING. Techniques, unit operations, and systems involved in underground mining. Criteria for selection of mining method. Reserve estimates, development planning, engineering drawings for development and extraction, underground haulage systems. Prerequisite : E.M. 10. 2 hours a week (class); credit 2 units.\n\nE.M. 42; COAL MINING. - Origin, classification, and composition of coal. Reserve computations. Methods of coal extraction : surface and underground. Equipment and methods selection. Conventional and Mechanized systems. Utilization and marketing. Environmental considerations. Prerequisite : E.M. 10. 2 hours a week (class); credit 2 units. \n\nE.M. 45; SURFACE MINING. - Merits of surface mining. Engineering and economic factors in the selection and use of various equipment and systems in surface mining. Ore estimates, grade control, short and long range planning, cost estimation, slope stability and control, and placer operations. Prerequisite : E.M. 10. 2 hours a week (class); credit 2 units. \n\nE.M. 46; ROCK MECHANICS and EXCAVATION PRACTICE. - Physical properties of rocks, theories of rock substance failure, and fundamentals of rock mass and rock substance response to applied loads. Principles of the design of underground openings and pit slopes, ground support, tunneling, and other practical applications. Prerequisite : E.M. 42, 45, and E.S. 13; or consent of instructor. 3 hours a week (2 class, 3 lab) : credit 3 units. \n\nE.M. 152; MINE MANAGEMENT AND SAFETY. - Principles of mine administration, industrial and human engineering, project management. Causes and prevention of accidents in coal and metal mines. Mines safety regulations. Prerequisite : Senior standing. 3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units. \n\nE.M. 154; MINE ECONOMICS. - Methods of sampling, ore reserve calculations and statistical analysis applied to the evaluation of ore deposits. Engineering economic principles applied to mineral project evaluation including : time value of money, cash flows, depreciation, depletion, risk, various profitability measures, cost of Capital. Prerequisite : Senior standing. 3 hours a week (class); credit 3 units. \n\nE.M. 156; MINE PLANT DESIGN. Analysis and design of materials handling system, mine de-watering, hauling, hoisting, compressed air and other power systems. Introduction to Systems Engineering. Prerequisite : Senior standing. 3 hours a week (class) : credit 3 units. \n\nE.M. 157; MINE VENTILATION. Fundamentals of mine ventilation including control of gases, dust, temperature and humidity. Analysis and design of ventilation systems. Prerequisite : Senior standing. 3 hours a week (2 class, 3 lab); credit 3 units.\n\nE.M. 170; INSPECTION TRIPS AND SEMINARS. - Visits to mines. Reports on such visits. Presentation and discussions of papers on assigned topics. Prerequisite : Senior standing. 1 hour a week (class); credit 1 unit. \n\nE.M. 197; SPECIAL TOPICS. Current issues and Problems in mining engineering. Credit : 3 units may be repeated for a maximum of units. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1609, 'E2-1609AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'Old curriculum\nProposed curriculum\nService Courses\n3 E.S. 31\nMet. E. 24 (Met.E. 20)\nMet. E. 25\nTotal Teaching Load\nFaculty Required at \na. 12 units each\nb. 9 units each\nc. 6 units each ', '', 'Faculty Requirements ', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1610, 'E2-1610AC', '', '', '', '', '', 'TABLE OF CONTENTS \n1. Proposed Five Year Curriculum leading to the Degree of Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering\n2. Curriculum Flowchart\n3. Summary of curriculum changes\n4. Comparison of Present and Proposed Curriculum in Electrical Engineering\n5. Institution and Revision of Courses for both Undergraduate and Graduate levels. ', '', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49');
