(1611, 'E2-1611AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'PROPOSALS TO REVISE THE CURRICULA LEADING TO THE DEGREES OF BACHELOR OF SCIENCE IN INDUSTRIAL ENGINE', 'Part I\nProposal to revise the curriculum leading to the degree of Bachelor of Science in Industrial Engineering\nI. BACKGROUND\nThe existing BSIE curriculum was instituted in 1978. By the end of School Year 1982-1983 the faculty of the Department of Industrial Engineering and Operations Research felt that there is already a strong need to make new revisions and therefore discussions have been made the result of which is this proposal. \nII. MAIN FEATURES OF THE PROPOSAL\nThe main features of this proposal are as follows :\n1. Increased emphasis on methods engineering and the use of statistical analysis.\n2. Redistribution of subject matter content in sequential courses.\n3. Reduction in the number of electives required.\n4. Rearrangement of courses in the different year levels to be able to integrate the student to the engineering program as early as possible.\n5. Renumbering of courses in line with the proposed University numbering system.\nPart II\nProposal to institute a Diploma Program in Industrial Engineering (Dipl. I.E.) and to revise the curriculum leading to the degree of Master of Science (I.E.)\nI. BACKGROUND \nThe graduate program in Industrial Engineering at the University of the Philippines has consistently attracted the largest enrolment at the University\'s Graduate Engineering Program. The accessibility of the program to students with different baccalaureate degrees appear to be the principal reason for attracting a large enrolment. On the other hand the number of graduates in the program are very few. A number of reasons could be identified. First, students with non-IE background need to take as much as 51 units to earn a degree. Second, many of the students are part-time students who find difficulty in carrying out their studies to completion. Third, many of the students are not very keen in getting the degree but are more concerned about learning the basics of IE for practical reasons. The possibility, however, that students become delinquent or uninterested in the program content cannot be discounted. \nRecent developments in the field and experiences gained in the administration of the existing IE graduate program have triggered a need to review and modify the curriculum. It is in this context that the concepts presented here are being proposed. \nII. A TWO-TIERED APPROACH\nAmong students admitted to the IE graduate program with non-IE background only a few are able to finish and earn a degree. Many among them, however, are able to go through the remedial courses prescribed. Notably, this category of students comprise the majority of the graduate IE students. This sector therefore cannot be ignored in trying to redesign the IE graduate curriculum. \nIt is therefore proposed that a program be made available for the non-IE\'s in such a way that there are first trained in the basics of IE, taking into consideration the fact that they already have a baccalaureatte degree in other engineering fields or in the physical and mathematical sciences and awarding them with a diploma after completion of the required courses. The courses to be offered in this program will differ from the undergraduate courses in the sense that they will be problem oriented and students will be required to carry out some research relevant to the subject matter. They will be classified as graduate courses. A student who earns this diploma will be eligible for admission into the masteral program.\nThe masteral program, on the other hand, will allow for a thesis and non-thesis option. Specialization will be in the field of Production Systems, Operations Research and Information Systems. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1612, 'E2-1612AC', '41', 'NCTS Graduate Programs in Transportation ', '', 'Office of the Graduate Program Coordinator ', 'June 2001', 'TABLE OF CONTENTS\n1. INTRODUCTION\n2. GRADUATE PROGRAM CURRICULUM\n2.1 Master of Science in Civil Engineering Transportation Engineering Program\n2.1.1. Curriculum and Sequencing of Courses for Full-Time Study Option\nM.S. Civil Engineering-Transportation Engineering Program Curriculum\n2.1.2 Description of Courses Under the MSCE-TE Program\nCore Courses in Engineering\nMajor Courses in Transportation Engineering\nElective Courses in Transportation Engineering \n2.2 Master of Arts in Transportation Planning Program\n2.2.1 Curriculum and Sequencing of Courses for Full-Time Study Option \nMaster of Arts in Transportation Planning Program (MATP) Curriculum\n2.2.2 Description of Courses Under the MATP/DTP Programs\nCore Courses in Engineering\nMajor Courses in Transportation Engineering\nElective Courses in Transportation Engineering \n3. ACADEMIC REQUIREMENTS \n3.1 M.S. in Civil Engineering - Transportation Engineering Program\n3.2 M.A. in Transportation Planning Program  \nSURP School Research Forum\n4. NCTS REQUIREMENTS\n4.1 Junior Year\nJoint Research Forum (JRF)\n4.2 Senior Year\nSchedule of Presentations for Graduate Students as Required by NCTS\nExpected Contents of the Presentations\nSuggested Format for Progress Report/Presentations :\nMid-Term Presentation\nThesis Oral Defense\nThesis Forms\n5. NCTS-IBS SCHOLARSHIP\n6. RESEARCH ACTIVITIES\n6.1 Research Equipment and Facilities\n6.1.1 NCTS Graduate Student Research Laboratory (Student\'s Room)\n6.1.2 NCTS Library\n6.1.3 Computing Facilities\n6.1.4 Transportation and Traffic Survey Equipment\n6.2 Recommended Research Topics by the NCTS Faculty\n\nNational Center for Transportation Studies - List of Master\'s Theses, 1995-2001\nDirectory of NCTS Faculty Affiliates, June 2001\nDirectory of NCTS Staff Relevant to the Graduate Program, April 2001\nList of NCTS Graduate Student-Scholars As of June 2001\nHouse Rules for NCTS Graduate Students\nBasic Rules for NCTS Scholars in Using the Computers\nSample Thesis Forms from the College of Engineering\nSample Thesis Forms from the School of Urban and Regional Planning ', 'General Information', '', '', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1613, 'E2-1613AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Valedictory Address ', 'Esguerra, Jasper Powell S. \nBS Chemical Engineering\nUP College of Engineering Recognition Rites 2013', 'Opportunity Cost\n\nFour to five years has again passed in our lives. How much difference did it make?\nDistinguished guests, Dr. Adolfo Jesus Gopez, Dean of the College of Engineering Dr. Aura Matias, Associate Deans, College Secretary, and Head Librarian, department and institute heads, professors and instructors, parents and guests, fellow graduates, ladies and gentlemen, good evening. \nMany people say that college has its way of changing people\'s lives. And I couldn\'t agree more. Bago mag-college, and enrollment, isang araw lang. Sa UP, isa, isang linggo. Sa start ng semester, tao ka pa. Sa kalagitnaan, wala ng buto, sabaw na lang. At bago matapos ang sem, zombie na. Dati, masaya ka lang kapag 100/100. Ngayon, 100/300, ok na, mag-curve nawa. O, akala nyo sobrang seryoso ng speech na \'to \'no? Cinram ko alng din \'to, tulad ng madalas nating ginagawa bilang engineering students. Joke lang po. \nBut seriously, we should all give ourselves a put on the back for surviving the College of Engineering adventure alive. The past years have been undeniably tough, and I\'m quite sure that for the majority of us, there has always been the question, playing at the back of our minds, of whether we can make it or not. Eventually, I got to discover that it was never a question of \"Can I?\", but a question of \"Will I?\" It was never a question of our abilities, but rather a question of our determination, our passion, of how much we want it. Look, nandito na tayo, nasa kaliwang balikat na ang mga sablay, handang handa nang anihin ang ating tagumpay.\nBut now, what? What lies after graduation? Life after college, according to some of my friends from previous batches, seems to give more uncertaintites than our time spent here in the university. It\'s because after college, we\'re on our own, no longer limited by university rules. Wala ng maximum of six absences. Wala ng math subjects na kapag twice mo binagsak, sisipain ka palabas ng office na pinagtatrabahuan mo. Basically, there are several paths that we could take, but how do we know if we are where we\'re supposed to be? I mean, after four to five years of enduring exams, feasibility studies, thesis, machine exercises, problem sets, and design projects, it would be a shame if we\'ll not find a venue where we could channel the education we received into its envisioned purpose. And actually, that\'s the problem. We became too preoccupied with preparing for own future that we forgot to imbibe to ourselves who we really should be. \nThis is the point when we go back to the core of UP education - an ideology that is so important because it is what should set UP Eng\'g apart from other engineering schools, something that we might have overlooked when we were too busy with our individual struggles. \nI know you\'re already expecting this, the reminder of giving back to the country, to be integral to this speech. But because we\'re all analytical and critically-minded engineers in the making, I\'ll making this as objective and as figure-based as possible. So please lend me a few more minutes of your time. This is the last lecture you\'ll be hearing anyway. \nBased on a study by Edita Tan from the UP School of Economics, the government has allocated a budget of PhP 95,000 for each UP student in 2009. That\'s 95,000 for me, another 95,000 for my friend Diana Gernan, another 95,000 for my friend Lou Aguion, another 95,000 for Mico Panis, and the same goes for each one of you. That is on an annual basis. Assuming the figure is the same throughout our stay in the university, the Filipino people would have spent around 400,000 to 500,000 pesos per student. And because nearly 800 of us are garduating today, that would total to nearly half a billion pesos spent for our batch alone to enjoy a subsidized yet the highest quality of education available in the country. \nWhat is the opportunity cost? That same half a billion pesos could have been used to augment the government\'s Pantawid Pamilay Pilipino Program. That same half a billion pesos could have been used for DSWD\'s supplemental feeding program, for the DOH Health Facilities Enhancement Program, for the Department of Agriculture\'s National Rice, Fisheries, Livestock Program, and so on and so forth. \nThe government could have allotted that for something else. Imagine the thousands of Filipino people who could have benefited more from that half a billion pesos. Then why invest on us? Simple. Because the government believes that UP students could also be a long-term solution to poverty. Dahil naniniwala ho ang taumbayan na pagka-graduate natin ng kolehiyo, mare-recognize natin na regardless of our degree, regardless of our social status, regardless of the tuition we pay, tayong lahat ay may malaking utang - not a debt that we literally pay back, but a debt that we ought to pay forward by creating changes intended to benefit the future of our motherland, a responsibility given to our hands today as we leave the university. \nAnd now as I speak, I recognize how ironic that at times, we still complain about our tuition, about how some of us got re-bracketed from B to A, when we do not even dare ask ourselves if we are worth every centavo that the Filipino people is spending on us. Wag naman sana natin isiping, \"Balang araw, magbabayad din naman ako ng tax eh, tax na mapupunta sa budget ng Pilipinas. Eh di parang nakapagpaaral na rin ako ng UP student.\" Well, if that\'s going to be our thinking, then the greater opportunity cost would be our seats, the very space that we are occupying right now. Dahil kung hindi natin piniling mag-aral sa UP, baka may ibang nakaupo sa inuupuan natin na mas makakaintindi sa tunay na kalagayan ng ating bansa. Because in the past days, I came to realize that a UP education fails when we exit the university without the capability of thinking beyond ourselves. \nSocial responsibility is such an inconvenient duty for almost all of us. Why? Because since we were young, we are already accustomed to believe that success is measured by how big we\'ll make it in life. Even in the real world, much focus is being given to the technical feasibility and market profitability. Only a few gives attention to social impact. \nMy closest friends know how difficult it was for me to come up with this speech. That\'s because I was struggling to find a valuable message that I could impart to you. But maybe, all I really wanted to say is this : that if we will it, then we can make our lives after college an adventure with the goal of affecting other people\'s lives in pursuit of our purpose of shaping, changing, and building this nation. Oo, dahil bilang UP Engineers, taglay natin ang kakayahang hubugin, baguhin, at buuin ang bansang ito. So that when we meet 40, 50 years from now, we will not ask each other the brand of cars we own, the retirement fee we\'re getting, the number of children we\'re able to send abroad for leisure and education. Instead, we will be asking ourselves, \"How much difference have you made?\" Bayad ka na ba sa PhP 500,000 na utang mo?\"\nMarami sa atin ang nakapagpa-picture, nagpapa-picture o magpapa-picture kay oble ngayong tapos na tayo ng kolehiyo. Wala ng sumpa eh. Hindi na tayo made-delay. Sana\'y wag lang natin limutin na kaya malapad na nakabuka ang kanyang mga braso ay dahil sinisimbulo nito ang walang pag-iimbot na pag-aalay ng sarili sa ating bansa. Sabi nga ni Albus Dumbledore, \"Soon, we must all face the choice between what is right and what is easy,\" At hihiramin ko ho ito mula sa isang Eng\'g org : I urge you to do the right thing. \nForty, fifty years from now, sana\'y napatunayan na nating lahat na tayo\'y karapat-dapat sa edukasyong tinamasa natin dito sa UP. Maraming salamat at magandang gabi muli. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
