(1620, 'E2-1620AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Name : Renato M. David\nTitle of Dissertations or Theses : Pyrolysis of Coconut Oil Fatty Acids Into Industrial Solvents. \nYear of Graduation : 1981\nAdviser : Teodorico F. Festin\nSuggested Discussants  (2) : Tedororico F. Festin, Rogelio A. Panlasigui, Ph.D. \n\nName : Reynaldo T. Generoso\nTitle of Dissertations or Theses : A Computing Method to Predict the Conditions at Which A Nuclear Reactor Core Attains Criticality.\nYear of Graduation : October 1985\nAdviser : Antonio E. Refre, Ph.D.\nSuggested Discussants (2) : Carlito Arleta, Ph.D., Leonardo S. Leopando\n\nName : Sabino M. Pinlac\nTitle of Dissertations or Theses : A Study of the PNPP-1 Spent Fuel Pool Heat Balance Using a Computer-Aided Simplified Calculational Technique.\nYear of Graduation : October 1985\nAdviser : Antonio E. Refre, Ph.D.\nSuggested Discussants (2) : Carlito Arleta, Ph.D., Leonardo S. Leopando\n\nName : Antonio F. del Rosario\nTitle of Dissertations or Theses : Media Wear in Grinding Phil. Sulfhide Ores.\nYear of Graduation : 1985\nAdviser : Dr. Manolo G. Mena\nSuggested Discussants (2) : Dr. Manolo G. Mena, Dr. Meliton U. Ordillas', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1621, 'E2-1621AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1987, September 9) Subject : College of Science \"Proposed Administration of Graduate Programs\"\n', 'College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City 3004 \n\nDr. PAZ G. RAMOS\nVice-Chancellor for Academic Affairs\nU.P. Diliman\n\nSubject : College of Science \"Proposed Administration of Graduate Programs\"\n\nDear Dr. Ramos :\n\nAs requested by Memorandum No. 13 dated 14 July 1987 of the Office the Chancellor we are submitting the following comments : \n\n1) The most heard remark was that : \"Why should the College of Engineering comment on a proposal that seems to concern only the College of Science?\" According to Dean Mena, since this proposal concerns the College of Science, \"it is not appropriate to discuss the pros and cons of their proposal without full knowledge of the background information which made them propose such a structure.\"\n\n2) When discussed at an informal faculty meeting, the consensus was that the College of Engineering has no serious objection to the College of Science proposal as long as a similar procedure is not applied or used in the College of Engineering. \n\n3) If pressed for further comments, the most often mentioned criticism of the proposal is that the Graduate Council as proposed should not be limited only to PhD degree holders. Several reasons have been mentioned : \na) What if the Dean does not have a PhD?\nb) This could produce an \"elitist\" group and is discriminating against non PhD holders.\nc) In some programs there may be a lack of PhD holders. It is difficult to retain or attract engineers with PhD\'s.\n\n4) Finally, based on the provisions of Article 19 of the existing U.P. Code (Article 57 of the Proposed Revised U.P. Code) the University Council has among others the power \"to prescribe courses of study\" and \"to fix requirements for admission to any college or school of the University\". The creation of a Graduate Council seems to run counter to the U.P. Code. Anyway those excluded from the Graduate Council may be at the University Council to block or delay action on the Graduate Council\'s proposals. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nADOLFO JESUS R. GOPEZ\nCollege Secretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1622, 'E2-1622AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1988, March 7) List of Comments of the Faculty of the College of Engineering on the Report of the U', 'Dr. Paz G. Ramos\nVice-Chancellor of Academic Affairs\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dr. Ramos, \n\nThis is with regard to the list of Comments of the Faculty of the College of Engineering on the Report of the University Council Committee Language Policy. \n\nItem 2, on page 1. The second sentence, \"There was however, a suggestion that students be made to take twelve units of courses specified in their curriculum in courses conducted in Filipino order to encourage the use of the Filipino language\" should be replaced by \"Instead of being required to take six units of Pilipino, the Faculty of the College recommends that the students be required to take twelve units of courses conducted in Filipino in order to encourage the use of the Filipino language\". \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nPROF. ROMEO G. SOLIS\nCollege Secretary\n\nNOTED : \n\nDR. GENARO T. MARZAN\nOfficer-In-Charge', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-19 06:24:07'),
(1623, 'E2-1623AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1988, April 4) Proposal and renumbering of courses and the renaming of the degree programs ', 'College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDr. EMETERIA P. LEE\nRegistrar\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Dr. Lee : \n\nWe are submitting for your consideration the following proposals for the institution and renumbering of courses and the renaming of the degree programs. These proposals were approved by the College Faculty in its 258th meeting held on February 29, 1988. We have forwarded nineteen copies of the proposal to Dr. Edgardo Pacheco, Cluster C Chairman. \n\nVery truly yours,\n\n\nProf. Romeo G. Solis\nCollege Secretary ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1624, 'E2-1624AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1999, July 5) Proposal for the Institution of a Graduate Diploma Program in Electric Power Engineer', 'Department of Electrical and Electronics Engineering \n\nTo : Jonathan Winston L. Salvacion\nCollege Secretary\nCollege of Engineering\n\nFrom : Rowena Cristina L. Guevara, Ph.D.\nChairman\n\nRe : Proposal for the Institution of a Graduate Diploma Program in Electric Power Engineering \n\nAttached herewith is our proposal for the institution of a graduate diploma program in Electric Power Engineering\n\nIf you have any questions, please do not hesitate to get in touch wiht me either by phone : 925-2957 (PLDT), 5513/5612 (U.P. local) or e-mail : gev@eee.upd.edu.ph \n\n__________________________________________\n\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDepartment of Electrical and Electronics Engineering\nGerman Yia Hall, Diliman, Quezon City, 1101\n\nPROPOSAL FOR THE INSTITUTION OF A GRADUATE DIPLOMA PROGRAM IN ELECTRIC POWER ENGINEERING (Diploma in Electric Power Engineering)\n\nA1. RATIONALE \n\nAs the country moves towards industrialization, there is an accompanying increase in the number of companies and agencies involved in the generation, transmission, distribution, and regulation of electric power. The diversification of the electric power industry can be seen in the imminent privatization of the National Power Corporation, which has been the sole supplier of electric energy in the past, and its eventual breakup into generation and transmission corporations. Recently, Independent Power Producers (IPPs) were allowed to generate electric power and connect directly to the electric cooperatives, private utilities, and other customer. The Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao power grids are fast becoming more complex to operate with the construction of new transmission lines and generating units. Customer requirements in power quality are also becoming more stringent. Load growth, the changing regulatory laws, and competition to supply electric power is keeping the electric utility industry in constant transition. Under these conditions, power system planning, design, and operation requires engineers and utility personnel with a wide range of power system knowledge and skills. Engineers and utility personnel may find themselves thrust into situations for which they are unprepared. The Diploma degree in Electric Power Engineering will supplement an engineer\'s undergraduate education with an in-depth study of the power generation, transmission, and distribution subsystems, and the interrelationships that bind them into a coordinated power system. \nA majority of those who enroll in the Master of Science graduate program of the Department of Electrical and Electronics Engineering are employed full-time. A few who are able to obtain a study leave are given only a maximum of one year to finish their studies. Still fewer are the employers who give study leaves with pay. Therefore, a large number of graduate students can only allocate one year to one-and-a-half-years for full-time study. The more rigorous requirements of a Master\'s degree, such as sufficient prepartion for a comprehensive examination or conducting research for a thesis, are not easily satisfied by these students due to time, work, and financial constraints. Some engineers even opt to pursue non-engineering graduate degrees in order not to be left behind in job promotions. Therefore, the Diploma program in Electric Power Engineering is being proposed in order to meet the needs of the large number students who would like to pursue a graduate degree in electric engineering but are strapped for time and resources. \n\nA2. PROGRAM GOALS \n\nThe Diploma degree in Electric Power Engineering will supplement an engineer\'s undergraduate education with an in-depth study of the power generation, transmission, and distribution subsystems, and the interrelationships that bind them into a coordinated power system. This provides the engineer with a working knowledge of the major disciplines of electric power engineering so that, regardless of assignment, he/she will have an understanding of the contributions and effects of the various power system components. Emphasis is placed on theoretical understanding and practical problem-solving ability to prepare engineers for assignment in planning, design, maintenance, operation and management of electric power systems. \n\nB. AN ASSESSMENT OF THE POTENTIAL DEMAND AND CURRENT SUPPLY FOR THE GRADUATES OF THE PROGRAM\n\nThe Diploma program in Electric Power Engineering is geared towards electrical engineers who want to undertake professional development and take up a career in electric power engineering and who can only allocate one school year of study. Graduates of the program will find employment in various electric utility companies, industrial companies, consulting firms, universities and colleges, and government agencies. \nThe impending approval of the Omnibus Power Bill in Congress will result in the deregulation and restructuring of the and tougher competition in the electric power industry. There is going to be a great need for a re-training of most of the electrical engineers and utility personnel of the various generation companies, transmission companies, and government agencies in order to meet the demands of the new environment in the industry. The major players are going to be the Manila Electric Company (MERALCO) and the transmission and generation companies that will be created from the present National Power Corporation (NPC). Smaller players in the new electric power industry will be composed of independent power producers, electric cooperatives, and private utility companies. MERALCO has about 1,200 electrical engineers while NPC has about 2,000 electrical engineers. With the goal of gaining a competitive advantage, electric utility companies will put a premium on electrical engineers with higher technical competencies. \nA survey of the records of the graduate students who entered the Master\'s program in Electrical Engineering from 1990 to 1997 showed who completed 18 units or more, did not finish the Master\'s program. These students should have pursued a Diploma degree. \nTherefore, the restructuring and deregulation of the electric power industry will force electric utility companies and their engineers to seek higher technical competency in order to be competitive in the new electric power market. To get a headstart over competitors, the education and training of a utility\'s engineers must be achieved in the shortest possible time without compromising the quality of education or training. The Diploma program in Electric Power Engineering meets these requirements of the electric power industry. \n\n___________________________________________\n\nAPPENDIX C\nIMPLEMENTATION DETAILS OF THE PROPOSED GRADUATE DIPLOMA PROGRAM IN ELECTRIC POWER ENGINEERING\n\nA. ADMISSION REQUIREMENTS\n\n1. Admission into the Diploma degree program in Electric Power Engineering shall require\n(a) a Bachelor of Science in Electrical Engineering degree from a recognized institution of higher learning,\n(b) a grade weighted average of 2.25 or better, \n(c) English language proficiency, and \n(d) satisfaction of additional University requirements such as health clearance and other special admission requiements that may be imposed by the EEE Graduate Committee.\nProof of English proficiency is required of students whose native language is not English, except those who graduated from institutions where the medium of instruction is Engilsh. For English proficiency, a score of at least 500 in the Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) administered by the Educational Testing Service (Princeton, New Jersey, 08540, USA) is required. \n2. Each application for admission into the Diploma degree program in Electric Power Engineering must be accomplished in the official University application form and accompanied by official transcripts of records, written recommendations from two (2) former professors or experts in the field of Electric Power Engineering, and the officially prescribed application fee. \n3. All applications shall be submitted to and processed by the College of Engineering Graduate Office, referred to the Graduate Committee of the Department of Electrical and Electronics Engineering for evaluation and decision, and endorsed by the latter to the Dean for official action. \n\nB. GENERAL DEGREE REQUIREMENTS\n\nTo satisfy the requirements for the Diploma program, a student must : \n(a) Complete a minimum of 21 units of formal graduate courses, and\n(b) Maintain a cumulative weighted average grade (CWAG) of \"2.0\" or better in his/her graduate courses at the end of each academic year. \n\nC. PROGRAM ADVISER/COMMITTEE AND PROGRAM OF STUDY\nProgram Adviser/Committee\nEvery student admitted into the Diploma program shall be assigned a Program Adviser/Committee by the EEE Deaprtment Chair. The Program Adviser/Committee shall advise, guide and evaluate the student.\n\nProgram of Study\nWithin the first of the student\'s initial year in the Diploma program, a Program of Study shall be designed by the Program Adviser/Committee in consultation with the student and on the basis of the latter\'s academic preparation and desired specialization. A copy of this Program of Study shall be submitted to the Graduate Office/Committee, through channels. Subsequent revisions in the Program of Study must be approved by the Program Adviser/Committee and communicated as soon as possible to the Graduate Office through the channels.\n\nStudy Load Per Semester\nThe normal study load for full-time students per semester shall be nine (9) to twelve (12) units of formal graduate courses. \n\nD. COURSE REQUIREMENTS \n\nEvery student in the Diploma degree program shall be required to complete a minimum of 21 units of relevant courses set by the EEE Graduate Faculty Council. \n\nE. GRADE REQUIREMENT\n\nGrading System\n\nThe following numerical grades shall be used in graduate courses : 1.0 (Excellent), 1.25, 1.5 (Very Good), 1.75, 2.0 (Good), 2.25, 2.5 (Satisfactory), 2.75, 3.0 (Pass), 4.0 (Conditional Failure), INC, (Incomplete), and 5.0 (Fail).\n\nA grade of \"3.0\" or better is a passing grade. A graduate student earns credit for a course when he/she obtains a grade of \"3.0\" or better.\n\nCumulative Weighted Average Grade\n\nTo remain in good standing in the Diploma program, a student must maintain a Cumulative Weighted Average Grade (CWAG) of \"2.0\" or better in his/her course work at the end of each academic year until the completion of his/her program of study. The student\'s CWAG shall be computed the Program Adviser/Committee at the end of each academic year (two semesters and one summer) and reported by the latter to the Graduate Office, through channels. \n\nThe CWAG shall be based on all courses taken by the student in the approved program of study, including those taken in compliance with the Residence Rules. \n\nFailure to Satisfy the Grade Requirement\n\nA student who fails to satisfy the CWAG of \"2.0\" at the end of the academic year shall be disqualified from the Diploma program unless the Dean/Director decides, on justifiable grounds and upon the recommendation of the student\'s Program Adviser/Committee, through channels, to waive the rule. \n\nF. RESIDENCE RULES\n\nOne-Year Residence Before Graduation\n\nThe student must be officially enrolled at least one (1) academic year prior to the concerment of the Diploma degree. \n\nRegular Period for Completion\n\nThe time limit for the completion of all Diploma degree requirements shall be no more than two (2) years. The period of residence shall start from the student\'s first enrolment in a graduate course after admission into the diploma program and shall include all leaves of absence from the program. The regular period for completion of a graduate student transferring from another university shall be reduced by one (2) semester. \n\nExtension of Residence \n\nIn exceptionally meritorious cases, extensions of residence beyond the above regular period of completion may be approved by the Dean/Director upon the recommendation of the appropriate bodies. This extension shall be for a period not exceeding one (1) semester at a time. In no case shall the extensions exceed more than one (2) year. The student granted an extension shall take 3 additional units of graduate courses in his/her discipline or area during the extension period. \n\nNon-Compliance with Residence Rules\n\nAny student who fails to complete all requirements of the degree within the regular period and any approved extension thereof shall be disqualified from the Diploma program. \n\nLeave of Absence (LOA) / Absence without Leave (AWOL)\n\nA student who goes on leave of absence (LOA)/absence without leave (AWOL) from the Diploma program shall seek readmission into the program form the Dean/Director, through channels.\n\nOption to Proceed to a Master\'s Degree\nStudent in the Diploma program may opt to proceed to a Master\'s program upon the recommendation of the Program Adviser and approval of the Dean. \n\nG. GRADUATION FOR THE DIPLOMA PROGRAM\n\nApplication for Graduation\n\nAfter completion of all requirements for the Diploma degree, the student shall be qualified to apply for graduation to the University Registrar through the college/unit Graduate Office. \n\nConferment of Degree\n\nAfter the graduation of the student shall have been recommended by the College Faculty Assembly and appropriate body, endorsed by the University Council, and approved by the Board of Regents, he/she shall be officially conferred the Diploma degree by the University. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1625, 'E2-1625AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1998, August 17)', 'MR. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nDean, College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines \nMelchor Hall, U.P. Campus\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Mr. Atanacio, \n\nThis refers to your letter dated 10 August 1998 regarding the draft Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) between the Metals Industry Research and Development Center (MIRDC) and the University of the Philippines (UPD).\n\nThe following are our comments : \n\na. Combine items 1.2 and 1.7 to be stated as follows : \n\n\"Design and provide skills training courses for the faculty members, staff and students of UPD Department of Mechanical Engineering in accordance with the negotiated fee\"\n\nb. Item 1.8 should be deleted since we cannot provide a lecture who will conduct a three hour per week lecture continuously. \n\nThank you and hoping to receive the approved MOA soonest. \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nROLANDO T. VILORIA\nExecutive Director ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1626, 'E2-1626AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1998, September 29) ', 'ADDITIONAL LIST OF PROJECTS FOR POSSIBLE FUNDING BY THE JAPAN GRANT\n\n1) Feasibility and operational plan for the piloting of Virtual Center for Advanced Technology  (VCAT) concept for electronics/information technology sector - a study should be conducted to do the following : \n\na) Identification of the network institutions as stakeholders of the VCAT\nb) Identification of the programs to be undertaken by the VCAT member institutions. \nc) Draw a mechanism for the operationalization of the VCAT. \n\n2) Selection of Engineering and Science tertiary institutions/centers of excellence, and their respective programs to be supported by ESEP II-the study would develop the necessary criteria for the different tertiary institutions/centers of excellence to qualify for support under the proposed project. \n\n3) Study on the effectiveness of the teacher training activities under the intitial implementation of  Project RISE - This study will look into the performance of teachers in the Initial batch of Project RISE grantees and their impact to their students. Data gathering for student performance will be timed when TIMSS-R national testing is done in February 1999. \n\n4) Determination of specific targets and performance indicator for the various project components - Development of performance indicators is necessary to measure the progress in attaining the project objectives. \n\nThe above mentioned studies are in addition to the proposed analysis of S&T sector and needs for S&T manpower, ESEP impact analysis, social assessments analysis and study of best practices. ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1627, 'E2-1627AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1998, October 16) ', 'Prof. EDGARDO G. ATANACIO\nDean, College of Engineering\nUniversity of the Philippines\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nAttention : Prof. Ferdinand G. Manegdeg\nChairman\nDepartment of Mechanical Engineering\n\nDear Prof. Atanacio, \n\nWe wish to inform you that the Second-Pacific Asia Conference on Mechanical Engineering (2PACME) held last September 9-11, 1998 at the Holiday Inn Hotel, Manila was a tremendous success. \n\nWe are very grateful for the University of the Philippines\' contribution as a cooperating agency in the implementation of the international conference on mechanical engineering. We wish to acknowledge receipt of your donation amounting to P10,000.00. In behalf of the Organzing Committee, I wish to thank you and your faculty for your support in the realization of this significant undertaking. \n\nHerewith are copies of the conference proceeding for your office and your Information Resource Center. We are also enclosing copies of the Conference Souvenir magazine for your office. \n\nAgain, thank you very much and we look forward to another fruitful cooperation with you in the future. Mabuhay! \n\nVery truly yours, \n\nFREDERICK SO. PADA\nPresident, Technological University of the Philippines and Chair, International Executive Council - 1988 Manila Conference ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-19 04:23:31'),
(1628, 'E2-1628AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1999, October 11) ', 'Dr. Emil Q. Javier\nPresident \nUniversity of the Philippines \nQuezon Hall\nDiliman, Quezon City\n\nDear Sir/Madam, \n\nThe National Mapping and Resource Information Authority (NAMRIA) in coordination with the Technical Committee on Statistical Concerns and Coordination and the DENR\'s Statistics Division will be holding a free seminar entitled \"Technology on Spatial Data Collection and Analysis\" at the Petrolab, Mines and Geo-sciences Bureau (MGB) along North Avenue, Quezon City on 14 October 1999 at 1:00 p.m. The activity is in line with the observance of the 10th National Statistics Month.\n\nIn this regard, we would like to invite you and your senior staff to participate in the said seminar. Resource persons from NAMRIA will present and discuss the processes as well as the technologies used in the collection and analysis of spatial data. \n\nEnclosed is the tentative programme for your reference. For further inquiry and confirmation, please contact Mr. Henry C. Bardeloza/Ms. Anna Maria Gapuz- Information Services Division (ISD) at phone nos. 8105466/63/60 or 8104831 local 401 / 440 or facsimile nos. 8105468/8102891.\n\nWe look forward to your participation in this event. Thank you very much.\n\nVery truly yours, \n\nLIBERATO A. MANUEL\nBGen. AFP (Ret.) MNSA\nAdministrator/Undersecretary', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-18 08:36:49', '2026-03-18 08:36:49'),
(1629, 'E2-1629AC', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '(1999, March 22) ', 'The National University of Singapore\r\n\r\nDr. Natalia Ma. Lourdes M. Morales ', '', NULL, NULL, 'Public (Metadata Only)', 'active', '2026-03-17 16:36:49', '2026-03-19 03:59:43'),
